<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT ORIOLES, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (w) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Octavio Dotel's performance on Mondy night
suggested he could be attractive enough, all by himself, for the
New York Mets to trade him for a top starter before the July 31
trading deadline. But now the Mets must decide if they want to keep
him instead.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth major league start, Dotel, a 23-year-old
right-hander, stymied the Baltimore Orioles on one run and three
hits over seven innings in the Mets' 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Mets' fourth in five games since the
All-Star Game break and second in a row here at Camden Yards. Since
June 6, the day they ended an eight-game losing streak, the Mets
(54-40) have a 27-12 record, best in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel (2-1) struck out 5 on just 91 pitches as the Mets pulled
to 14 games over .500, their best of the season, and moved within
three games of the first-place Atlanta Braves, who lost to Toronto,
in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Dotel could help down the stretch, Manager Bobby
Valentine said: ``Absolutely. I think he will only get better with
confidence and knowing that he can throw other pitches than his
fastball. He's a wild card, and unknown to other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Steve Phillips would not commit himself on
Dotel, saying: ``You have to ask yourself that question, whether he
can be the solution to our needs. It's a matter of whether he can
fill that void down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel said, ``I don't want to say that I'm the answer, but I'm
going to be here and they're going to see if I can do what they're
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   With about a dozen scouts watching, Dotel's fastball was
consistently clocked from 92 to 96 miles an hour through the first
six innings. And the Orioles were having a hard time catching up.
Only Will Clark, who blasted a 94-mile-an-hour pitch on an 0-2
count into the right-center-field bleachers, had the rookie figured
out.
</P>
<P>
   The other two hits Dotel had allowed through six innings were a
single to B.J. Surhoff in the fourth inning, which had followed a
one-out walk to Mike Bordick, and a leadoff single to Bordick in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Dotel got Albert Belle to line a slider hard to
center field for the second out. Then, after Dotel threw an
attempted pickoff into center field to allow the runners to advance
to second and third, he induced Harold Baines to fly out to right.
</P>
<P>
   And in the sixth, after Bordick's single, it took Dotel six
pitches to retire the side. And so the Mets took a 2-1 lead into
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets left the bases loaded in both the first (with one out)
and in the third (with two outs). And even when they scored a pair
of runs in the fifth off the rookie right-hander Jason Johnson to
drive him from the game, the Mets left another two runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson scored the first run to pull within one of
Willie Mays' 2,062 career runs, fifth on the career list.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson was the designated hitter on Monday night for the
first time since Sept. 18, 1997, when he was with the Angels. It
was Manager Bobby Valentine's way of giving the 40-year-old left
fielder's legs a little rest.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson walked to lead off the game before eventually being
stranded on third.
</P>
<P>
   To open the fifth, he beat out an infield single to shortstop.
He moved to second on Edgardo Alfonzo's grounder to short and went
to third on a deep fly ball to right-center off John Olerud's bat.
When Mike Piazza lined a 1-0 pitch to left, Henderson scored the
game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza scored after Robin Ventura and Benny Agbayani singled.
But Clark's homer in the fifth cut the deficit in half. Dotel
finally got a comfortable margin in the seventh inning when Alfonzo
and Ventura homered off Arthur Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel tossed a scoreless seventh but was tiring. He hit one
batter, and his fastball dropped to the range of 89 to 92 miles an
hour. Only when he struck out pinch-hitter Jeff Conine to end the
inning did Dotel's fastball hit 95 again.
</P>
<P>
   The thin right-hander pumped his fist as he walked off the
mound, knowing that he had turned in a job well done. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
