<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GAINS AND LOSSES ON HIV 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, July 20:
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of gay and bisexual men in New York City showed
encouraging evidence that many members of the gay community are
acting responsibly to reduce the risk of HIV infection. The survey,
an unusual collaboration between the Department of Health and the
Gay Men's Health Crisis, a nonprofit AIDS organization in New York,
supports a growing consensus that perhaps only half as many gay men
in the city are infected with HIV as in 1985. But the survey also
points to breakdowns in education about HIV, especially in black
and Latino communities.
</P>
<P>
   The survey reached more than 7,000 participants in all boroughs
of New York City, more than any previous effort. It showed that HIV
prevention efforts there have clearly made an impact among gay men.
But it offered no grounds for complacency. For example, the rate of
new HIV infections in black and Latino populations, heterosexual
and homosexual, is disproportionately higher than it is among
Caucasians. This is partly due to the persistent but false
perception that HIV is a disease affecting white gay men and drug
users. Moreover, education programs have tended to focus on white
gay men, while prevention efforts among heterosexuals and
minorities have languished. Thus many potential victims _ including
heterosexual women involved with drug users _ are not getting the
attention they need.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 200,000 Americans are unaware that they are
infected with HIV &UR; . &LR;  One antidote to such ignorance is more free
testing, along the lines of the annual National HIV Testing Day,
sponsored a few weeks ago by the National Association for People
with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Public-private cooperation is also essential. The joint survey
undertaken by New York City's Health Department and the Gay Men's
Health Crisis is a case in point. Chicago has gone even further,
involving political leaders, city agencies and an array of
community groups in a broad-based network designed to provide both
treatment and prevention. The program receives strong support from
the mayor and the governor of Illinois. New York politicians and
local groups should strive toward such a model.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
