<SLUG> BC-RIOT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 YEAR AFTER NAVAJO CHAIRMAN'S DOWN FALL, TURMOIL REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL DONOVAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDOW ROCK - When about 50 supporters of embattled Navajo
Tribal Chairman Peter MacDonald stormed tribal offices 10 years ago
today, they were seeking only to force release of payroll checks
for MacDonald appointees.
</P>
<P>
   But the riot, which lasted less than 10 minutes, would have a
profound affect on the political life of the Navajos and on the man
they were trying to restore to power.
</P>
<P>
   In its wake, bitter feelings remain among tribal members,
MacDonald remains in a federal prison, the tribe remains without a
charismatic leader and the tribal chairmanship has been replaced
with a less-powerful office of president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still seeing the effects of that time today,'' said
Tazbah McCullah, MacDonald's press officer in early 1989 _ which
tribal members still call ``the days of turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald, 68, is now in federal prison, along with three of his
supporters who participated in the disturbance. Seven others were
imprisoned and released for their roles in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   McCullah now runs the tribal radio station, but for years she
and others who served under MacDonald were unable to get jobs in
tribal government. In fact, she and several others were under
tribal court order for a year prohibiting them from entering
government buildings or participating in tribal government in any
way.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal officials cite the turmoil and the feelings it stirred up
as one of the primary reasons why voter turnout today for tribal
elections is down.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MacDonald supporters, who still number in the
thousands, say they are searching _ without success _ for a leader
as charismatic and visionary as MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald, who in 1983 was labeled by ``Mother Jones''``''
magazine as the ``most powerful Indian leader in America,''
dominated tribal politics for much of the 1970s and 80s. He
controlled the tribal council and single-handedly decided which
communities got federally funded projects and which did not.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1988, MacDonald's opponents seized upon the tribe's
purchase of the Boquillas Ranch just west of the reservation line.
U.S. Senate subcommittee hearings revealed that friends of
MacDonald made $7 million from the purchase, with MacDonald slated
to get part of it.
</P>
<P>
   That opened the door to a number of other tribal and federal
charges, resulting in the tribal council's suspending MacDonald
from office in February 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, his supporters held a number of
demonstrations, took over the chairman's office twice and generally
refused to accept any government that did not have MacDonald at the
top.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still feel that the council made a mistake by taking the
government away from the people,'' said Vern Lee, who now heads a
MacDonald support group in Shiprock, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Many MacDonald supporters still feel most bitter towards tribal
politicians of that time who went after MacDonald. By 1991, the
tribe had spent more than a million dollars hiring a special
prosecutor to investigate MacDonald, leading to convictions in
tribal court on charges including taking bribes and misusing his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Then MacDonald was convicted in federal court and sentenced to
14 years imprisonment for taking bribes and conspiracy-related
charges connected to the riot. He's not up for parole until 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But Wanda MacDonald, his wife, is still talking to federal and
state officials, trying to get support for a commutation or
compassionate release for her husband. She's also seeking to get
him transferred from a Texas prison to one in Arizona so family and
supporters could visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``His condition continues to get worse and worse. We need to
have him transferred as soon as possible to some place where he had
get adequate medical treatment,'' she said. Earlier this year, both
houses of the Arizona Legislature passed memorials supporting a
transfer to a state prison.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald is currently being treated for several medical
problems, the most serious of which stem from a minor heart attack
he suffered two years ago and hip problems that have confined him
to a wheelchair. Visitors say that his morale remains good but that
he seems to be losing hope of seeing his homelands again.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said that his supporters are also losing hope, even though
the tribal government has pardoned MacDonald and tribal leaders say
they have been pushing President Clinton for an early release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many have given up on current tribal leaders,'' said Lee, who
added that many Navajos just don't bother to vote anymore because
there are no leaders with the charisma of MacDonald or MacDonald's
long-time political foe, Peterson Zah.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, for the first time since 1970, there was no MacDonald
or Zah running for the tribe's top spot.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lot of Navajos were urging him to run, Zah, now a
special adviser to the president of Arizona State University,
declined. He said that ``it wasn't fun anymore'' to lead the tribe
because of the changes following MacDonald's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure no one would ever wield the power MacDonald did,
tribal council members did away with the chairmanship and replaced
it with a presidency with far less power.
</P>
<P>
   It also hasn't helped that three of the leaders after MacDonald
have either been indicted by a federal grand jury or forced from
office for violating tribal ethics laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who would be good leaders no longer want to get
involved in the tribal government,'' McCullah said. ``There's just
too much of a wild-dog pack mentality in the government where you
see tribal leaders being targeted for little things.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
