<SLUG> BC-CAESARIAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMES TO LIFE: C-SECTION DELIVERS TRIPLETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The miracle of life for the Diaz family began Monday
with some squeamish moments.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty family members, ages 1 through 86, gasped in unison at
the TV monitor as they watched surgeons cut into the belly of
Estrella Diaz. Meanwhile, thousands of strangers probably gasped
along with them.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz made history at Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center as
the first woman to deliver triplets by Caesarian section live on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Health resources on the Internet are expanding rapidly,
including transmission of surgical procedures. Critics call it
``edutainment,'' a blend between education and entertainment, but
others say the goal is to demystify the health-care process.
</P>
<P>
   In a hospital viewing room, Diaz family grandmothers and great
grandmothers shook their heads and placed hands over their mouths.
Some covered the eyes of their grandchildren and
great-grandchildren _ who seemed less disturbed by the graphic
surgery than their elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I was ready for that _ it was more than I wanted
to see,'' said Vivian Fisher, Diaz's mother.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of very long minutes later, quiet discomfort turned
to clapping when Desirae, Deanna and Christopher were born in less
than two minutes _ healthy and weighing from 4 pounds, 4 ounces to
5 pounds, 7 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gracias a Dios'' _ ``Thanks to God'' _ said the triplets'
fraternal grandmother, Lupe Urbano, raising her hands toward the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
   The tears she and others held back in the early uncomfortable
moments were joyfully released.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, the image was more muted than what the family
saw. In cyberspace, the image was small and blurry compared with
the hospital's large, sharp monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, thousands of Internet users jammed the Health Network Web
site _ thehealthnetwork.com _ preventing others from logging on;
the exact number won't be known until today. Those who missed it
can see the event in the Health Network's archives at the same
site.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said it was comforting to see the 23-year-old mom
remain calm throughout the surgery, as her 25-year-old husband,
George, crouched at her side talking to her.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time the cameras were tightly focused on the
surgical action, as the Health Network had promised the family;
Estrella's modesty was preserved as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   George made sure she could see each baby as soon as the infant
emerged. Dr. Michael Foley of Phoenix Perinatal Associates, which
handled the delivery, hopes this helped make the point that
C-section births can be a good bonding experience for parents and
newborns.
</P>
<P>
   Estrella and George, remembering how scared they were about
facing the C-sections required for their other three children, said
they hope Monday's broadcast will alleviate other parents' fears.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walt Larimore of the Health Network said its goal in showing
the 30 surgeries it's transmitted to date is to educate the public,
medical staffs and medical students.
</P>
<P>
   That point wasn't missed by 14-year-old Samantha Acosta-Garcia,
George Diaz's cousin. Her eyes never left the television screen
during the surgery, even in the bloodiest parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was educational, interesting and informational,'' she said,
adding that she is enthralled with medical shows and hopes to be a
doctor someday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jordan Perlow, who delivered the triplets, said that _
beyond delivering three healthy babies _ he believes the surgery
was a success because it allowed the public to see into a real
operating room, which is a different world than that portrayed on
``ER`` or ``Chicago Hope.``
</P>
<P>
   Many triplet pregnancies these days are the result of fertility
drugs, but Estrella's fertilization was natural _ about a 1 in
7,000 chance. The chance of having twins naturally is 1 in 85
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not such a rare event in this extended family. Angelita
Hernandez, 86, the aunt of the triplets' great-grandmother, noted
that multiple births run in the mother's side of the family, with
five sets of twins over five generations, including Estrella's
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Having six children will be a financial stretch for the family,
said George Diaz, who builds playgrounds for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will come to that when we come to that,'' he said. ``It
will be a big juggling act.'' They have a three-bedroom house now,
but will need a bigger one someday, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The babies, who were transferred to Phoenix Children's Hospital,
may be home in a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   Family members are now holding their breath, wondering who will
be the honored godparents for the three newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   After the event, Estrella's mother, Vivian Fisher, was the
official spokeswoman for the family. ``These are memories for a
lifetime,'' she said, adding that the family was glad to welcome
the rest of the world into their extended family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already knew that these babies were special. Now the whole
world knows they are special, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Health Network, a spokesman said their next baby
broadcast may feature surgery in utero.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't feature Estrella and George; the day she found out
she was pregnant was _ coincidentally _ the same day he went
through with a planned vasectomy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
