<HEADLINE>
BABY BOTTLE BRUSH PATENT HOLDER SUES COMPETITOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Baby products maker Munchkin Inc. has filed a
patent infringement suit against rival Luv N' Care Inc., claiming
the Monroe, La.-based company illegally copied Munchkin's combined
nipple cleaning and bottle cleaning brush design.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed June 25 in United States District Court in Los
Angeles, charges that Luv N' Care's brush infringes on the patent
for the brush that Munchkin first filed Nov. 4, 1994, and that was
granted Feb. 20, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Munchkin seeks up to three times the damage that it hopes to
prove at trial, plus interest and court costs as determined by the
court.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the nipple brush fits snugly into the handle of
the larger bottle brush and has a hook at the end, according to
Munchkin president and chief executive officer Steven Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   Munchkin sold about 2 million of the brushes in 1998, he said.
The company files an average of five patents a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of our top-selling units in our line,'' Dunn said.
``With the number of patents we file, we felt we had no choice but
to aggressively pursue (the suit), or we're wasting our money on
our patents. If we're not defending our patents, we should get out
of the patent business.''
</P>
<P>
   Luv N' Care attorney James Zellinger said the company had not
been formally served with the suit and would not comment in detail
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is, my clients don't infringe other
people's patents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what he did know of the suit, however, he said it
involved an ``insignificant'' volume of the product sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once my client is served _ if they're ever served _ it's not
something that will grab too much of my attention,'' Zellinger
said. ``It's a very minor amount of product.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dunn, Munchkin's vice president of sales first
spotted the Luv N' Care product June 7 at a Wal-Mart in Carrolton,
Texas. Two days later, company officials found it at the Wal-Mart
in Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   He said that court costs could range between $250,000 and
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
