<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS' ROLE CITED IN DAVIS CUP DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regrets, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Had they stuck to sport and saved the spite and suspicion for a
less momentous occasion, last weekend's elaborately planned Davis
Cup centennial quarterfinal between the United States and Australia
could have raised tennis' profile. It might also have recaptured
the essence of the first-ever Davis Cup match in 1900 at the
Longwood Cricket Club in Chestnut Hill, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Although Longwood still came through as an admirable host 100
years later, nothing else rang quite true: for starters, if this
centenary was all about tradition, it should have been played on
grass as was the original.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the least of the discrepancies in a round where the
backbiting began two months ago with Australia protesting the
arrangement the U.S. Tennis Association struck with the
International Tennis Federation to hold the matches at Longwood (by
home-and-away rights, it was Australia's turn to be the host), and
then protesting the USTA's attempt to stage the event on clay.
(Australia prevailed in that quibble and a hardcourt got the nod.)
</P>
<P>
   It seemed fitting that the actual competition, a 4-1 victory for
the visitors, concluded with a bizarre Sunday morning medical
squabble over the state of Todd Martin's health. The U.S. team
doctor proclaimed him too woozy to face Patrick Rafter in what
turned out to be the eliminator, but an ITF-appointed physician
disagreed and Martin was forced to play or forfeit the match.
Fortified by a pre-match intravenous, Martin made a remarkable
recovery and pushed Rafter, the defending U.S. Open champion, to a
fifth set before fizzling out.
</P>
<P>
   In between the furor over the site and surface choice and the
confusion over the first and second opinions Martin got when
doctors joined the fray, the biggest question mark hanging over the
competition was the limited role assigned to Pete Sampras, who
received a frantic telephone call from Tom Gullikson, the U.S.
captain, 90 minutes before Martin was due to meet Rafter. Gullikson
was irate about the speculation that Martin's medical woes were
calculated in order to bring Sampras off the singles sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have been trying to cheat, he would have already
hit and had eight racquets strung and been ready to play,''
Gullikson said. ``But he had no idea what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the best team won, and won with a vengeance that
included a triumphant 2-0 singles debut by 18-year-old Lleyton
Hewitt, there was a hollowness to the spectacle because it was
obvious to everyone, including Gullikson, that the United States
failed to mount the best possible team. Out of loyalty to his
first-round workhorses, Martin and Jim Courier, Gullikson brought
Sampras aboard in a doubles-only capacity. But after conceding the
round on Sunday night, Gullikson admitted he might do it all
differently ``in hindsight.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, the best player in the world but a late addition to the
1999 team, sat on the bench for all four singles losses because he
didn't want to upstage Martin and Courier, the players who laid the
groundwork for the quarterfinal by beating Britain in the first
round. So Sampras played cheerleader and, in an appearance that
only partially mitigated the disappointment of 5,300 fans who felt
they deserved better, secured the only American victory of this 4-1
debacle in Saturday's doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Martin nor Courier was 100 percent fit for dueling in
triple-digit temperatures. But they seemed convinced that
preserving a deserving first-round team, namely themselves, for the
test against Australia was more important than mobilizing the
personnel, namely Sampras, to beat the Australians.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Courier, the good soldiers, deserved to fight the
battle. But in order to give itself a chance to win the war, the
U.S. team clearly needed Sampras for more than a doubles cameo.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's attempt to excuse himself from the third singles match
and let Sampras step in against Rafter was too little, too late.
Sampras should have been playing singles from the start, and would
have been had he received a green light from his teammates and,
more to the point, from his captain.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gullikson's responsibility to remove the cautionary
yellow light Sampras encountered when he rejoined the team. In
wanting to reward Martin and Courier for services rendered,
Gullikson made it impossible to secure the services he needed to
fulfill his bottom-line commitment as the team captain: send out
the players most capable of winning a Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' conditional return to the Davis Cup squad included the
agreement that he would stick around and play singles for the rest
of the year, starting with the semifinals Australia earned to play
against Russia. Now there won't be any rest of the year for the
United States, which hasn't won the cup since Sampras factored into
all three victories against Russia in Moscow in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said repeatedly that a little dose of Sampras was
better than no Sampras, but now that the U.S. team has failed to
advance, that 1999 strategy is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you can put Sampras on the tennis court,
preferably singles but even doubles, it is a plus,'' Gullikson
said. ``It's not only important for the American Davis Cup team,
but obviously for tennis worldwide, to have the best player on the
planet playing Davis Cup is great for Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would have been greater, for the integrity of the sport
and for Davis Cup, if the best player on the planet had been
allotted a bigger role than half of a doubles team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a blur,'' Sampras said of his white-knuckle doubles
five-setter that staved off elimination, if only for a day. And now
that the United States is out of the competition, Davis Cup will be
back to a blur in this country.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
