<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6531 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HN     07-20 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ When the Comets put a bookmark on the 1999 season to
break for the WNBA All-Star Game eight days ago, they assumed they
could pick up where they left off after a 13-2 start.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, the Comets come home feeling the pain of their first
back-to-back losses since their inaugural 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   If one word describes the Comets' 60-48 loss to the Phoenix
Mercury at America West Arena on Monday night, it's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets established franchise lows for points, field goals
made (16) and shooting percentage (.281).
</P>
<P>
   Paving the way for those dubious distinctions was Tina Thompson.
One night after going 0-for-8 in a 13-point setback at Los Angeles,
Thompson went an even worse 0-for-12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're in a moment where we're not at our best,''
said Cynthia Cooper, who led the Comets with 19 points. ``But it's
best that it happens now, rather than at the end of the season or
at playoff time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adjustments that we need to make, we have time to make
them. Anything that we need to fix, we have time to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the world. It was a loss to a good
Phoenix team. And at the end of the day, we still have to go out
and win the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets (14-4) had been waylaid 78-65 by the Sparks on Sunday
night. But as anemic as the Comets' offense was at the Forum, a
massive infusion of red blood cells might have made little
difference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (6-10), which fell to the Comets in last year's WNBA
Finals, has won three games in a row for the first time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury had received an emotional boost from beating the
Sparks 84-76 on Saturday, but it was not at full strength for the
Comets. Starting point guard Michele Timms was out with the flu,
and her replacement, Kristi Harrower, turned her right ankle just
before the end of the first half and was taken to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   But Harrower returned in the second half and contributed to the
most monumental back-to-back wins in the history of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat the best team in the WNBA the last two years is
awesome,'' said Mercury forward Lisa Harrison. ``We needed this
big-time. I think we're more focused. We've been through so much
negative, and we're starting to get positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite experiencing a letdown on offense for most of the night
_ including a scoreless span of 7:26 in the second half _ the
Comets weren't completely out of contention until the final three
minutes. That's when Jennifer Gillom ``tore my heart out,'' said
Comets coach Van Chancellor, who coached Gillom in college at
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom, the Mercury's top scorer with 18 points, nailed a jumper
from the top of the key with two seconds left on the shot clock as
Phoenix took a 49-44 lead with 4:52 to play. She then got a
difficult fallaway 15-footer to bounce in with 2:37 to play, giving
her team a 51-46 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The next time down, after Harrower stole a pass from Polina
Tzekova, Gillom bombed in a 3-pointers to make it 54-48.
</P>
<P>
   Edna Campbell sealed the outcome with a pair of free throws with
44.2 seconds left that put the Comets in arrears 58-48.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't have it tonight,'' said Chancellor. ``We had it
defensively. We didn't have it offensively. We couldn't make a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sheryl Swoopes, who was 3-for-14 from the floor and had
just eight points, matching her season low: ``It is a loss, and any
time you lose, you try to learn from that. We're going to try to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who has been in an extended shooting slump that began
right before the All-Star break, said that before Sunday's game at
LA, she had never experienced an ``oh-fer'' at any level of her
basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were her usually reliable 3-point shots missing the
mark (0-for-6), but she even missed two layups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I let myself get the better of me, confidence-wise,''
Thompson said. ``But we have a couple of days off, then we go to
Charlotte. I'll work on that these next couple of days in the gym,
whether it takes me all day and all night.''
</P>
<P>
   She shouldn't want for company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
