<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PILOTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIN OR FALL SUGGESTS PILOT DISORIENTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The disclosure Monday that John F. Kennedy Jr.'s
plane plunged into the ocean far faster than previously believed
triggered speculation among area general aviation pilots that
Kennedy might have become disoriented and lost control of the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Radar data released Monday showed the plane dropped 1,100 feet
in 14 seconds or the equivalent of 4,700 feet per minute, which is
more than three times the rate reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he got it into a spin or stall, the plane could fall
straight down like that,'' said Brent Silva, 36, a 15-year pilot
and aircraft mechanic at Van Nuys Airport, the nation's busiest
general aviation hub.
</P>
<P>
   Like many pilots, Silva said Kennedy, who was presumed killed
along with his wife and her sister in the crash off Martha's
Vineyard, might have suffered vertigo under the difficult
conditions of flying at night over the ocean in haze while trying
to navigate by sight alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that rate of speed I'd have to assume the plane either
flipped over and nose-dived in, or he just went into a gradual bank
and without realizing had a fast descent and next thing he knew he
was right on top of the water and there was nothing he could do,''
Silva said.
</P>
<P>
   Tarren DeJong, 22, a flight instructor, said the
4,700-feet-per-minute rate of descent was too fast to indicate just
engine failure.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, this new data indicates Kennedy's Piper Saratoga
either fell into what aviators call a ``graveyard spiral'' or spun
down like a falling leaf.
</P>
<P>
   The spiral can happen if a pilot, during a bank, becomes
disoriented and pulls back on the controls, thus leveling out the
plane but in turn steepening the bank, DeJong said.
</P>
<P>
   A small plane also can descend rapidly if it stalls to the point
that its speed can no longer keep the plane aloft, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down like a maple leaf at a high rate of rotation _
spinning rapidly and falling fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McMann, publisher of Plane &AMP; Pilot magazine, said the
rate of descent, by itself, is not enough to draw a definitive
conclusion about the cause or circumstances of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one piece of the puzzle,'' said McMann, a pilot for
35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Among possible scenarios, McMann said, was that Kennedy might
have encountered some clouds or fog and tried to dip under them but
miscalculated his distance from the water.
</P>
<P>
   That rate of descent is not beyond the capability of Kennedy's
plane, but it was unusually fast, McMann said. And since he was
fewer than 2,000 feet from the ocean's surface, it would have been
very difficult for even an experienced pilot to pull up in time.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation experts said the normal rate of descent to ensure
passenger comfort is 500-700 feet per minute.
</P>
<P>
   The plane piloted by Kennedy, 38, was 17 miles from the airport
on Martha's Vineyard when it was last detected on radar about
9:40p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a massive search, investigators said it is
unlikely Kennedy, his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her
sister, Lauren Bessette, survived the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Several experienced private pilots at Van Nuys Airport,
including those trained to fly by instruments alone, said they
would not have attempted the flight taken by Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the day, when you're flying over the water and it's
hazy, you can't see the horizon,'' said Bob Roley, a 55-year-old
Glendale resident with 31 years of flight experience. ``At night
it's even worse. If you're not instrument rated, it'll freak you
out. You won't know if you're going up or down.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
