<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOLLYPARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY RAMSAMMY HAPPY WITH RESULTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ As he sat by his dressing cubicle between
races Monday at Hollywood Park, jockey Emile Ramsammy could take
pride in his best meeting on the Southern California circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsammy finished fifth in the jockey standings with 31
victories, compiling the second-best winning percentage behind only
veteran Chris McCarron as the spring/summer session came to a
close.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ramsammy knew how much better it might have been if he
hadn't suffered a fractured collarbone in a riding accident last
month at Woodbine Park in Toronto, a mishap that cost the
36-year-old rider 13 days of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very upset with the situation,'' Ramsammy said. `But
it's an occupational hazard, it could have been worse. It was
definitely a time you didn't want to get hurt, not that there's any
particular time you want to get hurt, but my business had just
started picking back up. It was a bad time. It definitely cost me a
lot of business.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ramsammy continues to ride like he did at Hollywood Park, the
business figures to return big time. He's looking forward to
Thursday's start of the Del Mar meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good meeting there last summer (10th in the jockey
standings),'' Ramsammy said. ``I like the atmosphere, the six days
of racing. It seems to bring back the sport in the game for some
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the thing about Del Mar is, you have some of the best
races there, and you also have the best 2-year-olds come out.
That's what everybody looks forward to, the young horses, and
looking forward to the next Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsammy, born in Trinidad, came to California during Santa
Anita's 1996-97 winter/spring meeting after six years in Canada. He
was dubbed the ``Sandy Hawley of the Caribbean'' for his exploits
at Woodbine Park, capturing the Sovereign Award as Canada's top
jockey in 1996 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   After he returned to Woodbine in March 1997 and finished the
year in Canada, he was back at Santa Anita for the 1997-98 meeting.
It seems the weather in California is more to Ramsammy's liking
than Canada's icy winters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Toronto we have a saying _ it's six months of cold and six
months of winter,'' Ramsammy said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsammy says he's here to stay. He would like to someday ride
in Europe, but California is his home for now. He figures riding
the local circuit will enhance his chances of finding that elusive
first Kentucky Derby mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of your aspirations when you become a jockey is to ride a
Kentucky Derby winner,'' he said. ``But I'm not just looking to
ride in the Derby, I'm looking forward to winning it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsammy, whose idol is fellow jockey Laffit Pincay Jr., hired a
new agent (Brian Beach) midway through the Santa Anita meeting.
He's been on the rise since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be back,'' he said. ``I'm as good as ever, and
I'm looking forward to Del Mar. It looks very promising.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexicon rolls: Lexicon, ridden by Kent Desormeaux and trained by
Richard Mandella, scored a one-length victory in the $100,000
Robert K. Kerlan Memorial Handicap for 3-year-olds and up.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux, who along with Corey Nakatani enjoyed a riding
double Monday, took Lexicon wire-to-wire for the 4-year-old colt's
second consecutive victory on the Hollywood Park turf course.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Conquistador Cielo covered the 5{ furlongs in 1:02
2/5 and, as the 2-1 betting favorite, returned $6, $4.20 and $3.20.
Fearless Pirate finished second and Cuvee Brut ran third.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is: Ronald McAnally won his fourth Hollywood Park
spring/summer training title of the decade with 25 victories. Alex
Solis won the jockey title with 57 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice, but it doesn't mean as much to me as having good
horses and winning big races,'' the 67-year-old McAnally said. ``To
me, winning a big race is still the greatest thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert was second in the trainer standings, followed by
Julio Canani.
</P>
<P>
   David Flores finished second to Solis. Garrett Gomez, who won
the Hollywood Park autumn meeting jockey title, was third in the
rider standings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
