r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     07-20 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY IN A FANTASY WOULD A TEAM WIN A TITLE AND NOT RAISE PRICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Strictly a fantasy, nothing more:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Local team wins world championship, and in doing so captures the
hearts and heads of a thrilled populace.
</P>
<P>
   We've had global champeens around here before (well, one to be
exact), but this was different. This was a feel-feel-feel good
story for one and all. This involved class, character and likable
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody won with this win. The team owner was hailed as
benevolent and much-beloved. The general manager as a mastermind.
The coach as part intellect and part Lombardi. The players as
courageous knights. (Luv that Little Ball of Hate).
</P>
<P>
   Even a 3-foot high piece of easily dented silver became the
local version of the Holy Grail. Long lines of humanity formed all
over North Texas, hoping for nothing more than a quick touch.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the fantasy:
</P>
<P>
   While everyone is still basking in the glow of positive vibes,
the Dallas Stars surprise everyone by piling more icing on their
big fat cake.
</P>
<P>
   As a thank-you to the fans for 50 consecutive Reunion Arena
sellouts last season, the club announcement comes down this week
that _ like I said, this is strictly fantasy _ there will ``no
ticket price hike'' for the coming season. And by the way, Stars'
training camp opens in 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   What a fine gesture. What a ton of good P.R. to be had. Win the
Stanley Cup and still hold the line on prices. Unheard of in
American sports.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there was a down-the-road benefit for the Stars. Every
game will sell out anyway for '99-2000, and in October of 2001 the
new arena opens in downtown Dallas, providing mass revenue bumps in
all areas, including ticket prices. That's what new arenas do, and
the bottom line is doubled if a championship team is involved.
</P>
<P>
   End of fantasy, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Stars' president Jim Lites said, ``that would make
a real nice story, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars notified renewing season-ticket holders last week of a
10 percent on the average ticket increase, and coming next will
probably be something close to a 20-percent bump for all other
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes in professional sports, but maybe more so in the
National Hockey League. With a weak TV contract, financial survival
comes at the gate, which drives ticket prices to a staggering
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come up with a balance on what's fair for our fans
and what's fair for our owner,'' Lites said. ``But the very last
thing we want is any perception we are gouging our fans because we
won the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, supply and demand figures in prominently. That's
just good bottom-line business. Demand will be strong for next
season and supply short. The Stars benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Lites wouldn't give a definite amount, but the club's claim is
it lost $5 million last season. ``Beyond the regular season, we
played 12 of a possible 16 home playoff dates,'' Lites said, ``so
it's not like we can make up the deficit next season even if we are
fortunate enough to be back \Rin the Stanley Cup Finals\S. But in
the new arena? Yes, we can. No question.''
</P>
<P>
   NHL figures for last season showed the Stars with the
ninth-highest average ticket prices. ``And since we had the best
team, we thought that was fair for our fans,'' Lites said.
</P>
<P>
   But luxury-suite prices in other arenas were factored into the
league average. Reunion has no luxury suites. Minus the suites, the
Stars may have the most expensive ticket in all of pro sports. Next
season, however, here comes that supply-and-demand bonus. Winning
the Stanley Cup created that, along with the trust factor owner Tom
Hicks established with the ticket buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Following the hockey expertise of GM Bob Gainey, Hicks invested
heavily _ some even said foolishly _ into the building of a
championship team. Over the past three years, he may be as much as
$20 million in the hole on hockey. In North Texas, what bank makes
that kind of sports loan on even the Cowboys, much less a so-called
``foreign'' game? But Hicks' long range financial plan was to
recover the loss with a new arena and a new regional TV sports
network.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, only in a fantasy would the line be held on ticket
prices for next season. Then again, go back to the early '90s, and
only in a fantasy would the Stanley Cup be joining us here in the
Chicken-fried Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Cowboys of 1995 demonstrated, just win and all else
is forgiven, the least of which is higher ticket prices. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
