<HEADLINE>
MOUND OF PROBLEMS FOR RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-MARLINS-REDSOX-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tomokazu Ohka's major league debut didn't last much
longer than the 32-minute rain delay Monday night that preceded the
Red Sox' 10-7 loss to the Florida Marlins in the soggy Fens.
</P>
<P>
   Ohka faced just 10 batters, including five who hit safely, one
who walked, and five who scored. The 23-year-old Japanese import
recorded just three outs before losing for the first time since
arriving on US soil, hardly enough time to form any lasting
impressions.
</P>
<P>
   But he left one after the game anyway, while surrounded by a
pack of Japanese TV cameras and tape recorders that expanded the
usual media contingent who follow the Sox from ``a rock pile to a
quarry,'' in the parlance of Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Ohka was given the chance to choose from a smorgasbord of
excuses. The rain delay. The shoddy fielding behind him, which
began on the first pitch of the game when shortstop Lou Merloni,
filling in for Nomar Garciaparra, booted Luis Castillo's ground
ball. That was one of three Sox errors on a night that Trot Nixon
also lost Mark Kotsay's bloop single in the sodden twilight,
breaking back on a ball that dropped yards in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   The last excuse was offered by both Sox manager Jimy Williams
and pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, who said Ohka had pitched just
three innings in the last 18 days, and the rust was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably not a fair way to evaluate the young man,''
Williams said. ``He just got hit.''
</P>
<P>
   To each of those possible alibis, Ohka shook his head with a
smile tinged with disdain.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, did he assess his own performance?
</P>
<P>
   ``Saiaku,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The worst.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes Ohka a standup guy on a night the Sox stumbled yet
again in interleague play, this time against a team that has
pummeled Sox pitching for 30 hits in two games, the last a
ninth-inning home run to dead center field by Preston Wilson,
a.k.a. the Son of Mookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are now 7-12 in their last 19 games and 5-12 vs. teams
with a National League East pedigree, including the lowliest of the
bunch, the last-place Marlins, who ran up a 7-0 lead in their first
three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox haven't won back-to-back games since Fourth of July
weekend in Chicago, one reason their lead over third-place Toronto
has shrunk to two games in the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   Despite closing to within 9-7 in the eighth inning, when John
Valentin's bid for a go-ahead three-run home run strayed just foul,
the Sox didn't inspire much confidence Monday night that pattern
will change anytime soon. Not on a night in which they announced
ace Pedro Martinez will miss his next start and the bullpen was
overtaxed yet again.
</P>
<P>
   In six games since the All-Star break, no Sox starter has lasted
more than five innings. Ohka's early departure Monday night fit
right in with the pattern set over the weekend by Mark Portugal and
Martinez, both of whom were gone before the grounds crew made their
first sweep of the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four games, Sox starters have worked 12 1/3 innings.
Sox relievers, meanwhile, have had nearly double the workload over
the same span, 23 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen has been used an awful lot,'' Williams said.
``From the second inning today. That's asking an awful lot of those
kids, to keep running them out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it'll take just one good game from our starter to get it
corrected. We have a good guy (Brian Rose) going tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope, of course, was that Ohka would be that guy, having
gone 11-0 while working his way up from Double A Trenton, where he
was 8-0, to Pawtucket (3-0) before arriving in Boston in his first
year of pro ball on this side of the international time line.
</P>
<P>
   That ascent was as rapid as the one made by Jin Ho Cho, the
Korean pitcher whose turn Ohka took Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the kid,'' Kerrigan said. ``I like the way he warms up.
He's got an idea about pitching, the way he goes about his
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins probably had no business scoring in the first
inning, when Castillo reached on Merloni's error, his ninth in 25
starts, stole second on the next pitch, and scored on Alex
Gonzalez's single. Bruce Aven followed with another base hit under
Merloni's glove, a ball the American League's starting All-Star
shortstop might have converted into a double play if the manager
hadn't ordered him to rest his strained left groin.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millar's sacrifice fly brought home a second run, Kotsay
dropped his bloop hit in front of a befuddled Nixon, and Wilson
doubled home a run with the first of his four hits. When Tim Hyers
ricocheted a ball off Ohka, the fourth run of the inning scored.
</P>
<P>
   Ohka was gone two batters into the second, after Mike Redmond
singled and he walked Castillo on four pitches. Pat Rapp replaced
Ohka, and after getting one out, watched the Sox make two more
errors. Center fielder Darren Lewis sprinted through puddles to
catch Aven's shallow fly, then threw wildly to second in an attempt
to double up Redmond, who took third. The error was the first in
519 chances in center field for Lewis, a streak that dates back to
Aug. 20, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the error trying to be aggressive,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   When Castillo stole second, Jason Varitek threw the ball into
center field, allowing another run to score. The Marlins would add
two more runs off Rapp, an original draftee of the expansion team
who came here as a starter but can't escape the bullpen, even as
the Sox audition one newcomer after another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
