<SLUG> BC-BBO-YOUNT-HALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBIN YOUNT'S NUMBERS SPEAK FOR THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Robin Yount never was a ``stats guy,'' as he put it, not even late
in the 1992 season when he was closing in on his 3,000th hit.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I guess if you play long enough and go to the plate enough
times, you're going to get a certain amount of hits,'' he said at
the time[ then]. ``It's really not that big a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong, of course. It was a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame voters are stats guys. Yount is going in[ along]
with contemporaries Nolan Ryan and George Brett because of his
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his 20-year career, all spent with the Milwaukee
Brewers, with 3,142 hits, 15th all-time. He had 583 doubles, 12th
all-time, and 4,730 total bases, 22nd all-time.
</P>
<P>
   Yount earned two American League Most Valuable Player awards, at
two different positions. He won in 1982 as a shortstop and in 1989
as a center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Those stats stamp you as one of the best ever to play the game,
and stamp your ticket to the Hall the first year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   But after being selected to take his place among baseball's
elite early this year, Yount still wouldn't tout his
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: I was good enough to stay in the
lineup,'' Yount said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right, of course. Statistics really are not that big a
deal. It's how you compile them that counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the attitude I wanted to play like it was the last time
I would play the game,'' Yount said. ``I gave it everything I got
every time I went out there. That's what I'm most proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount clearly had talent; there's no way to reach 3,000 hits or
play 20 seasons without it. Mostly, he had grit and determination,
hard work and hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a triumph of good,'' said baseball commissioner
and former Brewers owner Bud Selig. ``This is just a kid who was a
ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A ballplayer'' might be the ultimate compliment. It conjures
up an image of someone who plays for the love of the game, not for
the next contract; of someone who plays hard because that's the way
the game is supposed to be played, not for the sake of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   After being traded to Milwaukee in 1984, former Rangers catcher
Jim Sundberg got a closeup, everyday look at Yount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin went out there as hard as anybody,'' Sundberg said.
``Even when he was a little bit hurt you could always count on him
to do well. He was there, he was consistent, he was dependable.''
The natural When he started, way back in 1974, they called Yount a
phenom.
</P>
<P>
   He was drafted third overall in the '73 draft, behind David
Clyde and John Stearns. Yount hit .285 for Newark in the New
York-Penn League, and reported to Brewers' spring training camp in
'74 for his first taste of the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Yount surprised everyone by winning a job. At the tender age of
18, Yount was a big-league shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, home-run king Hank Aaron went home to
Milwaukee for his last couple seasons. Aaron had played with and
against a lot of great players in his career, and he saw another
one in his young teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him first put on a major-league uniform, I thought
this kid could go a long way,'' Aaron said. ``He learned quickly,
and each year he got better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount was a skinny, decent-field, decent-hit shortstop his first
three years. Then, after filling out because of weight training and
maturity, he became the best hitter at his position since Ernie
Banks and the precursor of later middle-infield sluggers like Cal
Ripken and Alan Trammell, and the current crop of Alex Rodriguez,
Derek Jeter and Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Yount hit .288 in 1977, and topped .290 in nine of the next 12
seasons. He led the league with 49 doubles in 1980, when he also
hit .293 with 23 home runs, 87 runs batted in and 20 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Yount had his best season in 1982. He batted .331 with 29 home
runs and 114 RBI, all career highs. He led the league in hits with
210, tied for the lead with 46 doubles and led shortstops with 489
assists.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first shortstop to lead the league in slugging and
total bases.
</P>
<P>
   Yount was rewarded with both the AL MVP award and a Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   Although he led the AL with a .985 fielding percentage in 1981,
it was his bat that made Yount special.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good defensive shortstop,'' Sundberg said. ``The big
thing for Robin was he hit so well. There were not that many good
hitting shortstops in the '70s who could actually hit home runs,
drive runs in and hit for a high average. You were coming from the
\RMark\S Belanger years where shortstops were good field and no
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Yount a great hitting shortstop, he was a great
clutch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers clinched the division title on the final day of the
1982 season when Yount hit two homers off Baltimore Orioles ace Jim
Palmer. Yount hit .414 in the World Series with a record-setting
two four-hit games, although the Brewers lost to the Cardinals in
seven games. He batted .344 in 17 career postseason games. Center
of the action After the 1984 season, Yount no longer was a
shortstop. He had shoulder surgery to repair frayed tendons, and
moved to the outfield so he wouldn't have to make as many hard
throws.
</P>
<P>
   It's only a few feet in physical distance from shortstop to
center field, but it's miles away in terms of the mental
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Robin about that, and the hardest aspect was
you're so much farther from home plate and you struggle more to
keep your head in the game,'' Sundberg said. ``I've looked up at
times as a catcher and seen guys in the outfield adjusting their
hands because of what happened in the previous at-bat. You don't
ever see that in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer to home plate you get the faster the action. The
farther away, you've got more time to goof off. He said it was at
times kind of boring out there, there wasn't enough activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount batted just .277 his first season as a center fielder, but
then took to his new position both defensively _ he led the league
in fielding percentage in 1986, when he made just one error _ and
offensively. Yount batted better than .300 for the next four
seasons, culminating in his second MVP season when he hit .318 with
21 home runs and 103 RBI to edge the Rangers' Ruben Sierra (.306,
29 homers, 119 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the position, Yount played the same way: like a
ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the guys that I played against, probably Robin is the guy I
enjoyed playing against the most,'' Brett said. ``He didn't get too
high when things were going well, and didn't get too down when
things were going bad. Milwaukee was never one of my favorite
places to go to, but I always looked forward to it, because of
Robin.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more numbers.
</P>
<P>
   He was the third-youngest player in history to reach 3,000 hits,
with only Ty Cobb and Aaron reaching the milestone at an earlier
age. Yount, Brett and Willie Mays are the only players with more
than 3,000 hits, 250 homers, 200 stolen bases, and 100 triples.
</P>
<P>
   For Robin Yount, though, it never was about the stats.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
