<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6543 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX     07-20 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS IN THE CARDS FOR THESE RYAN FAN-SITE AUTHORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Ming Cheung of Houston and Erik Millsap of Columbiaville,
Mich., their adoration for Nolan Ryan started with baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   They showed them to friends, baseball fans, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened that made Cheung and Millsap dangerous.
They learned HTML, hypertext markup language _ Internet coding.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, they joined the legions of amateur Webmasters who have set
up tribute pages of their sports heroes. Cheung and Millsap, who
worked on their efforts for more than two years, have the best
homemade pages dedicated to Ryan, the pitching great who is to be
inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came from a longtime admiration for Nolan,'' said Millsap
of starting his 2-year-old Ryan Express page
(www.eliteentertainment.net/ryanexpress). Also, Millsap, 21, had
``magazines, pictures, articles, cards and other memorabilia'' he
needed to put to good use.
</P>
<P>
   ``After learning how to create Web pages, I decided to showcase
this information in the form of a Web site,'' Millsap said.
</P>
<P>
   The same went for Cheung, who created original graphics and
culled information from media guides for his site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I have one of the biggest collections of Nolan Ryan, I
wanted to be the first to publish a Web page as a tribute to him,''
said Cheung, a fan since 1982. ``When mine hit the 'Net (on May 1,
1996), there was no other one out there at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ryan is listed on several sites, mainly for collectibles
and memorabilia. He even has a bigger presence than fellow
inductees George Brett and Robin Yount, who have one known fan site
between them. Star-Telegram.Com, the Star-Telegram's site, has
produced a section on Ryan (www.star-telegram.com/specials/99nolan)
with such features as screensavers and electronic postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan also has three other known tribute pages created by Ryan
fans Greg Speth (www.reliable-net.net/~speth/indexnolan.html), Mark
McCormick (www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Arena/3445) and Adam Shapiro
(www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Field/5578).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Ryan tribute sites have a lot of the same
information _ statistics and career highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's what happens when you turn trading cards into
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   HEY, MAVERICKS FANS: You know you're a Mavericks fan if you're
tracking the team's games in the Summer League in Los Angeles.
You're really a fan if you're following the team online.
</P>
<P>
   Through Aug. 1, fans can access play-by-play and box scores at
the 16-team league's official site (www.summerproleague.com). It's
like sitting on press row at the game. Woo-hoo.
</P>
<P>
   Using software developed by CyberSports Inc., of Redmond, Wash.,
games can be followed while they're in progress or they can be
accessed in an archive.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks play twice this week, meeting the Orlando Magic on
Thursday and the Cleveland Cavaliers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER BASEBALL: FOXSports.com has taken baseball updates to a
new level with a new Shockwave-powered application it unveiled
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With FOXSports.com's GameTracker, fans can watch up to four
baseball games at once and from five camera angles. GameTracker,
which was previewed for the All-Star Game two weeks ago and
continues to be in development, also allows users to access
real-time individual situational statistics, player portfolios,
on-demand instant replay and leaguewide scoreboards.
</P>
<P>
   According to FOXSports, users will need at least a 233-megahertz
Pentium II-class processor, and modem connections less than 56.6
kilobytes per second will result in slow downloads.
</P>
<P>
   CHAT HIGHLIGHTS: Second-year Oakland Raiders coach Jon Gruden is
scheduled to chat at 4 p.m. Tuesday at Raiders.com (raiders.com)
... Michelle Akers of the U.S. women's soccer team, 8 p.m.
Wednesday on ESPN.com ... Thomas Dooley, Major League Soccer
all-star and '98 U.S. National team captain, 6 p.m. Wednesday on
Yahoo! Chat (chat.yahoo.com).
</P>
<P>
   HAIL THE CHAMPIONS: Sites where fans of the 1999 Women's World
Cup champion U.S. soccer team can track their heroes:
</P>
<P>
   Elaine's Team USA Web Page
(www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Pressbox/6339): Massive undertaking by
Elaine Sun, a fan who has assembled an unofficial site with
everything about the team.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm on Athlete Direct (keyword: miahamm): Send Hamm a note
with a Hamm-Gram; also, read her journal and buy official Mia
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Akers' Soccer Page (michelleakers.com: Akers opens with
an audio ``Hey, dude, welcome to my home page'' and shares training
tips with fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Lilly Pad (www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Field/9748): This
unofficial site for Kristine Lilly has lots of images and links to
other soccer sites.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
