<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-NYT &LR;      07-20 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE MISSION IS HALTED 6 SECONDS BEFORE LAUNCHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ A last-minute engine shutdown aborted the
flight of space shuttle Columbia early on Tuesday and temporarily
thwarted the dreams of an Air Force colonel to become the first
woman to command a space shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Eileen M. Collins and her crew of four did not appear to be
in immediate danger, and controllers quickly went to work trying to
determine what had caused the three engines, among the oldest in
NASA's stock, to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia was to have lifted off its seaside launching pad at
12:36 a.m. on a five-day mission to deploy a powerful, $1.5 billion
X-ray telescope. The launching, which was aborted six seconds
before liftoff, would have come 30 years to the day after the
historic Moon landing by the American astronauts Neil A. Armstrong
and Buzz Aldrin in the Apollo 11 lunar module Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and several celebrities
and influential woman were gathered at the Kennedy Space Center to
witness the launching.
</P>
<P>
   The launching commentator, Bruce Buckingham, said engineers saw
readings that indicated a high concentration of hydrogen propellant
in the shuttle's aft engine compartment. There was no appearance of
fire.
</P>
<P>
   The three engines shut down while the shuttle was still on the
launching pad. This is an indication that at least one of the
engines, or its associated equipment _ valves, control computers or
related systems, did not perform properly during the start
sequence, which is 6.6 seconds long.
</P>
<P>
   There have been five previous shutdowns of this type in the
shuttle program. Three of those occurred in the post-Challenger
era. There were two in 1993 and one in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   This so-called redundant set launching sequencer shutdown does
not necessarily threaten the safety of the shuttle crew, but
hydrogen gas can be released through the engine nozzle during
shutdown. Hydrogen burns without a visible sign of flame, and it is
possible that a brief fire on the launching pad can follow the
abort. But Buckingham said controllers had seen no indications of
fire. The launching pad is equipped with a sophisticated fire
extinguishing system that automatically starts spraying the orbiter
with water. Fire detection sensors are located all over the pad.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a launching pad engine shutdown can delay another
shuttle launching attempt for at least three weeks, possibly four,
because of time needed to remove and replace the engines. NASA
officials had not said this would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Any time the engines are started, they must be inspected and
serviced, just as if the shuttle had taken off and flown. But it
did not appear that the engines had started.
</P>
<P>
   The engines were made by Boeing division in California. The
total number of engine starts by engine 1 is 27. Engine 2 has had
22 starts, and engine 3, 35. Engine 1 has been used on 11 shuttle
missions, engine 2 on 16 and engine 3 on 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
