<HEADER>
A6553 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANGELNOTES-LADN     07-20 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN ACTIVATED, PUT IN AT CLEANUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ San Diego Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn was
activated from the disabled list and started Monday's game against
the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was out May 22-June 12 with a strained left calf, then
placed on the DL again on June 24 with the same injury.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was penciled into the starting lineup Monday afternoon,
but the Padres didn't announce the move until after batting
practice and pregame drills to be sure he was ready. It was a
routine Gwynn has been through before, only this time it wasn't a
false alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like the fifth time I've been in the lineup,'' Gwynn
said before the game. ``I still feel productive, I can be
productive if I'm healthy. The team is playing well and I'm anxious
to get back. Not for the team's psyche but for my own psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect a lot right away. In my mind, I'm going to go
out there and have a chance to do something.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was the DH and batted cleanup. According to a Padres
spokesperson, it was Gwynn's first appearance as a cleanup hitter
``in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn went into the game with 2,982 career hits.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets demoted: In order to make room for Monday's starting
pitcher Ken Hill on the active roster, the Angels optioned utility
infielder Andy Sheets to Triple-A Edmondton.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets was the starting shortstop in 58 of the club's first 68
games, replacing the injured Gary DiSarcina. But since DiSarcina's
return June 22, Sheets appeared in only six games (one start) and
was hitless in nine at-bats. Overall, Sheets is hitting .205 with
three homers and 26 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon back in right: After two starts as the club's DH since
his return from a wrist injury, Tim Salmon was back in right field
for the Angels on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins said he has no concerns with Salmon's
wrist. ``The only thing I'm concerned about with Tim Salmon is late
in the game how tired he'll be,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien making progress:! Catcher Charlie O'Brien, on the
disabled list since June 3 with a partially torn ligament in his
right foot, ran on Monday. He has already begun throwing and
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   The time is now: With August less than two weeks away and the
Angels 8{ games out (going into Monday's game), Collins said the
time is now for his team. ``We need to get it together totally,''
he said. ``We can't point to any one guy or one area. If we're
going to try to make a run with 80 games to go, it had better be a
team thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
