   &UR; KENNEDY PLANE CRASH (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-EUROPE (London) _ Public and press reaction in Europe to
the Kennedy story.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-MAGAZINE (New York) _ John F. Kennedy Jr. had in recent
weeks begun to discuss the fate of his nearly four-year-old
political magazine, George, with advisers at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.,
the investment bank. Kennedy, an executive close to the talks said,
was discussing with advisers strategic options. In particular, the
executive said, Kennedy had hoped to find a financial partner and
had come up with a list of companies he was interested in
approaching. By Laura M. Holson and Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHINA-TRADE (Blagoveshchensk, Russia) _ Ten years of
trade, tourism and a regular flow of official exchanges _ begun
after a trip to China in 1989 by the last Soviet president, Mikhail
Gorbachev _ have left many Russians feeling bitter, disappointed
and often exploited by a hectic shuttle trade in Chinese goods and
food that has enriched their Chinese neighbors and left them as
poor _ if not poorer _ than before. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING _ Republicans and Democrats alike are
finding that the impeachment trial of the president remains a
potent fund-raising tool. Donors seem to want to punish either
Clinton (via the Democrats) or his prosecutors (via the
Republicans). By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-LOSERS (Undated) _ Since the beginning of 1999, many an
enterprising soul has founded an Internet company, offered stock,
and achieved a billion-dollar capitalization. But this gold rush
has a dark side: the losers. The rule of thumb for venture
capitalists is that for every 10 start-ups that receive financing
(and plenty do not), two will be home runs, three will be absorbed
by other concerns, and the rest will fail. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MANUFACTURING (Moscow) _ A rising generation of
manufacturers is finding opportunity amid the economic tumult in
Russia. The ruble's devaluation made imports too expensive for most
people, and as imports shrank, Russian manufacturers filled the
void with cheaper products. Large, Soviet-built factories have done
best, but individuals are also fashioning a role for themselves. By
Neela Banerjee.
</P>
