<HEADLINE>
RIVERA RUINS HILL'S RETURN FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins talked as
though he knew something nobody else knew Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how I feel about him,'' Collins said of Monday's
starter Ken Hill. ``He can dominate. Hopefully the warm weather
will help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Hill and the Angels, San Diego's Ruben Rivera
hit a three-run homer in the top of the 10th off reliever
Shigetoshi Hasegawa to carry the San Diego Padres to a 4-1 victory
before 25,217 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Angels could be cheered by Hill's performance. In
his first start since coming off the disabled list, Hill threw six
scoreless innings. He hadn't pitched since June 30 because on an
inflamed right elbow, the same elbow he had surgery on in June last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was on a pitch count of 90 to 100 pitches, but made only 84
before handing the ball to the bullpen with a 1-0 lead to start the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres tied it with a run off Mark Petkovsek in the eighth,
spoiling Hill's bid for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hill looked good from the start, retiring the first five batters
he faced before a two-out walk to John Vander Wal in the second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't allow a hit until Damian Jackson's groundball double
down the left-field line with one out in the third. Jackson stole
third with two outs, but was stranded.
</P>
<P>
   Hill walked Tony Gwynn with one out in the fourth, but got Wally
Joyner to hit into an inning-ending double play. He retired the
side in order in the fifth, and got the first two outs in the sixth
before running into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Owens lined a single to center and Reggie Sanders followed
with a line-drive single to left. Hill then fell 2-0 behind Gwynn,
which got pitching coach Dick Pole off the bench for a visit to the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Hill threw a called strike past Gwynn, then got him to ground
into a fielder's choice, ending the inning and his outing for the
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' only run came in the fourth off Padres starter Matt
Clement. Randy Velarde led off with a double and scored on Garret
Anderson's two-out, ground-rule double.
</P>
<P>
   Clement got help from his defense, which turned three double
plays, including two that Darin Erstad hit into. Erstad's second
came in the fifth after the Angels had runners on first and third
with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad hit into a double play with runners in scoring position
only once in 1998, but he has done it twice in the past two nights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
