<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIGSKY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE SCANDAL WAS FORESEEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ Even though he was a thousand miles away as
the Cal State Northridge football program was being investigated,
Eastern Washington head football coach Mike Kramer said Monday he
had an idea of what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew stuff was happening in late March,'' Kramer said,
adding this caveat, ``when (CSUN defensive coordinator) Craig Wall
and (running backs coach) Keith Borges weren't going into the
office.''
</P>
<P>
   One conclusion among the Big Sky football coaches is clear. CSUN
football is on rocky ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is this will be (CSUN's) last year of
football,'' Kramer said. ``The conference is moving itself farther
and farther away from Northridge. It would be a huge loss. You
could just see the level of the program improving year after
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the investigation _ which began after an anonymous
letter _ has yet to be released, but two coaches have been. Head
coach Ron Ponciano was fired Friday, two days before the Big Sky
Conference football meetings, and offensive coordinator Rob
Phenicie left the school the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said he was shocked by the timing of the firings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a difficult a thing as can happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Big Sky commissioner Doug Fullerton said he supports the
university's decision. Ellen Farris, the Big Sky assistant
commissioner in charge of compliance services, said she hasn't been
forwarded any information from the CSUN investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only assume the university had enough to go on,'' Ferris
said.
</P>
<P>
   Portland State head coach Tim Walsh, while prefacing his
comments by saying he's not aware violations did or did not occur,
said the school might have acted prematurely in asking for the
resignations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give (Ponciano) the benefit of the doubt,'' Walsh
said, ``because I know Ron.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh and Montana head coach Mick Dennehy agreed it was unusual
for a university to fire the head coach of a football program
before revealing its findings, as was the case with CSUN. Interim
university President Louanne Kennedy said the report, which will
detail Ponciano's specific misdeeds, won't be released for another
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the investigation is completed is kind of jumping the
gun a little bit,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferris, who worked at Southern Methodist for 13 years, was asked
about a school firing a coach before finishing an investigation.
``I've never seen anything like that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN athletic director Dick Dull said he supports Kennedy's
decision to fire Ponciano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically knew where the inquiry was going,'' Dull said. ``I
was involved. I had a role in (the firing). People really need to
wait until the report is released and draw the conclusion from
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano directed the Matadors to a 7-4 record last year,
including 5-3 and second place in the Big Sky. With the returning
talent _ Walsh said hardly anyone in the league matches CSUN's
athleticism _ CSUN could have been a top pick in the preseason
coaches' poll. The poll will be released today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they did a great job of recruiting,'' Walsh said.
``Athletically, there's no doubt they are a top-four team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy said CSUN is a wild card in the league race.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The players) are not going to roll over,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
