<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TACKLES AWKWARD POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ He didn't choke.
</P>
<P>
   Terrance Johnson made his first public comments since being
named the ``administrator-in-charge'' of the Cal State Northridge
football program, and he was put in the unenviable position of
making them in front of the Big Sky Conference head coaches and
media.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a part-time defensive-line coach for the Matadors last
season who was put in charge Friday when head coach Ron Ponciano
was fired, was uncomfortable _ at first _ during Monday's press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like the way Terrance is handling himself up here,''
said Montana head coach Mick Dennehy. ``He's doing and saying the
right things.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spoke in a professional manner, reading a list of the
Matadors' top players, including their height and weight each time.
He closed his seven-minute speech with optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan on representing our conference well this year,''
Johnson said after thanking CSUN athletic director Dick Dull for
giving him the chance to speak in Ponciano's place on the breakfast
program. ``We plan on making our presence felt in the Big Sky.
Nothing has changed, nothing will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This football team is one you need to watch out for,'' Johnson
said. ``You'll see an extraordinary effort. We're on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Interim only: Dull said Sunday night he plans to hire an interim
head coach for the season before seeking a full-time head coach for
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the California State system (the position) needs to be
advertised and you have to go through an interview process ... to
get a permanent coach,'' Dull said. ``We don't have time to do
that, so we're going to look on an interim basis to find somebody
with some stability that can provide stability for this program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the process of evaluating the interest that has been
provided to me by several people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the radio: The school reached an agreement Friday with
Antelope Valley-based radio station KUTY (1470-AM) to broadcast all
11 CSUN games this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Finney, CSUN's sports information director, said
negotiations are continuing with campus-based KCSN in becoming the
flagship station for Matadors football. The university's agreement
with KUTY and its sister station KRJJ is simple: Those stations
sell advertising, while non-profit KCSN does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``(With KCSN), we can't have bells and whistles,'' Finney said.
``We have to tweak our format a little to stay within their
(non-commercial) guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the air: The news wasn't so good for CSUN when FOX Sports
Net announced its 1999 Big Sky football schedule, which didn't
include the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Affeld, programming manager for FOX Sports Northwest, said
CSUN didn't fit into an attractive spot in the network's five-game
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The windows we had were really restrictive,'' Affeld said,
adding CSUN's in-house football investigation and Ponciano's firing
had nothing to do with CSUN being left off the air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
