<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-INDIANS-HN     07-20 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-INDIANS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It's getting to the point where coming to the Astrodome warrants a
permission slip from a physician. This is no place for the faint of
heart.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros won another nail-biter Monday night, scoring the
winning run on a wild pitch in a 3-2, 11-inning victory over the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleballer Tom Candiotti uncorked a wild pitch with the bases
loaded and Craig Biggio at the plate with no outs, allowing Bill
Spiers to hustle home with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had my `A' knuckler going tonight,'' Candiotti
said. ``That one just got away.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Astros' last four victories have come in their
final at-bat, and each of the five games since manager Larry
Dierker returned to the dugout have been decided by one or two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What little hair I have coming back is all coming out gray,''
said Dierker, who is undefeated since rejoining the team following
brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros extended their season-best winning streak to eight
games and pushed their National League Central Division lead to
three games over Cincinnati, which lost to Detroit for the second
day in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it is finding a way to win, and some of it is the
other team helping us,'' Dierker said. ``But most of it has been
really good pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Mike Hampton's lead from the previous day, Chris Holt
shut out the Indians for seven innings in his most impressive
outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who matched a season high by throwing 112 pitches, seemed
headed for his second victory until Indians All-Star Roberto Alomar
smacked a two-out, two-run homer off reliever Jay Powell to tie the
score at 2 in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   When the homer went out, Holt was denied a well-deserved
victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the third home run Powell has allowed in 43 innings
this season, and the first since San Francisco's Barry Bonds took
him deep April 13. The Indians had gone 16 consecutive scoreless
innings against Hampton, Holt and Powell before Alomar's homer,
which ended a string of 13 shutout innings for the Astros' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been getting Alomar all night with fastballs away and
down,'' Astros catcher Tony Eusebio said. ``That one was supposed
to be a sinker away, but it stayed right down the middle. I didn't
think he could hit it that far.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who held the Indians to four hits, retired 14 of the final
20 batters he faced and tallied six strikeouts before leaving.
Powell got pinch hitter Jacob Cruz to fly out to left field and
struck out Kenny Lofton to start the eighth before Omar Vizquel
singled up the middle, setting the table for Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for his pitch count, I probably would have let
Chris pitch the eighth inning,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he turned it over to the usually reliable Powell, who
had not allowed a run at the Astrodome since June 14.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar, known more for his glove than his power, homered to one
of the deepest parts of the building _ just to the left of
straightaway center field.
</P>
<P>
   Astros center fielder Glen Barker, who made two nifty plays
earlier in the game, climbed the wall Ken Griffey Jr.-style in an
attempt to rob Alomar and came within inches of making the
highlight reels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to catch it up until the time I missed
it,'' said Barker, making just his fourth start of the season and
second in as many days. ``He hit it right on the nose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros continue to set the standard in interleague play,
upping their record to 12-2. They are 22-6 against their
counterparts from the American League Central over the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo's two-run double in the third gave the Astros an
early lead, and _ perhaps more important _ it gave the struggling
outfielder hope that he still knows what to do with a pitch left up
in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, who has struggled with pitch selection, had only four
hits and three RBIs in his previous 32 at-bats. Hidalgo is 4-for-8
in his career against Indians starter Mark Langston, who walked six
batters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had Langston on the ropes in four of his six innings,
leaving the bases loaded twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get a lot of clutch hits,'' Astros shortstop Tim
Bogar said. ``If we were rolling on all cylinders, we would have
come through in those situations. But we battled through that, and
that's why we've been winning games.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest play of the Astros' winning rally may have been a
pinch-hit bunt by rookie Carlos Hernandez, who rejoined the club
from Class AAA New Orleans before Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Biggio said. ``Do you know how hard it is to
bunt a knuckleball?''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's bunt loaded the bases after Candiotti tried
unsuccessfully to throw out Spiers at third. Spiers walked to start
the inning, and Bogar was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to put it on the ground,'' Hernandez said.
``I wasn't trying to do anything special. It's hard not to bunt it
in the air when the ball is moving 100 times like that. It just
felt great to contribute to the win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' bullpen delivered 3 scoreless innings after Alomar's
home run, including a perfect 11th inning by Jose Cabrera, who
struck out Manny Ramirez, Richie Sexson and Jim Thome to earn the
win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
