<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-20 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT began badly, as it often does for Chris Holt. He walked Kenny
Lofton, the first man he faced. You sat there thinking, ``Oh, dear,
oh, my, here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Except this Chris-crinkling figured to be worse than usual
because these Clevelanders are no pikers in the run-producing
department. They have apparently mistaken the American League for a
Sunday-afternoon beer-league slow-pitch softball circuit. And
although Mike Hampton had bageled the Indians a day earlier with a
sublime four-hitter, that offered minimal comfort at best.
</P>
<P>
   Hampy's heroics _ arguably a more impressive artistic showing
than David Cone's same-day perfect game against the lowly Expos, if
we take into consideration the vast difference in the caliber of
the competition _ only figured to put the Indians in a crabby,
vindictive mood.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps Holt was just one bloop single shy of being routed
Monday night. Suppose the second little Indian, Omar Vizquel, had
snuck a bloop single into short center instead of being victimized
by Glen Barker's knees-first sliding bucket catch. The Indians
might still be batting as we speak. They are a team, remember, that
has scored at least 10 runs 16 times this year and 13 or more on
six occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland owns the majors' best record in no small part because
the Indians are averaging almost 6{ plate crossings per game,
baseball's most prodigious pace in nearly seven decades. They were
batting right at .300 as a team not long before the All-Star Game,
and five of their bats went to Boston for same.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros, who have themselves led the majors in ERA for
most of the season, dispatched three pitchers to Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, as it happened, the speedy Barker doubled up the
inexplicably streaking-for-home Lofton at second, and Roberto
Alomar's lazy fly to left ended the threat before it turned into
one. Six innings later, somewhat amazingly, Holt left with a nifty
four-hit shutout of his own intact, and the Astros ultimately,
albeit circuitously, wound up winning their eighth consecutive game
3-2. Two more W's, and they tie the franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   The winning run in the bottom of the 11th, most fittingly,
scored on a bases-loaded wild pitch by Tom Candiotti.
</P>
<P>
   The message in the aforementioned is clear and somewhat
axiomatic. Great pitching and defense will trump great hitting far
more often than vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you get a wee bit of hitting to go with it. The
Astros, as thin as they can possibly afford to be at the plate
these days, somehow made three singles and a two-run Richard
Hidalgo double stand up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we stress from the first day of spring training on
_ pitching and defense,'' said Larry Dierker, who remains unbeaten
(5-0) in his second incarnation as the Astros' manager after
undergoing brain surgery in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, this isn't brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always feel like we can score enough runs to beat
anybody,'' Dierker said. ``For us, it's going to come down to how
well we pitch and how many plays we make. For us to have the kind
of streak we've got going without having hit anywhere near as well
as we can because of all the people we're missing that says a lot
about how well we are doing the other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we've played tighter baseball than they (the Indians)
have. That's been the difference in the series. But no, I never
thought we would be holding their hitters down as effectively as we
have. I assumed we'd have to outscore them _ really outscore
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it stands Houston 5, Cleveland 2.
</P>
<P>
   Conceded Indians manager Mike Hargrove: ``This is the worst
(offensive) stretch we've had all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt may not be a ``great'' pitcher _ his 1-9 record sort of
gives him away on this count _ but he had it going perhaps like
never before against a Cleveland lineup that's being called a
latter-day Murderers Row. Not that Houston had seen a whit of
evidence of same until Alomar's eighth-inning home run off Jay
Powell landed in the center-field flowers barely beyond Barker's
reach.
</P>
<P>
   Until that unfortunate game-of-inches, game-tying moment, which
saddled the unlucky Holt with another no-decision, the Indians had
been as active as the cigar-store variety. Their linear linescore
for the pairing of the two leagues' respective Central Division
leaders now reads:
</P>
<P>
   000 000 000 000 000 020 00.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, back in front of their NL Central rivals by three
games, can go places with that kind of pitching. Places like the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Where they're liable, of course, to see the Indians again.
</P>
<P>
   In the AL, you see, there is no such thing as great pitching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
