<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE MISSION IS ABORTED 6 SECONDS BEFORE LAUNCHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating and rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ A last-second engine shutdown early
Tuesday dealt Air Force Col. Eileen Collins a temporary setback in
her drive to become the first woman to command a space shuttle
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Onboard computers halted the ignition sequence at 12:36 a.m.,
only 6.6 seconds before the shuttle Columbia was to have lifted off
its seaside Kennedy Space Center launch pad carrying Ms. Collins,
four other astronauts and a powerful $1.5 billion X-ray telescope.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts were in no immediate danger.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials said they were optimistic about the possibility
of a second launch attempt on Wednesday, but said Thursday was more
likely.
</P>
<P>
   The computers aborted the launching because sensors indicated an
abnormally high concentration of volatile hydrogen propellant in
the shuttle's aft engine compartment _ a potentially explosive
situation.
</P>
<P>
   The NASA launching commentator, Bruce Buckingham, said a
preliminary analysis indicated that one or more sensors might have
provided faulty readings to controllers in a firing room four miles
from the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at that situation right now to verify that,''
Buckingham said about 30 minutes after the abrupt shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers convened at 1:30 a.m. to study the problem. The
repairs, if the problem turned out to be so simple, would include
removing and replacing igniters that lit in the shuttle's three
main engines just prior to the cutoff. It is a two-day job.
</P>
<P>
   While ground crews drained the shuttle's 528,000-gallon external
fuel tank as a safety precaution, the five astronauts calmly went
about securing Columbia's cockpit before climbing out about an hour
after the shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Three liquid-fueled engines manufactured by Boeing's Rocketdyne
Propulsion and Power division in Canoga Park, Calif., power the
shuttle's nine-minute climb to orbit. They are designed to start at
120-millisecond intervals, 6.6 seconds prior to the ignition of the
shuttle's two solid-fueled booster rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The engines are controlled by computers that monitor their
performance 50 times a second during the startup sequence. If a
problem is detected, the computers can order an engine shutdown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There have been five previous shutdowns of this type in the
shuttle program. Three of those occurred in the post-Challenger
era. There were two in 1993 and one in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   This shutdown does not necessarily threaten the safety of the
shuttle crew, but hydrogen gas can be released through the engine
nozzle. Hydrogen burns without a visible sign of flame, and it is
possible that a brief fire on the launching pad can follow the
abort.
</P>
<P>
   But Buckingham said controllers had seen no indications of fire.
The launching pad is equipped with a sophisticated fire
extinguishing system that automatically starts spraying the orbiter
with water. Fire detection sensors are located all over the pad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
