<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS OFFENSE LETS DOWN HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ken Hill's elbow held up just fine in his
first start in nearly three weeks, but where he lacked support was
from his Anaheim Angels teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Hill pitched six scoreless innings, allowing only three hits.
But the offense scored only one run and the bullpen blew the lead
and eventually the game to the San Diego Padres 4-1 Monday in 10
innings before 25,217 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Rivera's two-out, three-run home run off Shigetoshi
Hasegawa in the 10th spoiled Hill's return and sent the Angels to
their fourth consecutive loss and sixth in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim trails first-place Texas by 9{ games in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his thoughts after the game, Angels manager Terry
Collins responded, ``they aren't good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a well-pitched game,'' Collins added. ``We just didn't
give Hill any help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels held a 1-0 lead through seven innings, but Mark
Petkovsek gave up a run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th, the Padres had runners on first and second with one
out when Eric Owens hit a chopper to Randy Velarde at second.
Instead of flipping to shortstop Gary DiSarcina at second to start
what might have been an inning-ending double play, Velarde tried to
tag Quilvio Veras coming from first.
</P>
<P>
   Veras backpedaled and avoided the tag before Velarde threw out
Owens at first. That gave Rivera a chance, and he delivered a
line-drive homer to left on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quilvio Veras did a hell of a job,'' Padres manager Bruce
Bochy said. ``That was the game right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was only in the game because Reggie Sanders was thrown
out after taking a called third strike in the eighth inning. He
threw sunflower seeds and candy on the field from the dugout and
was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Miceli (4-2) got the win over Hasegawa (1-4) and Trevor
Hoffman pitched the 10th to earn his 24th save.
</P>
<P>
   Hill looked good from the start, retiring the first five batters
he faced before a two-out walk to John Vander Wal in the second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the side in order in the fifth and got the first two
outs in the sixth before running into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Owens lined a single to center and Sanders followed with a
line-drive single to left. Hill then fell behind 2-0 Gwynn. But
Hill threw a called strike past Gwynn, then got him to ground into
a fielder's choice, ending the inning and his outing for the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' only run came in the fourth inning after Randy
Velarde led off with a double. He scored when Garret Anderson
ripped a ground-rule double into the right-field corner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
