<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 02:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6599 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BICKLEY_DIAMONDBA     07-20 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BICKLEY_DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW MUCH IS BUCK TO BLAME?  
 UNEASINESS GROWS WITH PICHING MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Second-guessing the manager is a guarded privilege of
all baseball fans, but in Arizona, it is fast becoming a cause.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no doubt that the honeymoon is over. And while Buck
Showalter claims ignorance to the rising tide of negative energy,
growing numbers of Diamondbacks fans are questioning his logic, his
style, his manner of handling a flammable bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, blaming a manager for a move that doesn't
work is an unexamined, knee-jerk response. After all, no one
remembers the subtle decisions that pay off. And no one can assume
that ``their'' alternative would bring a different result.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is true: With very few exceptions, Showalter's
recent bullpen maneuvering has resulted in disaster. And that has
only fueled the debate, spawning a faction of fans who actually
want Showalter fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has kind of happened all throughout baseball right now,''
Showalter said. ``The seventh, eighth and ninth innings have become
such a roll of the dice. Everybody is looking for normalcy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Showalter earned his nickname because of his
tremendous work ethic. His first manager, Ed Napoleon, claimed that
when he arrived at the park, Showalter was already there, buck
naked. When Napoleon headed for home, Showalter was still there,
buck naked, the last to leave. Hence, Buck.
</P>
<P>
   Which gives way to the critical question: Can a man so immersed
in detail, statistics and hours on the job lose his feel for the
game? Can he get so wrapped up in match-ups and pitch counts that
it shields him from the pulse of the sport?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Showalter didn't like the question and
adamantly denied the scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to use (statistics) to verify gut feelings,'' Showalter
said. ``You can't become prisoner to those things. I kind of
chuckle when I hear that (perception). I don't know how to work a
computer. I don't even know how to turn on one.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe that Showalter doesn't govern by numbers
or manage by the book, but that is his pledge. Whether you believe
him is your decision.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a recent night in Texas when Showalter yanked Randy
Johnson after eight scoreless innings, a move that precipitated a
bitter defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter was criticized because Johnson and the D-Backs are
starving for wins. Johnson's motto is to finish what you start. And
he claims Lou Piniella was the best manager he ever played for, in
part because he allowed Johnson to ``call my own game, whether I
want to come out or stay in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy has pitched more innings than anyone in baseball, and a
manager's top priority has to be the health of his people,''
Showalter said. ``I wish sometimes I was a little more callous to
the health of my players. Sure would make things a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter was criticized for anointing Gregg Olson as closer to
start the season, a reliever who had worked only a handful of
innings in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we tried to stick Vladimir Nunez in the fire from Day 1, he
probably wouldn't have been able to bring us (Matt) Mantei in a
trade,'' Showalter said. ``Because (Nunez) would've been horse
(expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter was criticized for allowing Byung-Hyun Kim to enter
his third inning of relief in Sunday's loss to the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I use Olson or (Greg) Swindell, I would've had no one left
for (Monday's) game,'' Showalter said. ``You have to look at the
big picture. That's the thing people can't identify with these jobs
the players, coaches and managers have. The everyday part of it.
When the players get frustrated, I tell them they've got to get
over thinking that you're going to get someone to understand what
you go through.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Showalter has a talent for rationalization. But in his
defense, he doesn't have a lot to work with. It is not his fault
that Darren Holmes can't pitch on successive days or that Dan
Plesac no longer can retire right-handed hitters or that Kim once
balked away a game.
</P>
<P>
   It is a players game, and managers get too much credit when a
team wins, too much blame when they don't.
</P>
<P>
   But the really good managers _ the ones who really feel the
pulse of the game _ know how to shake a team out of a swoon, know
the right buttons to push. While Showalter isn't the problem, he
hasn't been the solution, either. And in Arizona, the critics only
get louder. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 0255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
