2001, when the maquiladoras will lose their 35-year-old tariff
exemption for materials imported from Asia. Hatamiya and leading
California lawmakers predict that the state's factories will win
lucrative new contracts selling components to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But maquiladora executives say California shouldn't get its
hopes up. ``People are dreaming if they think California's going to
take over Asia's role as supplier,'' said Douglas Allday, president
of the Western Maquiladora Trade Association in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say the real success or failure of the Davis
administration's new strategy of seeking trade and friendship with
Mexico will depend on whether it can foster real, job-creating
exports to Mexico's domestic consumers rather than simply selling
to maquiladoras.
</P>
<P>
   Other big challenges to the cross-border relationship include a
wide range of social problems that in past years rarely received
government attention:
</P>
<P>
   -- Pollution: Toxic wastes discharged illegally from some
Tijuana maquiladoras pollute both nations' waterways. Although new
sewage treatment plants have been built on each side of the border,
Mexico's enforcement of its own environmental laws is poor.
</P>
<P>
   -- Education: Tens of thousands of children of migrant families
who crisscross the border in search of work are hindered from
advancing in school because Mexican and Californian school
districts cannot properly assess their grade levels. During Davis'
trip to Mexico in February, Mexican officials offered a plan for
``school cards,'' which would transfer class credits across the
border. The proposal is still being considered in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jobs and wages: San Diego County's economy is growing by 4.5
percent a year, one of the fastest rates in the state, but there's
a dark side: 19 percent of the population lives below the poverty
level, and the gap between high-income and low-income earners has
widened alarmingly. Experts say the trend's causes include the
weakness of labor unions and the oversupply of Mexican immigrants
willing to work for low wages.
</P>
<P>
   Baja California's economy depends on maquiladoras, which employ
44 percent of the salaried workforce. Wages in this sector average
less than $10 per day, despite consumer prices nearly as high as
California's.
</P>
<P>
   -- Labor rights: The maquiladora companies and Mexican city,
state and federal governments have an unofficial policy of banning
the formation of independent labor unions, saying they would damage
the investment climate. Californian and Mexican unions say this
violates Mexico's obligations under the North American Free Trade
Agreement and lowers wages on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   -- Highways, railroads, ports and airports: Moving merchandise
in the border area is slowed by poor infrastructure. Even on the
U.S. side of Otay Mesa, the main border cargo crossing, trucks must
navigate miles of city streets with frequent stoplights before they
reach interstate highways. A plan to upgrade the route to a freeway
has been delayed for years because of a lack of funds. The Davis
administration is planning to spend $1 billion in state and federal
funds on this and other border projects.
</P>
<P>
   -- Regional planning. For many years, there has been little
cross-border coordination between local governments. Analysts say
the lack of contact has been severe since 1995, when then-Governor
Pete Wilson eliminated funding for the Commission of the
Californias, a panel of officials from California, Baja California
and Baja California Sur that promoted economic, educational and
cultural relations. Davis has revived funding for the commission
and has made it a priority of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk about cross-border communication, but
it's very difficult, and we are still very different cultures,''
said Carlos Graizbord, director of Tijuana's city planning office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, when I want to solve some border-related problem, I have
to make dozens of calls,'' he said, motioning to the two telephones
on his desk. ``I have to talk with each of the 20 city governments
in the San Diego area, and this wastes lots of time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, where municipal officials are limited to three-year
terms with no re-election, economic planning usually consists of
mere political one-upmanship. For example, Tijuana planner
Graizbord took office in January and proceeded to discard a
development plan made by his predecessor _ who had done the same
when entering office, as had his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The region's promise will fizzle if Tijuana fails to change its
ways, said Enrique Mier y Teran, a Tijuana industrial park owner
who has long been the border region's chief booster and strategist.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Dijuana has it all for the 21st century _ the fiber
optics, satellites, transport, the convergence, the location. But
soon, ghosts will appear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tijuana has way outstripped our infrastructure. We need water,
public transportation, an expanded airport, better highways, a
railroad. We'll need research and development, and
industrialization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we haven't done any of that yet. We're still
mostly just cheap labor.''
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California _ which accounts for 85 percent of the
state's Mexico trade _ many analysts say the steady shifting of
jobs to Mexico's maquiladoras has worsened the divide between rich
and poor.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing employment in San Diego has shown slight growth in
recent years, buoyed by the economic boom, after a dramatic
downturn in the early 1990s. But in the Bay Area, which has been
hit hard by the Asian crisis as well as by job loss to the
maquiladoras, the number of manufacturing jobs fell last year by
1.8 percent, a decrease of 9,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, many firms are moving their plants to Mexico.
On June 25, IBM and Matsushita Electric Works announced that they
were laying off 1,300 manufacturing workers in Silicon Valley and
moving much of the work to maquiladoras in Mexicali and
Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term projections show that California's white-collar
sectors such as entertainment, communications technology and
biotech will continue growing rapidly. Meanwhile, more factory jobs
will be shifted to Mexico's maquiladoras _ a process that some
politicians will tout as ``trade'' and others will call low-wage
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot hope to keep low-value-added production in the
United States,'' said Raul Hinojosa, a trade policy expert at the
University of California at Los Angeles and a member of the state
World Trade Commission, an advisory panel to the Trade and Commerce
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, there's a major crisis looming on the horizon.
What are we going to do with this huge Latino labor force that has
been brought to the state over the past 25 years or so to work in
low-wage manufacturing in Southern California, but which now finds
that because of the incredible competition from Mexico and Asia,
that kind of manufacturing is inviable here?''
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa said the federal, state and local governments cannot
expect market forces to provide a solution by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must adopt a conscious strategy to upgrade, to recognize
the inevitability of job loss and make sure jobs are created for
those people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
