<HEADER>
A6604 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEANUP-ENVIRONMENTAL     07-20 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEANUP-ENVIRONMENTAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAFTA'S PROVISIONS IMPROVE ENVIRONMENT BUT POLLUTION PERSISTS  &HT;     BY ROBERT COLLIER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Tijuana River empties into the Pacific Ocean
here, and most of the liquid flowing between its banks is water.
</P>
<P>
   That is news.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is the river simply a toxic mix of raw sewage and
industrial wastes, polluting ocean waters and beaches for many
miles to the north and south.
</P>
<P>
   Large new sewage treatment facilities have been built on both
sides of the border, in a path-breaking attempt by the U.S. and
Mexican governments to join forces to clean up the border area's
chronic environmental mess.
</P>
<P>
   Their work has a long way to go, however. The river, which
crosses the border from Mexico about six miles from the ocean,
still is foul-smelling and carries plenty of sewage dumped
illegally from Tijuana's shantytowns and maquiladoras.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed record shows both the success and failure of the North
American Free Trade Agreement's environmental side accord, which
was billed as the solution for the border's pollution problem.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say progress has been blocked by Mexico's erratic _ and
in some cases nonexistent _ enforcement of environmental laws. They
say that although large firms like Sony usually are law-abiding,
many smaller maquiladoras are big polluters.
</P>
<P>
   In Tijuana, for example, huge piles of an estimated 6,000 tons
of lead slag and sulfuric acid are exposed to the elements at
Metales y Derivados, an abandoned battery recycling plant owned by
San Diego-based New Frontier Trading Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The poisonous mess gives the air at the plant a bitter,
breath-shortening tang. Nearby neighborhoods' water supplies may be
contaminated, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   Since the plant closed in 1994, the government has done nothing
to clean up the site, and it has done no studies of possible lead
poisoning of the local population.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, residents took the case to the Commission for
Environmental Cooperation, a tribunal in Montreal created by the
NAFTA side accord, but the proceedings are moving at a glacial
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the dark side of NAFTA,'' said Cesar Luna, an attorney
with the San Diego-based Environmental Health Coalition, which has
helped local residents file their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of danger to the public shouldn't be allowed in
Mexico or the United States or anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The bright side is the North American Development Bank
(NADBank), an environmental fund created through NAFTA. NADBank's
funds have helped leverage financing for major sewage-treatment and
water-supply projects along the border from the Pacific to the Gulf
of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of progress include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Tijuana's sewage. The $400 million South Bay International
Treatment Plant in San Diego, completed in 1997, treats an average
of 25 million gallons per day of Tijuana's sewage and discharges it
into the Pacific. However, the plant's effluent has failed to meet
U.S. federal standards, thus requiring the construction of more
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Mexico started work on a $20 million upgrading of
Tijuana's only sewage facility, at San Antonio de los Buenos. Most
of the funds were grants from the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency and from NADBank.
</P>
<P>
   -- San Diego's sewage. The South Bay Water Reclamation Plant
will rescue San Diego's severely overburdened sewage treatment
system. It is scheduled for completion in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   -- Brawley and Calexico water treatment plants. NADBank has
given $7.5 million in grants and loans to build badly needed
facilities to purify the severely polluted water supplies in these
Imperial Valley towns.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the border area's pollution occurs on the
Mexico side, the United States shares a big part of the blame, some
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just Mexico's problem, but a problem of the whole
binational maquiladora system, in which the environment is
deliberately sacrificed to create a favorable investment climate,''
Luna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to pollute without having to worry about real
enforcement of the laws saves these companies money, and neither
government has really tried to put a stop to that.''
</P>
<P>
   In total, NADBank has given $24.8 million in grants and $1
million in loans to California projects, and $16 million in grants
and $2.5 million in loans to Baja California projects. However,
these amounts are far below expectations _ and far below the $3
billion that the U.S. government estimates is needed for new
wastewater and treatment plants along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Luna and other critics say NADBank's work has been slowed by its
insistence on rigorous, top-level credit standards _ an unrealistic
requirement for Mexico's revenue-poor border cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis administration says it is working with the Mexican
federal, state and local governments to develop a plan to clean up
the border.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the California Environmental Protection Agency
recently announced a program to train hazardous-waste inspectors
from the Baja California and Tijuana governments to help them
identify and deal with pollution problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
