<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 03:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAQUILADORA-DEFINED-S     07-20 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAQUILADORA-DEFINED-SFCHRON(SIDEBAR </SLUG>
 W/BORDER)  
 HWHAT ARE MAQUILADORAS?  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Under a program started in 1966, Mexico's maquiladoras are assembly
plants that import their materials duty-free, then export the
finished products. Most maquiladoras are near the U.S. border, but
some have opened recently in the Mexican interior. The maquiladora
program was largely overridden by the 1994 North American Free
Trade Agreement and is scheduled to expire in 2001 _ but the term
is expected to remain widely used for export-only assembly plants.
Other aspects of maquiladoras include:
<P>
   -- Fast growth: Maquiladoras were scarce until the mid-1980s,
when Mexico's economic policies shifted from protectionism and
support for domestic industry to free trade and support for foreign
investors. Now, Mexico has more than 3,200 maquiladoras and 1.1
million maquiladora workers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Low pay: Although the wages in maquiladoras are higher than
average Mexican wages, they are generally only $8 to $10 per day.
U.S. and Asian companies say they save big money by locating
production facilities in Mexico rather than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   -- Criticism: U.S. opponents say that maquiladoras cause the
loss of U.S. jobs, routinely violate Mexican workers' democratic
labor rights and pollute the environment.
</P>
<P>
   -- Praise: Industry supporters say the maquiladoras create jobs
in U.S. plants that supply the maquiladoras, thereby increasing the
cost-effectiveness of American production and helping U.S. firms
remain competitive worldwide. Backers also say any U.S. jobs that
may have been lost to Mexican workers would otherwise have been
lost to even lower-wage workers in Asia or Central America.
</P>
<P>
   -- Role in Mexico's economy: Supporters have long said the
maquiladoras would help Mexico industrialize by introducing new
technology and buying components from local manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mexican government's low spending on technological
research and its focus on pleasing foreign investors may have
prevented that from happening. Only about 2 percent of all parts
used by maquiladoras are Mexican-made, and although Mexico's
manufacturing base has stagnated in recent years, maquiladora
production has soared to 81 percent of the nation's exports to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico hasn't used the maquiladoras in the same way as Asia
did after World War II,'' said Charles Nathanson, executive
director of San Diego Dialogue, a binational think tank on border
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, Taiwan, South Korea and others were known for cheap,
low-wage, labor-intensive assembly work then, he said. But unlike
Mexico, ``they also had comprehensive policies linking government,
the private sector and academia to help industrialize. And look at
them now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
