<HEADER>
A6764 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGAWY-IN-CUBA-NYT     07-20 3453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGAWY-IN-CUBA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERNEST HEMINGWAY IN CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By D.T. MAX  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    When he was in his mid-20s and searching quite deliberately for
the style that would transform American fiction, Ernest Hemingway
got this reminder from Gertrude Stein: ``Hemingway, remarks aren't
literature.''
 &HT;    That remark came back to me while reading ``True at First
Light,'' the writer's unfinished fictional memoir, published with a
great deal of hype this month (July).
 &HT;    The Hemingway sound is still there _ that unmistakable rhythm _
but there is something off-putting about the story of the 1953
safari the writer went on with his fourth wife, Mary Welsh.
 &HT;    It's as if Hemingway felt that anything that caught his
attention in the bush was worth writing down. You feel as if every
time Hemingway turns his back, Mary and the local hunters can't
wait to escape from his camp and get out of his sight.
 &HT;    What happened to the writer of the austere ``The Sun Also
Rises,'' the beautiful and sardonic ``A Farewell to Arms''? When
did being Hemingway get in the way of Hemingway the writer?
 &HT;    Creativity is ultimately a mystery, dissolving into the
metaphysics of personality and talent. Still, you can narrow
Fitzgerald's collapse to the '30s, when he was overwhelmed by
Zelda's mental illness, or Faulkner's decline to the '40s, when he
dissipated himself while writing screenplays for Hollywood.
Hemingway himself followed their slides with hardnosed interest.
Perhaps you could do the same, in gentler fashion, with him.
 &HT;    Scholars conventionally ascribe Hemingway's creative dissolution
to drinking and depression, but to me that has always seemed too
simple.
 &HT;    Since World War I, when Hemingway volunteered as an ambulance
driver on the Italian front, he was always drinking and frequently
depressed. In this era, he wrote his best books. He thrived on rest
and then battle. While his tolerance for this up-down lifestyle
lessened over the years, it wasn't what made him fall apart.
 &HT;    He fell apart in the early '40s, on 15 lush acres in Cuba.
Having triumphed with ``For Whom the Bell Tolls'' (1940), Hemingway
left the literary world and moved to the tropics.
 &HT;    As newly released documents from the period _ private letters,
declassified FBI files and other sources _ reveal, he isolated
himself from anyone who knew him as he really was. He confused his
fantasy self (a man of action) with his real self (a man who wrote
about action).
 &HT;    As World War II heated up, he embarked on a parody of his
previous wartime adventures. He formed a ``spy ring,'' which
uncovered little, and chased U-boats with a fishing boat. For
months at a stretch, Hemingway piloted through empty Cuban coastal
waters in search of a whale he would never catch.
 &HT;    Playing these war games, Hemingway stopped writing for the first
time in his career. A short-story collection he promised his
editor, Max Perkins, fell away. Various ideas failed to turn into
actual novels. For 10 years, he published no new fiction.
 &HT;    Finca Vigia, Hemingway's Cuban home, is in the small hill town
of San Francisco de Paula, 10 miles from Havana. Now called the
Museo Hemingway and run by the Cuban government, it is a shrine to
Papa. Each magazine and gin bottle remains where he left it when he
left Cuba in 1960 to sit out the revolution that brought Fidel
Castro to power.
 &HT;    He committed suicide at his second home, in Ketchum, Idaho, in
July 1961, but the Finca waits. The Schweppes inside the tonic
bottles has mostly evaporated, but the caps are still on.
 &HT;    There was an intense thunderstorm under way on the day I arrived
in June, the reverberations knocking the mangoes from the trees.
Tourists can look into the house only from outside, but as a
foreign journalist, I was given a full tour once the rain let up.
 &HT;    Inside the graceful Spanish-colonial building, I saw the study
where Gary Cooper slept on the couch because the beds were too
short for him and the pool where Ava Gardner swam naked. Next to it
were the gravestones of Hemingway's four dogs _ Negrita, Linda,
Black and Neron.
 &HT;    The Cuban government presents the house as Hemingway's private
paradise, but I didn't see it that way. Nothing hurts a writer more
than not being able to write as well as he once did, especially
when the writer is as competitive as Hemingway.
 &HT;    The eight-room house had four separate places to write: a study,
a library, his bedroom equipped with his Royal typewriter and an
office in an adjoining tower (built by Mary in 1947). It was set up
for writing. Hemingway's failure to do so must have been difficult
for him to endure.
 &HT;    Just outside the house lay his escape: the Pilar, Hemingway's
beloved 40-foot fishing boat. In 1973, the Cuban government pulled
the Pilar out of the harbor at Cojimar and placed it on blocks at
the Finca. It is now shielded by a plastic roof.
 &HT;    I knew that Hemingway essentially retreated to the Pilar during
the first three years of World War II, first to fish and get away
from his third wife, the journalist and author Martha Gellhorn,
then to conduct his clandestine military operations.
 &HT;    The Pilar's black oak was still polished to his standards. The
fighting chair, which he never sat in _ he caught his fish standing
up, the same way he wrote _ was waiting for the next fisherman. Up
on the flying bridge, you could see a copy of the drinks rack where
Hemingway lodged his hand grenades.
 &HT;    Gregory Hemingway, 67, the youngest son of the writer, lives in
southern Florida. In an interview, he said that his father had an
irrevocable crisis during the war years.
 &HT;    ``There was a real sea change in him,'' he recalled. ``There was
so much defensive stuff about how great the next book was going to
be that I got the feeling that he definitely thought he'd lost
it.''
 &HT;    Gregory remembered him taking it out on Gellhorn, whom Hemingway
married in 1940. She was a convenient target. She was his peer, his
competitor, in some ways his double. In his letters to her, which
were unsealed last year after her death, Hemingway sometimes calls
her ``brother.''
 &HT;    She was also the wrong wife for a man in turmoil. Gellhorn, like
Hemingway, was substantial. She was solidly built and smoked 40
cigarettes a day. Human frailty did not fit into her worldview. She
once wrote Hemingway that she could never respect the kind of men
``that must have women lick their wounds and flatter them.''
 &HT;    Soon after their wedding, as he struggled on with his story
collection, she accepted an assignment to cover the submarine war
in the Caribbean for Collier's. (She was also working on a novel
set in the Caribbean called ``Liana'' and wanted local details.) He
was furious at the news. Abandonment was upsetting enough, but wars
were his business.
 &HT;    With Martha gone, Hemingway grew anxious at the Finca. The newly
unsealed letters show him writing her often, badgering her to write
back and keeping her up to date on the household, often in
unintentionally comic ways. (``The thing about servants like Luis
is that they've been at it so long they lose their aficion.'')
 &HT;    He complained that an introduction to a war anthology he was
working on was the ``most awful no good piece of writing I've ever
done.'' He had wanted to make a clean statement about the stupidity
of the politicians who had caused the current war, but the
intensity of his convictions made the article hard to finish.
 &HT;    He soon came to feel that writing about the war was beside the
point. He had to do something. A solution presented itself in the
form of the new American ambassador to Cuba, Spruille Braden. He
was a round-faced man with a winning smile and a nice word for
everyone. Braden was status-conscious, Hemingway was famous and the
two men became friends.
 &HT;    Soon the idea came up that Hemingway's wide contacts on the
island might make him useful in regard to Cuba's Falangist problem.
Falangists were Spanish fascists. The American government was
worried that some were in Cuba, signaling the location of American
ships to U-boats and helping German agents infiltrate the island.
 &HT;    Approaching Hemingway was not as odd as it might seem. In those
years, and later, during the Cold War, the U.S. government
frequently asked prominent citizens traveling abroad to report back
on what they saw. Journalists, celebrities and the well-connected
had an excellent cover for going everywhere and looking at
everything. (The O.S.S. was jokingly said to stand for ``Oh So
Social.'')
 &HT;    Indeed, Hemingway had been pressed into service once before. A
declassified O.S.S. document gives a new explanation for a putative
vacation Hemingway and Gellhorn took to Mexico City in 1942.
Hemingway was asked to look into raising a private army of Spanish
Republican exiles to ship to the North African front. He evaluated
the situation and reported back, but the project went no further.
 &HT;    Hemingway liked Braden's offer. He thought of himself as a
natural spy. Intelligence work was like researching a novel you
didn't have to write.
 &HT;    What's more, it would give Hemingway a chance to be a patriot _
and trump Martha in the process. She had researched an article
about the Falangists for Collier's, and the editors had rejected
it. He would show her how it was done.
 &HT;    Braden's code name for the group was the Crime Shop. Hemingway
nicknamed it the Crook Factory. Quickly, Agent 08 _ as Hemingway
rechristened himself _ got to work.
 &HT;    His ``spy ring'' was a cross section of his social circle: a
bartender from his favorite bar, the Floridita; various wharf rats,
and several Basques who fled Spain when Franco won. The unruly
crowd showed up at all hours at the Finca, which they used as their
headquarters.
 &HT;    In one newly unsealed letter to Martha, then on assignment for
Collier's, he captures the atmosphere of a Crook Factory meeting:
``We were just twenty-one ... and twenty-four bottles of wine were
drunk. ... Tommy Shevlin sang some wonderful songs and everybody
threw bottles at Fernando as a form of applause. Chairs were thrown
to express disapproval. ... Thorwald had taken the pistol of the
soldado, who had fallen asleep, and was firing it. ... Juan was hit
on the ear by a loaf of bread and rendered hors du combat. ... It
was an all time high in Basque celebrations.''
 &HT;    Little of use came out of the Crook Factory, which at one point
consisted of six full-time operatives and 20 part-timers. The FBI,
as allergic to competition as Papa was, used its staff to discredit
Hemingway's.
 &HT;    Hemingway announced that Gen. Manuel Benitez, the chief of
police, was training his officers to seize power while Braden and
President Fulgencio Batista were in Washington. The FBI pointed out
that it had agents at Police Headquarters who had seen nothing
unusual.
 &HT;    A Hemingway operative brought in a suspicious box from the Bar
Basque in Havana; the FBI had the box opened and found only a copy
of ``The Life of Saint Teresa.'' A declassified June 1943 memo
reflects the agents' exasperation: Hemingway was just bringing in
his operatives' dispatches with a cover note, not even trying to
investigate their validity or place them in context. He would do
anything, it seems, but write.
 &HT;    J. Edgar Hoover followed Hemingway's operations with bemusement.
He sardonically noted in a memo to two staff members that
Hemingway's ``judgment is not of the best'' and that if he was
drinking as much as he had been ``some years ago,'' Braden was
foolish to use him.
 &HT;    Hoover grew worried, however, when Hemingway told an informant
that he was going to write a book about Braden, his intelligence
work and the FBI.
 &HT;    Consequently, FBI radiograms flew back and forth following
Hemingway's moves, as agents tried to determine if he was putting
pen to paper about his spying adventures. Hoover was probably
relieved when an agent reported that Hemingway had acknowledged
that he was ``doing no writing whatsoever at the present time.''
 &HT;    In April 1943, with FBI prodding, the embassy closed down the
Crook Factory. Hemingway didn't care. He had already found himself
a newer, better assignment: submarine chasing under the sponsorship
of the Office of Naval Intelligence (ONI). Although the threat of
German U-boats off Cuban waters was already subsiding, Hemingway
still saw a chance to make his mark on the war.
 &HT;    An aristocratic-looking cabin cruiser, the Pilar was hardly a
boat to take on a 1,000-ton U-boat. Because real, mounted
antiaircraft guns were too heavy for the Pilar's stern, the crew
had to limit itself to Thompson submachine guns, antitank weapons
and those hand grenades in the drinks holder.
 &HT;    For his crew, Hemingway surrounded himself with friends,
including Winston Guest, a millionaire polo player; two Basque
jai-alai players nicknamed Paxtchi and Sinsky, and a dour Catalan
sergeant named Fernando Mesa. The only professional among them was
a Marine communications expert named Don Saxon, who carried around
a submarine listening device known to Hemingway only as ``the
gadget.''
 &HT;    Hemingway obtained a letter from the U.S. Embassy to explain his
activity. Still in the archives of the Finca, it states that he was
conducting scientific experiments with ``a radio apparatus.'' This
didn't quite accord with the American Museum of Natural History
sign he had hung as cover on deck.
 &HT;    Hemingway's sub-hunting strategy recalled the adventure books he
read as a teen-ager. He imagined that German U-boats would spot the
Pilar, surface and come aboard to commandeer its fresh fruit and
fish. Once the U-boat opened its hatch, one of the jai-alai players
would toss a jury-rigged bomb down the narrow opening.
 &HT;    Martha quite rightly warned Hemingway that if they ever did lob
a bomb down a sub hatch, they would all be killed in the explosion.
She berated his ``shaming and silly life,'' which she saw as an
excuse to go fishing with government gasoline and avoid his
typewriter.
 &HT;    But he had found his war. His squad practiced shooting and
throwing grenades at wooden targets with faces painted on them,
which they called ``Hitlers,'' and practiced boarding procedures
and tossing incendiary devices down an imaginary hatch.
 &HT;    Military readiness was slow in coming, as an unpublished passage
from Hemingway's log shows: ``Left Cabanas at 8:30. Out 6 miles for
practice _ Win(ston) erratic _ Paxtchi same _ Fernando N.G. (no
good) Win bothered by gas in stomach _ Fernando stood ground swell
OK. Into Bahia Honda 1 pm.''
 &HT;    Patrick Hemingway, 71, the writer's middle son, sometimes
accompanied his father on the Pilar, much to Gellhorn's
consternation. When I reached him in Montana to ask about this
period, he compared his father to Don Quixote. ``He was losing the
ability to deal with reality,'' he remembered. ``He was just going
crazy trying to make the world better and more pattern-satisfying
than it was.''
 &HT;    On Dec. 9, 1942, with the crew still learning to hit targets,
the Pilar's moment came. Hemingway watched through his ``ten-power
Zeiss glasses'' as a Spanish steamer, the Marques de Comillas,
slowed down in the waters off the north coast, as if for a
rendezvous. Shortly after, he spotted a low gray craft approaching
with a tow.
 &HT;    In a report to the embassy's ONI attache, proudly entitled
``Submarine Sighted on December 9th,'' Hemingway reported that the
Pilar had closed for the kill ``at a trawling speed of seven knots
with lines out from both outriggers to simulate big game fishing.''
At this moment, as they prepared the ``anti-submarine
installations'' (explosives inserted in a fire-extinguisher
canister), something unlucky happened.
 &HT;    ``While we were headed directly toward her a large baracuda
(sic) of 48 pounds hit one of the outrigger baits,'' Hemingway
wrote. While the crew tried to land the fish, the vessel steamed
away.
 &HT;    That was it. Despite not being certain he had seen a submarine,
Hemingway sent the ONI a theory worthy of Simenon, his favorite
mystery writer: ``It would have been possible, due to the ships
encountering each other at the hour of the noon-day meal, for Axis
agents to have been put overboard during the time that passengers
were in the dining saloon without such an operation being any more
noticed, if the men were lowered from a hatch close to the
waterline than would be the picking up or dropping of a pilot under
the same circumstances.''
 &HT;    The FBI later interviewed all the passengers and discredited the
scenario, much to Hemingway's frustration.
 &HT;    In two-month stints over the next year, Hemingway and his crew
kept on patrolling, often 18 hours a day. Occasionally, a trawler
or fishing boat would pass, and Hemingway would note it in his log
alongside the crew's poker scores.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, Martha finished ``Liana.'' This sandbagged Hemingway.
During a visit to the Finca, he told Gregory that he was going to
quit writing. ``Let's give Marty a chance _ she deserves one,'' he
said.
 &HT;    In a letter to Gellhorn, Hemingway rationalized things: ``It is
enough of a job to keep everybody's morale up and get the work done
without having to write about it.''
 &HT;    The Pilar's orders ran out in July 1943. Despite Hemingway's
efforts, the Navy wouldn't renew them. Papa closed down the
operation and settled back down at the Finca, only to find Gellhorn
moving ahead on her next project: covering the war in England for
Collier's.
 &HT;    Eventually, Hemingway followed Martha to England, becoming
Collier's front-line war correspondent and her boss. He put himself
through extraordinary, foolhardy risks in France, refusing to duck
when snipers fired or when a shell struck near him. He told his
military friends that fighting Germans was the best job he had ever
had. He seemed a man determined to find death.
 &HT;    Yet when the war ended, he returned to the Finca to write _
though not before blaming Gellhorn, who left him in 1944, for his
difficulty writing.
 &HT;    In the guest bedroom at the Finca, I came upon a copy of
Gellhorn's 1948 war novel, ``The Wine of Astonishment,'' untouched
for 40 years. It was inscribed from Gellhorn: ``For the greatest of
critics ... with the best wishes of his knowing admirer.'' Behind
it was Hemingway's angry response: ``Dear author, Why don't you be
a nice good character and ... ship me my papers, so I can write
another fine book and autograph it for you? The Other Author.''
 &HT;    With great effort he began new work. In 1950, he published
``Across the River and Into the Trees'' _ his first novel written
in Cuba. The critics were savage. He would not easily be brought
down, however. A book, he liked to remind himself, was a battle,
not a war.
 &HT;    He succeeded in finding his voice again briefly with ``The Old
Man and the Sea'' (1952). But ``Across the River'' and ``Old Man''
were sections of a trilogy that never came together; the rest was
published posthumously in 1970 as ``Islands in the Stream,'' in
which his fruitless naval patrols were given a nobler fictional
aspect as a battle against a U-boat crew in which his alter ego,
Thomas Hudson, dies.
 &HT;    Moreover, he was beaten, as he might have put it, by two
unfinished books _ ``The Garden of Eden,'' published in 1986, and
then by ``True at First Light.'' Something had changed in his
relation to his material. What had for so long fed his art _ his
outsize will _ now deformed it.
 &HT;    Shortly after his block began, Hemingway wrote to Martha, ``I
suppose if you are a writer you're a writer till you die or it
dies.'' He knew what had happened, and he knew there was nothing he
could do.
 &HT;    One of the first stories he began upon his return to Cuba was
called ``The Faker.'' It was the story of a man returning from the
war pretending to be a hero. He never finished it.
 &HT;     c.1999 D.T. Max  
