<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6805 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEYOND-BARS21-TAKE1-C     07-20 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEYOND-BARS21-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Behind bars, mother-child reunions
 &HT;    (EDS: TAKE 1 OF 2 TAKES. ATTN: TEXAS EDITORS. ART AVAILABLE.)
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A wall phone rings shrilly, and seven women in
blue state jail uniforms spread out along vast windows. Their noses
nearly touch the panes of ceiling-to-rail glass, their eyes riveted
on an electronically locked door in the next building.
</P>
<P>
   A staccato buzz fills the room, and the women lean in. The heavy
door clicks open, and their daughters walk out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I didn't know she was coming. Look at her,'' says one
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my baby,'' says another.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's pretty,'' comments a third.
</P>
<P>
   The second door swings open, and mothers and nine daughters rush
to be together. They share tight hugs, soft kisses and rapid-fire
talk: Hi Mama. Hey baby. Look at that hair! Let me see those nails.
What are you wearing? What's for dinner? Mom, did I tell you that
... Mothers slowly stroke their daughters' hair and faces.
Daughters rub their mothers' arms and shoulders; they smile as they
talk, and their mothers smile back.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday meeting of Girl Scout Troop 1500 has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Missed moments
</P>
<P>
   Marisa was 31 when she was arrested the last time. She'd been
tangling with the law for years; this time she pulled a 15-month
sentence for drug-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in a dormitory jail cell, her days regimented by
life-skills classes, jail chores, strict meal times and counseling
sessions. Beyond the bars and living with family are her children:
Clarisa, 8, and a married teen-age daughter. (The last names of the
mothers and daughters are not used to protect the children's
identities.)
</P>
<P>
   Marisa has missed chunks of her daughters' lives. She wasn't at
the hospital when her older daughter gave birth. She was left out
of the summertime ritual of walking her daughters to the
neighborhood swimming pool. And she had to witness her baby girl
grow into a confident third-grader from the confines of the Travis
County Community Justice Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me she's still a little girl, but she's growing up,'' says
Marisa, with a sad but proud smile.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Mom is behind bars until August, Marisa and
Clarisa are together every other week because of an innovative Girl
Scout program that is new to Central Texas. The troop is aimed at
building a bond between girls and their mothers in jail.
Nationally, there are about 18 troops like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Jail officials recommend inmates for the program, and once the
mothers agree to participate, the Lone Star Girl Scout Council
approaches school-age daughters' guardians. If the guardians, and
the daughters, agree _ and some don't _ parent and child join the
troop. The first mother-daughter meeting was in October. Since
then, 11 mothers and their 13 daughters have participated in the
biweekly meetings at the state jail.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings of Troop 1500 have brought Clarisa back into her
mother's arms. ``There are things the Girl Scouts is really
bringing out that I never knew,'' says Marisa.
</P>
<P>
   The mother says she gets the most surprising things in the mail
from Clarisa. She sends her homework, complete with the teacher's
grades and comments; short letters and drawings with just mother
and daughter in the scene. But it is the first letter that still
makes her mother cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this white piece of paper; it was folded. I opened it
and saw the cursive writing. Clarisa loves to write in cursive. It
was a letter, only a few lines. It was signed, 'I loved you with
all my brain' Clarisa.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clarisa's schoolteacher, Virginia Lewis, says she has seen a
marked difference since her student joined the troop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her self-confidence is up, she's relaxed and is able to
concentrate,'' said Lewis. ``She's not nearly as anxious or as
needy for attention and approval as she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mom is the most important influence in her life. She has a
hunger for her mother's love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm finally being a mother,'' said Marisa. She
says she has learned how to handle Clarisa's extreme moods,
especially her temper tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to beg her to behave, but I've learned that she'll come
around sooner if I ease off, let her be. She sees it's not getting
her any attention, she stops. I had to learn that in here. I didn't
know about patience; I didn't have much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, mother and daughter set patience goals together. The
latest: growing fingernails. Clarisa is a heavy nail biter, but she
wants nails, and her mother decided to lead by example.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I let my nails grow, she would do the same,'' says Marisa.
``And she's doing it. I tell her how pretty her nails are now, and
she says mine look good, too; she always looks at them. I have to
tell you that letting my nails grow has been very hard. But I'm
determined to do it; it's a goal. If I can do something so small,
then I can go after something a little bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   At each meeting's beginning, Clarisa is always the first girl
through the door with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   At meeting's end, she is the most visibly upset, tears streaking
down her round face.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding bonds
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, an estimated 1.5 million children have a jailed
parent, and more than 200,000 children have imprisoned mothers,
according to the Child Welfare League of America. Nearly 11,000
women were incarcerated in Texas prisons in April, including the
Girl Scout mothers at the privately operated state jail.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal justice experts say parent-child contact is essential
to preserving emotional bonds while a parent is serving time. The
relationship will, hopefully, help the imprisoned parent to change
and the child to cope.
</P>
<P>
   But maintaining the relationship often requires structured
programs, such as Beyond Bars, which gets the mothers and daughters
out of the crowded, assigned-seat environment of routine weekend
jail visits. Without the programs, there is mounting evidence that
jailed parents' children will continue the cycle: Criminal justice
experts told The New York Times earlier this year that the largest
factor in the creation of juvenile delinquents and adult criminals
was having a parent behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Etta Moore, the Lone Star Girl Scout Council's executive
director, says the troop is part of the council's commitment to
bring scouting to underserved girls, particularly in poor and
isolated communities in rural and urban areas. The council has
nearly 13,000 Scouts, with more than 1,100 of them in customized
programs _ like Troop 1500 _ at community centers, public housing
projects, a homeless shelter, public schools and a home for unwed
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Troop 1500 mothers say the program is helping them. The women's
minimum-security residence is designed to be rehabilitative, and
improving their relationships with their girls is part of the
course. Two of the mothers _ Marisa and Felicia D. _ have been in
Beyond Bars since its start last year. Felicia W. joined in March.
Since they've been in Girl Scouts, though, the mothers say their
daughters are opening up _ sometimes slowly, but it's happening.
They hear their sadness about not having their mothers with them.
'We have gotten closer'
</P>
<P>
   Felicia D. only has a few weeks left. She's nearly finished with
her eight-month sentence for a theft-related offense. This will be
the last time that she will meet with daughter Crystal, 17, behind
bars. The pair hold hands in the troop dinner line for Papa John's
Pizza and red Hawaiian Punch. Crystal _ like most of the girls _ is
reluctant to talk to a stranger about herself or her mother, but
Felicia D., with a quiet reserve, explains their reasons for
joining the troop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to bond more with my daughter,'' she says. ``Since
we've been doing this, we have gotten closer to each other. She's a
bit more open (during their conversations) than she had been when
she just came to (weekend) visitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, she reports her daughter has offered a gift: ``She said
'When you get out, I'll pay for you to get your hair and nails
done.''' And Felicia D., who usually looks guarded, smiles and
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   At meetings, there is movement and a sense of freedom, and the
mothers say their daughters are at ease and more willing to share
what's on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to stuff all my feelings inside and then just explode,
lashing out my anger on anyone who was near, often the wrong
person,'' says Felicia W., who joined the troop with daughters
Dwanna, 12, and Shamica, 15. Then she noticed the same behavior in
her girls, particularly Dwanna, who wouldn't talk and would turn
her body away from the group during family visits.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Troop 1500, and Dwanna started talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the middle child. She said she felt like my son and
Shamica got more attention from me than she did, that she would
always have to compete with them for my time. I was shocked and
surprised to hear this. I always thought I gave her more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I understand why an A student would be acting out in
school, picking fights and getting into trouble; she was looking
for my attention and this is how she thought she could get it,''
says Felicia W. ``I used to buy the gifts and things, and all she
wanted was my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Felicia W. was arrested on her birthday. She's been serving time
for nearly a year on a drug-related offense, and she says her most
prized times are when her girls arrive for troop meetings. And the
most beloved part of the meeting is mealtime. It was during one of
these meals that Dwanna asked her mother what it was like to kiss a
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her she didn't have to kiss any boys if she didn't want
to,'' recalls Felicia W. as her eyebrows furrowed in seriousness.
``She said she hadn't, but she wanted to know what it was like.
Then she told me she had a friend who was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward I figured out this is what she really wanted to talk
about. I know she would never have brought it up with her
grandmother sitting here during a weekend visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwanna asked whether her mother would ask her to leave if she
got pregnant and whether her mother would still love her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her friend's family was threatening to kick her out of the
house, and Dwanna wanted to know if I would do the same thing. I
told her no, I wouldn't do that. I would love her just as much as I
do now, but I would be upset, even angry, but I would do everything
in my power to help her. But none of this meant she had permission
to go out and get pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   As the last paper plate and Styrofoam cup are tossed in the big
trash bin, a guard does an early-evening head count. Then, troop
activities begin. This night mothers and daughters learn dance
moves and Girl Scout songs, such as ``Alice the Camel,'' from the
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the two-hour meeting, Felicia D. gets a surprise
gift from the troop. It's a going-away bag filled with personal
items, such as shampoo, a laundry basket and a toothbrush. And, of
course, two boxes of Girl Scout cookies: Peanut Butter Patties and
Thin Mints.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, I've never had anybody be this sweet to me,'' said
Felicia D., tears in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   END TAKE ONE.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: nmartin(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
