</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEYOND-BARS21-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   BEYOND BARS: Take 2 of 2
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: TAKE 2 OF 2 TAKES. ATTN: TEXAS EDITORS. ART AVAILABLE.)
</P>
<P>
   Girls need their mothers
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids love their moms,'' said Karon Powell, the troop's
leader and full-time outreach program specialist. ``They are very
forgiving. They don't care what they've done. They just want to be
with their mothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell explains that Crystal, an emancipated minor, is so
dedicated to visiting her mother that she rearranged her work hours
to make the troop meetings every Tuesday. (Troop rules require the
girls to attend meetings on the weeks they don't see their mothers
in order to make the biweekly jail visits.)
</P>
<P>
   The Beyond Bars group does everything any Girl Scouts troop
would do. The girls go camping, attend ballets, create craft
projects, learn health and safety procedures and problem-solving
and conflict resolution skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping scouting alive, but it's not like what you're
used to,'' said Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Each troop meeting brings moments of suspense. The mothers never
know whether their daughters will show up until the group walks
into the jail's outdoor walkway. That's why they watch for their
children from the large windows. One Tuesday, Felicia W. sees
neither of her daughters. She knows Shamica is at basketball
practice, a sport that Felicia W. also played in high school. But
where is Dwanna?
</P>
<P>
   As the other mothers embrace their daughters, a Girl Scout
staffer tells Felicia W. that Dwanna missed the troop van because
of a late dental appointment.
</P>
<P>
   As the group finishes dinner, Felicia W. is clearly anxious
about her daughter making the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   She is constantly looking toward the windows, the telephone and
the heavy door.
</P>
<P>
   Then the phone rings; Felicia W.'s face opens into a wide smile.
Dwanna, with a puffy jaw and barely able to speak, walks through
the green door and straight into her mother's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was determined to get to that meeting,'' said Maxine,
Dwanna's guardian and Felicia W.'s mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so upset that she missed the van and thought she
couldn't go. I told her I would take her, but she was mighty upset
about being late.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, girls need their mothers,'' Maxine said. ``They
really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Promise and problems
</P>
<P>
   Do programs like Beyond Bars really work? Not many studies have
concentrated on children with incarcerated parents. Because the
Central Texas Beyond Bars is so new _ not yet a year old _ it's
still too early to predict long-term success. But so far, there are
promising outcomes as well as problems getting mothers to change.
Felicia W.'s mother, Maxine, wants Felicia to be prepared for her
release: ``I hope this program makes her understand how important
she is to her girls. How much they need her. How much she needs to
be a mother, be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   But in late June, Felicia W. was removed from the program for
breaking jail rules, including smuggling fried chicken from the
Girl Scout dinner into the inmate dormitory. Jail officials say she
sold the chicken; Felicia W. says she ate her chicken breast, and
she wasn't the only mother who took troop food back to the
dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   Another jail violation involved a gift from her daughter,
Dwanna. ``She gave me two hair barrettes for Mother's Day. Two
plastic butterflies. When I got the barrettes, I knew I shouldn't
have taken them. But I wanted them so bad because they were from
her.''
</P>
<P>
   The barrettes are considered contraband inside the jail. Felicia
W. says jail guards took the hair jewelry from her the day after
she got them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Dwanna to blame herself for this. It's not her
fault. It was on me to say 'thank you, but hold them until I get
out.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told I wasn't being a good role model,'' said Felicia
W., still angry days after her removal from the troop. ``I
disagree.'' Her daughters will continue with the troop on non-jail
weeks until they are reassigned to another troop.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia W. is scheduled for release in early August.
</P>
<P>
   Other mothers are finding more success. After getting out of
jail in March, Felicia D. went to work for a hotel. Her daughter,
Crystal, was expected to continue with the troop, but she dropped
out when her mother left.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months later, the teen-ager called Powell and said
she wanted to rejoin the troop. ``We must be doing something right
if we have a 17-year-old calling us,'' says Powell.
</P>
<P>
   In a short conversation one evening recently, Felicia D.,
fighting a cold, said she and her daughter were doing well. As
promised, Crystal paid for her first post-release salon visit.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia D. said she is still working. Her daughter has a new job
and is sharing an apartment with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and daughter see each other regularly, and Felicia D.
credits the Girl Scouts program with some of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't talked to her about it, but I think it drew us
closer. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: nmartin(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
