<HEADER>
A6807 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN21-COX     07-20 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teachers and students can keep humor _ and respect
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ In an heroic effort to bring respect back
into the classroom, the governor of Louisiana, recently signed
legislation making it mandatory for students in his state to
address teachers as ``Ma'am'' or ``Sir'' or by their title _ Mr.,
Mrs., Miss, or Ms. The law goes into effect this year for
kindergarten through fifth grade and will then sort of trickle up
with the kids, one grade at a time, until the entire system is
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The mandate does not carry a punishment with it since it'd be
tough to sentence a 1st-grader to 30 days without recess for an
infraction.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: ``Freddy, can you tell the class the name of Dick and
Jane's dog? The one that followed them to school one day?''
(Naturally, Freddy can't because while the rest of the class was
reading about boys and girls at school, he was surgically removing
the ears from his Mickey Mouse pencil holder.)
</P>
<P>
   Freddy: (guessing) ``Puddles.''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: ``Puddles, what?'' She's looking for a ``ma'am'' but
Freddy doesn't catch on so she helps him out. ``Puddles, ma'am.''
Freddy thinks that's an odd last name for a dog.
</P>
<P>
   If kids in the Louisiana schools haven't been taught the polite
(and very Southern) forms of address at home, then this is not
going to be an easy transition. The administration is going to have
to figure out a way to make good manners ``cool'' because everyone
knows, if it ain't cool, kids ain't gonna' do it.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget about the regulation number of parents who will
flop off the top of the imbecile scale and call in the ACLU because
their kids are being deprived of their civil right to incivility.
``My kid's no servant! He's not inferior to anyone,'' they'll bray.
Blah, blah, and more blah. Eventually they'll get over it, later in
the year when focus shifts to the annual witch hunt in school
libraries for ``dirty'' books or 150-year-old volumes suspected of
</P>
<P>
   preaching intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Most teachers worth their salt already have some standards of
address in place in their classrooms. Those who answer to a
``Hey!'' or tolerate a ``Yeh,'' in place of a ``Yes, Ms.
Boopydoop,'' are only doing half a job anyway, because manners are
a part of education. If teachers respect themselves and their
profession, they'll command respect from their students. And humor
helps.
</P>
<P>
   In my classroom, we always had a little fun with initial
breaches of courteous address, and that way no one was really
embarrassed (unless he or she insisted) and my point would be made
early on in the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher (that's me): ``Roger, did you make a noose of the window
shade cord and hang Shana's teddy bear?''
</P>
<P>
   Roger: ``Yeh.''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   Roger: ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: ``Roger, you may address me as `Yes, ma'am,' `Yes, Ms.
Schuett,' `Yes, Your Royal Intelligence,' or even `Yes, I did hang
the stupid teddy bear,' but `Yeh' is unacceptable. Get it?'' Roger
looks at his Nikes for a moment, like he's trying to make a choice
that won't diminish his monosyllabic masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   Roger: ``OK.'' I give him the evil eye. He grins and adds,
``Yes, Your Royal Intelligence; I hung the dumb bear.''
</P>
<P>
   I thank him and the episode ends with both of us maintaining our
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Roger has learned a valuable lesson, not so much about me or
hanging teddy bears, but about life. No matter how old he is, where
he goes, or what he does, there will always be someone worthy of
his respect. Polite speech is painless, costs nothing, and reaps
major rewards. There is no heart so stony that it can't be melted
with good manners.
</P>
<P>
   So for all of the Rogers out there, when the teacher asks, ``Are
you sure the dog ate your homework?'' you reply (truthfully of
course) ``Yes, ma'am, he sure did and he's got the bellyache even
worse than last week when he ate my book report.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust me, it'll work every time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
