<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK21-COX     07-20 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Large and small investors need asset allocation
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Asset allocation is a core concept for investors, from
the richest ones down to the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   It is a method for tuning up your portfolio, in hopes of getting
greater returns, without wandering into a pointlessly risky set of
investments.
</P>
<P>
   The process is simple.
</P>
<P>
   First you decide what percentages of your investments should go
into stocks, bonds and cash. Then you buy the appropriate mutual
funds or individual securities _ putting your money where your good
intentions are.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it so important?
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a difference in how well you eat for the rest of your
life,'' says certified financial planner Harold Evensky. He is
chair of the Certified Financial Planner Board of Governors and is
considered one of the nation's savviest planners.
</P>
<P>
   Evensky has developed a checklist to provide guidance for
beginners. To get it right, he tells clients to avoid these big
mistakes:
</P>
<P>
   1. Assuming your asset allocation is determined by your age.
</P>
<P>
   The long-standing rule of thumb is this: Subtract your age from
100, and the remainder is the percentage you should risk on the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of solution a sociologist would come up
with,'' Evensky said from his office in Coral Gables, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he recommends investing 50 percent to 75 percent in
stocks (and possibly more), keeping 2 percent to 4 percent in cash,
and putting whatever is left into bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The wide range in stocks is where individuals can adjust to
their own circumstances. A 50-year-old with a big portfolio, for
example, can be more conservative than a 50-year-old with few
assets.
</P>
<P>
   2. Not realizing your money needs to be properly allocated
within each category.
</P>
<P>
   ``For asset allocation to work, you must be diversified in each
category, so that your portfolio isn't a sitting duck when the
financial markets become choppy,'' Evensky advises.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning investors will have to keep it simple, he concedes.
``If you have a few thousand dollars, you would probably stay with
the Vanguard Index 500 fund.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the portfolio grows, the investor should refine his or
her allocations. On the stock side, for example, he recommends
putting 70 percent in U.S. stock mutual funds and the rest in
international stock mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   When there's even more money, the investor can subdivide the
domestic stock portfolio _ 75 percent to large-capitalization
companies and 25 percent to small-caps.
</P>
<P>
   3. Not regularly reviewing your fund manager's strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't allocate assets properly if you think your fund is
investing your money one way, while in reality the manager is doing
something else,'' says Evensky.
</P>
<P>
   His solution: Ask the fund company every six months how the
assets are allocated. Another alternative is to look for the data
in Morningstar's reports, either at a library or on the Internet at
www.morningstar.net. (At Ticker Lookup, type in the symbol of your
fund. Click on Portfolio, then click on Asset Allocation.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Believing that bonds are conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonds carry a different kind of risk than stocks _ enormous
inflation risk,'' Evensky said. ``Those who have 50 percent of
their money in bonds probably are facing the risk that their
investment won't outpace inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Letting your allocation ride.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to stay on track, you will have to rebalance your
portfolio from time to time. In the current stock market, for
example, what started as 50 percent in stocks may have become 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Evensky recommends a rebalancing whenever your stock, bond or
cash positions rise or fall by more than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One last warning: Sometimes it's hard to stick with the program.
I think of asset allocation not just as a technique but as a
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking with it could mean, especially right now, that you must
sell off some stocks while the market is rising. If you value the
system, you need to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asset allocation is not a free lunch,'' Evensky observed.
``You give up the risk of getting killed. But you also have to give
up the opportunity to make a killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
