<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '99 Isuzu sport-ute a standout
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Inside and outside, the '99 Isuzu VehiCross is an
eye-catcher that illustrates the diversity and exclusivity that
have come to the sport-utility market.
</P>
<P>
   Although based on the ruggedly luxurious Trooper platform, the
VehiCross is a radical departure for Isuzu and the closest the
Japanese manufacturer has come to marketing a vehicle (it even won
a car of the year award in Japan in '97). Base priced at $28,900,
the VehiCross comes _ quite properly, because of its cost _ with an
array of standard features that virtually eliminate the need to add
options. Air conditioning, leather seating, CD/cassette players,
power equipment and keyless entry are included.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long to notice, however, that two of the
striking features of the VehiCross have downsides. They are:
</P>
<P>
   _ The coupe-style body that has unusually shaped windows front
and rear. Visibility suffers, with the driver having little
rear-quarter view and rear passengers also facing limited views of
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   _ California-stylish red-and-black Recaro seats that are nicely
comfortable, supportable and adjustable. They also take up so much
of the potential entry and exit space that newcomers frequently
bump their heads on the roof getting in, and just about anyone has
to go through some contortion to enter and exit.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the VehiCross doesn't lack is power. The only
engine choice is the 3.5-liter V-6 found in the Trooper. It needs
to run to 5,400 rpm to make its peak power of 215 horsepower, but
whomps out 230 pounds-feet of torque at a relatively quiet 3,000
rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Couple that engine with a smooth four-speed automatic
transmission and a ``torque on demand'' system that automatically
determines which of its four wheels get how much power, and the
VehiCross becomes another vehicle that's near-foolproof in adverse
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   No one, least of all folks who've spent time in luxury
sport-utes, is going to confuse the VehiCross' ride and handling
characteristics with those of a car, though. The ride is stiff, and
its height (66.9 inches) and short wheelbase (91.8 inches) will
make most drivers cautious about quick or sharp turns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the VehiCross' decidedly different styling, the use of
carbon-fiber-look materials, its glare-fighting black hood and
Recaro seats mean it will stand out in the crowd. Isuzu plans to
import about 200 a month. That, along with the price, will make the
VehiCross appealing to SUV buyers who want to be different and
don't mind some trade-offs that compromise comfort and utility.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Isuzu VehiCross two-door, four-passenger,
four-wheel-drive sport-utility vehicle
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $29,687 (base: $28,900)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 3.5-liter V-6 engine with 24 valves (215
horsepower), four-speed automatic transmission with winter-start
and power modes, high/low transfer case with automatic torque
distribution
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: Dual air bags, side-impact beams, power
anti-lock disc brakes, height-adjustable front shoulder belts
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: Reversible cargo mat, $92
</P>
<P>
   Standard features include: Air conditioning, stereo with CD and
cassette players and six speakers, Recaro leather front bucket
seats
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 15 mpg regular unleaded city, 19 mpg highway.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
