<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The NAACP is making big noise about the
blanching of network TV entertainment, and not without reason. But
there's more to this tale than a fit of racial absentmindedness on
the part of programmers. It's an energetic commercial tribalizing
of American life, as economic interests dice us into small bits.
(Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ There's a new type of creature, one
who seeks out tornadoes and hurricanes supposedly for the thrill of
it. ``Weather tourists,'' the article called them. As a victim of
the 1992 monster called Hurricane Andrew, I was offended. (Howard
Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ PARIS _ The notice outside Shakespeare and
Co. invites visitors to ask about the legendary bookstore's plans
for celebrating the millennium. Don't ask. ``I don't know if I'll
make it that long,'' proprietor George Whitman croaked. ``I'm 88
years old. The people who work here will have to organize it for
themselves.'' (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ This Kennedy, we thought, would be the Kennedy
to carry the torch into the 21st century. But it wasn't to be.
(ERNEST Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ John F. Kennedy's death and the
spectacular media and public reaction that attended it forms a
meditation on what it means to be famous in America. (Rosenfeld,
Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ So for all of the Rogers out
there, when the teacher asks, ``Are you sure the dog ate your
homework?'' you reply (truthfully of course) ``Yes, ma'am, he sure
did and he's got the bellyache even worse than last week when he
ate my book report.'' Trust me, it'll work every time. (Schuett,
Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ ``We know your work,'' said the afterlife
attendant, holding up the current Examiner showing John F. Kennedy
Jr. and his wife, Carolyn, in an apparent argument. The magazine
was in the weekend checkout lines as the nation worried and mourned
for JFK Jr., his wife and sister-in-law. ``Unfortunate timing, that
piece,'' said the tabloid CEO. ``Like you and the steamroller,''
the attendant said. The tabloid CEO felt hot. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
