<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-LASERSURGERY21-     07-20 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-LASERSURGERY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New laser procedure gives heart patients relief
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Along with the dull, aching pain in his chest,
Robert Seaver would break out in a sweat and have trouble
breathing. Whatever he was doing, he had to stop, sit down, take
his nitroglycerine pill and wait for the angina attack to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' he says. ``You don't get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes just walking from the bedroom to the living room would
trigger it. ``I couldn't lift much of anything,'' he says. He
couldn't walk around the block. ``No way. Not even to the corner
and back.'' If he went shopping anywhere, he had to pick a small
store where he wouldn't have to walk much.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors were out of options for him. At 60, Seaver already
had been through three open-heart bypass operations, another
surgery to put in an artificial heart valve, catheterization to
clean out his arteries and all the medications that help relieve
angina. His cardiac arteries were too scarred for creating another
bypass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of patient we were just telling, `I'm sorry you
have pain, but there's nothing else I can do for you,' '' says Dr.
Mohey Saleh.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is something else. Saleh is one of two local heart
surgeons performing a laser procedure that drills small holes
through the heart wall. That minimal damage coaxes the body into
building new blood vessels to the heart, and the additional blood
eases the shortage of oxygen to the heart that causes angina.
</P>
<P>
   Seaver was the first Dayton area patient for transmyocardial
revascularization, or TMR. Four months later, after the time it
takes to grow the new blood vessels, he now says, ``I'm still
alive.'' More than that, he's mowing his lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I've got a riding mower,'' he says, but even
climbing onto the mower would have been unlikely several months
ago. He's not taking nitroglycerin anymore. The TMR hasn't cured
him, but he didn't expect that. ``It's definitely made a
difference,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Good Samaritan in Dayton is one of 30 hospitals in the country
doing TMR surgery, which was approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration last August. About 80,000 Americans a year are
diagnosed with severe coronary artery disease, untreatable with
bypass surgery or angioplasty and often leading to heart attacks.
With TMR, says Saleh's partner, Dr. K.H. Lim, ``Now we can
significantly improve the quality of life for literally thousands
of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't replace the conventional treatments, Saleh emphasizes.
When patients have cardiac arteries blocked, surgeons will still
try first to open the blockages with balloon angioplasties or
stents, or reroute the blood around the blockages in open-heart
surgery. But as Seaver illustrates, there's a limit to how often
that can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``In laymen's terms, the arteries are chewed up all the way from
beginning to end and there's no place to hook up a bypass,'' Saleh
says.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes medications can control the angina. Nitroglycerine and
other drugs dilate the remaining small arteries to increase blood
supply. Beta blockers and calcium channel blockers slow down the
heart muscles to decrease the demand for blood and its oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   So TMR is a treatment of last resort. It doesn't require
stopping the heart, and it's done through a 4-inch incision that
doesn't require breaking bones, but it carries the danger of
potentially fatal heart-rhythm irregularities if the computerized
laser bursts aren't properly synchronized with the heart's moments
between beats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complication rate is very high if you do it on patients
who are not stable,'' Saleh says. Clinical trials back him up with
a death rate of 20 percent in unstable patients, compared with only
3 percent otherwise. So Saleh won't do TMR on patients still
recovering from heart attacks, for example.
</P>
<P>
   It generally works well on stable patients. The trials show 70
percent have had significant reductions in their angina, with an 80
percent decrease in hospitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon typically bores 30 to 40 tiny holes through the
muscular heart wall with a carbon-dioxide laser, although Seaver
had only 28. The drilling is timed to when the heart is full of
blood, so the blood protects other tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of creating channels in the heart wall to increase
circulation came from observing reptiles, whose hearts are
nourished that way instead of through arteries outside the heart,
as in humans.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turns out, Saleh says, the laser-drilled channels
themselves don't deliver more blood to the heart. The body
considers them slight wounds to the heart and responds by creating
new blood vessels as part of the healing process. ``It's the new
vessels that increase the blood flow,'' Saleh says.
</P>
<P>
   An even less invasive TMR procedure is in the experimental
stages. Instead of going through a hole in the patient's chest, the
laser is guided through a catheter the size of a cocktail straw
that is threaded through an artery from the groin. Even newer
research is using gene therapy to stimulate blood-vessel growth
without any type of surgery.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the challenge is making TMR available to
everyone who needs it. These are patients who had exhausted their
medical options, remember, so cardiologists aren't in the habit of
sending them to surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say how many we'll do, because we never saw these
patients before,'' Saleh says. Starting with Seaver's TMR surgery
four months ago, Saleh and Lim have done five. ``But I expect it to
be more as people find out about it,'' Saleh says. ``You know. If
you build it, they will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
