<HEADER>
A6817 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC21-COX     07-20 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emissions repair? Ask questions first
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Repair Watch, a ``report card'' for auto shops
performing emissions repairs in metro Atlanta, was developed to
meet requirements of federal clean air legislation to assist
motorists in identifying effective repair facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Every emission test station is required to have at least one
copy of the Repair Watch document available for public review.
While this report is not a recommendation or endorsement by the
Georgia Environmental Protection Division or its management
contractor, it is ``an information source to help vehicle owners
locate repair facilities conducting emission-related repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   What it means is that locating the right shop to fix your
particular vehicle's problem is going to require a little sleuthing
on your part.
</P>
<P>
   Inspection/Maintenance (or emissions) test stations also have
blue-and-white ``When your vehicle fails'' pamphlets that are full
of great information.
</P>
<P>
   Under the heading ``Where do I go for repairs?'' are some
questions that should be asked at a prospective repair shop. One
is: ``Do they have the necessary diagnostic tools to help identify
the emission-related problem(s) including: a four-gas (for newer
vehicles) or five-gas (for vehicles six years or older) exhaust
analyzer to measure the emissions?''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the key!
</P>
<P>
   Every shop on the list has a gas analyzer, but which one? A
four-gas analyzer monitors carbon monoxide, hydrocarbons, oxygen
and carbon dioxide. This is sufficient for use in diagnosing and
confirming repair of newer vehicles that fail the TSI (two-speed
idle, or standing still) test because they are the only gases
tested.
</P>
<P>
   However, a five-gas analyzer is needed for any older vehicle
that has been ASM (acceleration simulation mode, or dynamometer
driving) tested because, in addition to the other four gases, it
also monitors NOx (oxides of nitrogen). Even if the vehicle didn't
fail the emissions test for NOx, adjustments and/or repairs made to
correct whatever failure it had can affect NOx production.
</P>
<P>
   If the shop doesn't have a five-gas analyzer to confirm the
final repair, the car could fail the next test for a different
reason. In short, a five-gas analyzer can be used to diagnose and
verify repair of all vehicles, but a four-gas analyzer can only be
used on those failing the TSI test.
</P>
<P>
   Another tool needed is a scan tool to read and analyze error
codes held by the emission control computer.
</P>
<P>
   Scan tools come in many flavors and are essential to diagnostic
work. Almost all of them, equipped with the right adapters and
software, work with older vehicles, although the amount of
information that can be accessed from the computers varies greatly.
</P>
<P>
   Newer cars require more-sophisticated scan tools with features
especially for 1996 and newer OBD II (onboard diagnostics)
vehicles. The question you need to ask: Will the shop's scan tool
communicate with your car's computer?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, ask the shop if it has an engine analyzer to monitor
the vehicle's ignition and overall engine performance.
</P>
<P>
   These also vary from large console units to small hand-held
ones. Bigger does not necessarily mean better.
</P>
<P>
   If you're shop shopping, ask the questions listed inside the
pamphlet. Be sure to tell them your vehicle's make, year, model and
what test it failed. The shop should be able to determine if it can
meet your needs.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
