<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     07-20 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S PURCHASE LAND TO CREATE MAINE WOODS NATIONAL PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c.1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a movement afoot to create a 3.2-million-acre national
park in Maine that extends from Umsaskis Lake and Priestly Mountain
in the north to Sebec Lake and Monson Pond in the south. The
western-most boundary is Quebec Province, Canada and Green Mountain
to the east. The proposed national park lies about 40 miles north
of Bangor.
</P>
<P>
   The Baxter State Park will be entirely surrounded by the
proposed national park, but it will remain a state-run park. In
1919, former Maine Rep. and later Gov. Percival Baxter attempted to
secure state protection for the Mt. Katahdin area. He was
unsuccessful. So, he purchased the land with his own money and
donated it to the people of the state of Maine as the ``forever
wild'' state park.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists from around the nation see this as a last
chance to save the famed North Woods. Jym St. Pierre, the Maine
director of RESTORE: The North Woods, the regional conservation
group which has proposed creating the national park, wrote
recently, ``Establishing a Maine Woods National Park would
safeguard a national treasure where the haunting yodel of loons
echoes through the warm, blue summer air. It would give us an
opportunity to restore the legendary forests of Maine, the song of
the wolf, the splash of the Atlantic salmon, the magic of caribou
gliding through wild woods like massive, mysterious shadows. It
would be a magnificent people's park for the Twenty-first Century
and a fitting millennial memorial for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre isn't the first person to wax poetic about this area,
Henry David Thoreau, after his visit in 1853, declared that it
should be saved as a national preserve. Thoreau, in his book ``The
Maine Woods,'' a profound study of woods and camping, wrote: ``From
this elevation, just on the skirts of the clouds, we could overlook
the country, west and south, for a hundred miles. There it was, the
State of Maine ... immeasurable forest for the sun to shine on ...
No clearing, no house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did not look as if a solitary traveler had cut so much as a
walking stick there. Countless lakes ... and mountains also, whose
names, for the most part, are known only to the Indians. The forest
looks like a firm grass sward, and the effect of these lakes ... is
that of a mirror broken into a thousand fragments, and wildly
scattered over the grass, reflecting the full blaze of the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, there is a great opportunity to purchase some of the
land necessary to create this national park. Approximately 5
percent of Maine is currently up for sale. Two major paper
companies, Sappi Ltd. and Bowater Inc., are offering to sell nearly
three million acres of forest land, which constitutes 17 percent of
the forested area in Maine. A number of state conservation groups
are attempting to arrange a package to buy Sappi land.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wish to preserve these lands as a national park have
to overcome the reluctance of politicians and local residents who
see the timber industry as the backbone of Maine's economy. And
there are those who fear that if this stretch of land becomes a
national park, they won't be able to hunt or fish or use
snowmobiles in the park. They worry that they will lose access to
the land.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists who are attracted to Maine now will increase
tenfold if this national park is created. And nearby towns will
reap greater economic benefit from the park than they have from the
timber industry.
</P>
<P>
   The people of America hunger for more wilderness and greater
tracks of land that preserve nature: the wildlife, the streams and
rivers, the forests and undergrowth, the deep silence and sense of
connection to the earth we need to escape the pressures of work and
the busyness of life.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, former U.S. Supreme Court Justice William O.
Douglas wrote, ``Nature must be left undisturbed in ever-widening
circles, so that she can heal the wounds of civilization and
re-create the wonders of God's wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heal the wounds of civilization.'' Yes. How often we seek the
solace of the wilderness. The wonder of a massive, 750-year-old
Sitka spruce on the Oregon coast that has survived numerous
lightning strikes _ yet bares their scars in deep, jagged cuts
through its bark. The quiet that the deep foliage brings, the red
of rotting tree trunks, the green canopy of leaves, the light
shimmering green to complement the red wood slowly turning to soil.
</P>
<P>
   Who among us has never felt the sanctity of the wilderness? Who
has not felt cleansed by walking through a forest hearing the wind
sing through the branches and leaves, the pines and firs? Or
cleansed by lying down beside a river so the purling waters hush
the din of civilization we carry within ourselves?
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time to secure the great North Woods of Maine. The
Maine Woods National Park would rival the Yellowstone National
Park, which so many of us cherish. The nation's economy has created
a windfall of taxes for the federal government. And here is a
worthy investment for this nation's future _ purchase the land
necessary to make the proposed Maine Woods National Park a reality.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better way to spend a small portion of the nation's
tax dollars. The entire purchase will cost less than we taxpayers
pay for a B-2 bomber. And one never has to worry about a wilderness
area becoming obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-19-99 1921EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
