<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, July 20, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING (San Francisco) _ Like an omen from the Book of
Revelation, a wispy, silvery-blue noctilucent cloud hovered over
Colorado late last month. The timing couldn't have been more
appropriate. The cloud _ the ``miner's canary'' of climate change,
some call it _ appears as global warming research is becoming a
major scientific industry in fields ranging from atmospheric
physics to biology. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GUNS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Gov. Gray Davis declared
California the state with the strongest gun laws in the nation,
after signing two bills that will help restrict the manufacture and
sale of assault weapons. But critics say the measures will only
lead to confusion and litigation when they take effect Jan. 1, as
gun makers, dealers and buyers try to decode the new laws. By PETER
HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BABOONS-HEALTH (San Francisco) _ Robert Sapolsky of Stanford
University runs a lab where he does important work on the
neurobiology of stress and disease. He been journeying to Africa
just about every summer for over two decades to study baboons. His
work suggests lessons for humans. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-HBO (Pasadena, Calif.) _ About five or so years ago my wife
and I ditched HBO. There was nothing really to watch, except for
the same movies over and over and over. We must not have been the
only ones. Not much later HBO set out in a ``definitely conscious''
effort to crank out more original series, Chairman and CEO Jeff
Bewkes told a gathering of television critics last week. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-UPN (Pasadena, Calif.) _ At no other time in its history has
the UPN network been more likable. Yes, that's likable _ not
dislikable. Considered the sixth-place network in a six-way race,
UPN always has been picked on by the critics, often deserving its
status as the butt of some ``Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer''
joke or for imploding almost on cue. What's changed since then? by
TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-PROFILE-HORSES (Salinas, Calif.) _ Monty Roberts,
best-selling author and acclaimed horse trainer, is a hero to horse
lovers around the world, but his name is still mud in Salinas, his
hometown. Two years after ``The Man Who Listens to Horses'' took
the literary world by storm and assured Roberts' celebrity, his
relatives still are boiling mad over its claims that his father was
a child abuser, killer, racist and cruel to horses. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The death of John F. Kennedy, Jr.,
seems to pose a perplexing problem for Kennedy-haters. They can't
criticize JFK, Jr. for romancing mobster molls, like his old man.
They can't fault him for an unseemly thirst for booze and broads,
like his Uncle Teddy. They can't accuse him of laziness or
stupidity or greed. So, they're stuck with assailing him for hubris
_ for letting his courage as a fledgling pilot outweigh his skills.
By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Don't you know that some days
the b.s. is just too thick for the filter of absurdity, and the
whole system has to back up? In Washington, in less time than you
can say, ``minimum wage,'' members of the House of Representatives
gave themselves and their Senate colleagues a 3.4 percent salary
increase. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
