<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-LA-BREAUX-BUSH-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        BREAUX'S SON GIVES MONEY TO BUSH
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark Stricherz   c. 1999 States News Service   WASHINGTON,
<TEXT>
July 19 -- John Breaux has indeed donated money to George W. Bush,
the Republican's leading presidential candidate.
<P>
   It just happens to be John Breaux, Jr., the son of the Louisiana
Democratic Senator.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics, a Washington-based
government watchdog, reported Monday that Breaux, in a stunning
display of turn-coat style politics, had given Bush $1,000 for the
latter's presidential bid. Breaux's Washington office received a
bevy of calls about the matter, wondering how could the senior
senator could do such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   It just happened to be wrong, though. The real distributor of
the money was Breaux's son.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Breaux, who lives not far from Washington in
Alexandria, Va., works as a lobbyist for Johnston &AMP; Associates, the
lobbying firm set up by former Louisiana Sen. Bennett Johnston,
according to Breaux spokesman Bette Phelan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
