<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGET FONDA DIVES INTO `LAKE PLACID'
</HEADLINE>
 BC - FONDA-BRIDGET-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Eds: note italics below 
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In her dozen years as a film actress, Bridget
Fonda's pale, slender beauty has lent itself to roles as a Single
White Female, a bong-smoking beach bunny and a waitress. Now, she's
trying something a little different _ playing a reluctant crocodile
chaser in the quirky/scary creature flick ``Lake Placid.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a body-hugging black sweater set and slim skirt (from
which, she discovered, she hadn't yet removed the price tag),
Fonda, at 35, seems to look more like a Fonda every day. The lanky
frame and piercing eyes bear a strong resemblance to those of
father Peter, grandfather Henry and aunt Jane. Though she says she
has to watch her weight a bit more now than in the past, it's hard
to sympathize when she pinches what she imagines is a bit of fat on
her leg. (BEGIN ITAL) Please, (END ITAL) you think, (BEGIN ITAL)
allow me to show you what fat really looks like. (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   It may not be coincidental, then, that Fonda was offered the
lead role in ``Ally McBeal.'' The huge TV hit was created by ``Lake
Placid'' writer David E. Kelley; Fonda says she's just not
interested in doing television right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if something came along that I wanted to
do (on TV),'' Fonda said. ``I love the character and writing on
`Ally McBeal,' but my favorite part of making a movie is the
preparation. I'm not that spontaneous, to work on a series the way
they do, changing things up to the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   It's often said that Kelley is the busiest man in show business:
He has three shows on the air (``Ally,'' ``The Practice'' and
``Chicago Hope'') and finds time to write movies on the side when
he's not busy being a family man with wife Michelle Pfeiffer.
Everyone involved with ``Placid'' says Kelley's smart,
tongue-in-cheek writing was a main attraction in doing the film and
that Kelley was always available to make small tweaks when needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never actually seen him on the set of anything, but he's
always there,'' said director Steve Miner. With credits that range
from ``Halloween: H20'' to TV's ``Dawson's Creek,'' Miner seems to
have been a natural choice to bring this mixture of horror and
dark, offbeat humor to the screen. ``We had a little trouble
setting (the movie) up,'' admits Miner, ``because people had a
little trouble understanding what kind of movie it was. But David
and I always knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda plays a paleontologist called in to figure out how a giant
crocodile may have made its way into a Maine lake. As part of her
preparation, Fonda paid a visit to the Museum of Natural History in
New York, where she was debriefed on the fine points of identifying
a crocodile from one of its teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda admits she can relate to the insecurities of her
character, who's a bundle of insecurities because she's fresh off a
broken relationship and is out of her element in the wild. ``I
loved this character. She's been having a bad time. She's a bitch
because she's so afraid of being not good enough ... her
self-esteem is so low that she doesn't want to leave her cubicle
and her microscope,'' said Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   As for her own insecurities, Fonda admits she's afraid of
heights _ and doesn't relish looking back at her own work on film.
``I'm not that crazy about my own work ... I'll watch the dailies
and go to the premiere,'' Fonda said, ``but looking back _ I don't
really get into what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she grew up among Hollywood royalty _ or perhaps
because of it _ Fonda says she can relate to the fear that grows
from insecurity. But according to Fonda, who recently ended a long
relationship with actor Eric Stoltz and is currently dating
singer/actor Dwight Yoakam, she doesn't suffer from it when it
comes to feeling like she has to measure up against anyone else's
fame, or the Fonda ``legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any sense of competition. That's probably from
being the child of someone famous,'' Fonda says, ``that I don't
look at fame as a register of anything real. Fame just doesn't mean
anything concrete. It's so changeable. You can't count on it. It
passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda says that, unlike her father, who released a juicy
autobiography last year (``Don't Tell Dad: A Memoir''), she's
learned to keep a part of her life private. ``The way I grew up was
that there was no privacy. My father is very, very open,'' Fonda
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up thinking that's the way you had to be. But then,''
said Fonda, ``I found out I didn't want to be that way ... I had to
sort of learn how to not feel bad about not answering certain
questions. My natural instinct is to try to give an answer _ that's
the gracious thing to do. I'm a people pleaser, which makes me feel
bad about not giving an answer, but I'm also kind of shy and
private. So sometimes I'm torn.
</P>
<P>
   Workwise, Fonda says she's conscious these days of moving beyond
parts that cast her as merely window dressing: ``corsage parts,''
as she calls them. She says she'd be interested in developing her
own projects if she could ``find a way to do it: It takes time _
and a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   But overall, Fonda says she's happy and grateful for the parts
she's gotten so far in her career and is just trying to take things
one role at a time. ``Do I think about my legacy? I can't really
think about that,'' Fonda said. ``If I think about that ... it's a
setup for a feeling of failure for me; I'll never measure up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get objective about my own work,'' Fonda admits, ``so
I just have to let go of that and hope other people like what I
do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6926 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREECH-AZR &LR;      07-20 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREECH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIST WELCOMES ALL FOLLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE REV. JIMMY CREECH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The Bible is the written witness to God's saving
activity in the history of Israel, the person and ministry of Jesus
and the early church. It bears witness to a loving God who creates
all things and calls all that is good, a God in whose image all
humankind is created, a God who acts to overcome oppression and
death. It tells of a Jesus who embodies God's compassion and
justice and who instructs us to be like God, compassionate and
just, in our life together.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible is a marvelous treasure for instruction and spiritual
growth, but it is not easily understood. The Bible must be
interpreted to be understood, using all available knowledge about
the historical, cultural and literary settings of each passage
being studied. There are six passages in the Bible that contain
references to same-gender sexual activity. Not all Christians will
agree on the exact meaning and significance of these passages.
</P>
<P>
   I find no discussion of homosexuality in the Bible.
Homosexuality is a word that was invented by psychoanalysts in the
late 1800s to describe their discovery of a natural and innate
same-gender sexual orientation. There was no understanding of
sexual orientation in biblical times. There was not even a word for
it in the languages of the Bible: Hebrew, Aramaic and Greek.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, a few references to same-gender sexual
activity in the Bible, and in each case the sexual activity is
condemned. But each reference is found in a context related to
violence, idolatry, promiscuity and exploitation. In each of these,
it is the violence, idolatry, promiscuity or exploitation that are
the reasons why the same-gender sexual activity is condemned.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual activity is first and fore most a good gift from God that
blesses intimate, loving relationships with shared physical
pleasure. The potential for creating new life need not be a
requirement for wholesome sexual activity. Otherwise, sharing
physical intimacy would be denied to persons who are infertile.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is this: There is no biblical reference that
condemns same-gender sexual relations between two people who are in
a mutually loving, nurturing, caring and supportive relationship.
Consequently, there is no condemnation of homosexuality in the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   This was a surprising discovery to me! I did not study the Bible
about this until a gay member of the United Methodist church I was
serving in 1984 told me of the abuse he experienced in the church.
I learned that the teachings and practices of Christian churches
were causing gay and lesbian persons to believe themselves rejected
by and separated from God because of who they are.
</P>
<P>
   I believe this kind of teaching to be spiritual abuse and that
it is contrary to the ministry of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus proclaimed a realm of God where all were welcome,
especially those who were cast out of community because they were
different. God's realm is defined by compassion, freedom from
oppression, justice and peace.
</P>
<P>
   What is important in regard to sexual ethics is not the gender
of the people involved but the quality of the relationship in which
sexuality is expressed.
</P>
<P>
   Genesis 19: 1-29 contains the legendary story of the destruction
of Sodom and Gomorrah. God is about to destroy these cities because
of their prior sinfulness and sends two angels, who appear to be
men, to save Lot and his family. The men of Sodom threaten to
sexually violate the angels.
</P>
<P>
   This is a story about violent gang rape that in ancient times
was a way men humiliated and showed dominance over other men. The
Sodom story clearly illustrates and condemns the inhospitality of
uncaring arrogance and sexual violence. It is not a story about
loving, caring same-gender sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   The passages in Leviticus are in a collection of laws known as
the Holiness Code. The Israelites were to be different from their
neighbors, especially in regard to the religious practices of the
Egyptians and Canaanites.
</P>
<P>
   The religion of Baal, practiced in Canaan, was a fertility
religion. Its temples had prostitutes, male and female. Sexual
intercourse with either by male worshipers was believed to enhance
and ensure the fertility of the land. The men of Israel were
forbidden to ''lie with a male as with a woman,'' because doing so
imitated the worship of Baal, which was idolatrous, was called an
''abomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Romans is Paul's letter to a Jewish community living in a
Gentile world. In the first chapter, Paul refers to Gentile pagan
practices used in the worship of ''lies and creatures'' (other
words for idols). Such practices included sexual intercourse with
male and female temple prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   He was familiar with the Holiness Code and its prohibition
against behavior that imitates pagan worship. Paul has no
understanding of sexual orientation and its diversity. He assumes
sexual relations to be natural and acceptable only between men and
women. So, for him, same-gender sexual activity turns the world
upside down and is unnatural, contrary to the created order. What
he describes is idolatrous, lustful and promiscuous sexual
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this passage is that, when taken seriously, it is
an affirmation, not a condemnation, of loving, caring and committed
same-sex relations for gay and lesbian persons. For them, same-sex
relations are natural and honor the creator.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite-sex relations would be contrary to their nature and a
rejection of the creator's design.
</P>
<P>
   This passage is a saving message for lesbian and gay persons who
act with integrity as the persons God created them to be, just as
much as it is a judgment against those who ''exchange natural
relations for unnatural.''
</P>
<P>
   In I Corinthians 6: 1-10 and I Timothy 1: 8-10, Paul lists vices
that are condemned, using some Greek words whose meanings are
uncertain. Unfortunately, these words have been inaccurately
translated to refer to same-gender sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   The first word is malakoi, which means soft. The second word,
arsenokoitai, has no clear meaning. Paul is the first to use it and
he does not define it. The first part of this word, arseno, means
male. The second part, koitai, means bed. There is no clue what
Paul means by this.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the early Christian church used these words when
talking about same-gender sexual activity. Many of the early church
leaders discuss same-gender sexual activity but never use these
words or refer to these passages. John Chrysostom (fourth-century
theologian) wrote commentaries on both I Corinthians and I Timothy
and did not identify any references to same-gender sexual activity
in these passages.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Cantor (12th century) made a list of all passages in the
Bible that he believed referred to same-gender sexual activity and
did not include these two passages. It was not until the 13th
century that Thomas Aquinas associated these words with same-sex
sexual activity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREECH-AZR &LR;      07-20 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREECH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIST WELCOMES ALL FOLLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE REV. JIMMY CREECH  
 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The Bible is the written witness to God's saving
activity in the history of Israel, the person and ministry of Jesus
