Consequently, there is no condemnation of homosexuality in the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   This was a surprising discovery to me! I did not study the Bible
about this until a gay member of the United Methodist church I was
serving in 1984 told me of the abuse he experienced in the church.
I learned that the teachings and practices of Christian churches
were causing gay and lesbian persons to believe themselves rejected
by and separated from God because of who they are.
</P>
<P>
   I believe this kind of teaching to be spiritual abuse and that
it is contrary to the ministry of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus proclaimed a realm of God where all were welcome,
especially those who were cast out of community because they were
different. God's realm is defined by compassion, freedom from
oppression, justice and peace.
</P>
<P>
   What is important in regard to sexual ethics is not the gender
of the people involved but the quality of the relationship in which
sexuality is expressed.
</P>
<P>
   Genesis 19: 1-29 contains the legendary story of the destruction
of Sodom and Gomorrah. God is about to destroy these cities because
of their prior sinfulness and sends two angels, who appear to be
men, to save Lot and his family. The men of Sodom threaten to
sexually violate the angels.
</P>
<P>
   This is a story about violent gang rape that in ancient times
was a way men humiliated and showed dominance over other men. The
Sodom story clearly illustrates and condemns the inhospitality of
uncaring arrogance and sexual violence. It is not a story about
loving, caring same-gender sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   The passages in Leviticus are in a collection of laws known as
the Holiness Code. The Israelites were to be different from their
neighbors, especially in regard to the religious practices of the
Egyptians and Canaanites.
</P>
<P>
   The religion of Baal, practiced in Canaan, was a fertility
religion. Its temples had prostitutes, male and female. Sexual
intercourse with either by male worshipers was believed to enhance
and ensure the fertility of the land. The men of Israel were
forbidden to ''lie with a male as with a woman,'' because doing so
imitated the worship of Baal, which was idolatrous, was called an
''abomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Romans is Paul's letter to a Jewish community living in a
Gentile world. In the first chapter, Paul refers to Gentile pagan
practices used in the worship of ''lies and creatures'' (other
words for idols). Such practices included sexual intercourse with
male and female temple prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   He was familiar with the Holiness Code and its prohibition
against behavior that imitates pagan worship. Paul has no
understanding of sexual orientation and its diversity. He assumes
sexual relations to be natural and acceptable only between men and
women. So, for him, same-gender sexual activity turns the world
upside down and is unnatural, contrary to the created order. What
he describes is idolatrous, lustful and promiscuous sexual
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this passage is that, when taken seriously, it is
an affirmation, not a condemnation, of loving, caring and committed
same-sex relations for gay and lesbian persons. For them, same-sex
relations are natural and honor the creator.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite-sex relations would be contrary to their nature and a
rejection of the creator's design.
</P>
<P>
   This passage is a saving message for lesbian and gay persons who
act with integrity as the persons God created them to be, just as
much as it is a judgment against those who ''exchange natural
relations for unnatural.''
</P>
<P>
   In I Corinthians 6: 1-10 and I Timothy 1: 8-10, Paul lists vices
that are condemned, using some Greek words whose meanings are
uncertain. Unfortunately, these words have been inaccurately
translated to refer to same-gender sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   The first word is malakoi, which means soft. The second word,
arsenokoitai, has no clear meaning. Paul is the first to use it and
he does not define it. The first part of this word, arseno, means
male. The second part, koitai, means bed. There is no clue what
Paul means by this.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the early Christian church used these words when
talking about same-gender sexual activity. Many of the early church
leaders discuss same-gender sexual activity but never use these
words or refer to these passages. John Chrysostom (fourth-century
theologian) wrote commentaries on both I Corinthians and I Timothy
and did not identify any references to same-gender sexual activity
in these passages.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Cantor (12th century) made a list of all passages in the
Bible that he believed referred to same-gender sexual activity and
did not include these two passages. It was not until the 13th
century that Thomas Aquinas associated these words with same-sex
sexual activity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
