<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, July 21. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   HEAT: Temperature expected to hit 99 or 100 today with heat
index near 110. Heat advisories in effect with no relief in sight
until the weekend. And despite having more rain this year overall,
July has been a dry and weary month. Lee Hill Kavanaugh and Alan
Bavley. 25. Photos; graphics.
</P>
<P>
   HAKC: Housing leaders from around the country are in Kansas City
this week to learn about new urban initiatives. The conference puts
the Kansas City Housing Authority into the spotlight. Five years
ago, a federal judge took over the public housing agency because of
numerous problems. Today the agency, under court-appointed
leadership, has earned HUD's highest marks. Challenges remain,
though, such as returning the authority to public control. Ruth
Igoe. 25. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN. Police find a brain in a car in Lawrence, Kan. Richard
Espinoza.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT _ The Kansas wheat harvest is nearly complete. By Victoria
Sizemore Long. Photo (tent.)
</P>
<P>
   JCNIC _ An Overland Park company that provides Internet-based
government electronic services goes public. Julius Karash.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. They go for a sweep of the Cubs at Wrigley. 1:20 p.m.
start.
</P>
<P>
   SINGLE WING. Seventy-five coaches from 21 states participated
last week in the third annual Single-Wing Symposium at William
Jewell College. It is a tribute to a ``dinosaur of football.''
James Powell. 18 AND GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   BRETT. 18. A look at some of the George Brett memorabilia that's
in the marketplace these days.
</P>
<P>
   BASES. When Pittsburgh catcher Jason Kendall snapped his ankle
on first base a couple of weeks ago, it brought to mind two
questions: Could the bases be safer? And why don't major leaguers
run the bases properly? Heather Dinich. 25.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBRA: Americans have come to expect our automobiles to be
fully loaded. But our underwear? There's a brassiere currently
under development that has more options than you could have
imagined possible in your car, let alone a mere undergarment. The
Techno Bra is sophisticated enough to monitor the wearer's heart
rate, call the police or some other predetermined number, and
disclose its precise location thanks to a computer chip that
communicates with the global positioning satellite system. And
exactly why does a bra need to do anything more than lift and
separate, you ask? Fear, freedom and empowerment have a lot to do
with it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-Presidents: If you want to catch TV's most captivating series
this summer, don't look to HBO. Don't look to MTV. Look to C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly ``American Presidents: Life Portraits,'' three-hour
treatments of each of the nation's 41 chief executives, may be
television's most ambitious documentary project ever.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from its obvious value to history buffs, what makes
``American Presidents'' so compelling are the unexpected, ongoing
and often contentious debates that take place between the program's
featured historians and its viewers who call in and offer very
different takes on the American presidents. Aaron Barnhart. 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   Theater-Jazz: On stage and screen, dramas that address the jazz
life mostly depict a pathetic character: irresponsible, out of
touch, doomed. An eccentric figure who performs music disdained by
the mainstream. Or worse, an outright loser who regularly escapes
from reality by means of a needle.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Side Man,'' a Broadway drama given the Tony Award for Best
Play in June, the title character is a journeyman musician who has
disappointed his wife and son by virtue of his dedication to music.
Another recent play, ``Oo-Bla-Dee,'' centers on a saxophonist whose
hunger for success stems from a troubled past. Calvin Wilson. 1,400
words.
</P>
<P>
   Copland-Biography: Cowboys and common men, Appalachian settlers
and Abraham Lincoln: Aaron Copland created the very definition in
music of what it means to be American. Which brought him his share
of pooh-poohers, who could sniff at a musical Norman Rockwell
enshrining rose-tinted myths of masculinity, family and community.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, of course, was much more complex. On the eve of the
composer's centenary _ he was born Nov. 14, 1900 _ we now can see
him as a true giant of 20th-century artistic creation. Scott
Cantrell. 1,625 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
