<SLUG> BC-OLY-US-MENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD OF FUN FOR GARNETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ After every game, he tries to be as inconspicuous as
a 7-footer can be. A hat covers his head, which is always looking
down. A discman is in one hand, earphones in the other. He tries to
blend in. It doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The fans in the stands, directly across from the so-called
``free zone'' where players congregate after games, instantly
recognize Kevin Garnett and the cheers and calls soon begin, as if
on cue. Eventually, Garnett acknowledges them and then spends time
chatting with reporters, something he actually seems to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   He is quickly coming to grips with his international celebrity
here in the pre-Olympic Qualifying Tournament of the Americas. As
he put it before Monday's game with the Dominican Republic, ``I'm
looking at this international thing this way: I'm going to have
fun. I've never been here. I'm soaking it all in _ period. End of
story.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's really just the beginning of what could be a very long
story. Gary Payton and Tim Hardaway are the veterans and Tim Duncan
clearly is the local favorite; it's only a 20-minute flight from
his native St. Croix. But if there's one player on the United
States team who is playing well and playing to the crowd, it's the
23-year-old Garnett. As much as any individual on this team, he is
epitomizing what the team is, how it plays, and where it's going.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to pick a word to describe the team, he said, ``predators.
We're a team full of predators, but we also have fun. We're a team
that really comes out and competes. But we're a predator team,
putting a team 6-feet deep, trying to set the tone. But, at the
same time, have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He's having a blast. This tournament, against what can
charitably be called ``competition,'' is giving Garnett a stage for
the show he likes the best: running, dunking, blocking shots,
chatting up opponents who don't understand him, playing to the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too early to call him The Ambassador?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to enjoy this,'' he said. ``I think the crowd
recognizes that I'm playing hard. I play with a lot of passion and
emotion and the crowd feeds off my energy and my attitude toward
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then continued. ``You have to understand, man. We are
sending a message to young kids everywhere who might one day want
to become basketball players. The message is this: it's good to go
out and have fun. It doesn't matter who you dunk on, or who dunks
on you. Or how bad you play or how good you play. The whole object
is to have fun, man. This is for the crowd. The great Charles
Barkley said fans pay a lot of money, so you want to entertain
them. I'm just happy to be here, man . . . Dunks or no dunks.''
</P>
<P>
   He's had mostly dunks. In the first four games of this
tournament, all blowout US wins, Garnett led the Yanks in scoring
at 16.5 points a game and blocked shots at 2.3. He was second in
rebounding (7.0) and minutes played (23.8), he's shooting an
astonishing 69.8 percent (30 for 43) and virtually all of his field
goals have been authoritative dunks or layups.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Garnett sees (and hopes) is the NBA of the future,
one of running, cutting, dunking, and, most of all, smiling. Now
all he has to do is get rid of the coaches and he might be on to
something.
</P>
<P>
   And don't bother him with any Dream Team comparisons. He won't
listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a different breed, man,'' he said. ``We're so far
new school that you can't compare us. It's totally different. I
don't think it's fair to the guys in the Hall of Fame. I don't
think it's fair to the great ones like Michael, Magic, or Larry.
This is more like an up-tempo-type generation. (It's) a lot of guys
having fun. (It's) a lot of competitiveness. That's where our
league is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett is unquestionably one of the people who will carry it
into the next century. US coach Larry Brown, an unabashed,
unapologetic, old-schooler, marvels at Garnett's sheer athleticism
and skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's only 23 and he's already one of the elite players in the
league,'' Brown said. ``He's only going to get better. I can't
fathom a better, all-around package.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, too, has noticed that the fans warm to Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they enjoy the way he plays,'' Brown said. ``He makes
the spectacular plays. But he also plays hard. You can make a case
for any of our guys, but I don't think anyone is more popular than
Kevin is. The one thing I've noticed over the years is that there
are a lot of good players, but they don't really enjoy playing.
Kevin loves to play. He is enjoying himself out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett also was involved in, at least in Argentina, probably
the most memorable play of the tournament. A 19-year-old Argentine
named Andres Nocioni drove by him and then did a reverse dunk on
both Garnett and Duncan. Garnett traded trash talk with Nocioni the
rest of the way, although neither could understand the other.
</P>
<P>
   That followed a game against Uruguay in which he was asked
during a stop in play if he'd pose for a picture after the game. He
told the unsuspecting Uruguayan he'd have to clear it with the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   He'd never had that experience before, but a lot of things are
new and different for Garnett. Next year in Sydney should be even
more eye-opening, even though the hoop world already has some idea
of how he can play.
</P>
<P>
   But Garnett has always been more than that. We've seen it the
last four years and now everyone else is getting a chance. It's not
simply that he plays well. It's how much he enjoys it and lives for
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
