<HEADLINE>
GREAT SCOT: LAWRIE THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ From the streets of Aberdeen to the
larger neighborhoods of Edinboro and Glascow, there may have been a
pint or two hoisted Sunday night when native son Paul Lawrie won
the 128th British Open in the moist air of the Carnoustie Golf
Course. Just last Wednesday, Rhode Islander Billy Andrade had said
whoever wins in these grueling conditions will be, in his mind, the
world's best golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lawrie? He was 159th on the world ranking list, and had won
just twice since turning pro in 1986. He won the Catalonian Open in
1996, and the Qatar Masters in February. This didn't strike fear
into anyone's hearts, did it? Wife Marian stayed home in Aberdeen
to put infant son Michael and 4-year-old son Craig to bed as the
rest of the family was on holiday in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   This was a historic sporting moment. Lawrie had been 10 shots
back entering the final round, and nobody had overcome that large a
deficit to win a major championship. Jackie Burke Jr. had trailed
by eight entering the final round of the Masters in 1956 before
winning.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the best way to put the enormous accomplishment into
some perspective. The last Scottish-born player to win a major on
home turf was Tommy Armour, who had emigrated to the United States
and won the first of the five British Opens played at Carnoustie,
in 1931. That was the year Bobby Jones was trying to put the wheels
in motion to create the Augusta National GC where the tournament
known as the Masters would be played.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrie, 30, started in the game selling Mars Bars as an
assistant in the shop at Banchory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I got my qualifications and learned my trade,''
he said after the excitement had died out Sunday. He had to make
the journey to Downfield last weekend to qualify, and had to stage
a remarkable comeback on the second nine of the second qualifying
round just to make it to Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   Since qualifying was introduced in 1962, a qualifier had never
won the game's oldest _ and to many, the most prestigious _
tournament. He found himself in the game's only four-hole playoff
format Sunday evening when the sinking Frenchman Jean Van de Velde
triple-bogeyed the 18th to open the doors. Van de Velde and 1997
champion Justin Leonard, who had registered two 6s on the finishing
hole out of the Barrie burn, joined Lawrie in the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   This gets Lawrie into the Masters, the PGA Championship next
month at Medinah, the Dunhill Cup at nearby St. Andrews, and the
World Cup, where he will team with Colin Montgomerie and represent
their country. Montgomerie has been Scotland's best golfer over the
past decade, but Lawrie now has something Montgomerie has failed to
win _ one of golf's four major championships.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Van de Velde let it get away, when he
was on the verge of giving France its most notable golfing triumph
since amateur Catherine Lacoste won the US Women's Open in 1967.
After the triple, Van de Velde took a double bogey on the first
playoff hole and a bogey out of the bunker on the second hole.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrie, who vaulted to second on the European Ryder Cup team
standings that will defend against the United States at The Country
Club in Brookline, Mass., in September, closed with a 67. This for
a player known as an underachiever.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who say that to me,'' said Lawrie.
``I've been given a hard time for being an underachiever. I
practice hard. I practice my chipping and short game a lot. I'm
trying hard. I'm working hard at my game. Sometimes I don't get as
much out of my game as I maybe should, but I don't really know why
that is. Yeah, a lot of people have told me that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel my career is just starting. I think the win in Qatar
was the breakthrough. I feel as though I can compete with these
guys on a regular basis. If you can't get yourself up for playing
in the biggest tournament in the world, then there's something
wrong with you. You know, the best players in the world are here
and you want to beat them. You want to compete with them and you
want to show them that you can play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
