<HEADLINE>
HUMMING ECONOMY, FUNDAMENTALS FIRING UP SMALLER TECH FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who pays even the slightest attention to the stock market
knows that the big technology companies are flying high. Microsoft
last week topped $500 billion in market value; Lucent, Cisco, and
IBM are all worth more than $200 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the news has also been good at lower altitudes for smaller
technology companies, including a long list of Massachusetts firms.
Netegrity of Waltham has seen its stock price appreciate more than
twentyfold since October. LTX Corp. of Westwood, Mass. is up more
than tenfold. Helix Technology Corp. of Mansfield, Mass. and Cognex
Corp. of Natick, Mass. have both more than tripled in value.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph of the little guys raises two obvious questions:
What's driving it and is it too late to still jump in?
</P>
<P>
   A little background is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Last October was an awful time for the stock market. The
collapse of the Russian economy and the near collapse of Long Term
Capital Management, a hedge fund, convinced investors that the sky
was falling. Technology stocks got clobbered; little technology
stocks were obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything got overdone,'' says John Golden, a technology
analyst with John Hancock Funds.
</P>
<P>
   There was some method to the madness. In difficult times, small
companies frequently lose market share to their bigger,
better-financed competitors. Under those circumstances, investors
get nervous. They keep the names they know and dump the ones they
don't.
</P>
<P>
   But as 1999 began investor sentiment started to shift. The sky
didn't actually fall. The news from most Third World countries was
better than expected. The US economy kept chugging along. ``It was
as if someone turned on a switch and said it is okay to buy
small-cap stocks again,'' says Jon Hickman, a money manager with
Jurika &AMP; Voyles in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Small-cap stocks have done well this year after several years of
poor performance. Small technology companies have done better
still, in part, because the fundamentals of the business are
improving.
</P>
<P>
   Take semiconductors, an industry that can go from feast to
famine practically overnight. Last year was famine time. This year
the food has returned. Orders have rebounded, driven by a better
economic picture and strong growth in the telecommunications
business.
</P>
<P>
   Big companies, like Boston's Teradyne, which makes test
equipment for the industry, have seen the improvement. But enough
crumbs have spilled from the table for the little guys to eat well
too.
</P>
<P>
   A surprisingly large number of Massachusetts companies are
suppliers to the industry. Local beneficiaries of the upturn
include LTX, Applied Science and Technology, IBIS Technology, PRI
Automation, Brooks Automation, Helix, and Cognex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rode the downside in '98 and we are following the pickup in
'99,'' says Richard Morin, chief financial officer at Cognex, a
maker of vision systems. Morin notes that most participants at last
week's big semiconductor trade show in California were quite
bullish, a suggestion that the good times could continue for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   A few local Internet companies have also enjoyed big gains this
year. Netegrity, the big winner, makes products that control user
access to e-commerce on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Project Software of Bedford got the market's attention this
spring when it said it was forming a subsidiary, mro.com, which
will help companies manage inventory over the Internet. The
announcement noted that the subsidiary will ``have increasing
losses over the next several quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Those magic words were enough to double the stock price in a
two-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Where do we go from here? Most analysts say that while the best
gains are behind us there are still opportunities to make money.
Fred Wolf, an analyst with Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill, recommends ADE
Corp., a Westwood semiconductor supplier that has experienced only
a modest run-up in its stock price so far.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the economic fundamentals for the second half of the
year should provide support to the little tech companies. Assuming
the world economy stays on track and the Federal Reserve doesn't
hike interest rates dramatically, these money managers say the
stocks can continue to do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this will last,'' says Hickman of Jurika &AMP; Voyles.
``We've had three years of underperformance by small-cap stocks.
Maybe we're ready for three years of outperformance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
