<SLUG> BC-POP-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO OZ WITH EYES WIDE WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unforeseen disaster whisks a wide-eyed innocent away from the
doldrums of a black-and-white home. Family, and all that is
familiar, are forsaken in search of something grander. Meeting
several loyal compatriots and strange characters along the way, the
naif is plunged into a world of temptation, wonder, and danger,
only to discover, when all is said and done, there's no place like
home.
</P>
<P>
   We spent 2 1/2 years expecting ``Eyes Wide Shut'' to be a
masterpiece. What we got is a silly, sexed-up version of ``The
Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' the last work by acclaimed filmmaker Stanley
Kubrick, may have been ``inspired'' by the 1926 novella
``Traumnovelle,'' by Arthur Schnitzler, but it plays like a
decadent twist on the beloved 1939 classic. It's Tom Cruise as
Dorothy, Manhattan's Upper West Side subbing for Kansas, and Chris
Isaak's ``Baby Did a Bad Bad Thing'' instead of Judy Garland's
``Over the Rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the tornado that snatches Dorothy away, Cruise's Dr.
William Harford is blown asunder by his wife revelation's that she
briefly considered kicking everything to the curb _ her marriage,
her daughter, her tony Manhattan digs _ for a roll in the hay with
a dishy naval officer she spied while she and hubby were on a Cape
Cod vacation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a ripe setup, disturbing all those uncomfortable places
where we silently question our partner's fidelity, how well we know
the person, and by extension, how well we know ourselves. It isn't
enough, however, to send a sane man off in search of sexual
misadventure. Yet, there's Cruise straying from his Central Park
West comforts for a nefarious Oz netherworld in Greenwich Village,
and especially a castlelike mansion where rich people don masks,
and engage in what I guess passes for doin' the nasty among the
financially flush. At this rate ``Eyes Wide Shut'' may replace Pink
Floyd's ``Dark Side of the Moon'' as the favored trippy companion
piece to ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Kubrick died in March, there's no way of telling whether
this tedious, somnambulistic version of ``Eyes Wide Shut'' in
theaters is what he intended audiences to see. Kubrick was a
notorious tweaker, known to fiddle with his films until the last
possible moment _ and sometimes beyond, as was the case with ``The
Shining,'' on which Kubrick performed a nip-and-tuck after its
opening in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   It's already been reported that, to avoid a kiss-of-death NC-17
rating from the mean ol' Motion Picture Association of America,
some digital characters were added to obscure certain sexual acts
during an orgy scene. Those involved with the film maintain that
Kubrick approved the changes, but whether he did or didn't hardly
matters. Adding a naughty minute of skin wouldn't have made this
film any more interesting. Sold as a thought-provoking erotic
thriller, it is not erotic _ this is cold, sterile antisex _ and
the only thought the film provokes is, ``This is how Kubrick spent
the last years of his life?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' George Lucas will be happy to hear, now
holds the distinction as most disappointing film of the summer.
Don't be fooled by those touting this as Kubrick's final
``masterpiece.'' If Kubrick had stopped making films after 1971's
``A Clockwork Orange,'' that would have been his final masterpiece.
This pretentious piffle most certainly isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Second Coming would have trouble living up to the
tsunami of hype ``Eyes Wide Shut'' has received _ magazine covers,
endless Internet speculation, and toothy Tom Cruise making his
prerecorded rounds on the talk-show circuit are just a teaspoon's
worth. But then, people had a right to expect a lot. Kubrick has
made some of the great films in history, including ``Dr.
Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb,''
``Paths of Glory,'' ``A Clockwork Orange'' and ``2001: A Space
Odyssey.'' ``Eyes Wide Shut'' was his first since 1987's ``Full
Metal Jacket,'' and his usual adherence to complete secrecy from
the prying public only made people mull over that much more any
morsel of information, regardless of its veracity. (Turns out most
of what leaked out was dead wrong, although the rumored script
would have made a better movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the titillating possibilities offered by watching
Cruise and his wife, Nicole Kidman, playing a married couple locked
in a psychological, erotic drama. Even if it were just a movie, it
seemed a delicious invitation into the lives of one of Hollywood's
most intensely private couples.
</P>
<P>
   But, to borrow from Gertrude Stein, there's no there there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it seems as if Kubrick may have spent too much time on
his decade-long filmmaking hiatus watching Dorothy and the gang
make their way to Emerald City. And lest you think I've spent too
much time in the poppy field, there are several rainbow references
in the film; one woman, seeking a tryst with Cruise, even invites
him to ``go where the rainbow ends.''
</P>
<P>
   So as he makes his way up the neon-splashed Yellow Brick Road of
London _ a poor stand-in for the film's New York setting _ Kidman
is the left-at-home Auntie Em. And as stagnant as her chemistry is
with Cruise on screen, she might as well play his aunt. The
Scarecrow, Tin Man, and Cowardly Lion are transformed into any
number of very attractive, very naked women (all the nudity, of
course, is of the female variety: so tired, so trite) escorting
Cruise through his fanciful journey; Sydney Pollack, as one of
Cruise's patients, is Glinda the Good Witch, (well, sort of,
considering his taste for hookers), who helps Cruise see that
everything he's looking for is right in his own backyard, uh,
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   And at the center of it all, hovering just beyond reach, is
Kubrick as the mysterious Wizard _ all smoke and mirrors, rewrites,
and reshoots _ who, as unveiled with his final film, has very
little worth paying attention to behind the curtain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1329EDT &QL; 
