<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CUP COMPETITION SERVED WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Toni Baume went home speechless but happy. She had
sacrificed her voice for her country, and what more could Australia
ask of a woman?
</P>
<P>
   For three days Toni, the wife of Australian Consul General
Michael Baume, had given new meaning to the term ``siren song.''
Her sturdy soprano, issuing from the first row of Longwood Cricket
Club's south stand, kept piercing the general din of the weekend
Davis Cup series with encouragement and consolation: ``Good on you,
mate! No worries, Aussie!''
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll recover,'' said her less vocal husband as they headed
back to New York. ``But it was worth it.'' She nodded in agreement,
and may have a future winning hog-calling contests in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Australian win on the tennis court made up for a
defeat in Washington and the angry voices raised at home by
President Clinton's upping the tariff on Aussie lamb?
</P>
<P>
   ``Welll . . . '' Baum smiled, ``about that we say, `Baaa,
humbug!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Their flesh-peddling agents will likely tell you that the price
has gone up, too, on Aussie beef, Patrick Rafter and Lleyton
Hewitt. Nothing sheepish about the way those two go for the
jugular. Wolves in short clothing, although Hewitt's baggies
contain enough cloth to make a Marblehead mainsail.
</P>
<P>
   One of his illustrious Davis Cup predecessors, compatriot Roy
Emerson, is amused. Emmo used to cut the pockets out of his shorts
to diminish even the slightest bit of cloth weighted by sweat.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of sweat on or off court during the
feverish clash that brought out the town's appetite for pro tennis.
The sellouts were antidotes to the sound of doldrumming that some
had interpreted as a death rattle for the game in a neighborhood
that stands forth as the fountainhead of American tennis.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the US Tennis Association was wavering on bringing a
Davis Cup series to Boston, afraid that Longwood might not be able
to handle it. Only months ago, as one of the few private clubs
maintaining a foothold in pro tennis, Longwood considered folding
its US Pro tournament, the Aug. 23-29 date on the ATP World Tour.
To the rescue galloped a Boston promoter, Woolf Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm of the weekend and the first-rate cooperative
presentation by Longwood and the USTA appeared to have a
revitalizing effect. Club president Steve Roiter is savoring ``the
feeling that tennis is making a comeback. Our ticket sales for the
US Pro are very favorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is the to-be-continued Jim Courier story. Courier
sat in the locker room Sunday yearning for a Todd Martin victory
over Rafter that would have set up a decisive winner-take-all
battle for him and Hewitt. His call to duty never came. But Jim
will resurface in the Bean for the US Pro, and Martin and Hewitt
are being lobbied. Dominik Hrbaty and Felix Mantilla, French Open
semifinalists this year and last, respectively, have been signed
up, and James Blake, NCAA runner-up in May, is deserting Harvard to
accept a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   When guys the caliber of the Yanks and Aussies, from Sampras and
Rafter throughout, compete so relentlessly, yet uncomplainingly and
respectfully of their foes, you have the essence of what Dwight
Davis envisioned when he sent the grand old crock into circulation
in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   The progenitor's charming 85-year-old daughter, Helen Davis
Hermes of West Reading Conn., sweltered joyfully along with
everyone else for three days in an open grandstand. But Sunday
evening, like numerous hackers, she felt it was high time ``I got
back to my own game. Not moving to my left as well these days, but
I'll never stop playing.'' Why should anyone?
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Sampras stopped playing singles after Wimbledon
was, of course, costly to the US. Losing to Australia was no
disgrace. However, it was disappointing that Sampras, captain Tom
Gullikson and other team members lost sight of the large picture:
American tennis as a whole. What a tremendous lift victory would
have given the game over here, putting them in the semis against
Russia, and in position to win the whole thing, what with ordinary
France and Belgium in the opposite half.
</P>
<P>
   By going along with Pete's announced plan to confine himself to
doubles, they crippled themselves at that starting gate. It should
have been settled at Wimbledon, where Martin publicly suggested
that Sampras take his place. But thinking doubles-only, Pete didn't
condition himself to labor three straight days. Learning of the
fiery weather forecast, he may also have feared coming apart
somewhere in three matches blanketed by intense heat. His genetic
dysfunction, thalassemia, that can cause anemia, may have undone
him on other occasions when he's been overextended.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless Pete nearly made it into the third day as a
stand-in when the US team physician, Dr. David Altchek, said that
Martin was unfit to play against Rafter. The decision fell to a
Bostonian, Dr. Rich Paul, the International Tennis
Federation-appointed neutral physician, who had final say in the
matter of substitution because of physical impairment.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow Longwood member suggested that Paul might be,
understandably, a homer. ``How is he going to turn down a US
captain trying to put Sampras into the match in the USA? Now that's
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although you can usually find a doctor to certify anything, Paul
didn't choke. He declared Martin able. So Todd was. At least until
he'd toiled mightily for 3 hours and led, 4-2, in the fifth set,
whereupon his legs wobbled, betraying his heart. Hippocrates would
have faxed Dr. Paul, an orthopedic surgeon: ``Your backhand may be
suspect, but you did nothing backhanded.''
</P>
<P>
   This recalls a similar Cup situation in 1974, Romania at Italy
in Mestre. Italy led, 2-1, when the Romanians requested a
substitute for Ion Tiriac. Tiriac, onetime player-coach of the
since-departed Boston Lobsters, may have been a rugged character,
but he was suffering a painful kidney stone attack. The examining
physician, an Italian, naturally turned down the Romanians.
Hobbling about, Tiriac was beaten by Corrado Barazzutti, 6-3, 6-0,
6-0.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor, proclaiming himself a specialist, said he had
examined Tiriac thoroughly and was highly qualified in such
matters. He was a gynecologist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
