<HEADLINE>
ADDO'S UP FOR MATCH AGAINST AJAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Addo should know better than most of his Revolution
teammates what to expect when they meet Ajax Football Club in an
exhibition Wednesday night at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This will be an evaluation game for Addo, 27, who played in the
Dutch League before moving to Ethnikos in Greece, which confirmed
his release Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Addo, 27, is a central defender who appears to have the class,
skill, and speed to complement Dan Calichman and fortify the
Revolution defense for the second half of the MLS season. Addo
might have broken in with a less difficult test, but he is
welcoming the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ajax is one of the best teams in the world,'' Addo said.
``They are changing a lot of players because they weren't happy
with how last season went, so I don't know how they will be. But
they are always well-organized and they always play the same
system. You have to fit into their system to play for them. So you
might be the best player in the world but you won't play for them
if you don't fit into the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's always great to play against Ajax because they play
the ball. They are not in a hurry to score because they know they
will get their chance. They like to possess the ball, and that is
the style I like to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Addo has had little difficulty acclimating to the Revolution. He
has been playing in Europe _ Stuttgart and Frankfurt (Germany),
Sparta Rotterdam (Holland), Belenenses (Portugal), Ethnikos _ and
before that he attended George Mason University in Fairfax, Va. His
friends and teammates have included US national team members Gregg
Berhalter and Claudio Reyna and his collegiate opponents included
US coach Bruce Arena, formerly at the University of Virginia and
D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Arena attempted to bring Addo to D.C. United after the
1996 Olympics, after Addo had helped Ghana advance to the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to come back here and play,'' Addo said. ``I
always take my vacations here and my girlfriend lives in the US. I
know a lot of guys in the MLS and I want to help raise the level of
the league. It's good now, and I think I can help bring more
professionalism and I would love to be a part of the league's
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have come here in 1996 but the contract terms were not
satisfactory then, and I had some other good offers in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Addo hoped to play in Italy and was negotiating with Cagliari
and Padova, but ended up at Castel Di Sangro, recently promoted to
Serie B. He seemed set for the team, but at the last minute was
sent away by coach Osvaldo Jaconi, and became involved in the
recently-published ``The Miracle of Castel Di Sangro'' by Joe
McGinniss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it there and all the players liked me,'' Addo said.
``They saw the skill and professionalism I brought to the team but
all of a sudden I was gone. I was told not to ask any questions. It
wasn't a big deal for me but I would have liked to stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than be turned off by his Italian experience, Addo felt
compelled to pursue the chance to play for the Revolution's Italian
coaches, Walter Zenga and Giuseppe Galderisi. He is also
anticipating returning to action for Ghana's national team, coached
by Italian Giuseppe Dossena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 34 caps for Ghana but it was getting hard to go back
and forth to Africa, so I told the coach I needed to concentrate on
playing for a good club,'' Addo said. ``That's what Ghana's other
defenders are doing _ Sammy Kuffour (Bayern Munich), Mohammed Gargo
(Udinese), Alex Nyarko (Lens). The MLS standard is good enough,
plus the coaches here have European professional experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Ghana is known for the high skill level of its players,
the country has never qualified for the World Cup finals. Addo was
among the first from his country to receive a chance to play in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in the streets, scraping my elbows and knees, and
didn't have a pair of shoes until I was 14,'' Addo said. ``But we
always knew how to play. We only need to stop the corruption, and
an African country will win the World Cup someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
