<HEADLINE>
VICTORY A THRILL FOR BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boys from Brazil are back. A year after their disappointing
France '98 World Cup final, the Brazilians captured the Copa
America title with a 3-0 victory over Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Most countries went with revamped, young teams as a buildup to
World Cup 2002 qualifying. Uruguay went a step further, fielding a
team of local players under coach Victor Pua, who is scheduled to
cede the job to Argentine Daniel Passarella. But the surprising
finish by the Uruguayans raised the stock of both Pua and the
young, unknown players. Uruguay continues to produce dozens of
top-level professionals despite being the smallest country in the
South American Confederation.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil coach Wanderley Luxemburgo also went in a new direction.
Though the names are familiar _ Rivaldo and Ronaldo, top scorers in
the tournament with five goals; defenders Cafu and Roberto Carlos;
midfielders Emerson, Flavio Conceicao, Ze Roberto _ this is still a
relatively young squad.
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo, suspended after being red-carded against Mexico early
in the tournament, scored twice in the final in Asuncion and his
performance was compared to Zinedine Zidane's in the World Cup
final. Zidane had been suspended for two games but returned to
score twice in a 3-0 victory for France over Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The result also contributed to Brazil's continuing campaign to
make up for its incredible defeat against Uruguay in the 1950 World
Cup final, the only time the tournament has been held in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the new campaigns start.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil will begin its World Cup 2002 quest with a home match
against Ecuador in March. The qualifying tournament format has been
changed to a one-group, home-and-away round-robin, meaning South
American countries will be playing 18 qualifiers, twice as many as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   And, this week Brazil is sending a group of former World Cup
champion captains to FIFA headquarters in Zurich to bid for the
2006 World Cup finals. The tournament has not been held in South
America since Argentina '78 and will not likely return until a
later date, but this is a political move designed to keep the
continent on the agenda with FIFA's powerful European members.
</P>
<P>
   After Brazil won the USA '94 tournament, it was pointed out to
Julio Grondona, president of the Associacion del Futbol Argentino,
that South America had a disproportionate number of finalists _
five out of 10 members. Grondona replied: ``Our continent has won
eight World Cups, and no continent has won more. That is why we
deserve to have that many places.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bolivia and Brazil are preparing for the
anti-climactic Confederations Cup. Brazil opens the tournament
against Germany Saturday, then meets the US July 28 in Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   Bolivia's Argentine coach, Hector Veira, called the tournament
``a truly crazy thing'' because his team will play three games in 4
1/2 days. Even the host country, Mexico, threatened to pull out of
the event as its players protested the suspension of Paulo Cesar
Chavez and Raul Rodrigo Lara after they tested positive for an
anabolic steroid.
</P>
<P>
   Only the underdogs _ Egypt, New Zealand, Saudi Arabia, the US _
appear to be taking the event seriously.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   College try not enough
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Title IX was good for soccer while it lasted. But the
Educational Amendments Act of 1972 can only take the game so far.
Other countries have nearly caught up to the US women's national
team in less than a decade by bypassing any equivalent of Title IX
and simply promoting the game on the club level.
</P>
<P>
   If Brazil and China continue to improve at this rate, the US
will have to take a harder look at its development system.
</P>
<P>
   Collegiate programs will always struggle to prepare athletes for
high-level professional soccer _ unless the hypocrisy of the system
is acknowledged and modified.
</P>
<P>
   In the US, collegiate sports are virtually professional in
everything but name. If collegiate sports teams were allowed to
compete outside their bailiwick, some interesting results might
occur. For instance, they could enter teams in the US Open Cup
competition. Maybe they could provide an upset, as the Mid Michigan
Bucks nearly did in a 2-1 loss to the Tampa Bay Mutiny, and as the
Staten Island Vipers did in a 3-2 overtime victory over the
MetroStars last week.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no room for 19th-century notions of amateurs being
tainted by professionalism in the next century. FIFA dispensed with
that by establishing the World Cup as a global soccer tournament
outside the Olympics in 1930. Soccer has the capacity to continue
to show the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
