<HEADLINE>
SPEED KING? IT'S `TRUE'
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Yes It's True, a 3-year-old, established himself as the top
sprinter in the country when he captured the $300,000 DeFrancis
Dash at Laurel Saturday, defeating older rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The DeFrancis Dash is one of the few Grade I sprints and marked
the sixth win this year for Yes It's True, a son of Is It True. All
of his tallies have come in graded sprint events. Ridden by Jerry
Bailey, Yes It's True sat third off a speed duel in the DeFrancis,
then rallied four-wide into the stretch to outfinish Good And Tough
and prevail by three-quarters of a length at odds of 7-10 ($3.40 to
win). The time of 1:08 3/5 for 6 furlongs was just three ticks off
the track record.
</P>
<P>
   Good And Tough, a top 4-year-old who won the Suffolk Downs
Breeders' Cup May 29, had to give Yes It's True 9 pounds under the
allowance conditions, 123 to 114, making the task of the 17-10
second choice most dificult. Good And Tough came up the rail under
Shane Sellers, but he wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Yes It's True is trained by D. Wayne Lukas, who will be inducted
into the Hall of Fame at Saratoga Aug. 9, and Lukas is going
straight for the Eclipse Award with the bay colt, who is owned by
the Padua Stables of Satish Sanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go on and win the championship with him,'' said
Lukas. ``He's a great physical specimen, and he truly typifies what
a great sprinter should be. He has the ability to adjust to
different surfaces every time. We've really been enjoying the
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanan bought Yes It's True, who was a $200,000 yearling, for
$800,00 as a 2-year-old in training, and Yes It's True gave Sanan
his first Grade I victory. Yes It's True was an outstanding
2-year-old, as long as the distances were short. He came into the
Breeders' Cup Juvenile at Churchill Downs with a record of 8-5-2-1,
but the mile and one-16th was too much for him, and he faded to
11th after setting the pace. This year, Yes It's True won the Swale
at Gulfstream, and the Lafyette at Keeneland, but his flirtation
with the Triple Crown events ended when he couldn't even handle the
flat mile of the Kentucky Derby Trial, finishing fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who was in the process of training Charismatic to victory
in the Derby and Preakness, recognized he had a pure sprinter on
his hands, and entered Yes It's True in the Maryland Breeders' Cup
Handicap, on the Preakness undercard at Pimlico. That is the race
made famous when a man walked on the track and interfered with the
stretch run, but the intruder's actions didn't affect Yes It's
True, who was clear on the fence and sailing to an easy victory.
Yes It's True ran right past the man, who then impeded the horses
battling for second.
</P>
<P>
   Yes It's True proceeded from there to take the Riva Ridge at
Belmont June 5, and Jersey Shore at Monmouth June 19. He has a
record of 17-11-2-2, and has earned more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Reraise, the top sprinter in California who won the $1 million
Breeders' Cup Sprint last year, was recently retired to injury, and
Kelly Kip, winner of the 1998 Suffolk Breeders' Cup, generally
regarded as the fastest horse in the East, is also battling
injuries and may be finished, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Yes It's True now stands alone atop the division, and Lukas has
already laid out a clear path for him. Next will be the A
Phenomenon at Saratoga Aug. 11, followed by the King's Bishop at
The Spa Aug. 28, and the Vosburgh at Belmont Sept. 25. That will
put Yes It's True within hailing distance of the Breeders' Cup at
Gulfstream Park Nov. 6, which will likely decide the trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of studs
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm and Charismatic, the two horses who just missed
winning the Triple Crown for owners Bob and Beverly Lewis have been
assigned to stud. Silver Charm, age 5, will go to Three Chimneys in
Midway, Ky., and stand for $25,000; while Charismatic, 3, will go
to Lane's End, in Versailles, Ky., and stand for $35,000. ``We're
extremely pleased to have our near Triple Crown winner standing
alongside noted Triple Crown winner Seattle Slew,'' said Bob Lewis
of Silver Charm . . . Buck's Boy, last year's Eclipse Award-winning
turf horse who has not run since winning the $2 million Breeders'
Cup Turf in November, has arrived at trainer Noel Hickey's barn at
Hawthorne after recovering from a stomach ailment. ``He was sent to
me in Florida in mid-January,'' said Hickey. ``A few weeks later,
he developed an abscess in his stomach, and I took him out of
training. (Owner) George Bunn wanted him back at his farm in
Illinois, and he has been there ever since. I understand he has
been in training for the last 65 days.'' Hickey has yet to devise a
game plan for Buck's Boy, but hopes he will be able to defend his
Breeders' Cup championship . . . Val's Prince, a prominent grass
horse last year before fracturing his left front sesamoid while
finishing second in the Sword Dancer in August, returned to the
races with a second-place finish in an allowance at Belmont Friday.
``He underwent surgery, and the doctors also removed an old chip
that he had in his right front ankle,'' said trainer Jimmy Picou.
``He proved that he's a tough racehorse, and we've got big plans
for him.'' Picou hopes to start Val's Prince, age 7, in the Sword
Dancer (Aug. 14) again, then go on to the Turf Classic at Belmont
Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Durkin calls it quits
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Durkin, the popular voice of the New York Racing Association
and the Breeders' Cup, has resigned from calling the races at
Gulfstream Park. Durkin's move comes shortly after the volatile
Frank Stronach purchased the Hallendale, Fla., track for $95
million. ``Only about 5 percent of my decision had to do with
that,'' said Durkin, who had called at Gulfstream for five years.
``I had only planned to work at Gulfstream one more year, and I
felt, with the change in administration, that it would have looked
bad for everybody if I had resigned after just one season. Leaving
Gulfstream will allow me more time to focus attention on my two
most important professional priorities, New York racing and the
Breeders' Cup. Equally important, the lighter work load will allow
me more time at home in New York, and more time for personal
development.'' No word yet on who might succeed Durkin, but Larry
Colmus, who calls at Suffolk and Monmouth, is one of the best in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks and the
Daily Racing Form was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
