<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PRINCE-BOS &LR;      07-20 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PRINCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CYNICAL LOOK AT AMERICAN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT L. TURNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE NEW PRINCE 
By Dick Morris 
Renaissance Books, 256 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reviewer approaches Dick Morris's new book with caution, as
one would a mangy dog. Is it clean? Is it dangerous?
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Prince,'' it turns out, is even scruffier than it
looks, but its contents are essentially harmless _ except in the
unlikely event that anyone would take them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Appearances count. The cheesy faux-parchment cover of the book
is adorned with an enormous faux-Florentine ``P'' giving the
impression of a put-on. Can it be that this hurried book from
President Clinton's infamous political manipulator is just for
laughs? No, the cover promises a serious tract ``in the spirit of
Machiavelli's classic work on statecraft and government'' written
by the great Italian's ``modern equivalent.''
</P>
<P>
   What the book delivers is a deeply cynical perspective on
American politics from its most notoriously sleazy practitioner.
Morris says essentially that the way to lead is to give the people
what they want. Every president, governor and mayor, he says,
``needs a popular majority every day in his term.'' The way to
achieve this is simple: Take polls, and follow them.
</P>
<P>
   One variation on this theme: women candidates, according to
Morris, ``should be Thatcheresque in their positions on crime,
taxes and defense.'' It matters not, apparently, what these women
candidates might believe. A ``leader's'' own goals can become a
factor, but only if carefully circumscribed and packaged.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers may suffer a twinge of sympathy for Morris because
it seems his book could not have had an editor. Many high schoolers
can write better _ at least 42 grammatical and syntactical gaffes
clog his text. And a sixth-grader knows to avoid cliches _ or at
least if one seems necessary, then don't repeat it _ certainly not
six times in 150 pages, as Morris does with Thoreau's ``different
drummer.'' Slapdash Dick didn't bother to check the spelling of
Democratic consultant Bob Beckel (``Bekel'') or US Senator George
Voinovich (``Voinivitch'').
</P>
<P>
   It might be possible to overlook slips, but Morris's
contradictions and factual errors too often make a hash of what is
supposed to be his argument. He says President Clinton's 1994
health care initiative failed partly because it was too bold, but
has ``happened incrementally'' since. This will be news to the 4
million more persons who are uninsured today. Likewise, he says
that national student testing was defeated when the proposal called
for mandatory tests, but says this changed when Clinton agreed to
voluntary tests. Wrong again: Republicans, including Morris client
Trent Lott, have killed all national test proposals.
</P>
<P>
   And what lesson is the reader to draw from Morris's views of one
modern president? He writes, ``Harry Truman did an inestimable
disservice to politics by popularizing the notion that the public
likes a feisty candidate who `gives 'em hell.' They don't. Voters
feel such candidates are irresponsible, negative windbags who don't
have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Six pages later: ``As Truman gained popularity, his feistiness,
aggressiveness, willingness to speak plainly, and his tendency to
`give 'em hell' endeared him to voters. A new form of charisma
attached itself to his personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Patient readers will find a few sensible nuggets. Morris
observes that both Hillary Rodham Clinton and Al Gore have enlarged
the roles of their jobs, perhaps permanently, while the national
parties continue to diminish their own roles. And Morris is right
in saying the press would perform a valuable service if it took
more seriously its function in policing campaigns. Still, nothing
is insightful enough to take attention away from Morris's inane
attempts at self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Most galling is the passing reference he makes to his tawdry
role in the Monica Lewinsky scandal. When Clinton called as the
story broke, Morris writes, ``I urged him to consider telling the
truth.'' Yet several accounts, including the report of Kenneth
Starr, whose office took grand jury testimony from Morris, give a
different story. After taking a quick survey for Clinton, Starr
reported, ``Mr. Morris explained that the poll results suggested
that the president should not go public with a confession or
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   The book does not deserve actual comparison with ``The Prince.''
Suffice it to say the Machiavelli is entertaining to read and
offers both wisdom and heart along with his steely advice _ all
beyond Morris's reach.
</P>
<P>
   Tossed in at the end of ``The New Prince'' is a snapshot of a
tubby Morris looking very small in front of Machiavelli's tomb in
Florence. Read Morris's book and he'll become even smaller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
