<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-20 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EVOLUTION OF `DEVOLUTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the time, devolution trots onstage to play a sober
geopolitical role _ describing the transfer of powers, for example,
from the United Kingdom to local governments in Scotland, Wales,
and Northern Ireland. But devolution (along with its verb form,
devolve) has a lighter side, too. We use it to suggest our species
is losing its grip on civilization, or vice versa: ``White tie and
tails have all but vanished from the fund-raising scene here, which
is as lamentable a devolution of style as can be imagined,'' wrote
the Globe's John Robinson in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is amused. Skip Ascheim, a Globe correspondent
who writes about theater, puts the jocular devolve first on his
list of bugbears, above comprise for compose, reticent for
reluctant, and nonplused for blase. These are bad enough, he
writes, but ``particularly grotesque'' is using of devolve ``as if
it meant de-evolve _ assuming there is such a concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Does this devolve deserve to be deep-sixed? First, the short
answer: History is on its side. Devolution, meaning degeneration,
surfaces in an 1882 citation in the Oxford English Dictionary: ``If
there be e-volution, there surely is de-volution, a degradation of
the species.'' The meaning is still current in Webster's 3rd
unabridged dictionary (1961), which gives ``retrograde evolution''
as a definition of devolution. And a mere 17 years later, along
comes the rock group Devo, short for devolution _ the band's
``dystopian notion of backward progress,'' as one reporter
summarized it.
</P>
<P>
   So the popular senses of devolve and devolution have been with
us for more than a century. There is, indeed, such a concept _ but
do you want it in your vocabulary?
</P>
<P>
   The answer depends partly on what you think of evolution. Long
before Darwin, the word _ whose root meaning is ``unroll, roll
out'' _ had a variety of meanings related to unfolding or
development, whether of organisms or logical arguments. As
evolutionary theory was refined, these older meanings marched
alongside the newer ones: Darwin himself referred to ``the gradual
evolution of the young animal or plant from its egg or seed.'' But
evolution by natural selection was something else entirely, and
unlike the growth of a chicken from an egg, it did not imply any
kind of progress.
</P>
<P>
   So strictly speaking, for Stephen Jay Gould and his colleagues
in the evolution game, there is no ``devolution.'' Organisms adapt
or die out, and some adapt in more complex ways than others, but
things don't get better or worse by evolving; they just get
different. If the Earth's conditions changed to favor survival of
the less sapient members of Homo sapiens, the species might flunk
 &UR; today &LR; 's SATs, but evolution would call it a success.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us, though, don't speak strictly about evolution.
Whether we think human beings were planted atop the Great Chain of
Being by God, like the couple on a wedding cake, or are _ like all
other surviving species _ the result of random events, we feel as
if we're on top of the world. That image of our long climb from the
primordial slime is as powerful as any creation myth, and here we
are, with our Miatas and our laptops and our own sweet selves;
science or no, it sure looks like progress. So we joke about whose
whose husband is ``more evolved'' _ that is, more sensitive and
egalitarian, further removed from his caveperson forebears _ even
if we know doing the laundry is probably neither adaptive nor
maladaptive in evolutionary terms.
</P>
<P>
   In the past couple of decades, such casual usage has spread _ a
story of a failure is headlined ``Devolution of a Deli,''
restaurant sauces and Garry Shandling are both described as ``very
evolved.'' Whatever it means _ and sometimes you wonder _ evolved
is clearly a compliment in everyday lingo, if not in science.
</P>
<P>
   Should we try to stamp out these usages? Well, science has a
defense for our imprecision about scientific concepts. Humankind,
says psycholinguist Steven Pinker, occupies ``the cognitive niche''
of the local habitat; we're clever enough to overcome our
deficiencies in other realms (smell, strength, and so on), and thus
we consider our deficiencies trivial. If we persist in talking as
if we're evolution's top dogs, that's because we evolved to think
that way; we're metaphor-making animals as well as reasoning
animals. And some days, even in an age of science, we find we need
the metaphors more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Word appears every other week through summer. Write Jan
Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
