<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA'S ICY SIDE REMAINS INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here it is the middle of July, the heart of what should be a
carefree summer, and death hangs in the air like a cloud bank too
heavy to be blown out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. is gone before we ever really knew what he
might become. His graceful wife and her accomplished sister died
with him. They crashed on the same weekend that, three years ago,
TWA Flight 800 exploded in its ascent over the shores of Long
Island, a calamity that nags even now.
</P>
<P>
   TWA is an airline, in short, that refuses to get things right.
Recall their actions in the aftermath of the July 17, 1996,
explosion of the 747 jet bound from John F. Kennedy Airport to
Paris that killed all 230 passengers and crew on board.
</P>
<P>
   The company's CEO was nowhere to be seen. When he did appear in
New York the day after the tragedy, he spoke for less than a minute
and abruptly left without answering questions or spending time with
the families.
</P>
<P>
   TWA didn't notify some families of the dead until 36 hours after
the explosion. Its toll-free information line was so understaffed
that frantic callers couldn't get through for hours, and when they
did, were offered no information about passenger identities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seven members of my family trying to get through,'' said
Frank Carven, a Maryland lawyer whose sister and nephew died. ``It
took from 9 p.m. to 1 a.m. to get through, and then I was put on
hold for 20 minutes. And the person on the other end was just
taking information. They kept saying, `I don't have that
information. I don't have that information. We'll get back to you.'
And of course, they never did.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was, in the words of some management consultants at
the time, a case study in how not to react to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   And the problems have continued over the years. When TWA
hurriedly planned a group memorial service for 15 passengers whose
remains could not be found, burying empty caskets in a Long Island
plot, families fumed.
</P>
<P>
   When TWA reluctantly agreed to fly family members to New York in
1997 for the first anniversary of the tragedy, executives initially
asked passengers to sign liability waivers in case of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold and cruel,'' Carven said Monday. ``That's been how
they've dealt with us all along.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, as the long investigation winds to an uncertain
completion, TWA is at it again. As families struggle with their
loss on the anniversary of far too many deaths, TWA is fighting a
request that it pay some of the exorbitant costs of warehousing the
wreckage of its downed plane.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jim Hall, the chairman of the National Transportation
Safety Board, publicly complained that TWA shirked federal requests
to contribute to the costs of recovering the plane's scattered
wreckage at sea and storing it during the investigation. The
government has paid $4.5 million a year to keep the reconstructed
wreckage at an aircraft plant in Calverton, N.Y. The cause of the
explosion is believed to be a mechanical failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They refused to participate at all, even though we
requested,'' Hall told reporters. To back up his point, he made
public a 1996 letter he sent to TWA requesting $5 million in
assistance, and he also produced TWA's letter of rejection. He
indicated that airlines have helped with such costs in the past.
</P>
<P>
   TWA executives have their reasons, and most of them probably
have to do with the company's finances. It was once one of the
premier international airlines in the world, the lone rival of Pan
Am. But now the company has been in and out of bankruptcy for
years, its stock is currently trading near a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was wholly inappropriate for TWA or any airline or
any private party to contribute to a congressionally funded
investigation,'' TWA spokesman Jim Brown said Monday. He said that
a private contribution might be perceived as having unduly
influenced the course of a federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Of the recovery costs, Brown said that because the plane was
lost at sea, aviation law doesn't require the airline to pay for
the search and collection of wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Questions remain over who now owns the plane and what will be
done with it when the investigation ends. Brown said, ``They've had
that wreckage for so long that we consider them to have ownership
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   How typically thoughtful. Tragedy brings out the best in some,
the worst in others _ a lesson to remember in a week when mourning
will be the way of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
