<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COSMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSMO'S LITTLE SISTER DOWNPLAYS S-E-X 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   X-rated board games. Man-melting sex moves. Women who snag
celebrity husbands. Cosmopolitan magazine has covered it all for
women since the liberating '60s. Now _ in a new crusade _ the racy
monthly is targeting teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Magazines, Cosmo's publisher, recently unveiled
CosmoGIRL!, a ``spunky kid sister'' magazine aimed at 12- to
17-year-olds. ``We are taking the original Cosmo formula created by
Helen Gurley Brown and adapting it for the teenage girl,'' says
Cathleen P. Black, Hearst president.
</P>
<P>
   What? A teen 'zine version of headlines like July's ``Sex Tricks
He's Never Seen Before'' and ``5 Perfect Pickup Lines''?
</P>
<P>
   Relax. As a little sister, CosmoGIRL! is decidedly virginal. The
first issue _ for August/September _ features a modest covergirl
(actress Melissa Joan Hart) in minimal makeup, a non-revealing tank
top, and khakis. Even her bellybutton is covered by a headline. The
stories are no more daring. Consider: ``Back-to-School Fashion
Blitz;'' ``The One Thing That Really Bugs Guys;'' and ``How to Get
an Easy A.'' The word orgasm appears only once, in a Dr. Ruth
column.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did our research, we found out that girls are very
embarrassed by sex stories. They don't want to read about it,''
says CosmoGIRL! editor Atoosa Rubenstein. ``We certainly will cover
sex as a health issue. But we're not about advice or anything else
on that topic. . . . I want it to be known that we are definitely
Cosmo's little sister but not in the way some people assume.''
</P>
<P>
   Why bother with a typical teen magazine at a time when
newsstands are filled with competitors like Teen People, Twist,
Girl, Jump, Seventeen, YM and Teen? Economics. Black says teenagers
in the United States spent, or encouraged their parents to spend,
almost $125 billion in 1998. ``This is a growing market and the
time is right for us to introduce this title,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein says CosmoGIRL! stands out because of its connection
to the legendary Cosmopolitan and its focus on the ``inner girl.''
``A lot of other magazines focus on the outer girl _ fashion and
beauty,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk to the reader about every relationship in her life.
Her changing body. The new way boys might be treating her. Issues
with her parents, other girls, popularity, self-esteem. I want to
address the language barrier that comes between mom and daughter.
When mom says she doesn't like your pants, it's not because she
hates you. My goal is to step in there as a big sister and give
them advice. I'm young enough to understand where they're at,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at 27, Rubenstein remembers her experiences growing up
on Long Island very well. In a nutshell: high school was miserable.
``I really felt it couldn't have gotten any worse. At camp, boys
beat me up. I didn't go to my prom. I took a job at Carvel's just
because I needed something to do the night of the prom. My friends
butted me out of conversations. Why? Because girls can be mean,''
she says, adding quietly, ``I think I'm going to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   In her editor's letter, Rubenstein describes herself as ``the
biggest loser in school. . . . I had the hairiest legs (Mom
wouldn't let me shave), the worst skin . . . and a Pinocchio nose.
. . . I could barely get the crossing guard to be nice to me, much
less get a date!'' The editor then points out her extremely bushy
eyebrows in an accompanying photo of her at 15 years old. ``Nice
eyebrows, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein majored in political science at Barnard College in
the early '90s. She interned at Sassy magazine before being hired
as a fashion assistant by Gurley Brown after graduation in 1993.
After that, she served in various roles as a fashion editor. When
Hearst conceived of CosmoGIRL!, Kate White, Cosmo's editor,
recommended Rubenstein for the job, much to her amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little pipsqueak of a girl who never believed in
herself. When I met with the president of the company, all I kept
saying was `What am I doing here with you?' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubenstein has signed on to the mission. Surrounded by a
staff of 20-somethings (and one 30-year-old), she works 16-hour
days sometimes, honing ideas like a money page that recommends ways
to make more money babysitting (teach the kids how to use the Web)
or how to turn a Sweet-16 $500 gift into $1,000 (invest in a mutual
fund).
</P>
<P>
   Her first issue profiled a teenaged entrepreneur, eating
disorder activists, and five girls who survived hardships and
changed their fates. ``These stories need to be heard,'' she says.
``When things are (bad), as we know they can be in teen life, it's
good to have these role models.''
</P>
<P>
   CosmoGIRL! hit newstands June 29 with an initial print run of
850,000. Two additional issues are expected in 1999. ``There's
nothing firm planned for 2000,'' says Rubenstein. ``We have our
fingers crossed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
