<SLUG> BC-TV-HBO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOOD TELEVISION, SIGN UP FOR HBO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ About five or so years ago my wife and I
ditched HBO. There was nothing really to watch, except for the same
movies over and over and over.
</P>
<P>
   We must not have been the only ones. Not much later HBO set out
in a ``definitely conscious'' effort to crank out more original
series, chairman and chief executive Jeff Bewkes told a gathering
of television critics last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago we set out to dramatically increase what we
could hopefully find in series,'' Bewkes said. ``We were looking
for the hour drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to this past spring. When the largest-grossing
movie of all time splashes across your television screen, it's big
news. But when HBO hosted the cable premiere in April of
``Titanic,'' it was not even close to the networks' most shining
moment of the season. Which, to HBO, was great news.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the premium movie outlet has now become the home
to premium series. Not fair series. Not good. Not very good. Great
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oz.'' ``Sex and the City.'' ``Arli$$.'' The late ``Larry
Sanders Show.'' ``Real Sports.'' Not a dog in the bunch. Can any
network make such a claim? Did we miss any? Oh yeah, just the best
show on television: ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the original movies, often good to stellar, as
well as first-time-on-television theater films. Although HBO costs
extra, it has become basic that cable viewers should shell out the
bucks. Once considered an overvalued luxury, HBO is riding a wave
that should make it the artistic envy of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it feels like a high-water mark,'' Bewkes said.
</P>
<P>
   HBO really has two seasons: summer, when shows like ``Oz'' and
``Sex and the City'' start up, and January (``The Sopranos'').
</P>
<P>
   This past week HBO highlighted special events coming up in the
fall, including Cher live in concert, and original movies like
``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge''; ``RKO 281,'' about the making of
the legendary movie ``Citizen Kane''; and ``Witness Protection,''
starring Forrest Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' justifiably a critics' fave, fell into HBO's
lap after Fox took a pass on the original script from David Chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get sent every busted script, every busted pilot,'' said
Chris Albrecht, president of HBO original programming. But Albrecht
said Chase rewrote the script for HBO. Added were the edgier
sensibilities (vulgarities, nudity) that is out of bounds even for
out-there Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did for Fox did not take full advantage of what he
could do for HBO,'' Albrecht said. Being a premium cable outlet
gives producers for HBO latitude that does not exist elsewhere. For
one, the absence of commercials allows more of a movie feel rather
than the traditional four-act, television drama.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the network is able to air shows with obscenities and
nudity, which in context allow for greater dramatic effect. Hey,
Tony Soprano needs to curse.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, HBO shoots most of its series on film, as opposed to
video before a live audience, a more expensive proposition but one
that gives its shows a distinct feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our mission ... is to do something different on
HBO,'' Bewkes said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year my wife and I did something different, too. We signed
up for HBO again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
