<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-JUDGES &LR;      07-20 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-JUDGES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGING THE CELLUCCI BENCH: MUCH EXPERIENCE, LITTLE DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Governor Paul Cellucci's 34 choices for new
judgeships, for the most part, have been a lot like him: non-Ivy
League, white, male, with years on end of practicing
bread-and-butter law in small towns, dabbling in politics, and
living in Central and Western Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern, unintentional or not, is subtly changing the face
of the state's courts from one that looked like his predecessor,
William F. Weld, who had a penchant for appointing federal
prosecutors, academicians, or those with blood as blue as his own.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Weld, while Michael S. Dukakis was governor,
Massachusetts was reputed to have a state judiciary that was
unusually well-tutored in legal theory.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's appointees, however, generally have more hands-on
experience than legal scholarship. His prototypical selection
offers a possible glimpse at two high-impact Supreme Judicial Court
appointments he will make by the end of the summer, from more than
three dozen resumes.
</P>
<P>
   While many in the legal community have praised the governor's
choices to other courts, saying they are seasoned judges who
understand people and the system, others see potential downsides
should the pattern hold for the SJC _ which Cellucci has a rare
opportunity to remake.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, his choices for the bench have hardly been
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   A review of the judicial files shows that less than a quarter of
the 34 new appointments were female. Two were black, and one was
Hispanic _ and they were named just before the election last
November, when diversity was a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   And with nearly half of the justices coming from communities
west of Inteerstate 495, some are questioning whether
accomplishments matter as much as connections and associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not plugged in . . . there are a lot of doors that
are still closed,'' said June Miles, a Dukakis-appointed justice at
Boston Juvenile Court and president of the 30-plus-member
Massachusetts Black Judges Conference, which represents a small
fraction of the state's 400 judges.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, eight of Cellucci's selections have held political
jobs, including Thomas J. Curley Jr., a member of the Massachusetts
Turnpike Authority board. At least one, Diane E. Moriarty, ran for
office, specifically mayor of Boston. Another, David B. Locke, is
the son of former Senate Republican leader David Locke.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph I. Macy, appointed to Taunton District Court, contributed
$13,000 in three years to Republican party causes, prompting a few
people who scrutinized his qualifications to question whether he
was trying to buy a judgeship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being involved in politics . . . doesn't hurt you,'' said
Ralph Boyd Jr., a member of the Judicial Nominating Committee and
an attorney at Goodwin Procter &AMP; Hoar.
</P>
<P>
   However, party affiliation does not appear to be an issue when
judicial candidates are winnowed out. Of the GOP governor's 34
justices, 19 are registered Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   More than party registration, Cellucci culls from district
attorneys' offices for ``judges who are going to apply the law, not
judges who are going to make law from the bench,'' said his
spokeswoman, Ilene Hoffer. ``And he looks for law-and-order types,
people with a background of putting victims' rights and concerns at
the top of their agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld had similar prosecutorial inclinations, although his
choices often came from the US attorney's office in Boston, which
he ran for years before making the leap into politics. He is now a
member of the New York firm of McDermott Will &AMP; Emery.
</P>
<P>
   It is not lost on many practicing lawyers that some of Weld's
lower court appointments, yanked from big law firms, were stunned
to discover they had to do their own typing when they became
judges.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's picks may not be as surprised, or as annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   And so lawyers are warmly greeting the subtle shift in judicial
personnel under Cellucci, although many like the Weld picks, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``For lawyers, they want judges who have been in a courtroom and
know how it operates,'' said Benjamin Fierro 3d of Lynch &AMP; Fierro
of Boston. ``I think the broader view is Paul Cellucci was an
active lawyer who practiced in the courts. . . . Bill Weld, I
wonder if he ever stepped foot in the state courts until he became
governor. Less so with ideology, but I think their backgrounds and
experiences may be reflected in their appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Boston College Law School, Cellucci, the
son of an immigrant car dealer, practiced family law at the small
Marlborough firm of Kittredge, Cellucci and Moreira. He settled
divorces, estates, and other issues before judges in the Worcester
area for 17 years, also serving in the Legislature for most of that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Grounded in that life experience, Cellucci admits a preference
for lawyers who work hard to get where they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like people who have had to overcome some adversity and
stuck with it,'' the governor said recently. ``I think they become
very good role models and very good judges. I certainly have worked
my way up the ladder. I don't think anyone can deny that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming up the hard way is a theme among many of his judicial
appointments. Although 27 of them passed the bar exam on the first
try, six of them took it twice, and one succeeded on her third
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Also, while the premier law schools are represented on the
judges' resumes, not one has graduated from an Ivy League law
school. (That may change soon. Last week, Cellucci nominated Leila
Kern, a cum laude Harvard Law alumna.) Suffolk Law, Boston College,
and Western New England College School of Law have issued most of
the diplomas to this crop of judges.
</P>
<P>
   But they have much experience. On average, the new judges had
been lawyers for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll probably see there's more people who worked in
a district attorney's office, been a public defender, worked in the
community,'' Cellucci said. ``I think you might see that more often
than you'll see someone from a top-notch law firm. That doesn't
mean we don't appoint people from top notch lawfirms . . . but I
like life experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana L. Maldonado, who was appointed to Chelsea District Court
last year, might fit the prototype.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of 10 children, Maldonado grew up in the South
Bronx. Her parents had emigrated from Puerto Rico. She went to
public schools, graduated from the State University of New York at
Stony Brook, and got her law degree from Northeastern University in
1985. The 40-year-old has spent much of her career as a public
defender.
</P>
<P>
   Maldonado, one of Cellucci's three minorty selections, says she
got the judgeship the old-fashioned way: She applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the blueblood. I wasn't someone who had the best
education or background. And I think he was willing to say, this
person shows comitment,'' she said recently. ``I think he's really
looking for people who bring a lot to the job, not just by their
academic background. I'm impressed by that, actually. And I think
it makes the lawyers respect the process more.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Maldonado, who has had to jump in as the courtroom
Spanish interpreter when none is available, said there still are
not enough minorities on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think more can be done,'' she said. ``Just because
you put a couple people up there doesn't end the demand for
diversity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
