<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSHI, SAKE, SUMO _ ALL IN NEWPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japan is coming to Newport, R.I. July 22-25. It's the 16th
anniversary of the Black Ships Festival and it's going to be a
great opportunity to experience Japanese art, culture, and foods.
</P>
<P>
   Among events will be a sushi and sake sail, sumo wrestling, art
and culture workshops and demonstrations, a Japanese food market, a
festival of drums, kite flying, karate, a tea ceremony, paper
folding, sushi making demonstrations, activities for children, and
a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Ships Festival commemorates Commodore Matthew C.
Perry, a Newport native, who negotiated the Treaty of Kanagawa in
1854, opening Japan to trade from the West and ending two centuries
of isolation. Black Ships refers to foreign vessels that were
excluded from Japan until the treaty was signed. Shimoda, Japan,
Newport's sister city, also commemorates this celebration of
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   For information or tickets to events, call 800-976-5122 or
401-846-2720 or visit www.NewportEvents.com. Newport is an easy
drive from Boston, and is known for its mansions, colonial history,
dining, and water activities. A great weekend destination anytime,
but especially during the Black Ships Festival.
</P>
<P>
   For those who wonder just how fat a sumo wrestler is, a Japan
Airlines newletter reports the average weight is 412 pounds, up
from 317 in 1953. Now sumo wrestlers have to have their body fat
measured, and possibly go on a diet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gillette Castle
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Gillette Castle in East Haddam, Conn., is closed for
renovations until next summer. The 22-room castle was built in a
medieval design by actor/playwright William Gillette. The 184-acre
state park that surrounds it is still open. Other attractions in
the area still open include the Goodspeed Opera House, where
musicals have been presented since 1876, and the Nathan Hale
Schoolhouse, where the Revolutionary patriot taught. For more
information, call the Connecticut River Valley &AMP; Shoreline Visitors
Council at 860-347-0028.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`No second place'
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The schooner AmericA(cq), a replica of one of the most famous
racing boats in history, is in Boston through September for tours
and sails. The 139-foot schooner will be docked at Rowes Wharf
behind the Boston Harbor Hotel. The vessel is a replica of the
America, which in 1851 soundly defeated 14 British yachts and won
the 100 Guinea Cup around the Isle of Wight. The race was attended
by Queen Victoria who asked, ``Who is first?'' ``America has won,''
she was told. ``Who was second?'' the queen asked. The famous reply
was, ``Your Majesty, there is no second.'' The race was renamed
America's Cup. AmericA is owned and operated by Historic Tours of
America, which owns the Boston Tea Party Ship and Museum and Old
Town Trolley Tours. While in Boston AmericA will be managed by The
Liberty Fleet of Tall Ships. For information, call 617-742-0333.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Old Manse, located next to the famed North Bridge in
Concord, Mass., is best known for its literary connections to Ralph
Waldo Emerson and Nathaniel Hawthorne, but on July 24 and 25, it
will be the scene of a Civil War reenactment of the day the 29th
Regiment of Massachusetts Volunteers marched through town, then
into the back door of the house and out the front for a lawn party.
The house, now owned by the Trustees of Reservations, will be the
scene of events ranging from an encampment to book signings and a
Punch and Judy show. House tours are by admission. For information,
call 978-369-3909.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th annual Lawn Cotillion at Ocean Edge Resort and Golf Club
in Brewster on Cape Cod will be Aug, 1 from 3:30 p.m. to 9 p.m. The
lawn cotillion is a Great Gatsby-style benefit featuring a croquet
clinic and tournament, along with foods prepared by celebrity
chefs, including Jacques Pepin, host of the PBS-TV series ``Jacques
Pepin Kitchen: Cooking with Claudine.'' Tickets are $110 a person,
or $275 for a family (up to four children under 16). The cotillion
benefits Habitat for Humanity of Cape Cod, Massachusetts Breast
Cancer Coalition, Cape Libraries, and the James Beard Foundation.
For tickets, call 508-896-9000.
</P>
</TEXT>
