<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6987 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-KENNEDY-HNS &LR;      07-20 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KENNEDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JFK JR. STORY: MORE VOYEURISM, OVERKILL ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It's uncomfortable to be cynical in the face
of sadness.
</P>
<P>
   The networks said they were going to learn their lesson _
particularly after the funeral of Dianna, Princess of Wales, and
then the long Clinton-Lewinsky nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   And then Littleton, Colo. Where the only thing that could wash
away the dime-store analysis was the tears.
</P>
<P>
   How often do you cut an industry slack when, after the lights go
down, it begs forgiveness and promises change, only to revert to
its bad, old ways? You don't. It will be easier, then, to just
accept the truth:
</P>
<P>
   Journalistic standards on television are not relevant in today's
world. In fact, we're not getting much journalism on television _
we're getting entertainment and therapy and voyeurism, but not
credibility, restraint when necessary and a fundamental belief that
there's a difference between reporting the news and leaving the
camera turned on.
</P>
<P>
   Our latest example: The fate of John F. Kennedy Jr. _ a death
put on hold. For television, it's the perfect story. Tragedy,
celebrity, history, shock and breaking news. Without coming out and
saying, definitively, ``They all died in that crash,'' television
news didn't feel obligated to have any boundaries. It could go on
forever, a sad solo story for 24-hour news networks and one hell of
an extended special report for everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 24 hours of the story, they were at the same game
all over again: Nonstop coverage of a story even when there was
nothing to add. Relentless archival tape-loops of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with so-called experts, even if that meant
journalists at the same network who happened to know Kennedy. And
anchors killing inordinate amounts of time, rambling, trying to
create first a sense of drama, then of regret, then shared memories
and lastly that best friend to all, the sad, big-picture
retrospective, complete with heart-tugging music.
</P>
<P>
   On that initial day, what else could they do? It's the nature of
the news beast to never, ever waver. Go away from the story and
viewers will flip somewhere else. Move off a story too early and
risk missing the slow unraveling of news fragments that could
advance the story.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Kaplan, president of CNN/U.S., stood in a room full of
television critics from around the country in Pasadena and
dismissed the notion of cutting back that first day because ``this
is of extraordinary importance, especially to Americans.'' And to
CNN's credit, the coverage had some restrictions that seemed to go
unheeded by others.
</P>
<P>
   In an internal CNN memo that indicated the direction came from
Kaplan, staffers got this notice early: ``Do not refer to JFK Jr.
in the past tense. He is missing. Stop eulogizing him. And do not
talk about a Kennedy family curse.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just good journalism, nothing more. These days, that
translates into a noble effort rather than business as usual on
television. So, if in those first 24 hours it was just the nature
of the beast, the networks were begrudgingly excused for the
overkill.
</P>
<P>
   And viewers certainly didn't mind. No question about it. Like
Diana before, this death had soap-opera elements that lured in
virtually everyone. But what about after 48 hours? What excuses can
be used then, when network teases imply that coverage would
continue wall to wall, right after this commercial break.
</P>
<P>
   What about when everyone had seen the same watery footage
endlessly? Or when there were catchy titles to the coverage? Or
when the aforementioned eulogizing, which CNN tried hard to
contain, simply busted loose all across the dial?
</P>
<P>
   We were back to tragedy as ratings. Another sad day in
television journalism.
</P>
<P>
   An argument often made by networks, tired of stinging rebukes of
their habits, is that newspapers are equally guilty, that the news
often remains on the front page for days. But the equation doesn't
hold up. Newspapers, in addition to telling a story more
thoroughly, never fill space when there's no advancing the story.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't news articles that capture that same kind of vacant
nothingness of cameras watching helicopters watching rescue boats.
</P>
<P>
   Also, most newspaper coverage doesn't turn maudlin so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper account can't show Kennedy and his wife attending
the same function or making the same speech every half-hour. A
newspaper does not fill 24, 48, even 72 hours with static
storytelling, or give time to an unceasing array of half-qualified
pundits or distant friends who illuminate nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Television news is unique in its overkill. And it's not getting
better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's coverage, as usual, was loathsome.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Brian Williams talked breathlessly about a government
search vessel that possibly had uncovered evidence of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   The boat, Williams said, ``is stopped over _ something.''
</P>
<P>
   That something could be anything, was the implication. And that
anything could be something _ ``possibly bodies,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Was there a need to watch further? Well, sure, because the
Kennedy curse had to be resurrected again. It must have been
difficult for MSNBC _ and to most networks covering this story _
that a funeral wasn't already under way.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be. And the wedding- to-funeral tale will arise
again. Mary Jo Kopechne will take her place on the anchors' lips
one more time. Sad to say, this Kennedy story is a cash cow that
will continue to be milked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
