<HEADLINE>
GOT   A LIGHT? YES, 575,000 OF THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than two decades, the crowds cheered when an
other-worldy voice proclaimed:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls, Disneyland
proudly presents our spectacular pageant of of nighttime magic and
imagination in thousands of sparkling lights and
electro-syntho-magnetic musical sounds . . . the Main Street
Electrical Parade!''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   And now the crowds are cheering again. The original Main Street
Electrical Parade from Disneyland in California is again being
performed nightly _ but it has moved 2,400 miles to Walt Disney
World's Magic Kingdom in Florida. Disney World itself had a version
of the parade for 15 seasons, but this is the one that ran the
longest, from 1972 to 1996, with just a couple of time-outs for
specially themed events. Here are some facts about this shimmering
spectacle, which features the most beloved Disney characters:
</P>
<P>
   --There are approximately 575,000 lights in six colors: amber,
blue, chartreuse, green, pink, and red _ plus clear.
</P>
<P>
   --Amber is the most-used color, with 152,000 lights.
</P>
<P>
   --The patriotic finale stretches 122 feet and involves 80,000
lights.
</P>
<P>
   --The Blue Fairy from ``Pinocchio'' glitters in a gown of more
than 10,000 blue, amber, and crystal lights.
</P>
<P>
   --More than 27 tons of batteries power the lights, audio, and
float movements. Together, they could provide enough power to light
32 homes.
</P>
<P>
   --When the parade made its final appearance in California, it
had been performed almost 3,600 times for more than 75 million
guests. And we'd wager few were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of Disney parks: Tarzan is making his swinging
presence known in both Disney World and Disneyland. ``Tarzan
Rocks'' is a 30-minute, high-energy stage show at Disney World's
Animal Kingdom. Disneyland, meanwhile, has converted its Swiss
Family Treehouse into Tarzan's Treehouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: What is the only letter not used in the spelling
of any of the 50 states? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``There isn't a train I wouldn't take, no matter where
it's going.'' _ Edna St. Vincent Millay.
</P>
<P>
   In a name: Cape Tribulation in Queensland, Australia, was named
by Captain James Cook, who must have been having a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today's loopy law: Los Angeles doesn't allow bathing two babies
in the same tub at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For women only: The Ojai Valley Inn, a luxe property in Ojai,
Calif., says that sometimes women just have to escape from
husbands, boyfriends, children, jobs, and pets (especially if they
have pets like a certain cat in my house). The Girlfriends Package
offers hotel accommodations, two 50-minute spa treatments per
person per night (and it's an attractive new spa), and a choice of
one group activity each day, ranging from an art class to a guided
trail ride on horseback to a wine seminar and tasting. The package
is available Sunday through Thursday nights with a two-night
minimum stay and a four-person minimum participation. Rates are
$408 single occupancy and $608 double occupancy. Weekend rates are
slightly higher. For more information or reservations, call
800-422-OJAI (6524) or visist www.ojairesort.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
