<P>
   A while back we mentioned places that are easy to visit in
various cities when you've got a few hours between planes. A
Virginia reader adds Underground Atlanta to the list. The
shopping-dining-entertainment complex is quickly reachable from
Hartsfield International Airport via the MARTA rapid transit
system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fasten your seat belts: The longest scheduled flight in North
America is reportedly a 12 1/2-hour Canadian jaunt. The First Air
flight leaves Ottawa in the morning, stops in Iqaluit and Nanisivik
on Baffin Island, heads farther north to Resolute Bay, then arcs
southward through Yellowknife in the Northwest Territories and on
to Edmonton, Alberta. (With thanks to Herbert Pence of Manchester,
N.H.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claims to fame: Boston's Union Oyster House lays claim to being
the oldest restaurant in Boston (having opened in 1826) and the
oldest restaurant in continuous service in the United States. But
the achievement that really impresses us is this one: The toothpick
was said to be first used in the United States at the Oyster House.
(With thanks to Valerie A. Russo of Weymouth, Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attention, Cookie Monster: Since 1981 Doubletree Hotels has been
giving guests, upon arrival, two freshly baked chocolate chip
cookies. In 1998, the 175 Doubletree properties baked more than 20
million cookies, using approximately 800,000 pounds of chocolate,
or 1 billion chocolate chips, and more than 600,000 pounds of
sugar.
</P>
<P>
