<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UPN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPN: FOR YOUR GUYS ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ At no other time in its history has the UPN
network been more likable.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's likable _ not dislikable.
</P>
<P>
   Considered the sixth-place network in a six-way race, UPN always
has been picked on by the critics, often deserving its status as
the butt of some ``Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' joke or for
imploding almost on cue.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed since then? Not a lot, but UPN, on the air since
January 1995, no longer seems in the business of explaining itself
or of trying to please the masses, its ill-fated first goal as a
network.
</P>
<P>
   As of this coming season, broadcasting _ in its purest sense _
is out the window. Women, older people, the thirtysomething crowds
_ watch if you want, but UPN is going, unapologetically it seems,
after young males. The network that tried to do a little bit of
everything to attract people from across the social fabric is done
with the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   The commander in chief of the new approach is Dean Valentine,
president and chief executive of the network. When pressed several
times Monday to explain violence and sexism in wrestling, one of
the coming linchpins in the UPN turnaround, Valentine would have
none of it.
</P>
<P>
   The ``WWF Smackdown'' block _ a full two hours every Thursday _
is just a ``soap opera for young guys,'' he said. ``There's not a
`Rocky' movie made that hasn't been more violent than any WWF
episode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think wrestling is popular entertainment and I don't have
any problems with the message it sends,'' he said. That led to a
flurry of examples of wrestling's past and present sins against
political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe there's anything sexist or violent on WWF,''
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   All he needed then was a dismissive wave of his hand and it
would have been perfect theater. Valentine, one of the few real-guy
leaders in the TV industry, is not always easy to read.
</P>
<P>
   One moment he puts on a lousy show and confronts television
critics when they don't like it. The next minute he apologizes for
the show and says he was wrong about its redeeming qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UPN lost about a third of its audience as viewers
couldn't grasp its direction, its message or its brand.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of Valentine's reign _ about 18 months ago when
he launched the new ``Love Boat'' idea _ UPN has been everyone's
favorite whipping boy. To this day, the network suffers from the
perception that it couldn't produce anything of quality, despite
the fact it has created a number of good shows.
</P>
<P>
   But things are changing for UPN _ even if a lot of people aren't
noticing. The network made money in the all-important advertiser
courtship period known as the ``upfronts,'' when potential buyers
see new products. The network generated $140 million in sales,
compared with $135 million the previous year. Remember, this comes
after losing a third of its viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Why the increase? Simple. UPN knows what it's all about now.
</P>
<P>
   It's about young males _ the hardest-to-reach audience and
therefore one of the most lucrative demographics. UPN will get them
through wrestling and action movies and a couple of pretty cool new
series _ ``Secret Agent Man'' and ``The Strip'' _ that feature guys
with guns, cool gadgets and a healthy dose of personal attitude,
much like Valentine possesses.
</P>
<P>
   These are good changes. UPN is even repositioning itself ever so
subtly, with Valentine and Entertainment President Tom Nunan
repeating, like a good Hemingway paragraph, the idea that, ``We
function as an alternative network.'' Translation: We won't win the
total viewers race, but we'll form a nice niche. In turn,
expectations get lowered (so get off our backs). And just to
dismiss the sense that a death knell will toll soon for the sixth
network _ a favorite preoccupation with critics _ Valentine said,
forcefully, ``We're never going away.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a refreshing change. UPN and Valentine in particular are
ill-suited for actively courting respectability. We need a network
that says, ``We know our audience. You're not it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, UPN is putting out an early contender for worst show of
the season _ a ludicrous hip-hop-esque version of ``The Monkees''
called ``Shasta McNasty,'' and there's a feeling that the network
(whoops, ``alternative network'') knows the show is awful and
doesn't care what critics think.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe, just maybe, ``Shasta McNasty'' will mix well with the
wrestling and the two promising new action shows, not to mention
last season's decent addition, ``7 Days,'' to become a watchable
option. Probably not _ it's likely to flop. But, hey, that's how it
goes. If you don't like it, don't watch it. UPN doesn't care about
getting everyone's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes the network infinitely more likable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
