<HEADLINE>
BIG VOTE OF APPROVAL FOR MIDNIGHT BUFFET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What time is the midnight buffet?'' That's one of those silly
questions heard on many a past cruise. (Maybe not so silly _ some
began at 11:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   The midnight buffet, once a staple on all cruise ships, has been
disappearing from many lines in favor of smaller specialized
buffets such as a chocolate feast. And with the increase of pizza
parlors on the seas and 24-hour dining rooms, who needs another
buffet? A lot of people, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Omega World Travel/ CRUISE.COM online survey found
respondents going 2 to 1 in favor of keeping the midnight buffet.
That question drew the widest majority of any of the poll's four
questions.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of on-board casinos (a major moneymaker for
cruise lines), only 42 percent said they were important. On the
question of smoking, 51 percent said they though non-smoking
cruises were a good idea (many lines do offer smoke- free dining
rooms; Carnival has a smoke-free ship, the Paradise).
</P>
<P>
   Preferenes twoard ship sizes also drew a mixed response. Medium
ships were preferred by 35 percent of respondents, large ships by
30 percent. Megaships received only 22 percent approval, and small
ships had just 13 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Omega World Travel is a travel management company, and polled
2,416 people in June. Participation in the current on-line cruise
survey is available at www.cruise.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sail overnight
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of New England's treasures is its windjammer fleet that
sails along the Maine coast. While these authentic sailing vessels
offer short sails of three or four days, that's still too long for
some visitors. The schooner Wendameen that sails out of Rockland,
Maine, offers one-night sails. Passengers board the 67-foot yacht
at 1:30 p.m. and soon set sail guided by the wind. The 1912
schooner returns around 10 a.m. the next day. For information, call
207-594-1751.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
What next?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now you can sail without ever boarding a ship. Princess Cruises
found its Grand Princess BridgeCam to be one of the most popular
features of its Web site. Now additional live cameras have been
added to six more Princess ships and there is a second view to the
Grand Princess. This Internet feature allows visitors to visit
www.princess.com to enjoy the view from the bridges of Sun
Princess, Dawn Princess, Sea Princess, Crown Princess, Royal
Princess, and Sky Princess as they cruise Alaskan and European
waters. This marks the first time a Web site has offered such a
feature. Visitors to the Grand Princess site reportedly spend up to
15 minutes viewing the scene. The BridgeCams are placed on or near
the ship's bridge, and the image is updated every 60 seconds,
allowing viewers to ``sail'' with the ship.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also offers visitors information on all Princess
ships including the onboard experience, itineraries, and
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Princess has also announced that the original Love Boat, the
Pacific Princess, will begin sailing from New York to Bermuda next
year. The weekly cruises begin May 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
