<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HERE TO ABSURDITY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Don't you know that some days the b.s. is just
too thick for the filter of absurdity, and the whole system has to
back up?
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, in less time than you can say, ``minimum wage,''
members of the House of Representatives gave themselves and their
Senate colleagues a 3.4 percent salary increase.
</P>
<P>
   This occurred without debate or apology on the same day the
Senate passed a pathetic rights bill for the patients of managed
care providers that is guaranteed a presidential veto and,
according to the Chicago Tribune, ``all but smothered the slim hope
that patients would gain any new federal protections before the
2000 elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Two bits of related nonsense:
</P>
<P>
   _ House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who has been widely
trashed _ as being a total non-force _ by many of his own party
members, will now pull down an annual salary of $175,400.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the same day, the House passed by a single vote a $28
billion Treasury appropriations bill that included the doubling of
the salary of the next president of the United States (from
$200,000 to $400,000). Many Republicans voted against the bill, not
because they wanted to short the commander in chief, but because
the bill included a provision that requires most federal employees'
medical plans to cover prescription birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Still in our nation's capital, 99 more managed care
organizations announced that, come January, they will boot 327,000
old people from their Medicare-supplementing health maintenance
organizations, or HMOs. Eight months ago, nearly 100 HMOs
self-destructed, leaving some 400,000 Medicare patients with no
HMO.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry says it had to make the cuts because
the federal government is stingy with its Medicare reimbursements;
the feds say the managed care providers did it to increase their
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Why do we believe they are both lying but correct?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
