<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-GAYS (Washington) _ The Rev. Robert Nugent, rebuked by
the Vatican last week for ministering to gays around the nation for
the last 25 years, says the action was ``a setback and a
disappointment'' for Catholic homosexuals seeking greater
acceptance in the church. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   SWEEPSTAKES-SCAMS (Washington) _ Support for a bill to crack
down on sweepstakes companies is growing in the Senate as more
evidence of deceptive practices by small firms is uncovered. The
measure, offered by Sens. Susan Collins, R-Maine, and Carl Levin,
D-Mich., has 33 co-sponsors. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. Will also
be filed in the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'') category.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-BANKS (Washington) _ Consumers should be given the right
to stop banks from releasing to other companies private information
about them such as what they buy or how much they earn, business
and privacy experts tell Congress. By MARK HELM. Will also be filed
in the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'') category.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The split-up of that champion of
traditional family values, ex-House Speaker Newt Gingrich, and his
wife Marianne confirms that his political claim to spousal devotion
didn't mean beans. And Gingrich isn't the only politician who
preaches high moral standards for others and fails to behave
accordingly himself. So let's get off the family values kick. It's
hypocritical. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
