<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT-21-COX     07-20 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT-21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, July 21,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIANS _ WASHINGTON _ Library of Congress officials and
Russia's ambassador take part in an announcement of a $10 million
program to bring up to 3,000 Russian leaders to this country for
10-day visits to a variety of locations, staying in the private
homes of Americans. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GORE-TOBACCO _ WASHINGTON _ In his first campaign for president,
Al Gore cited his plan to strengthen the warnings on cigarette
packages as a profile in courage. But his recent hiring of Carter
Eskew, an old friend and media adviser has prompted charges of
hypocrisy because Eskew helped kill the administration's
anti-tobacco legislation. A look at Gore's conflicted history on
the tobacco issue. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-SWITCHING _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Special Aging Committee
holds a hearing on ``Drugstore Surprise: the Impact of Drug
Switching on Older Americans.'' (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE-TOBACCO _ WASHINGTON _ In his first campaign for president,
Al Gore cited his plan to strengthen the warnings on cigarette
packages as a profile in courage. But his recent hiring of Carter
Eskew, an old friend and media adviser has prompted charges of
hypocrisy because Eskew helped kill the administration's
anti-tobacco legislation. A look at Gore's conflicted history on
the tobacco issue. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ ANDREWS, N.C. _ FBI is expected to hold a news
conference Tuesday to offer updates on the hunt for bombing suspect
Eric Robert Rudolph. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND-BARS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As the last paper plate and
Styrofoam cup are tossed in the big trash bin, a guard does an
early-evening head count. Then, troop activities begin. This night
mothers and daughters learn dance moves and sing Girl Scout songs,
such as ``Alice the Camel.'' But this isn't a typical Girl Scout
meeting because mothers are prison inmates. Nationally, an
estimated 1.5 million children have a jailed parent, and more than
200,000 children have imprisoned mothers, according to the Child
Welfare League of America. Nearly 11,000 women were incarcerated in
Texas prisons in April. Criminal justice experts say parent-child
contact is essential to preserving emotional bonds while a parent
is serving time. The relationship will, hopefully, help the
imprisoned parent to change and the child to cope. But maintaining
the relationship often requires structured programs, such as Beyond
Bars, which gets the mothers and daughters out of the crowded,
assigned-seat environment of routine weekend jail visits. (Martin,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS If a budget line or story is marked
with photos or graphics, those are available from the New York
Times News Service at 212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more
information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The news manager is Paul Foutch, 404-526-5429,
pfoutch(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The day news editor is Tom Oder, 404-526-5887,
toder(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The night news editor is Todd C. Duncan, 404-582-7282,
tduncan(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338, artd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
