<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      07-20 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, July 21:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-RDP (Bourne, Mass.) _ Developments in the disappearance
of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and sister-in-law. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-PILOT (Undated) _ A look at how pilots deal with the
situations JFK Jr. may have faced. By Carl H. Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   MUSHROOM-WORKERS (Quincey, Fla.) _ Ending a three-year battle,
the United Farm Workers sign a contract covering 450 mushroom
workers, making them the first Florida farmworkers to be covered by
a union contract and signaling the union's more cooperative
approach to management. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PBS-DONOR-LISTS (Washington) _ A congressional hearing examines
the controversy involving sharing of donor lists by PBS stations
with the Democratic Party. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate puts the finishing
touches on the tax bill. House leadership meets in a test between
the Republican leaders and moderates, who want less of a tax cut.
By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TAX-BREAKS (Washington) _ Imbedded in both the House and Senate
tax cutting measures are all sorts of special interest tax breaks.
By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TEACHERS (Washington) _ The House is to vote on a bill
to establish block grants for programs to train and hire teachers
nationwide. It authorizes $2 billion a year and is part of a larger
effort by house Republicans to have an education agenda. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Undated) _ Fifteen months after the
Clinton administration ordered a controversial overhaul of the
nation's system for distributing human organs, an independent panel
of experts has concluded that while the current arrangement is
``reasonably equitable for the most severely ill patients,'' the
government is nonetheless justified in demanding that hospitals
share their scarce hearts, lungs, livers, pancreases and kidneys
more broadly. 1,200 words. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ Ehud Barak, the visiting Israeli
prime minister, travels to Capitol Hill to meet with congressional
leaders whose approval is needed for several pieces of the Israeli
aid package. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: What changes
in the U.S. role in the Middle East peace effort can be expected
after the Clinton-Barak meetings. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROTEST (Beijing) _ Chinese authorities detain some 70
leaders of the spiritual movement known as Falun Gong in a
nationwide crackdown. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Taipei) _ Taiwan's syntactical backflips to
explain the bizarre crisis with China over this island's status,
with President Lee emerging to speak again, but only making things
worse. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ Militants swoop on a village in the
Indian part of Kashmir and kill 15 people before dawn. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-JOURNALIST (Moscow) _ A Russian military court sentences
the journalist Grigory Pasko to three years in prison for
disclosing classified materials, but immediately frees him,
declaring him eligible for an amnesty. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FAT-SUBSTITUTE (Undated) _ Two years ago, Procter &AMP; Gamble
thought it could make the fat substitute olestra into a staple, and
it projected nearly $1 billion in sales by the end of this year.
But consumers didn't bite _ partly because regulatory approval was
so long in coming that the fickle cycle of consumer taste had edged
away from low-fat food, partly because olestra has an image _
backed up by numerous complaints _ of causing stomach upset. And
sales may now hit only half that $1 billion target. While olestra
is hardly a flop, the backpedaling from the original lofty goals
represents a stark reversal for a company that never likes to tap
the brakes. And it is a testament to the struggle the global
behemoth has had in coming up with the next hot brand to rev up its
slowing growth engine. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit surged in May
to another record as oil prices jumped to their highest level since
late 1997, spurred by higher prices for oil imports. The Commerce
Department reported that the trade deficit ballooned to $21.3
billion _ wider than forecasts and a 14.8 percent increase from the
$18.6 billion deficit in April. The deficits with Europe and China
widened, while the deficit with Japan narrowed. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-YEN (Undated) _ The Federal Reserve bought dollars on
behalf of the Bank of Japan, the sixth time in six weeks that the
Japanese central bank has sought to stem the yen's rise. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   GM-EARNINGS (Detroit) _ General Motors says earnings rose more
than fivefold from last year's strike-weakened second quarter,
topping forecasts on rising United States sales of high-profit
pickup trucks. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-EARNINGS (Undated) _ American Home Products, Johnson &AMP;
Johnson and Smithkline Beecham report quarterly results. By David
J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSICO-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Pepsico is expected to report
earings later today, with 29 cents a share the forecast. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc. reports
slightly better-than-expected results. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Jane
L. Levere.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-APPOINT (Geneva) _ The World Trade Organization is to name a
former New Zealand prime minister, Mike Moore, as its next director
general later this week, ending an eight-month deadlock. By
Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are lower in morning trading, with
the Dow down 0.30 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 down 0.95 percent, and the
Nasdaq down 2.04 percent. Micosoft, IBM and other computing stocks
are sharply lower. European markets were also lower, with London
down 1.05 percent and Frankfurt down 2.08 percent. Hong Kong rose
1.14 percent. Tokyo was closed for a national holiday, Marine Day.
By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
