<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7018 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC &LR; - &UR; FONDA-BRIDGET-LADN     07-20 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGET FONDA DIVES INTO `LAKE PLACID'
</HEADLINE>
 BC - FONDA-BRIDGET-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Eds: note italics below 
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In her dozen years as a film actress, Bridget
Fonda's pale, slender beauty has lent itself to roles as a Single
White Female, a bong-smoking beach bunny and a waitress. Now, she's
trying something a little different _ playing a reluctant crocodile
chaser in the quirky/scary creature flick ``Lake Placid.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a body-hugging black sweater set and slim skirt (from
which, she discovered, she hadn't yet removed the price tag),
Fonda, at 35, seems to look more like a Fonda every day. The lanky
frame and piercing eyes bear a strong resemblance to those of
father Peter, grandfather Henry and aunt Jane. Though she says she
has to watch her weight a bit more now than in the past, it's hard
to sympathize when she pinches what she imagines is a bit of fat on
her leg. (BEGIN ITAL) Please, (END ITAL) you think, (BEGIN ITAL)
allow me to show you what fat really looks like. (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   It may not be coincidental, then, that Fonda was offered the
lead role in ``Ally McBeal.'' The huge TV hit was created by ``Lake
Placid'' writer David E. Kelley; Fonda says she's just not
interested in doing television right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if something came along that I wanted to
do (on TV),'' Fonda said. ``I love the character and writing on
`Ally McBeal,' but my favorite part of making a movie is the
preparation. I'm not that spontaneous, to work on a series the way
they do, changing things up to the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   It's often said that Kelley is the busiest man in show business:
He has three shows on the air (``Ally,'' ``The Practice'' and
``Chicago Hope'') and finds time to write movies on the side when
he's not busy being a family man with wife Michelle Pfeiffer.
Everyone involved with ``Placid'' says Kelley's smart,
tongue-in-cheek writing was a main attraction in doing the film and
that Kelley was always available to make small tweaks when needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never actually seen him on the set of anything, but he's
always there,'' said director Steve Miner. With credits that range
from ``Halloween: H20'' to TV's ``Dawson's Creek,'' Miner seems to
have been a natural choice to bring this mixture of horror and
dark, offbeat humor to the screen. ``We had a little trouble
setting (the movie) up,'' admits Miner, ``because people had a
little trouble understanding what kind of movie it was. But David
and I always knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda plays a paleontologist called in to figure out how a giant
crocodile may have made its way into a Maine lake. As part of her
preparation, Fonda paid a visit to the Museum of Natural History in
New York, where she was debriefed on the fine points of identifying
a crocodile from one of its teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda admits she can relate to the insecurities of her
character, who's a bundle of insecurities because she's fresh off a
broken relationship and is out of her element in the wild. ``I
loved this character. She's been having a bad time. She's a bitch
because she's so afraid of being not good enough ... her
self-esteem is so low that she doesn't want to leave her cubicle
and her microscope,'' said Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   As for her own insecurities, Fonda admits she's afraid of
heights _ and doesn't relish looking back at her own work on film.
``I'm not that crazy about my own work ... I'll watch the dailies
and go to the premiere,'' Fonda said, ``but looking back _ I don't
really get into what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she grew up among Hollywood royalty _ or perhaps
because of it _ Fonda says she can relate to the fear that grows
from insecurity. But according to Fonda, who recently ended a long
relationship with actor Eric Stoltz and is currently dating
singer/actor Dwight Yoakam, she doesn't suffer from it when it
comes to feeling like she has to measure up against anyone else's
fame, or the Fonda ``legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any sense of competition. That's probably from
being the child of someone famous,'' Fonda says, ``that I don't
look at fame as a register of anything real. Fame just doesn't mean
anything concrete. It's so changeable. You can't count on it. It
passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda says that, unlike her father, who released a juicy
autobiography last year (``Don't Tell Dad: A Memoir''), she's
learned to keep a part of her life private. ``The way I grew up was
that there was no privacy. My father is very, very open,'' Fonda
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up thinking that's the way you had to be. But then,''
said Fonda, ``I found out I didn't want to be that way ... I had to
sort of learn how to not feel bad about not answering certain
questions. My natural instinct is to try to give an answer _ that's
the gracious thing to do. I'm a people pleaser, which makes me feel
bad about not giving an answer, but I'm also kind of shy and
private. So sometimes I'm torn.
</P>
<P>
   Workwise, Fonda says she's conscious these days of moving beyond
parts that cast her as merely window dressing: ``corsage parts,''
as she calls them. She says she'd be interested in developing her
own projects if she could ``find a way to do it: It takes time _
and a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   But overall, Fonda says she's happy and grateful for the parts
she's gotten so far in her career and is just trying to take things
one role at a time. ``Do I think about my legacy? I can't really
think about that,'' Fonda said. ``If I think about that ... it's a
setup for a feeling of failure for me; I'll never measure up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get objective about my own work,'' Fonda admits, ``so
I just have to let go of that and hope other people like what I
do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
