<HEADER>
A7025 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLAY-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      07-20 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATFORD-ON-SHAKESPEARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
What:  ``Play On!''  
Where:  Pasadena Playhouse, 39 S. El Molino Ave., Pasadena.  
When:  8 p.m. Tuesdays through Fridays, 5 and 9 p.m. Saturdays, 2
and 7 p.m. Sundays; through Aug. 22.  
Tickets : $20 to $50. Call (800) 233-3123.  
Our rating:  2 stars 
 
 
 
 
By REED JOHNSON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Shakespeare was the house playwright of kings and
queens, but he never neglected the unwashed mob. He pitched his
plays not only to the swells in the balconies but also to the hoi
polloi thrashing around in ye olde mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   A similar high-low sensibility marked the prolific career of the
African-American composer known by his regal moniker. While Duke
Ellington's mature orchestral works are embraced at Carnegie Hall,
his bouncy pop standards still endure as urbane masterpieces of
compressed, streetwise vitality.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, then, if you take a few of Duke's greatest hits and
combine them with ``Twelfth Night,'' the Bard's ever-popular comedy
of love and gender-swapping identity, you should have a work of
bipolar genius _ sophisticated yet soulful, classy yet down to
earth. Three years ago, director Sheldon Epps and book writer
Cheryl West turned that promising idea into the musical ``Play
On!'' which opened in San Diego and enjoyed successful runs in
Chicago and Seattle after a mixed New York reception.
</P>
<P>
   But in its present form at the Pasadena Playhouse, where Epps is
now artistic director, ``Play On!'' plays like an over-cautious
experiment in cultural cross-pollination. While the show has
flashes of robust wit and jazzy sensuality, its conceptual miscues
and reluctance to court danger, plus an erratic cast, keep it from
conveying the full creative heat of its twin icons.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely transposed from the mythical Illyria to the magical
Harlem of the 1940s, ``Play On!'' streamlines Shakespeare's story
about a young woman, here called Vy (Natalie Venetia Belcon), who
impersonates a man in order to gain access to a lovelorn ruler. In
``Play On!'' the ruler is a prince of jazz, naturally named Duke
(Raun Ruffin), who's in a royal funk over his standoffish
mistress-muse, the haughty, golden-throated Lady Liv (Nikki
Crawford).
</P>
<P>
   Vy has come to Harlem from rural Mississippi hoping to break
into the sex-segregated composing world, and her entrance to the
strains of ``Take the `A' Train'' instantly sends the ensemble of
dancers, brilliantly costumed by Marianna Elliott, into
high-stepping overdrive. Set against designer James Leonard Joy's
splashy, abstract urbanscapes, the sequence feels like an Archibald
Motley Jr. painting sprung to life.
</P>
<P>
   But the number also underscores the hazards of mixing and
matching familiar tunes with unfamiliar contexts. For example, when
Duke first appears at a candle-lit piano, pouring his unrequited
passion into ``I Let a Song Go Out of My Heart,'' the lyrics are
too diffuse, too tangential to what's actually happening on stage
to register much impact.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington's songs have a self-contained, universalized
perfection that tends to work against the musical theater's
nuts-and-bolts need for specifics. Of the show's 21 songs,
elegantly orchestrated by Rahn Coleman, only about five or six
succeed in moving the singer from point A to point B.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the score often resembles a revue more than a
narrative. With a couple ofexceptions, so do the lively but
emotionally unexpressive dance numbers choreographed by Ellington's
granddaughter, Mercedes. And West's rough paraphrasings of
Shakespeare's text mostly fail to take up the poetic slack.
</P>
<P>
   One happy exception occurs when the mischievous trio of Jester,
Sweets and Miss Mary (well-performed by Kevin Ramsey, Clinton
Derricks-Carroll and Yvette Cason) urge Lady Liv's dour protector,
Rev (Richard Allen), to loosen up a little. Epps wittily sets the
scene to a pleasantly relaxed version of ``It Don't Mean a Thing If
It Ain't Got That Swing.'' Allen, a gifted vocal interpreter and
supple comic actor, supplies a bright spot as the puritanical Rev,
later reborn as a hip-swiveling, zoot-suited would-be ladies' man.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three principals, only Crawford, with her torchy soprano
and feline swagger, seems made for her part. The petite Belcon has
a dignified bearing and a rich, husky voice that bottoms out in
Marian Anderson territory _ fine attributes but perhaps too severe
for a Chaplin-esque schemer like Vy. Ruffin's honey-voiced Duke
unfortunately comes up flat once or twice, and his character, like
his performance, lacks psychological coloring.
</P>
<P>
   Like the uptight, ultra-respectable Rev, ``Play On!'' apparently
knows how to swing but seldom leaves itself room to do so. Apart
from the raunchy blues wailer ``Rocks in My Bed,'' performed by
Ramsey and Derricks-Carroll with exhilarating comic abandon, the
show's creators give a very wide berth to anything that might smack
of sexual raciness or ethnic caricature _ an understandable
instinct that nonetheless cramps their material.
</P>
<P>
   Why not explore, as Shakespeare does, the Duke's sexually
ambivalent attraction to Vy, a woman he believes to be a man? Might
there not be an interesting parallel here with Ellington's own
romantic attachment to his real-life collaborator Billy Strayhorn?
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reasons, such gray areas are beyond the ken of this
hot-color, but strangely cool-blooded show. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
