<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PROFILE-HORSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR AUTHOR REMAINS A PARIAH IN HIS HOMETOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALINAS, Calif. _ Monty Roberts, the best-selling author and
acclaimed horse trainer, is a hero to horse lovers around the
world, but his name is still mud in Salinas, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after ``The Man Who Listens to Horses'' took the
literary world by storm and assured Roberts' celebrity, his
relatives still are boiling mad over its claims that his father was
a child abuser, killer, racist and cruel to horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monty sold his soul to the devil for money,'' said Salinas
taxidermist Al Martins, Roberts' cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Martins was among 200 friends of the late Marvin Roberts Sr. who
gathered Thursday at the Monterey County Sheriff's Posse Grounds to
celebrate publication of a book rebutting many of the basic claims
of his son Monty's million seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horse Whispers &AMP; Lies,'' written by Monty Roberts' niece Debra
Ann Ristau of Modesto and aunt Joyce Renebome of Galt, argues that
exaggeration, improbability, fibs, whoppers and fantasy so pervade
their relative's bestseller that it is essentially a work of
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Ristau and Renebome acknowledge that discrediting Roberts with
3,000 copies of their own privately published (Veracity Books,
Berkeley, 332 pages) book is like pinging away at an elephant with
a BB gun. Nevertheless, Ristau said, ``the truth does matter. I
know that somehow, some way, it will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Monty Roberts, 64, a trainer and breeder of thoroughbred stakes
winners at his Flag Is Up ranch in Solvang, has popularized a
nonviolent method of breaking or starting horses that he has
trademarked as ``join up.'' Roberts' public demonstrations of the
technique, in which an unbroken horse is gentled, saddled, bridled
and ridden in about 30 minutes draw gasps of astonishment and
appreciation from spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he developed the join up process in reaction to his
father's brutal treatment of horses and from his days alone in the
high desert of Nevada, where as a 13-year-old, he observed wild
horses and began deciphering horse language, which he calls
``Equus.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Roberts Sr., who died at age 77 in 1985, was a Salinas
icon _ a teacher, a police officer, and a horse trainer whose
techniques, some say, anticipated his son's.
</P>
<P>
   With his redoubtable wife, Marguerite, he schooled generations
of Salinas youngsters in horsemanship, instructed students in
traffic safety, and was widely regarded as a paragon of probity and
an indulgent parent.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Monty Roberts' assertions that his father
frequently beat him, was cruel to horses and was a racist who,
while on duty as a police officer, beat a black man to death jolted
Marvin Roberts Sr.'s family, friends and former students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monty was their golden boy, their tuxedo son,'' Joyce Renebome
said. ``We all knew Monty was arrogant and conceited ... but this
was indescribably reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bare-faced liar,'' said Larry Roberts, a former bronc
and bull rider who scoffed at several of his brother's claims,
including one that the late film star James Dean buddied up and
stayed with Monty at the Roberts house while filming ``East of
Eden.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We slept in the same room, and if somebody's going to be
sleeping in my bed for four months, I'd know about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way in hell he went to Nevada to get wild horses.
... None of these things ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd just have left his parents alone, nobody would've said
anything,'' said Monty Roberts' childhood friend, Dick Gillott.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin and Marguerite Roberts have been memorialized at the
National Steinbeck Center in Salinas, where friends have raised
nearly $50,000 _ some of it at an auction Thursday _ to dedicate
the center's popular ``Red Pony'' exhibit to them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism of ``The Man Who Listens to Horses,'' Roberts
stands by the accusations he made against his father and goes from
triumph to triumph, both in the show ring and on the bestseller
lists. Monty Roberts' son Marty said Friday that his father had not
yet read the Ristau-Renebome book and had no comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   His second book, ``Shy Boy: The Horse That Came in From the
Wild'' (Harper Collins), a lavishly illustrated account of his join
up with a wild horse after a 100-mile chase, was published this
spring. It hit No. 1 on the Washington Post's bestseller list and
No. 2 on the New York Times list.
</P>
<P>
   Andree Forzani, a Carmel Valley horse trainer who knows the
Roberts family, called the venture that produced the book a sterile
and unoriginal stunt. ``Just to prove you could chase him (the
horse Shy Boy) until he was so tired you could catch him was plain
stupidity. ... It had a very Hollywood flair,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ristau-Renebome book is somewhat shapeless, lacks narrative
flow and suffers from disorganization and repetition as it alleges
inconsistencies and errors of fact in Monty Roberts' book. Many of
the testimonials from friends and former students of Marvin Roberts
Sr. verge on hagiography.
</P>
<P>
   It is, nevertheless, unmistakably a cry from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvin and Marguerite didn't have much in their lives, but
they had their good names'' that their son has sullied, Ristau
said. ``It's so hard to disprove something that's just a total
imaginary thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
