<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS UNVEIL STRATEGY TO ADD COLOR TO TV PROGRAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Executives at Black Entertainment Television
don't admit relishing the major networks' lily White new fall
season, but they don't deny trying to take advantage of it to reach
more African-American viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say we're pleased,'' Debra Lee, president of BET,
told a gathering of critics here last week as she announced a slate
of 10 original movies _ all made with Black talent and money _ her
network will broadcast this fall. ``I mean, we're all part of the
African-American community, and we think that they should be part
of the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it does present an opportunity for us to showcase the
films that we're here to talk about . . and the other programming
that we plan to launch in the fall season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest commitment that BET has ever made to
original programming, so I think it does provide us a window of
opportunity. But we think the networks should be held accountable
for not showing the diversity in this country today.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not the only one who thinks so. None of the 27 new
comedies and dramas premiering on the top four networks this fall
has a minority in a leading role, and few have them in supporting
roles. So the NAACP announced June 13 that it would monitor and
seek action on what it called the ``virtual whitewash'' in fall TV
programming.
</P>
<P>
   The group's new NAACP Television &AMP; Film Industry Diversity
Initiative will monitor the entertainment industry. NAACP president
Kweisi Mfume called for congressional and Federal Communication
Commission hearings on licensing and ownership of networks, adding
that the campaign could lead to lawsuits and boycotts of
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have responded by saying that diversity is a
priority but that more work needs to be done. Meanwhile, Robert
Johnson, BET's chairman, said his network is already doing that
work with its original movies, which begin airing in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, Black business people and Black creative
people are saying, `We're going to solve this problem our way,' ''
he said. ``We're not going to do it the other way, we're going to
do it our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the actors involved in the movies, all of which are
adapted from the Arabesque line of African-American romance novels,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities for actors of color are definitely stronger
in the cable area,'' said Khalil Kain, who stars in ``Intimate
Betrayal.'' ``There is more interesting work available and more
work available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about what's going on with the NAACP, I think, is
valid only because nobody's actually talking about the fact that
there is a large number of actors that depend on work in television
to help pay their bills, to help support their lives. And if you go
an entire season with absolutely nothing available in TV, that
impacts the acting community hugely. Hugely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all very proud and respectful to have these
opportunities set forth,'' said Phil Morris, who stars in
``Incognito.'' ``We hope the networks follow suit. But we can't
wait for them. So on we go.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
