<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANSTA-MOVIE-BOS &LR;      07-20 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANSTA-MOVIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM BASED ON TRAGIC ROLE OF UNDERCOVER POLICE OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RIC KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Almighty drug lord is hooked into most of the city's
hard-core crime. Heroic undercover agent vows to bring him down by
infiltrating the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The police officer helps undo the ruthless gangsta but pays a
heavy price _ tearing his soul in the eternal struggle faced by
undercover cops who try to preserve their identity while
play-acting as hardened criminals.
</P>
<P>
   It's the stuff of pure Hollywood, and it's coming to a theater
near you next month, in a Miramax film called ``In Too Deep''
starring Omar Epps, Pam Grier, Stanley Tucci, and LL Cool J.
</P>
<P>
   It is also, as they say in Tinseltown, partly ``inspired'' by
one of the most searing real-life cop dramas this city has known:
Boston undercover operative Jeffrey Coy's final mission to topple
drug kingpin Darryl Whiting, a man whose power was reflected in a
nickname that even Hollywood chose not to top: ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-screenwriters/producers Paul Aaron (``A Force of One'') and
Michael Henry Brown (``Dead Presidents'') said they have produced a
contemporary Jekyll-and-Hyde police story that will scorch the
silver screen with the edgy reality of the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In their good-triumphs-over-evil version, hero cop Jeffrey Cole
(Omar Epps) recaptures his own life after capturing Dwayne ``God''
Gittens, played in a projected breakthrough role by rapper/actor LL
Cool J.
</P>
<P>
   In the hauntingly true tale of Boston's undercover operator,
Jeffrey Coy emerged from his deep cover assignment _ which helped
send Whiting to prison for life _ financially broke and emotionally
spent. In 1994, at age 33, he committed suicide by hanging himself
from a belt slung over his bedroom door.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Coy says he fears that the upcoming celluloid story
will not serve as an everlasting epitaph, but it could be the final
indignity to a man who spent his last days unsuccesfully trying to
sell to moviemakers an authentic portrayal of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Jones, former chief of the Boston Housing Authority
police who launched Coy's undercover career, said he worries that
Hollywood's penchant for rewriting history might do a disservice to
Coy's memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie was an opportunity for him to become financially
stable, and in the long term his life would have been depicted in a
way that gave value and creedence to all the work he had done in
trying to make a difference,'' said Jones, who now serves as a
national consultant on community reinvestment.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron (Keanu Reeves's stepfather) said he had picked Coy's brain
about undercover work for several days after first reading a news
story about the case. Then he and Brown melded Coy's experiences
with those of undercover operatives in Los Angeles and New York,
and came up with a composite character that could be compared to a
sort of ``Serpico of the 'hood.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is set in Cincinnati, not Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the Jeff Coy story,'' Aaron said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said that because Coy died before the movie deal was
clinched, he did not receive any financial compensation for his
input, but might have had he lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``His death was a loss not only to Boston police,'' Aaron said,
``but to lots of people who may have been able to understand the
life of a cop better if he had been allowed to'' illuminate it.
</P>
<P>
   The promo for ``In Too Deep'' breathlessly describes the dilemma
of undercover detective Jeffrey Cole: ``Will he be able to separate
himself from the character he created after the mission is
finished, or will he lose himself in the same evil he hopes to
destroy? Now, with every friend he makes and every threat he faces,
he's getting one step closer to the man he's after, and one step
further from the man he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Coy found his identity as a religious and righteous
police officer overtaken by Jay Reed, the ruthless Rhode Island
drug dealer he'd adopted as his undercover alias.
</P>
<P>
   During nearly five years of undercover work, Coy had a gun
thrust into his chest in the Franklin Field housing complex, a
knife put to his throat at Orchard Park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, federal authorities recruited Coy to complete the
assignment he'd started under Jones: to infiltrate the organization
of Whiting, who'd come from New York and maneuvered to unite the
city's youth gangs into a drug-dealing force.
</P>
<P>
   Playing Jay Reed, Coy made undercover buys of cocaine, witnessed
money-laundering, and pistol-whipped a guy to avert suspicions that
he was a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   But after eight months, Coy was pulled off the case. He was in
too deep: Holed up in an undercover apartment protected by actual
wolves, he snorted coke and swallowed Valium, trying to chase away
post-traumatic stress flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   He was also arrested for assaulting a police officer following
an altercation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a year of psychotherpay, Coy declared himself whole.
But he had trouble finding work that could be fulfilling to a man
whose star testimony helped defeat ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his last jobs: surveilling shoplifters at a Somerville
Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking redemption, Coy developed his own script about an
undercover cop. He hoped to star in the movie. But in 1994, Coy
rewrote the ending: He hung himself, fading his life to black.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Kayce Ataiyero contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
