<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONCORDIA-MYSTIQUE-AR     07-20 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDIA-MYSTIQUE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLET OF CLASSIC BEAUTIES GRACES BUZZARDS BAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PADANARAM, Mass. _ They look like nothing else on the water.
</P>
<P>
   They enter a harbor as a beauty enters a room. The mere presence
of one in San Diego Bay earlier this year set the huge sailing
community there on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was saying, `Did you see? Someone brought a Concordia
yawl into the bay,' '' recalls Dan Nowlan, director of the Offshore
department of the US Sailing Association, the national governing
body for the sport. ``There are thousands of boats in San Diego
Bay, but this is the one everybody wanted to see.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been that way since the late Ray Hunt picked up Harrier,
his Concordia yawl, at the Abeking and Rasmussen shipyard in
Lemwerder, Germany, in 1955 and walked off with six firsts in six
races at Cowes, the prestigious international race week off
England. A year earlier, Dan Strohmeier won the Bermuda race on his
Concordia, Malay, at 39 feet the smallest boat ever to win that
celebrated contest.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday (July 16), 25 of these ocean aristocrats glided to
South Wharf by Dartmouth's Concordia Boatyard here to celebrate
their 60th anniversary, which was to have been held last summer but
was postponed because of a bad storm. There were also five owners
on hand who came without their boats. Kersten Prophet, who owns the
only Concordia in Germany, flew from the Baltic for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   These saltwater folk traded stories and fibs over libations that
evening and then raced a 15-mile course Saturday in the chop of
Buzzards Bay. The wind was out of the southwest at a spirited 20
knots, good air for the yawls.
</P>
<P>
   These guys are obsessed. ``We're all nuts,'' says Walter Schulz,
owner of Absynthe. ``But instead of fast women and booze, I've done
it with wooden boats.'' He first saw Absynthe a few years ago under
a tarpaulin. It was badly in need of repair. ``I opened the cover,
and that was the kiss of death,'' he adds, shaking his head. ``Life
has never been the same since.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, who owns the Shannon Boatyard in Bristol, R.I., finished
building a 43-foot, state-of-the-art, fiberglass sailboat last week
that will sell for $650,000. Yet he sails a Concordia, modest by
those standards. ``It keeps me in touch with the Phoenicians,'' he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Such remarks surprise no one familiar with the Concordia
mystique. Owners of the yawls, built at 39 or 41 feet with their
mizzenmasts located behind the rudder post, will drop whatever they
are doing to sail. And they're great on water. ``The Who's Who of
America yachting got into these boats,'' says Brodie MacGregor, the
current owner of the Concordia Boatyard and organizer of the
reunion. More Concordias would have been here this weekend but for
the regatta at Edgartown and the New York Yacht Club cruise to
Halifax, Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   Concordia owners even have their own newsletter, published twice
a year by Skip Bergmann (owner of Paramour), in which they write
detailed narratives about endless maintenance and cruising.
</P>
<P>
   To own one of the 103 Concordia yawls made between 1938 and 1966
is to belong to a club as subtle as it is exclusive. ``It is a
cult,'' says Strohmeier, now 88, who has skippered 15 Bermuda and
18 Halifax races. A cult, yes, but an active one. No boat has been
lost yet, and almost all are still on the water _ a stunning
record.
</P>
<P>
   There are far more expensive boats to be had, far faster ones,
too. But then there is pride, first among the seven sins. In words
eerily intoned by other Concordia owners, John Bullard, who sails
Captiva, the yawl his father bought 34 years ago, says, ``I love
sailing into a harbor and watch everyone on every other boat turn
their heads.'' What's more, adds Ted Danforth, owner of Oriane,
``They all know the make. They ask, What number hull is that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Concordia yawl speaks about the values and taste of an owner
as do few other possessions. It is wooden boat in an age of
fiberglass, an elegant one in an inelegant time. ``If God had said
`yacht,' he'd have thought of a Concordia,'' says Danforth, who has
sailed on 150-foot schooners. ``It is an entirely simple elegance.
It is exactly the right size. It is the perfect Zen thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The yawl was built to cruise Buzzards Bay but excelled as an
ocean racer as well. It was designed in 1938 by Ray Hunt, better
known for the Boston Whaler, the deep V hull craft that
revolutionized the power boat industry; the 110 and 210 classes of
sailboats; and Easterner, the 12-meter that sailmaker Ted Hood said
was ahead of its time.
</P>
<P>
   But the driving force behind the Concordia yawl (and most
everything else in these parts) was the late Waldo Howland, who
owned the boatyard and tapped Hunt to design a boat after his
father's boat was destroyed in the hurricane of 1938.
</P>
<P>
   The first four Concordias were built in New Bedford and Boston.
After World War II, though, an extraordinary relationship began
between Concordia and the Abeking and Rasmussen shipyard in
Germany. From 1950 to 1966, the next 99 boats were built there,
then shipped from Bremen by steamer to Boston and towed through the
Cape Cod Canal to Padanaram, where they were finished. All of them
were built without a single contract. Everything was based on the
handshake.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, the Concordia is simply easy on the eyes. Up
close, it is an exquisite piece of work, crafted from oak, African
mahogany, locust, and butternut. Its spars were made of Sitka
spruce, its decks of teak, sometimes topped with canvas. ``Every
screw, visible or not, is lined up with the grain of the wood,''
says Bullard. ``You know the hands that screwed that screw.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, it is spare. ``My father was always reducing things
to their essence,'' says Kinnaird Howland, one of his four sons.
</P>
<P>
   Waldo Howland wanted a boat that would be timeless. He got it in
the Concordia. Part of the allure of his yawls is that they have
never been out of fashion because they were not built to the
strictures of International Offshore Rule.
</P>
<P>
   When other boatyards built to the IOR, ``All the boats began to
look the same,'' says Dan Nowlan. ``None looked like the graceful
Concordia yawls.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard recalls that in 1975 he crewed on a boat in the one-ton
world championships that was considered the fastest in its class at
the time. By August 1976, it had been outdesigned. ``In nine
months, we went from the fastest in the world to a boat with no
chance,'' he says. It is notable, then, that a Concordia won the
Bermuda race in 1978, 24 years after its first victory.
</P>
<P>
   Howland abhorred what he called ``the IOR horror'' almost as
much as he despised fiberglass. ``That's not where the truth was,''
explains his son, who recalls his father asking, voice laced with
sarcasm, ``Why not have a fiberglass diningroom table? They're
easier to clean. Or why not a fiberglass violin?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved wood,'' explains the younger Howland. ``It's kind to
the touch. It requires that you take care of it, and it's good to
take care of things. He felt that a wooden boat was something that
is worth having.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldo Howland had particular ideas about a lot of things. ``When
you had a daiquiri with my father, it had to be with Key limes, not
Persian limes,'' he adds. ``He could never get a decent one at a
bar.''
</P>
<P>
   The boat's sheer beauty explains in part why people pay $120,000
for a Concordia yawl in good shape _ seven times what one cost new
in the early Sixties. But never lost in its looks is its marvelous
sailing ability. It is a dream to handle in most conditions and
superb when it starts to blow. ``Two knowledgeable sailors can sail
that boat in almost any weather,'' says Larry Moulton of
Marblehead, owner of White Wave.
</P>
<P>
   The yawl is also narrow, heavy, wet, and a tight squeeze for the
crew of six needed for serious offshore racing. It doesn't like
light air. A new boat half its size has far more room below. ``It's
a canoe,'' says Kinnaird Howland. Worse, upkeep means the
hemorrhaging of time and money. But, he adds, none of this matters
because of ``the Concordia thing'' _ the mystique of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Logic does not prevail here,'' concedes Rusty Aertsen, owner
of Snowbird and a smaller Concordia sloop, Kestrel. ``They grow on
you like golden retrievers.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was just what Waldo had in mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
