<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREEN-TEA-EATING-WELL     07-20 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-TEA-EATING-WELL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS SHOW FAITH IN THE POWER OF GREEN TEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer, iced green tea has become the beverage of choice
for the health conscious, threatening to leave such standards as
black tea, coffee and even white wine in the dust. While some
drinkers are no doubt drawn to green tea for the novelty of it,
most are probably hoping that it will reduce their risk of certain
diseases, including cancer and arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies have indicated that green tea's pharmaceutical
properties may do just that. The tea contains polyphenols, powerful
antioxidants with cancer-fighting capabilities. Studies have
indicated that polyphenols may help protect against cancers of the
breast, lung, mouth and pancreas.
</P>
<P>
   But those studies were done in animals. The studies done in
humans, looking for green tea's effects on colon, rectal, stomach,
esophageal, pancreatic and bladder cancer, have had conflicting
results.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, all that has been proven for sure is that green tea
kills cancer cells in test tubes. There is epidemiological evidence
that the Japanese and the Chinese, who have been drinking a lot of
green tea for centuries, have a lower risk for several kinds of
cancer. Maybe it is the green tea, maybe it is something else. But
for many Americans, those laboratory studies seem to be enough to
start believing in green tea. Miriam Novalle, the owner of T Salon
T Emporium in Manhattan, says sales of green tea in her shop, which
carries 480 varieties of teas, of which 60 to 75 are green, have
risen 25 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't have to go to a tea shop. Last week, I found 22
varieties of green tea at one health food supermarket. There were
plain green teas and plenty of green teas flavored with ginger,
lemongrass, jasmine, spearmint, lemon verbena and citrus, as well
as those that had echinachea or ginkgo biloba, complete with claims
to health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Food and beauty products that loudly boast of green tea as an
ingredient have also proliferated. That same health food market had
three kinds of green tea pills, as well as a body cream containing
green tea and ginkgo biloba. It was not clear from the package what
the tea was suppose to do for the skin. But it is also not at all
certain that any product can claim bona fide health benefits just
because it contains green tea. Yet, many people seem willing to put
their faith in all kinds of unproven remedies, despite recent
history.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the oat bran craze? It turned out that people were not
willing to consume the large amounts that would reduce cholesterol.
And then there was the run on beta carotene supplements because
studies suggested the nutrient would reduce the risk of cancer.
Beta carotene in whole foods is indeed good for you, but clinical
trials determined that beta carotene supplements did not reduce the
risk of cancer and might actually increase it.
</P>
<P>
   Will green tea ultimately suffer the fate of oat bran? Stay
tuned. Among the studies under way are those trying to determine
whether green tea extract in the form of a pill would be effective.
But before consumers get to the point of taking a pill, research
will have to determine whether green tea is actually effective and
whether it is more effective than black tea; 95 percent of the tea
consumed in this country is black. Dr. John Weisburger, director
emeritus of the American Health Foundation in New York, doesn't
believe there is much difference between the two, but other
scientists disagree.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the caffeine question. Six ounces of green tea
has 25 milligrams of caffeine; black tea has about twice as much,
while brewed coffee has 105 milligrams. When green tea is
decaffeinated, it may lose some of its polyphenols, according to
studies at the Mayo Clinic. If it is decaffeinated by the water
process, the tea retains about 95 percent of the compounds. If it
is decaffeinated with ethyl acetate, which is also used to
decaffeinate coffee, it retains only about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With or without caffeine, not everyone likes the taste of green
tea, which can be astringent or bitter. But Ms. Novalle of T Salon
says the new spring teas, which have much younger leaves, are much
less astringent.
</P>
<P>
   There appear to be no downsides to making green tea your drink
of choice. How much you have to drink before any health benefits
kick in is another unknown. Some studies suggest two or three cups
is enough; others say 10 cups.
</P>
<P>
   There is already green tea jelly and green tea ice cream. Can
green tea muffins be far behind? But how much green tea ice cream
would you have to eat to get enough of those polyphenols? And would
their effectiveness be canceled out by the cream and egg yolks?
</P>
<P>
   This week, at least, I think I'll take my green tea in a
smoothie with lush peaches. As a hot weather refresher, it can't
hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
