<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER ACCENT ON HERBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 This is the first of eight columns by Waldy Malouf, the chef and an
owner of Beacon in Manhattan. His collaborator on these columns is
Melissa Clark.  
 By WALDY MALOUF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If fresh fruits and vegetables are the vocabulary of summer,
fresh herbs are the accent, instilling the light dishes of the
season with character and liveliness.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs are so plentiful and full of flavor at this time of year
that I always find myself experimenting more than usual. But it's a
risky business _ these little things have very big flavors. They
can easily overwhelm a dish or, in combination, fight each other so
violently the dish is left in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   So I don't use herbs indiscriminately or with abandon. No matter
how casual the dish, there's rarely that
handful-tossed-in-at-the-last-minute. I prefer a lighter, more
subtle touch, one that lets the meat or fish or vegetable be the
star, and the herbs a complement to their natural flavors.
</P>
<P>
   I am, of course, especially careful with the stronger herbs like
tarragon, sage, cilantro and rosemary. It's fine to have a dish
flavored primarily with one of them, like tarragon chicken, but
then, it's best to use the herb by itself, or with just a little of
a light, fresh counterpart like parsley or chives. I'm also wary
about mint or cilantro in cooked dishes. They have a tendency to
taste medicinal once they are heated.
</P>
<P>
   Once I've settled on the specifics, I tend to use the same
technique with almost everything I cook with herbs, layering their
flavors so they can be tasted in all their permutations. I like to
start with a marinade or rub, and then finish the dish with chopped
fresh herbs _ stirred into a sauce at the end of cooking, tossed
into a salad that's served alongside or just sprinkled on as a
garnish.
</P>
<P>
   This lets you experience the herbs as they infuse the food while
it marinates, as they cook and change in the heat, and in their
natural state, lively and fresh, at the very end.
</P>
<P>
   This chicken dish is a perfect example of that layering, and of
my summertime experimentation. It shows how a wintry dish can be
transformed with herbs, and a lot of trial and error, into
something lighter and more seasonal.
</P>
<P>
   Roast chicken is classic with a brown sauce and mashed potatoes,
but I was looking for something lighter and brighter for the warm
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a compound, or flavored butter under the chicken skin
before roasting is a traditional way to add seasoning. But instead
of using just butter, I use a lighter mix of olive oil and butter.
And instead of using only three or four herbs, I use ten.
</P>
<P>
   For something that sounds so simple, it turned out to be one of
the harder dishes for me to develop. Deciding which herbs I would
use was the easy part. I picked the ones whose flavors I knew would
work well together. There are lots of fresh, minty-flavored ones _
cilantro, chervil, mint and parsley _ because they give the dish
its zesty, summery quality.
</P>
<P>
   The more complex, pronounced herbs _ licorice-flavored tarragon,
piney rosemary and woodsy thyme _ add depth. Chives, oregano and
sage round out the mix _ but there's no basil. I find that it
fights with tarragon and rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out the proper proportion of each herb was the tricky
part. I probably made this dish 20 times before I settled on a
combination I was truly happy with.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the rosemary would overpower everything, and I'd have
a chicken that tasted like Vicks Vaporub. Other times, the tarragon
would be too strong, and I'd have licorice chicken. One mix ended
up tasting grassy, like lawn mower clippings.
</P>
<P>
   We kept charts in the kitchen and marked off how much of each
herb we used in the butter mixture, and how we would modify the
next day's mix. All I wanted was a succulent chicken covered in a
very crisp skin with a layer of herbs underneath.
</P>
<P>
   We forged on. Eventually, I got the chicken I imagined, and the
herb mixture became one of the few things we measure in the
restaurant kitchen, to insure the right proportions.
</P>
<P>
   I serve the chicken with a bread salad, made with the same herbs
I use in the butter compound, plus lightly sauteed wild mushrooms
and fresh tomato. In the end, it's the earthiness of the mushrooms
that gives the chicken a final roundness and brings the entire dish
together.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant, I cook this chicken on the rotisserie, but
you can easily roast it in the oven at home. The recipe for the
herb butter makes more than you'll need.
</P>
<P>
   Form the remaining butter into a log, roll it up in plastic wrap
and freeze it. It's a terrific thing to have on hand. Just slice
off a few coins whenever you want to add a little zing to grilled
meats, fish or vegetables. It's a perfect summer condiment. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   TEN HERB ROASTED CHICKEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours, plus 4 hours' marinating time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 3{-pound chicken
</P>
<P>
   { cup plus 2 tablespoons Ten Herb Butter (see recipe), softened
</P>
<P>
   Reserved herb stems from Ten Herb Butter
</P>
<P>
   { cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   \ cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   Herbed and Mushroom Salad (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced chopped herbs like those in Ten Herb
Butter, for garnish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Rinse chicken and pat dry with paper towels. Place chicken on
its back. Using a small, sharp knife, make 6 incisions into bird:
one in meaty part of each drumstick (go through the flesh), one at
joints of thighs (go under skin) and two under skin of breasts (one
cut on each side). Turn chicken over and make an incision on upper
part of each thigh.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place { cup herb butter in a heavy-duty resealable plastic
bag. Snip off a corner of bag and use it like a pastry bag. Squeeze
butter from opening into incisions in chicken (try to use an equal
amount in each incision). Massage herb butter into chicken. If any
squeezes out of incision, wipe it into cavity.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stuff cavity with reserved herb stems. Rub remaining 2
tablespoons herb butter all over outside of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   4. Using a piece of kitchen string, truss chicken, beginning at
neck and tying legs together. Place chicken in a bowl and cover.
Let chicken marinate in refrigerator for at least 4 hours, or
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   5. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place a rack in a roasting pan
and chicken on rack, breast side up. Roast chicken for 30 minutes.
Reduce oven to 300 degrees, and add chicken stock and wine to pan.
Roast chicken for another 25 minutes. Turn oven off and let chicken
rest inside it for another 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Remove chicken from oven and pour off all chicken juices,
reserving them. Spoon fat offtop and measure drippings; you should
have about { cup. Reserve for salad.
</P>
<P>
   7. When ready to serve, carve chicken into 8 pieces. Place
Herbed Bread and Mushroom Salad on platter and top with chicken.
Garnish with chopped fresh herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEN HERB BUTTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons truffle oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced, seeded jalapeno
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped parsley, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons chopped chervil, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons chopped cilantro, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon chopped sage, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon tarragon, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon oregano, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon rosemary, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoons chopped fresh thyme, stems reserved
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons chopped mint. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients but herb stems (reserve for chicken) in
food processor and blend well. Or, mix by hand until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Yield: 2\ cups herb butter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HERBED BREAD AND MUSHROOM SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces wild mushrooms (a combination of crimini, shiitake,
oyster, chanterelle or portobello), stems removed, caps sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   } cup freshly made 1-inch croutons (from 1 large slice toasted
sourdough bread)
</P>
<P>
   { cup reserved pan drippings from Ten &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herb Chicken (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup diced, seeded tomato
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced chopped herbs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small saucepan, heat 1{ tablespoons oil over medium high
heat. Add mushrooms and salt and pepper to taste and saute until
mushrooms are tender, about 5 minutes. Transfer mushrooms to a
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add remaining ingredients to mushrooms and toss well. Serve
immediately with the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
