<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-20 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: JOURNEYING INTO THE WORLD OF THE UNFAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's a vacation without guilt? For most Americans, no vacation
at all. Elsewhere in the world, a trip to the beach is a mindless,
happy frolic in the sun. An American takes a book, a serious book.
``Irregular French Verbs,'' perhaps, or a Dostoyevsky novel. And
doesn't read either one.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a self-improvement course of a different sort. Stay with
it and you'll love it; drop out and it won't make the slightest
difference to anybody. You'll just miss out on a few very good
wines.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is white wine season, and Americans drink more white wine
than anybody, most of it California chardonnay. Much of it is
excellent, but nevertheless there are hundreds of alternatives,
probably thousands. Many may be hard to find at your local
purveyor, as Americans are stick-in-the-muds when it comes to wine.
They find something they like and stay with it.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps we can change that. Just for the summer, why not
join me while we explore some little-known white wines? A tour
d'horizon, as it were, of the world's white grape vineyards.
There's nothing to sign, and no one will call. There are even a few
chardonnays on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The only serious contender to the chardonnay crown in this
country is sauvignon blanc. Almost everyone in California makes a
sauvignon blanc, but we're going to go far afield to search for
others: to New Zealand and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Sauvignon blanc is at its best, I think, when it has good acid
and the taste and smell of green vegetables. There are good ones
from France, but New Zealand astonished the wine world a few years
back with Cloudy Bay sauvignon blanc, a delicious, pungent wine
that seems to take your breath away. Cloudy Bay is still hard to
find _ it's that popular _ but there are other excellent sauvignon
blancs from New Zealand. Try Stoneleigh's, for example, or the new
Seresin, or one from Brancott.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's Mulderbosch sauvignon blanc is normally a bit
more fleshy than the New Zealanders' but gives up none of the
exciting bite and herbaceousness that characterizes these great
wines. Mulderbosch sauvignon blanc can be as hard to find as
Springsteen tickets, but rest assured, it's worth the search.
</P>
<P>
   If there is such a thing as an offshore grape, it's vermentino,
which grows on Corsica and thrives on Sardinia. Probably related to
the malvasia family, vermentino produces an assertive, full-bodied,
slightly lemony white wine that's just right for summer. Sella &AMP;
Mosca, Sardinia's best-known winemaker, turns out a delicious
vermentino.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to mix up pinot gris and pinot blanc: both are white
wine grapes, and both are derived from pinot noir, the red wine
grape of Burgundy. Pinot blanc has more body and a more pronounced
bouquet than pinot gris, which tends to be softer. Both grapes are
more popular in Eastern Europe than in the West, except for Alsace,
where pinot blanc weighs in as a respectable featured player billed
just below riesling and gewuerztraminer.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger's pinot blanc is a worthy example of what Alsace
can do with the grape. The wine is lean and flavorful, but with
little of the complexity of a good riesling. In Santa Barbara
County, Calif., Au Bon Climat makes a delicious pinot blanc.
</P>
<P>
   For pinot gris, we'll pass over the obvious, the many Italian
pinot grigios, and settle on an Oregon version from the King
Estate, a relatively new player on the Oregon scene.
</P>
<P>
   More and more Oregon wineries are experimenting with pinot gris,
with interesting results. The best are fresh, lively wines, often
with an intriguing mineral taste. They might give Oregon chardonnay
some serious competition.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing exotic about a wine from St.-Veran; it's
basically a good Macon blanc with an upgrade. The Macon region,
technically a part of Burgundy, is a huge, white-wine-producing
region between Burgundy proper and Beaujolais. About 30 years ago,
the powers that be combined six towns near Pouilly-Fuisse into one
appellation, St.-Veran. The wines, 100 percent chardonnay, often
approach Pouilly-Fuisse in quality and are invariably cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   From Galicia in Spain's wet and wild northwest corner comes
Albarino, a wine high in alcohol and rich in both body and flavor.
It has been compared with France's viognier but is, to my taste,
more restrained and elegant. Albarino is one of only a handful of
Spanish varietals, wines identified by the name of the grape. And
while little known outside Spain, it is arguably Spain's finest
white wine.
</P>
<P>
   Equally obscure is Italy's arneis, a wine found almost
exclusively in the Piedmont, where for years it was used to soften
wines like Barolo, made from the powerful nebbiolo grape. Because
of this connection, it was once known mostly as the nebbiolo
bianco, or white nebbiolo. The best-known arneis is made by Bruno
Giacosa, who is known principally for his red wines. Angelo Gaja
introduced me to arneis in a little restaurant near his winery in
Alba.
</P>
<P>
   Marsanne and roussanne are the white wine stars of the Northern
Rhone Valley. Marsanne is more plentiful and is more readily found
blended into the region's better white wines like St.-Joseph,
Crozes-Hermitage and white Hermitage. In California, it turns up
now and then as a varietal. Roussanne, the more attractive of the
two, has an aroma that has been likened to green tea. Its
pronounced acidity enables it to age for many years. Chateau de
Beaucastel in Chateauneuf-du-Pape and Bonny Doon Vineyard in
California both make delicious roussannes.
</P>
<P>
   For New Yorkers, particularly those who regularly frolic on the
golden strands of the Hamptons, an enticing little reward awaits
them if they travel to Long Island's North Shore: it's the
gewuerztraminer at Lenz Winery in Peconic. Gewuerztraminer is not
for everyone; its pungent flowery bouquet and pronounced taste can
be off-putting for the faint of heart. But this is summer and, for
even the most timid enophiles, a time for adventure. What's more _
and this from an old gewuerz fan _ Lenz's version of this Alsatian
favorite is delicious.
</P>
<P>
   And there you have it. Not a long list, but a reasonably serious
one. And _ be honest, now _ more fun than Dostoyevsky on the beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
