<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISSOLVING YEAST IN MILK OR WATER  
 EXPLAINING MODIFIED FOOD STARCH  
 CHIPOTLE CHILI POWDER, SO DISTINCTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why does yeast dissolve in water but clump in milk? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yeast will clump in any liquid that is cold, whether water or
milk. The temperature must be around 105 degrees to dissolve it.
But milk, unlike water, needs to be scalded first, or heated to 198
degrees, to break down enzymes that inhibit the growth of the
yeast. After scalding, the milk must be cooled to 105 degrees (it
will feel very warm to the touch) and then stirred to eliminate any
hot spots that can kill the yeast. (Uneven heating is common with
milk because of its fat and protein content.) The yeast can then be
safely added. However, it's much easier and less risky to dissolve
yeast in a small amount of warm water and to add the milk later.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Modified food starch is listed as an ingredient in many
foods. What is it made from, and why is it used? Are there any
health drawbacks? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Modified food starch is simply a starch from a vegetable like
corn that has been chemically treated to make it easier to
incorporate into processed foods like puddings and gravies. It may
also be found in baby food, where it works to keep the purees from
secreting liquid. According to the Food and Drug Administration,
modified food starch is perfectly safe to consume. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I want to make a chili recipe that calls for chipotle chili
powder. Can I use regular chili powder instead? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Chipotles are actually smoked jalapenos. It's difficult to
find a substitute for the powder because the flavor is so
distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Kalustyan's _ at 123 Lexington Avenue (28th Street) in New York
City; (212) 685-3451 _ sells chipotle powder for $3.99 for 4
ounces. The store also fills mail orders.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor fades as the powder sits, so you may want to buy
whole chipotle chilies ($3.49 for 1.25 ounces at Kalustyan's),
which keep almost indefinitely. To use them, toast them in a dry
skillet for about a minute on each side and then grind them in a
food processor or by mortar and pestle.
</P>
<P>
   You could also consider the canned chipotle chilies in adobo
sauce sold in large supermarkets and Mexican markets. Stirring in
one or more of the chopped chilies will impart that characteristic
smoky taste to your chili.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
