<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      07-20 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SIDE OF EGGPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eggplant is so strongly associated with the cuisines of Italy
and southern France that no matter what the cooking method, it is
usually prepared with olive oil and garlic. But with a few changes,
you can make a relish that turns a plain boneless chicken breast
into an unusual and appealing dish.
</P>
<P>
   The flavors of ginger, shallots and cilantro, which I prefer
here, are not strictly linked to any style of cooking, nor are they
the only possible ones. If you want a more traditional dish,
substitute garlic for ginger (or use half of each to make the
total) and revert to olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting additions include seeded and chopped tomatoes,
stirred in at the last minute to boost color as well as flavor; the
combination of tomatoes and ginger is unexpectedly pleasant. (Peel
the tomatoes if you like, but I don't think it's worth the effort
in this case.) Or you could cook some chopped red or yellow bell
pepper along with the eggplant.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of grilling or broiling chicken breasts to serve with
the eggplant mixture, you could use any reasonably tender steak of
beef, pork or lamb, or a sturdy piece of fish like tuna or
swordfish.
</P>
<P>
   Some may wonder whether or not to salt the eggplant. For years,
I believed this time-consuming step aided in browning. But browning
is more of an issue when you slice eggplant and want crisp
tenderness. Here you want it to become soft, almost mushy, so don't
waste your time salting.
</P>
<P>
   Do spend a few extra minutes to cook the shallots before the
eggplant, letting them brown and begin to soften. And hold out the
ginger until near the end. Ideally, this dish combines creamy
eggplant with tender but slightly crunchy shallots and sharp
ginger. With the cilantro, it's downright exotic. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN BREAST WITH EGGPLANT, SHALLOTS AND GINGER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces shallots (about 6 large)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup neutral oil, like canola or grapeseed
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1\ pounds eggplant, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh ginger or 2 teaspoons dried ginger
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds skinless, boneless chicken breasts (4 half-breasts)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup or more minced fresh cilantro for garnish, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel shallots. If they are small, leave them whole.
Otherwise, cut them in half the long way. (Most large shallots have
two lobes and will naturally divide in half as you peel them.) Heat
the broiler or a gas or charcoal grill.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place oil in a large nonstick skillet, and turn heat to
medium high. Add shallots, and cook about 5 minutes, stirring
occasionally, until they begin to brown. Add eggplant, salt and
pepper, and lower heat to medium. Cook, stirring occasionally,
until eggplant softens, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. When eggplant begins to brown, add half the ginger, and cook
3 minutes or so more, until eggplant is very tender and the mixture
fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   4. Meanwhile, rub chicken breasts with salt, pepper and
remaining ginger. Grill about 4 inches from the heat source for 3
minutes a side or until done.
</P>
<P>
   5. Stir half the cilantro into eggplant mixture. Serve chicken
breasts on a bed of eggplant. Garnish with remaining cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
