<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7167 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-MEDIA-HNS &LR;      07-20 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-MEDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVERAGE OF KENNEDY TRAGEDY AN EXAMPLE OF MEDIA OVERKILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK RANZENBERGER  
 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT PLEASANT, Mich. _ John F. Kennedy Jr. was missing. His
private plane was flying to Martha's Vineyard, disappeared from
controllers' radar screens and didn't land on time. The Coast Guard
launched a search, as it does in every case of a missing aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The media went gaga.
</P>
<P>
   I had been out in the woods of Northern Michigan for a week, and
returned Saturday, stopping off at a laundromat in Mio, Mich., a
tourist town on the Au Sable River, to wash my filthy camp clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Like many public places, the Sit and Spin Laundromat has a
television. When I walked in, the tube was showing pictures of
water with a ``Breaking News'' logo.
</P>
<P>
   Was it another Flight 800? Was the president's plane missing?
Had a cruise ship gone down, with the Coast Guard desperately
pulling children and grandmothers from the icy ocean? Had
terrorists or some rogue nation managed to torpedo the USS Harry S.
Truman, the United States' newest and most powerful aircraft
carrier, provoking World War III?
</P>
<P>
   I noticed something else. No one was watching.
</P>
<P>
   I got closer to the TV so I could hear the sound. No one had
turned it up. The rumble and clatter of the washers and driers,
along with the bangs and squawks from the lineup of video games and
a couple of old-fashioned pinball machines, made it hard to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The picture cut to Dan Rather. I got close enough to hear him
explain, obviously for what seemed to the 47th time for the benefit
of those who just tuned in, that the airplane piloted by John F.
Kennedy Jr. was missing. Details remained sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I understood why no one was watching.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people my age, I will never forget where I was that
November afternoon in 1963 when Kennedy's father, President John F.
Kennedy, was murdered in Dallas. I was in the third grade at St.
Helen School in Saginaw, Mich., and the principal, Sister Marie
James, was in tears as she announced the assassination of the
president on the school's public address system.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot forget the photograph of the president's son,
John-John, saluting his father's casket. Great photos are great
photos, and it still brings a lump to my throat.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the emptiness I felt after the killing of Robert
Kennedy in California in 1968. The world had gone crazy. But life
went on. The story was over, except for the supermarket tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in high school and college, it seemed that not a week
went by without some sleazy tale about Jackie O. I ignored it all.
</P>
<P>
   About the time John Jr. got his law degree, I started making
decisions about what to put in news reports, first in broadcast,
later in print. I was aware Kennedy had had trouble passing the bar
exam, but I also knew he passed eventually. He was just like
thousands of other aspiring lawyers. His failures and his successes
weren't news, as far as I was concerned. The New York media kept up
their heavy breathing and Kennedy became famous for being famous.
</P>
<P>
   He started a magazine about politics. He called it ``George.''
I, too, have dreamed of starting a magazine. What stopped me was
the fact that I didn't know enough rich people to cover the
inevitable startup costs.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. had money and knew rich people.
</P>
<P>
   I bought George on the newsstand because its edgy attitude
appealed to me. I bought it despite the fact it was edited by a
Kennedy, not because of it. I bought it because it was a good
magazine. I suspect JFK Jr. would have appreciated that.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. was famous and had an impact on society,
both through his charitable work and his specialty magazine. His
passing is tragic. It certainly was news. But the wall-to-wall
coverage given the event by the national media was overkill, pure
celebrity-driven hype.
</P>
<P>
   The customers of the Sit and Spin understood that. They sent the
message loud and clear by turning away from the TV and dropping
quarters into the video games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ranzenberger teaches journalism at Central Michigan
University in Mount Pleasant, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
