<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Washington) _ President Clinton says he told
Chinese President Jiang Zemin the United States would have serious
concerns with any abridgment of the peaceful dialogue between China
and Taiwan. Meanwhile, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
announces that U.S. envoys are headed to Beijing in next day or so,
and she plans to discuss the China-Taiwan rift with her Chinese
counterpart in Singapore. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-FUNERAL (Washington) _ As the families consider final
tributes for John F. Kennedy Jr. and his wife, they have a rich
legacy of farewells on which to draw. For the Kennedys, with their
stunning series of services for those who have died too young or
very old, funerals have become a poignant art form that weaves into
a the framework of the Roman Catholic Mass touches of the
patriotic, political and very personal. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO-11 (Washington) _ On the 30th anniversary of man's first
step on the moon, the crew of the historic Apollo 11 mission visits
President Clinton at the White House and at a ceremony at the
National Air and Space Museum received the Samuel P. Langley medal,
the highest honor bestowed by the Smithsonian Board of Regents. The
medals are given to Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins
by Vice President Al Gore. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-GAYS (Washington) _ The Rev. Robert Nugent, rebuked by
the Vatican last week for ministering to gays around the nation for
the last 25 years, says in an interview the action was ``a setback
and a disappointment'' for Catholic homosexuals seeking greater
acceptance in the church. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECH (Washington) _ President Clinton invokes the name
of President John F. Kennedy three times _ in a speech calling on
the nation's legal community to ensure greater racial diversity,
Rose Garden remarks calling for Senate passage of the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty and in lauding the Apollo 11 astronauts. By NANCY
MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   SEATBELTS-BLACKS (Washington) _ Federal transportation and
health officials announce plans to urge African-Americans to wear
car seat belts in the wake of a report that found young blacks half
as likely as whites to be buckled, doubling their chances of being
killed in car crashes. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SWEEPSTAKES-SCAMS (Washington) _ Support for a bill to crack
down on sweepstakes companies is growing in the Senate as more
evidence of deceptive practices by small firms is uncovered. The
measure, offered by Sens. Susan Collins, R-Maine, and Carl Levin,
D-Mich., has 33 co-sponsors. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. Will also
be filed in the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'') category.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-BANKS (Washington) _ Consumers should be given the right
to stop banks from releasing to other companies private information
about them such as what they buy or how much they earn, business
and privacy experts tell Congress. By MARK HELM. Will also be filed
in the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'') category.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-CRASH (Woods Hole, Mass.) _ Divers searching for
wreckage of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s aircraft are back in the water
though there is no evidence yet of any significant discoveries.
Also, a Cape Cod newspaper reports that registration papers from
the plane washed up on the beach of John and Caroline Kennedy's
estate on Martha's Vineyard. By JOE STINEBAKER.
</P>
<P>
   HELICOPTER-ACCIDENTS (Houston) _ Emergency medical helicopter
accidents so far this year equal the number of crashes that
occurred in all of 1998, focusing the attention and concerns of
industry observers on what some call ``hazardous helicopter duty.''
The seven accidents have happened in Florida, Illinois, Kentucky,
Nevada, Ohio and Texas. By JANETTE RODRIGUES. (Graphic available on
NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ NASA prepares a second bid
to launch the shuttle Columbia with the Chandra X-ray Observatory,
perhaps the only opportunity it will have to begin the much delayed
mission until next month. The space agency targeted the second
attempt from the Kennedy Space Center for 12:28 p.m. EDT Wednesday.
By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The split-up of that champion of
traditional family values, ex-House Speaker Newt Gingrich, and his
wife Marianne confirms that his political claim to spousal devotion
didn't mean beans. And Gingrich isn't the only politician who
preaches high moral standards for others and fails to behave
accordingly himself. So let's get off the family values kick. It's
hypocritical. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-MEDIA (Mount Pleasant, Mich.) _ John F. Kennedy Jr. was
famous and had an impact on society, both through his charitable
work and his specialty magazine. His passing is tragic. It
certainly was news. But the wall-to-wall coverage given the event
by the national media was overkill, pure celebrity-driven hype. By
MARK RAZENBERGER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros will be aiming for
their ninth consecutive victory _ one short of the franchise record
_ as they try to complete a three-game sweep of the Cleveland
Indians on Wednesday night at the Astrodome. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   RAC-SPEEDWAY (Houston) _ With superspeedways sprouting up across
the country to lure the red-hot NASCAR drivers, it was only a
matter of time before somebody decided to try to build a
motorsports facility in Houston. After all, the area draws record
crowds to the drag races in nearby Baytown twice a year and had a
sellout crowd for its inaugural Houston Grand Prix CART race last
fall. One entrepreneur already has announced plans for a
superspeedway, but he's not the only one in the race. By TERRY
BLOUNT.
</P>
