<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAPE-$ADV25-CO     07-20 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAPE-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAPE COD: THE KENNEDY LEGEND AND MUCH MORE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 25.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNIS PORT, Mass. _ Our travel plans to Cape Cod had not
included a sunny weekend of staking out the Kennedy compound
overlooking the sparkling blue waters of Nantucket Sound.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, that's what happened after my wife, Sherry,
clicked on the TV in our hotel room and said, ``Hey, you'd better
come look at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Before journalistic duty called, however, we had explored other
parts of the scenic peninsula that extends 70 miles into the
Atlantic. There's much more to the Cape than the exclusive Kennedy
enclave, a cluster of white clapboard houses that has served as a
TV backdrop since John F. Kennedy Jr.'s private plane disappeared
into the waters off the nearby island of Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod is shaped like a flexed arm with the Massachusetts
mainland at the shoulder, the Chatham Lighthouse at the elbow, Cape
Cod Bay above the biceps, and funky old Provincetown at the fist.
</P>
<P>
   Spread over the Cape's 399 square miles are 15 towns _ similar
to counties, each containing several villages. Hyannis Port, for
instance, is a village in the town of Barnstable.
</P>
<P>
   With about 560 miles of shoreline, there are stretches of
crowded beaches, scores of secluded coves, dozens of docks, a
desert of sand dunes, 13 lighthouses and waves of waterfront
restaurants where the staples are local lobsters and clam chowder.
</P>
<P>
   Along the crowded sidewalks of Main Street in Hyannis and
Commercial Street in Provincetown, there are all sorts of bars,
shops and eateries and pedestrians. The style ranges from tattooed
torsos in tank tops to polo shirts, cargo shorts and Topsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilgrims explored Cape Cod before deciding to settle in
nearby Plymouth. Sandwich, the Cape's oldest town, was established
in 1637. Naturally, history provides much of the allure for
tourists. There are museums and weathered old shingled houses and
antique shops galore.
</P>
<P>
   We took two drives along 6-A, the scenic road also known as the
Old King's Highway, that winds along the northern shore of the Cape
from the Sagamore Bridge to Provincetown, although at times it
merges with the multi-lane Highway 6.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was formidable. The year-round population of about
208,000 swells to more than 500,000 between Memorial Day and Labor
Day. With many winding byways and small communities, there are
frequent ``rotaries'' _ the local term for terrifying traffic
circles where three or five roads converge.
</P>
<P>
   Route 6-A provided glimpses of the restored houses of sea
captains, many set in yards abloom with blue hydrangea. Two
centuries ago, Cape Cod was the bustling home port for whaling
vessels.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the road wound beneath a canopy of leafy interlocking
branches, and at other times it passed prairies of salt marshes or
inlets crowded with sailboats.
</P>
<P>
   One evening, passing through the town of Orleans, we drove down
a side street to the Rock Harbor docks and found the seafood shanty
of Cap'n Cass. A charitable adjective would be ``rustic'' for the
tiny place, where old buoys served as decor. But our meal was
delicious _ a salad of lobster and crab meat surrounded by wedges
of fresh tomatoes from nearby gardens. We drank iced tea, but
noticed that other diners, aware of local blue laws, had brought
their own bottles of wine or small coolers of beer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps liquids were on our minds because a few hours earlier we
had traversed the hot, dry and seemingly endless sand dunes in the
Cape Cod National Seashore _ 20,000 acres of undeveloped terrain
that President John F. Kennedy preserved in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1946, Art Costa has been conducting tours of the inner
dunes near Provincetown. Riding in an aging Chevy Suburban on
under-inflated tires, we crossed miles of sand, passing scrub oaks
and pitch pines that were more like shrubs than trees, and
marveling at the few remaining dune shacks where folks still live
without electricity or running water.
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Eugene O'Neill and automotive mogul Henry Ford once
owned dune shacks here, our driver declared. But he couldn't shed
much insight on why anyone would want to live amid such hardship
and isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be a good place to have a party,'' he reckoned. ``You
could whoop and holler all you want, with no neighbors to
complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Running out of ice would be catastrophic, however.
</P>
<P>
   Art's Dune Tours, which cost $12 and last about an hour, begin
and end in Provincetown, where the Pilgrims first landed in the New
World in 1620. Nowadays, P-town's Commercial Street offers a
lively, tawdry strip of T-shirt shops, art galleries, sidewalk bars
and restaurants near the docks that was reminiscent of both Key
West and the New Orleans French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Brassy men wearing miniskirts and Dolly Parton wigs rode
tricycles down the street and passed out invitations to the Barbie
Drag Review. Families lined up nearby to take the Portuguese
Princess out to watch whales in Cape Cod Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Another center of activity on the Cape is Main Street in
Hyannis, where the promenade continues practically around the
clock. Indeed, we ate two meals at Main Street establishments on
one Saturday _ an 8 a.m. breakfast at The Egg and I and an 11 p.m.
dinner at the Hyannis Brewing Company. Both seemed great _ perhaps
because all we had to eat in the intervening 17 hours was an ice
cream cone at the Four Seas. This was the day after the Kennedy
plane went down, so there wasn't much time to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The Egg and I serves only breakfasts. We went for the regional
fare _ cranberry pancakes for me and crab cakes egg benedict for
Sherry. Sticking with this theme for our late dinner, we both
ordered baked lobster topped with a seafood mixture of shrimp, crab
meat and scallops. No complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few miles from Main Street, Joseph P. Kennedy Sr. bought
a beach house in Hyannis Port in 1929. A decade later, the Four
Seas shop opened in nearby Centerville. Four generations of
Kennedys have eaten its ice cream _ charging their cones, since
vacationing members of the family rarely carry cash. The homemade
peach was Jacqueline Kennedy's favorite flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Kennedy compound is several houses around a
cul-de-sac in a quiet waterfront neighborhood. The best way to view
the houses and their private beach is from the boat cruises that
leave from Hyannis Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to overstate the Kennedy presence around Hyannis.
</P>
<P>
   The John F. Kennedy Hyannis Museum is located on Main Street,
and its exhibits focus on the Kennedy family's ties to the Cape.
The John F. Kennedy Memorial is located in a park overlooking
Hyannis Harbor. There is a Joseph P. Kennedy Jr. Memorial Bowling
Alley, and the lobby of the Four Points Sheraton, the hotel where
we stayed, is decorated with pictures of the Kennedy family at the
Cape.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
