<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG AND STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chalone Vineyard Chardonnay 1997, Monterey, Calif. About $30.
</P>
<P>
   Among its many unusual distinctions, Chalone Vineyard, in the
Gavilan Mountains east of Soledad, Calif., can claim its own
appellation.
</P>
<P>
   To have, let's say, a Napa Valley appellation, a wine must be
made at a Napa Valley winery from Napa Valley grapes. Dozens of
wineries can claim the Napa appellation.
</P>
<P>
   The Chalone appellation, however, was created and approved by
the federal government solely for Chalone because its setting, its
soil and its climate are truly unique. So are its wines, when at
their best, and this chardonnay is at or near that level.
</P>
<P>
   Chalone wines have had some rough years but those times seem to
be in the past. This is a big and intense chardonnay. There is
plenty of oak but the wine sustains it handily. Acidity is
assertive enough to guarantee considerable age. For me, it recalled
a great Corton-Charlemagne, a Faivelely or a Latour, white wines
that sometimes seem eternally young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
