<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO GAPPERS SPARE ABILENE _ THIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Taylor County Old Settlers Reunion in Buffalo Gap, Texas,
went off without a hitch during the weekend, and the courthouse in
Abilene remains standing.
</P>
<P>
   It was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Gappers are still angry about losing the county seat 116
years ago, and there has been some talk around town that they might
storm the courthouse in Abilene to recover the old county records.
They also want the desk the records were stored in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has been done at this time,'' Velma Prentice, the
Buffalo Gap city secretary, said this week. ``I have some knowledge
of what's going on, but I am not going to say anything at this
time. When it all comes about, it will be a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Gap is a picturesque bend in Farm Road 89, nestled in a
small valley and shaded by huge live oak trees. Many of the people
who live there are descendants of the 200 founding settlers who
made their homes in the cut through the Callahan Divide _ a small
range of hills often called the Tonkawa Mountains. It was the first
town in Taylor County.
</P>
<P>
   It was also Taylor County's first county seat. The sandstone
courthouse is the centerpiece of Buffalo Gap Historic Village, a
small, neatly kept remnant of the town's past.
</P>
<P>
   The first floor of the 2,448-square-foot, 2-story building was
used as the courthouse, the upper level was Taylor County's first
jail. The sandstone was quarried from the nearby hills, and civil
war cannon balls were placed between the stones for support.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Gap had everything it needed _ plenty of trees, shade,
water and protection from both the Indians and the elements _ but
it didn't have the railroad, and that's where the rub came.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bitter fight for the Texas &AMP; Pacific Railroad, but
the rails were laid across a much flatter terrain into a tent city
called Abilene. In 1883, the 1,174 voting residents of Taylor
County agreed to move the county seat there. The county papers were
transferred, along with the desk.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Buffalo Gap say they were deceived by the railroad and
the election was nothing more than a theft of their county seat and
their economic future.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a newly formed group of Gap zealots who not only
want to promote the virtues of Buffalo Gap _ which are plenty _
they want the historic desk and its contents returned as well.
</P>
<P>
   There were secret plans made to raid Abilene during the weekend,
but group President Tom Perini cautioned the Gappers to use
restraint. Knowing it was meant only as a good-natured poke in
Abilene's ribs, Perini still warned that officials in Abilene might
not see the humor in a full-fledged frontal assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might want to let somebody at the courthouse know what
we're going to do,'' The Abilene Reporter-News quoted him as
telling his group. ``We really don't want to surprise Taylor County
with this. You know, they've grown quite a bit since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the group heeded his advice and backed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean anything,'' Prentice said of the forestalled
attack. ``There was too much going on down here anyway with the Old
Settlers Reunion. When the raid comes, it will be a celebration
within itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
