<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-GUARDS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENTS RECALL PROTECTING YOUNG JFK JR. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (bl)  
 By YOLANDA RODRIGUEZ   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Secret Service agents who watched over John F.
Kennedy Jr. as a child worked hard to keep him safe and out of the
hands of kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are trying to come to terms with his death, much as
they did when his father was killed while they were charged with
protecting the children more than 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think, God, I busted my butt to keep anything from
happening to that kid when he was vulnerable and not able to take
care of himself,'' said John Giuffre, a retired Secret Service
agent who lives in Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then later on, it comes to something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, Giuffre was part of the team of agents who were
assigned to guard Jacqueline Kennedy, Caroline and John Jr. He
guarded the children until 1964, when the family moved to New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much was done to help them and bring them along and to see
it end like this. It's just really sad, really sad. It's tough,''
said Giuffre, 64. As he spoke Monday tears came to his eyes and
flowed down his cheeks before he wiped them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had one word to describe him, he was probably an imp,''
Giuffre said of JFK Jr. ``He was not really a very adventurous
child. He was not one of those `I'll get into anything, do
anything.' He cried just like other little kids do. It was not
drilled into him `Kennedys don't cry.' ... That was the Bobby
Kennedy family. ... That was not the case with these children. And
like I said, he had the glint of the devil inside of him at times.
You just knew he was up to something.''
</P>
<P>
   After the family moved to New York, Giuffre did not keep in
touch with them. Instead he watched the children grow and maintain
their grace under the glare of the media lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were two great kids,'' largely because of Jacqueline
Kennedy's influence on them, said Giuffre, who was in the Secret
Service from 1959 until 1986. ``Those two kids were brought up in
such way that you just knew good things were going to come from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Kennedy wanted the children to have as normal a life
as possible and she taught them to be well-mannered and respectful.
The agents were never referred to by first name, Giuffre said.
</P>
<P>
   The children were taught that the dark-suited men were not there
to be their playmates. But every now and then, the agents got to
play with the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bounced John on my knee. He was an active little boy,'' said
Don Brett, who is also a retired Secret Service agent living in
Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   Brett guarded the children during the summers of 1962 and 1963,
when they vacationed in Hyannis Port with their mother, and again
during Christmas 1963 in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   That Christmas was a poignant one for the agents. It was a month
after President Kennedy had been assassinated. They were away from
their own families and guarding Jacqueline and the children.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her grief, the first lady made sure that each of the
agents received a Lacoste shirt for Christmas, Brett and Giuffre
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the children ignored the toys they were showered with and
made their own fun, Brett said.
</P>
<P>
   Of ``all these elaborate gifts that John and Caroline had they
took more pleasure in playing in an empty box,'' said Brett, 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask what kind of kids they were? They didn't care if the
toys came from FAO Schwarz or from Woolworth's. They were
interested in playing with the empty boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yolanda Rodriguez writes for the Herald-Tribune, Sarasota,
Fla., a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
