<SLUG> BC-BABOONS-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY MAY BE BABOONS, BUT THEY'RE NOT AS MACHO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Humans have bigger brains than those of baboons,
but many of us, sad to say, don't have much better personalities.
Members of both species are vicious, overly aggressive and
competitive to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder a human who's called a baboon takes it as an insult _
and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sapolsky of Stanford University, a onetime MacArthur
Fellow, runs a lab where he does important work on the neurobiology
of stress and disease. He has a terrific book (``Why Zebras Don't
Get Ulcers'') and a great reputation.
</P>
<P>
   So why has he been journeying to Africa just about every summer
for over two decades to roll in the muck and mire of baboonland?
Science. It makes people do strange things.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s and early 1980s, Sapolsky carved out a niche
by observing a troop of baboons in the Serengeti Plain of Kenya. By
plugging selected males with sleep-inducing darts, he was able to
extract blood and tissue for lab examination.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered something that was immensely reassuring to all
those guys who aren't quite kings of the hill: Top guns _ alpha
males who always got their way _ paid a price.
</P>
<P>
   While the testicles of dominant males had better supplies of
blood under stress _ thus increasing the levels of circulating
testosterone, a hormone likely to enhance muscle metabolism,
conferring a competitive advantage _ they were more susceptible to
disease when any slippage in rank occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical enabling them to function at high levels under
stress _ cortisol, an adrenal steroid _ was associated with
hypertension, impaired immunity and other ills. As they dropped in
rank, their basal, or resting, levels of cortisol tended to rise
and remain elevated whether or not they were under stress.
</P>
<P>
   It was a finding with important implications for humans.
</P>
<P>
   Then something terrible happened: Sapolsky's subjects began
dying.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-year period, the macho males critical to his work
indulged themselves at a tourist lodge's garbage heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each morning they barreled out of the trees, ran a mile and
hit the dump,'' Sapolsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, the meat in the dump was crawling with
tuberculosis germs, thanks to a scam run by a Kenyan meat inspector
and the lodge operator. TB kills people slowly. Baboons die from it
in a month. Sapolsky's pals _ Jessie, Shem, Saul and the others _
dropped like flies.
</P>
<P>
   He published two papers on TB in baboons, then called it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disgusted. It was a trauma. It wiped out my work. I
switched my attention to a new troop 40 miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, in the early 1990s, Sapolsky mustered up the
stomach to show his new wife the baboons of his professional youth
_ those that remained, at least. The experience shocked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was apparent this was a different troop than any I'd seen.
There were much lower levels of aggression. They were grooming each
other all the time. I saw a lot more male-to-male grooming.''
</P>
<P>
   The new guys weren't gay, they'd been socialized differently.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions were down dramatically. The No. 1 baboon still
dominated No. 10, but he didn't rub 10's nose in it.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the new guys in the troop were no longer peripheral
figures _ living at the literal edge, without sex lives, hammered
into the dust anytime an alpha had a bad day. Now they were treated
with some civility. Still no sex, but punching bags no more.
</P>
<P>
   What had happened, Sapolsky discovered, was this: The vacuum
left by the dead alpha baboons had been filled by adolescent
baboons from another troop. Those young males, in turn, had been
socialized by the baboons remaining from the old troop _ females
and males who hadn't pigged out at the garbage dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were living in a hippie commune-type troop,'' Sapolsky
said. ``They had lower stress hormones than I'd ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapolsky decided to return to his old troop and resume his work,
beginning next month. This time, he'll look at the whys and
wherefores of mellow baboon behavior, instead of the macho stuff.
</P>
<P>
   He'll test the theory that ``reconciliative behavior'' improves
health by bolstering the immune system and reducing disease caused
by stress.
</P>
<P>
   The work is being funded by ``A Campaign for Forgiveness
Research,'' an organization with a touchy-feely name that's engaged
in important work. It's on the Internet at Forgiving.org.
</P>
<P>
   The co-chairmen of the organization are Archbishop Desmond Tutu
of South Africa and former President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
