<HEADLINE>
THE PUBLIC'S RIGHT TO GET GRUMPY
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, July 27)  
(lb) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not that the public is always wanting to pick a fight. It's
just that it tends to not trust what it can't see.
</P>
<P>
   It feels that way particularly about corporations where
decisions seem to be made in a galaxy far away by someone who cares
more about money than people.
</P>
<P>
   So when the public thinks something is being foisted on it that
is not in the public good, it protests.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the San Francisco Bay Area public is protesting what
is being done to public radio. The public, at least a large, vocal
group of dismayed listeners, has rallied by the thousands to
protest management changes at KPFA-FM in Berkeley and apparent
moves by the Pacifica Foundation, its parent organization, to
muffle and mainstream the good old leftie.
</P>
<P>
   KPFA has long billed itself as a bastion of free speech, a truly
alternative media source that encourages dissent and debate.
</P>
<P>
   It was for and by the people. So now the people demand to know
what's up.
</P>
<P>
   During pledge season, public radio solicitors make a point of
saying that without you, the public, the station would not exist.
That the station cares most what you, the public, wants to hear.
And thanks to your individual pledge dollars, the station can bring
you what you will never get on commercial radio.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, KPFA convinced its listeners that they meant
exactly that, and that its loyal fans were part of the KPFA
community. The public, with all its warts and rants and opinions on
everything from the bombing of Iraq to goddess art, would always
have a voice on KPFA.
</P>
<P>
   The voice believed it so much that now the voice is in the
streets and at the front door of the station demanding to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Now it looks as if the public is being more true to the radio
station's mission than the station itself, celebrating dissent,
encouraging debate and demanding to know the story behind the
story.
</P>
<P>
   KPFA's public helped create something so Berkeley, so Bay Area,
so Californian and so American in terms of healthy diversity that
those who believe in all the above are naturally fried. They worry
that KPFA will be permanently replaced by bland, predictable,
middle-of-the-road radio in order to appeal to big corporate
donors.
</P>
<P>
   You don't expect people in public radio to care about making
money. They don't drive SUVs and play golf. They are a different
breed, spending their time worrying over places in the world that
commercial radio doesn't even try to pronounce.
</P>
<P>
   The public gets mad at people at the top when it thinks the top
isn't listening.
</P>
<P>
   It's why the public can work itself up over coffee sites and
bookstore chains. A few city blocks from KPFA headquarters,
shoppers and residents have their choice of four coffeehouses on
Piedmont Avenue in Oakland. But now Starbucks wants a piece of the
action and the neighbors are upset.
</P>
<P>
   Now, why is Starbucks insisting on shoving into a place so amply
caffeinated? And where it's not particularly welcome? There is
already a Starbucks close by, at a strip mall, a place where
shoppers might be grateful for an espresso break. But on classic
old Piedmont Avenue, it's seen as an affront.
</P>
<P>
   It's become a common adversarial position _ corporate vs.
community _ so much so that some communities are on knee-jerk alert
to all newcomers. The one-bookstore town of Calistoga is fighting a
Copperfield's Books coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Independently operated and locally owned (local being over the
hill and county line from Napa to Sonoma County), Copperfield's
Books would normally seem like a compatible neighbor. But because
Copperfield's has other stores, its move into Calistoga is
challenged by the same town law that keeps out a Starbucks. It's
ironic, because Copperfield's had to deal with book giant Barnes &AMP;
Noble moving across the street from one of its stores.
</P>
<P>
   In Calistoga, it's less a David vs. Goliath contest and more a
David vs. Dave challenge. But the newcomer is still going to have
to convince a public naturally worried about being homogenized.
</P>
<P>
   Back to KPFA and its riled public. I think that even casual
listeners are identifying with the radio staff because of the issue
about corporate or outside control.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of people are wary of corporate control. We suspect that
people at the top have a ``whatever'' attitude toward the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   And the public is at the bottom. That isn't always the case and
it hasn't always been that way.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think it was the public that changed.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COCKTAILS-SHAKE-ART-2     07-20 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCKTAILS-SHAKE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE CUBES IN MIXING DRINKS: SIZE DOES MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shaken or stirred? It's a question that sounds like
the ultimate in sophistication. But the truth is that James Bond,
despite his smug smile, knew only the half of it. Cocktail-making
technique, a highly evolved skill, is as important to bartenders as
a drink's recipe. And often it's the technique _ including the
style of the shaker and the size of the ice cubes _ that
distinguishes one great mixologist from another.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, I was at Eleven Madison Park, searching for
something cool and refreshing to take the edge off the summer heat.
I ordered a Stanford: Bombay sapphire gin infused with chartreuse,
fresh lemon juice and mint, served straight up in a martini glass.
The liquid shimmered like a jewel, and the glass was as cold as a
beer from an ice cooler.
</P>
<P>
   What really made the drink, though, was not the cool glass or
the zip of fresh lemon juice. It was the tiny flat shards of ice _
almost imperceptible to the eye _ that floated on top of the liquid
and that melted on my tongue as I drank it, making it that much
more refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Had Francis Harris, the bartender, added shaved ice to it before
serving? No, he said, he just shakes his cocktails hard. So hard
that the ice shatters into shards, some of which slip through the
strainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bartenders are fussy,'' said Gustav Lee, the head bartender at
City Hall in Tribeca. ``I'm extremely particular about what I use
and how I use it.'' His fussiness begins with equipment. Lee uses a
silver-lined shaker, rather than the standard stainless-steel and
glass model.
</P>
<P>
   Silver shakers are expensive and difficult to find. ( Lee bought
his in an antiques store, and totes it back and forth to work every
day.) He insists that the difference is marked; silver shakers, he
says, get colder faster than the stainless steel ones, and stay
colder longer. He also detects a slight metallic taste to a drink
shaken in steel.
</P>
<P>
   He mixed two drinks for me, one in the silver, one in the
stainless steel. I put my palm to each shaker containing ice and
spirits. The silver shaker was so solidly cold it was difficult to
keep my hand on it for more than a second or two. The stainless was
mildly but perceptibly warmer. As for the metallic taste, that,
too, was apparent _ but not something I would want to prove in a
blind taste test.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Lee's dedication to silver requires more attention
than most bartenders are willing to give their shakers. Silver must
be relined just like tin-coated copper cookware, and it is simply
too much of a luxury for a piece of equipment that gets banged
around all day long. A used, silver-plated shaker is $50 to $100,
if you can find one (Jean's Silversmiths, at 16 West 45th Street,
will keep an eye out for them by request). Tiffany &AMP; Co. sells two
solid silver models _ for $775 and $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   A more common shaker that is falling out of favor lately is the
stainless-steel one with a cap and built-in strainer. It usually
comes in small sizes for individual portions. Some bartenders find
it clumsy; the cap rarely makes a tight seal, and it is too small
to shake vigorously enough to break up large pieces of ice.
</P>
<P>
   The great challenge of cocktail making is to get the liquids as
cold as possible as quickly as possible so the alcohol mixture
doesn't become too diluted. Which is why bartenders also obsess
over ice cube size.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Maher, the beverage manager at Beacon in midtown, uses
3/4-inch ice cubes. Dale DeGroff, the head bartender at Blackbird
on East 49th Street, insists on large one-inch cubes. Lee uses
flat, Frisbee-shaped ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use a one-inch cube, they won't break down,'' Ms. Maher
said. Though, she added, they are better for drinks on ice, because
they melt more slowly, keeping the drink intense for a longer
period. Lee contends that his flat ice has more surface area and is
less solid, therefore cooling liquids down more quickly and
breaking up amply in the shaker.
</P>
<P>
   No issue of cocktail making, though, causes more argument than
shaking.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking serves two purposes. First, by shaking liquid in ice, it
splashes up against the ice and against the cold sides of the
shaker, cooling it very rapidly before the ice has time to melt and
dilute the liquid. Stirring will also chill down the liquid, but
not as thoroughly and not as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking a drink also homogenizes, or emulsifies, it. Think of a
vinaigrette. If you stir the vinegar and oil together, they will
fuse loosely and separate. But if you whisk them together
vigorously, they will form a tight bond and emulsify into a uniform
liquid. The same goes for a shaken drink. The liquids, a small
amount of water from the ice and a little air emulsify, creating a
uniform, cold, lightly frothy drink. The temperature and particles
of water refresh and the air bubbles spread the flavor across your
palate. Traditionally, drinks with any kind of citrus juice are to
be shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want that spritz in a cocktail,'' DeGroff of Blackbird
said as he made me a Hemingway daiquiri. He poured rum, lime juice,
grapefruit juice, maraschino liqueur and simple syrup into a shaker
with those big cubes, fitted a glass into the open end and gave it
a shake so vigorous, his arm and the shaker were merely a blur.
</P>
<P>
   He strained it into a frosty chilled martini glass. When it
splashed in, the drink melted like whipped cream in hot chocolate,
frothing and bubbling. It was as cloudy as milk, then it settled.
As I drank it the bubbles in the liquid seemed to lift the flavor
out of each component; the froth was like cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Craddock of the Savoy once said `You shake them to wake
them up, not to put them to sleep,''' DeGroff said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is also an adamant and vigorous shaker. His technique is so
finely tuned, he works like a machine. When he makes a drink, he
adds the ice first to get the shaker chilling immediately.
Sometimes he will chill the vessel, dump the ice and refill it with
new ice before adding any liquor. Then he moves as if in
fast-forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to my ear,'' he said of the shaker. ``You can hear the
ice cracking and you can hear when it's done. It has a denser sound
when it's done. At that point you need to immediately pour it. You
can't dillydally.''
</P>
<P>
   His movements are so quick and powerful that the ice breaks up.
Though he strains his drinks well, all of his shaken drinks have
flecks of ice scattered across the top. ``I think they add a
certain something,'' he said, ``like a crema on espresso.'' He even
shakes a Manhattan, though he does it with less force, what he
describes as more of a flip or a toss.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Justin Hatch, the bartender at Union Pacific on East 22d Street,
does not worry about crema. He lets shaken drinks rest for 30
seconds before pouring. This method, he says, allows the drink to
get extremely cold without a lot of dilution.
</P>
<P>
   Though shaking techniques can vary as much as golf swings, the
idea is to hold the vessel with two hands and shake it back and
forth over the front of one shoulder, near your ear. Most
bartenders shake a drink for less than 10 seconds. If the drink has
many components and large ice cubes, they may go the full 10
seconds. If it is simply two liquids, they may shake it for as few
as five.
</P>
<P>
   Drinks made of pure spirits _ like vodka, gin or bourbon _ are
traditionally stirred. Shaking supposedly ``bruises'' the spirits,
by adding water and flattening their flavor. This issue divides
many bartenders today.
</P>
<P>
   DeGroff is a traditionalist. He stirs. If you shake a martini,
for instance, he said, ``the first thing that hits your tongue is a
frothy aerated drink.'' He prefers that first thing to be cold,
heavy and silky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martinis you are not supposed to shake,'' said Charlie Nezaj,
who has been the bartender at La Cote Basque for 19 years.
``Otherwise, it is not a martini. It is water.''
</P>
<P>
   More watery and some believe inferior. ``Because of the
vigorousness of the shaking,'' explained Ms. Maher, a stirrer of
martinis, ``the air bubbles remove the nuances of the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   In a stirred drink, you may taste layers of flavor. A Manhattan,
for example, is not a homogenous cocktail. If stirred lightly, a
sheet of whiskey may cover your tongue, then a splash of sweet
vermouth, or an uneven mix of the two. The vermouth has a greater
density, and because the two are not emulsified, they will slowly
separate and the vermouth will sink to the bottom as you drink it.
</P>
<P>
   DeGroff stirs his drinks about 50 times, but he uses large ice
cubes. With smaller cubes, he would stir less, perhaps 25
rotations, so that the drink doesn't become diluted. The method is
simple: you slide a cocktail spoon down the side of the shaker,
with the concave side of the spoon facing the side of the shaker,
and rotate the handle along the edge of the shaker.
</P>
<P>
   Which method is better? It depends on what you want out of a
drink. I tasted, side by side, two martinis made by Lee. One was
shaken. One was stirred. There was something more herbal, more
intense about the stirred one. I would not have refused the shaken
one. It was simply more mellow.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy, of course, is good. Today, new cocktails are
created as often as the weather changes. Techniques come and go.
There is often more flair than form. What is important is that
there are bartenders who continue to raise drink mixing from a
craft to an art. They are as much philosophers as they are drink
makers with a curiosity for the physics behind their craft.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until you push them too far. When I asked Lee why he
puts three olives in his martinis, he responded instantly, with a
grin: ``It's a prime number. Superstition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
