<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PIONEERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROVIDES NAMES OF `PIONEER' FUND-RAISERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By R.A. DYER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Under criticism from citizen groups, Gov. George W.
Bush has defended his ``Pioneer'' fund-raising efforts in which
individual supporters have each pledged to raise $100,000 or more
for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He also agreed to release the names of the 115 Pioneers, saying
they have led a grassroots effort on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who have decided to go out and solicit
contributions on behalf of my candidacy,'' Bush said on Monday.
``This is a grassroots organization and these are people who have
decided to take time out of their lives to help me become
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Although campaign finance law prohibits individual contributions
of more than $1,000, the influential supporters each volunteered to
collect $1,000 from up to 100 acquaintances and businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has come under fire by Texans for Public Justice
and the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington, D.C., both of
which contend that it skirts campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This buys access and influence,'' said Texans for Public
Justice director Craig McDonald. ``A $100,000 donor is going to
have more clout than a $1,000 donor. ... And that's what's going
on: In essence, these Pioneers are turned into $100,000 donors _
with all the clout that that implies.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hendrie, spokesman for the Center for Responsive Politics,
said the Pioneers will end up becoming ``ambassadors and attending
state dinners'' if Bush wins the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a private club you buy your way into,'' Hendrie
said. ``The people who are doing this certainly expect some perks
out of the whole thing. ... But this certainly is not unique to
Governor Bush _ he just is doing it better than any of the other
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the names on the list of Pioneers released by the Bush
campaign were former U.S. Rep Tom Loeffler of Texas; Bradford
Freeman of Los Angeles, a Stanford University trustee;
Michigan-based Heinz C. Prechter, who served as chairman of former
President Bush's Export Council; Democrat James Langdon, an old
friend of the governor's from Midland; Fort Worth businessman Lee
Bass; and Rusty Rose, who with Bush headed a group that purchased
the Texas Rangers in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the key fund-raisers would have greater access to
him if he were elected president, Bush responded: ``You either have
somebody in the process who is honest or not honest.''
</P>
<P>
   He said many of his best friends are among the Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to let the people respond, in order to give the
people a chance to express their decision in the year 2,000, it
requires organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, whose Texans for Public Justice had called on Bush to
release the names of the Pioneer fund raisers, and Hendrie, of the
Center for Responsive Politics, each praised Bush for identifying
members of the group.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush joked during an afternoon news conference Monday that
he wanted to publicize the names in order to pressure those who had
failed to reach the $100,000 goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I want you to publish the list,'' Bush said when
asked whether he would also provide the names of would-be Pioneers
who failed to meet the $100,000 goal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, having raised $37 million for his presidential bid, has
far outpaced fund raising of other presidential contenders. The
Bush campaign has also announced that it will not accept public
campaign matching funds, which will allow the campaign to avoid
strict spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said yesterday that the system gives undue advantage to
Vice President Al Gore, who is seeking the Democrat's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to put their candidate on a plane _ paid for by
taxpayers _ that's called Air Force 2,'' said Bush. ``And that
person can fly around the country, the whole time on taxpayer
money, making all kinds of promises _ and in the meantime, have an
opponent stuck with a bunch of limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Others on Bush's Pioneer list include Michigan Gov. John Engler;
state Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo; Houston lobbyist and attorney
Joe B. Allen; former Florida Gov. Bob Martinez; and Colorado Gov.
Bill Owens.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
