A7225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHORT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-20 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHORT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHORT AND SWEET': QUICK MEANS, SWEET ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even people who love to cook have days when they don't have time
to dawdle at the cutting board. So, cookbook writers have responded
with many books geared toward speed. They are rarely filled with
original recipes. Rather, they are packed with familiar ones that
have been dissected and reconfigured _ much in the way
manufacturers retool a production line _ to save the home cook a
few precious minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, food is not a widget, and many times these
streamlined recipes are disappointing. The shortcuts erode the
authenticity, force you to sacrifice ingredient quality with
packaged foods or result in dishes with inferior flavor for other
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Barnard, the author of ``Short and Sweet'' (Houghton
Mifflin, $25), understands this problem, and in her collection of
more than 175 desserts, she proves over and over that the recipes
can be pared down without losing their integrity.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the book appears as gimmicky as so many other
quick-cook books. But after using it, I almost forgot its theme. It
is smartly assembled with recipes that are appealing and
sophisticated. And there is no flab. There is a brief, well-written
foreword, and each recipe is introduced with an interesting tidbit.
That is all.
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes, like those for rhubarb fool, ice cream sandwiches
and chocolate pudding, serve as reminders: even years ago, home
cooking was not always a labor-intensive ordeal. Almost all of the
recipes are made from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barnard is inventive, too. Tangelos in warm caramel sauce is
a clever dish. She takes two flavors, citrus and herbs, that have a
natural kinship in savory dishes, and places them under a sweet
lens: the caramel sauce contains rosemary, bay leaves and B&AMP;B
liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   Many of her desserts contain ingredients that are like a nudge
in the side, that wake up the senses. There is curry in a fruit
salad, salted mixed nuts in honey-nut shortbreads, and Strega in a
syrup splashed over pears with pecorino and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barnard pays great attention to flavor and relies on
elementary techniques, like broiling fruit or whisking zabaglione,
to emphasize it. As a result, the recipes are efficient without
sacrifice. I spent no more than 20 minutes (excluding baking) on
any single recipe. The peppered pineapple papayas, which had a
sauce of pineapple, lime juice, rum and jalapeno, were the only
disappointment. The sauce lacked sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Every other one I tried, though, was startlingly good. The
Tuscan rosemary and pine nut bars took about two minutes to
assemble and turned out coarse, crumbly and heady with rosemary,
just as I imagined a Tuscan cookie would be. Candied ginger and
brandied plum sundaes were beautiful _ a sweet and fragrant
rose-colored syrup, soft pieces of tart plum and ginger, all
sliding down a scoop of sweet vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   The butterscotch pudding was a revelation. It takes a few
minutes longer to thicken than the recipe says, but when it does,
it is a treat _ silky, buttery and fantastically rich. Though it
takes very little time to make, it takes even less time to eat.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIED GINGER AND BRANDIED PLUM SUNDAES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Short and Sweet'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pound tart red or purple plums, pitted and thickly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons brandy
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped candied ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   1. In medium skillet over medium heat, melt butter with sugar,
stirring until smooth. Add plums and brandy, reduce heat to
medium-low. Simmer, uncovered, stirring until plums are soft but
not mushy and juices form a light syrup, about 5 minutes. Stir in
ginger; simmer 30 seconds. Cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   2. Divide ice cream among 4 shallow dessert dishes or goblets.
Spoon warm plums and sauce over top. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
