<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GERALDO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEAR SAILING FOR GERALDO IN MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. &LR;   &LR; _ In those final seconds of the year, when
most of world's 6 billion people are experiencing millennium
moments among the throngs, Geraldo Rivera will be bobbing on a
70-foot ketch called the Voyager, as close as he can get to the
international date line in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   It might be Fiji. Tonga is a possibility, too. The king of Tonga
apparently is a big Geraldo fan _ he sort of tilts toward big,
period _ and he's planning a party to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very large man with a very big family and seems like a
real fun guy,'' Rivera says.
</P>
<P>
   But Rivera seems to be aiming for an off-coast placement when
midnight arrives, the better to capture the moment for his Travel
Channel cable documentary, ``Sail to the Century With Geraldo
Rivera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be among the first to experience the new
millennium, and that's why we're doing it,'' Rivera said an
interview on the TV press tour. ``That's why the date line.''
</P>
<P>
   For all you sticklers out there, Rivera knows that yes,
technically, 2000 will be the last year of the current millennium.
Still, ``going nine-nine to zip-zip is pretty dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, even if Tonga's tops, Fiji's fine. The point is, this is
an altogether good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Come the millennium observance this New Year's, I'll want to
know where Geraldo is, and I'll like knowing he's thousands of
miles beyond serious mischief. Sailing somewhere in the serene
South Pacific, searching for an invisible line in the ocean, seems
a splendid thing to keep Geraldo occupied.
</P>
<P>
   One down, a few dozen to go. If there's room on the ketch for
Jerry Springer, Y2K would be looking sunnier still.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera has been at this for two years, sailing around the world
with his family since they left Cape Cod on Aug. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That was thousands of miles ago, though Rivera hasn't been under
sail continuously. He does have a day job. No, it's been a ketch as
ketch can kind of trip. Right now, the Voyager is docked in
Australia awaiting Rivera's arrival for another leg of the journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually came to the Travel Channel,'' he said, explaining
the two one-hour specials that make up ``Sail to the Century.'' The
first half is supposed to be shown in December, and the New Year's
Eve climax will be televised sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to document it. At first, I thought I would write a
book about it, and then I said it would probably be better if I
made a movie. We were doing some home video anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be a traditional travel documentary, Rivera said. Of
course not. They'll be stopping periodically to search for empty
bottles and Satan worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   No! Kidding. It'll be unusual because it'll be the Riveras _ dad
Geraldo, wife C.C., their two small daughters and Geraldo's son,
who was 18 at journey's start _ caught in the act of being
themselves, on a cramped 30 feet of floating real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of think of it as National Geographic meets the Loud
family,'' Rivera said. ``Or MTV's `Real People.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera signed an NBC News contract after he set off on his epic
sail. NBC allowed him to continue with the Travel Channel project,
and that decision has produced dividends.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rivera says he was in the Mediterranean and one of
the last to know that Princess Diana died two years ago. So that
delayed his coverage. Same thing with the Kosovo crisis;
incommunicado for more than a week, Rivera was crossing the Indian
Ocean when he heard, late again, that the NATO bombing had begun.
But he was soon behind Serb lines in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightly News'' anchor Tom Brokaw, not as big a Geraldo fan as
the king of Tonga, must have approved of keeping Rivera on board
the ketch and away from breaking news as long as possible. Brokaw
has successfully barred Rivera from the newscast, leaving Geraldo
with the ``Today'' program and with his one-hour specials on NBC.
Rivera says he can manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never be `one of the guys' over there,'' he said.
``But, you know, I'm on my fourth special now. They've been,
generally speaking, highly regarded by most of you all'' _ we all
would be the critics _ ``which is a great pleasure after having
survived six generations of TV critics ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And NBC is big enough that Brokaw and I can co-exist. You
know, it's like hopefully in the future the Kosovars and the Serbs
will get along.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
