<HEADER>
A7236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CODE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-20 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CODE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BETWEEN SILK AND CYANIDE': BRITAIN'S WARTIME SPIES AND SABATEURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In July 1940, after the Nazis had turned much of Europe into
occupied territory, Winston Churchill created the Special
Operations Executive, with instructions to ``set Europe ablaze.''
The idea was to infiltrate agents into conquered countries,
including France, Norway and the Netherlands, to collect
intelligence, engage in sabotage and prepare secret armies to
harass German forces once Allied landings took place.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the agency was a young cryptographer named Leo
Marks, the son of London's most famous old-book dealer and later
the screenwriter of the cult classic ``Peeping Tom.'' He was 22
when he was hired in 1942 to ``keep an eye on the security'' of the
agents' codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between Silk and Cyanide'' is Marks' memoir of his nearly four
years in the agency. It is an enthralling book, one full of an
eccentric charm as well as fascinating, previously undisclosed
details of the secret war waged in the occupied countries. It is
also consistently informed by an understated kind of moral passion,
and that makes it not only a fascinating memoir but an inspiring
one as well. As much an account of his own contribution to the war,
it is a testament to those who risked their lives behind enemy
lines and whose precarious communications with home it was Marks'
duty to protect.
</P>
<P>
   His book is valuable despite some flaws in its execution. In a
few places his story is muddled and difficult to follow. His book
could have used better editing, and the index is unreliable. Marks
is one of those people who cannot resist a witticism, and this
gives his narrative a perpetual and predictable flippancy.
</P>
<P>
   His wisecracks are sometimes pretty funny, but they are often
strained, sophomoric and tiresome. (``When I realized what I
 &UR; should &LR;  have done, I hit my forehead so hard I improved its
shape.'') Still, his story is intrinsically interesting, and he is
very likable. The tendency is to forgive him his foibles and
appreciate him for his many good qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Marks' story is about cryptography and the battles he
fought against bureaucratic resistance to the innovations he knew
were necessary to make agents safer. He insisted, for example, that
unending efforts be made to decode the many agents' messages that
arrived so mangled as to be indecipherable. The pre-Marks practice
was to require the agent to repeat the indecipherable message in
the next scheduled transmission, a practice that increased the risk
that the agent would be caught.
</P>
<P>
   Marks pioneered clever new decoding techniques, and he exhorted
the young female volunteers who did most of the routine decoding
work never to give up on an indecipherable message. In a speech to
the women he evoked a young female agent who has had no sleep for
three nights, is being hunted by the Gestapo and has to re-encode a
message she has already sent:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasn't that agent a right to make a mistake in her coding?
And, if she does, must she pay for it with her life? Must she come
on the air again to repeat her message, whilst German
direction-finding cars get her bearings?''
</P>
<P>
   Marks' book is also an anecdotal history of the agency and some
of its operations. One of his duties was to give final briefings on
codes and coding to agents about to go into the field, and he got
to know many of the men and women who went behind enemy lines.
Among them were members of the commando team that destroyed the
heavy-water plant in Norway that the Germans were using for their
atomic bomb program. The destruction of the Norsk heavy-water plant
is one of the better known episodes of derring-do in the war, but
Mark's portraits of the Norwegian commandos are vivid and intimate.
</P>
<P>
   Marks' account of the Gestapo's capture of almost the entire
network of agents that had been sent into the Netherlands is one of
the best and most concrete you are likely to read about the awesome
uncertainties of behind-the-lines warfare. The agents continued to
send properly coded messages to London. The crux of the matter
therefore was ascertaining from small clues in those messages (one
of which was the absence of the more common coding mistakes)
whether they had indeed been captured and were sending
disinformation with the Gestapo at their shoulders. Marks also
tells the stories of several other agents he briefed or trained,
and his portraits are always deft and touching.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is the man known to Marks as Tommy (real name Forest
Frederick Yeo-Thomas), a Royal Air Force lieutenant who spoke
perfect French and was part of the Free French branch of the
British agency. How Marks remembers verbatim conversations he had
with Yeo-Thomas that took place 50 years ago is not explained. But
these conversations have a terse, rough sort of camaraderie about
them, and they ring true.
</P>
<P>
   Yeo-Thomas made several undercover trips to France, the last one
to try to rescue another leader of the Free French Resistance,
Pierre Brossolette, captured by the Gestapo in Brittany early in
1944. The story of Yeo-Thomas' rescue effort as filtered through
the eyes of his friend back in England would alone justify this
book.
</P>
<P>
   But there is much else here as well, including the stories of
two memorable women who flew into enemy occupied territory but
never made it back. There are funny scenes, too, as when Marks
persuades a roomful of proud and touchy French officers that the
code they believe impregnable is actually easy to break. Marks
tells the suspicious Frenchmen that if they don't change that code,
their agents in France won't be around after the war. Stories like
that one give this book its wonderfully concrete, practical and
ultimately moral character.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BETWEEN SILK AND CYANIDE
</P>
<P>
   A Codemaker's War, 1941-1945'
</P>
<P>
   By Leo Marks
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 614 pages. Free Press. $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
