<HEADER>
A7241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-SOUL-1STLD-WR     07-20 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-SOUL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN CHICAGO REWRITE THE SOUL FOOD GOSPEL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs to add recipes at end) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Lore has it that Muhammad Ali is partial to the rice
and beans. The Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. liked the fried
chicken, Sammy Davis Jr. and Cab Calloway the corn muffins and
catfish. And Mayor Harold Washington held legendary strategy
sessions over the baby back ribs and black-eyed peas.
</P>
<P>
   The place is Army &AMP; Lou's, smack on the South Side of Chicago, a
city that over the years became perhaps the greatest stronghold of
soul food in the North. Army &AMP; Lou's, like soul food itself, is
still a stalwart, still serving chitterlings and smothered chicken,
still attracting politicians like Mayor Richard M. Daley and the
Rev. Jesse Jackson to take the pulse of the black neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But soul food in Chicago has been breaking out of some of its
familiar boundaries _ geographically and gustatorially. At new
``soul'' restaurants in new neighborhoods, the catfish may be
studded with pecans and the cook may not even be black. And as soul
food branches out, it reflects changes in the city, in Chicago's
black population and in the very role of soul food itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Chicago has become far more diversified,'' said Sterling
Plumpp, a professor of African-American studies and English at the
University of Illinois at Chicago. ``African-American culture has
arrived to the point where it's being accepted in other
communities, and African-American cuisine is being mainstreamed.
There are select geographies in the city now where skin color is
not used as a passport for participation in communal life.''
</P>
<P>
   That is no small feat in Chicago, still one of the country's
most segregated cities, where, beginning early in the century,
waves of blacks migrating from the South clustered primarily on the
South and West Sides. Soul food, passed down through generations of
plantation and sharecropper families, swept into these
neighborhoods the same way the blues did, as people from
Mississippi and Georgia and Alabama brought their mothers' or
great-aunts' recipes for sweet potato pie, collard greens and the
parts of the hog like the feet and intestines that were
traditionally left to slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them set up cafes, which became pivotal gathering
places. Black celebrities and sports stars stopped in, and
politicians of all races knew the value of visiting prospective
voters there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost, in some way, as important as the church or the
barbershop or the beauty parlor,'' Plumpp said. ``It's a safe place
to meet and talk and discuss. At a time when the city was not as
open to African-Americans as it is now, it was a place to call
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Some soul food restaurants still serve that purpose, but others
are simply intended to be entertaining places to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul food has quote-unquote come out of the closet, and it's
no longer perceived as scraps,'' said Dolores Reynolds, the latest
owner of the 54-year-old Army &AMP; Lou's.
</P>
<P>
   But another kind of stratification is taking place, Plumpp and
others say. The blacks and whites who eat at the new soul food
restaurants like the Shark Bar, where pork chops sell for $14.95,
rarely make it to more traditional, less expensive places like
Nina's on the far West Side, where pork chops cost only $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the assimilation of soul food is traveling in both
directions, with some of the old-timers braiding in new ideas. At
Army &AMP; Lou's, Ms. Reynolds has tried to sprinkle in updated
approaches, using turkey instead of bacon to season collard greens
and replacing fatty pork neck bones with beef, without alienating
her regulars or disregarding the homespun tradition of soul food.
When she took over the restaurant seven years ago, the patrons were
about 80 percent old-timers, ``which really worried me,'' she said.
Now about half are new diners.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in homage to the ``Amistad'' movie and opera craze,
she whipped up a spicy black-eyed-pea soup with okra and tomatoes
and called it M'baazi. It's still on the menu, but to keep her
regulars comfortable, she deleted the African name and calls it
black-eyed-pea and okra soup.
</P>
<P>
   More seismic changes are noticeable at places like Soul Kitchen,
a colorful, eclectic restaurant in the Soho-esque Wicker Park
neighborhood. The menu is a melange of Cajun, Caribbean and even a
few Indian, Mediterranean and Mexican influences. Many dishes are
piled high in arty layers, like the fried green tomato special
stacked like a napoleon with smoked trout and horseradish sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few classic soul food dishes are served, and even those
take liberties. The catfish is gussied up, coated with pecans,
sauteed and flavored with Dijon mustard and lemon juice. Grits
arrive with Cajun shrimp, tasso, mushrooms, tarragon, scallions and
Herbsaint, an anise-flavored liqueur. Monique King, who until
recently was the chef, said she made the grits not with water or
even milk but with heavy cream, Parmesan and a little nutmeg,
``treating them a little more like polenta.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. King, who is of Puerto Rican descent, is well aware that the
``soul'' in Soul Kitchen is a metaphorical emotion rather than a
literal culinary tradition. She said she occasionally hears a ``How
dare you?'' from customers, ``mostly people of color.'' But she
said she sees her menu's mission as a melding of tastes from many
cultures. ``What makes us the same as any sort of soul food place
is the notion of making not the most fancy ingredients out there
taste good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Just west of the Loop at the Shark Bar _ part of the New York,
Los Angeles and Atlanta chain _ soul food sticks closer to
tradition but still hits the trends. The menu features pork chops
smothered in skillet gravy and honey-dipped fried chicken. But the
chef, Michael Marquez, also serves catfish with the usual side
dishes of black-eyed peas and collard greens stuffed inside, or
hickory-smoked barbecued salmon with sauteed spinach and
horseradish whipped potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't understand that soul food is a
feeling,'' said Marquez, who grew up in Bedford-Stuyvesant in
Brooklyn. ``It's a way of cooking, allowing flavors to come out
without sitting here measuring this and measuring that.'' He said
his mother, who was from the South, cooked a sweet potato pie so
good he is trying to persuade the management to do it her way,
roasting the potatoes rather than boiling them, because boiling
takes away some sweetness and color.
</P>
<P>
   With all the tweaking and teasing going on, there are still
plenty of places in Chicago where, quite consciously, nothing has
really changed.
</P>
<P>
   One classic is Nina's, a homey place with green and white
checked tablecloths and green vinyl booths. The Rev. Snirly
Simpson, 56, started it 15 years ago with his mother-in-law as cook
and his mother as baker. His mother-in-law moved back to
Mississippi and his mother died, but Nina's still attracts
regulars: city workers, school employees and tradespeople, mostly.
Simpson, who is the pastor of the Mound Ridge Baptist Church,
dishes out pastoral advice on occasion along with his Mississippi
sausage, country ham, salt pork, grits, ham hocks, candied yams and
peach cobbler.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said one hallmark of soul food has always been
affordability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to make sure if a person don't have but a dollar and
dime, he can still get something to tide him over for the day,'' he
said. ``Everybody doesn't want to spend what the price for pork
chops is, so they might be eating ham hocks _ ham hocks are less
expensive. We have a meal in a biscuit: a sausage patty, one egg in
a biscuit, for 99 cents.'' But even more important is making sure
his food remains a touchstone of tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us who have migrated from the South were accustomed to
their mother, their grandmother, who went into the kitchen and put
some things together,'' he said. ``When you get to changing with
the changing times, you lose some of that. You get away from Big
Mama's potatoes, you get away from chicken and dumplings.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   BREAD PUDDING WITH LEMON SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Army &AMP; Lou's
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the pudding:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Butter for baking dish
</P>
<P>
   5 cups French bread cubes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   { pound (2 sticks) butter, cut into pats For the sauce:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. To make the pudding, combine
eggs and sugar in a large mixing bowl. Mix well. Add condensed
milk, whole milk, vanilla, nutmeg and cinnamon. Stir to blend well.
</P>
<P>
   2. Butter a shallow 2-quart baking dish. Put bread cubes in the
dish, and sprinkle with raisins and butter pats. Pour in egg
mixture, making sure all bread cubes are covered. Cover the dish
with foil.
</P>
<P>
   3. Put baking dish on middle rack of oven, and place a pan of
water on the lower shelf directly beneath it. Bake until the
mixture is browned and set, 1 hour 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Meanwhile, to make the sauce, combine the sugar, cornstarch
and 1 cup of water in the top half of a double boiler. Place over
boiling water, and stir until thickened. Stir in lemon zest and
juice, and remove from heat. Drizzle over warm pudding, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 10 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED COLLARD GREENS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Soul Kitchen
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds collard greens, trimmed of tough stalks, cut into thin
strips and thoroughly washed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   { cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red pepper flakes.
</P>
<P>
   1. Put all ingredients in large stockpot with just enough water
to cover. Bring to a boil over high heat, and reduce heat to low.
</P>
<P>
   2. Simmer until greens are tender, about 1{ hours. Serve greens
with a slotted spoon, topping with a little of the pot liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
