<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA TIGHTENS GUN LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gov. Gray Davis declared California the state
with the nation's strongest gun laws after signing into law a bill
that will help restrict the manufacture and sale of assault
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the measure will only lead to confusion and
litigation when it takes effect Jan. 1, as gun makers, dealers and
buyers try to decode the new law.
</P>
<P>
   The new restrictions, which Davis signed into law on Monday,
will ban guns with some accessories typically found on assault
weapons. A second bill he signed limits the purchase of handguns to
no more than one per month per person.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deadly weapon of war is not going to destroy one more
future,'' Davis said, holding up a cut-in-half Chinese-made SK-47
with several features that will be illegal starting Jan. 1. ``This
bill is now law.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who owns guns defined by the law will have to register
them with the state attorney general by 2001. No one has to turn in
legally owned guns. Davis and other legislators said the new law,
which bans semiautomatic weapons with accessories such as pistol
grips and magazines that hold more than 10 rounds of ammunition,
will end the sale of copycat assault weapons that don't fall under
a 10-year-old law.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Hensley, the state liaison for the National Rifle
Association, said the new law will not stop the flow of weapons,
only force confused dealers to make small modifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come the first of the year, everyone will discover that this
is not a ban,'' Hensley said. ``We'll be in court because there are
all sorts of terms in the bill that are not defined.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hensley said he doesn't know what to make of the
ban on pistol grips that protrude ``conspicuously beneath the
action of the weapon'' on semiautomatic rifles.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the measure, sponsored by state Sen. Don Perata,
D-Alameda, said the law is clear and will stand any test in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten the best legal minds that we could to work on
this bill,'' Perata said. ``I'm as confident as any one person can
be that what can be done has been done in this law.''
</P>
<P>
   Perata said California now has the most widespread ban of
copycat weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Tolley, the Western director for the Handgun Control
advocacy group, said California's assault weapons laws are the
strongest in the country, particularly because of the provision
banning large magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no state that comes close,'' Tolley said.
</P>
<P>
   Tolley said only Maryland, Virginia and South Carolina have laws
that restrict handgun purchases to one per month.
</P>
<P>
   The bills were set up to remove loopholes in the 1989 California
assault weapon law, which outlawed specific gun models but was
easily thwarted by slightly modifying and renaming the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Popular guns like the Colt AR-15 and TEC-DC9 will be illegal to
possess, because of the size of their pistol grips, magazines or
other features, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the types of guns used in mass killings at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo., would be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   The law bans detachable magazine semiautomatic rifles with
thumbhole stocks, vertical or forward handgrips, folding or
telescopic stocks, grenade or flare launchers and flash
suppressors.
</P>
<P>
   It also bans detachable magazine pistols with threaded barrels,
a second vertical handgrip or a shroud that allows the gun owner to
fire without burning his or her hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
