<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-TOBACCO21-COX     07-20 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TOBACCO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIRING OF AIDE HIGHLIGHTS GORE'S TANGLED HISTORY ON TOBACCO
ISSUE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his first campaign for president, back in 1988,
Al Gore would occasionally cite his proposal to strengthen the
health warnings on cigarette packages as an example of his own
political courage.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Tennessee, a state with about 100,000 tobacco
farmers, ``it was not easy ... to lead the fight (in Congress) for
the toughest possible health warnings,'' the then-junior senator
from the Volunteer State would say.
</P>
<P>
   But critics charge that Gore's recent hiring of Carter Eskew, an
old friend and media adviser, to help him in his current
presidential campaign is hypocritical because Eskew helped kill
tobacco reforms backed by the Clinton administration last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore really believed his own speechifying about values,
he wouldn't hire a front man for the merchants of death, the
tobacco industry,'' said Gary Ruskin, director of the Congressional
Accountability Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It smacks of hypocrisy, because the vice president has taken
such a militant stance against tobacco over the past few years,''
said Darrell West, a political science professor at Brown
University. ``And that helps opponents who want to paint Gore as
just another Washington politician engaging in politics as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides say the hiring of Eskew, considered one of the most
skilled image-shapers in politics, has nothing to do with Gore's
policy on tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``has worked hard to keep tobacco out of the hands of
children and he will continue to do so,'' said Roger Salazar, a
presidential campaign spokesman. The addition of Eskew to the
campaign team ``doesn't change that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Even some people dismayed by Gore's hiring of Eskew do not
question the vice president's support for anti-smoking initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carter Eskew did a terrific job of harming the greatest piece
of legislation ever to come down the pike,'' said Bill Novelli,
president of the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids. ``I also believe
Vice President Gore's commitment to protecting kids from tobacco
was and is genuine. I find it all ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Eskew is just the latest twist in Gore's long and
conflicted relationship with tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who only months ago announced a $142 million
federal research effort to combat underage smoking, has supported
the federal government's tobacco allotment program virtually
throughout his 23-year career in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The program restricts the acreage on which tobacco can be grown.
The restrictions keep the price of tobacco high, making it a
lucrative cash crop for small farmers who either grow it themselves
or sell their allotments to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it's legal and is going to be grown and sold, ...
then of course we have the right to structure the marketplace and
say the money that is earned growing tobacco should go to the small
family farmers rather than to a few large companies,'' Gore said in
a presidential debate in Iowa in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In a subsequent campaign swing through North Carolina, Gore
tried to emphasize his own emotional ties to tobacco farming with
words the Republican National Committee gleefully faxed to
reporters following the hiring of Eskew:
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout most of my life, I raised tobacco. I want you to
know that with my own hands, all of my life, I've sprayed it, I've
chopped it, I've shredded it, spiked it, put it in the barn and
stripped it, and sold it. I know what what it's about, how
important that way of life is.''
</P>
<P>
   Those comments were intended, in part, to relieve tobacco
farmers's worries about Gore and the legislation he had introduced
five years earlier in the House to require cigarette makers to
place stronger health warnings on their product.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation grew out of the illness of Gore's sister,
Nancy, a smoker who only recently had been diagnosed with lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans did not know of his sister's death until Gore
spoke of her in an emotional speech at the 1996 Democratic National
Convention, concluding with a vow to protect children from the
dangers of smoking ``until I draw my last breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, however, Gore acknowledged that he continued to
receive annual checks from his family's tobacco farm for several
years after his sister's death.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the twists and turns in Gore's relationship with
tobacco, one of his biographers and harshest critics, former ABC
news correspondent Bob Zelnick, insists there has been ``no
substantial change'' in Gore's position: endorsing government
efforts to discourage young Americans from smoking while supporting
the system that guarantees good prices for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
