<HEADER>
A7275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-REAL-ESTATE-NYTR &LR;      07-20 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-REAL-ESTATE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE SITES OFFER VIRTUAL HOUSE HUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Material for an infobox is at the end of this report.) 
(lb) 
 By DWAYNE FATHERREE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet revolution is changing the way a lot of businesses
interact with potential clients, but nowhere as visibly as in the
real estate industry.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers used to be at the whim of local agents when searching for
a new home. Because not everyone has access to the listings that
agents use to market properties, the layman had to depend on
professional help to get a true picture of the home market.
</P>
<P>
   Now all prospective buyers need is a computer with an Internet
connection, and the whole world is at their feet. And at this
year's Real Estate Connect '99 conference in San Francisco, online
industry leaders were recognized for their achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate sites have moved beyond simple property listings and
pictures of homes for sale. Many now offer step-by-step guides for
getting the best deal possible on your home, from advice on
choosing agents or lenders to looking for potential trouble spots
in your new home.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you wanted to, you could find, finance and close on
a home without ever seeing it in person.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the preferred method, of course, but it shows how the
real estate industry has embraced the Web. For example, many
lenders work with online sites to accept applications now, turning
what used to be an interminable wait for approval into a 24- to
48-hour process.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the move to consolidate online listings (such as
on Microsoft's HomeAdvisor site) means shoppers can get a better
idea of home values in specific areas nationwide without a lot of
trouble. Just pick a ZIP code and you can see a fairly
comprehensive selection of available properties.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to find an agent to help you secure the property you
want, there is online help for that as well. HomeGain.com offers
agent listings and advice on selecting the right agent for your
needs. Additionally, the American Association of Realtors site
(www.realtor.com) will help the uninitiated find a local licensed
Realtor.
</P>
<P>
   Like most businesses, the real estate industry doesn't want to
replace its offices with online services. But re-engineering those
functions that can be moved to the Internet makes it easier for
incoming clients to be more aware of the process. That sort of
education makes the job of the agent much easier.
</P>
<P>
   It could also serve to remove some of the mystery from the loan
process, which is still listed as one of the most stressful life
events humans experience. Although making so much information
available to the public may make the agent a redundant fixture in
real estate trading, there is still no replacement for an
on-the-ground representative protecting your rights. And, if you
are better informed going into a purchase, the agent's handholding
will be that much less time consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of sites recognized at the Real Estate Connect
'99 conference
</P>
<P>
   _ www.eloan.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.inpho.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.liveassistance.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.realtor.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.homeadvisor.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.loopnet.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.comps.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.colliers.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.remmgroup.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.improvemet.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.springstreet.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.fsbomadison.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.homestore.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.homebid.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.rig.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.rentnet.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.pikenet.com
