<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of heavy showers and thunderstorms will erupt over the
southern Great Lakes on Wednesday morning as a stream of very humid
air flowing northward impinges upon a slow-moving warm front.
During the day, the showers and storms will move east and
southeast, reaching the upper Ohio Valley and western Pennsylvania
by evening. Local flooding is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of showers and thunderstorms will form over the
southern Middle Atlantic States near the eastern extension of the
front. Partial sunshine and very humid conditions will cover the
remainder of the Southeast with spotty, mainly afternoon
thundershowers occurring.
</P>
<P>
   Sinking currents of air associated with high pressure over New
England will promote ample sunshine and pleasantly warm conditions
over the Northeast on Wednesday. Humidity will stay low, though
breezes from the south will bring increasing humidity on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A weak disturbance near 20,000 feet will spiral slowly westward
into southern Texas, causing numerous showers and thunderstorms.
Showers will be most likely just inland from the coast where
developing sea breezes undercut and lift sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-altitude disturbance will cross the interior
Northwest, sparking spotty thundershowers east of the Cascades
while onshore breezes bring patchy clouds to coastal areas.
California will be mainly sunny, aside from a few morning clouds
near the coast. Elsewhere, residual moisture in the lowest few
thousand feet of the atmosphere will cause scattered thunderstorms
over the high ground of the southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Trading Places
</P>
<P>
   While Newark, N.J., set a record high of 100 degrees on Monday,
marking the fourth time this month of reaching the century mark,
Las Vegas notched its 12th consecutive day with readings below 100
degrees, setting a new record. So far in July, Las Vegas has had
100-degree temperatures on only seven days. The fewest number of
days of 100 degrees was 18, in 1984. Unless the mercury reaches 100
every day for the rest of the month, this record will also be
broken. Clouds and thunderstorms associated with an active monsoon
have kept the desert city unusually cool by summer standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
