<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7287 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARTER-CHANGES-TEX     07-20 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER-CHANGES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CARTER LEADS THE WAY TOWARD THE MUSEUM OF THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In less than two weeks, our sleepy, mild,
small-town summer is going to end. Forever.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. on Aug. 1, the Amon Carter Museum will close its doors
on the intimate art space it has been for nearly 40 years.
Demolition will commence within days and, with that, the Carter
will become Fort Worth's first museum building to begin catching up
with contemporary times.
</P>
<P>
   I won't pretend to miss the part of the Carter's structure
slated for removal _ the two awkward additions to the original
porticoed box, which opened in 1961 and will be the only piece of
the structure left standing, according to the plan. But I already
feel nostalgic about the quiet encounters with art that it has
stood for, for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Inaugurated as a memorial to a Fort Worth and West Texas legend,
the Carter quickly grew into a study center for American art.
Almost as quickly, it developed into an important gallery with an
exemplary and growing collection. Its following expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the Carter was caught in a loop that bedevils countless
other American museums. Its success _ and the success of American
art museums in general _ had rendered the Carter's old building
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   But with its new building, a workmanlike design from Philip
Johnson and his associates, the Carter will be a museum in the most
contemporary sense.
</P>
<P>
   When it reopens in two years, it will be a place where large
groups of people can view a considerable number of artworks. Where
they can socialize, shop, see and be seen.
</P>
<P>
   On an obviously more modest scale, it will be the sort of art
place that came into being with Cesar Pelli's addition/redesign of
New York's Museum of Modern Art and I.M. Pei's East Wing for the
National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C. It will reflect what a
number of museum construction projects from San Francisco to
Houston to New York (and another new building for MoMA) continue to
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   They all serve art. But, even more, they serve people.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton Kramer addressed this in his 1984 essay ``MOMA
Reopened.'' Art museums, he wrote, had acquired ``a new public
which, while lacking both the knowledge and the sensibility to be
found in the elite art public,'' possesses ``a keen appetite for
whatever modes of cultural experience are persuasively and
conspicuously commended to its attention.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``new'' public continues to exert enormous pressure on
museums.
</P>
<P>
   For this public _ and that means a lot of people reading this
column _ the museum experience includes a lovely and congenial
ambience, information supplied through a variety of media, food,
shopping, social interaction, live entertainment and, yes, art.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Carter's transformation gets under way, crews
working for the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth will begin site
preparation for its new building, designed by Tadao Ando.
</P>
<P>
   Its appearance alone _ to say nothing of the artworks its ample
galleries will be able to show _ will transform everyone's
perceptions of this museum. It will cease to be a regional art
center whose ambitions have fluctuated over the years: It will be a
site of national and international importance in the world of
modern and contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new Meadows Museum is being constructed in Dallas
for similar reasons. A mediocre, Georgian-styled structure, the
Meadows' future home withstands no comparison to those buildings
planned for Fort Worth, although its collection of Spanish art is
of superb quality.
</P>
<P>
   In notable contrast, the Dallas Museum of Art is pursuing a very
different goal. Unlike its sister institutions, the DMA has the
building required for today's and tomorrow's public. But DMA needs
to realize its reason for existing, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   With plenty of help, its new director, Jack Lane, is going to
get it there. And, when the DMA arrives, joined by the Nasher
Sculpture Garden planned for an adjacent lot, there'll be no more
jokes about people going to Dallas to shop and to Fort Worth for
museums.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kimbell, the arrival of new buffet furniture and the
possibility of temporary fabric panels for some of the walls are
about all that's likely to happen this fall. But don't be
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, at least five years from now, Kimbell officials likely
will seek an architect to design a building for the site they
purchased across the street. In the meantime, though, director
Timothy Potts and his curators are considering new shows and
acquisitions. They're planning a new handbook of the collection
and, in general, readying for the future.
</P>
<P>
   So, contemplate the forces that have worked on American museums
for the past two decades: They are now at work in North Texas, in a
dramatically compressed length of time.
</P>
<P>
   Look around at museums in North Texas _ and Texas overall _ and
you'll see history repeating itself. And being made.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
