<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HELICOPTER-ACCIDENTS-     07-20 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELICOPTER-ACCIDENTS-ART-1STLDWR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL HELICOPTER CRASHES INCREASING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Graphic available on NYT database) 
(Attn: Fla., Ill., Ky., Nev., Ohio and Texas) 
 
(Eds.: Sub to include Sarasota, Fla., Rockton, Ill., and Toldeo,
Ohio) 
 
By JANETTE RODRIGUES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A sudden upswing in the number of emergency medical
helicopter crashes has the specialized wing of the aviation
industry looking at re-evaluating its safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, seven air ambulances have
crashed, including one Saturday that killed a Life Flight crew of
three from Hermann Hospital in Houston. In February, a Hermann
Hospital Life Flight helicopter struck a high-tension wire as it
left an accident scene. Though damaged, it was able to land without
injuring any of the three crew members or two patients on board.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven such accidents occurred in all of 1998, according to
the Air &AMP; Surface Transport Nurses Association, which tracks them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of accidents are a little bit high for the industry
this year,'' said Dick Wright, director of safety and flight
operations for the Helicopter Association International, an
industry organization. ``It does have our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten helicopter crew members have died in the rash of crashes,
and three injured, caused by everything from adverse weather
conditions, poor visibility, mechanical breakdown and pilot error.
It is still unknown what caused the fatal crash Saturday in
neighboring Fort Bend County.
</P>
<P>
   In June, two University of Kentucky Hospital pilots, a nurse and
a paramedic returning to base at night in the fog were killed when
their aircraft ran into a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   In April, an emergency medical pilot and two nurses died when
their helicopter crashed on their return to Valley Hospital Medical
Center near Las Vegas in the snow. The other crashes this year
occurred in Sarasota, Fla., near Rockton, Ill., and in Toldeo,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Flanagan, Hermann's administrative director of emergency
services, including Life Flight, said the Houston hospital stands
by its program, which is one of the busiest in the nation. He said
that in 22 years it has had only four accidents, including the one
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers and air ambulance crews say they have been
unable to identify any trends in the accidents. In the 1980s, acute
and chronic pilot fatigue was implicated in 14 crashes in one year.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency medical helicopters, unlike commercial airplanes, are
not required to have flight data instruments that record the
movements of the aircraft and the actions taken by the pilot,
including part of cockpit conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk comes with this type of work,'' said Tom Reiser,
immediate past president of the air ambulance nurses association.
``You are called out at a moment's notice, in all kinds of
conditions and the pilot has to make a decision on whether to take
the mission based on the weather and the forecast predictions.
There are a lot of judgment calls they have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an industrywide practice not to tell a pilot the age,
condition or nature of the injuries of the patient being
transported. The officials' reasoning is they want the pilot's
decision to launch to be based only on safety matters, such as
weather, not an emotional sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Air Medical Services, another industry
organization, says that the emergency helicopters' unusual takeoff
or landing sites _ they often do not have access to helipads and
have to avoid power lines, tall buildings and other obstacles _
have not been a problem historically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the weather or pilot error,'' said Dawn Mancuso,
executive director of the Alexandria, Va.-based association.
``Safety is one of the topics that are always at the top of the
list in terms of our information programs. The policy of the
industry has always been safety has to come first even if that
means the patient doesn't get a helicopter.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry estimates put the number of air medical services
operations in the United States that use helicopters at 225.
Annually, they log about 200,000 hours in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Danko, an aviation lawyer and pilot whose firm specializes
in helicopter cases, says fatigue is a probable culprit in many
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been coming to light recently is the duty conditions
for the pilots,'' he said from California. ``They are very harsh,
and the big thing pilots seem to be complaining about is the lack
of sleep. It's one thing to be awakened in the middle of the night
to make a call, and another to have to fly the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue isn't a problem with Life Flight, hospital officials in
Houston say, pointing out that it has 12 pilots and, until
Saturday, three helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not anticipating that something is wrong,'' Flanagan
said. ``We are still very proud of our safety record and our
operations.``
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan, president of the state Association of Air Medical
Services, acknowledged that the group is aware of the 1999
nationwide accident rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at what is causing these accidents,'' Flanagan
said. ``Is it related? Is it pilot error? Is it mechanical
failure?''
</P>
<P>
   He said air ambulance programs employ the best pilots, provide
them the best equipment and follow all federal rules and
regulations, but accidents still happen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a Hermann Life Flight crew was injured in an accident
attributed to pilot error; there were no patients aboard. In 1995,
another helicopter had a failure in both engines and landed safely
at an area shopping mall, with no injuries to crew and or the
patients aboard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
