<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY LEGEND, MEMORIES RETAIN TIES WITH TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas tried for a quarter century to forget the Kennedy
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the city now helps the world remember.
</P>
<P>
   As mourners in Massachusetts and New York grieve the loss of
John Kennedy Jr., others gather at what might seem an unlikely
shrine: the Dallas corner where his father was fatally shot 36
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Until 10 years ago, no polite Dallas conversation ever included
certain names and words: ``Dealey Plaza. School Book Depository.
Triple underpass. Grassy knoll.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Dallas salutes the memory of President John F. Kennedy in a
Sixth Floor Museum, built inside the Elm Street textbook warehouse
where accused assassin Lee Harvey Oswald is said to have perched.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas will forever walk a tightrope. An entire planet expects
the city to remember and preserve the history of Kennedy's visit
Nov. 22, 1963 _ but never insult his family. The assassination site
has become the city's unofficial No. 1 tourist attraction, almost a
branch location for the seemingly perpetual cycle of Kennedy grief.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fort Worth wants onto the same tightrope. A proposed
memorial statue at the site of Kennedy's final speech, Eighth at
Main streets, is ``nearly ready to be announced,'' city tourism
executive Doug Harman said this week.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, tourism official Greg Elam drew a breath before
offering advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would only tell Fort Worth,'' he said, ``that whatever the
city chooses will create a great concern for sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more sensitivity over this than anyone else can
possibly comprehend.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy family members originally praised the Sixth Floor Museum
for its dignity and historical accuracy. But when the museum posted
a live ``Sixth Floor Webcam'' street view for World Wide Web
readers last month, a family spokeswoman called it ``insensitive''
and ``tasteless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think someone over there tried to do something special with
new technology,'' Elam said. ``It has been widely criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   The Webcam recreates what is believed to have been Oswald's view
of the oncoming presidential motorcade, but not the supposed path
of gunfire. All weekend, a lobby Webcam monitor was switched to
live television coverage of John Kennedy Jr.'s triple-fatality
plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   A steady line of mostly young adults filed into the museum
lobby. The younger Kennedy's generation _ the same generation that
often seems more obsessed with celebrity than with history _ now
dominates crowds at the Sixth Floor Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``People react one of two ways,'' Elam said. ``If they remember
the assassination, they become lost in their own thoughts. They
start remembering where they were that day, their mother, their
brothers, their childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is interesting is how so many visitors are younger. They
want to know what life was like then. They have an active interest
_ a curiosity _ in knowing the entire experience.''
</P>
<P>
   When three young adults fell suddenly into the sea, a new
generation inherited custody of the Kennedy family legend _ and the
lore of their recurring family tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, we can no longer try to forget the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   We must safeguard the memories.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
