<HEADER>
A7318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALIST-NYT     07-20 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT CONVICTS, THEN FREES, JOURNALIST WHO WARNED OF NUKE-WASTE
DUMPING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A crusading Russian journalist was freed from a
Vladivostok jail on Tuesday after a military court ruled that he
had misused his office but was entitled to amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia these days, government authorities virtually never
admit making a mistake. So the decision on Tuesday was probably the
best that Grigory Pasko, the 37-year-old military journalist, could
have expected from the three-man tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Captain Pasko, who spent 20 months in prison while his
case dragged on, said he would fight for a complete vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a slight feeling of euphoria,'' he said in a telephone
interview from Vladivostok, Russia's main Pacific port. ``But we
have not won in general. The verdict indicates that the wolves are
alive and the sheep are alive as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pasko, who was kept in solitary confinement, had been charged
with treason after documenting the Russian navy's practice of
dumping nuclear waste at sea. The military prosecutor had demanded
that he be stripped of his rank and sent to prison for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   But protests from international human rights groups had turned
the case into an embarrassment for the Kremlin. And on Tuesday, the
Vladivostok court appeared to seek a face-saving way out.
</P>
<P>
   Though the seven-month trial was conducted behind closed doors,
the court allowed the press in for Tuesday's dramatic verdict.
Pasko sat in a metal cage as a judge read out the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The charge of treason was dropped, and Pasko was convicted of
the lesser crime of overstepping his authority as a military
journalist. Then the military court sentenced the officer to three
years in prison but freed him immediately by granting him amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Galina Morozova, Pasko's wife, fainted as it became clear that
he would finally be released.
</P>
<P>
   Pasko said in an interview Tuesday night that he was determined
to appeal his conviction to the Supreme Court. But Anatoly Pyshkin,
his attorney, later suggested in an interview that his client might
be wise to quit while he was ahead because there was a risk the
court might order a new trial, renewing Captain Pasko's ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Under Russian law, the appeal would be considered by a special
Supreme Court panel made up of seven military officers. A final
decision on whether to appeal will be made next week, Pyshkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety over an appeal is not the only indication of the
fear security authorities have instilled in Russia's environmental
movement.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Federal Security Service raided the
Vladivostok laboratory and home of Vladimir Soifer, looking for
classified information. Soifer, an internationally known scientist
and confirmed Communist, has investigated the problem of nuclear
waste and storage in Russia's Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Nikitin, a retired navy captain, has also been accused
of espionage for helping the Norwegian environmental organization
Bellona document nuclear pollution by Russia's Northern Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin is no longer in prison. But after Russia's Supreme Court
refused to drop treason charges in February, the Federal Security
Service in St. Petersburg has moved to renew the case.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Putin, the director of the Federal Security Service,
recently defended his agency's vigilant stance against
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, foreign secret service use not only diplomatic cover,
but also all sorts of ecological organizations,'' he told the
newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists say the security service is simply trying
to help the military cover up an embarrassing legacy of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   The saga of Pasko, a career naval officer, began two years ago,
as he chronicled the Russian navy's environmental abuses.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a reporter for Boyevaya Vakhta (Battle Watch), the
newspaper of the Russian Pacific Fleet. But he also did freelance
work for NHK, Japan's largest television network.
</P>
<P>
   After he provided NHK with a videotape about the ocean dumping
of nuclear waste, Pasko was arrested in November 1997, and charged
with treason for selling secret information.
</P>
<P>
   Denied bail, Pasko kept up the fight from behind bars,
documenting his life in a Soviet jail on the Internet. Throughout
the ordeal, he has insisted he was innocent. And on Tuesday the
court acknowledged that some of the evidence amassed against him
had been collected illegally and, in some cases, was even
fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   While Pasko said he would ask to be reinstated at his military
newspaper, he said his main ambition now is to publish a book on
his experience n solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal has left him with a dim view of the human rights
situation in Russia. And for all the grit he has displayed, he
seemed stunned that he had been allowed to resume his once familiar
life once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like Neil Armstrong on the moon,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
