<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES-SCAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT FOR SWEEPSTAKES LEGISLATION GROWS IN SENATE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Support for legislation that would crack down on
sweepstakes companies is growing in the Senate as more evidence of
deceptive practices by small firms was uncovered Tuesday by a
Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered a pattern of highly deceptive solicitations by
dozens of smaller companies,'' said Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine,
chairman of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations,
which has been probing the marketing practices of sweepstakes
operators. Collins held a hearing Tuesday to discuss the deceptive
practices used by some small sweepstakes firms.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said 33 lawmakers have now signed on to legislation that
she and Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., introduced earlier this year,
that would impose new rules on sweepstakes operators.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would regulate those sweepstakes companies that use
deceptive practices to entice people to buy products such as
magazines and compact discs by offering contests that give people
the chance to win prizes like cars, stereos and thousands or even
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   After the Senate panel held hearings earlier this year focusing
on larger sweepstakes firms like Reader's Digest Association, Inc.
and Publishers Clearing House, Collins said she received more than
1,000 letters from people who had received sweepstakes letters from
lesser known companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these smaller companies tend to be fly-by-night
operations that use multiple trade names to hide their identities
and to confuse consumers,'' Collins said. ``Often their mailings
are designed to deceive even the most cautious consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   One such company, operated by Anthony Kasday of Las Vegas, Nev.,
uses a letter that appears to be from a Lake Forest, Ill., law
office.
</P>
<P>
   The letter says an anonymous client has requested that the
recipient of the letter be located to receive ``your portion of the
disbursement fund.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter goes on to say the client has ``authorized Mellon,
Astor and Fairweather to disburse your portion of the client
fund.'' It then says a $10 fee is required to obtain a $3,000 cash
savings voucher folio.
</P>
<P>
   The voucher turns out to be coupons from national hotel chains,
rental car companies, car service firms like Jiffy Lube and food
chains like Dunkin Donuts, but that is not clearly explained in the
fine print. In most cases a person would have to spend thousands of
dollars to fully use the $3,000 worth of discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Another promotion offered by Kasday tells people they are a
``guaranteed winner'' of $10,000 cash or a 1999 Ford Escort.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Collins, Kasday admitted that Mellon, Astor
and Fairweather is a fictitious name and that the office address is
really a Mail Boxes Etc., a company that rents mailboxes. In many
cases Kasday asserted his Fifth Amendment right to remain silent
when asked whether his promotions were misleading.
</P>
<P>
   The practices used by Kasday and other sweepstakes firms would
become illegal under the bill sponsored by Collins and Levin.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would:
</P>
<P>
   _ ban companies from telling people they are winners when they
haven't actually won anything;
</P>
<P>
   _ require promoters to use much larger print in describing such
details as the long-shot odds of winning a contest and in telling
people no purchase is necessary to win.
</P>
<P>
   _ allow U.S. district courts to impose nationwide restraining
orders to stop delivery of mail in cases where the U.S. Postal
Inspection Service has determined a sweepstakes company is engaging
in a deceptive marketing scheme. Under current law the government
must file for restraining orders in each of the districts in which
consumer response mail is received.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Previous Senate hearings have focused on how elderly people are
particularly vulnerable to sweepstakes contests and showed that
many spent thousands of dollars purchasing magazines and other
items to enter contests.
</P>
<P>
   David Dobin, who runs a firm called Lone Star Promotions based
in Merrick, N.Y., said he uses up to 40 different company names to
promote the same $10,000 contest. He also offers a $3,000 coupon
booklet that can be purchased for $10.
</P>
<P>
   He also said people who purchase a coupon book could be sent as
many as 25 to 30 additional mailings from his various companies
enticing them to enter the same $10,000 contest offered by Lone
Star.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers blasted that practice and said it should be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they are entering different contests,'' Levin
said. ``It is so fundamentally deceptive what you are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Dobin pointed out that the more often a contestant
enters the sweepstakes, the greater his or her chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
