<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARABIA-THEATER-REVIEW     07-20 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARABIA-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IN ARABIA, WE'D ALL BE KINGS': A LOT OF DEGRADATION, A LITTLE
HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The desperation is anything but quiet in ``In Arabia,
We'd All Be Kings,'' a harrowing new play by Stephen Adly Guirgis
that is being given a menacing staging under Philip Seymour
Hoffman's direction by the Labyrinth Theater Company.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the lights come up on the seedy bar that Adly
Guirgis' misfits call home, Lenny, a week out of prison and very
angry about life in general, snarls at anyone who crosses his line
of vision, and pulls a knife on a sniveling addict he calls Skank,
just for reaching for a bowl of peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   The decibel level keeps rising as the emotional stakes get
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Arabia'' is an old-fashioned slice-of-life play that takes
place around Times Square before Walt Disney replaced Damon Runyon
as resident folklorist, and it involves a collection of modern-day
losers that even Runyon might find hard to stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Zoot-suited craps players have been replaced by junkies in dirty
T-shirts who will do anything for drug money, and the Salvation
Army evangelists are now religious nuts who carve up the
prostitutes rather than preach to them.
</P>
<P>
   There is no romance in this Times Square. The happiest ever
after one teen-age girl can imagine is for her, her friend and her
boyfriend to end up together in the Betty Ford clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Adly Guirgis spends the first half-hour introducing a lineup of
characters one would be loath to meet offstage. But just when it
seems the play will settle for the shock value of its raw and
violent language and imagery _ with some comic relief thrown in at
the expense of the wasted lives it portrays _ Adly Guirgis begins
to tie all his loose ends together in a grim and sad portrait of
life on the streets, almost an updated ``Balm in Gilead'' for the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lenny (David Zayas) and Skank (Trevor Long),
there are Demaris (Ana Ortiz), a teen-ager who pulls a gun on her
mother (Begonya Plaza); Chicky (Tiprin Mandalay), Skank's devoted
girlfriend except when she needs crack money; Charlie (Sal
Inzerillo), a kindhearted bartender, and Jake (Richard Petrocelli),
the bar's owner.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a gem of a performance by Mark Hammer, there is Sammy,
an elderly alcoholic who can't hold a thought for more than 30
seconds and who provides cryptic commentary on life from a corner
table.
</P>
<P>
   Adly Guirgis pulls no punches and offers no sociological lessons
about the failures of society. The degradation these characters
endure to feed their habit _ in one brutal scene Skank is
humiliated by Greer (Russell G. Jones), a gay man slumming, as he
negotiates sex for $20 _ is only occasionally broken by humor.
</P>
<P>
   One funny scene finds Demaris and Chicky trying unsuccessfully
to hustle tricks on the street. ``You've got to smile,'' Chicky
advises Demaris, who keeps scaring off prospective customers.
``You've got to be like a party waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When Demaris immediately frightens off another prospect, Chicky
suggests, ``You could do something else to get money, like rob.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, an actor making his directorial debut, has mounted a
crisp and taut production and has molded his good cast into a
strong ensemble that never seems to pause to catch its breath. Ms.
Ortiz and Long are especially effective.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for the characters in ``In Arabia'' is bleak. In a
scene in which Lenny applies for a job handing out fliers, the
interviewer asks him, ``Where do you see yourself in five years?''
The line gets a laugh in performance. But as one leaves the
theater, the question returns to haunt. If any of these characters
is alive in five years, it will be a small miracle.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IN ARABIA, WE'D ALL BE KINGS'
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Adly Guirgis; directed by Philip Seymour Hoffman;
produced by Eric and Jill DeArmon and David Deblinger. Lighting by
Sarah Sidman; costumes by Mimi O'Donnell; sound by DeArmon;
composer, Daniel Harnett; sets by Max DeArmon; assistant director,
Adly Guirgis. Presented by Labyrinth and Center Stage, N.Y. At 48
West 21st St., fourth floor, New York.
</P>
<P>
   With: Russell G. Jones (Greer), Trevor Long (Skank), David Zayas
(Lenny), Ana Ortiz (Demaris), Tiprin Mandalay (Chicky), Sal
Inzerillo (Charlie), Richard Petrocelli (Jake), Mark Hammer
(Sammy), and Begonya Plaza (Mrs. Reyes).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
