<HEADER>
A7369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-REMBRANDT-NYT     07-20 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-REMBRANDT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERIES IN THE MIRROR OF A DUTCH MASTER'S SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For more than 40 years, Rembrandt made a point of
looking into the mirror and recording what he saw. As a result,
more than for any other major artist, self-portraits came to
represent an important part of his life's work. They show his
development and virtuosity as a painter. They also chronicle his
aging until shortly before his death at 63 in 1669. But why did he
paint himself so often?
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery's striking new exhibition, ``Rembrandt by
Himself,'' which presents all but a handful of this 17th-century
Dutch Master's 75 or so surviving self-portraits, raises this
question and more. Why did he dress up in exotic costumes? Was he
showing off his talent to potential buyers? Was he testing new
techniques on a model who charged nothing and always showed up?
Were the self-portraits true likenesses? Was he peering into his
soul?
</P>
<P>
   These questions have of course long surrounded Rembrandt van
Rijn and, since there are no sure answers, the organizers of this
show have wisely invited visitors to make up their own minds.
``Rembrandt by Himself,'' which includes 60 of his paintings and
etchings as well as works by seven of his pupils, is at the
National Gallery in London through Sept. 5 and will then be seen at
the Mauritshuis in The Hague from Sept. 25 to Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint foreword to the exhibition catalog, National Gallery
director Neil MacGregor and Mauritshuis director Frederick Duparc
say their aim is to cast new light on Rembrandt's ``meaning and
purpose'' in his self-portraits, but they are also realistic.
``What that significance was _ and it was probably not the same
throughout Rembrandt's life _ remains one of the puzzles of the
history of art,'' they note.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is compounded by some unresolved questions of
attribution (such was Rembrandt's prestige that even his
self-portraits were copied by his pupils and admirers) as well as
conflicting definitions of self-portrait, a concept that did not
exist until the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The most romantic interpretation, one that has gained sway in
post-Freudian times, has Rembrandt writing his ``autobiography in
paint,'' engaging in a personal dialogue and steadily acquiring
self-knowledge. But available evidence suggests a more mundane
explanation: that, until the death of his wife, Saskia, in 1642,
when he was only 36, he used himself as a convenient model for
studying light and facial expressions and for portraying archetypal
figures in a popular genre known as ``tronies.''
</P>
<P>
   Saskia's death may explain a subsequent pause in self-portraits.
Yet after he resumed them in 1652 and in the years that followed,
his face gradually wrinkling and sagging into old age, the sheer
force of his presence overwhelmed any suggestion of
experimentation. Now an acclaimed painter at the height of his
powers, he no longer enhanced his image with finery, instead
wearing dark working clothes that insure that his face was the
center of attention. And more than ever he seemed to be
contemplating his mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that is what some viewers see today.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst van de Wetering of the Rembrandt Research Project in
Amsterdam begs to differ. ``It is extremely unlikely that Rembrandt
made his self-portraits as a personal form of self-analysis,'' he
writes in a catalog essay in which he argues that emotional
self-awareness was a product of the later Romantic Age. In his view
Rembrandt belonged to a different age in which an artist might use
a self-portrait to test his techniques and increase his fame.
Rembrandt's self-portraits, he notes, were appreciated in his day
because they were ``typical'' Rembrandts that ``had an added
attraction in that they also showed the face of the creator.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet this does not answer why alone among his contemporaries,
who at one point included Rubens and van Dyck, Rembrandt was
continually drawn to self-portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1606, he began painting himself in his late teens in his
home town, Leiden, although his first appearance in oil was not in
a self-portrait but rather as a wide-eyed and tousled-headed
bystander in two large works, ``The Stoning of St. Stephen'' and
``History Piece'' (cameo roles he later repeated). By his early
20s, though, he has painted his first self-portraits, remarkable
studies of light as it caught his chubby cheek, his eyes shrouded
his darkness.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in physiognomy and expression is apparent in a
series of minuscule etchings, in which he portrayed himself
variously wide-eyed, with angry expression, smiling, open-mouthed,
as a beggar, with fur hat, in a cloak and with loose hair. Yet,
perhaps strangely, with only a couple of exceptions, his painted
self-portraits always show his face at rest, with little hint of
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Still in Leiden, Rembrandt began using himself as a model for
``tronies,'' a 17th-century Dutch word for head or face that came
to describe portraits of character types in which the identity of
the sitter was less important than the image of, say, a soldier or
an Oriental lord. (One 17th-century inventory referred to ``a trony
by Rembrandt, being his own likeness.'') Rembrandt apparently
enjoyed dressing up in rich costumes and plumed hats, often giving
his self-portraits a historical air by wearing 15th- and
16th-century styles.
</P>
<P>
   When he moved to Amsterdam in 1631, while he painted one
self-portrait dressed as a worthy burgher of his day, he soon
reverted to using his face in tronies, often dressed in fur-lined
gowns with gold necklaces around his neck. These paintings were in
turn powerful examples of his portraiture, and he was soon much in
demand.
</P>
<P>
   As important, in the view of some experts, this work showed off
his special talent for rendering fabrics and the human skin. It was
also in these years that thick paint (impasto) began to distinguish
his work from his contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the final gallery of this show, however, where a dozen of his
late self-portraits are displayed, it becomes difficult to avoid
seeing Rembrandt more as the man than as the commercial painter.
These works also include two, ``Self-Portrait as the Apostle Paul''
(1661) and ``Self-Portrait as Zeuxis'' (1662), in which he seems to
be performing before the camera: as St. Paul he looks inquiring,
and as the Greek painter Zeuxis he is cackling mischievously.
</P>
<P>
   In the last self-portraits of his life, though, he looks at
peace with himself. In ``Self-Portrait With Two Circles,'' wearing
a white cap and a freely painted dark gown, he is holding his paint
brushes and a palette. In ``Self-Portrait at the Age of 63,''
painted the year of his death, he looks piercingly from the canvas,
perhaps a slight smile playing on his lips. Having tracked his life
through 60 different images, the visitor can be forgiven for
wondering what he is thinking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
