<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIEST-GAYS-HNS &LR;      07-20 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCIPLINED PRIEST CALLS VATICAN REBUKE ON GAYS `A SETBACK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Robert Nugent, who has specialized in
ministering to gays and lesbians around the nation for the past 25
years, said Tuesday that his rebuke by the Vatican was ``a setback
and a disappointment'' for Catholic homosexuals seeking acceptance
in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a very negative message,'' said Nugent, 61, in an
interview. ``A lot of people are saying, `If they silence us ...
what hope is there?'''
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican disciplinary panel _ the Congregation for the Doctrine
of the Faith _ ruled last week that Nugent and Sister Jeannine
Gramick were barred for life from ministering to groups of
homosexuals. In addition, the two must submit for approval any
future theological writings and are barred from holding any office
in their respective religious orders.
</P>
<P>
   The punishment, known as a formal ``notification,'' was issued
by Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, had of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised at the severity of the judgment,'' said
Nugent, adding that he expected the punishment to be a forced
year-long sabbatical, which the Vatican has dispensed in the past
to what it views as errant theologians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several other disciplinary options they had. Short
of excommunication, this was the most severe,'' said Nugent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the penalty, which was approved by Pope John Paul II,
acceptance of Catholic gay and lesbian people in individual
parishes is growing, Nugent said, adding: ``It's a movement that
can't be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramick is a School Sister of Notre Dame and Nugent is a
Salvatorian priest.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent, who said he will comply with Rome's cease-and-desist
order, and Gramick, who has indicated that she will decide by the
end of July whether to comply, co-founded the New Ways Ministry in
Mount Rainier, Md., in suburban Washington, D.C., where they have
conducted seminars and retreats for gay and lesbian Catholics since
the early 1970s. They have been under investigation by church
officials for several years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to conducting seminars and speaking around the
country, Nugent and Gramick wrote ``Building Bridges: Gay and
Lesbian Reality and the Catholic Church'' in 1992 and edited
``Voices of Hope: A Collection of Positive Catholic Writings on Gay
and Lesbian Issues'' in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the punishment, a Vatican statement said that
Gramick and Nugent in their writings and seminars have contradicted
church teaching by failing to stress the Catholic doctrine that
homosexual orientation is a ``disorder'' and that homosexual acts
are ``intrinsically evil'' because they don't lead to procreation.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican said the pair ``have caused confusion among the
Roman Catholic people and have harmed the community of the
church.'' It called their teachings ``erroneous and dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Vatican asked Nugent and Gramick to submit
written statements showing their compliance with official doctrine
on homosexuality. But they refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could sign a statement about homosexual acts and
orientation, but I couldn't use the language of `evil and
disorder.' They will settle for nothing less,'' Nugent said.
</P>
<P>
   In their ministry, Nugent said he and Gramick discuss the
church's view on homosexual orientation and sexual behavior but
steer clear of condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am trying to win gay and lesbian people back to the
church, I certainly don't want to use language that's going to
cause them alienation and pain,'' he explained. ``If we are working
with divorced people, we wouldn't constantly harp about the evil of
divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Robert Friday, a theology professor at the Catholic
University of America in Washington said Nugent and Gramick have
been careful not to trod too heavily on church teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have emphasized the dignity of the individual person and
have tried to stay away from taking a stance apart from church
teachings,'' said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Gerald Coleman, president of St. Patrick's Seminary in
Menlo Park, Calif., said the Vatican action has sent a strong
signal to Catholic clergy: ``It is important not to dilute or to
falsify or misrepresent church teaching,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
