</P>
<P>
   BEYOND-BARS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As the last paper plate and
Styrofoam cup are tossed in the big trash bin, a guard does an
early-evening head count. Then, troop activities begin. This night
mothers and daughters learn dance moves and sing Girl Scout songs,
such as ``Alice the Camel.'' But this isn't a typical Girl Scout
meeting because mothers are prison inmates. Nationally, an
estimated 1.5 million children have a jailed parent, and more than
200,000 children have imprisoned mothers, according to the Child
Welfare League of America. Nearly 11,000 women were incarcerated in
Texas prisons in April. Criminal justice experts say parent-child
contact is essential to preserving emotional bonds while a parent
is serving time. The relationship will, hopefully, help the
imprisoned parent to change and the child to cope. But maintaining
the relationship often requires structured programs, such as Beyond
Bars, which gets the mothers and daughters out of the crowded,
assigned-seat environment of routine weekend jail visits. (Martin,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
