<SLUG> BC-KULA-SHAKER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KULA SHAKER TAPS MILLENNIUM VIBE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Eds: Fact box at bottom 
By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's fitting that Kula Shaker was the first rock
act to sign up for the Lizard _ a five-day celebration, taking
place in Britain's seaside Cornwall, of the total eclipse of the
sun next month.
</P>
<P>
   Kula Shaker's retro psychedelic vibe and blend of Indian
rhythms, mantras and catchy pop melodies could be the perfect
soundtrack for the Aug. 11 eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nature's celebration of the millennium,'' says Kula
Shaker's Crispian Mills. ``The timing of the eclipse and the year
2000 are going to make this the most happening event of the year.
New Year's Eve may be a bit of a disappointment, actually. But when
the sky goes black for two minutes, it's a good opportunity to
think about change and how nature reflects change.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true child of a '60s star _ which Mills is. He's
the 26-year-old son of Hayley Mills, the former teen ingenue who
starred in such '60s films as ``The Parent Trap,'' ``Pollyanna''
and ``Whistle Down the Wind.'' Mills' grandfather is John Mills,
well-known in Britain for starring in many World War II films.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is I've been culturally privileged,'' Mills says
of his lineage. ``I haven't led a sheltered life. Performing comes
naturally to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills has embraced such concepts as numerology, astrology and
the power of certain letters of the alphabet, including ``K,'' the
title of Kula Shaker's acclaimed 1996 debut.
</P>
<P>
   Just out is the quartet's latest effort, ``Peasants, Pigs &AMP;
Astronauts'' (Columbia), produced by Bob Ezrin (Pink Floyd) with
Mills. Kula Shaker appears Wednesday at the Mayan downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the millennium is simply about inspiration,'' Mills
said. ``We're all looking for things to inspire us to move forward,
give us hope and a sense of excitement about the possibilities of
the future.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Who: Kula Shaker. &QL; 
Where: Mayan, 1038 S. Hill St., Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Wednesday. &QL; 
Tickets: $15. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
