<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COCKTAILS-ART-3TAKES-     07-20 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCKTAILS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COCKTAIL MAKES A SPLASHY RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also COCKTAIL-SHAKE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's 6:30 in the evening, and the crowd is sipping
mint-garlanded mojitos, sparkling flutes of Champagne-and-vodka
mambo kings and lovely, apricot-toned Floridians with squiggles of
orange peel angling from the rims of the glasses. The scene is not
South Beach or the Bahamas, but Madison Avenue, on the four-sided
balcony bar at Asia de Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Sober bottled water and iced tea may wash down lunch, but by
evening, New York has become a cocktail party of sexy, colorful
fruit-filled drinks. Vacation-style drinks. And not just because
it's summer.
</P>
<P>
   Cocktails rule in suave lounges, venerable hotel bars, Upper
West Side sidewalk cafes, funky downtown spots, hot new restaurants
for the latest in fusion food and even in chic temples of haute
cuisine like Daniel, Le Cirque 2000 and Jean Georges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cocktail is back in a big way,'' said Dale DeGroff, the
``drink chef'' at Blackbird in midtown, where drinks are designed
to be sipped with dinner, not just before or instead of. ``Food led
the way, making palates more adventuresome,'' he added. ``Now the
interest in Latin and Asian cuisines has people drinking cocktails
inspired by those regions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Asian and Latin-fusion trends that prepared taste buds for
the pungent, sweet-and-sour flavors of Southeast Asia and South
America have given rise to a new breed of drinks. Martinis, which
steered a generation back to the cocktail shaker, are now made with
sake or fresh ginger or, at Lot 61 in Chelsea, shiso leaf. Other
new cocktails have the alluring tartness of mango and passion
fruit. Rum and tequila drinks are more in demand than ever. But
increasingly, drinks are getting their kick from once unfamiliar
spirits like pisco, a potent Peruvian brandy; cachaca, the
Brazilian sugar-cane juice distillate, and aguardiente, a similar
Latin American spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of experimentation now, a lot of interest in
new alcohols,'' said Fernando Saralegui, the owner of L-Ray in
Greenwich Village, which specializes in drinks made famous in Cuba
and New Orleans, like mojitos and hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Today's cocktails have an upbeat exuberance, a technicolor
dazzle that sets them apart from the suave, black-and-white-movie
glamour of the previous cocktail era, the 1930s and 40s, when gin
reigned and the cigarette holder, not the cell phone, was in the
hand not grasping the martini glass. Once vodka came onto the scene
in the late '50s, the classic cocktail succumbed to an assault from
tall, vodka-based drinks or flavorless, colorless vodkas on the
rocks. Vodka is still big, but now, with a host of flavorings, it
inspires ever more new drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, cocktails are mixed to the rhythmic slosh of the
ice-filled metal shaker, not the deafening whir of the blender.
Bartenders are also learning to muddle, using a stick with a
rounded end called a muddler to crush herbs, fruits and peels in
the glass or shaker to release the aromatic essences.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants as diverse as Marion's Continental on the Bowery and
Eleven Madison Park have added cocktail menus to the reading
material that customers must consult before ordering. They list
prices averaging $8, sometimes as much as $12. The mint julep at
Daniel, in its silver tumbler, will set a patron back $10.
</P>
<P>
   While not as lucrative as a cup of tea, many of the drinks are
moneymakers. At Ruby Foo's on the Upper West Side, one-third of all
beverage sales are specialty cocktails, like the Blue Buddha and
the ginger martini.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid-'80s you had mostly big frozen drinks or liquor on
the rocks, but for about the past three years, all our restaurants
have had drink menus with special cocktails,'' said Steve Hanson,
whose company, B.R. Guest, owns seven restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson and other restaurateurs said that the cosmopolitan, made
with vodka, sugar syrup, lime and cranberry juice, paved the way
for today's diversity of drinks. Now the martini's stiffest
competition, the cosmopolitan is on the list of 61 martinis at Lot
61, and it is the No. 1 cocktail at downtown spots like Moomba as
well as at the high-end Jean Georges.
</P>
<P>
   And the cosmopolitan is evolving. At Ruby Foo's, where it's
known as the Ruby Foo, it's made with sake, vodka and cranberry and
pineapple juices, and it outsells the traditional cosmopolitan 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Drinks like this are created in most restaurants by managers and
bartenders, often by trial and error. For example, Le Colonial's
managers wanted a ginger drink and finally came up with a ginger
martini made with ginger liqueur and candied ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Many new drinks are being made with cachaca (pronounced
cah-CHAH-sa), which may be the vodka of the next millennium. It is
also clear but a little rougher tasting than vodka, yet it provides
a clean slate for the concoction of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Cachaca is essential in the caipirinha, a Brazilian drink made
with sugar syrup and lime, which has taken New York by storm and is
served not just in churrascerias or pan-Latin places like Calle
Ocho and Bolivar, but even in bastions of tradition like the ``21''
Club.
</P>
<P>
   At Blackbird, the caipirinha is open to interpretation. DeGroff
muddles fresh sour cherries, now in season, with lime for a cherry
caipirinha. At Viva Brasil on the Upper West Side, the drink is
interpreted with the fruit of the day, like mango or peach.
</P>
<P>
   But such drinks are not syrupy cousins to the old pina colada
and strawberry margarita. And in their own sly way, they also taste
more sophisticated than the cloying drinks that characterized
places like Trader Vic's, extravaganzas sprouting paper parasols,
skewers of fruit and sometimes flames.
</P>
<P>
   At Ruby Foo's, the Emerald Dragon, made of Midori, orange vodka,
blue Curacao and pineapple juice, looks garish and carnival green
but tastes tangy and delicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinks are becoming less sweet,'' said Clark Wolf, a
restaurant consultant. ``There is a lot of fruit and rum, but the
drinks are drier, balanced with a sour note. The 20- and
30-year-olds are really into these cocktails, and the 40-to-'60s
crowd are rediscovering them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Klein, the director of Authentic Bartending School in New
York, said that for the last two years, the program, which includes
a 48-hour training course and job placement, has been busier.
``More places are opening,'' he said. ``And the drinks are becoming
more complicated. We update our course every year with trendier
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the going-out-and-drinking trend, especially among
people in their mid-to-late '20s, the Zagat Survey is publishing a
New York night life guide. Due out in the fall, it will list about
1,000 places.
</P>
<P>
   But the taste for cocktails is not limited to bars and
restaurants. Tiffany &AMP; Co.'s bridal registry has more couples than
ever listing bar paraphernalia, especially martini glasses and
cocktail shakers, but also ice buckets, tongs and swizzlers.
Elisabeth Ames, the vice president for retail sales, says Tiffany's
has reintroduced a 1930s silver cocktail shaker set with
moonstones.
</P>
<P>
   ``As never before, what the drink is in is as important as
what's in it,'' Wolf said. For instance, silver julep cups, which
hold flowers on the table in some restaurants, are used at Daniel
for classic mint juleps. But who orders mint juleps at Daniel when
the menu offers Champagne with crushed strawberries? ``People see
it on the list and they're intrigued,'' said Michael Lawrence, the
assistant manager.
</P>
<P>
   While new drinks are making inroads everywhere, nostalgia is
also coming on strong in this cocktail revival. At Marion's
Continental, a restauant and bar on the Bowery, the next four weeks
will be devoted to crazy Polynesian-style concoctions served in
coconut shells and oversize glasses as the restaurant becomes a
palm and bamboo fantasy Kahiki Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are drinkers like Adam Rodriguez, 37, an
insurance executive, who was ignoring the Floridians, mojitos and
mambo kings around him at Asia de Cuba the other night. He ordered
classic Manhattans for his friends from Arizona. And for himself,
his favorite: rye and ginger ale.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to cocktails and drinks, anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some cocktail recipes call for ingredients that home bartenders
may not have on hand, or may be reluctant to use. Here are some
basic ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Sugar syrup: Simmer 1 cup sugar in 1 cup water for 2 to 3
minutes, until sugar dissolves. Cool and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Sour mix: A commercial product. For a substitute, mix four parts
lemon juice to one part confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Egg whites: Powdered egg whites, dissolved in water according to
package directions, can replace raw egg whites in drinks like pisco
sours.
</P>
<P>
   VONG ROYALE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Vong
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 ounce Poire William
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 ounces white Lillet
</P>
<P>
   2 Pear Chips (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   1. In a metal cocktail shaker half filled with ice, combine the
Poire William and Lillet.
</P>
<P>
   2. Shake well to mix, and strain into two martini glasses.
Garnish each glass with a pear chip.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 drinks.
</P>
<P>
   PEAR CHIPS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Vong
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 2 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 Bartlett pear
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Using a mandoline, slice pear (with skin) along its length
into thinnest possible slices.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 225 degrees. On a nonstick baking sheet, or
baking sheet lined with parchment paper, arrange slices close to
one another without overlapping. Sprinkle lightly with
confectioner's sugar.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bake pear slices until they are dried and somewhat brittle
when cool, 2 to 3 hours. To test for doneness, remove a chip after
two hours of baking. Allow to cool. If chip is brittle enough for
edges to crack when chip is bent, remove and cool remaining chips.
Store chips in an airtight container; humidity will cause chips to
soften.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 30 chips.
</P>
<P>
   WATERMELON MARTINI
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Cub Room
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound (about 3 1/2 cups) watermelon cubes, seeded
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces lemon vodka.
</P>
<P>
   1. Using a blender, puree watermelon until smooth. Place a fine
strainer over a bowl and strain watermelon puree; reserve juice and
discard any remaining pulp.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a metal cocktail shaker half filled with ice, combine
vodka and 1 cup watermelon juice. Shake well, and strain into two 7
1/4 ounce chilled martini glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 drinks.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDIAN
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Asia de Cuba
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 2/3 ounces orange vodka
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Cointreau or Triple Sec
</P>
<P>
   4 splashes sour mix
</P>
<P>
   2 splashes cranberry juice
</P>
<P>
   2 twists of orange peel.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a metal cocktail shaker half filled with ice, combine
vodka, Cointreau, sour mix and cranberry juice.
</P>
<P>
   2. Shake well, and strain into two martini glasses. Garnish each
drink with a twist of orange peel.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKBERRY JULEP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Blackbird
</P>
<P>
   Time: For marinated berries, 5 minutes, plus 2 hours'
marinating; for cocktail, 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the marinated berries:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mixed berries (blueberries, black raspberries, red
raspberries and quartered strawberries), washed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce Cointreau or Triple Sec
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce brandy
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the cocktail:
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces blackberry liqueur
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce sugar syrup.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare marinated berries: In a large container with a
tightly fitting lid, combine berries, Cointreau, brandy and sugar.
Do not stir.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mix ingredients by putting the lid on the container and
gently turning it back and forth. Allow mixture to marinate at room
temperature for about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Make cocktail: In a metal cocktail shaker half filled with
ice, combine blackberry liqueur, lemon juice, sugar syrup and 2
ounces cold water. Shake well and strain into two chilled highball
glasses. Garnish with marinated berries.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 drinks.
</P>
<P>
   EMERALD DRAGON
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Ruby Foo's
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces Midori melon liqueur
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 ounces orange vodka
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce blue Curacao
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   In a metal cocktail shaker half filled with ice, combine all
ingredients. Shake well, and strain into two chilled martini
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 drinks.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHSIDE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the ``21'' Club
</P>
<P>
   Time:10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces gin (or vodka, rum or bourbon)
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Club soda (optional)
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh mint.
</P>
<P>
   Place gin, lemon juice and sugar in shaker half-filled with ice
cubes. Shake well and pour into a glass along with ice, or pour
into a tall glass and top off with club soda. Garnish with mint.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 drinks.
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY CAIPIRINHA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Blackbird
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, quartered, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   10 pitted cherries, preferably sour cherries, plus 2 stemmed
whole cherries for garnish
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces sugar syrup
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces cachaca.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place lime and pitted sour cherries in a mixing glass or
cocktail shaker. Add syrup and muddle (lightly crush) the lime
pieces and cherries. If using sweet cherries, add an additional
lime. Add cachaca and 1 1/2 cups of cracked ice. Shake well.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour contents into old-fashioned glass and serve garnished
with a cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 drinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
