<HEADER>
A7393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVACY-BANKS-HNS &LR;      07-20 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-BANKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY EXPERTS CALL ON CONGRESS TO PROTECT CONSUMER INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Consumers should be given the right to stop banks
from releasing private information such as what they buy or how
much they earn to outside financial and marketing firms, business
and privacy experts told Congress Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers and the Internet are making it easier and easier for
companies to track almost everything that we as consumers do and to
store that information forever,'' Mary Culnan, a business professor
at Georgetown University, told a House subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   She said Congress should require banks to notify customers that
they are considering releasing their private financial data to
outside firms and then give the customers the option of blocking
them from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to have control of their private information,''
she told the House Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit
Subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Litan, director of economic studies at the Brooking
Institution, a Washington think tank, said consumers are tired of
banks selling their private information to marketing companies that
use the data for direct mailings and telemarketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a bank needs to pass along information for business
purposes, that's one thing,'' he said. ``But when they sell your
private information to some company that has nothing to do with
banking or servicing your account, that's something Congress should
take a look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Clayton, senior privacy analyst for Stone Investments, a
technology investment firm in Dallas, Texas, said growing consumer
concerns over privacy threaten to slow the growth of commerce on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are still not comfortable giving out personal and
financial information on the Internet, and that could pose a real
problem for companies such as banks that would like to increase
their online operations,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee Chairwoman Marge Roukema, R-N.J., said the
``quickening pace of technology'' has left many people, including
herself, questioning how access to their private information has
been obtained and how it is being used.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be able to trust that our financial, medical and other
personal information is being used in the right way,'' Roukema
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the House passed a measure that would give people
the right to block banks and other financial companies from sharing
their personal data with outside firms.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was attached to sweeping legislation that would
allow banks, securities firms and insurance companies to merge. The
Senate passed similar merger legislation in May, but its version
contained no privacy-protection provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The two bills must be blended into one by House and Senate
negotiators before legislation can be sent to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer activists have maintained that the financial overhaul
legislation would create serious privacy risks for people because
banks, brokerages and insurers have compiled profiles of customers'
buying habits, hobbies and health information. Critics see the
potential sharing of these profiles as a particular threat to
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to convince our friends in the Senate that privacy
protection must be a part of this legislation,'' Roukema said.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers agree that a consumer's private information should be
kept confidential. But they argue that to do their job, banks need
to release certain account information.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barsness, president of Prior Lake (Minn.) State Bank,
testified that his bank relies on ``dozens'' of outside firms to
handle many of its functions including data processing, check
clearing and processing, check printing, credit card processing and
ATM processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to get a customer's approval for each of these
operations, that customer would be getting a stack of letters every
day,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard Barton, senior vice president for congressional
relations for the Direct Marketing Association, an international
group representing 4,500 marketing firms, told lawmakers that
despite some annoying phone calls, consumers usually benefit from
the information-gathering done by companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more information we have, the more able we are to pinpoint
the kinds of products a consumer wants and doesn't want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barton added: ``Actually, the last thing any marketing firm
wants to do is bother somebody who doesn't want that product, and
information helps us avoid targeting the wrong people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
