<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHEIST-COINS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI LOOKS FOR COINS LINKED TO ATHEIST FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In a weird twist in the case of missing atheist
figure Madalyn Murray O'Hair, a gang of burglars apparently ended
up with most of the $500,000 in gold coins that vanished along with
O'Hair and her two adult children in late 1995, officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out breaking into storage warehouses, which was
their livelihood, and they just happened to hit the right one at
the right time,'' Roderick Beverly, the FBI agent-in-charge of the
San Antonio office, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Beverly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As best we can tell, these people did not keep records, and
they have very little to show for the pot of gold at the end of the
rainbow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly said the thieves apparently made the score of a lifetime
in late 1995 when they found a heavy suitcase during a break-in at
the Burnet Road Self-Storage in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   It contained an estimated $420,000 in Krugerrands, Canadian
Maple Leaf and American Eagle coins, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, in spending the windfall, the San Antonio thieves
eventually caught the attention of federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about three primary suspects in the theft, and another
8 or 10 who were involved in the aftermath. But based on their
cooperation and candid comments to us, none have been charged,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly declined to say who put the coins in the storage locker,
an never mentioned O'Hair at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference was called to encourage anyone with
knowledge of unusual activity involving gold coins to contact the
FBI, the Austin Police Department, the San Antonio Police
Department or the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Details in an FBI news release as well as information in other
court documents make it clear that these were the coins purchased
in San Antonio in September 1995 by O'Hair's son, Jon Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, O'Hair and her daughter Robin Murray O'Hair disappeared
shortly after the coin purchase. They are presumed to be dead,
although their bodies have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   In May, three men were named in a federal affidavit as the
abductors and killers of the family. Two of them, David Waters and
Gary Karr, are behind bars on weapons charges. Waters has pleaded
guilty, and Karr is awaiting trial in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The third man, Danny Fry, was killed and his head and hands cut
off, allegedly by Waters and Karr, shortly after the O'Hair family
members vanished.
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, has been charged with any crimes relating to
the O'Hair or Fry cases.
</P>
<P>
   Madalyn Murray O'Hair gained prominence more than 30 years ago
for her brash legal battles to remove religion from schools and
went on to lead an atheist organization that had followers around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal affidavit, a confidential source described
renting unit No. 1640 for Waters at the Burnet Road Self-Storage in
late September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The source quoted Waters as saying he was going to ``put a
briefcase with a half-million in gold coins inside the storage
unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Three or four days later, Waters reported someone had broken
into the unit and taken the coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said something to the effect of, `Oh, well! It's gone,'''
said the source.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents said they have recovered only one coin from the
$420,000, and approximately $80,000 remains unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly said there are no apparent links between the burglars
and the various figures in the O'Hair case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe they discovered the coins by accident. The only
affiliation we have found is among themselves,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
