A7404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUG-SWITCHING-0721-C     07-20 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-SWITCHING-0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT SAYS MEDICARE BENEFICIARIES ARE VICTIMS OF ``DRUG
SWITCHING''
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In many cases, Medicare beneficiaries show up at a
pharmacy only to find that their prescription is no longer covered
by their health maintenance organization. Instead, they're given a
lower-cost generic drug that could be harmful to their health, a
congressional report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report from the General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress, found that 15 of the 16 Medicare HMOs examined
including seven in South Florida made changes to their list of
covered drugs. In one-fourth of the cases, HMOs did not notify
beneficiaries about the alterations, GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs were not identified in the report to the Senate Special
Committee on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that three-fourths of the HMOs require the
substitution of lower-cost generic drugs when available. Seven of
the HMOs allowed patients to pay a higher copayment for brand-name
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members agreed there should be adequate information
available to seniors about how their HMO covers prescription drugs
and they should be notified before a change is made. They
emphasized the need for more accurate information on ``drug
switching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Older Americans should know what they're getting with managed
care plans,'' said Sen. Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, the committee's
chairman. ``It's like buying a car. Before you buy, you expect to
know all of your options. If prescription drug coverage is part of
a benefit package, seniors should know the extent of that coverage
before they sign on the dotted line.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said that there is potential harm to beneficiaries when
they are switched ``to other drugs, which may have different side
effects or clinical outcomes'' and which may react differently when
combined with other prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., warned that abuses by HMOs, such as
``drug switching,'' will make it difficult for Congress to allow
the managed care industry to regulate itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have in our country the situation where seniors sign up
believing that they're going to get specific pharmaceuticals, and
then they show up at the pharmacy and can't get it, that is going
to undermine our efforts to reinvent Medicare,'' Wyden said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Helms, a spokesperson for Citizens for the Right to
Know, a patient advocacy group, said that most patients cannot make
an informed choice when their drug is changed. She said it should
be as easy as reading the ingredient labels on food products.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
