<HEADER>
A7409 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-ART-2     07-20 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADER SEEKS TO CHANGE IMAGE OF ISRAELI SETTLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ISRAEL-U.S., ISRAEL-U.S.-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.  Map  is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAALE ADUMIM, West Bank _ Enter this king-size bedroom community
for Jerusalem, and the frontier image of the hard-core Jewish
settlement fades fast.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere can be seen the stereotypical mobile homes and makeshift
water tanks staking out hills for Jewish believers. Instead, Burger
King, Ace Hardware and a concrete canyon of apartment towers
dominate the landscape, beacons of a more prosaic lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Benny Kashriel, 47, mayor of this suburban city,
belies the image of the typical religious Zionist settler leader.
</P>
<P>
   He is clean-shaven and wears no skullcap. Although once
militant, he now seems to be more bureaucrat than true believer.
With 25,000 residents and a land area larger than Tel Aviv under
his charge, he is too busy _ too settled _ to wage an ideological
war.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kashriel is no anomaly, but the new public face of the
increasingly practical-minded settlement movement. Eight days ago
he was elected chairman of the Yesha Council of Jewish Settlements,
assuming a high-profile post as the top-ranking Jewish civic
activist in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Kashriel is determined to change the settlers' pariah image,
moderate their far-right politics and teach them to redefine
themselves as part of the Israeli mainstream. It is a survival
instinct, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important what we did in the 1970s and the 1980s,
settling this land for ideological reasons,'' he said in an
interview Tuesday. ``Now we are 200,000 people, and we have needs
that should not be sacrificed to a hard ideological line. We have
to be pragmatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming into office just days after Ehud Barak, the new prime
minister, Kashriel ushered in a new relationship between the
government and the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong member of the conservative Likud Party, he met with
Barak, the Labor Party leader, and emerged with an agreement:
Neither side would surprise the other. The settlers would refrain
from occupying new hilltops and the government would not make any
private decisions to evacuate them.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a mutual dependency. The settlers do not want to move.
And Barak, who brought the settlers' political party into his
coalition, needs both their political and their grass-roots leaders
to support his peace initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Jewish settlements in the West Bank is one of the
thorniest issues as Israel negotiates a final peace with the
Palestinians, and the settler population has the potential to act
as a destabilizing force.
</P>
<P>
   In Kashriel's view, previous radical activity by the settlers
not only failed to accomplish its goal _ halting the territorial
concessions of land-for-peace agreements like the Oslo accords and
the recent Wye memorandum _ but harmed the settlers' standing in
Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to my predecessors: This is the message of one who does
not wear a yarmulke,'' he said. ``You did what you did, you were
extremist, you lost land and you got Oslo. But that's not all. Now
you are no longer a pioneer. You are a burden on the shoulders of
Israel. It's time to try to win back some sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interim period before a final agreement is reached, the
Palestinians, backed by the United States, see every new Jewish
outpost in the West Bank as a unilateral act of aggression that
compromises the final deal. Barak has said he will not allow new
ones to be built during the interim period but will not dismantle
existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   As a goal, though, Barak favors preserving large blocs of
settlements under Israeli control. That would, although it goes
unsaid, mean relinquishing the many small ones scattered through
the craggy hills.
</P>
<P>
   Kashriel's predecessor, Pinchas Wallerstein, used very strong
language to condemn Barak's plan as ``ethnic cleansing.'' More
tempered, Kashriel says only, ``I don't agree with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we don't expect him to be a settler,'' Kashriel said.
``But our first meeting with him was good. For him, we are part of
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven miles from Jerusalem, Maale Adumim has no real fear of
extinction, and some analysts think its mayor has become a
pragmatist because his chief battle has been won.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man who has a status equal to that of the mayors of such
cities as Netanya and Rehovot no longer needs a revolutionary
ideology,'' Meron Benvenisti, an author and former deputy mayor of
Jerusalem, wrote in an Op-Ed column in the newspaper Haaretz last
week. ``His revolution has succeeded.``
</P>
<P>
   Kashriel moved to Maale Adumim about 15 years ago, influenced by
the religious Zionist movement, whose schools he attended as a
youngster. The thousands of families in subsequent waves settled
there primarily because housing was affordable, taxes were low and
the quality of life was, in their eyes, more like that of a small
town.
</P>
<P>
   Many settlers have long enjoyed the financial benefits of living
in frontier towns _ tax breaks and special loans for housing from
the government _ but residents of the established Maale Adumim no
longer get government subsidies, Kashriel said. Two-bedroom
apartments sell for from $140,000 to $180,000.
</P>
<P>
   Like many settlers, many residents of Maale Adumim, where 27
percent voted for Barak, are resigned to the idea that peace means
territorial concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Kashriel protested outside the prime minister's residence when
Benjamin Netanyahu, the former Likud Party leader, was in Maryland
negotiating the Wye Memorandum last fall. This week he stayed off
the streets when Barak visited Camp David to talk about peace with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now sitting quietly, not protesting,'' Kashriel said.
``We accept reality. To make a Palestinian country _ I'm not happy,
but they are on the way there, thanks to my Likud government.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kashriel said he would organize demonstrations if Israel
withdrew from more land in the West Bank before final status talks
were well under way. That is considered likely; Barak is expected
to undertake at least a modest pullback of Israeli troops in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Kashriel said he would have a hard time controlling
radical settlers if the leftist members of Barak's coalition
antagonized them. He cited a recent decision by Ran Cohen, the new
trade minister, to suspend financing for new factories in the West
Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   To Cohen, the move meant freezing the special subsidies that the
settlements have enjoyed at the expense of poor towns in Israel
proper. To Kashriel, however, the decision was simple-minded. He
said that the industrial park in his city is completely integrated,
mixing 1,000 Palestinian and 1,000 Israeli workers; only 100 of the
Israelis are settlers, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A huge photograph of Yitzhak Rabin, the late prime minister,
sits at the entrance to Kashriel's office in City Hall. It is a
curious sight, given that in Rabin's final days he was at war with
the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, though, Rabin was Maale Adumim's patron. He
authorized its creation during his first term in office, and during
his second term it was the first settlement to become a city. It
was under his watch that a military commander signed an order to
expand Maale Adumim's land vastly, by another 3,000 acres, mostly
desert.
</P>
<P>
   That order became tangible when Moshe Arens, in his final weeks
as defense minister last spring, authorized an urban construction
plan to link up Maale Adumim with Jerusalem. The plan was seen as a
last-minute land grab by the outgoing administration and drew fury
from the Palestinians and worldwide condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, a U.S. official in Israel suggested that
Kashriel might not be as moderate as he was trying to portray
himself. ``Is he a wolf in grandma's clothing, or really grandma?''
the official said. ``Sometimes you can see his teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashriel said he thought the Americans should sponsor dialogues
between the Palestinians and the Israelis in the West Bank. He said
that relations were more normal on the ground than in political
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   He said that residents of his city shopped in the neighboring
Arab town of Al Azariya, where they used to be stoned, and that
Palestinian neighbors attended movies at the new theater in Maale
Adumim.
</P>
<P>
   A drive through Al Azariya did not reveal a single settler
shopping, but Saturday is probably the busy day for the secular
settlers, who are the most likely to shop there.
</P>
<P>
   Kashriel also said that some high-level meetings between
settlers and Palestinians were already taking place. He said he
flew to the Greek island of Rhodes to meet with Palestinian
officials eight months ago _ which he said he was acknowledging
publicly for the first time on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone brought statements and we had fights,'' he said.
``Then afterward, over coffee and even a glass of beer, they made
jokes about Arafat and we made jokes about Bibi Netanyahu.'' He was
referring to Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and using
Netanyahu's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extreme right-wing settlers are the ones who are all the
time in the media, disrespecting the law,'' he continued. ``But
they are not representative. I was elected; I am representative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
