<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20 HINDUS KILLED IN GUERRILLA ATTACKS NEAR KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(yn) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Twenty Hindus were killed in three incidents
before dawn on Tuesday in what is feared to be a stepped-up
campaign of hit-and-run tactics by Muslim insurgents in remote
areas of the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The worst attack left 15 dead in Lihota, a village in the
forested Himalayan foothills of Doda District 90 miles northeast of
the Kashmiri winter capital of Jammu.
</P>
<P>
   Five of those killed were members of a village defense committee
that was armed, the police said. The authorities have set up dozens
of such militia groups to prevent raids in vulnerable areas, but
the brigades may themselves now be targets. The other 10 victims,
including eight women, were believed to be committee members'
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   India has been bracing for a violent backlash by militants after
two months of furious fighting along the northern frontier of
Kashmir between Indian armed forces and hundreds of infiltrators
who had built bunkers in mountaintop positions above a strategic
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Those infiltrators, which India believes to be a combination of
Pakistani army regulars and Muslim guerrillas, have been defeated,
although sporadic fighting continues.
</P>
<P>
   That ``humiliation'' is now driving the Pakistani-backed
fighters to mount new attacks, said the chief minister of Jammu and
Kashmir, Farooq Abdullah. The killings in Lihota ``demonstrate the
level of frustration among militant ranks and expose their sinister
designs to curb peace and tranquillity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the two other incidents, heavily armed guerrillas attacked a
labor camp in Poonch District and killed four men, the police said.
An Indian soldier also died in a rocket attack on an army post in
Poonch.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, an Indian news agency reported that government
forces in Poonch had retaliated against the militants, killing
five. That could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Violence again seems to be increasing in Kashmir, where, by
conservative estimates, 24,000 people _ half civilians _ have died
in a decadelong insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths in Lihota represent the fourth mass killing in three
weeks. On July 1, nine Hindus, including a 100-year-old and his
90-year-old wife, were killed in the village of Ari. Two days
before, 15 Hindu laborers were killed in the village of Sandhu. The
police said Muslim militants were responsible in the two cases.
</P>
<P>
   On June 28, however, 15 Muslims were killed in Poonch. The
police said those deaths were a result of infighting among militant
factions.
</P>
<P>
   Several militant groups operate in Kashmir. They do not always
agree on religious beliefs or military tactics, and there are
rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   According to Indian authorities, a majority of the insurgents
are no longer native to Kashmir. They are said to come from
Pakistan, Afghanistan, Algeria, Egypt and other Islamic nations.
The fight for Kashmir, in dispute by overwhelmingly Muslim Pakistan
and predominantly Hindu India for 52 years, is viewed as a jihad by
the so-called mujahadeen, or holy warriors.
</P>
<P>
   The militants and Indian authorities have repeatedly been
accused of human rights violations. Scores of well-documented cases
are in the record.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch has in the last week issued a report that
criticizes both sides, but especially focuses on the Indian army.
The rights group accuses the army of continued abuses, summary
executions of suspects, indiscriminate shootings, rapes and arsons.
The report notes that the army has consolidated its control over
the Kashmir Valley and says the ``brutal tactics'' used there in
the early 1990s were being instituted in areas like Poonch and
Doda, where the militants operate with more frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggravating the situation, the army has recruited
ex-servicemen, who for historical reasons are almost exclusively
Hindu, to serve in village defense committees that assist the army
in military operations,'' the report said. ``In Doda and the border
districts, where the population is nearly evenly divided between
Hindus and Muslims, there is a growing concern that tensions
between the two communities might ignite a wider communal
conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
