<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCARTIN MAKES MOVE: HE'S SECOND AFTER WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIAU-ENGALY, France _ The Spaniards had a premonition Tuesday.
The Tour de France stage traveled through southern France, dipping
into Spain and finishing just miles from its border. So the
Spaniards dragged out their giant yellow and red flags and flocked
to the course, looking for an inspring countryman to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The premonition came true.
</P>
<P>
   Fernardo Escartin pedaled past thousands of cheering and
flag-waving fans up to the ski resort here, and he not only won the
race but shook up the standings. Escartin, who had been fifth
overall, moved up to second with his time of 5 hours 19 minutes 49
seconds, thanks to the demise of Abraham Olano. The fellow Spaniard
finished seven minutes back and dropped to eighth overall.
</P>
<P>
   Another crowd favorite, Frenchman Richard Virenque, also inched
up the standings to fifth overall after his third-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that made any difference to American Lance
Armstrong, whose overall lead slipped only slightly. He has a 6:19
advantage over Escartin with five days of racing to go.
</P>
<P>
   Drug rumors continued to haunt Armstrong, though, as it was
reported in Le Monde that small traces of certain anti-inflammatory
drugs had showed up in Armstrong's urine after the prologue.
Corticosteroids are banned except when used for legitimate medical
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But when Armstrong was asked about it after the race, he
continued to deny any drug use. It should be noted that as the
wearer of the yellow jersey, Armstrong is tested for drugs every
day. If found positive, he would be disqualified immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong stayed out in front of the pack for virtually the
entire 108-mile race, as the man in the yellow jersey was
surrounded by Postal Service teammates Frankie Andreu, Tyler
Hamilton, and Kevin Livingston. But over the course of the
sweltering, up-and-down race in the Pyrenees, the others lost steam
one by one. By the penultimate climb, Armstrong's teammates were
nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on your own, it's best to attack and hope someone
goes with you,'' said Postal Service team director Johann Bruyneel.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss rider Alex Zulle, hoping to preserve his third place in
the standings and a spot on the podium, did. But Escartin got an
even better jump and rode solo up the final climb to finish 2:01
ahead of Virenque and Zulle and 2:10 in front of Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Escartin, 31, has ridden seven Tours on three different teams
but has never won a stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I crossed the line, I thought of all the times I just
missed a big victory,'' he said. ``I was scared the guys behind me
might catch me, so I just put my head down and went all out.''
</P>
<P>
   The first American to finish after Armstrong was Hamilton, in
14th place. He's now 19th overall, 23 minutes behind the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Greg LeMond, the only other American to ever win the Tour, was
watching the race Tuesday not on a bike but from the comfort of a
car with a French TV crew. LeMond has been in France for the past
week, cycling some of the Tour courses with a tour group out of
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time Tour winner, who retired in 1994, has a touch of
gray in his hair and is a little heavier than he was five years
ago, but he still attracts almost as much attention as when he wore
the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   When he stops in a town for the start, he's surrounded by
cameras and affably chats with anyone _ in fluent French, of
course. And he acknowledges that even though his tour group wasn't
allowed to ride all the way up Alpe d'Huez, since cyclists are
banned from the last 3 miles of the mountain course, he probably
could have talked his way past the gendarmes if he had told them
who he was.
</P>
<P>
   But LeMond didn't, and he had to just sit and watch the race
that he once dominated. He said he's not really jealous but is ``a
little envious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like watching it but at the same time have bittersweet
memories,'' he said. ``I still want to be doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   But at age 38, LeMond, who is suffering from a muscle disease,
knows he can't. ``You realize that part of your life goes by
awfully fast,'' he said. ``When you're young, you don't see that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
