<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, July 21. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Dateline to kum) _ There are signs of a rift in the
gun industry as one manufacturer is reported ready to break ranks
on issues of government control.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-PILOT (Boston) _ There are two major challenges a pilot
faces flying in low-visibility conditions: flying straight and
level, and recognizing when the plane, against the pilot's
intentions, is turning, descending or climbing. At 3 miles a
minute, the cruising speed of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s Saratoga, even
a small deviation can quickly become a huge problem. By Carl H.
Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Republican leaders in the House
scrambled Tuesday to head off a revolt by moderates within the
party and avert a humiliating defeat on their signature issue of
tax cuts. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TAX-BREAKS (Washington) _ Like most other tax bills before
Congress in recent years, the measures in the Senate and House this
year contain dozens of narrow provisions benefiting one particular
interest or another _ or, to put it another way, benefiting one
particular constituent or another of an important senator or
representative. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROTEST (Beijing) _ In what could be the start of a broad
crackdown, dozens of leaders of the Buddhist Law movement were
detained by the police Tuesday in 14 Chinese cities, according to a
Hong Kong-based human rights group. At least 70 leaders of the
group, which stunned authorities last April when 10,000 adherents
silently materialized in a protest outside the Communist
leadership's compound here, were picked up in the police sweep that
began Monday night. By Mark Landler. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-EXODUS (Miami) _ In the heaviest exodus since Fidel Castro
turned his back and allowed 33,000 people to exit the island in
1994, more than 1,500 Cubans have made it ashore in South Florida
so far this year. More than 1,000 Cubans have been stopped at sea
and forced to return to the island in compliance with the so called
``wet-foot, dry-foot'' policy, that allows those Cubans who make it
to shore to apply, ultimately, for asylum, but sends those caught
at sea back to Cuba. The policy has led to high drama at sea and on
the beaches of South Florida, as Cubans try almost anything,
including threatened self-immolation and suicide, to hold off the
Coast Guard long enough to put at least a foot on dry sand. By Rick
Bragg. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLERS (Maale Adumim, West Bank) _ Benny Kashriel, 47,
mayor of this suburban city, belies the image of the typical
religious Zionist settler leader. He is clean-shaven and wears no
skullcap. Although once militant, he now seems to be more
bureaucrat than true believer. Kashriel is no anomaly, but the new
public face of the increasingly practical-minded settlement
movement. Eight days ago he was elected chairman of the Yesha
Council of Jewish Settlements. He is determined to change the
settlers' pariah image, moderate their far-right politics and teach
them to redefine themselves as part of the Israeli mainstream. By
Deborah Sontag. 1,600 words. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Undated) _ Attempting to resolve one of
the most bitter feuds in medicine, a panel of scientific experts
recommended that the nation's system for distributing donated
organs be overhauled so that scarce hearts, lungs, livers, kidneys
and pancreases are spread across broad geographic areas and given
to patients with the most urgent medical need. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
