<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPES TO DEFUSE TENSIONS BETWEEN CHINA, TAIWAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton dispatched U.S. envoys to Beijing
and Taipei on Tuesday in hopes of defusing tensions between China
and Taiwan. He also voiced concern about the inflammatory rhetoric
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reaffirmed the United States' one-China policy, but he
declined to respond when asked if America would defend Taiwan from
an attack by China.
</P>
<P>
   ``China knows very well what our policy is, and we know quite
well what their policy is,'' Clinton told reporters when asked
about his weekend telephone conversation with Chinese President
Jiang Zemin. ``I made it clear our policy had not changed,
including our view under the Taiwan Relations Act that we would
take very seriously any abridgement of the peaceful dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the administration
would send Stanley Roth, assistant secretary of state for East Asia
and Pacific, to Beijing and Richard Bush, chairman of the
nongovernmental American Institute in Taiwan, to Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui enraged China when he suggested
during a July 9 interview that the island should be treated on a
``state to state'' basis by Beijing. China considers Taiwan one of
its provinces and responded with hints of military reprisal should
Taiwan take any step toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``However one assesses what is going on in terms of statements
being made, I think that the important point here is that the only
way to resolve this is peacefully,'' Albright said. Roth also will
pave the way for Albright's upcoming meeting with her Chinese
counterpart at an Asian foreign ministers meeting in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton reported he had a positive conversation with
Jiang when they spoke Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the action of the United States in affirming
our support of the one-China policy and encouraging Taiwan to
support that and the framework within which dialogue has occurred
will be helpful in easing some of the tensions,'' Clinton told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. relations with China have ebbed in recent months as federal
agents investigated the possibility Beijing attempted to influence
the 1996 elections and the possibility that Beijing stole critical
nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The accidental bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia,
which Beijing suggested was intentional, prompted a three-day,
rock-throwing melee in front of the United States Embassy in China.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's comments prompted Chinese leaders to renew threats to
reunify Taiwan with China by force. China also made an
unprecedented military disclosure last week when it announced it
had developed the neutron bomb, statements viewed as attempts to
intimidate Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years, since the defeated Chiang Kai-shek fled to Taiwan,
the two have coexisted through diplomatic ambiguity. The United
States ended its formal recognition of Taiwan as the true China in
1972 after President Nixon visited mainland China ruled by
Communists. The United States officially recognizes one China _ the
mainland _ and maintains Taiwan has a right to self defense if
attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese media Tuesday reported heavily on military exercises and
published a survey indicating the majority of Chinese support
reunification by force.
</P>
<P>
   Lee continued to stand by his statements, adding ``only after we
have democratic reunification shall there be the possibility of one
China.'' Lee maintains Taiwan, which is far more economically
prosperous and democratic, and China cannot begin unification talks
unless they negotiation on a ``state to state'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese Foreign Ministry countered that Taiwan ``should not
underestimate the determination of the Chinese government to oppose
separation and oppose Taiwan independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Taipei also downplayed the possibility of expanded Chinese war
games in the Taiwan Straits, which separates the mainland from the
island. A similar attempt in 1996 by China to intimidate Taiwan
with military exercises prompted the United States to move several
warships to the area.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' defensive relationship with Taiwan may be
ambiguous at best and President Clinton offered no clarification
when asked, stating only that the United States views ``very
seriously'' any breach of the Taiwan Relations Act.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said Clinton placed the
call to Jiang on Sunday ``because he was concerned about some of
the rhetoric ...There's always some concern when you have this
rhetoric, but the president made clear he believes the best way to
resolve any issues between the parties is in the context of the
cross-straits dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the United States believes any issues that need to
be resolved between the two should be done through talks. ``I think
any rising tension in that area is something we do take seriously,
and we do have concern about,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
