u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MINORITY-BOS &LR;      07-20 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MINORITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WB FACES QUESTIONS ABOUT LACK OF MINORITY SHOWS, ACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ The issue of diversity on television took
center stage again Tuesday as the top executives of the WB network
faced sharp questions about the lack of minority characters in the
network's fall schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Of two dozen stars and producers who took part in morning
interview sessions to discuss three new fall shows on the WB, none
were African-American or Asian-American (one, an actress in a minor
role, is Hispanic). The afternoon sessions, in which another three
new shows were presented, were likewise dominated by white actors
and producers.
</P>
<P>
   The WB, known for its teen-oriented fare, was not a target of a
recent broadside by the NAACP. The civil rights organization
threatened a boycott and legal action against NBC, CBS, ABC, and
Fox to protest the fact that no minorities are in starring roles in
the 26 new shows, which NAACP president Kweisi Mfume called a
``virtual whitewash.'' But as it became apparent that the WB is
also vulnerable to a similar charge, executives of the network _
which has been riding high with critically acclaimed shows _ were
thrown on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Kellner, chief executive officer of the WB, pointed to its
sitcoms with black themes, including ``The Steve Harvey Show'' and
``The Jamie Foxx Show'' in arguing that ``our track record thus far
is a good one.'' He also noted that the network is developing a new
comedy series to star black standup comic Nick Cannon, which will
be produced by Will Smith. However, that show is not expected to
air until the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Even the producers of the new WB shows, mindful that the NAACP
criticism has intensified the focus on TV diversity, scrambled to
point to minority supporting characters they have cast or plan to
cast. For instance, it was noted that Majandra Delfino of
``Roswell,'' a new drama that has been called a ``teenage
`X-Files,' '' is the child of a Venezualean father and
Cuban-American mother. But Delfino plays a relatively small
supporting role as the best friend of the show's star.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Mayem Singer, creator of a new romantic comedy in an urban
setting titled ``Jack &AMP; Jill,'' said she plans to ``spread it out
ethnically'' by adding a couple of black supporting characters. But
the lead roles in ``Jack &AMP; Jill,'' as with all six new shows
presented Tuesday, will continue to be occupied by white actors.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of diversity on television has created a ``uniform
frustration'' among minority actors in Hollywood, according to
producer Yvette Lee Bowser, who is African-American. ``There's a
very unfortunate reality that we have to deal with this season,''
said Bowser. ``But it was the same last season, and the season
before that. It's not a new issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowser said the solution is to open up more opportunities for
``talented writers of color'' to work on more shows in order to
``kick down a few more doors.'' She suggested that may be easier
now that the NAACP's angry denunciation of the networks has created
a ``heightened sense of responsibility'' among TV executives.
Bowser herself is developing a drama featuring a ``multicultural''
cast that the WB will consider for the fall 2000 series, according
to WB president of entertainment Susanne Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels insisted concerns about diversity are ``something we do
take seriously,'' adding that the network will ``make changes where
it appropriate'' in casting to address those concerns. (Kellner
noted that the WB was in talks with Smith and Bowser regarding the
proposed shows before the NAACP issued its critique of the
networks.)
</P>
<P>
   On another social issue, Kellner acknowledged that the Columbine
High School massacre has been a wakeup call for television
executives when it comes to violent programs. However, he added,
``I don't think that (TV) is contributing the violence problem that
exists in America today.'' He also said that the WB lost millions
of dollars in advertising revenue by postponing the season finale
of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' due to post-Columbine concerns
about violent scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels announced that Nicholas Turturro of ABC's ``NYPD Blue''
has signed a deal to star in a WB sitcom for the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
