<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 25,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHWARZ-CONDUCTOR (Undated) _ There was talk, as there always is
when a young American conductor, in this case, Gerard Schwarz,
begins piling up accomplishments of a future at the helm of a major
American orchestra. ``With talent on this order,'' Harold C.
Schonberg wrote in The New York Times in 1980, after a New York
visit by the Los Angeles Chamber Orchestra, ``there is no place for
him but up.'' Nearly 20 years after that prediction, it is fair to
ask whether Schwarz, now 51, has indeed made his way up in the
music world. But how one answers that question is bound up with
one's view of what constitutes success for a conductor. Schwarz
continues to direct Mostly Mozart at Lincoln Center in Manhattan,
which opens its 33rd season on Tuesday evening. But the festival
has been scaled back in recent years to make way for the Lincoln
Center Festival, and Schwarz has become less of a presence. By
Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SINGAPORE-DANCE (Singapore) _ Not many years ago the Singapore
arts scene was largely invisible. Now it is exploding. With a
combination of seduction and subsidies, the Singapore government is
aggressively wooing artists and arts organizations around the world
to make their homes in this affluent city-state. The first annual
Singapore Arts Festival closed its monthlong run in mid-June,
attracting 29 international troupes, more than 200 fringe
performers and a mammoth citywide sculpture exhibition, thanks to
generous government support. By Susan Heller Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WALTZ-MUSIC (Undated) _ ``Walzen,'' as any bibulous Viennese
will tell you, is ``to twirl.'' The word means more than
``rotate,'' less than ``wanken,'' or downright stagger. Drop the
umlaut, and we have what Johann Strauss the Younger and his father
had Europe doing for a good part of the 19th century. Waltzes had
existed under other names during the century before. Mozart might
call them ``Landler''; Schubert gave waltzes their proper name and
created a body of piano music stunning both for its simplicity and
for its subtlety. Weber, Liszt and Berlioz raised them to the title
of high art. Tchaikovsky and another Strauss, Richard, made a
twirling, almost staggering, three-in-a-bar ballroom dance a form
to set next to the rondo or the passacaglia. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   GOETHE'S-FAUST (Undated) _ Although Schumann's ``Scenes From
Goethe's `Faust,''' has elements of both opera and oratorio, it
fails to fit comfortably into either form. Running two hours and
requiring full orchestra and a large chorus as well as vocal
soloists, it demands much from concert presenters and audiences
alike, and is thus something of a rarity. Although it has been
performed by the American Symphony and the Orchestra of St. Luke's
the last decade, it was last presented by the New York Philharmonic
in 1973 and has not been heard at Carnegie Hall since 1891, when
the third and last part was given. New Yorkers can hear the work
Sunday evening at Avery Fisher Hall, where John Eliot Gardiner and
the Orchestre Revolutionnaire et Romantique conclude their
four-night Schumann celebration as part of the Lincoln Center
Festival. By David Mermelstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEHLDAU-JAZZ (Undated) _ Brad Mehldau, at 28, is among the most
celebrated jazz pianists of his generation. If you've heard his
name mentioned, you've probably heard that he's ``the next Bill
Evans.'' High praise, to be sure. But like most such comparisons,
this one is more than a little misleading, as unfair as it is
flattering. By Adam Shatz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ART (Washington) _ Major exhibitions of the art of India
are rare in this part of the world. They always have been. Why?
Nobody knows. This art has everything: epic drama and swoony sob
stories, gods, gremlins and glamour queens, the human at its most
human, the spiritual at its most ineffable. Formally, it is pure
seduction. Intellectually and emotionally, it looks you in the eye
and says, over and over again in a thousand different ways: wake
up, change your life, look again, things are not what they seem.
Which are the fundamental messages of great art, sacred or secular,
anywhere. All these elements play a role in ``Devi: The Great
Goddess,'' a gathering of 120 sculptures and paintings at the
Arthur M. Sackler Gallery of the Smithsonian Institution through
Sept. 6. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
