<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CCE-EARNINGS-COX     07-20 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CCE-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CCE shows sharp drop in earnings after recall
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The financial fallout from the recent European recall
of Coca-Cola Enterprises' soft drinks became clearer Tuesday when
the bottler reported a sharp drop in second-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Coke system's largest bottler said it earned $33 million, or
8 cents a share, which includes an expected one-time $103 million
charge, or 16 cents a share, to cover the recall's cost.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the charge, CCE said it would have earned 24 cents a
share, 3 cents more than analysts expected. In the year-ago period,
CCE earned $111 million, or 27 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had already cut their estimates on what CCE would earn
in the quarter and in the coming months because of its troubles in
Europe, where two of its plants were linked to contaminated soft
drinks. Restrictions on the bottler's products, which included bans
in several countries, have been lifted.
</P>
<P>
   The average estimate among analysts surveyed by Zacks Investment
Research is that CCE will earn 23 cents a share in the third
quarter and 24 cents for the year. In the third quarter last year,
the company earned 21 cents a share, and 28 cents for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is they will be in a good position to show
improved cash flow in the second half,'' said Marty Romm of CS
First Boston. Romm, who rates CCE's shares a ``buy,'' expects CCE
to earn 23 to 25 cents a share in the third quarter and 25 cents a
share for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very encouraged,'' said Prudential Securities Inc.
analyst George Thompson told Bloomberg News. ``The issue is how
quickly volume will come back in Europe, and I think it will be
relatively quickly.'' Thompson has a ``strong buy'' rating on the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Volume in the countries where the products were recalled, mainly
France, Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands, dropped 29 percent
in the second quarter, with a decline of almost 70 percent in June,
the beginning of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But in Great Britain, where no soft drinks were recalled, volume
in the second quarter rose 6 percent, including a 9 percent
increase in the month of June.
</P>
<P>
   In another key measure of performance in the beverage bottling
industry, CCE reported cash operating profit, which excludes
interests, taxes, depreciation and other items, fell 6 percent in
the second quarter to $574 million, compared with $611 million in
the year-ago period. Excluding the charge, however, operating
profit would have been higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the disruption in our business from the product
recall in Europe, we are pleased that we were able to produce 6
percent second-quarter 1999 comparable cash operating profit growth
excluding nonrecurring costs,'' said Henry A. Schimberg, president
and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co., which owns 40 percent of CCE, also took a
financial hit because of the European health scare. The world's
largest soft drink company reported recently that its
second-quarter profit fell 21 percent from a year ago. It blamed
about 25 percent of the profit decline on the recall.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, CCE's stock closed unchanged at $29.37 1/2
Tuesday. Coca-Cola Co. shares closed lower with other Dow
industrials, ending the day at $62.93 3/4, down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Seward writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOLOGY-LIMITS-COX     07-20 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOLOGY-LIMITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beyond silicon: Microchip industry faces big change
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scientists at Lucent Technology's Bell Labs recently
highlighted a seemingly jarring fact: The use of silicon-dioxide
based transistors to make ever smaller microchips, as has been done
for decades, may have to end soon.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon, as it happens, has just about reached its limits in
terms of miniaturization, or how small the chips can be made and
still provide the information needed to make them work.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is more directly concerned with this red flag than James
Meindl, the crew-cut, laid-back Georgia Tech professor who is
directing research by Tech and other universities into the
microchips of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Meindl, who just returned from an assignment as the keynoter for
an international convention on the future of semiconductors, was
ready for the question. The meeting he attended, the International
Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors, was held earlier this month
in Santa Clara, Calif. and attracted futurists, scientists and
researchers from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, Meindl said, there is no basis for great
concern about the limits of silicon because, currently, technology
can improve chips ``by a factor of 10'' over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall outlook is to continue to improve as we have in
past years,'' Meindl said, ``but down the road there are some
formidable problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that, barring a breakthrough in another direction,
the basic material of the transistor may have to switch from
silicon oxides, a naturally occurring material related to sand, to
oxides of tantalum, a more artificial material that behaves
differently and will require different procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would be overstating to say that in the next
50 years we may have a change comparable to the shift from the
steel-based industries of the first half of the 20th century,''
Meindl said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as many plants and manufacturing processes changed because
of the decline in traditional uses of steel, so may the economics
and processes for making semiconductors change in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it costs about $1 billion to set up a plant for
manufacturing microchips under the current technology,'' Meindl
said, ``and we will be working hard to recapture those investments
over the next decades, producing silicon-based chips as efficiently
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the new technology of using tantalum oxide as
well as other new ingredients will gradually grow and replace the
old technology. Meindl, a Pittsburgh native, said the trick will be
to manage that changeover more smoothly than we did steel, when
obsolescent plants littered the landscape of metropolitan centers
like Pittsburgh, Cleveland and other former industrial powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, given the huge investments, factories will be
used longer to capture the investments, and innovation will
probably occur less rapidly,'' Meindl said.
</P>
<P>
   Tantalum is not a brand-new ingredient in the technology world,
Meindl said. It is now used to produce memory chips called DRAMS or
dynamic random access memory chips. But its expanded use will
introduce broader changes in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes in chip technology, he said, will include the
substitution of copper for aluminum as a conductor in new chips,
even though copper presents side effects that must be managed.
</P>
<P>
   An allied problem during the period of change will be to protect
the valuable manufacturers of tools used in the production of
chips, said Meindl, and this problem is being addressed through
meetings like the road map conference in Santa Clara, where papers
were presented outlining the details of what will happen in the
next years.
</P>
<P>
   ``By paying attention to the road maps, manufacturers of tools
will be able to prepare for the changing needs and stay
profitable,'' Meindl said.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, however, miniaturization will continue as it
has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   With a twinkle in his eye, Meindl said the next hot development
will likely be whole communicating networks on a single chip,
``networks not unlike wireless phone networks now so heavily
used.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
