<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRINCE PICKS UP THE PIECES IN BASEMENT JAM SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some arrived at 6 p.m. to line up for tickets, others
showed up when doors opened at 9; some were told the show started
at 10:30, and others came as late as midnight and even 2 a.m. They
all had to wait until nearly 3:30 Tuesday morning, when the Artist
Formerly Known as Prince came onstage at Life for a small club show
that was first announced earlier that day. His first words: ``Do
you mind if we take a few minutes to tune up?''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the concert let out, the sun had come up, and some
fans had spent nearly 12 hours in the low-ceilinged basement of
Life in the West Village. But the music was well worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a band that included the saxophonist Maceo Parker
(from James Brown's and George Clinton's bands) and former Sly and
the Family Stone members, including the bassist Larry Graham, the
Artist (as he likes to be called) led one of the jam sessions that
he has been increasingly fond of holding at small clubs directly
after performing full-scale shows.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, however, he was in town courting the Internet
community, which is holding conferences, conventions, concerts and
awards shows in Manhattan this week.
</P>
<P>
   From the stage, the Artist (who after several years of releasing
records independently has said he will put out his next album,
``Rave Un2 the Joy Fantastic,'' on a major label in September)
offered self-styled wisdom about computers, for example: it's OK to
``use the computer, but don't let the computer use you.''
</P>
<P>
   While his arena shows focus on hits and crowd-pleasing stage
moves, he steps out of the spotlight during the small shows,
performing few of his own songs, giving his band members and guests
ample time to solo and often keeping his back to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Like any jam, sometimes the music reaches new heights and other
times it never gets off the ground. Fortunately, the concert
Tuesday morning contained some of the best music the Artist and
friends have done in any of the recent late-night sessions that
this critic has seen.
</P>
<P>
   In a world in which musical styles are strictly subdivided and
categorized, the band insisted on seeing the complete picture,
incorporating pieces of everything from the old blues song
``Motherless Child'' to the new rap song ``Wild Wild West'' into
seamless funk workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Graham played a 10-minute crowd-roaming, feedback-filled bass
solo more inspired than at his own solo shows; Doug E. Fresh and
Kool Moe Dee appeared onstage to rap, beatbox and work the crowd;
Parker stepped up for at least four solos, and the Artist turned
``Alphabet Street'' into a country song.
</P>
<P>
   Much more time was devoted Tuesday morning to songs in the Sly
and the Family Stone catalog than in the Artist's, and Graham did a
lot more performing and playing than the Artist did. But in those
few, precious, savored moments when the Artist (wearing a giant
hoop earring, a grown-out beard and funk hippie garb) stepped
forward, he took control gently but forcefully, reminding fans who
admire him as a performer, songwriter and eccentric that he's also
one of the best guitarists in his field.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing the audience only one bone, the Artist performed
``Purple Rain'' to close the show, introducing it with a long,
soulful speech about love, respect and how Graham had convinced the
Artist _ the performer of such hits as ``Erotic City'' and ``Dirty
Mind'' _ not to swear onstage anymore, despite how much he likes to
use those words as emphasis. He then began a slow version of the
ballad that exploded near the end with a slow, grinding, dripping
wet solo more emphatic than any curse words.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
