<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-AD-COLUMN-NY     07-20 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BASEBALL TRAVELS IN TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An unusual promotional marketing effort co-sponsored
by Major League Baseball and a big corporate advertiser, Century
21, will try turning tradition on its head by turning the clock
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is centered on the first national series of
``Turn Ahead the Clock'' baseball games, which begins Wednesday
night, when the San Francisco Giants play host to the San Diego
Padres, and continues through Sept. 18. The time-travel gimmick got
a test run on June 26 when the Anaheim Angels played the Oakland
A's, generating jokes about outlandish 21st-century concession
prices that were actually unchanged from what fans are charged in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The games will feature futuristic-looking team uniforms and
logos, scoreboards augmented with special effects and predictions
for updated argot. For instance, the position of shortstop becomes
``the intermediate station'' and left field becomes ``the left
sector.'' The rules, however, remain contemporary and the games
will count in the pennant races in this century.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion, which could be dubbed the All-Stars Meet ``Star
Wars,'' is meant as a lighthearted counterpart to the ``Turn Back
the Clock'' games that have long been popular at ballparks
nationwide, when teams revert to their long-ago apparel. One such
game was played on Saturday when the New York Mets wore vintage
uniforms to commemorate their World Series victory in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   In a fast-forward flash-ahead, the Mets will pretend to move for
a ``Turn Ahead the Clock'' game in Shea Stadium next Tuesday
between the Pittsburgh Pirates and the ``Mercury Mets.'' And you
thought the Dodgers had a long schlep when they left Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion _ involving 22 of the 30 major-league teams
playing 14 games _ is indicative of efforts by large marketers to
help build their brand images through campaigns that supplement
traditional advertising measures like commercials and print
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to elevate our brand visibility,'' said Steve Savino,
senior vice president for marketing, products and services at
Century 21 Real Estate Corp. in Parsippany, N.J., a unit of Cendant
Corp. Century 21 is sponsoring the promotion as part of a two-year
partnership with Major League Baseball signed in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to more clearly define our brand's personality and
identity,'' Savino said at a news conference Tuesday at the
baseball office in midtown Manhattan, ``to position Century 21 as
cool, state-of-the-art, forward-thinking _ not how people have
traditionally thought of real estate companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make our brand more approachable,'' he added,
``to help reduce the apprehension people feel when they're buying
or selling a home. And one way to do that is to make the brand more
fun.'' That's also why new ads for Century 21 by Lowe &AMP;
Partners/SMS in New York _ part of the Lowe Group unit of
Interpublic Group of Cos. _ takes a humorous tack.
</P>
<P>
   Century 21 is spending about $2.5 million a year for its
baseball sponsorship, including other promotions like the Home Run
Derby at the All-Star game last week. The company is spending about
10 percent of its annual marketing budget of $45 million to $50
million on promotions, Savino said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Turn Ahead the Clock'' promotion is based on a game played
on July 18, 1998, at which the Seattle Mariners prematurely
celebrated their 50th anniversary by decking themselves out as if
it were the year 2027. Steve McKelvey, vice president for marketing
at PSP Sports in New York, developed the idea of turning that local
promotion into a national one for Century 21 to sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   For the trial game last month in Anaheim, Calif., and the 13 to
come in cities like Baltimore, Chicago, Denver, Detroit and St.
Louis, the turned-ahead calendar is being turned back to 2021. Why
that odd number? Well, if you guessed it's because Century 21 is
the sponsor, you can serenade your friends by mixing ``Take Me Out
to the Ball Game'' with the theme song from ``The Jetsons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Century 21 intends to be more aggressive marketing its
brand,'' said Tim Brosnan, the baseball senior vice president for
domestic and international properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our partnership is a new one,'' he added, ``but it's one
that's indicative of the types we intend to form going forward.''
Other corporate sponsors include Anheuser-Busch, Gillette and
Mastercard International.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion is also ``a recognition by baseball of the market
reach that companies like Century 21 give us,'' Brosnan said, ``in
bringing baseball to the casual fan, to the fan who doesn't go to
the ballpark too often.'' To further woo such fans, the ``Turn
Ahead the Clock'' games will include give-aways of futuristic team
caps and auctions of autographed game jerseys, with part of the
proceeds donated to charities.
</P>
<P>
   The 21st-century-flavor togs were designed by Major League
Baseball; the participating teams; the athletic division of Russell
Corp., which provides uniforms to teams; New Era Cap Co., which
provides caps, and Century 21. Each team will get about 60 of the
fanciful outfits, at a cost of $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Among the eight teams not taking part in the promotion are the
Chicago Cubs, Los Angeles Dodgers and New York Yankees, all
considered to be among baseball's more tradition-minded franchises.
Some already had their promotional calendars filled for the 1999
season, Brosnan said, and some perceived the promotion ``a little
different'' from what they typically do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider it to be extraordinarily successful'' that 22 of
30 teams would take part, he added.
</P>
<P>
   A preview of the outfits yielded mixed results. Most teams
outlined their logos in silver. Some will wear striking
reinterpretations of their current clothing. The Cleveland Indians
will keep their venerable mascot, Chief Wahoo _ a prediction that
the club intends to keep ignoring complaints he is racist?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most way-out look, literally and figuratively, will
be for the Mets, who are replacing the ``NY'' logo on their caps
with the symbol for Mercury as they rename the franchise for the
one game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are ``poking fun'' at franchise moves with the
renaming, Brosnan said. ``It's the ultimate expansion team,
perhaps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1900EDT &QL; 
