<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7462 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICIAL-ATTITUDE-TEX     07-20 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICIAL-ATTITUDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYWRIGHT HAS THE `ATTITUDE' FOR A MUSICAL
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: diannetucker is cq) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Who said that somber subjects can't be
turned into a musical?
</P>
<P>
   That person hasn't seen a whole slew of musicals on Broadway
recently, from ``Parade'' to ``Side Show.'' And wait until they get
a load of what Dallas playwright diannetucker has cooked up, with
the help of Joe Rogers, for Fort Worth's Jubilee Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The show's title, ``Attitude, Girlfriend, Attitude,'' hints that
it's a musical full of sass and ``go-on-girl!'' snaps. And it is.
</P>
<P>
   But the premise is one not many people would find humor in. And
the only reason diannetucker saw the sunny side is that it really
happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several years ago, I got a call to come to Parkland
Hospital,'' she says. ``A friend of mine had been in a car accident
and hit her head on the windshield. She had a slight case of
amnesia. She was not living in Dallas anymore, so I was surprised
when I got a call from Parkland.''
</P>
<P>
   The story follows the experience to a T. The victim's three
``best friends'' show up and find that not only is she in town
without telling them, but she is with a man who is not her husband.
To make matters worse, that man has a wife who shows up to check on
his less-severe condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people wouldn't have found this funny,'' the playwright
says. ``And it wasn't, but the way (the hospitalized friend)
responded to us was highly comedic.''
</P>
<P>
   Diannetucker is in the middle of an oral five-year contract with
Jubilee. In the past three years, the company has premiered her
plays, ``Hershey With Almonds,'' ``Daddy's Maybe'' and ``Madam
Queen,'' in that order. All are dramas with nice comic touches
thrown in. Like ``Attitude,'' all center on strong female
characters, the hallmark of diannetucker's work. ``Hershey'' is
about a woman who compares men with chocolate, ``Daddy's'' focuses
on a single mother, and ``Madam'' was based on a true story about a
wealthy black woman in the early 20th century who controlled the
lives of everyone around her, including the men.
</P>
<P>
   When Jubilee executive director Rudy Eastman asked diannetucker
if she had a musical in mind, she responded, ``I've always wanted
to write something about this experience I had in a hospital one
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastman hooked her up with frequent Jubilee collaborator and
musician Rogers, whom she had met a few months before, and they put
the idea in motion. ``I have so much admiration for Joe Rogers,''
she says. ``And we worked remotely so well. I could e-mail him
ideas and suggestions and I had so much trust and confidence. I had
no questions with his ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a hilarious and touching musical about the power
of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Diannetucker has used her unusually spelled name for 25 years,
since she pledged Alpha Kappa Alpha at then North Texas State
University. (The members were required to sign their names with
lowercase letters, and she found it easier to write it as one
word.) But she has been doing theater her whole life.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Marshall, Texas, where she would put on plays on
her grandmother's front porch. ``On Saturday mornings, all the
neighborhood women would gather and I'd put on a show. And they'd
give me a quarter or something for my effort.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, she started the Dallas Drama Company, mainly as a forum
to get her own plays produced. ``I thought, I'll do this and
instantly I'll be famous,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The company folded 10 years later, but she didn't fade from the
scene. She has worked with other organizations, such as the Irving
Arts Council, but is best known for her association with Jubilee.
Many of her shows there received extended runs.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not writing, she's leading ``whole-brain thinking''
seminars and workshops on leadership skills, diversity and
creativity. For research in writing, she attends every local
theater production, from equity houses to community theater. ``For
me, it's like a doctoral program, getting exposed to all this
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   For future projects, she's working on a piece called ``Dear
Crooner'' and has long harbored a fantasy for writing something
about Solomon and Sheba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of ideas all the time. Someone might be talking, and
I'm thinking of something else. I have to race for a pencil. You
can't control the muse.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
