<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-OF-FRIENDS-KENNEDY-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate is transmitting a TIMELY article
titled ``BEST OF FRIENDS: CHRISTIANE AMANPOUR ON JOHN F. KENNEDY
JR.,'' which was created from a transcript of the TV news show ``60
Minutes.'' The show, telecast July 18, featured an interview by
Mike Wallace with Christiane Amanpour, chief international
correspondent for CNN and special correspondent for ``60 Minutes,''
who recalled her friendship with John F. Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Kennedy and Amanpour were students at
neighboring colleges in Rhode Island, and they became close
friends.
</P>
<P>
   The article is available for oneshot purchase.
</P>
<P>
   (FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION, SEE BELOW.)
</P>
<P>
   From the article ...
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE: Did the two of you ever talk about what you wanted to
be when you grew up?
</P>
<P>
   AMANPOUR: I was very clear from the beginning. I came to the
United States from Iran ... knowing that I wanted to be a foreign
correspondent. So when I came to college, I knew, and also I'm
about three years older than him so I had a much clearer idea.
</P>
<P>
   With John, everybody has always tried to project what they think
he should be. So everybody leapt to the inevitable conclusion that
he will be an office holder and president of the United States, if
he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   ... But, of course, whenever we asked him that question, `What
will you be? What do you want to be?' he used to say `Oh, shut up,
Chrissy,' you know, and `I don't want to talk about that kind of
stuff.' He never sort of bought in or never allowed himself ... to
be swept away by other people's projections and other people's
image of what he should be or what he shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   The article is slugged BC-KENNEDY-CLOSE-FRIEND-INTERVIEW-NYTSF
and has been sent to category codes ``a'' general news and ``k''
commentary news.
</P>
<P>
   FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION: Contact Sales Representative Debra
Weydert by phone, (732) 390-4480, or fax, (732) 390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
