<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KENYA-MALARIA-ART-N     07-20 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KENYA-MALARIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYA ALARMED AS MALARIA INVADES HIGH ELEVATIONS WHERE IT WAS ONCE
RARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISII, Kenya _ Ward 6 in the hospital here could not be much
more crowded: Bethsheba Bosibori, 52, lay in bed with a woman she
did not know, with another sitting at her feet and a third coughing
on a mat on the floor. In all, 113 women were packed into a room
with 23 beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are small, there can be three'' in a bed, said Sister
Elizabeth Maranga, a nurse. ``Big bodies _ only two.''
</P>
<P>
   Kisii, a small city in western Kenya, is the center of a serious
outbreak of malaria, one of the worst in recent years, and all the
more worrisome to experts because malaria has not usually been a
widespread problem here. At an altitude of nearly 6,000 feet, Kisii
had been considered too high for the mosquitoes that harbor the
parasites that spread the sickness to live very long.
</P>
<P>
   But since May, more than 300 people have died of malaria in this
regional hospital alone, among some 18,000 cases the staff has
seen. Several hundred more _ no one is sure how many _ have died
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   One million people die in Africa each year from malaria, the
second biggest killer on the continent, after AIDS, according to
the United Nations. The problems in Kisii underscore how the
disease is changing and spreading on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons not fully understood, doctors say, the disease seems
to be moving to higher altitudes and to other places where
transmission has been low. Resistance to various drugs used for
treating the disease, particularly chloroquine, is also rising
steeply.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual rain patterns since the El Nino storms last year also
seem to be driving the numbers upward. In Kisii it rarely rains
this time of year, but on a recent day, it poured down, draining
into pools of water that stagnate and breed the mosquitoes that
carry the malaria parasite.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think it will disappear, then it rains again,'' said
Dr. Wycliffe Mogoa, a pediatrician and the medical superintendent
at Kisii District Hospital. ``There will be more stagnant water,
the mosquitoes will hatch and there will be problems again.''
</P>
<P>
   The rains have been so irregular that the outbreak has stretched
out for longer than three months. Last year, the worst year in
memory for malaria in Kenya because of the El Nino rains, the
outbreak here lasted only a month and a half, Mogoa said.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak has been especially hard on children and on women
weakened from recent childbirth. But no one is immune. On a recent
day, on a hill in a village near here, Machoge Akunga, a farmer
about 50 years old, lay dead under a gray blanket on a straw mat,
his wife and sister waiting next to the body inside their hut. He
had 11 children.
</P>
<P>
   His family said he came down with a headache, fever and
dizziness, and his joints became sore, all symptoms of malaria. But
they did not take him to a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem serious,'' said his niece, Kemunto, 26. Three
days later, at noon, he died.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say both lack of information about malaria and poverty
help it spread, and both problems were evident at Akunga's hut. His
cousin, Samuel Kebwarwo, also has malaria but said he was turned
away from a hospital because he could not afford treatment, which
costs a little more than $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd of perhaps two dozen people there, no one could say
exactly how malaria was spread or how to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have experience,'' Akunga's niece said to visitors,
``maybe you can explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cases of malaria in the highlands of western Kenya have been
rising slowly over the last five years, including in Kisii, and it
remains a mystery exactly why, said Col. Ronald Rosenberg,
commander of the U.S. Army Medical Research Unit, which is studying
malaria in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   One possible theory that appears not to be borne out is global
warming, which would theoretically create better conditions for
mosquitoes, he said. An analysis of 65 years of hospital admissions
in the nearby town of Kericho, at roughly the same altitude as
Kisii, showed that climate was unrelated to the number of malaria
cases reported.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg said he believes drug resistance and unusual rains, at
least in the last two years, are major reasons. He theorized a
third: that public transportation has improved, and people in the
highlands are traveling more often to malaria-infected areas and
returning sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of a sociological explanation that may have some
truth to it,'' he said. ``It's probably not everything but it could
be a contributing factor.''
</P>
<P>
   But what makes the disease worse still _ often to the point
where it cannot be treated _ is that people often take only pain
relievers or go to herbalists or even quacks, cheaper than most
real doctors, said Dr. Bart De Porter, field coordinator in Kisii
for the French branch of Doctors Without Borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it works, they don't come to us,'' De Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   International aid groups have camped themselves in Kisii,
sending in doctors like De Porter as well as drugs and mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the outbreak has become a political issue. Local
politicians have accused President Daniel arap Moi of purposely not
controlling the epidemic as a way of punishing one of his most
formidable challengers, former Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae. He
represents this district in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   To show his concern, Moi toured the hospital here earlier this
month, and it was bursting with patients _ 800 people were here,
when the capacity is only 250. Aid organizations say that the
medical staff at a nearby government health center was beefed up
only briefly, seemingly as a show for his visit.
</P>
<P>
   But Mogoa said the government has responded well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president had come to assess a serious epidemic in good
faith,'' he said. ``And instead of local politicians joining him,
they are making noise, and in the end they have never stepped foot
in this hospital, which belongs to them. You can't play politics
with an epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Still Kenya's health officials say they do not have enough
drugs, doctors or transportation to cope with the crisis. In
frustration, they are focusing their hope on better education about
malaria in the future _ which drug companies and some international
health agencies and researchers hope someday will also include a
vaccine and aid groups hope will include greater use of preventive
measures like mosquito nets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, doctors say that July is shaping up to be the worst
month yet this year. On a recent evening, an 8-year-old boy,
Richard Mukuya, lay in a malaria-induced coma, his hand held by his
father, Anthony. Mrs. Bosibori lay in the crowded women's ward and
said many people she knew were infected with malaria, including
several of her grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen so many people sick with malaria,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At nightfall, a hard and steady rain began, the drops pounding
on the ward's tin roof, making it impossible to hear anything else
and dripping into yet more puddles for mosquitoes to breed and
spread sickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very bad news,'' De Porter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
