<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-RUSSIANS21-COX     07-20 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIANS21-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   EXCHANGE PROGRAM TEACHES FUTURE RUSSIAN LEADERS ABOUT DEMOCRACY
</P>
<P>
   650. Moving on international and national wires.
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Deans
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Hoping to widen Russia's circle of pro-democracy
disciples at a critical moment in the country's post-Soviet
struggle, Congress is spending $10 million to send 2,000 budding
Russian political figures on a journey across the American
heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Some 150 of them are bound for Atlanta, where they'll each spend
a week living with a local family and meeting with area political
and civic leaders, under the sponsorship of the Atlanta-based
Friendship Force.It's the 22-year-old organization's single-largest
Russian exchange program in nearly a decade, executive director
George Brown said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the cultural exchange program that brought to Atlanta 300
citizens from various walks of life in the former Soviet republic
of Georgia in 1990, this program targets rising political and
government leaders in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to have an impact on the political and economic
evolution in Russia, then these are the key people,'' said Brown.
``These are the future leaders of Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are expected to visit Atlanta in 10 groups of about
15 participants during staggered trips between mid-August and the
end of September.
</P>
<P>
   The Friendship Force, a non-profit organization that promotes
international cultural exchange, has enlisted a number of
Atlanta-area host families for the Russians, and is looking for
several dozen more, said Brown, who was here for a Capitol news
conference to announce the Russian Leadership Program.
</P>
<P>
   The program is the brainchild of Russian scholar James
Billington, the Librarian of Congress. Concerned that Russia's deep
economic woes and its geopolitical uncertainty could press the
country's democratic reforms into retreat, Billington urged
Congress to provide funding to bring a new generation of political
leaders from Russia to this country. Here, the Russians could
experience firsthand the workings of U.S. political and civic
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a $10-million program to send groups of Russians
to all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest-ever, one-time visitation program to bring
current and future Russian leaders to the United States,'' said
Billington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a process of exposure,'' said Billington. ``I think it
will enable people better to understand how this kind of society
functions.''
</P>
<P>
   The government of Russian President Boris Yeltsin backs the
program, anticipating that it will help to cement public support
for the painful economic and political reforms the country has been
undergoing since the collapse of the Soviet Union in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that it will lead to better relations between our
countries and between our two peoples,'' said career diplomat Yury
Ushakov, the Russian Federation's ambassador to the United States.
``It has become especially essential in the context of the current
stage of U.S.-Russian relations.''
</P>
<P>
   That relationship only began to right itself last month after a
spring of deep strains over the U.S.-led NATO air campaign against
Yugoslav military forces in the province of Kosovo. Russians have
close historical and cultural ties to their Slavic kin, the Serbs,
the dominant ethnic group in Yugoslavia's main state of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's domestic ills, combined with a rise in anti-American
sentiment stemming from the NATO strikes, have sparked fears in
this country that Russian voters could reject pro-democracy
reformers and back a less democratic or perhaps even an
authoritarian regime in parliamentary elections scheduled for
December.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Ak., a supporter of the Russian Leadership
Program, said he would soon introduce legislation proposing that
Congress make the program a continuing project. He said he would
propose spending between $15 million and $20 million a year to
bring up to 3,000 Russians to this country annually.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
