<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7502 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS &LR;      07-20 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA RESETS SHUTTLE LAUNCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ NASA on Tuesday prepared for a second
attempt to launch the shuttle Columbia with the Chandra X-ray
Observatory, perhaps the only opportunity it will have to begin the
much delayed mission until next month.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency targeted the second attempt from the Kennedy
Space Center at 12:28 a.m. EDT Thursday. There is a small chance of
rain forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning's launch attempt was halted by a ground
controller at seven seconds from liftoff when a sensor in the
shuttle's rocket engine compartment picked up a potential leak of
explosive hydrogen fuel. Shuttle engineers determined there was no
leak, just a faulty sensor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lay out the data in hindsight, it looks like we have
a data problem with one of our hazardous gas detection systems,''
said &UR;  &LR; Ralph Roe, the NASA launch director. ``It was not a real
leak.''
</P>
<P>
   The console operator who monitors the detection system from
Kennedy's launch control center stopped the count as he saw the
hydrogen levels rise to 640 parts per million, more than twice the
limit. Engineers believe the sensor reacted improperly to a
pressure change in the engine compartment as it was ventilated
during the final seconds of the countdown.
</P>
<P>
   The effort required to recalibrate the sensors and replace an
igniter system that burns off stray hydrogen vapors, which can
accumulate in the exhaust trench of the shuttle's launch pad,
prohibited another liftoff attempt Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's attempt may be the last for Columbia until
mid-August, though the space agency was negotiating with the Air
Force and Boeing for another opportunity Friday night, if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chandra at this point is a very high priority for us, and at
the first opportunity we will launch it when we can safely do so,''
said Don McMonagle, chairman of NASA's mission management team.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force operates the ground radar tracking facilities that
are required to ensure that commercial as well as NASA and military
rockets do not stray over populated areas. Boeing has reserved the
use of the one-of-a-kind facilities Saturday for the launching of
an expendable Delta rocket with four communications satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force then plans to suspend all launching until Aug. 12
so that it can upgrade its tracking network.
</P>
<P>
   Originally scheduled for last August, Chandra's launching has
already been postponed by a succession of difficulties. They
include problems with the satellite's flight control software,
electronic circuitry and most recently the propulsion system that
is to loft it to an orbit higher than it can reach with the shuttle
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Columbia's launching was halted early Tuesday a
half second before its three rocket engines ignited. A shutdown
following the ignition would likely have required technicians to
replace all three shuttle engines, an operation that takes at least
a month.
</P>
<P>
   Had that happened, Chandra's launching could have been delayed
until late 2000. The oldest of NASA's shuttles, Columbia is already
overdue for a yearlong overhaul. None of the other orbiters has the
room in its cargo bay for the telescope and its propulsion system.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's flight will also mark the first command of a space
mission by a woman, veteran astronaut Eileen Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The milestone drew a number of prominent onlookers, including
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, her daughter, Chelsea, and the
U.S. womens' soccer team, victors in recent World Cup play.
</P>
<P>
   NASA said it felt no undue pressure to launch in response to the
presence of a prominent audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response the team has to a problem is independent to any
high level public appearance. We're proud of the team's capability
to operate without being influenced by that,'' McMonagle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole crew salutes the vigilance and professionalism of
the launch team, and we fully support the decision they made,''
Collins added. ``We will be ready whenever.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton departed Cape Canaveral after the scrub, but
NASA made preparations to receive the first lady if she elected to
return.
</P>
<P>
   Chandra is the center piece of a $2.8 billion mission. The
observatory was developed so astronomers can study black holes,
stellar explosions and galactic collisions and their influences on
the evolution of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   If Columbia lifts off successfully early Thursday, Collins and
crewmates Jeff Ashby, Catherine ``Cady'' Coleman, Steve Hawley and
Michel Tognini would attempt to deploy the telescope later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
