<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HONORS KENNEDY'S LEGACY IN HONORING ASTRONAUTS, URGING
PASSAGE OF NUCLEAR TREATY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a daylong salute to President Kennedy's
policies, President Clinton on Tuesday marked the 30th anniversary
of the Apollo moon landing, pressed the Senate to pass a
comprehensive test ban treaty and urged lawyers to renew their
commitment to racial justice.
</P>
<P>
   The repeated nod to Kennedy timed to coincide with a series of
historic anniversaries also came as the nation mourned the death of
John F. Kennedy Jr., the former president's son, from a weekend
plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   The president held an Oval Office meeting with the three Apollo
11 astronauts _ Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins _
to celebrate the first moon landing in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, he appeared in the Rose Garden to call on the
Senate to vote on the treaty banning nuclear weapons testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Kennedy, who set a goal of putting a man on the moon
by the late 1960s, was committed to using technology to unlock the
mysteries of the heaven. But President Kennedy was also concerned
that technology, if misused, literally could destroy life on
Earth,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted Kennedy was the first to negotiate a limited
test ban treaty, barring all but underground testing. But he said
for too long nations have failed to ban all testing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on opponents to the 1996 Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty to at least allow Senate hearings on the issue. The treaty
has been stymied by conservatives such as Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major nuclear powers, Britain and France, Russia and
China, have signed the treaty. Do we want to walk away from a
treaty under which those countries and scores of others have agreed
not to conduct nuclear tests? I believe it is strongly in our
interest to ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said 151 nations have signed the treaty and 41 have ratified
it. Pakistan and India, two rivals that exploded nuclear devises
last year, are being pressured to sign the treaty by the United
States and others.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton spoke to a gathering of lawyers from the American
Bar Association in a session patterned after Kennedy's East Room
address to the same group 36 years ago Wednesday. Clinton renewed
Kennedy's call for the lawyers to fight for racial justice at the
height of the civil rights battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Vice President Johnson and Attorney General Robert
Kennedy at his side, the president asked the lawyers there to
remember their duty to uphold justice, especially in places where
the principles of justice had been defied,'' Clinton said. ``I ask
you here today because we need your help as much as ever in our
most enduring challenge as a nation, the challenge of creating one
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on the lawyers not only to renew their commitment
to racial justice issues but also to increase the hiring of
minorities within their own firms.
</P>
<P>
   He also asked them to support the administration's New Market
Initiatives to provide tax incentives to businesses moving to
depresses regions and the administration's education proposals to
hire more than 100,000 classroom teachers, which the Republican
Congress wants to scrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle for one America today is more complex than it was
36 years ago. For then there was the clear enemy of legal
segregation and overt hatred. Today the progress we make in
building one America depends more on whether we can expand
opportunity and deal with a whole range of social challenges,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also noted that overt discrimination remains. He pointed
to the white supremacist spree killer in Indiana and Illinois, the
dragging death of James Byrd Jr. in Jasper, Texas, and the murder
of gay college student Matthew Shepard in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's honoring of Kennedy's legacy was planned prior
to the deaths of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn, and her
sister Lauren Bessette. Clinton made no mention of the plane crash
but in previous days spoke at length about the nation's sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
