<SLUG> BC-MARKET-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH STOCKS LEAD SHARP DROP IN PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices declined sharply Tuesday on worries that
conditions couldn't get much better _ and could get worse.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff was led by such bellwether technology issues as
Microsoft, Lucent Technologies and IBM _ stocks that have enjoyed
enormous gains so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the market was altitude,'' said Al Goldman,
chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards Inc. ``The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 is up 9 percent in the last eight weeks, and many
technology stocks are up 30 percent to 40 percent. This looked like
very normal profit-taking in a market where high-tech stocks were
due for some blood-letting.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the major market indexes, the technology-heavy Nasdaq
composite index bore the brunt of the damage. Led by Microsoft,
Cisco Systems and Intel, the Nasdaq suffered the fourth-largest
point decline in its history. It fell 98.11 points, or 3.5 percent,
to 2,732.18. Even with the drop, so far this year the index is
still up 24.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, big point drops in a handful of stocks _ IBM,
Hewlett-Packard, American Express and J.P. Morgan _ contributed
heavily to a 191.55 point decline in the Dow Jones industrial
average. The blue-chip index closed at 10,996.13, down 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, America Online and EMC were heavy losers among the
stocks that comprise the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. The S&AMP;P
fell 30.55 points, or 2.2 percent, to 1,377.10.
</P>
<P>
   Even small stocks got hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller-cap companies fell 7.82
points, or 1.7 percent, to 453.55.
</P>
<P>
   While sessions like Tuesday's are unpleasant, they are not
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last five years, there have been 30 times, including
today, when technology stocks have declined 3 percent or more and
the Dow has dropped by more than 1 percent,'' said Laszlo Birinyi,
who heads his own stock-market research firm in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may think this is the beginning of the end, but it has
happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, there have been four such trading days,
Birinyi added.
</P>
<P>
   Selling began early, and seemed to be tied to strong earnings
reports from Microsoft, Lucent and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and IBM reported strong earnings after Monday's close.
And early Tuesday, Lucent topped Wall Street's expectations with a
45 percent increase in profits. However, all three companies have
seen their stocks go up by more than 25 percent so far this year,
and were ripe for profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   By the close, IBM was down 6 3/8, to 128 1/4. Microsoft fell 5
1/16, to 93 5/16. And Lucent shed 6 57/64, to 69 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year at this time, people were sitting with gains that
many would have considered great for a whole year, only to see them
evaporate in a couple of months,'' said Michael Molnar, a managing
director in retail sales and trading at Salomon Smith Barney. ``So
there is an inclination to lock in some profits.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, which was up strongly after it tapped a top
Lucent executive as its chief executive, fell 5 5/8, to 110 5/8.
American Express fell 5 3/8, to 133 13/16. And J.P. Morgan dropped
4, to 134.
</P>
<P>
   A few stocks bucked the trend, most notably Genentech Inc. The
biotechnology stock began trading Tuesday after Roche Holding AG
sold 16 percent of the company at an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which was initially priced at 97, soared 30, to 127.
</P>
<P>
   And the selloff did not seem likely to postpone the pricing of a
number of other widely anticipated initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Tuesday bankers at Credit Suisse First Boston were
moving ahead with plans to price 9 million shares of Mp3.com, a Web
site named for a technology to compress music.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, demand for the stock was strong enough for the
underwriting syndicate to raise the target price range to $24 to
$26 from an earlier range of $16 to $18 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, paper and forest products stocks rallied for the
third time in the last five sessions on hopes that earnings will
surge as inventories drop, providing companies the leeway to raise
prices.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper was the best-performing Dow stock Tuesday,
gaining 1 3/16, to 54 1/16. And Fort James gained 1 1/16, to 41
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International was another winner. The conglomerate gained 2
3/16 to 103 3/8 after it said its earnings rose 75 percent and
announced a two-for-one stock split.
</P>
<P>
   And Qualcomm bucked the trend on the Nasdaq, rising 4 1/4, to
162 15/16. The developer of the world's second-most-popular
cell-phone technology said earnings and revenues surged in its
fiscal third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues outnumbered
those that rose in price by a ratio of more than 2-to-1. Volume on
the Big Board was a bit heavier than recently, at 758.7 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq stock market, losers beat winners by a margin of
about 2.5 to one. Just over 1 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
