<SLUG> BC-BILL-LANN-LEE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE OFFICIAL, ASIAN-AMERICANS RENEW CONFIRMATION FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Lann Lee, who has served as acting head of the
Justice Department's civil rights division for the past 20 months,
said Tuesday he still wants to be confirmed by the Senate because
it would bolster the clout of his division.
</P>
<P>
   Official Senate approval would help his team of lawyers ``speak
with a louder voice,'' Lee said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's comments came on the eve of the two-year anniversary of
President Clinton's July 21, 1997, nomination of Lee to be the
assistant attorney general in charge of civil rights, the nation's
top civil rights post.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee's nomination stalled in the Senate after some Republican
senators expressed concerns that he would use his position to
advance quotas for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear that the Senate wouldn't vote on the
nomination, Clinton in December 1997 appointed Lee to the job on a
acting basis, which allows him to serve through the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-American groups plan rallies Wednesday on Capitol Hill,
and in San Francisco, Los Angeles, New York City and Salt Lake City
to press for his confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 50, who oversees 270 government lawyers, said Senate
confirmation is ``not important in a personal sense,'' but that he
could do ``a more effective job if I were confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lawyers need to know that the American people support
their work in every way possible,'' Lee said. ``Sometimes our cases
aren't popular. I think it would help the work of the division if
they had a leader who was confirmed by the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of Chinese immigrants, Lee grew up in New York City and
won a scholarship to Yale University and eventually graduated from
Columbia University Law School. He is a former lawyer for the NAACP
Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Clinton met with Lee in the Oval Office along with
civil rights leaders and supporters to underscore his message that
Lee should be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   During his 20-month tenure at the Justice Department, Lee said
he has focused the attention of his staff on combating hate crimes,
fighting housing discrimination and enforcing the Americans with
Disabilities Act, the 1990 landmark civil rights law for the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he has been focusing on hate crimes, the acts of
violence against people because of their race, ethnicity or
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come across these heinous hate crimes that spring up,
it reminds us of how you need stronger civil rights,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said his lawyers have successfully settled many housing
discrimination cases. Housing discrimination is still rampant 31
years after the Fair Housing Act was passed, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of problems with minorities, women and
families being able to buy homes and get loans,'' he said. ``These
are some of the most basic elements of the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee also said his department has succeeded in enforcing civil
rights for 40 million disabled Americans, including enforcing laws
requiring public accommodations for the disabled and adequate
multifamily housing.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, who as chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee has the power to block Lee's confirmation, said
Tuesday he had ``serious questions'' as to whether Lee has misused
the law to promote quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is he has misused the law,'' Hatch said. ``There
are indications he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he was reviewing material compiled by Senate
investigators that indicates Lee ``has been using consent decrees
and litigation to impose unjustified quotas under the law'' on
school districts and churches. Hatch added, ``I like the man very
much. I don't feel good about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, in the interview, said he has ``absolutely not'' used the
law to impose quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quotas are wrong,'' Lee said. ``They are divisive and have not
been used by the division.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Choy, executive director of the National Asian Pacific
American Bar Association, said Lee has been wrongly labeled as a
``quota king'' by critics.
</P>
<P>
   Lee deserves to be confirmed because ``he is more than well
qualified for the job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an ideologue,'' Choy said. ``He's not radically
enforcing civil rights law.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's acting status ``feels kind of second-class'' to Asian-
Americans, Choy said. ``The feeling is that the contributions of
Asian-Pacific Americans to this country are not recognized,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Kwok, who chairs the National Council of Asian Pacific
Americans, a coalition of Asian-American organizations, said Lee's
nomination ``has so much significance to the civil rights community
and the Asian-American community (that) we just cannot cave in and
be defeated on this nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House counsel's office,
said it ``remains a concern of the president'' that Lee's
nomination has not been acted upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly deserves to have the `acting' title removed so he
has the full-fledged position of assistant attorney general for
civil rights,'' Kennedy said. ``It's important to the president and
to many in the country that he be allowed to be confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the Senate's failure to vote on the nomination was
an ``insult to the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To leave somebody in limbo like this is really unfair to (Lee)
and to the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
