<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS LEAD SELLOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US stock market Tuesday experienced its fifth-biggest point
drop this year as anxious investors cashed in their profits,
especially in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which had risen 22 percent
before Tuesday, lost 191.55 points, or 1.71 percent, closing at
10,996.13. The technology-heavy Nasdaq stock index suffered a worse
drubbing: its 98.11-point plunge amounted to a 3.47 percent loss.
That was the Nasdaq's steepest point loss since April 19, when the
index dropped 138.43.
</P>
<P>
   The decline, oddly, came on the heels of better-than-expected
earnings reports at the nation's dominant computer companies,
Microsoft Corp., IBM Corp. and Lucent Technologies. Wall Street
analysts said some investors are grabbing their gains in those
companies, and Internet and other technology stocks, because they
fear such a spectacular performance may not continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an attack on tech,'' said Marshall Acuff, equity
strategist for Salomon Smith Barney, a New York securities firm.
``It's profit-taking. I don't see any more to it than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, for example, reported on Monday that revenues were 29
percent higher in fiscal 1999 than a year ago, but warned sales
growth would slow in 2000. Investors, sensing Microsoft may be
peaking, pulled the stock down 5 1/16 Tuesday to close at 93 5/16.
IBM fell 6 1/4, closing at 128 3/8; Lucent declined 6 57/64,
closing at 69 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology stocks were taken down with them.
Doubleclick, an Internet advertising company, fell 7 3/16, closing
at 87 5/8. Amazon.com, the on-line bookseller, plunged 11 9/16 to
120 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley, chief investment officer for BankBoston Corp.,
attributed Tuesday's drop to a combination of ``a little
profit-taking'' and investors' ``anxiety'' about what Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, may say in
testimony Thursday before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The market also remains jittery about the future direction of
interest rates. The Fed on June 30 raised interest rates a quarter
of a percentage point, to 5 percent, but few investors would like
to see further rate hikes, which could bring an economic slowdown.
``They don't know what he (Greenspan) will say,'' Riley said. But,
he added, ``They're worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley noted the exodus was not limited to technology stocks. The
selloff's impact spread to financial stocks, especially banks, and
health care and oil stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-5 ratio on
the New York Stock Exchange. Composite volume came to 926.13
million shares, compared with 789.81 million the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two weeks have seen a loss of momentum,'' said Ralph
Bloch, chief technical analyst at Raymond James &AMP; Associates. The
disparity between rising and falling stocks marks ``an extreme
warning time.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts were less concerned but hardly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get really excited about the market doing a lot
between now and year-end,'' Acuff of Salomon Smith Barney said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the market's steep losses, some new issues thrived.
Genentech, a biotechnology company partially spun off by Swiss
pharmaceutical Roche, was priced at 97 and ended its first day of
trading on the NNSE at 127. The NYSE Composite index fell 11.30 to
647.27, and the American Stock Exchange composite index fell 11.76
to 805.90.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
