<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-MITCHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDES IN ULSTER DEBATE ACCEPT MITCHELL AS `FACILITATOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Seeking to breathe new life into the stalled peace
process in Northern Ireland, the British and Irish governments
Tuesday dusted off a tried and trusted American trouble-shooter:
George J. Mitchell, the former US senator from Maine.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting for a little more than an hour at 10 Downing St.,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie
Ahern, emerged with Mitchell to say that the former Senate majority
leader will serve as a ``facilitator'' of their review of the
stalemated process.
</P>
<P>
   After appearing with Blair and Ahern at a brief news conference
at Downing Street, Mitchell left to meet with the Ulster Unionist
leader David Trimble, who had met earlier in London with Ahern.
Mitchell is scheduled to meet with other parties Wednesday in
Belfast for an initial round of consultations, take the month of
August off, then resume his shuttle diplomacy in Belfast for
another two or three weeks in September.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the governments hope that Mitchell will have worked
some of the same magic he did in chairing the negotiations that led
to the Good Friday Agreement of April 1998. The peace process has
stalled over the implementation of that agreement, with the Ulster
Unionists demanding that the Irish Republican Army begin disarming
before they will sit in government with Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political allies.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, whose patience and evenhandedness won over the vast
majority of both Protestant unionists and Catholic nationalists in
Northern Ireland, said he hoped that the parties will ``see the
importance of moving this process forward, see the risk of not
doing so, and come together soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the political parties that supported the agreement, the
major risk has already been taken, in that support, and therefore I
believe it's now time to move forward with implementation,'' he
said, demonstrating the same low-key approach and restrained
language that helped bring about compromise in a bitterly divided
society where compromise is often regarded as treason.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell made it clear that he takes the challenge of reviving
the peace process personally. In his recently published book
``Making Peace,'' Mitchell wrote that he dreams of taking his
18-month-old son Andrew to the Northern Ireland Assembly in a few
years to watch debates on ``the ordinary issues of life in a
peaceful democratic society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like and admire the people of Northern Ireland,'' Mitchell
said Tuesday. ``Having been involved there now for more than four
years, I feel more and more like a member of the community. And I
want to do all I can to be helpful to what I now regard my
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mitchell has told the two governments that he has
obligations to his Washington law firm and his wife and young son,
and that his involvement in trying to revive the process cannot be
open-ended.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of fruitless negotiations in Belfast, Mitchell
set a deadline, sequestered the parties, and told the politicians
they would have to reach an agreement or explain to the world why
they failed. A former judge, his jurist tactics paid dividends with
the signing of the agreement. But this time he will seek compromise
away from the glare of publicity and the pressure of deadlines that
accompanied Blair's and Ahern's marathon efforts to secure an
agreement this month.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts collapsed in a sea of recrimination and farce last
week when the Ulster Unionists refused to attend the Northern
Ireland Assembly session at which the 10 cabinet posts were to be
filled for the local government, making the process null and void.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is well-versed in the dilemma over what to do with
paramilitary weapons. Before he chaired the negotiations that led
to the Good Friday Agreement, he chaired the commission that
recommended a compromise to get around a similar dispute that
derailed the peace process in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, Mitchell recommended that disarming begin at
the same time as negotiations, but the unionists rejected it,
refusing to talk to Sinn Fein unless the IRA disarmed first.
</P>
<P>
   The then-British government, which had promised all-party talks
if the IRA called a cease-fire but needed the unionists to maintain
its slim parliamentary majority, sided with the unionists. Saying
it had been lied to, the IRA ended its cease-fire in February 1996,
but reinstated it after Blair's landslide election victory in May
1997. Mitchell by then had been made chairman of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political vacuum created by the stalled process,
there are no obvious indications that any of the main paramilitary
groups are prepared to end their cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
   In calling on Mitchell yet again, Blair and Ahern are hoping
that he can succeed where they failed. Blair acknowledged that his
high-pressure tactics didn't work, but that he took heart from the
public assertions by all the parties that signed the Good Friday
Agreement that it was the only way forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the parties weren't ready last week to do the
agreement, but I think it's obvious in the aftermath that the
parties want to do an agreement,'' Blair said. ``I think the
aftermath has been positive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
