<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-QUALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT QUESTIONS METHOD USED TO MONITOR HOSPITAL QUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a regular hospital inspection, the surveyor from the
national accrediting agency spotted potential trouble in a graph
charting staff performance. But when he got no explanation, he
dropped the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In another hospital, a surveyor expressed surprise that nobody
had pulled the medical records he had requested. But he didn't
insist on getting the requested files.
</P>
<P>
   These and other anecdotes illustrate the ``collegial tone'' and
``nonchallenging manner'' that characterize the nation's principal
mechanism for monitoring hospital quality, federal investigators
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system to control quality in hospitals has some serious
flaws that need to be corrected,'' said George Grob, deputy
inspector general in the US Department of Health and Human
Services. ``If a hospital doesn't want you to find a problem, you
won't find it.''
</P>
<P>
   A four-volume report issued Tuesday by Grob's boss, Inspector
General June Gibbs Brown, is a provocative contribution to an
ongoing national debate about ``collegiality'' versus
``regulation'' as the best way to improve the safety of medical
care.
</P>
<P>
   The movement toward collegiality, which has gathered momentum in
the last several years, adopts an educational approach rather than
a punitive one. It encourages hospitals to report serious errors
with the promise that candor won't result in a black mark on their
public image.
</P>
<P>
   The collegial movement has been led by the Joint Commission on
the Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations, a 48-year-old
private organization deputized by federal statute to certify that
hospitals and other health institutions meet minimum quality
standards for participation in Medicare and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report is a harsh indictment of the
Chicago-based Joint Commission, whose board is dominated by
representatives of hospitals and other health-care groups.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report asserts that the Joint Commission
has tilted too far toward a ``gentler'' approach to hospital
quality control. ``The emerging dominance of the collegial mode may
undermine the existing system of patient protection,'' the
inspector general concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Commission's regular surveys, which Grob called
``tightly scripted,'' are ``unlikely to detect substandard patterns
of care or individual practitioners with questionable skills,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   After accompanying Joint Commission officials on hospital
inspectors, federal investigators noted that surveyors allow the
hospitals themselves to select most medical records for inspection,
``tend to be accepting of information and answers provided by
hospital staff,'' and do ``little probing to determine if surface
appearances describe actual practice.''
</P>
<P>
   They criticized the Joint Commission's reliance on scheduled
surveys that permit hospitals to rehearse and prepare for months in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's emphasis on confidentiality of hospital error
reports comes ``at the expense of public accountability,''
investigators said. ``It leaves the general public with minimal
information about how an incident happened and what, if anything,
is being done to prevent more.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the hard-hitting report sparked objections
from the Joint Commission and the American Hospital Association.
But even they acknowledged the merit of some criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Commission supported the report's call for ``an
appropriate mix'' of scheduled and surprise inspections, timely and
effective responses to complaints and adverse events, better
measures of hospital performance, and more focus on patient safety.
The commission also ``affirms the inspector general's call for
public disclosure'' of hospital performance, noting that it already
makes detailed information available to the public by request and
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clearly opportunities for improvements in the Joint
Commission's accreditation process,'' said Dr. Dennis S. O'Leary,
the organization's president. In fact, he added, the inspector
general's findings agree in part with ``our own internal
self-assessment.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate written response to the report, however, O'Leary
called its criticism of the collegial approach ``unfounded and
unsubstantiated.'' He said all its suggested reforms are either
already in effect or under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The American Hospital Association, in its written response to
the inspector general, sharply disagreed that ``the oversight
pendulum must swing back towards the punitive mode.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mary S. Grealey, the Hospital Association's chief legal
counsel, was more muted in her response Tuesday. ``I think the
question is: What is the value of the collegial approach versus the
`gotcha,' policeman approach?'' she said. ``It's a fine balance,
and we need to collaborate on improving things.''
</P>
<P>
   Other observers agreed that both non-punitive and regulatory
approaches need to be part of the effort to improve hospital
patients' safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that health care organizations and
individuals have to be held accountable and we need regulatory
oversight to do that,'' said Dr. Lucien Leape of the Harvard School
of Public Health, perhaps the most prominent advocate nationally of
a non-punitive approach to quality improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's also no question that you don't get safety by
requiring it,'' Leape said. ``You get safety by creating an
environment in which people work individually and collectively
toward it. And you can't do that in an atmosphere of fear and
distrust. If people are punished then they hide and they're fairly
effective at doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leape said the ``right blend'' involves getting tougher with
institutions while making it safe for individual professionals
within hospitals to report and analyze errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how it can be anything other than some sort of
blend,'' agreed Janet Corrigan, who is directing a two-year Quality
of Care in America Project at the National Institute of Medicine.
``Regulatory approaches put some teeth into the system, but we've
got to have a positive culture within institutions that encourages
and rewards quality improvement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
