<HEADLINE>
A NEW FRANK PERETTI BOOK; NEW DELIRIOUS NOT THE OLD DELIRIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
BOOK REVIEW
``The Visitation'' By Frank Peretti Word Publishing, $24.99
(Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez)
<TEXT>
<P>
   A young Methodist woman encounters a being she supposes is an
angel, seemingly in answer to prayer. A custodian at a Catholic
church is miraculously healed of arthritis by tears from a carved
wooden crucifix. A Pentecostal woman sees an image of Jesus in the
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, a young, bearded man with long hair and a
flowing robe appears in the eastern Washington farming town of
Antioch and begins to perform miracles. He doesn't exactly claim to
be Christ, but neither does he deny it.
</P>
<P>
   The stage is set for author Frank Peretti to launch into his
usual gripping tale of angels battling demons, and wars in the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
   But then Peretti does the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   He gets subtle.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told through the eyes of burned-out former pastor
Travis Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's on the outside looking in, Jordan takes a
skeptical if not cynical view toward organized religion. Through
his protagonist, Peretti takes shots at mainstream, liberal
Protestants, at the excesses of Pentacostalism, at megachurches, at
Catholicism, at Christian jargon.
</P>
<P>
   Just about anyone who has set foot inside a church in the past
couple of years is likely to be offended at some point. But then,
the truth often hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Jordan must become involved. He sets out to learn
the truth about the visitor and along the way he learns _ and
teaches the rest of us _ what it truly means to be a Christian.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the usual Peretti fare, but he's never been better.
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
``Mezzamorphis'' Delirious Sparrow Records (Reviewed by Simon
Gonzalez)
</P>
<P>
   A fresh, youth-oriented, praise-and-worship band from England
hit these shores late in 1997 with the release of ``Cutting Edge.''
The band was Delirious, and the album was a compilation of songs
they had been singing to Christian youth, songs that were on the
soundtrack of a revival in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years later, a band calling itself by the same name
is back.
</P>
<P>
   The name, though, is about the only thing that remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerating the trend that started with ``King of Fools,''
their second album, Delirious has morphed from its
praise-and-worship roots to a thoroughly modern rock band.
</P>
<P>
   That's not necessarily a bad thing. Their goal is to go from
leading worship for youth in the church to evangelizing youth in
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   They just might do it. The album is being released into the
secular market on Virgin Records, and the sound _ aggressive rock
with pop hooks _ should attract an audience. The lyrics could get
that audience thinking about matters of faith.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good thing. It's not good enough, however, to prevent
some of us from lamenting the passing of that praise-and-worship
band.
___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the week
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic city seal pervasively invades the daily lives of
non-Christians and sends a message that they are outsiders.''
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. District Judge Russell Clark, in ruling that the city of
Republic, Mo., must remove the image of a fish from its city logo
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
