<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7529 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     07-20 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKE 'EM UP, RANGERS; BRING IN JUNIOR, AROD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Doug Melvin has become predictably boring.
Every time he's asked, which is daily, he echoes there are no trade
possibilities for the Rangers that] even remotely juice his
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Based on all available current information, Melvin speaks the
truth. But what we also seem to have here is a lack of imagination
from the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin obviously needs help in the Stirring-It-Up Dept., which,
of course, is a personal speciality.
</P>
<P>
   Without even being asked, I volunteered my expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Think big, Doug. Knock 'em on their tails with this deal:
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, Ruben Mateo and Royce Clayton go to Seattle for
Junior Griffey, Alex Rodriguez and outfielder-leadoff man Brian
Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Impossible? Absolutely not. In fact, it's doable, and it
addresses certain needs and concerns of both clubs, starting with
the financial hole Safeco Field in Seattle dug for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   It has got to be a first _ brand-new ballpark opens and the
tenant finds itself immediately $100 million in the red due to
construction cost overruns. Nice planning.
</P>
<P>
   But this financial brainlock left Mariners' ownership publicly
wondering how it could afford new contracts for Griffey and Alex
after the 2000 season. Plus, the overall direction of the Mariners
had already touched off speculation about those two moving on
anyway after next season. If so, why not Arlington?
</P>
<P>
   You already know the baseball resume of a Gonzalez, a Junior and
an Alex. You already know what's expected from Mateo. Like the
Seattle twosome, Juan's contract is up after next season. Juan and
Junior will both turn 30 in the fall, meaning prime years are still
ahead. Rodriguez turns 24 next week.
</P>
<P>
   Juan would give the Mariners one big contract to deal with
instead of two. Mateo would mean several seasons of low pay due to
his rookie status. For the Rangers, there would be close to a
contract wash between what Juan will have coming, and what either
Junior or Alex will eventually be paid.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Mariners don't think they can handle the new Gonzalez
contract, how about Rusty Greer, Jeff Zimmerman, Mateo and Clayton
for Griffey, Alex and Hunter. That's even a cheaper financial
option for the Seattles, along with filling critical baseball
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Think of a Rangers' lineup in August with Hunter leading off,
Alex hitting second, Griffey third, Juan fourth, Rafael Palmeiro
fifth, Pudge Rodriguez sixth, Lee Stevens seventh, Todd Zeile in
the eight hole and Mark McLemore ninth. Who needs pitching, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   I ran all this past Melvin yesterday. I'm not sure if he liked
it or not. He said he'd get back to me in a couple of days, once he
stopped laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates wouldn't like the deal, particularly if he has
heard the rumor on Junior Griffey. The one about any free-agent
deal on him for 2001 has to include the stipulation his father, Ken
Sr., would manage the team.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there are a few problems attached. If Kevin Brown is
worth $15 million a year, which he's not, Junior Griffey is looking
at a new contract averaging $20 million. And the dreaded Scott
Boras, agent for Alex, is already talking about $20 million for his
man.
</P>
<P>
   Just how deep are Tom Hicks' hip pockets?
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Gonzalez contract with the Rangers includes 10 teams
where he won't accept a trade, but Melvin wasn't saying yesterday
if Seattle was included.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you also noticed there are no pitchers involved for the
Rangers. Seattle, of course, has none of value, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   For pitching help, Melvin's only out is either from the minors
or more likely, the free-agent market in the winter. Free-agent
acquisitions for the rotation were already a Rangers objective _
make that the main objective. Seattle has gone nowhere in several
seasons, even with Griffey and Rodriguez. No pitching.
</P>
<P>
   But to add Junior and Alex, plus free-agent pitchers, the
payroll for Hicks goes to ...
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I can't count that high.
</P>
<P>
   But we are talking here about excited butts cramming ballpark
seats in Arlington. And thus far this summer, I don't know what has
been more low-profile _ the yawns about the opening of Cowboys'
training camp or the Rangers being in first place.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, however, maybe Doug Melvin needed a good laugh
on an otherwise slow day at the office.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
