<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-TAXCUTS-BOS &LR;      07-20 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TAXCUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCRAMBLE IS ON TO COME OUT ON TOP IN TAX CUT ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's leaders appear to face the happiest of
conundrums: What to do with a projected $3 trillion windfall over
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   But they are entangled in a tug-of-war over using the whopping
surplus for tax cuts in ways that could define the guiding
principles of their parties, determine the outcomes of federal
elections for years to come, and help shape President Clinton's
place in history.
</P>
<P>
   With the House poised to vote Wednesday on a Republican plan for
the largest tax cuts in nearly a generation, Clinton and
congressional leaders are scrambling for the political high ground
over an issue that could affect every voter's personal finances.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, GOP leaders in the House and Senate are
struggling to stave off revolts by moderate Republicans that could
doom their plans for massive, across-the-board tax cuts. Both the
House and Senate Republican plans would reduce taxes by $792
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But a band of GOP moderates in the House Tuesday proposed a $514
billion tax cut over the same period, a crucial threat to the
Republican leadership because of the GOP's fragile six-vote
majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, calling the larger Republican measure fiscally
reckless, announced opposition to any tax cut greater than $300
billion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't one where you just split the difference,'' said the
White House spokesman, Joseph Lockhart. ``There is a fundamental
economic policy debate that we're engaged in right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the unified Democrats in Congress argue that the
surplus should be targeted at shoring up Social Security and
Medicare as well as providing tax cuts. Democrats raised the
possibility of an exorbitant tax cut leading to the kind of
recession that occurred after Congress, at President Ronald
Reagan's urging, cut taxes by $749 billion in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican tax plan threatens to reverse the robust
economic growth and fiscal responsibility of the last seven years
and replay a re-run of the 1980s-style voodoo economics,'' said the
House Democratic leader, Richard A. Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the tax cuts are necessary to prevent
Washington politicians from using the surplus to expand the federal
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This debate is about downsizing the power of Washington,''
said the chief architect of the GOP plan, Representative Bill
Archer of Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican plans, all income-tax rates would be
reduced by 10 percent over 10 years. Capital-gains taxes would drop
for individuals and businesses. Estate and gift taxes would be
gradually abolished.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to expanding tax credits for education, health and
retirement purposes, the GOP measure would ease the so-called
``marriage penalty'' by raising the standard deduction for couples
who jointly file their income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders, in midday news conferences Tuesday,
tried to persuade their renegade moderate colleagues to abandon
their revolt by predicting the $792 billion plan would be approved
Wednesday. ``We will have the votes by the time we vote,'' said the
House majority leader, Richard K. Armey.
</P>
<P>
   But the moderates, led by Represetantive Michael N. Castle of
Delaware, pressed for the smaller package, which would primarily
target middle- and lower-income families for tax reductions. Castle
described the plan as ``a responsible and reasonable approach
towards handling our nation's good fortunes.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers held a news
conference on Capitol Hill to press a $295 billion Democratic
alternative that is also aimed at reducing taxes for middle- and
lower-income families. Summers warned that the Republican plan
could undo the current economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax cuts that have been put on the table represent a
reversal of course,'' Summers said. ``Confidence is crucial. It is
time for us to make the right and prudent decision.''
</P>
<P>
   With prospects for the House plan growing increasingly
questionable by late afternoon, Speaker J. Dennis Hastert addressed
a closed-door meeting of Republican members and appealed for unity.
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from certain whether Hastert and his leadership
team would prevail. And the possibility loomed that GOP leaders
could postpone the debate if they are unable to ensure victory for
the $792 billion plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
