<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEWIRELESS-COX     07-20 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEWIRELESS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Wireless Networks seeks to offer next stage of technology
</P>
<P>
   By Ernest Holsendolph
</P>
<P>
   c, 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the hottest areas of communications going into
the next millennium lies within the modest environs of the house _
wireless home networks.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless networks that link home computers, telephones, printers
and fax machines are leading the way in making computers and other
devices within the house work better together and more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of the experts, home networks could become one of
the next gold rushes in technology, all based on a new level of
residential convenience that could prove infectious.
</P>
<P>
   And a hometown company _ Norcross, Ga.-based Home Wireless
Networks _ might become the star of that play.
</P>
<P>
   Home Wireless Networks, in business since 1996, is poised to be
one of the leaders in this service.
</P>
<P>
   Already allied with Lucent Technologies, one of the HWN
investors, Home Wireless' equipment is now being tested by
BellSouth and other regional phone companies for compatibility with
the phone network. If they like it, the phone companies could
decide to market the technology along with their phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   An integral part of the HWN effort is Lucent Technologies, an
early investor in the technology, which stands ready to add its
market muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent already supplies many kinds of equipment to phone
companies, such as its own wired home systems, and already has the
big name, the sales force and the ear of distributors to get the
merchandise moving. If the phone companies give the green light for
accepting home wireless systems, Lucent will be able to add that
equipment to its sales inventories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though we mostly deal in wired systems now, which are being
installed in new subdivisions, the wireless systems will certainly
be important for existing houses and for people who prefer that
system for its flexibility,'' said Jim Messenger, a spokesman for
Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   By adding wireless networks to its catalog of items, Lucent will
be able to cover the market better, he said. The market for
communications equipment for the home is huge. Forrester Research,
which examines many technology issues, says that the home market
amounted to more than $22 billion in 1998 and has plenty of
potential for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the major phone companies, in their competition with
cable companies and other communications purveyors, will benefit
from carrying systems that make dependable phone lines more
productive.
</P>
<P>
   What home wireless networks do is extend the use of a phone line
dramatically by allowing several computers to get on the Internet
through one line or to use a single printer. Therefore, for
example, instead of using two cheap printers, one for each
computer, wireless interconnection gives the option of buying a
quality printer with access to several computers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the way it works: A base unit, much like the base unit of
a portable phone, is attached to the phone wire where it enters the
house. This unit can send signals with information from the
telephone wire to facsimile machines or from the Internet to
computers and also send fax and data from computers out over the
phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   The system can also be set up to allow computers to exchange
information within the house, such as swap computer files, or share
a computer game that would be available for several people to play
at once.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that new broadband access, such as cable modems or
DSL (digital subscriber line) technology from the phone company,
means that even more goodies can be brought into the house to be
shared over a wireless network.
</P>
<P>
   The technology used by HWN was put together by two friends,
Stuckey McIntosh and Richard Snelling, back in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   They adapted it from Digital Wireless Corp., a company that
specialized in cordless phone systems.
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh, the idea man, became the initial chief executive,
supported by Snelling, a veteran phone industry man from BellSouth.
A bit later, he came aboard to be the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The company has just begun to make shipments to smaller vendors
and independent phone companies who have signed contracts to be
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   An average home wireless system by HWN costs about $620, but
more elaborate systems to handle up to five phone lines, go for
$1,100.
</P>
<P>
   HWN is not alone in introducing home wireless-type technology.
</P>
<P>
   Others moving into the field from different market directions
include Tut Systems in Pleasant Hill, Calif., and Epigram in
Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, none of these companies stands to suffer much from
competition because the task at hand is to get this new technology
in front of the public and its market, and the more salesmen the
better,'' said Boyd Peterson of the Boston-based Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   Snelling, one of the home wireless founders, retired as
executive vice president of BellSouth in 1991, after 35 years in
the Bell system. He said the phone company was always searching for
``a sophisticated home gateway'' to the phone network. In many
ways, home wireless fits that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that this is a wireless system makes it all the
better,'' said Snelling. ``The rising importance of the Internet as
a source of information makes home networking a convenience people
will want, and the wireless system a product for our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Snelling said he has been a student of home communications
technology ever since he observed the videotext trials conducted
years ago by Knight-Ridder, the media company.
</P>
<P>
   From Home Wireless' perspective, no city is a better home base
for launch than Atlanta, Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the marketing tricks is to sell this technology to the
early adopters, the people who like to be seen with the latest Palm
Pilot and other devices,'' he said, ``and I think in that regard
Atlanta, with its growth and vitality, is an excellent place to
launch this new wireless communication.''
</P>
<P>
   And a successful launch could be the start of something really
big.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market will move very, very quickly, for all the existing
players and more, once the word gets out,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketing is really the key,'' said Barbara Stafford, whose
job is to handle residential and business marketing for Home
Wireless Networks. ``We will be really dependent on the phone
companies to assist in the marketing and the distribution of the
wireless systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the phone companies have taken the first
step. BellSouth and the other regional phone companies, notorious
for taking a long time to clear a new technology, have at least
accepted the Home Wireless products for the extended laboratory
testing that could lead to the
</P>
<P>
   phone companies adopting it for sale and promotion to phone
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Although BellSouth reserved comment until the tests are
complete, Debbie Locker, a spokeswoman for consumer services at
BellSouth, said, ``We welcome any equipment that can make our
consumers' lives better and that can help the home function as an
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, commercial and business users may lead the way to
popular acceptance of the new technology, much as they did with
wireless phones. In one of the commercial applications of the
technology, teams of consultants and contract employees will be
able show up at the office of a new client with their own
communications system. For instance, a consultant team could get
use of one phone line in the client's office, patch it into a base
unit and create a wireless network for use exclusively by the
visitors while they are there, then dismantle it when their project
is completed.
</P>
<P>
   As was true with early cellular communications, the new
technology in the hands of actual users will spawn new, real world
ideas for its use. And once the convenience is recognized and
becomes a habit, the technology will take off, driving down prices
amid competition, and then spurring still wider popularity and
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
