<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA BARBARA AS THE DOWN-HOME NAPA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food &AMP; Wine's  &UR; Merrill Shindler &LR;  claims that Santa Barbara
County is the up-and-coming, down-and-dirty version of the Napa
Valley, at least when it comes to winemaking. The implication is
that the Napa Valley has become something of a wine Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napa has a lot invested in buildings, lots of nice chateaus.
Here it's just a metal building with barrels inside,'' says  &UR; Jim
Adelman &LR; , general manager of Au Bon Climat wines in Santa Barbara
County. ``A lot is spent on winemaking and a lot less on amenities.
We don't have ornate gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Doug Margerum &LR; , owner of Santa Barbara's Wine Cask, says  &LR; Santa
Barbara  &LR; is like Napa was 25 years ago. ``You go to the winery, and
the guy looks at you mean, maybe he doesn't even come to the door.
If he does, maybe he'll open some wine for you, maybe he won't. But
you're actually talking to the guy who makes the wine. He's the
owner. There are no stewardesses in blue blazers giving standard
tours to groups of 20 at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Barbara has an ``outlaw image,'' says  &UR; Krysten Hommel &LR;  of
Cambria Vineyards. ``It's not a tourist destination.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jamie Davies &LR;  of Schramsberg Vineyards near Calistoga said that
``Santa Barbara County is a tourist destination'' and becoming more
so, but ``obviously Napa has gone further down the path.''
</P>
<P>
   She says the issues of agriculture and tourism are ``always a
concern. Our primary use of the land is to grow grapes to produce
wine. The more we invest in tourist facilities, the more difficult
it is to maintain the balance. It is a concern everybody in Napa
has to deal with in terms of how far we can go and still maintain
what we have.'' The particular dilemma she cited is that ``you have
people coming in at all times along the road, and people see what
they like and want to be part of it, and you can't close the
gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, she said, ``I think Napa has probably the best zoning
to maintain the agricultural preserve of anywhere in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUEEN TO HAWK VIDEOS TO BUY OATS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR;  plans to release a video she's made about
raising horses, says the Times of London. A hundred thousand of the
videos will be produced in hopes of raising a million pounds
(that's $1.57 million to you) for the upkeep of the royal stables.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said that the queen will make an effort to appear
``warm'' and ``intimate. ... She fed sugar to the horses and
discussed details of their breeding and bloodlines with her
stable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Victoria &AMP; Albert Museum is interested in buying  &UR; Posh &LR; 
 &UR; Spice &LR; 's $96,000 wedding dress, which was designed by Vera Wang,
reports artnet.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Irresistible names:  &UR; Cinnamon Eclipse &LR; , who was described by
 &UR; Bruce Higton &LR;  as his ``favorite waitperson in our favorite
Sebastopol restaurant, 101 Main.'' Also,  &UR; Lorien Rifkin &LR;  remembers
her Ukiah classmates  &UR; Quail &LR; ,  &UR; Kuchen &LR; ,  &UR; Omaha &LR; ,  &UR; Parsley &LR; ,
 &UR; Harvest &LR;  and  &UR; Leaf &LR; .  &UR; Jennifer Elder &LR;  and  &UR; Lisa Morrill &LR;  both
remember a junior high school classmate,  &UR; Fillmore Love &LR; . And  &UR; Lisa
Ortiz &LR;  remembers the birds of Mendocino ( &UR; Sparrow &LR; ,  &UR; Raven &LR; ,
 &UR; Eagle &LR;  and more) and the famous Flower twins:  &UR; Flower Star Flower &LR; 
and  &UR; Star &LR; 
 &UR; Flower Flower &LR; . And with that, the name game ends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATINAS AND SOCCER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Although Latinos usually are huge soccer fans, the Los Angeles
Times reports that there were relatively few Latino fans for the
Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also notes that there were few competitors from
South American countries, except for Brazil. Half the players on
the Mexican team were Mexican Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's machismo,'' Los Angeles sports commentator  &UR; Manolo &LR; 
 &UR; Cevallos &LR;  said. Latinos ``do not want women to step out of their
feminine role _ the home, children, housework _ because it
challenges the masculine role. The countries that performed the
best (in the World Cup) are countries where women have a greater
role in public life and society _ and so, of course, in soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Her hands can look very white. When told this, she pulled her
top down a little, revealing the tops of her beetle-brown bosoms,
and held her hands up against them. The hands are very white
indeed. `Oh, great,' she said. `I don't know what's wrong with me
now. They do look pale. Sometimes they turn gray, too. I don't
know. I asked the doctor, and he's like, ``Weird!'' ' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; From a US magazine profile of Tori Spelling, who shared her
dismay over the heartbreak of white hands.
</P>
