<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SUGGESTS WAY TO CUT HOSPITAL PHARMACY ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having a pharmacist accompany physicians as they make the rounds
of critically ill patients may help cut hospital medication errors
by as much as two-thirds, according to a study conducted at
Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out that millions of medication errors occur each year,
the study's authors urged hospital officials to consider having a
pharmacist go on medical rounds, in addition to taking other
measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common cause of accidental injury to patients in
hospitals is prescribing error,'' said Dr. Lucian L. Leape, adjunct
professor of health policy at the Harvard School of Public Health
and lead author of the study in the current Journal of the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to say there are millions of medication errors a
year,'' Leape said. While most of the errors are minor, even one
serious injury or death is too many, he added. Some studies,
including an earlier one by Leape and colleagues, have estimated
that between 770,000 and 2 million US hospital patients are injured
each year by medication errors.
</P>
<P>
   The study measured the rates of preventable medication errors at
an intensive-care unit before and after a senior pharmacist was
added to the medical team making the rounds. The rate dropped by 66
percent, from 10.4 such errors for every 1,000 patient days, to 3.5
for every 1,000 patient days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies conducted by Leape and colleagues have found
that more than a quarter of drug-related injuries _ some caused by
errors, some not _ are preventable, and that medication errors can
also be drastically reduced through the use of a computer to take
physician medication orders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the studies, published last year, credited a $1.9 million
computer system at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston with
cutting the medication error rate there by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   But not all hospitals can afford a computer medication
entry-order system like the Brigham's.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggests that a less costly but still effective
alternative is a more intense use of hospital pharmacists, by
either having them accompany physicians on medical rounds or
positioning them on patient floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adequately trained pharmacists on the floor can in fact reduce
the number of preventable drug errors,'' said Harold DeMonaco,
director of drug therapy management at MGH and one of the authors
of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharmacists tend to be somewhat expensive personnel, but there
is a very adequate return on investment _ multiples of the
pharmacists' salary,'' said DeMonaco, a pharmacist himself. He
added that he believes a computer has not yet been designed to take
the place of a well-trained pharmacist, in terms of understanding
complex drug interactions, the merits of one drug over another for
certain patients, and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've documented that putting pharmacists on the floor
actually saves money,'' DeMonaco said. ``It's a good thing for
patients and a good thing for hospitals as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My own feeling is that the pharmacist is the most
underutilized resource in the hospital,'' agreed Leape.
</P>
<P>
   Each preventable medication error costs an estimated $4,685,
according to research by Leape and colleagues. At the
intensive-care unit where the study was conducted at MGH, 58 such
errors a year were estimated to have been prevented, for a total
savings of about $270,000, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the study have led MGH to add more than a half
dozen more pharmacists to the staff. In addition, the hospital has
installed the same computer medication-order system that its sister
hospital, the Brigham, uses, according to DeMonaco.
</P>
<P>
   While the study at MGH provides strong evidence supporting a
more intense use of pharmacists to reduce medication errors, the
authors cautioned that other hospitals may have different results,
depending on such factors as whether physicians make rounds at a
predictable time, thus allowing pharmacists to accompany them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
