<SLUG> BC-TVTOUR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Geller reborn with new `Buffy' season
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Sarah Michelle Gellar isn't real sure where
she's going, but she sure knows where she's been.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the fourth season of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,''
Gellar says she feels as if she's starting a new series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like starting from scratch,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will be profound in Sunnydale, following the season
finale in which most of the cast graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   When the series goes back into production Friday, Buffy Summers
will give up her dream of going away to college and instead stay in
town and attend college there, the better to fight all the undead
and monsters that plague the place. She'll also meet a new
potential romantic interest in psych class. Best buds Xander and
Willow stay in town too.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Giles is gonna become Buffy's love slave!'' Gellar jokes
in her giddy, hyper way.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change will be the departure of Angel (David
Boreanaz), her brooding vampire lover, who's getting a spin-off
series that will follow ``Buffy'' in the fall, also produced by
``Buffy'' creator Joss Whedon. In ``Angel,'' the 244-year-old
vampire, who's ``cursed'' with a conscience, moves to Los Angeles
to help people in need.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-overs are already being planned _ look for Buffy to visit
Angel during November sweeps, but will be kept to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very daunting,'' Gellar says. ``What if I can't do it on
my own? What if I need David? But it's very exciting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gellar, who's 22, is diplomatic about the WB's postponement of
``Buffy's'' finale, which featured violence at a high school, out
of respect for the shootings at Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my place to agree or disagree. I understand it. I
wanted my show to air when it was supposed to air, but God forbid
if anything had happened, I don't see how any of us could have
lived with ourselves,'' she adds, referring to chance that someone
might have tried to copy the final violent scene at the high
school.
</P>
<P>
   She gets even more excited talking about how she spent her
hiatus _ particularly spending a week in the Dominican Republic
building a Habitat for Humanity house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've always wanted to do,'' she says. ``They
didn't know who I was. I made a very good window sill, I laid a lot
of floor, I mixed a ton of cement. I've never had calluses like
that. My fingers were just bloody.''
</P>
<P>
   And for once, it wasn't stage blood.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
