<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7567 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-FUTURE-BOS &LR;      07-20 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE'S SUPPORTERS ARE ON TOP OF THE (MAC)WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Normalcy isn't a word commonly associated with Apple
Computer Inc., a firm that prides itself on its eccentricity. And
yet that's exactly the spirit that prevails in the run-up to the
MacWorld trade show in New York. There's the usual anticipation as
people await an electrifying keynote speech from Apple cofounder
Steve Jobs. And speakers at an Apple ``town meeting'' Tuesday
morning warned of open rebellion if Jobs doesn't announce Apple's
long-awaited low-cost portable Macintosh computer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the attitude here is one of confidence that Apple
Computer is firmly set on its new course. Says Apple analyst Tim
Bajarin of Creative Strategies Research: ``Fundamentally, they're
going to make it a love fest. They haven't had a MacWorld with this
much positive news in quite awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of years ago, the cover of Wired magazine urged
readers to pray for Apple's survival, and Dell Computer Corp.
founder Michael Dell suggested that Apple should close up shop. The
pain of those bitter days has been assuaged by seven straight
quarters of profits and a hit product _ the iMac _ that has become
one of the most successful computer models ever. At this MacWorld,
the fear is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that survival is not high on their list of
priorities right now,'' says Apple-watcher Lou Mazzucchelli of the
New York investment firm Gerard Klauer Mattison. Instead, he said,
Apple is busy making moves to continue the firm's extraordinary
comeback. ``What they need is a continuing stream of base hits,''
said Mazzucchelli, ``and I think they're doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody foresees a return of the days when Apple contended with
Microsoft for total domination of the personal computer business.
The big money, of course, is in the highest reaches of corporate
America, and Apple's presence there is small, and likely to remain
so. So Jobs has stuck to his strategy of stabilizing Apple's core
markets in graphic arts and education, while also reaching out to
consumers with radically designed Macintosh computers for the
masses.
</P>
<P>
   Once criticized for its one-piece, quirky design, the iMac's
popularity has proven a hit with consumers. Better yet, in a world
in which hit products can fade quickly, the iMac just keeps going.
According to Salomon Smith Barney, Apple sold 487,000 of them
between April and June. In addition, sales of Macs to schools rose
22 percent over the same period last year. That's a sign that Apple
may be reasserting itself in the education market _ a segment the
company once dominated, but where it has lost ground to cheap
machines running Microsoft Corp.'s Windows software.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jobs, who after two years on the job still insists on
being called Apple's ``interim'' CEO, last week reported the
company's seventh straight quarterly profit. Much of the $114
million profit came from continued solid sales of the Apple iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the iMac's success, computer software and accessory
makers are suddenly eager to make products for Macintosh computer
users. According to IDG Expo, the Norwood firm that runs MacWorld,
80 percent of the exhibitors at the show will have new products to
offer. For instance, Microsoft Corp. will display a new version of
its Outlook Express electronic messaging software; LucasArts
Entertainment Co. will be showing off Macintosh versions of its
``Star Wars: Episode I'' computer games; and Bell Atlantic will
offer a version of its Infospeed high-speed Internet access service
for Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   But to keep the momentum going, Apple must look beyond the iMac.
The most widely rumored next step is the development of a new kind
of laptop. Apple's PowerBook series is well respected for technical
excellence, but they're heavy and expensive machines that don't
appeal to the mass market. In 1996, before Jobs took the helm in a
boardroom coup, Apple produced the eMate, a simple laptop computer
that had no disk drive and a black-and-white screen, but which ran
for days on a battery charge, was easy to use, and cost just $800.
Jobs killed the product after he came to power. But last year he
vowed to get Apple back into the market for low-cost laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Today (July 21) could be the day. Computer mavens expect Jobs to
announce a new Apple laptop that'll probably come down somewhere
between the PowerBook and the eMate. The rumored machine is
expected to cost somewhere around $1,000, but Apple officials are
extremely secretive about the topic, refusing even to say whether
Jobs will announce any new products today. ``If I told you, I'd
have to kill you,'' said Steve Wilhite, Apple's vice president of
marketing. Indeed, it's possible that the notebook still isn't
ready. Predictions of possible delays jolted Apple's stock price
last week.
</P>
<P>
   There's another long-awaited product that'll almost certainly go
missing _ OS X. The Unix-based overhaul of the Macintosh operating
system promises to be dramatically more reliable than Microsoft's
Windows 98, but such promises have been heard for years and Apple
has yet to deliver. The company has produced a version of OS X for
use on server computers linked to networks, but the version for
desktop users is supposed to appear sometime before year's end. A
skeptical Mazzucchelli predicted it won't show up until 2000. ``So
what?'' he added, saying the product has little chance of stealing
market share from Microsoft anyway. If so, a few months' delay will
only matter to hard-core Mac geeks tired of an operating system
that's showing its age.
</P>
<P>
   However, OS X may already be making a mark. Apple recently moved
to provide free access to the underlying source code at the core of
the product _ the OS X ``kernel.'' This ``open source'' approach
imitates the successful strategy of Linux, the most popular open
source operating system. If Apple's open source software, called
Darwin, becomes popular with programmers, Apple could profit by
selling them add-on software, programming tools, and technical
support.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the Darwin strategy raises the prospect of
Mac-based operating systems running on standard PCs. Open source
programmers routinely ``port'' software written for one type of
machine onto another. Linux, for instance, has been modified to run
on practically every type of computer. If a PC version of Darwin
comes along, it could be the first step in creating a PC market for
Mac software _ a back-door tactic that could further ensure the
long-term survival of the Mac.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
