<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-20 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Focusing on Peace
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. George Mitchell will conduct a ``tightly focused''
review of the halted Northern Ireland peace settlement, Prime
Minister Tony Blair said. Mitchell will meet with party leaders in
Belfast this week, then break for August and resume talks in
September. The parties failed to meet a deadline last week for
starting up the new assembly that divides power between Catholics
and Protestants because of an impasse over guerrilla disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   European Union: Parliament Election
</P>
<P>
   The European Parliament elected Nicole Fontaine of France as the
new president of the 626-member body. Ms. Fontaine belongs to the
center-right Union for French Democracy and to the Christian
Democratic Group in parliament, where she has been a member since
1984. She got 306 votes. Mario Soares, a Socialist and former
president of Portugal, came in second with 200 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Soccer Riot Charges
</P>
<P>
   A court ordered two retired police officials to face trial on
manslaughter charges stemming from a riot in Hillsborough, North
England, in 1989 that killed 96 soccer fans. The victims' families
brought the case against former Chief Supt. David Duckenfield, 54,
and former Supt. Bernard Murray, 57.
</P>
<P>
   France: Questions Over Kickbacks
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Paris, Jean Tiberi, was questioned in court for six
hours in connection with kickbacks allegedly paid by construction
companies, court officials said Tuesday. Magistrates are
investigating whether kickbacks from public housing contracts went
into the coffers of the Rally for the Republic in 1991 to 1994,
when President Jacques Chirac was mayor of Paris and Tiberi worked
for him. Tiberi has not been formally charged.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Indictments in Basque Killing
</P>
<P>
   In the latest case examining a shadowy campaign against Basque
terrorists in the 1980s, a judge in Bilbao, the largest Basque
city, indicted a former Interior Ministry official, Julian
Sancristobal, and eight others for their roles in the killing of a
Basque leftist leader, Santiago Brouard, in 1984. Meanwhile,
Spain's highest court ordered the release of 22 leaders of a Basque
leftist coalition who were sentenced in November 1997 to seven
years each for collaborating with separatists.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Indians Sentenced
</P>
<P>
   Twenty Indian villagers were each sentenced to 35 years in
prison for killing 45 rebel sympathizers in the hamlet of Acteal in
Chiapas state in December 1997. Trials are scheduled for an
additional 81 people accused in the killings. The villagers were
from a pro-government group armed by the Mexican Army and the
police.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Open Books
</P>
<P>
   Humberto Roque Villanueva, one of four politicians seeking the
presidential nomination from the governing party, known as the PRI,
urged the party to allow public scrutiny of the finances of
President Ernesto Zedillo's 1994 campaign. The government and the
party have blocked investigations. ``I'm sure there's nothing to be
embarrassed about,'' Villanueva said.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Iran: A Warning to Moderates
</P>
<P>
   Commanders of the Revolutionary Guards have warned President
Mohammad Khatami that they are running out of patience with his
moves toward political and social reform and blamed him for
encouraging sentiments that exploded in last week's pro-democracy
protests. The warning, first made in a July 12 letter to Khatami,
was made public by the Kayhan newspaper, a reliable barometer of
conservative sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem: Changed Residency Policy
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, Israel's new interior minister, said he wanted
to stop the policy of stripping Palestinians of residency rights if
they leave Jerusalem for more than seven years. Critics have called
the policy a ``quiet deportation'' of Arabs from the city that
Israel claims as its capital. Sharansky said that ``a united
Jerusalem'' must treat all residents equally.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: 7 Killed in Squatter Camp
</P>
<P>
   Seven African National Congress supporters were shot dead late
Monday in the Mandela Park squatter camp in Katlehong, east of
Johannesburg. Witnesses said they suspected members of the rival
United Democratic Movement, but a local party leader said
``criminals'' were exploiting political tensions and asked for an
inter-party meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
