<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFC-COFFEE-COX     07-20 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFC-COFFEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seattle's Best Coffee opening in Japan
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Seattle's Best Coffee Tuesday announced two major
deals to open 167 cafes in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   This is the company's first major entry into the lucrative
Japanese market. The company has sold its coffee in Eddie Bauer
stores in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strong and growing familiarity with not only the
brand, but American coffee,'' said President Jim Clarke. ``Right
now we're reviewing a variety of different real estate locations
ranging from department stores to street-side locations.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Best Coffee is a subsidiary of Atlanta-based AFC
Enterprises, which also owns Churchs Chicken, Popeyes Chicken &AMP;
Biscuits and Cinnabon International.
</P>
<P>
   The development agreements are with Nippon Brunswick Co. Ltd.
and Osaka-based Mifune Corp. Nippon Brunswick is a joint venture
between Tokyo-Mitsui &AMP; Co. Ltd., one of the world's largest trading
companies, and Brunswick Corp. of the United States. The
partnership will develop 100 coffee cafes over five years.
</P>
<P>
   In the other deal, Mifune will open cafes, kiosks and coffee
carts this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has the third-highest coffee consumption in the world,
according to Gary Goldstein, a spokesman for the New York-based
National Coffee Association of the U.S. The United States is first.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second major international deal in recent months.
The company recently announced an agreement with a Saudi Arabian
firm to develop 65 Seattle Best Coffee cafes and Cinnabon bakeries
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
