<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EQUIFAX-COX     07-20 0220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUIFAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Equifax results in line with expectations
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Equifax reported second-quarter earnings
that would have been flat from the year-earlier results if it were
not for a gain on the sale of a stake in a Brazilian company and
some assets in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The results, however, met Wall Street expectations. Also, while
there was an after-tax gain of $2.9 million, or 2 cents per share,
Equifax boosted research and development spending, which affected
earnings. Analyst Gregory E. Gieber of Brown Brothers Harriman
called the latter good for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Equifax, best known for its credit report business, reported net
income of $52.1 million, or 37 cents a share, on revenue of $442.6
million. A year earlier, the company earned $50.6 million, or 35
cents a share, on revenue of $393.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, Equifax said it remains comfortable with Wall
Street's forecast that the company will earn $1.52 to $1.58 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Equifax shares lost 81 1/4 cents to $34.18 3/4
on a down day for the market.
</P>
<P>
   David McNaughton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
