<SLUG> BC-SEATBELTS-BLACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS URGE BLACKS TO WEAR SEAT BELTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal transportation and health officials Tuesday
pledged to spearhead a campaign to encourage blacks to wear seat
belts following a report that young blacks are half as likely as
whites to be buckled in and, hence, twice as likely to be killed in
a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and Surgeon General David
Satcher called the failure to wear seat belts a public safety and
health problem that will continue unless governmental and community
leaders intervene. Ricardo Martinez, head of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration, added that wearing seat belts is a
``simple solution'' to the deaths and injuries in car crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by Meharry Medical College in Nashville, Tenn.,
provided no explanation for the disparity in seat-belt use by
blacks and whites. But the report offered chilling statistics on
the lack of belt use, estimating that 1,300 blacks killed each year
in car crashes would survive if they buckle up.
</P>
<P>
   The study found automobile crashes to be a ``silent epidemic''
among blacks and the leading cause of death among black children up
to age 14. Crashes also are second only to homicide as the chief
cause of death among blacks between ages 15 and 24, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
   Slater, speaking at a a news conference to announce the study's
findings, urged governmental and community leaders to ``give voice
to that silence'' by alerting blacks to wear seat belts. The
transportation secretary also encouraged police to beef up their
enforcement of state laws requiring motorists to wear the belts
under penalty of fines.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said he anticipates criticism of his call for stricter
enforcement, particularly from some blacks who fear police will use
seat-belt laws as a pretext for pulling over black motorists. Black
leaders in many communities have criticized police for allegedly
targeting and even harassing black motorists, who fit law
enforcement's invidious stereotype of drug dealers, the rights
advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   But Slater said the federal government would ensure that police
fairly enforce safety laws while protecting the civil rights of
black motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repeatedly, we see that the violence of crashes is color
blind,'' Slater said. ``All of us, our children and families, are
affected by car crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, seat belts saved 65,290 lives between 1982 and 1994,
according to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
But, while 62.6 percent of all whites reported wearing seat belts
in 1996, only 51.2 percent of blacks buckled up, NHTSA added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The available data show this problem as particularly acute for
African-American males in the 18 to 29 year age range,'' stated the
report by Meharry, a historically black medical college. ``A (1998)
study by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention shows that
seat-belt use has largely `remained stagnant' for African American
males in this age range, while the rest of the population has
experienced an increase in usage rate of about 19 percent from 1987
through 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   Satcher, the federal government's top doctor, called the low
rate of belt use among blacks ``a public health problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that increasing seat-belt use will save thousands of
young lives each and every year,'' Satcher said. ``The more we know
about the particular needs of diverse populations, the more we are
able to develop sound prevention strategies to produce healthy
communities for Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, an emergency room doctor before being appointed to the
highway-safety agency, said, ``The violence of crashes does not
discriminate.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with the three federal officials, Rep. Eddie Bernice
Johnson, D-Dallas and vice chair of the Congressional Black Caucus,
praised Texas' seat-belt law for encouraging people to buckle up.
But, she said, greater efforts must be made to educate blacks _ and
particularly black men _ of the danger of not wearing belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking the first step in getting the word out to use
seat belts,'' Johnson said. In a message directed at black
teen-agers, she added that refusing to wear a seat belt ``isn't
cool, it's foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire is the only state without a law requiring
motorists to wear seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
