<HEADER>
A7584 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOETHE'S-FAUST-$ADV25     07-20 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOETHE'S-FAUST-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT QUITE OPERA, NOT QUITE ORATORIO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 David Mermelstein writes about music for The New Criterion.  
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The classical-music canon does not lack for oddities. Neither
fish nor fowl, works like Debussy's ``Martyrdom of St. Sebastian,''
Richard Strauss' ``Enoch Arden'' and Schoenberg's ``Survivor From
Warsaw'' entice music lovers through their esthetic merits while
confounding with their unconventional structures.
</P>
<P>
   Schumann's ``Scenes From Goethe's `Faust''' is another example.
Though it has elements of both opera and oratorio, it fails to fit
comfortably into either form. Running two hours and requiring full
orchestra and a large chorus as well as vocal soloists, it demands
much from concert presenters and audiences alike, and is thus
something of a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been performed by the American Symphony and the
Orchestra of St. Luke's in the last decade, it was last presented
by the New York Philharmonic in 1973 and has not been heard at
Carnegie Hall since 1891, when the third and last part was given.
(Schumann himself considered the work more effective in partial
performance.)
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers can hear the work Sunday evening, July 25, at Avery
Fisher Hall, where John Eliot Gardiner and the Orchestre
Revolutionnaire et Romantique conclude their four-night Schumann
celebration as part of the Lincoln Center Festival.
</P>
<P>
   For those unable to attend the performance, the Belgian-born
conductor Philippe Herreweghe _ like Gardiner, a stalwart of the
period-instrument school _ has recorded the piece for Harmonia
Mundi France (HMC 901661/2; two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   ``Scenes From Goethe's `Faust''' was first performed in 1862, 6
years after Schumann's death and 30 years after Goethe's. Like
Goethe, who worked on his magnum opus off and on for 60 years,
Schumann labored long over his Faust meditation. Typically a fast
worker, he took nine years to finish this piece, in 1853, a
testimony to the reverence with which he approached the project.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Berlioz, in his grand dramatic legend ``The Damnation of
Faust'' (1846), or Gounod, in his famous opera ``Faust'' (1859),
Schumann found most of his inspiration in the second book of
Goethe's masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   So rather than ending with Gretchen's death and ascension to
heaven, his version follows Faust to his death at the hands of
Mephistopheles' minions and into an ethereal plane, where he
encounters angels and spirit forces. It concludes with a moving
chorale, the ``Chorus Mysticus,'' using the eight lines with which
Goethe ended his work.
</P>
<P>
   Schumann wrote the third of his ``Faust'' scenes first, and only
that part of the work was performed publicly during his lifetime.
On the centenary of Goethe's birth, in 1849, it was heard
simultaneously in three German cities: Weimar, with Franz Liszt
conducting, Dresden and Leipzig.
</P>
<P>
   The new recording, in which Herreweghe marshals the Orchestre
des Champs-Elysees, the Collegium Vocale, La Chapelle Royale, the
RIAS Chamber Choir and eight vocal soloists, faces relatively
little competition. Though Claudio Abbado recorded the work for
Sony Classical in 1994, the handful of performances on disk are
measured mostly against Benjamin Britten's celebrated 1972 Decca
recording, which is available in America only as a special import.
</P>
<P>
   Herreweghe achieves bolder dynamic contrasts than Britten, and
his textures are leaner, but not everyone will appreciate the more
frenzied character here. (The timpanist is especially aggressive.)
In the overture _ which Schumann tackled last _ Herreweghe
generates real excitement, even if Britten trumps him in its final
pages.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Midnight'' scene, when the crones Want, Guilt, Care and
Distress enter to torment Faust, now blind, Herreweghe summons
palpable drama, and William Dazeley, an English baritone as Faust,
proves particularly rousing. In ``Faust's Death,'' at the end of
Part 2, Herreweghe drives his forces to fierce heights, turning the
high-pitched chorus of Lemurs (``zombies,'' in our parlance) into a
leering assemblage, then finishing the episode with eerie calm.
</P>
<P>
   Herreweghe, an old hand at sacred music, is right at home in the
serene choruses of Part 3, with their theistic overtones.
Especially powerful is the scene in which angels bear Faust's
remains to the heavens (``Gerettet ist das edle Glied'') and
celestial choirs rejoice at the flawed man's transformation.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Chorus Mysticus,'' Herreweghe chooses Schumann's
revised version, which was composed almost immediately after the
original. Less opulent, though longer, than what Schumann first
envisioned, it overflows with empathetic emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Some will undoubtedly prefer the tauter, more highly charged
earlier conception, for which Britten makes a spirited case. But
Herreweghe clearly understands the inspiration Schumann felt in
setting the words ``The eternal feminine/Leads us upward'': for the
composer, a paean to his beloved wife, Clara.
</P>
<P>
   The vocal soloists, though little known, are able. Dazeley sings
Faust earnestly if occasionally dryly. Camilla Nylund proves
dramatically convincing as Gretchen, and Hans-Peter Blochwitz sings
the spirit Ariel with soft-grained tenderness. Kristinn
Sigmundsson, a versatile bass, brings gravity to the role of
Mephistopheles and warmth to Pater Profundus. Simone Nold, a
fresh-voiced soprano, also stands out, as Care and in various
choral solos.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Dazeley is no match for Britten's Faust, Dietrich
Fischer-Dieskau in his honeyed prime. Ms. Nylund lacks the shimmer
that Elizabeth Harwood lends the Decca set. And Blochwitz, as good
as he is, can't quite compete with Britten's Ariel, the
incomparable Peter Pears.
</P>
<P>
   Herreweghe's real strength is the choral sound he fuses from the
various forces, crisp, resonant and strong. Though this recording
does not _ cannot _ displace Britten's esteemed account, it offers
its own rewards, including superb sound and exquisite packaging.
</P>
<P>
   More important, it affords the musically curious a chance to
explore afresh a masterpiece that puzzles and dazzles, appealing to
the striver in us all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
