<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7595 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CONGRESS-950&AMP;ADD-     07-20 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CONGRESS-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN SCHISM OVER TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Ohio, Texas, N.J., N.Y., Ill.)  (See also TAX-BREAKS) 
(lh) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House scrambled Tuesday
to head off a revolt by moderates within the party and avert a
humiliating defeat on their signature issue of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   With a vote on the biggest tax cut since 1981 scheduled for
Wednesday on the House floor, Republicans said it was unclear
whether enough of the 20 or so moderates would break with the
leadership to defeat or block passage of the bill, the centerpiece
of the party's domestic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates have been pressing Speaker Dennis Hastert and his
deputies to scale back the 10-year, $864 billion tax-cutting
package approved last week by the Ways and Means Committee, saying
the bill leaves none of the projected federal budget surplus to
help reduce the national debt or address issues like education.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership agreed to cut the package to $792 billion, the
size of a corresponding bill taken up Tuesday by the Senate Finance
Committee, in part to mollify the moderates and in part to sidestep
a procedural problem. But the Republican moderates, led by Rep.
Michael Castle of Delaware, insisted Tuesday on a package of no
more than $514 billion.
</P>
<P>
   During a lunchtime meeting, the moderates listened to pleas for
support from Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, the chairman of the Ways
and Means Committee, and Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, the chairman of
the Budget Committee. But afterwards, Castle reiterated that he
would not vote for the $792 billion package, and that enough other
moderates shared his view to block passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now, clearly they would not be able to pass the
bill,'' Castle said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said a preliminary count Tuesday showed that
the leadership remained short of the 218 votes need to ensure
passage, and that intensive horse trading was under way. But such
jockeying is common before high-stakes votes, and senior
Republicans said they were confident of getting enough votes to
pass the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have the votes,'' said Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the
majority leader. ``We're talking with all of our members and
listening to all of our members.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is the latest illustration of the difficulty that
Republicans are having maintaining a working majority in the House,
where the party is tugged constantly between different factions,
each of which is capable of blocking legislation. The leadership's
situation has been made more difficult by the defection from the
party last week of Rep. Michael Forbes of New York, who abruptly
announced on Friday that he was joining the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans currently have 222 members in the House. There are
211 Democrats, plus one independent who almost always votes with
the Democrats. There is one vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the votes of as few as five Republicans can deprive
the party of a majority, assuming all Democrats and the independent
stick together. Castle said there are at least half a dozen
moderates intent on voting against the $792 billion Republican
package.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by projections of rapidly growing federal budget
surpluses, Republican leaders had planned for this year's tax bill
to be the vehicle for an ideologically charged showdown with
Democrats and President Clinton over the size of the federal
government and the nation's priorities in an era of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has signaled a willingness to discuss a
compromise, he sent his top aides to Capitol Hill Tuesday to
underscore his opposition to any plan approaching the size of the
$792 billion package contemplated by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax cuts that have been put on the table will represent a
reversal of course that would put the economic strategy we have
been pursuing and the prosperity it has brought us at risk,'' said
Lawrence Summers, the Treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans reached out to Democrats by writing a
bill that was somewhat more targeted to the middle class than the
House version. Democrats have responded with compromise overtures
of their own, with a few centrist Democrats saying Tuesday that
they would support a tax cut of around $500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been no attempt at bipartisanship in the House,
where issues tend to be more polarized. The problem for Republicans
in the House has been almost completely from within their own
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Already Archer has had to rework the bill that passed the Ways
and Means Committee to bring it down to $792 billion over 10 years.
He said Tuesday that he had done so primarily by phasing in the
bill's main components _ its 10 percent reduction in income tax
rates and its repeal of the inheritance tax on large estates _ more
slowly than he had originally contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   But several moderates said the reduction from $864 billion to
$792 billion was not enough to deal with their objections.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the moderates are from the Northeast and from districts
where voters are more centrist than those from Republican districts
in other regions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., said she was opposed to the $792
billion tax package because it was too big and because it was based
on projections of federal budget surpluses that are likely to prove
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I strongly recommended is that we postpone action until
we get to a position where we have consensus on this and get a more
realistic bill,'' she said. ``I think the leadership has been
somewhat surprised at the definitive nature of the criticism and
the number of people willing to speak up. I want Denny Hastert and
the Republican leadership to succeed, but we can't have only a
minority from the South and West setting policy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other moderates said they would be willing to vote for the tax
cut if the leadership allowed them time to make their case on the
House floor on Wednesday. Rep. Ray LaHood of Illinois said he
currently intended to vote against the bill, but might change his
position if the moderates were given two hours of time on the floor
and the chance to vote for a smaller package.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we got our shot, that would satisfy me,'' LaHood said.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates are not the only headache for the leadership. A
group of social conservatives is pressing for the tax package to be
changed to reflect their No. 1 tax issue, the repeal of the
so-called marriage penalty, the quirk in the tax code that hurts
many two-income couples. But the conservatives said they are
unlikely to withhold their support for the main Republican bill
over the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
