<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-INSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS HOSPITAL INSPECTORS ARE TOO LENIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal investigators said Tuesday that hospital
inspectors were generally unable to detect substandard care or to
identify incompetent doctors because the inspectors ``strive to
foster a collegial atmosphere'' and do not aggressively scrutinize
practices that could threaten patients' lives.
</P>
<P>
   In a new report, the inspector general of the Department of
Health and Human Services, June Gibbs Brown, said the inspectors
announced their visits in advance and did not examine a random
sample of medical records, but usually relied on hospital employees
to select the records, so clinical problems could easily be
concealed.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving advance notice of inspections, some hospitals
have been found to hire temporary employees or to buy extra
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said researchers had estimated that 18 percent of
hospital patients received inappropriate care that could cause
injuries or other ``serious adverse events,'' like drug overdoses,
the mistaken amputation of a leg or surgery on the wrong side of a
patient's brain.
</P>
<P>
   In her report, the inspector general harshly criticized the
private organization that inspects hospitals for compliance with
federal health and safety standards. The organization, the Joint
Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations, works with
hospitals in a collegial way and has moved away from the idea of
regulation or the aggressive enforcement of federal standards, Ms.
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she said, the commission's inspectors are unlikely
to identify incompetent doctors or ``substandard patterns of
care.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission plays an important role in the American health
care system, accrediting 80 percent of the nation's 6,200
hospitals. Under federal law, hospitals accredited by the
commission are automatically deemed to meet federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   The results of commission surveys can mean the difference
between commercial success and failure for a hospital. In an
intensely competitive health care market, hospitals that receive
high scores often advertise that fact, and they have an advantage
in trying to obtain contracts with managed care organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dennis O'Leary, president of the joint
commission, said he agreed with much of Ms. Brown's report. But, he
insisted, ``The evaluation of a hospital does not have to be
adversarial.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, O'Leary added, ``there are opportunities for
improvements in the commission's accreditation process.'' He said
he would welcome ``more feedback'' and guidance from the Health
Care Financing Administration, the federal agency that runs
Medicare and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general said that federal Medicare officials were
``deferential'' to the commission. For example, she said, the tone
and content of new federal regulations closely follows the approach
favored by the commission, and Medicare officials defer to
commission employees when they visit a hospital at the same time to
investigate problems.
</P>
<P>
   While consumers can learn if a hospital is accredited, Ms. Brown
said, the commission often refuses to disclose the cause or other
details of unexpected deaths and injuries at hospitals. And
Medicare officials provide the public with ``little information''
on the performance of either hospitals or the commission, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown portrayed the commission's surveyors as passive
observers rather than aggressive watchdogs. ``They allow the
hospital to select the majority of records to be reviewed,'' she
said of the inspectors. ``They tend to be accepting of information
and answers provided by the hospital staff, with little probing to
determine if surface appearances describe actual practice. They
seldom reflect any wariness that hospital staff, in their eagerness
to impress surveyors, may exaggerate points or omit information.''
</P>
<P>
   In her report, Ms. Brown also made these points:
</P>
<P>
   _ Inspectors from the joint commission do not judge whether the
care given to a specific patient is good or bad, right or wrong.
They are unlikely to detect inappropriate surgery or bad outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Joint commission surveys are unlikely to identify individual
practitioners whose judgment or skills to practice medicine are
questionable.'' Hospital inspectors make ``a preliminary and
superficial assessment'' of the credentials and privileges of the
medical staff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inspectors typically have little information about special
problems at the hospitals they visit.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates and labor unions welcomed Ms. Brown's
findings. Candice Owley, chairwoman of the Federation of Nurses and
Health Professionals, a division of the American Federation of
Teachers, said the report showed that ``the fox is guarding the
chicken coop and placing patients' health and well-being at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Grealy, a lawyer at the American Hospital Association,
said the commission's collegial approach served the interests of
patients because it helped hospitals improve the quality of care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
