<SLUG> BC-R-YUGO-ARMY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE MOVES TO GIVE OVERDUE PAY TO RESERVISTS, PENSIONERS,
TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note)  (ART ADV: Locator  map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ In an effort to assuage popular
grievances and to stop a wave of protests by unpaid army
reservists, the Yugoslav government will authorize overdue payments
to reservists, pensioners and teachers in a meeting Wednesday,
senior officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The payment plan is an indication of the anxieties of the
government of President Slobodan Milosevic, despite the inability
so far of its political opposition to channel popular anger after
the defeat in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Army reservists, many of whom retain their weapons from their
service in Kosovo, have been protesting in towns across Serbia to
demand their pay for the months spent in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday in Krusevac, a town run by the governing coalition
where up to 8,000 men were mobilized for Kosovo, the reservists
blocked main roads and passenger trains and demonstrated in front
of City Hall. The police did not intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The reservists say each is owed 6,000 dinars for serving in
Kosovo, or $600 at the official exchange rate. Some are also
demanding help to pay electricity and telephone bills.
</P>
<P>
   The new federal payments are quite likely to increase inflation
in an economy damaged by NATO air strikes and nine years of
international sanctions. Last week, the commander of the 3rd Army,
Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic, said that reservists had been paid $80
million and that an additional $120 million was owed to them. The
total amount that the government plans to pay was not clear.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Cabinet minister, Goran Matic, said in an interview
that the government would surprise the West and the divided
political opposition by providing sufficient electricity, heat and
food for Serbia's winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the war you have an effort at political destabilization,
to try to organize despair and hopelessness in every person,'' said
Matic, a minister without portfolio who often speaks for the
government. ``But it's more propaganda than reality. There will be
enough food and electricity. There was a bridge finished today, and
we have the potential and resources to rebuild. What we need is
political stability for reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Matic rejected opposition calls for Milosevic's resignation and
early elections, saying federal and local voting will proceed as
scheduled in November 2000, with elections in Serbia and
Montenegro, the two republics that remain in Yugoslavia, in 2001.
Milosevic, elected by Parliament in 1997, has a single five-year
term.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Vuk Draskovic, a leading opposition politician who
had joined the government but was ousted in the war, Matic said,
``Draskovic hasn't won national elections, and the opposition
hasn't won, and now they are trying to get what they couldn't get
through the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in a ceremony in the town of Beska, Serbian officials
reopened the first bridge to be repaired after the bombing. It is
on the main highway from Budapest through Belgrade to Nis, and the
destruction has caused significant traffic delays. Milosevic
presided last month over the beginning of the repairs.
</P>
<P>
   At least 59 bridges were destroyed or damaged in the bombing.
This one was fixed with the help of a donor from Switzerland, who
gave $360,000. Hundreds of people were bused in for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   In continuing moves against what remains of the independent
press, the government imposed a new license fee of $40,000 on the
Radio Pancevo, which reported carefully but factually in the war.
The courts also issued notices to report to jail for two reporters
for the newspaper Dnevni Telegraf, or The Daily Telegraph, which
was highly critical of Yugoslav authorities and was banned in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters, Srdjan Jankovic and Zoran Lukovic, were sentenced
in March but told to start five months in jail Monday for an
article in December in which they linked a Serbian official from
the party of Milosevic's wife to a killing.
</P>
<P>
   The article did not directly accuse the official, Dr. Milovan
Bojic, a Serbian deputy prime minister, of the killing of a friend
of his, another doctor. the article said only that the dead man had
criticized Bojic but implied his involvement, which turned out to
be untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, lawyers for the two reporters argued Tuesday that the
case had been brought very quickly under a new information law and
that the outcome was harsh and vindictive.
</P>
<P>
   Branka Prpa, wife of the owner and editor of The Daily
Telegraph, Slavko Curuvija, who was killed in April, during the
war, by two men who shot him in front of his apartment building,
said in an interview Tuesday that the jailing ``shows the fear of
the regime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The paper.'' Ms. Prpa added, ``doesn't print any more. The
owner was killed. The journalists are unemployed and have no
influence. It's a continuation of the message and a warning of how
journalists will be treated in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovic, 27, said in an interview that he thought that ``the
case was absolutely over after the murder of Curuvija'' and the
repression of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be in their interest to push aside the
whole thing,'' he said. ``They just want to instill fear in other
journalists and anyone who thinks for himself in Serbia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
