<SLUG> BC-ENGAGE-IPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGAGE STOCK ZOOMS IN OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Engage Technologies Inc., an Andover, Mass. Internet marketing
firm with ties to CMGI Inc., more than doubled in price on its
first day of trading Tuesday on the Nasdaq Stock Exchange, opening
at 15 and closing at 41.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by Engage's relationship to Web venture firm, CMGI,
whose earlier ventures included Lycos Inc., the Internet search
engine and portal site, investors bid up the newcomer to a
midafternoon peak of 47 in a marketplace that, only a few weeks
ago, seemed to be shying away from untested Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   With almost 14.9 million shares traded, Engage was the eighth
most active stock on Nasdaq Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Engage was one of several Internet and technology firms expected
to attract attention during this week's debut of more than 20 IPOs.
The Engage sale, handled by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., raised $90
million for CMGI. At day's end Engage's total market value was
$1.92 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the stock's quick rise to CMGI's reputation.
CMGI, also based in Andover, owned 96 percent of Engage prior to
the offering and will retain 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Lycos, an existing firm in which CMGI invested, Engage
was a CMGI creation. ``This is the first wholly owned CMGI company
to be sold,'' said Michael Graham, an equity analyst at BancBoston
Robertson Stephens in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also another piece of evidence that CMGI has a savvy
management team that has been able to make very good investments.
Eventually, as Engage executes its strategy and grows, it will most
likely raise the value of CMGI stock,'' Graham added.
</P>
<P>
   Ullas Naik at First Albany Corp. in Boston called Engage's first
day of trading a ``huge validator that bodes well for CMGI's
strategy going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Engage Technologies offers products to Internet users that
include software to help corporations serve up on-line ads to an
immense collection of user behavioral data, sorted by race, age,
place of residence, Internet browsing habits, and other purchasing
and demographic characteristics. The company says its database
represents more than 30 million anonymous consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using (Engage's) data base, servers can actually track to see
how people behave on line,'' noted Naik. ``So ads become much more
targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   Engage has reported it will use a portion of the money raised
Tuesday for working capital and product development.
</P>
<P>
   Engage was among several high tech and Internet firms expected
to go public this week.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Art Technology Group Inc., whose software allows
on-line companies to personalize their advertisements, plans to
offer 5 million shares at between $10 to $12 per share, hoping to
raise $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Netsilicon Inc. of Waltham, filed its intentions
with the SEC to to offer 5 million shares at between $8 and $10 per
share at an unspecified future date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
