<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAT-SUBSTITUTE-ART-2T     07-20 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAT-SUBSTITUTE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS APPETITE FOR OLESTRA FALLS SHORT, P&AMP;G SCALES BACK GOLDEN
FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ In a corporate dining room at the Procter &AMP; Gamble
Co.'s headquarters two years ago, John E. Pepper, the chief
executive, stabbed his fork, by turns, into salad,
chicken-vegetable stir fry and carrot cake.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch, during which Pepper asked the chef to set aside a
little extra dressing for him to take home, was a carefully
orchestrated attempt to show that he was putting his mouth where
his money was _ in P&AMP;G's much-ballyhooed olestra, a fat substitute.
The salad dressing, stir-fry oil and cake frosting were all made
with olestra.
</P>
<P>
   Though olestra is approved for use only in potato chips and
other salty snacks, the menu made clear that the company's ultimate
goal was to turn olestra into a staple, just as its Crisco was a
generation earlier. It confidently projected nearly $1 billion in
worldwide sales by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Olestra did rack up decent sales last year, but the company
grossly miscalculated the size of the market. Part of the problem
was that regulatory approval was so long in coming that the fickle
cycle of consumer taste had edged away from low-fat food. P&AMP;G never
overcame olestra's image problem _ backed up by numerous complaints
that it causes stomach upset in some people. It did not help that
few companies followed the lead of Frito-Lay, which until recently
had exclusive rights to put olestra in its snacks.
</P>
<P>
   What this adds up to is that with luck, sales may hit half that
$1 billion target. P&AMP;G, under a new chief executive, admits that
olestra, an amber-colored fake fat marketed as Olean, will probably
not be the liquid gold that management once envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acknowledge the current performance isn't what we would
have liked,'' Sydney McHugh, a company spokeswoman, said. Far from
it, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Durk I. Jager, who in January replaced Pepper, now
chairman, stunned analysts and investors by disclosing that olestra
production last year at a new $250 million plant was 30 percent to
40 percent below forecasts. Plans to seek broader regulatory
approval to add olestra to foods like french fries and cookies have
been put on hold. Management simply ``cannot speculate on future
sales projections,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that olestra is a pure flop. ``Consumers have now enjoyed
more than 1.5 billion servings of snacks that are made with
Olean,'' Ms. McHugh said. The company said it remained confident in
olestra's long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay, by adding olestra versions of its already popular
Doritos, Ruffles, Tostitos and Lay's chips and calling them Wow
snacks, pulled in $347 million last year, according to Information
Resources Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble's olestra version of Pringles chips added $100
million, the company said. But all this falls far short of what P&AMP;G
dreamed of when it forecast $500 million in domestic revenue and
$400 million in international sales by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There is always the chance that just as Nutrasweet took about a
decade to catch on, olestra may one day truly blossom. ``I think
olestra still has potential, we'll just have to wait and see what
other products they introduce it into,'' said Tony Vento, an
analyst with Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the backpedaling from the lofty goals is a a
testament to the struggle P&AMP; G, long known as a marketing
powerhouse, has had in coming up with the next hot brand to rev up
its slowing growth engine.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble has set a highly publicized 10-year goal of
doubling its revenues to about $70 billion by 2005. It said it
would almost certainly miss that target but was confident it would
return soon to its traditional double-digit earnings growth rate.
Analysts say that without large acquisitions, P&AMP;G will be
hard-pressed to move the needle that far.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently restructured its business to speed product
introductions, which should make it more competitive with smaller,
more nimble rivals. It recently introduced several products that
show potential, like Febreze, a spray that removes odors from
fabrics, and Swiffer, an electrostatic mop with a disposable cloth.
</P>
<P>
   With olestra, though, the question is how a company that brought
the world Tide, Pampers and Crest could have invested half a
billion dollars and about 25 years in a product that came up so
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the headline is, `The consumer has spoken,' and it's
like a political campaign that never got off the ground,'' said
Mark Godfrey, a senior analyst with the Invesco Funds Group, which
holds 1.6 million shares of P&AMP;G ``It seemed like people had a
negative perception of it right off the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that it took 15 years to develop and another
decade to gain regulatory approval from the Food and Drug
Administration. Unfortunately for P&AMP;G, by the time olestra chips
and crackers hit grocery shelves nationally in the summer of 1998,
the fat-free fad had begun to wane. In addition, olestra chips are
sold at as much as a 40 percent premium to regular chips.
</P>
<P>
   The appetite for reduced or nonfat foods has steadily fallen in
recent years, with many consumers disappointed not only by the
taste and texture of some products but also by a lack of
significant weight loss from passing up fat-packed snacks, said Tom
Vierhile, general manager of Marketing Intelligence Service,
publisher of Product Alert, a new-product publication. Annual
consumption of low-fat and fat-free snacks peaked in 1997 at 22.6
eatings per person and declined to 19.7 eatings last year,
according to the NPD Group, which tracks consumer consumption.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans have added fat back into their diets, P&AMP;G has
struggled to convince skeptical consumers that olestra snacks are
nothing like the pre-olestra cardboard-like chips and bland
crackers that had turned them off in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is this product was just too late in the
trend,'' Vierhile said. ``The momentum in this just seems to be
going away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
