<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7610 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-FUNERAL-HNS &LR;      07-20 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE KENNEDYS, FUNERALS HAVE BECOME A POIGNANT ART FORM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the family considers final tributes for John F.
Kennedy Jr., it has a rich legacy of farewells on which to draw.
</P>
<P>
   For the Kennedys, with their stunning string of services for
those who have died too young or very old, funerals have become a
poignant art form that weaves a touch of the patriotic, political
and very personal into the framework of the Roman Catholic Mass.
</P>
<P>
   During the last four decades, members of one of the nation's
most famous dynasties have been remembered in rites marked by
majesty as well as moments of mirth.
</P>
<P>
   Moving rhetoric has stood side by side with singing by the
family's virtual court musician, crooner Andy Williams. And there
have been bits that some might consider mawkish, as in the 1998
funeral of Michael Kennedy, who was killed in a skiing accident,
when a choir sang ``Michael, Row the Boat Ashore.''
</P>
<P>
   The powerful are often present or at least represented. When
matriarch Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy died at age 104 in 1995, Pope
John Paul II sent a telegram of condolences, which was read by
Cardinal Bernard Law during the service at Old St. Stephen's Church
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In planning a service for JFK Jr., for which neither the date
nor place has been announced, the Kennedys also may be considering
the wishes of his wife's family, who lost two daughters in the
crash Friday night off Martha's Vineyard _ Carolyn Bessette Kennedy
and Lauren Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Kennedys' penchant for sometimes media-heavy rites
figured in a statement from the Bessette family Monday, which said
in part: ``John and Carolyn were true soul mates, and we hope to
honor them in death in the simple manner in which they chose to
live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple,'' however, is not an adjective always associated with
anything the Kennedys do, be it funerals or less solemn events.
And, anyway, as family friend and columnist Mary McGrory once
wrote: ``The Kennedys have a way of overwhelming their in-laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a search for human remains and wreckage continued
Tuesday, a family source said the Kennedys, many of whom have
remained since the weekend at the family compound at Hyannis Port,
Mass., were discussing arrangements for a memorial service. New
York, where JFK Jr. and his wife lived, is the likeliest venue for
a service, and it would not be held before Friday, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   JFK Jr.'s sister, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, has generally
shunned high-profile appearances and may favor as low-key a service
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg has remained in New York, at her home near
Bridgehampton on Long Island, since returning quickly Saturday from
an Idaho vacation. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., flew to New
York to visit Schlossberg on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zwilling, a spokesman for the Roman Catholic archdiocese
of New York, said Tuesday afternoon that the church hierarchy had
not been approached by the Kennedy family regarding a service.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said it was ``certainly possible'' for a memorial Mass
to be held without the presence of human remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens literally every day,'' said Zwilling. ``You are
praying for the repose of the soul'' of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Because the graves of President Kennedy and Jacqueline Kennedy
Onasis are in Arlington National Cemetery, there has been
speculation that whatever remains of JFK Jr. and his wife may be
found could also be buried there.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said he had no comment on the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who is married to
a Kennedy, was acting as unofficial liaison between the government
and Kennedy family on ``a number of matters.'' Those apparently
include arranging whether President Clinton will attend a memorial
service, which depends on how expansive the family decides the rite
will be.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1963, the nation and, in many cases, the world have
witnessed a succession of Kennedy funerals _ from the grand to the
grandmotherly.
</P>
<P>
   For President Kennedy, of course, his funeral was a state
occasion _ with royalty and rulers of more than 100 nations in
attendance at the pontifical low Mass in St. Matthew's Cathedral in
Washington. But there were intensely personal moments, as when
Cardinal Richard Cushing of Boston, at the conclusion of the
service, interpolated his own affection for the martyred president
into the final words of the service: ``May the angels, dear Jack,
lead you into Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   The body of the Mass was in the then-traditional liturgical
Latin. Just five years later, the service of Sen. Robert F.
Kennedy, D-N.Y., in St. Patrick's Cathedral on Fifth Avenue in New
York, marked not only a changed world but also a different Roman
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Second Vatican Council, RFK's funeral Mass
was in English, and the fire and brimstone of the old service _ the
``Dies Irae'' or ``Day of Wrath'' section of the requiem _ was
omitted.
</P>
<P>
   Music for the service included the New York Philharmonic,
conducted by Leonard Bernstein, playing a movement from Gustav
Mahler's ``Fifth Symphony'' and family friend Andy Williams singing
``The Battle Hymn of the Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, for the funeral of Michael Kennedy, a son of
Robert and Ethel Kennedy, Williams sang ``Ave Maria'' in Our Lady
of Victory Church in Centerville, Mass., near the family's Hyannis
Port compound.
</P>
<P>
   The family also is often participants _ active or inadvertent _
in the obsequies.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous picture of JFK Jr. was taken when he was
3 years old and he saluted his father's coffin on that chill
November day in Washington almost 36 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest national public memories of former Rep.
Joseph Kennedy III, D-Mass., was as a 16-year-old helping to carry
the coffin of his father into St. Patrick's in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years ago, Michael Kennedy's 14-year-old son led
his father's shiny mahogany coffin out of the family's parish
church on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   During Michael Kennedy's funeral, members of the congregation
said, then-Rep. Kennedy provoked laughter with the story of an
impromptu family football game in which the field of play ranged
from inside his apartment and out onto the lawn. On the first down,
a call for a pass sent the ball flying through an unopened window _
and quickly ended the game.
</P>
<P>
   And Kennedys use funerals to shape the historical view of their
family and loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   At RFK's service in 1968, as opposition to the war in Vietnam
intensified and tore apart the family's beloved Democratic Party,
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, by then the only surviving son, eulogized
his brother:
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother need not be idealized or enlarged in death beyond
what he was in life: to be remembered simply as a good and decent
man who saw wrong and tried to right it, saw suffering and tried to
heal it, saw war and tried to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
