<HEADER>
A7611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAT-SUBSTITUTE-ART-2N     07-20 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAT-SUBSTITUTE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
CINCINNATI: going away.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The company's other headache is that olestra has a huge image
problem to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Snacks containing it are required to carry what is arguably the
most unappealing food product label in history: ``Olestra may cause
cramping and loose stools.''
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer has been dogged by a consumer advocacy group,
the Center for Science in the Public Interest, that has
successfully reminded consumers at every turn of the possible ill
effects from munching olestra snacks.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA, which as a condition of its approval required P&AMP;G to
track and report consumer reports of adverse reactions to olestra,
says nearly 16,700 complaints have been received by the company and
by the public-interest group, which has been independently
monitoring possible side effects.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, olestra molecules, made of soybean or cottonseed
oil heated to high temperatures and blended with sugar, are too
large to be broken down in the digestive system. That is why they
add no calories. But the substance inhibits the absorption of
vitamins A, D, E and K, as well as nutrients like carotenoids,
which some researchers say help prevent cancer. Olestra products
are fortified with vitamins but not with carotenoids.
</P>
<P>
   The company contends that olestra causes no more stomach upset
than beans or broccoli. It has sought to position olestra as
natural and healthy, using farmers in ads and showing soy beans to
connote wholesome goodness. But P&AMP;G seems to have fallen short in
persuading enough consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very different to create brand awareness for a product
than it is for just an ingredient,'' said Clive Chajet, president
of Chajet Consultancy in New York, which advises corporations on
brand-building strategies. ``With Tide, P&AMP;G doesn't talk about what
kind of soap it uses in the flakes. They talk about what Tide is as
a brand. P&AMP;G controls every single aspect of the Tide image, but
they do not control the ultimate image of Olean as an ingredient in
someone else's brand.''
</P>
<P>
   While P&AMP;G sells Pringles olestra chips, analysts said
Frito-Lay's Wow snacks were the real yardstick because they
accounted for more than two-thirds of olestra sales. The Wow line,
they say, has already peaked.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of Wow's sales came from consumers trying the
product out. Though Frito-Lay, a unit of Pepsico &UR;  &LR; Inc., says repeat
use remains high, demand is dropping sharply as fewer new consumers
switch to the products, analysts say. Volumes of Wow products
declined 43 percent in the eight weeks ended June 20 from the
period a year earlier, according to a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
analysts' report.
</P>
<P>
   While P&AMP; hoped that other snack makers would rush to add olestra
to their lines, that has not happened. Nabisco Foods, which sold a
version of its Ritz and Wheat Thins crackers containing olestra in
test markets more than a year ago, said it had no current plans to
roll them out nationally. Nabisco declined to give a reason.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G clearly had loftier expectations: the company included a
picture of olestra products, including fat-free Ritz crackers, in
its annual report last year under the heading ``new to the world
brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Another snack maker, General Mills Inc., tested olestra in its
Bugles chips and has not decided whether it will sell them
nationally. Since the deal that granted Frito-Lay exclusive rights
to use olestra expired in May, only two mid-size snack makers, Utz
and Herr's, have added chips containing olestra.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble says more olestra products are in the works.
The company said it had signed contracts with more than a dozen
companies besides Utz and Herr's that were interested in using
olestra. The company declined to name them, however, and said not
all of the interested snack makers were expected to ultimately
introduce additional olestra products.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G is not entirely dependent on competitors to push olestra.
The company said it might add the ingredient to some of its other
food lines, like Eagle snacks. The company has asked the FDA for
approval to extend the salty snack category to microwave popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   But ``that's about as off-trend as you can get,'' said Vierhile
of Marketing Intelligence. ``If you look at the popcorn industry,
the big trend in the past two years has been extra butter. You
can't get enough butter on microwave popcorn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
