<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS MANAGEMENT BANKING ON REVENUE SPIKE FROM STANLEY CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two days after the Stars won the Stanley Cup, delirious hockey
fans so swamped the souvenir shop at the Dr Pepper StarCenter in
Irving that the store's computer suffered a meltdown and orders had
to be taken by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was organized hysteria,'' Stars director of merchandising
Steve Shilts recalled. ``We were going as fast as we could, but
there was still a 2 1/2 wait just to get in the shop.''
</P>
<P>
   The last month of the playoff run accounted for nearly one-third
of all Stars' merchandise sales for the year, Shilts said, one sure
sign of championship frenzy and the cash-register-ringing impact it
has had on the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   There are others.
</P>
<P>
   Stars season-ticket renewals are projected at 95 to 96 percent,
and 800 people are on a priority waiting list for season tickets
for 1999-2000, up from 450 on the list last year. The club's 14,000
season-ticket limit is being pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Stars owner Tom Hicks said the franchise's success on and off
the ice is the culmination of a business plan hatched when he
bought the team nearly four years ago. The plan: Invest now, reap
dividends later.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to win the Cup was millions of dollars in annual
financial losses since Hicks bought the club, largely because of a
player payroll that hit $39.4 million last season. Now, finally,
the reaping has begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of dreamed it would work this way,'' Hicks said during
the Finals. ``The reality is, it's a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate financial impact on the Stars came from
playoff-ticket revenues and merchandise sales. That revenue will
cut the club's expected year-end losses, which could have exceeded
$10 million without the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a big lift for us,'' Hicks said. ``We'll lose
several million dollars this year, but we could've lost quite a bit
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the team's play, the Stars' financial performance has shown
steady improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said that when he bought the team in 1995, it generated
about $350,000 per game in total revenues from ticket, merchandise
and concession sales. That figure rose to about $800,000 per
regular-season game this year, he added, and increased each round
of the playoffs. Team president Jim Lites said the Stars took in
about $1.8 million per game during the Stanley Cup Finals, although
the team didn't keep all of that revenue.
</P>
<P>
   While Stanley Cup mania has eased somewhat since the frantic
days after the victory against the Buffalo Sabres, the benefits
continue for the Stars franchise as the club looks to move into the
American Airlines Center, where it will have premium seating,
suites and more sponsorships to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Cup, said Stars vice president of marketing and
promotion Jeff Cogen, should help sell premium seats and season
tickets in the new arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good ball rolling down the hill,'' Cogen said,
``but this is an accelerator, a catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said capturing the Cup ``cemented the bond we need to have
with our fans. We'll sell out every game next year, and I think
we'll sell out every game the year after that. By the time we move
into the American Airlines Center, we should have a great tradition
of hockey in Dallas. We ought to be a showcase franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Of greater long-term value, the Stars' playoff success will help
broaden interest in hockey in North Texas through greater
youth-league participation, club officials said. It should also
increase the value of Hicks' planned regional sports TV network.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing interest in hockey in Fort Worth-Dallas was evident from
the Stars' playoff TV ratings, which set records for local
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's huge. That's the most significant thing that could
happen,'' Lites said. ``People took the time to watch, even if it
was casually, in prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   The rising fan interest, Hicks said, has helped allow him to
build a championship team. Stars fans, he said, have been willing
to pay the ever-rising ticket prices to attend the team's games,
generating much of the revenue necessary to cover the club's
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, the Stars hope to hold the line on payroll, and
perhaps even reduce it, by shedding some higher-priced veterans and
replacing them on the roster with talented younger players who earn
less.
</P>
<P>
   Like all NHL clubs, the Stars are extremely dependent on ticket
sales for revenue because the league's national TV contract pays
each club only $4 million a year _ a pittance compared with the
rights fees received by teams in other pro sports. Stars
season-ticket prices increased 11.75 percent on average last year
and are going up again next season, with the estimated average hike
only slightly lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the success of the Stars has been a true partnership
between Tom Hicks and the fans because we've both had to pay,''
Hicks said. ``Our payroll when I bought the team was under $20
million, and it's over $40 million today. The prices of our tickets
have gone way up, but not enough to cover the payroll we've got. So
these fans are my partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Stanley Cup has had long-term benefits for other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Avalanche won the Stanley Cup the year they
relocated from Quebec, and that helped spur interest in the Denver
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went all the way that first year, it created new
hockey fans,'' Avalanche spokesman Jean Martineau said. ``We had a
pretty good core of fans before we came here because there had been
an NHL team previously \Rthe Colorado Rockies\S. But winning the
Cup really enlarged our fan base.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks expects interest in the Stars to continue to rise, too, so
long as the team continues to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we disappoint them,'' he said, ``I think they'll stick
with us.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
