<HEADLINE>
WORLD TRADE GROUP AGREES ON SPLIT TERM FOR DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Members of the World Trade Organization resolved a
prolonged and bitter dispute over who would be their next leader
Tuesday by agreeing that the two finalists will share the job in
consecutive three-year terms, with the New Zealand candidate going
first, followed by his Thai rival.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise, which had been gathering support in the last few
weeks, was introduced Tuesday at the organization's decision-making
General Council. It is likely to be formally approved on Friday,
representatives said.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, it would end a struggle that had pitted Mike Moore,
a former New Zealand prime minister, against Supachai Panitchpakdi,
a Thai deputy prime minister, to head the 134-nation organization
that sets the rules of global commerce.
</P>
<P>
   And, though the dividing lines were not always neat or clearly
drawn, the leadership struggle also pitted Western economic powers,
many of whom supported Moore, against Asians and others in the
Third World, who saw Supachai's candidacy as a way of gaining some
equality in international councils.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of both candidates agreed that the trade organization
had worked its way out of an embarrassing and potentially crippling
episode in its young history. ``No one pretends that this is an
ideal solution, but it is certainly the most practicable,'' said
Iftekhar Chowdhury, the representative from Bangladesh, which first
proposed the idea of a divided term.
</P>
<P>
   The previous director general, Renato Ruggiero of Italy, who
left the post at the end of April, served a four-year term after an
initial fight over his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which had supported Moore and was privately
accused by some countries of trying to sabotage Supachai's
candidacy, said it was satisfied with the outcome. ``We accept this
knowing that we have to move forward with the trade agenda,'' said
Rita Hayes, the American representative at the trade organization.
``These are two very qualified individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   A formal announcement of the sharing arrangement was partly
dependent on negotiations over who would become the deputy
directors general in various world regions. But even if
disagreements arose over these posts, representatives said, the
split-term arrangement for director general would not be derailed.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to fill the top post had been threatening the smooth
functioning of the Geneva-based trade group. The director general
oversees a staff of 500 and has the power to appoint arbitration
panels in trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The main question surrounding the split-term compromise was on
who would go first. Last week, the Thai government helped expedite
a solution by announcing that Supachai could take the second term,
and that broke the last significant obstacle to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted that the meeting today reached a conclusion on
term-sharing,'' Supachai said in a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the compromise, Moore will take over on Sept. 1 and serve
through Aug. 31, 2002. Supachai's term would start the following
day and finish on Aug. 31, 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's first priority will be to guide negotiations for the
coming round of global trade talks scheduled in Seattle at the end
of November.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Moore quipped that his best qualification for
the job ``is that I look like Rocky'' _ the nickname of Ruggiero.
But at 50, Moore is 19 years younger than his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   He has held a number of New Zealand government posts, notably a
brief tenure as prime minister in 1990. ``I was there such a short
time it made Gerald Ford look like Franklin Roosevelt,'' Moore
remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations on how the deputy director general posts will be
filled remain a potential source of conflict in the trade
organization, the successor to the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old GATT structure, there were two deputies, one from
the United States and the other from India. Another deputy position
was added and filled by a Latin American _ from Mexico _ in 1993.
Two years later, when Ruggiero was named as director general of the
new World Trade Organization, the number of deputies grew again
when a South Korean was named a deputy.
</P>
<P>
   With the Europeans relinquishing the top slot, which they held
throughout the history of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade, they are anxious for a deputy post. But many developing
nations are similarly intent on getting deputy posts for Asia,
Africa and Latin America. The United States also wants a deputy.
</P>
<P>
   The math adds up to five deputies, three more than the trade
organization had planned. For now, the proposed compromise
indicates the need for ``equitable geographical balance'' in the
deputy selection, but interpreting that phrase is certain to lead
to a lot of hard bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how to deal them out,'' Pakistan's trade
envoy, Munir Akram, said. ``They're important because it's like
having a sympathetic ear in the court. It's somebody you can pick
up the phone and talk to if there's a problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
