<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-PBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WGBH MAY FACE PENALTIES IN DONOR LIST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ WGBH-TV, whose practice of exchanging donor lists
with the Democratic Party prompted a furor over public
broadcasting, could face retroactive penalties, several House
Republicans said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A House Commerce subcommittee addressed the list-swapping
controversy at a hearing, questioning top officials of the
Corporation for Public Broadcasting about how widespread the
practice is. Members of both parties demanded strict laws to
prevent similar trading in the future, especially as officials
revealed for the first time that 26 of 75 public television
stations surveyed so far swapped donor lists with politicians or
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Representative W. J. ``Billy'' Tauzin of Louisiana, chairman of
the subcommittee that oversees funding for public broadcasting,
said future violators could be punished with a fine or even jail.
</P>
<P>
   But the possibility of punishing past offenders was also raised.
Representatives Christopher Cox, a Republican from California, and
Barbara Cubin, a Republican from Wyoming, favor investigating WGBH
and issuing sanctions if wrongdoing were found. Tauzin also said he
would not oppose investigating the previous activity at WGBH, even
though the station claims to have implemented tougher standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress may decide to sanction the stations individually, by
witholding federal funds for a period of time,'' said Ken Johnson,
a spokesman for Tauzin.
</P>
<P>
   The statements came as public broadcasting officials revealed
that at least seven public stations _ including New Hampshire
Public Television _ swapped donor names with Republican groups,
including the 1996 presidential campaign of former Senate majority
leader Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy at first focused on exchanges with Democratic
organizations, as disclosures that WGBH traded donor lists with the
Democratic National Committee fueled Republican suspicions that
public television is biased toward liberals.
</P>
<P>
   But in answering questions from subcommittee members about the
nature of the list-swapping, Robert Coonrod, president of the
Corporation for Public Broadcasting, was careful to point out the
practice included both sides of the political aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bipartisan nature of these transactions begs the ethical
question: Should public stations that receive federal financial
support deal in this way with any political entity?'' Coonrod said
in his prepared testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Representative Edward J. Markey of Massachusetts, the
top Democrat on the subcommittee, agreed: ``I think it was clear
today that members on both sides understand that both parties
engaged in practices which should not be permitted. The more
extensive the search becomes, the more instances in both parties
will be identified.''
</P>
<P>
   In documents provided to Democrats on the panel, the Corporation
for Public Broadcasting identified seven stations that exchanged
donor lists with Republicans: KCET in Los Angeles, WKNO in Memphis,
KCPT in Kansas City, New Hampshire Public Television and Iowa
Public Television.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Goen, a spokeswoman for KCET, said the Los Angeles
station did purchase names from Republican entities but never sold
its own lists of donors to either political party.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for New Hampshire Public Television could not be
reached Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the controversy is whether public stations
violated their tax-exempt status by making their resources
available to one political party over another. KCET said because it
did not make its lists available to political parties it did not
commit any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But broadcasting officials and subcommittee members Tuesday
clearly were interested more in public perception than the letter
of the law. Ervin Duggan, the chief executive officer of the Public
Broadcasting Service, dismissed the idea that stations were
exonerated if they employed ``list brokers,'' outside companies to
sell and buy their donor lists. And Coonrod said that even if
list-swapping is legal, ``public broadcasting cannot afford, either
in appearance of in fact,'' to undermine the trust of its
viewership.
</P>
<P>
   Coonrod apologized repeatedly for the entire imbroglio, saying
list-swapping was ``such a manifestly stupid thing to do.'' At the
same time, both Coonrod and Duggan said the issue of list-swapping
should not jeopardize overall funding for public broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Before the controversy erupted last week, Tauzin supported a
significant increase in funding for public broadcasting, including
authorizing money to help public stations make the transition to
digital broadcasting, which they are required by law to do by 2003.
Now, that funding increase appears unlikely, and the $250 million
public broadcasting has received in annual appropriations in recent
years may not increase at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the funding will not be addressed until the hearings have
ended in September at the earliest. In the meantime, aides said the
Internal Revenue Service is expected to investigate the
list-swapping to determine if the stations violated their
tax-exempt status. Cox also requested a report from the General
Accounting Office, although aides in other congressional offices
said such a report could take more than a year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Markey said, the question of punishing WGBH and
other public stations would be moot until any investigation had
taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did they do wrong? They didn't break any laws,'' he said.
``I think that would first have to be established before we talked
about the penalites for something that has yet to be determined as
the offense. There isn't any indication at this point that they
did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
