<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rudolph search still very active, FBI says
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ A year after suspected Atlanta Olympic Park and
Birmingham, Ala. abortion clinic bomber Eric Robert Rudolph came
out of hiding, then quickly disappeared again, the federal task
force searching for him in the rugged Appalachians reiterated its
commitment Tuesday to keeping up the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   In their first news conference in more than three months, task
force officials warned Rudolph not to get comfortable, that agents
aren't leaving the area any time soon _ even with the team's top
agent retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Task force chief Woody Enderson, who retires next month after a
28-year career with the FBI, said during the briefing that there
have been Rudolph sightings since last July and that he believes
agents have prevented other bombings by keeping the suspect
cornered in western North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident as long as we maintain the pressure that he
will not be free to commit any more violence,'' Enderson said.
</P>
<P>
   He declared that ``nothing has changed,'' that the fugitive will
be hunted until he's caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it happens while he is 32 years old or 62, we will be
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Enderson introduced Steven C. McCraw, the man who will replace
him next month as the chief inspector for the task force. McCraw,
45, had FBI tours in Tucson, Ariz., Dallas and Los Angeles before
moving to FBI headquarters in Washington in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On July 7 last year, Rudolph came out of hiding and allegedly
stole food and other supplies from a local resident. Nearly 300
searchers descended on the Nantahala community but failed to corral
the fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   In the mountains where investigators say they believe Rudolph is
still hiding, life goes on. Pink mimosas bloom in the thick woods,
and rafters ride the nearby Nantahala River. Hikers on the
Appalachian Trail have been warned to be on the lookout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize it's very, very possible that we could have
walked right by him and didn't see him,'' Enderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph is charged with the July 27, 1996, bombing at Atlanta's
Centennial Olympic Park; the 1997 bombing of an Atlanta abortion
clinic; the 1997 bombing of The Otherside Lounge in Atlanta; and
the fatal 1998 bombing at a Birmingham abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Enderson said there are more agents attached to the command post
now than a year ago, despite reports that only a dozen or so people
remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about three times the number that we had when he
surfaced here last July,'' Enderson said. ``At that time, we had 20
to 30.'' However, the number of tactical searchers is less than
this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
