<HEADER>
A7633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBS-DONOR-LISTS-ART-6     07-20 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-DONOR-LISTS-ART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 28 PBS STATIONS SHARED DONOR LISTS WITH POLITICAL
ORGANIZATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Wyo., La., Mass., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At least 28 public television stations have
exchanged the names of their donors with political organizations
affiliated with either or both of the major political parties,
according to a partial survey made public Tuesday by officials for
the Corporation for Public Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The practice appears to extend as far back as 1981 and to be
most prevalent in the nation's major markets. And while it may not
be illegal, public television officials acknowledged Tuesday that
it was wrong and undermined their credibility and the public trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We blew it,'' Robert Coonrod, president of the corporation,
said at a hearing on Capitol Hill Tuesday as he and other public
broadcast officials were called on the carpet by both Republican
and Democratic members of Congress. Ervin Duggan, president of the
Public Broadcasting Service, admitted the practice was
``inappropriate, embarrassing and downright stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nervous that the reports of list swapping with political
organizations could endanger their federal funding, the officials
were quick to say that they would cooperate with congressional
calls for an independent review of the fund-raising practices of
the nation's 353 public television stations. The federal government
provides nearly 15 percent of the industry's $2 billion annual
budget.
</P>
<P>
   But they said they would not punish any of the stations
retroactively. Rather, they said, they would require the stations
to certify from now on that they are not violating the Internal
Revenue Service code that requires nonprofit organizations to make
their donor lists available to all political organizations equally.
</P>
<P>
   That promise was not enough for members of Congress,
particularly Republicans, who said the list-swapping with political
organizations was bad enough to require new controls and to force
the eventual privatization of public broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Bird is nearly 30 years old, and it's time to leave the
federal nest,'' said Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla. Rep. Barbara
Cubin, R-Wyo., said that public broadcasting's tax-exempt status
``should be revoked, and Congress should phase out public
funding.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual number of cases of publicly financed stations giving
their lists of donors to political organizations is probably much
larger than the 28 cited Tuesday because the corporation said it
had surveyed only 75 of the 353 stations. It did not identify the
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Coonrod said that of the 75 surveyed, 53 had used list brokers
as intermediaries to exchange their donor lists with other
non-profit organizations. He said the motive appeared to be to
raise money efficiently, not partisan politics. He also said that
the stations traded names not only with the Democratic National
Committee, as has been reported, but with Republican organizations
too, including Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican organizations with which stations exchanged
lists included the Viguerie Fundraising Superfile, the Conservative
Republican Superfile, Country Club Republicans, Golden Aged
Republicans, Republican Party Builders and Great American Donors.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat-linked organizations, apart from the national
committee, included Handgun Control Inc., Planned Parenthood and
Zero Population Growth.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who is chairman of the subcommittee on
telecommunications, which held Tuesday's hearing, appeared less
eager than some of his colleagues to cut back the funding. But he
said he would introduce legislation to make it illegal for stations
to make their lists available at all, directly or indirectly
through intermediaries, to any political organization or
politician.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move appears to have strong backing from members of both
parties, but Democrats clearly hoped that their support for new
controls would mitigate Republican calls for slashing federal
funding. Tuesday's hearing indicated that next year's allocation,
which is to be set by Oct. 1, the start of the fiscal year, could
become a major partisan battleground.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The top Democrat on the subcommittee, Rep. Edward Markey of
Massachusetts, said list-swapping with political organizations was
``inappropriate and should be prohibited.'' But, he said, the
disclosures should not prompt Congress to ``starve'' the public
stations. Doing so, he warned, would force the stations to seek
more commercial support and give more air time to commercial
underwriters, spoiling what he said was ``an electronic oasis in
the vast wasteland of commercial broadcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was prompted by the disclosure last week that four of
the biggest public television stations in the country _ in New
York, Washington, Boston and San Francisco _ had exchanged their
donor lists with the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The swapping was uncovered after the mother of a 4-year-old boy
in Wellesley, Mass., sent a $40 contribution to WGBH in Boston to
support its children's programming. Shortly thereafter, the boy
received a solicitation letter from the Democratic National
Committee, prompting the Boston Globe to investigate the station's
fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   In defending the corporation's failure to exact any penalty from
the stations that gave their lists to political organizations,
Coonrod said that public humiliation was enough. ``Public
humiliation, given the fact that we operate on the basis of trust
with our viewers and listeners, is pretty bad,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
