<HEADER>
A7634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MP3-COX     07-20 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Downloadable music hits high notes at conference
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you can imagine a place where Amazon.com is
considered an established retailer, then you might have some idea
of the uncertainty and opportunity felt by the attendees at Jupiter
Communications' fourth annual Plug.In conference going on this week
here.
</P>
<P>
   This is where 1,300 Internet-hungry music mavens have gathered
to discuss the intensifying buzz over digital downloading of music
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The very idea has some music industry executives quaking in fear
of piracy, but others are pouring money into the concept, including
Atlanta-based Cox Interactive Media, which recently bought a 10
percent stake in MP3.com, the Website in the center of the vortex.
</P>
<P>
   As the record industry tries to make order out of chaos, MP3.com
prepares to launch its initial public offering as early as today,
expecting to collect around $300 million on its 12.3 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com is one of the most popular sources of news, information
and free digital music downloads available on the Web. It has the
audience the record companies look for, although it hasn't turned a
profit yet. Cox Interactive Media, a unit of Cox Enterprises,
pumped $45 million into it, believing it would be the business
center where profits begin as the digital music download gold rush
begins.
</P>
<P>
   Cox's investment in MP3.com comes at a time when the music
industry is looking for established media partners to lend their
experience as well as their databases of users and customers to
help it identify and market to potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of merging databases of music lovers with databases
of online shoppers is something the record industry is eager to
experiment with. Cox and MP3.com have said they plan to build new,
independent sites, which may well incorporate some of the
strategies as well as the security and copyright protection devices
being discussed and displayed at this conference and touted as the
keys to online success.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Internet was invented, its creators were not thinking
about e-commerce,'' said Francois Xavier Nuttall, founder and chief
executive officer of AudioSoft, ``and especially not music
commerce. It's very sophisticated and you need an international
framework and technical devices to make this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly twice as many music industry executives as last year are
attending this conference. They want to find out how to make music
merchandizing on the Web profitiable for themselves and fun for
their customers without cutting into the business of music stores
or deprive artists of royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Dowloadable digital music is the final frontier in the world of
electronic commerce. Part of the reason it's been so late in coming
is not just security and copyright issues, but the sheer number of
parties involved who all want to profit: retailers, record
companies, musicians and consumers, who want still more ways to buy
music in a way that's quick, inexpensive and fun.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout at conferences such as this one seems to indicate
the recording industry wants to adapt, or as analyst Mark Mooridian
put it, ``to stop worrying and learn to love MP3.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3 demonization obscures the greater marketing profits and
start-up initiaves,'' Mooridian told the standing-room only
audience. He said today's market was for ``physical online sales''
of prerecorded material, but he said the industry will eventually
move toward digital downloads as a source of online sales. ``It's
more efficient and will make people more money.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to find anyone here who doesn't want to make
money from digital music downloads. The debates and the arguments
arise over how to do it without compromising any aspect of the
industry as it now exists.
</P>
<P>
   BMG CEO Strauss Zelnick said in his keynote address, ``It will
create new products.Hopefully, a standard recording device will
emerge. We love this. It creates a new demand for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick said it was time for the music industry to seriously
consider the best ways to sell downloadable music on the Web. He
also dismissed the notion that piracy would eat into any potential
online profits. ``Even with the piracy we have now, we are still a
billion-dollar industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He told the crowd change was invevitable, but the industry would
certainly not be destroyed by MP3 or any other digital download
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertainment is going to change. New technology will vastly
improve our products. The Internet is an amazing tool for
communication,'' Zelnick said. ``It can enhance our creativity, but
it cannot replace it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
