<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOVER-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: HOOVER'S IS AN INTERNET COMPANY WITH A DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoover's Inc. has seen its main business grow 145 percent a year
since 1995 and has been in existence for almost a decade. It has
little debt and nearly turned a profit last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it's an Internet stock.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which sells data on more than 14,000 public and
private businesses and institutions, priced its shares at $14
apiece on Tuesday night, raising over $40 million in its initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   While the offering did not generate the buzz that many Internet
companies have created lately, financial analysts say Hoover's may
be around long after the high fliers fall back to earth. They note
that along with its strong record of producing Hoover's Handbook, a
staple of libraries, and a CD-ROM, the company has moved
aggressively to deliver information over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock begins trading on Wednesday, investors will have
a chance to determine how valuable that information is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm for the stock is not the same tone'' as that of
some recent initial offerings, said John Fitzgibbon, a stock
analyst at Redherring.com who says he uses Hoover's frequently.
Shares of Gadzoox Networks Inc., for example, more than tripled on
Tuesday in their first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's sold 3.25 million shares, giving the company a market
value of $160 million. That valuation does not count 6.9 million
more shares that can be issued through stock plans or outstanding
warrants.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Austin, Texas, already had some weighty
investors. Among its largest stockholders are a Time Warner
subsidiary, and a company backed by Michael Milken, the former
Drexel Burnham Lambert junk-bond chief, which just bought a 9
percent stake for about $7.25 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's now gets more than 80 percent of its revenue from
Hoover's Online, its Internet Web site (www.hoovers.com). The
company estimated that it had 30 million page views by 2 million
different people in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those used Hoover's free services. But the company says
it has 29,000 individual subscribers and 1,300 more corporate and
academic accounts. They pay fees ranging from $109.95 a year for
individuals to between $1,500 and $30,000 for institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's Internet sales soared to $7.7 million in the fiscal
year ended March 31, nearly double the level of the previous year.
Total sales were $9.2 million in the most recent fiscal year, with
the balance coming from CD-ROMs and publications. Though Hoover's
posted a $2.2 million net loss for the fiscal year, up from $1.8
million the year before, losses for the two most recent quarters
narrowed from year-earlier periods.
</P>
<P>
   Not that valuation comparisons mean much for Internet stocks,
but the company's numbers stack up well against those of some
competitors. Marketwatch.com, which has a market value of $600
million, had sales of $7 million last year, but a $12.4 million
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's plans to use $10 million from the offering for
marketing purposes. The remaining $30 million will be used to
expand its online products and for general corporate purposes. The
marketing and online expenses will cause operating losses and
negative cash flow ``for the foreseeable future,'' the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Fleming, an analyst with Renaissance Capital, in Greenwich,
Conn., likes the company but notes that it will have to fight to
get the attention of institutional buyers. ``Lots of Web companies
are coming public and competing for attention with other web
startups,'' Fleming said. ``That's been the main concern about
Internet IPOs; there are a lot of them, potentially too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's warnings about future losses, Hoover's
would have turned a profit in the quarter ended in March if it had
not expensed certain noncash stock compensation. The marketing
campaign ``more than likely means losses for the next few
quarters,'' Fleming said. ``Right right now, it is about building
brand equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge Universe LLC, whose primary investors include Milken,
his brother Lowell, and Oracle Corp. chief executive Lawrence
Ellison, has agreed to spend $2 million on Hoover's services, along
with taking a stake in the company. Geoffrey Moore, a senior vice
president at Knowledge Universe, said, ``We don't make short-term
investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's also sold a 2 percent stake last month to NBC, a unit
of General Electric Co., for $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Books Inc., a Time Warner unit, owns 22 percent of
Hoover's, while Media General Inc., the Richmond, Va., newspaper
publisher, owns 19.7 percent. Directors and executive officers hold
11.1 percent. All of the insiders are generally prohibited by the
lead underwriter, J.P. Morgan, from selling their shares for 150
days.
</P>
</TEXT>
