<HEADER>
A7636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-FINANCE-NYT &LR;      07-20 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN GETS PLEDGE OF FALL DEBATE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Miss., Wisc., Vt., S.D., Ky.)  (mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., on Tuesday dropped his
threats to force an immediate Senate confrontation over campaign
finance legislation after winning a commitment from Senate leaders
to hold a full debate no later than mid-October on an overhaul of
the law governing campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   After originally pressing for the debate this week, McCain
called the plan a ``reasonable compromise'' under which Sen. Trent
Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, would allow for the first time
a full-scale debate on the issue across five days with amendments
to be voted on freely.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wisc., said they were hoping
that an unfettered amendment process would allow them to build
support and gain the 60 votes needed to break a filibuster against
their bipartisan legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, for his part, by promising a debate no later than Oct. 12,
avoided an immediate clash that could tie the Senate up in knots
for days when it is trying to pass the annual spending bills. And
he secured a commitment from the two men that they would bring the
issue up only that one time this year.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation sponsored by McCain and Feingold would ban the
unlimited and unregulated donations to political parties known as
soft money. It would also put some restraints on issue advocacy ads
that are thinly veiled commercials designed to support or oppose a
particular federal candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill won a majority vote in both the House and
Senate last year, its sponsors had only 52 supporters in the
Senate, eight short of the 60 needed to break a filibuster. McCain
said he thought he now had 54 votes, ``but we are still not at 60
and I have no illusions about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact it was unclear how many of McCain's allies would have
supported him if he had moved ahead with his threats to tie up the
floor. Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., said Tuesday that he had agreed
to work with McCain but added, ``to try to get it done these next
two weeks would not be a productive move.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have staunchly opposed McCain's bill, saying
it violates constitutional guarantees of free speech. Republicans
also traditionally raise more in soft money than Democrats do.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Feingold said they had not yet decided whether to
begin the autumn debate with the same bill as last year or whether
to strip the legislation down to a core that would ban soft money
and see what other provisions could be added through amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy could prove risky. Ranit Schmelzer, a
spokeswoman for Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the minority leader, said
he considered the McCain-Feingold bill ``the bare minimum. If they
start talking about taking apart the pieces that becomes a problem
for us.'' Democrats have provided the vast majority of the votes
for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   And while McCain said an amendment to raise the current $1,000
limit on individual donations to federal candidates might draw more
Republican votes, Feingold said he would oppose such a provision.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who has led the opposition to the
bill, said that it was ``reasonable to assume'' that he would
launch a filibuster against the legislation again ``if the bill
resembles the form it has been in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
