<SLUG> BC-NETBANK-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NetBank down 12%; earnings fail to hit target
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Net.Bank failed to meet analysts' expectations in its
quarterly earnings report Tuesday. Its shares dropped 12 percent,
closing at $27.06 1/4, down $3.68 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   The company said a weak market for technology stocks hurt its
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Alpharetta-based Net.Bank earned $768,000, or 3 cents per share.
Analysts had expected 4 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank's net interest income for the three months ending June
30 was $4.7 million, an increase of 204 percent over the year-ago
period. Net.Bank said its non-interest income was $232,000, up 123
percent from the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank said it had 39,000 accounts, an increase of 114 percent
since Jan. 1 and 11 percent since June 9.
</P>
<P>
   D.R. Grimes, Net.Bank chief executive, said, ``The market, and
Internet stocks in particular, were down, and we're an Internet
stock. It doesn't have a lot to do with performance.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Keane, who covers Net.Bank for BancBoston Robertson
Stephens, said the stock dropped because the company did not meet
analysts' published expectations. Still, Keane maintains a ``buy''
rating on Net.Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Keane said the company's interest income was less than what he
expected, but accounts grew by $15 million more than Keane had
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Norcross-based CheckFree, which took a 23.7 percent
hit in June when three large banks announced they were forming a
competing company, have started a slow climb back to
pre-announcement levels.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree, which processes electronic payments, closed at $31.37
1/2, down 75 cents. But shares are up 9 percent since falling from
$37.68 3/4 to $28.75 June 23. CheckFree shares are up 34 percent
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Craft, an analyst with EOffering, maintained a
``hold/sell'' rating on CheckFree.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
