<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safety program takes aim at Ohio employers
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ At Hohman Plating &AMP; Mfg., a metal treating
company in Dayton, Ohio, officials constantly look for better ways
to insure the safety of workers who coat products for automotive
and aerospace companies and other customers.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Art Hattan, Hohman sales manager and spokesman, said
the ``Safety Works for You!'' program announced Tuesday in Columbus
by the Ohio Bureau of Workers' Compensation might have something to
offer the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly worth taking a look at,''Hattan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company expects to send a representative to an Aug.
10 town meeting at the Dayton Convention Center to be hosted by the
bureau. The meeting, which will go from 8 a.m. to noon, is one of
12 being held around the state. It is geared toward employers but
is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Through $4 million in grants, low-interest loans of up to
$50,000 and other ingredients, the safety program is aimed at
reducing workplace injuries that cost Ohio employers $1 billion
annually, said James Conrad, bureau administrator.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau usually aids workers after they're injured on the
job. The safety program is an effort to stop injuries before they
happen, Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . We're so sure that safety works for you that we're
putting our money where our mouth is,'' Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are for employers who participate in the bureau's
Drug-Free Workplace program and for employers who want to prevent
``cumulative trauma disorders'' such as back pain, tendinitis and
carpal tunnel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   In the drug program, private sector employers are eligible for
2-1 matching grants up to a maximum of $5,000 from the state. With
the employer's $2,500 share, this would mean a total of $7,500.
Public employers are eligible for 2-1 matching grants up to $10,000
from the state _ which means a total of $15,000 with the employer's
$5,000 contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau will award private and public employers 4-1 matching
grants of up to $40,000 to study and prevent cumulative trauma
disorders. With $10,000 from the employers, this could total
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hattan said Hohman, at 814 Hillrose Ave., might be interested in
applying for the grants but also could seek help with another issue
_ the full face shields that workers are required to wear to comply
with requirements of the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   While the shields are supposed to protect the workers, they're
not comfortable and it's a continuing struggle to persuade
employees not to take them off, Hattan said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety program's loan grants could not be used to find a
solution to this issue, but the company might qualify for one of
the loans, said J.C. Benton, a bureau spokesman. The bureau also
will provide consultants to help employers with concerns such as
the face shields, Benton said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dayton area, the bureau program will help efforts already
under way by the Dayton Area Chamber of Commerce, said John Husted,
chamber vice president for business and economic development. The
Dayton-Miami Valley Safety Council, an affiliate of the National
Safety Council, is housed in the chamber, Husted said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help what we're already doing,'' Husted said. ``We
are, on a continuing basis, trying to help businesses tap into
safety resources and understand how a good, strong safety campaign
within an organization is a cost-saving investment.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is spending $250,000 on television and newspaper
advertising and brochures to promote the program, bureau officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
