<HEADER>
A7645 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS     07-20 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL RECOMMENDS NEW ALLOCATION SYSTEM FOR LIVER TRANSPLANTS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an attempt to settle a bitter economic and
scientific feud over who should get donated organs, a panel of
independent experts on Tuesday recommended that scarce livers be
distributed across broad geographic areas so that the sickest
patients receive them first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current system of organ procurement and allocation works
reasonably well,'' Dr. Edward Penhoet, who chaired the panel at the
Institute of Medicine that drafted the report, said in a prepared
statement. ``But significant improvements in both its fairness and
effectiveness could be made.''
</P>
<P>
   The report comes 15 months after the Clinton administration
ordered the United Network for Organ Sharing, the private
organization that runs the allocation system, to revamp its system
so that organs are shared more broadly across city and state lines.
But the network complained so vigorously that Congress delayed the
regulation until Oct. 21 and asked the Institute of Medicine, an
arm of the National Academy of Sciences, to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   With the long-awaited report now in hand, Donna Shalala, the
secretary of health and human services, said on Tuesday that she
would revise the regulation so that the rule can quickly be put
into effect. ``The bottom line is clear,'' Shalala said in a
statement. ``Changes are needed to better serve patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, Congress will have the final say. If the
moratorium is not lifted by Congress by Oct. 21, Shalala can put
the rule into place. But already, Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla.,
has introduced legislation that would give the organ sharing
network, not the government, control over allocation policies.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's report, a carefully-worded 210-page document, is
as Solomon-like as the dispute it is intended to resolve. It looked
at the use of donated livers _ as opposed to hearts, lungs, kidneys
or pancreases _ because that is where the shortage is most severe,
and found that the current system is ``reasonably equitable for the
most severely ill.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the authors noted, the severely ill make up only 20 percent
of those on the liver transplant waiting list. And at the same
time, the report said Shalala is justified in demanding more
widespread organ sharing. Specifically, it called for the nation to
be broken up into regions of about nine million people each, with
organs distributed to the sickest patients first within each
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that the net result of this will mean that more
transplantation will occur in the most medically urgent
situations,'' Penhoet said to reporters in making the report
public. While patients who are less sick will inevitably have to
wait longer, the panel said its proposal would not adversely affect
them.
</P>
<P>
   The institute initially intended to release the report on
Thursday. But with so much interest in its findings, several news
organizations, including the New York Times, obtained draft copies
of the report independently. That prompted the institute to make
the study public on Tuesday. Within hours after the study was made
public, both sides pronounced themselves vindicated. ``The system
is fair,'' said Margo Akerman, a kidney transplant recipient and
vice president of the organ sharing network. ``It is time to
withdraw the regulation, rethink it and rewrite it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shalala countered that the panel's findings ``strongly
validate the concerns which HHS has had about the present system,
and they support the approach we have put forward for improving
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Human organs are the nation's scarcest medical resource. An
estimated 62,000 Americans are currently waiting for a heart, lung,
liver, kidney or pancreas, and 4,000 people died last year before
they could get one. So intense is the fight for access to organs
that last year, when Shalala announced her plan, some states
responded by passing laws that prohibited organs from being shipped
to hospitals in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, which has been in place since Congress
passed the National Organ Transplant Act in 1984, patients are
ranked according to the severity of their sickness. The nation is
divided into 62 local areas, which range in size from a few
counties, to entire states, to several states, and range in
population from 1 million to 12 million. Those 62 areas are lumped
into 11 regions. When an organ becomes available, it is offered
locally first. If a matching patient is not found, it is then
offered regionally.
</P>
<P>
   But the waiting time varies greatly from area to area and region
to region. In announcing the new rule last year, the government
noted that a patient with Type O blood in need of a liver
transplant in New York City might wait 511 days for a transplant,
while a patient in the same category might wait only 56 days in
nearby Newark, N.J. Shalala said her goal was to even out those
waiting times.
</P>
<P>
   But the 16-member panel of scientific experts, which did not
include transplant surgeons because the institute did not believe
they could be objective, found that the discussion of waiting time,
``which has dominated the policy debate, is a poor measure of
differences in access to transplantation.''
</P>
<P>
   In analyzing records of 68,000 liver patients who were on
waiting lists between 1995 and the beginning of this year, it found
that the times were relatively even, about three or four days, for
the sickest patients. The authors recommended that decisions about
whether less urgent patients should receive organs be based soley
on medical criteria, as opposed to how long they have been waiting.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the panel concluded that the network needs to
make better information available to the public so that the system,
in Penhoet's words, can become ``much more transparent.'' The
current perception, he said in an interview, is that organs are not
distributed fairly.
</P>
<P>
   The authors also urged the government to create an independent
panel to exercise greater authority over the organ sharing network,
which is run primarily by transplant surgeons who have vigorously
opposed any changes to the current system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot of transplant surgeons running their own
business out there,'' said Nancy Neveloff Dubler, a bioethicist at
Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx who served on the committee.
``It's the chicken coop theory of oversight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
