<TEXT>
<P>
   Smoking settlement spending stirs debate
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Wagner
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Renovating the state morgue in North Dakota.
Repaving sidewalks in California. Bailing out states' debt in New
York and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas on how states should spend their share of $206 billion
from a federal settlement with tobacco companies range from the
bizarre to the expected. And many have little to do with tobacco
prevention or anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio will soon unveil its recommendations on how to spend nearly
$10 billion from the settlement. The state, which will get the
money over the next 25 years, expects receive its first check _
$120 million _ next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio will likely spend its money in more conventional ways.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggestions: Repair Ohio's aging school buildings, finance
health care for the working poor, provide tax cuts, increase
technology at universities and fund anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco prevention experts on Tuesday at the Midwestern
Legislative Conference told lawmakers and officials from 11 states
that they should spend large chunks of their money to keep kids
away from cigarettes and other tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the opportunity exists for you to attack the Number
One preventable cause of death in this country,'' said Peter
Fisher, of the National Center for Tobacco-Free Kids. ``The
opportunity is in your hands I just hope you seize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio lawmakers will decide how to spend annual payments ranging
from $323 million to $422 million. A task force assembled by Gov.
Bob Taft is close to recommending how to spend the money. Groups'
requests are expected to exceed the $10 billion Ohio will receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of suggestions and it's important we
listen to all of the ideas,'' said Ohio House Speaker Jo Ann
Davidson, R-Reynoldsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Major tobacco companies agreed to a ``master settlement
agreement'' last November and experts say the amount could grow
beyond $206 billion.
</P>
<P>
   State governments then had to fight Washington for the money.
U.S. Sen. George Voinovich, Ohio's former governor, led an effort
in Congress to block the Clinton administration from using any of
the tobacco money to support Medicaid and other health care
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The states won that battle, but some officials say federal
lawmakers will still try to keep money from state governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sentiment in Washington that `we let the states
have $206 billion so now we can take away some of their welfare
money, we can take away some of their Medicaid money,''' said Mike
Dawson, Voinovich's press secretary. ``This fight is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   Spending the money on anti-smoking programs is especially
important in Ohio, which leads the nation in smoking among males
and is third among all adult smokers, according to a 1996 Centers
for Disease Control study. Nearly 20,000 people die in Ohio each
year from smoking-related illnesses such as heart attacks and lung
cancer, according to the Ohio Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy of ideas on how to spend the money reaches far beyond
the Midwest. Many states plan to use large portions on projects
other than anti-tobacco programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles mayor has proposed using some money to repave
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island's governor wants to use the money to help eliminate
a car tax.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana, Idaho and New York may use tobacco settlement funds
to reduce state debts.
</P>
<P>
   And in North Dakota, the governor has talked about using part of
the proceeds to renovate the state's morgue.
</P>
<P>
   A few states _ Maryland, Virginia, Florida, Montana, Maine,
Arizona, Minnesota and Washington _ have agreed to use large
portions of their settlement funds for anti-tobacco efforts,
according to a survey by the American Heart Association and the
Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe morgue construction is the best way to spend the
money,'' said M. Cass Wheeler, chief executive officer of the
American Heart Association, ``because approximately 1.2 million
kids start smoking each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
