<HEADER>
A7654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ACC-GATECH-COX     07-20 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ACC-GATECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackets eager to challenge 'Noles
 &HT;    By J. C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The conversation seems to come up every year.
Each season that Florida State has ruled the ACC, it seems some
team gets the, uh, honor of being tabbed to make a charge at the
Seminoles' dominance.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Georgia Tech, 10-2 a year ago, gets the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Yellow Jackets quarterback Joe Hamilton said
Tuesday at the ACC Kickoff. ``They're no Goliath. ... But you have
to understand, just being picked to challenge them doesn't mean you
will beat them. You have to go out there and beat them yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto, adds Tech coach George O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity down there,'' the fifth-year Jackets
coach, who is 0-4 against FSU, says of the Sept. 11 game at
Tallahassee. ``But it's funny, our kids really love playing that
game. They really love getting after that type of team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think you sneak up on them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for certain.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina and Virginia have taken more stabs at being the
designated Seminoles slayer. Albeit, not with any success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've haven't been able to pull the trigger,'' coach Carl
Torbush laments about the Tar Heels, who are 0-7 against FSU in
conference play, and three times have finished as ACC bridesmaids
to the 'Noles.
</P>
<P>
   The Heels are not alone in their plight.
</P>
<P>
   Since entering the ACC in 1992, FSU is 54-2, with five outright,
unbeaten league titles, and twice has shared the trophy with a
single loss.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia did stop the Seminoles' 31-0 ACC start with a 33-28
upset in 1995, and North Carolina State stunned FSU 24-7 last
season. But with the Seminoles returning 16 starters from a team
which played for the national championship, there's little wonder
Tech's chances of reversing the ACC's fortunes are not deemed good
by most.
</P>
<P>
   In a preseason media poll, FSU received 84 of 87 first-place
votes with Tech receiving the other three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until somebody is able to do it, they're still who they are,''
Torbush said. ``I've said it time and time again: `It's not like
they're going to get worse. Everybody has to get better, or get
whipped.'''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, this will be the best Georgia Tech team since 1990
when the Jackets won a share of the national championship.
Hamilton, a contender for the Heisman Trophy, is a proven winner
who commands an impressive, diversified offense (2,255 yards
passing, 2,021 rushing yards in `98), with a strong stable of
running backs and talented, speedy receivers.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, Tech surrendered a lot of yards last season (397 per
game), but played many younger players during second-half blowouts.
The added experience should mean improved depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can compete with everybody I've seen in the Top
10,'' O'Leary said. ``Now, whether you can beat them or not, that's
the difference. (But) right now we're very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   To topple FSU, however, the Jackets, who played the `Noles close
for three quarters but lost 34-7 last season after Hamilton was
injured, will have to overcome two hurdles _ one mental, the other
physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just believing you can win, that's the biggest thing about
playing Florida State,'' Hamilton said. ``You just have to be the
one (team) on that given day to go down there and do it. That's the
bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the other part of the beat-FSU-equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play them because its a contact game,'' O'Leary
said. ``They play it the way it's supposed to be played and I enjoy
playing football that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better go in ready to play: Tape 'em tight, buckle your
chin straps. That's the way you beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, O'Leary put his team through a physical spring
practice. All designed for one purpose _ to beat Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach O'Leary doesn't do things without letting you know
why,'' Hamilton said. ``He told us we needed to be a more physical
team.''
</P>
<P>
   J. C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
