<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-NY-SCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAD AND THE CURIOUS KEEP FLOCKING TO KENNEDY'S STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KENNEDY-RDP, KENNEDY-PILOT, KENNEDY-NJ-AIRPORT) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT19 and NYT20, which may be used with this
story, have been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They came with votive candles, handwritten poems,
American flags and video cameras. Since last Saturday, when the
news broke that John F. Kennedy Jr. was missing over the sea off
Martha's Vineyard, people have been flocking to this cobblestone
street in lower Manhattan where Kennedy and his wife, Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy, lived during their three years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday night, the sidewalk in front of 20 N. Moore St. had
become so clogged with visitors that more than a dozen police
officers were called in to control the flow of the mourners and the
merely curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep it moving, folks,'' an officer kept yelling to the crowd.
``Limit yourself to one picture and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   A ring of wooden barricades hemmed in the throngs as well as the
phalanx of television reporters from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those in the crowd, like Leslie Hogan, 57, discreetly
wept as she laid a bouquet of roses on the growing floral shrine.
Although she never met him, Ms. Hogan, a flight attendant for Delta
Airlines, said she felt an indescribable kinship with Kennedy. ``I
was 27 when he was born, and I remember everything about his
life,'' she said. ``His life is interwoven with the fabric of
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Raisa Mammon, 60, an immigrant from Russia, said she came out
from Brooklyn to pay her respects to the son of a president who
meant so much to her. ``Kennedy was such a good man,'' she said in
halting English. ``When he died, all the workers cried. I feel so
sad for this boy, so, so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who stopped to read the handwritten tributes or
pose for a snapshot in front of the shrine were tourists excited by
the scene; others simply wanted to witness a bit of history.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki Cerbo drove in from New Jersey with her daughter after
spending the last three days watching television coverage about the
Kennedy plane crash. ``I just wanted to be here,'' she said after
asking a stranger to take a picture of her and her 15-month-old
daughter, Gianna Marie. She laid three white carnations on the
pile, and released a white balloon.
</P>
<P>
   A single mother who is studying computers, Ms. Cerbo, 29, said
she believed her generation had missed out on the excitement and
the momentous tragedies of the 1960s. ``Until now, I felt that
nothing major had happened in my lifetime,'' she said. ``This is
really history in the making, and I want me and my daughter to be
part of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
