</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-NJ-AIRPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRATERNITY OF PILOTS MOURNS A COLLEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (See also KENNEDY-RDP, KENNEDY-PILOT) 
(DW) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, N.J. _ At the Essex County Airport, the last spot on
earth that John F. Kennedy Jr. walked, well-wishers brought flowers
and hand-penned messages over the last couple of days, and pilots
talked of him as if he was one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief time, Kennedy was a member of an exclusive club of
those for whom the romance of flying is bound up tightly with all
the precision and paperwork that taking to the skies demands. It
was from this airport that Kennedy took off on Friday evening, as
he had many times since he bought his six-seat Piper Saratoga II HP
several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, his plane plunged into the waters off Martha's
Vineyard, presumably ending his life and that of his wife Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy and sister-in-law, Lauren G. Bessette, who were
flying with him. But here at the airport, where everyone shares the
love of flight, it was difficult to find critics of Kennedy's
decision to take off after sundown, even though he had limited
experience flying at night, when a dependence on instrument
readings is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was inexperienced,'' said Richard Duffy, 51,
a court clerk who drove in the middle of the day to the Essex
Airport, where he took flying lessons several years ago, because he
felt some affinity with the fellow pilot. ``How do you get
experience except by flying?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying at night is very different from flying in the daytime,
but I don't know what happened up there,'' he said. ``Accidents
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators continue to try to find out whether Kennedy's
plane went down because of equipment failure or pilot
disorientation or other problems. But at the airport, which has
been besieged by journalists looking for scraps of evidence about
the plane crash, the members of the flying fraternity were more
prone to judge him as a member of their group _ one who constantly
has to make split-second decisions thousands of feet up in the air
_ rather than as the only son of a slain president who may have
been caught up in the family curse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody makes mistakes,'' said Mark Schachtel, 40, a pilot
for Executive Jet, a charter jet company out of Columbus, Ohio, who
had just flown a corporate jet into Essex County Airport. ``That
doesn't mean you're a bad pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Schachtel, who said he flew into Martha's Vineyard the following
Saturday, refused to criticize Kennedy, even though he said he
himself would not have flown that route at night if he had little
training in instrument reading.
</P>
<P>
   Essex County Airport, about a 20-mile drive west of Manhattan
straight out of the George Washington Bridge, is home to about 350
planes, most of them small private ones like Kennedy's. Owned by
the Essex County Improvement Authority, the airport is spread over
278 acres and dotted with buff-colored hangars housing several
aviation companies that offer flight lessons, rent spaces for
planes and provide maintenance and charters. Every year, officials
said, 251,000 planes take off and land here.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who work at the airport knew Kennedy well enough
to nod hello, as they saw him coming and going or stopping by the
pilot shops. They bristled at the rush to judgment about Kennedy's
decision to fly at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people haven't flown with him, they don't know his skill
level,'' said Edward Gacio, a pilot who was behind the counter at
Caldwell Air Service. ``They didn't see his logbook. That's like
someone saying you're a horrible driver because you're a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy kept his single-engine, six-seat Piper at the southern
end of the airport, a nook protected from the west by a grove of
trees, in an area operated by Airbound Aviation. Tuesday,
Airbound's owner emerged from his office to put a letter in the
mailbox, and politely declined to discuss the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not, out of respect for the family,'' he said,
before going back behind a padlocked chain-link fence. ``John was a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   In an area near the Air Traffic Control tower at the airport,
well-wishers had set up a makeshift memorial.
</P>
<P>
   One sign read: ``John John, Carolyn and Lauren: You were here
last. Now you join JFK with our Almighty Father in the skies
above.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose someone from your community, it's sad,'' Gacio
said. ``People here knew him. He was a pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   But should this accident serve as a reminder about the hazards
of piloting a small plane? Gacio took umbrage at the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Rollerblading in the streets of Manhattan safe?'' he said.
``Probably not, but people do it. It's no more hazardous than
anything else you do in life. As long as you stay within the
confines of the envelope, you're fine. If you don't ... well, we
still don't know what happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
