u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-ART-580&AMP;A     07-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK SEEKS TO REASSURE ARAFAT ABOUT WEST BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also ISRAEL-U.S.-ASSESS, ISRAEL-SETTLERS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak tried to reassure Yasser
Arafat on Tuesday that Israel would move to complete withdrawals
from the West Bank sooner than the 15-month target he had set for
an overall Middle East peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of his maiden voyage to Washington as the
Israeli leader, Barak was replying to complaints on Tuesday by
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, that the 15-month timetable was
unacceptable for carrying out the accords signed in Wye, Md., last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully agree with him,'' Barak said. ``There is no reason to
wait. We do intend to implement the Wye accords. I will check with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wye accords called for Israel to withdraw from another 13.1
percent of the West Bank. But that was stalled under the last prime
minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, and it has been a major concern of
the Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the pressure on Arafat to get Israel to complete
the withdrawals, the Palestine Liberation Organization's Executive
Council said in Ramallah on Sunday night that the Wye accords
should be carried out in their entirety before negotiations begin
on so-called final-status talks. Those talks will address the
boundaries of a Palestinian entity, the disposition of Jerusalem
and the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Barak spent most of Tuesday visiting members of Congress, where
he delivered one of the messages of his visit: that he intends to
stand firm in negotiations that he hopes to have with the
Palestinians and Syrians on not returning to the borders that
existed before the 1967 war, and that Jerusalem will remain the
capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans in Congress, who were a bulwark of support for
Netanyahu, are key to the passage of the administration's requests
for financial aid to Israel _ including $1.2 billion tied to the
Wye accords that President Clinton said this week he wanted
expedited.
</P>
<P>
   Some outspoken supporters of Netanyahu said Tuesday that they
were impressed with the new Israeli leader. Rep. Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, the majority whip, said after meeting Barak that he liked
what he heard.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the House, Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., released
a statement that echoed some of Barak's recent remarks, saying that
Israel _ not the United States _ should be the final decision-maker
about its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you pursue your policies of economic and political security
for Israel, we in Congress firmly believe that in the final
analysis, Israel must determine its own destiny,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's first encounter on Capitol Hill on Tuesday morning was
with 30 Jewish members of Congress, many of whom support
legislation that calls for moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel from
Tel Aviv to Jerusalem soon. Congress enacted a law in 1995 that
called on the administration to move the embassy by May 31 of this
year, but President Clinton used a waiver provision in the law to
delay the move.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress support legislation that would repeal
Clinton's waiver. But at his meeting with congressmen on Tuesday,
Barak gave a muted response to a question about the proposal, a
participant said. The prime minister said the legislation should
not be pushed now, but he added that he would not openly oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have said that mandating the move of the
embassy before negotiations are completed with the Palestinians on
the final status of Jerusalem would make the negotiations almost
impossible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barak was also asked about the transfer of nuclear technology
from Russia to Iran, a congressman said. The prime minister, a
former chief of staff of the Israel Defense Forces, gave a detailed
analysis of the seriousness of the problem and was supportive of
the Clinton administration's efforts to discourage the Russians,
the congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, Barak met with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright for the second time during his visit. They
discussed her scheduled trip to the Middle East, which is expected
to help set the stage for the opening of negotiations between
Israel and President Hafez Assad of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's trip, originally scheduled for the first week of
August, was moved back to the middle of the month to give the
Israelis more time to consult with the Palestinians and the Syrians
and among themselves on how negotiations on an overall settlement
might proceed, administration officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
