<HEADLINE>
AMWEST PROFITS UP 2%  
 GAINS DESPITE RISING FUEL COSTS, Y2K READINESS EXPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
AMWEST AmWest profits up 
2% in 2nd quarter 
AMWEST By PETER CORBETT(at) 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Higher fuel prices and a $9.7 million Y2K-readiness expense
increased operating costs at America West Holdings Corp. in the
second quarter, but the carrier managed to increase profits 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe-based holding company for America West Airlines
reported earnings Tuesday of $42.2 million, or a record $1.06 per
share, a 23.3 percent increase from the second quarter of 1998. The
earnings per share are much higher than profit gains because the
company has been aggressively buying back shares of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   America West has purchased $35.8 million of its stock since it
reported first-quarter earnings in April.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call had predicted per-share earnings
of 90 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the results for the quarter ending June 30 was a
$2.7 million pretax gain on the sale of stock for Priceline.com
Inc., an Internet site for purchasing airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for America West, the ninth-largest U.S. carrier,
increased to $554.2 million from $519.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Operating costs per available seat mile increased 1 percent, due
in part to the Y2K expense and an 11 percent jump in fuel costs to
$53.1 mil lion.
</P>
<P>
   The company spent only $1.2 million in the second quarter of
1998 on preparing for the year 2000, which could affect operation
of some computers.
</P>
<P>
   A fuel-hedging program managed to save the company $1.3 million,
according to Doug Parker, America West executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost per gallon was 51.08 cents, up 3.8 percent from
a year ago. Each penny increase over a year's time costs America
West about $1 million, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Average fuel prices should increase to 55 cents per gallon in
the third quarter and 56 cents in the final quarter of 1999, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger traffic also increased in the second quarter. Revenue
passenger miles were up 4.4 percent. Revenue per available seat
mile was up 0.1 percent to 8.08 cents.
</P>
<P>
   That's despite a 4.8 percent increase in the average length of
the company's flights from 819 miles to 858 miles. America West has
been adding additional long-haul flights to key business markets.
</P>
<P>
   America West reported that the number of employees is up 6.2 per
cent from the second quarter of 1998 and salaries and related costs
increased 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other major carriers also reported profitable second-quarter
results Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest, the sixth-largest carrier in terms of passengers
carried, reported earnings of $120 million, or $1.29 per share.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Southwest said it earned $157.8 million, or 29 cents per
share. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at (602) 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
