<SLUG> BC-BEANIEBABIES-SUSPENSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher who traded toys faces transfer
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Cobb County school board will render a decision
this week regarding a Campbell High School teacher who traded bonus
points for Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Richard Benjamin recommended teacher Carol
Penland be transferred and suspended for 60 days after the
arrangement came to light this spring, and a tribunal of three
board members agreed with his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Penland requested the tribunal, said Betty Gray, a board member
who served on the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   The full board will discuss the matter Thursday during an
executive session and take a vote later that evening, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not prepared to give up,'' said Terry Thomas, the Georgia
Association of Educators attorney who is representing Penland, who
he said has taught for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Beanie swap taught both economics and charity.
Penland, who has given extra credit to students who participated in
food or blood drives, meant to give the Beanies to foster children,
Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very upset about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Penland was awarding 3 points of extra credit to students who
brought her money to buy McDonald's Happy Meals and let her keep
the Ty toys the restaurant included as part of a promotion, Gray
said.
</P>
<P>
   Students who brought in a Beanie Baby got 5 points, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The district likely will work on guidelines for extra credit,
Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a difficult decision when you want to be fair to
children and employees,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Brett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
