<HEADLINE>
SCENIC TOURIST TRAINS RETURN TO THE ROCKIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANON CITY, Colo. _ A century ago, it was the busiest train
route through the Rockies: a ribbon of rail down a 1,000-foot-deep
canyon, a granite gorge so narrow that at one point, engineers hung
a bridge from the walls to suspend the rails over the rushing
waters of the Arkansas River.
</P>
<P>
   This May, for the first time since 1967, passenger trains
started running again through the ``the Grand Canyon of the
Arkansas,'' a route described by one rail buff and author, David P.
Morgan, in 1960 as ``the most arresting single scenic site in all
of American railroading.''
</P>
<P>
   With air horns echoing off the hard rock walls, the
orange-and-blue streamlined locomotives of the Royal Gorge Route
Railroad now pass through the gorge three times a day, making
24-mile round trips in two hours, with a pause on each run on the
Hanging Bridge. Looking down about 20 feet, passengers can watch
boatloads of rafters battle roiling rapids. Squinting to the sky,
passengers can spy the silvery underbelly of the Royal Gorge
Bridge, the world's highest suspension bridge, strung almost a
quarter-mile overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The return of train whistles to the Royal Gorge is part of a
nationwide renaissance in tourist railroads. Over the last 25
years, the number of tourist trains has roughly doubled, to about
200 today.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the annual peak season for railroading, as many as
five million passengers may travel on tourist trains, according to
Steve Shoe, a former director of the Tourist Railway Association, a
museum and train group.
</P>
<P>
   The leading states are California, with 19 railroads;
Pennsylvania, with 15; and Colorado, with 11. In Colorado, where
2,000 miles of track once penetrated the mineral-rich mountains,
some of the most scenic snippets survive as tourist railroads.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgetown Loop Railroad, (888) 724-5748, leaves Georgetown,
45 minutes west of Denver, and climbs through a series of loops to
Silver Plume. The Ski Train, (303) 296-4754, runs on selected dates
in late summer from Union Station in Denver through the Continental
Divide to Winter Park.
</P>
<P>
   The California Zephyr, an Amtrak train, (800) 872-7245, follows
the same route, attracting a good number of tourists. It leaves
Denver every morning in the summer at 9:20 for Utah, Nevada and
California.
</P>
<P>
   From the other side of the Continental Divide, the Leadville,
Colorado &AMP; Southern Railroad, (719) 486-3936, leaves Leadville, the
nation's highest incorporated town (10,152 feet), for a
high-altitude ride that affords stunning views of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Near Colorado Springs, the Cripple Creek &AMP; Victor Narrow Gauge
Railroad, (719) 689-2640, goes to the ghost town Anaconda. Also in
that area, the Manitou &AMP; Pikes Peak Railway Co., (719) 685-5401,
climbs to the 14,110-foot summit of Pikes Peak, making it the
world's highest cog railway.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Colorado, the Durango &AMP; Silverton Narrow Gauge
Railroad, (970) 247-2733, used in the filming of ``Butch Cassidy
and the Sundance Kid,'' travels through remote areas of the San
Juan Mountains reachable only by train. Another stretch of that
historic railroad lives on today as the Cumbres &AMP; Toltec Scenic
Railroad, (719) 376-5483. Covering 64 miles and climbing to 10,015
feet, it is the nation's longest and highest narrow-gauge steam
railroad.
</P>
<P>
   By 2003, a tourist-train operator hopes to restore service to a
third mountain section of the old Denver &AMP; Rio Grande Western, a
22-mile stretch between Creede and South Fork.
</P>
<P>
   With 800,000 people expected to ride tourist trains in Colorado
this summer, it is clear that these excursions attract a wider
audience than rail buffs.
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition, the Royal Gorge Route train, leaves at 9
a.m., noon and 3 p.m. daily from the newly restored 1913 depot in
Canon City, (888) 724-5748, an hour's drive from Colorado Springs.
As the train progresses up the standard-gauge track, the gorge
narrows and evidence appears of the Royal Gorge War of 1877, a
fierce competition between two railroad companies to get through
the gorge, a natural bottleneck, to reach the rich silver mines of
Leadville.
</P>
<P>
   On the south bank, a rail bed graded by the losing company was
later used for a wooden water pipe, which brought drinking water to
Canon City until it was abandoned in 1974. Rail workers traded
potshots from stone forts, remnants of which are visible to the
riders.
</P>
<P>
   Today's passengers, needing protection only from the sun, can
watch the passing scenery from a roofless observation car. Moving
slowly through the gorge, the train, pulled by diesel electric
locomotives, offers views of rafters fighting Class 5 rapids, one
grade below impassable. On one June Sunday, the noon train
evacuated the casualties of the rocks: two injured and one dead.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp-eyed riders often spy wildlife: ducklings on the river's
quieter stretches, mule deer on far meadows and, occasionally,
Rocky Mountain bighorn sheep. For comfort, the train also offers
five enclosed passenger cars and, at the end of the two-hour ride,
an Italian restaurant awaits at the red-roofed Mediterranean-style
Canon City station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
