<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-YEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO AND YEN MOVE _ IN OPPOSITE DIRECTIONS _ AGAINST THE DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Europe's single currency rallied sharply against the
dollar Tuesday after a key economic report showed business
confidence in Germany growing much more than expected. In contrast,
the dollar climbed against the Japanese yen after the Bank of Japan
sold yen for dollars through the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   For the beleaguered euro, the new currency that had dropped as
much as 13 percent since its introduction in January, the rally may
signal that it has reached a bottom. But what kind of rebound may
be ahead is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   For the yen, the Japanese intervention was aimed at preventing
the currency's value from rising too quickly. This year's rally in
the Japanese stock market, and signs that the economy may be
turning around, have led many investors to jump back into stocks
and into the yen needed to buy them. But a big rally in the yen
would make Japanese exporters less competitive abroad and put a
drag on an economic rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, in trading Tuesday, was worth $1.04130, up from
$1.02940 Monday. Its low for the year was $1.0136 last Wednesday.
Against the yen, the dollar climbed to 118.95 yen, from 117.80 on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The spark for Tuesday's rally by the euro, which represents the
currencies of 11 nations, was a report by the Ifo economic research
institute of Munich that put its business confidence index for
Germany, the largest economy in Europe, at 92.9 in June, up from a
revised 90.5 in May. The rise was much sharper than analysts
expected.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, interest rates in Europe have recently been rising.
While interest rates are still higher in the United States, the
narrowing of the gap increases the euro's attractiveness to
investors. In recent comments, leaders of the European Central Bank
have hinted that their next move will be to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take further confirmation that the economies of
Germany and other European nations are turning around before many
analysts will be ready to declare that the euro can climb back to
its January level of $1.17, and higher.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy P. Fand, senior foreign exchange strategist at
BankBoston, said that he expected that the euro would rally in the
short term. But he has not changed his long-term outlook. In fact,
BankBoston is still predicting that the euro will drop below $1.00
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The intervention to weaken the yen against the dollar Tuesday
was prompted in part by the yen's sharp rise on Monday, when it
jumped 2.3 percent against the dollar. That rally, analysts said,
was started by speculation, which no official confirmed, that
American officials had told the Japanese that the United States
would not help them slow the appreciation of their currency.
</P>
<P>
   To some that meant that the new Treasury secretary, Lawrence
Summers, did not support the strong-dollar policy of his
predecessor, Robert Rubin. After the intervention Tuesday, Summers
said the U.S.' policy favoring a strong dollar had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts do not think that the intervention by the Bank of
Japan alone can keep the yen from getting stronger. Tuesday's yen
selling was the sixth time that Japan has intervened since June 10,
when the yen was 118.96 to the dollar, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``This slows down the recovery of the yen against the dollar,''
said Karen E. Parker, currency strategist at the Chase Manhattan
Bank. She predicts that the yen will rally to a range of 110 to 115
to the dollar in the next 6 to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for one central bank to intervene in the
currency markets on behalf of another central bank, and usually
such a move does not signal any policy change by the central bank
that is asked to intervene. The Bank of Japan probably used the
Federal Reserve Tuesday because Japanese markets were closed for a
holiday and on Monday the yen jumped back to the 118 level, where
the intervention process began on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   The intervention would have been more significant if the Fed
were doing it for its own policy reasons in conjunction with the
Bank of Japan, as it had in June 1998. Then, the Fed joined the
Japanese by intervening to support the yen when it was falling
sharply, threatening to worsen a global economic crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
