<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-DIVERS-BOS &LR;      07-20 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-DIVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERS FOCUSED ON 5 SQUARE MILES OF FOREBODING SEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN AND BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AQUINNAH, Mass. _ The underwater recovery team assigned to
retrieve the bodies of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren Bessette are focused on
five square miles of unpredictable seas off Gay Head Light.
</P>
<P>
   The waters can be foreboding even on tranquil days, but now they
seem even more eerily mysterious because they contain the clues to
a tragedy that has captured the world's attention.
</P>
<P>
   And on Martha's Vineyard itself, the search has cast a grim
shadow over the Aquinnah estate that Jacqueline Onassis Kennedy
treasured and the island where neighbors knew John Jr. since he was
a boy.
</P>
<P>
   As the National Transportation Safety Board directs the
underwater investigation by U.S. Navy and State Police divers,
local sea captains also scanned the Atlantic Ocean for any traces
of debris, and dozens of local volunteers combed the shore for
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The crash has many islanders saying they will never again enjoy
the view from the striking cliffs of Gay Head as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how anyone could go in those waters now,'' said
Anne Vanderhoop, owner of the landmark Aquinnah restaurant where
the Kennedys often dined. ``I don't think I will ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, divers crossed yet another potential target off the
list of those within the possible debris fields. However, officials
said there are at least four others, identified by underwater sonar
equipment, which fit the characteristics of airplane wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of Navy and State Police divers recovering the
bodies will depend on how much of Kennedy's Piper Saratoga HP II
stayed intact when the powerful, single-engine plane smashed into
the ocean, officals said.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to any recovery effort, officials said, is how well
divers can see underwater. And others are mindful that the waters
this time of year attract plenty of sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you don't want to think about,'' said captain
Everett ``Porky'' Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's seas were as flat as they have been for days, and
Francis stood on the tower of his fishing vessel, scanning the
water for evidence of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not hoping to find anything but I feel like I have to
look,'' Francis said, ``because I know those families must be
devastated, not to be able to have a burial.''
</P>
<P>
   While the investigation continues on the ocean, searchers who
have spent days along the pristine southern beaches of Martha's
Vineyard Tuesday ended their quest for clues.
</P>
<P>
   From Tisbury Great Pond eastward to Wasque Point on the tip of
Chappaquiddick Island, three dozen walkers and support personnel,
working in teams, scanned scattered clumps of seaweed and man-made
debris that the surf had cast up on 12 miles of shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   The search concentrated on beaches that had not yet been
examined for evidence of the crash. By now, the entire southern
coast of the island has been covered.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's yield: a headrest believed to be from Kennedy's plane,
and various pieces of shattered plastic that also might have been
ripped from the aircraft on impact, search coordinators said.
</P>
<P>
   Each item _ even sightings of unidentifiable objects at sea _
were reported to the Dukes County search-and-rescue command center
at South Beach in Edgartown. Satellite readings were used to log
the precise location of each artifact.
</P>
<P>
   For Paul ``Zeke'' Wilkins, an Oak Bluffs resident who led one of
the teams, his three-mile trek westward from South Beach might have
been the last of a volunteer effort that began Saturday. No
additional searches are scheduled; ``The manpower resources have
run out,'' said William Searle, search-and-rescue coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us want to have closure to this,'' said Wilkins, a
41-year-old carpenter who sacrificed a couple of paydays to scour
the beaches. ``It's not just because it's a Kennedy and a Bessette.
We would go out there for the likes of you and I. At least I hope
they would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem a little trivial, but at this point of the search,
anything is worth investigating,'' Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers, whose idea of civic service includes trudging
through shifting beach sand in hot, heavy boots, do not boast. They
speak economically and good-naturedly, and they have an awed
respect for the power of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ocean doesn't give up its secrets. That's my personal
opinion,'' Wilkins said. ``The ocean just seems to swallow them
up.''
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the intense shoreline search, the investigation
now centers soley on a six-mile section of the sea. As the nation
waits for recovery of the wreckage that could explain the crash,
some who knew John Kennedy Jr. and remember him walking hand in
hand along the beach said they do not need to suffer the sight of
the recovery of his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's better to have a watery grave,'' Vanderhoop said.
``Maybe it's just better to let him rest here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
