<HEADER>
A7678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-REPORT-1STLD-WR     07-20 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRADE DEFICIT BREAKS ANOTHER RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Adds to earlier story, starting with 10th graf, ``The
Japanese...'')  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A surge of imports driven by the continued strength
of the American economy pushed the U.S. trade deficit to another
record in May _ over $21 billion, a figure fueled by rising oil
prices and growing evidence that China is using exports to support
its lagging economy.
</P>
<P>
   The China deficit comes at a politically inopportune time for
the Clinton administration: Next week the House of Representatives
is expected to vote on a one-year renewal of China's preferential
trade status.
</P>
<P>
   While the House is expected to approve the measure, the rising
deficit with China _ it totaled more than $23 billion in the first
five months of 1999 _ further complicates a relationship already
deeply strained by the accidental bombing of the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, and China's renewed threats to use force if
necessary to keep Taiwan from declaring itself an independent
state.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit is also one of the few economic indicators
that Republican candidates for the presidential nomination can
seize upon to argue that not all is well with the U.S. economy. But
it is, in fact, a byproduct of American economic health: With
unemployment here at record lows, low-cost imports have helped keep
inflation to near zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``The May trade figures reflect the continuing large gap between
the strong growth in the United States and weaker conditions in
many foreign countries,'' Commerce Secretary William Daley said
Tuesday. He estimated that the deficit was running at an annual
rate of $224.8 billion, which would total nearly 37 percent more
than last year's record of $164.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   China is not the only cause: The trade deficit with Japan
remains large _ though it dropped slightly in May _ and there is a
rising deficit with Canada and Mexico, the two other members of the
North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the May deficit surprised many economists, and led a
few on Tuesday to lower modestly their predictions for American
economic growth in the second quarter. But perhaps more important,
it was a strong indication that the U.S. consumer spending binge is
moving ahead unabated, which is bound to worry the Federal Reserve
Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago if we had seen numbers like this, what you
would have heard on Capitol Hill was politicians blaming the
Japanese and the Chinese,'' said Richard Medley, who heads Medley
Global Advisors, an international investment firm in New York.
``Now what you hear more often is that this proves we are spending
too much and saving too little.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact a number of economists and U.S. officials are
increasingly concerned that the accumulating current account
deficit could ultimately hurt the value of the dollar _ and that,
in turn, could trigger an international exodus from the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese, meanwhile, are clearly worried about the effects
of a weakening dollar _ not on the United States but on their own
hobbled economy. They intervened Monday night to weaken the yen and
prop up the dollar, in hopes of making their own exports cheaper on
world markets.
</P>
<P>
   While the purchase was carried out through the New York Federal
Reserve, acting as Japan's agent, there are increasing signs that
the United States and Japan are at odds on exchange-rate policy. A
stronger dollar would further hurt declining U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report suggested that the decline is modest but is
made worse by the growing demand for foreign-made cars, crude oil
and medium-technology electronics. Oil prices increased in May to
an average of $14.54 a barrel, the Commerce Department said, from
$12.71 a barrel in April.
</P>
<P>
   Exports decreased to $77.6 billion from $78.2 billion in April,
but they were up fractionally from May 1998. Imports increased to
$98.9 billion from $96.8 billion in April and $92 billion a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures suggest that some of the areas that the
Clinton administration concentrated hardest on bolstering during
President Clinton's first term in office _ autos, auto parts and
machinery _ are the exports now in greatest decline. They are also
the products that are being imported in increasing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials who once boasted of the auto and
auto-parts agreement they reached with Japan in 1995, after a trade
dispute that nearly resulted in an embargo on Japanese luxury cars,
now rarely discuss the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there much discussion from the White House about how to
deal with the complex trade problems with China. Overall, Chinese
exports to the world are in decline. But their continued rise here
suggests that the United States, now more than ever, has become the
market of last resort for the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the trade deficit with China are messy.
Opponents of Clinton's China policy _ on both the left and the
right _ say the trade figures show that the president's decision to
delink human rights and the annual renewal of China's trade status
has helped neither dissidents nor American companies. Arrests by
Chinese authorities continue _ there was a major crackdown on
Tuesday _ and exports to China are clearly not increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there has been little real resistance to the renewal of what
was once called ``most favored nation'' trade status, which has
been delicately renamed ``normal trade relations.'' U.S. companies
have argued annually on Capitol Hill that unless China has the
benefit of low tariffs on their imports here, the Chinese market
will gradually be shut down for them.
</P>
<P>
   If China and the United States reach an agreement this year on
Beijing's entry to the World Trade Organization, the terms of its
move to join the group should, in theory at least, open more
markets to U.S. goods.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents on Capitol Hill, both those on the left who are
concerned with China's human rights record and those on the right
who see the country as a growing threat, view WTO admission as a
favor to the Chinese, and not one that will necessarily benefit
American workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
