<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY WAS LOST OR DISORIENTED, EXPERTS BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: An expanded version is tentatively scheduled to move by 10
p.m.) 
(With KENNEDY-PILOT, KENNEDY-SCENE, KENNEDY-TEXT,
KENNEDY-BESSETTE-TEXT) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURNE, Mass. _ John F. Kennedy Jr. turned sharply away from
Martha's Vineyard before his plane began plunging toward the sea,
federal investigators said Tuesday, leading several authorities on
aviation to conclude that he had become lost or disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure came on the fourth day of an around-the-clock
search for the wrecked plane and the remains of Kennedy and his two
passengers, and investigators warned that they might never find any
large pieces of the plane. The six-seat Piper Saratoga hit the
Atlantic Ocean at a speed that ``might be more than 5,000 feet per
minute,'' according to Robert Pearce, who is leading the
investigation for the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 38, had been heading for a family wedding on Friday
night with his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, 33, and his
sister-in-law, Lauren Bessette, 34. Radar records are beginning to
fill in the harrowing details of their last seven minutes. At a
news conference Tuesday evening, Pearce said that Kennedy had been
headed straight toward Martha's Vineyard, about 34 miles out and
traveling at 5,600 feet, when the plane began to descend at about
700 feet per minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The descent continued for about five minutes to 2,300 feet,
when the airplane was about 20 miles from the airport,'' Pearce
said. ``The airplane started a turn to the right and climbed back
to 2,600 feet. It remained at that altitude for about one minute on
a southeasterly heading. Thirty seconds into the maneuver, the
airplane started a turn to the right and descended at a rapid rate
of descent. The rate of descent may have been greater than 5,000
feet per minute. The last radar return was about 16 miles from the
airport and the altitude indicated 1,100 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Kennedy was headed away from the airport when
the plunge began. Pearce would not characterize the information
beyond saying that Kennedy had been on the right path before he
began turning. ``Anything from that would not go to Martha's
Vineyard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Barr, the director of the Aviation Safety Program at the
University of Southern California, a leading training center for
accident investigators, said Kennedy apparently lost his way after
making the first turn, then went into a dive as he tried to right
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this getting yourself in a square corner, when you run
out of ideas and experience at the same time,'' said Barr, who was
a fighter pilot during the Vietnam War. ``He would have been
looking straight out at the dark ocean on a nearly moonless night.
He probably looked over his right shoulder for lights, then when he
started to sink, he would have been trying to get the nose back to
the horizon, get the wings level and find where he was, all at the
same time. Even for a good pilot, that could produce a death
spiral.''
</P>
<P>
   An armada of search and salvage vessels planned to work all
night as officials here on Cape Cod and in Washington were peppered
with questions about the propriety of continuing what could be a
fruitless search. President Clinton, who has continued to talk with
the Kennedy family since the crash, said Monday that he believed
the search should continue. A White House official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, acknowledged that the recovery effort had
reached the point that it ordinarily would be called off. But the
official said the government does not want to leave any wreckage
that private salvage firms or curiosity-seekers might try to
retrieve.
</P>
<P>
   The president's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said Clinton had not
given any specific order to federal agencies to go all out in the
search. ``But given the national interest in this and extraordinary
contributions that the Kennedy family has made to the country and
the pain they've gone through, he believes we should see this
through to resolution,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference here, Rear Adm. Richard Larrabee of the
Coast Guard was asked how long he would continue what could be a
fruitless search. ``You know, that's a question that I think we
have been pondering and certainly I have been pondering,'' he said.
``We've used the word `a reasonable amount of time.''' He went on,
``When we get to the point where we believe that we're no longer
effectively doing something out there, we will get to that point
and conclude this phase.''
</P>
<P>
   The delay in finding bodies poses an awkward dilemma as Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and other family members try to plan a
funeral or memorial service. The Kennedy family has not requested
that Kennedy be buried with his parents, at the eternal flame in
Arlington National Cemetery, a White House official said Tuesday
afternoon. ``We don't think they are going to ask,'' the official
added, citing informal contacts with members of the family. Because
Kennedy does not qualify for burial in the military cemetery,
interment there would require a presidential waiver.
</P>
<P>
   As the family waits in seclusion at Hyannis Port, two Navy
ships, two Coast Guard cutters and two research vessels from the
National Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration are being
used in the effort to map the sea off of Martha's Vineyard, using
high-resolution sonar to detect objects with straight edges,
indicating they are manmade. Then 10 divers from the Massachusetts
State Police and 20 from the Navy use those maps to look for
wreckage. But many of the seemingly promising targets turn out to
be things like barrels or fishnets.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, investigators zeroed in on an area that is
described as a few hundred yards in diameter. Sonar images
suggested it could contain pieces of plane, and it was close to the
theoretical ``splash point,'' or crash site, that investigators had
determined using computer models. Nothing had been determined by
nightfall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
