<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7680 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOMENT-AZR &LR;      07-20 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMENT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE WERE YOU? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the stunning display of media attention might suggest
otherwise, the crash deaths of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and
sister-in-law probably will never in the future register as a
``where-were-you-when'' moment.
</P>
<P>
   These are the moments that so often define who we are as much as
where we were. Every generation has its own litany of traumatic
moments, but the ones that last as cultural signposts are the ones
that cut us most deeply to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more rarely, those things that uplifted us beyond our own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The defining traumatic event for anyone in their mid-40s or
older is the assasination of JFK. It would be a tough challenge to
find any lucid person in that age group who doesn't remember that
moment on a Friday afternoon in 1963 when that horrifying piece of
news was first heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment is frozen in time, and we remember how we felt and
what we were thinking,'' said Gloria Malone, a Paradise Valley
psychologist. ``Where you were and who told you, you remember these
things because of the shock and the sadness that followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These memories that shock, that trauma is formed in your mind
for all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Shock, disbelief, denial and grief. The stronger these emotions
are, the more likely a moment will become etched in our memories.
Personal losses and tragedies that touch close to home have all
these ingredients, naturally, and remain with us always.
</P>
<P>
   But public, widely acknowledged traumas that today are closely
linked with the news media also register personally while becoming
part of the collective memory. Remembering the assassinations of
Robert Kennedy and Martin Luther King, the plane crash that killed
Buddy Holly, Richie Valens and J.P. ``The Big Bopper'' Richardson,
the death of Elvis Presley, and murder of ex-Beatle John Lennon all
produce that time-freezing recollection of where you were, what you
were doing and who told you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When JFK was killed, I was at an awards ceremony in high
school,'' Malone said. ``When RFK was killed, I heard about it when
I was coming home from a date.''
</P>
<P>
   For a generation that has passed, the sinking of the Titanic or
the traumas of World War I would have had that effect. For senior
citizens today, it would be those events surrounding World War II,
the bombing of Pearl Harbor, the death of President Roosevelt and
the atomic bombs over Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And younger people have their own traumas to mull over. The
Challenger disaster, the Oklahoma City bombing, the deaths of
grunge-rock pioneer Kurt Cobain and Princess Diana. Or even the
bizarre televised coverage of the O.J. Simpson ``slow-speed
chase.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John Lennon would be my first memory,'' said Nina Moore, a
36-year-old Phoenix mother. ``I had just moved out here, and I was
living in my apartment at ASU. I was 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from New York City, plus I have two older brothers, and
one was a major Beatles freak. And I had seen John Lennon in
Central Park many times.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all the collective memories are bad. There are those
splendid moments that so uplift that they can never be forgotten.
Just 30 years ago, the first Apollo moon landing became permanently
ingrained in everyone's mind. Some historians believe that far into
the future, that will be the defining moment of our time.
</P>
<P>
   And there are others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I recall was Lindbergh,'' said Lloyd Clark,
76, speaking of the stunning solo crossing in 1927 of the Atlantic
Ocean by Charles Lindbergh. ``I was a tot, 4 or 5 at the time. My
dad and mom took me down to the ``Houston Chronicle'' to pick up
the first edition.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a Sun City historian and journalist, said that although
he is a lifelong newspaper man, many of his memories of great
events of the day surround the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was listening when the Hindenberg crashed, and I can
remember the announcer crying,'' said Clark, speaking of the famous
1937 broadcast from Lakehurst, New Jersey, that culminated with,
``Oh, the humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Another frozen-in-time memory, Clark said, was when he and his
family were transfixed by a broadcast from Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Hitler berating the Germans, and they were giving the
sieg heils,'' he said. ``I could hear them over the radio set we
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was chilling. He was ranting. He was getting them to a
fever pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pearl Harbor attack is another powerful memory, he added,
recalling how he was in the ROTC in high school, marching out on
the field with his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we began to parade out, we saw people gathering in two
clusters, one around a car that had a radio, and the other around a
portable radio in the stands,'' Clark said. ``They were listening
to accounts of Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard planes flying overhead, and they were two P-38s
racing toward the West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that one monumental event that is only dimly recalled
today is the ``greatest industrial disaster that ever happened in
the United States,'' the horrendous harbor explosion in 1946 in
Texas City, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Another event that made a big impact in its day, he added, was
the 1945 crash of a B-25 into the Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   But the tragedies of the Kennedys keep coming back to haunt us
all. It's one reason why the death of the man whom so many people
remember as a toddler saluting his father's casket should touch us
deeply. Deep enough for now to have meaning for all, but most
likely not deep enough to register as one of the permanent cultural
scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following President Kennedy's death, we began following the
entire family,'' Malone noted. `'There's a lot of disbelief with
such tragic losses, sadness and tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grieve for ourselves as well as for them and their
families. Sudden deaths are very difficult grief losses to
resolve.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
