<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-PAYTON-KIDD-HNS &LR;      07-20 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-PAYTON-KIDD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ A decade ago, when the first Dream Team was
still just a dream, Jason Kidd made his way from ``the hills'' to
``the flats'' and did some fantasizing of his own.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were likely times when he indulged in the usual fantasies
_ last-second shots, championships and All-Star Games.
</P>
<P>
   But when Kidd played at Rainbow Center, the home of the best
competition the East Bay of Oakland could offer, he thought of the
local hero and dreamed of the day he would share a backcourt with
Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always came down to the flats to play with him,'' Kidd said.
``That's where the best basketball was. Wherever Gary was, that's
where there was the best talent. And I always imagined playing with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   As things worked out, Kidd became too great a player himself to
have much of a chance of being paired in an NBA backcourt with
Payton. Players of that level _ to say nothing of the endangered
species of true point guards _ are spread thin.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, however, they are finally running and trapping
together. They have led the almost-cruel defense of the United
States team in its 5-0 start in the Americas Olympic Qualifying
Tournament. They have been the most dominant part of a thoroughly
masterful team. And along the way, they've gotten to live a dream
almost forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like the name of this team, the Dream Team,'' Kidd
said. ``This is a dream opportunity for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Back when Kidd first imagined himself running alongside Payton,
the notion of putting NBA superstars together began gaining steam.
By 1992, Michael Jordan, Charles Barkley, Larry Bird and Magic
Johnson headed the first Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   As a part of that squad's latest descendants, Kidd and Payton
are playing together just as they always imagined. They have
combined to torment opposing ball-handlers. They pass with a flair
and precision that produce too many layups to allow even a thought
of an upset. And when they need to, they score with ease, usually
with layups set up by the other.
</P>
<P>
   Through five tournament games, Kidd is averaging 8.6 points and
8.8 assists. Payton has made 78.3 percent of his shots, averaging
17 points to lead the United States. He is averaging five assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like playing in our pickup games back in the Bay
Area,'' Kidd said. ``It would be a lot of fun to see that 82 games
a year. We could cause a lot of problems picking up full-court. You
know you're really going to have to work.''
</P>
<P>
   On one Dominican Republic possession Monday, Kidd and Payton
trapped Felipe Lopez until Kidd smacked the ball free. Payton began
the break before flipping a no-look, underhanded pass off the
backboard, setting up a Kevin Garnett dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to get the ball,'' Kidd said. ``That's the way we
love to play. We thrive on trying to get the ball from our
opponent. We have fun doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd says that teaming a pair of pressing, ballhawking point
guards in the same backcourt has always been his idea of a
basketball dream, even as he moved on to the NBA and gave it up as
too much to ask for.
</P>
<P>
   The sticky-fingered hunger of the United States backcourt is a
Payton trademark; it gave him the nickname ``The Glove.'' Kidd
emulates that approach, making the Kidd-Glove backcourt perhaps the
greatest nightmare posed by the Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is our offense,'' Kidd said. ``The biggest key for
us is we thrive on playing defense. Everything else is second.
Being able to pass, knocking down a shot, taking the ball to the
basket _ that's secondary for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just overmatched guards in this tournament who are a
poor match for a Payton-Kidd backcourt. Asked if they could
similarly harass NBA guards, Payton said facing him and Kidd
together ``would be hell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've both been first-team all-defense,'' Payton said. ``We
both like to cause havoc, get steals. If we played in the NBA
together, that would be crazy to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both trying to cause havoc and trying to get steals and
to get baskets for our teammates. That's what we do. We just play
like each other.''
</P>
<P>
   On the offensive end, Kidd is a little bit more of a playmaker.
Payton is the better shooter. But this, too, seems to serve the
United States team well. Determined to ``show the right way to
play,'' U.S. coach Larry Brown said his players have been
``unselfish almost to a fault.''
</P>
<P>
   On a team lacking a player with the one-on-one explosiveness of
an Allen Iverson or Stephon Marbury, Payton might be the most
irrepressible offensive talent and thus has been an off guard when
he and Kidd share the court. Against the Dominican Republic, Payton
had 25 points, making 11 of 11 shots inside the 3-point arc, all on
layups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason wants to do more things _ be a rebounder, the assist man
and to get his points when he has to,'' Payton said. ``Right now,
they've got me as a two where they want me to score all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of Payton's successful transition to scorer is that he
considered himself unfairly maligned for assuming a greater scoring
load with the SuperSonics in 1999. Payton said his place on the
Dream Team has been an escape from the disappointment and criticism
of this past season. But scars clearly remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't shoot the ball on our team, we wouldn't have won
25 games,'' Payton said. ``If I didn't score, we probably would
have been 10-40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what they say. If you have talent around you, and
I can go to the basket, I don't have to score 20 and 25 points a
night. (But) nobody else on my team was scoring more than 12, 13
points. And we struggled. We barely won 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a proud man. Every time I go out on the floor, I want to
win. And if it takes me taking the ball and shooting the ball all
the time on the Seattle SuperSonics, I'm going to do it. And if
they don't like it, tell them to go get another team and trade
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has joked about playing with Kidd again, Payton said
he has not asked to be dealt. He would prefer that the Sonics work
to upgrade the talent around him. If that happens, he said, he
would assume the responsibility to lead it and would accept
criticism if he cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle, but I had to deal with it,'' Payton said of
last season. ``I had to try to bring my play up to another level.
Then I was criticized. They would have criticized me for not doing
it. Then they criticized me for doing it. So what can I do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the hole. If something happens to the team, it's always
the best player on the team's fault. So I take it. I'll take the
blame.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, there are no critics, no losses to explain. And for
Payton, there is a specific dream to live on the Dream Team. A
breath after he lamented the toughest of his 10 NBA seasons,
Payton's mind turned to the sort of daydreaming Kidd enjoyed back
in Oakland. It is still a comforting thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a guard like Jason playing with me, and I could be
on the two, and I could score when I want to score and pass the
ball and know I'm going to get the ball back to a point guard that
is going to do good things with it, yeah, I'd be happy with that,''
Payton said. ``I don't care. I could score 10 points or whatever.
If I can have fun like this, I'm going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm having a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd always expected as much. Living the dream of youth should
be, at the very least, fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
