<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAS-PRICES-SFCHRON &LR;      07-20 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WHOPPING LEAP FOR BAY AREA GAS PRICES  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Bay Area gasoline prices have soared in the past
month to an average $1.61 a gallon, or 44 cents more than the
national average, the California State Automobile Association said
Tuesday.
<P>
   This is a full dime more than four weeks ago, the association
reported, attributing the increase mainly to production cutbacks
resulting from fires and an explosion at local refineries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices will continue to creep up or may level off, but we
won't see any relief any time soon,'' said &UR;  &LR; Paul Moreno, spokesman
for the state chapter of the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Chevron Corp. was granted permission to sell
``dirty'' gasoline that violates California's stringent
environmental standards. The company said its gas stations might
otherwise run out of fuel following a blast at Chevron's Richmond,
Calif., refinery on July 10, which has left the facility running at
only 30 percent capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dirty,'' insisted Mike Libbey, a Chevron spokesman.
``It's less clean.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he said the company has not yet brought in any
untreated fuel because additional supplies of environmentally
friendly gas have been found within the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making ends meet right now,'' Libbey said. ``We've found
enough supplies to last the next few days. As for next week, we
don't yet know.''
</P>
<P>
   While Chevron alone is not to blame for the recent increase in
gas prices, its difficulties have exacerbated an already tough
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's Law has been solidly in effect as minor mishaps at
refineries throughout the state have combined with a recent
explosion at a pipeline in Washington State to hamper shipments up
and down the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shortage of gasoline,'' said Rob Schlichting, a
spokesman for the California Energy Commission in Sacramento,
Calif. ``People are having to pay a high price to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the statewide average jumped 8 cents in the last week
to $1.46 a gallon, according to energy commission figures, while
the AAA said the Northern California average has reached $1.59.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be outraged,'' said Linda Sherry, a spokeswoman
for Consumer Action, a San Francisco consumer-advocacy group.
``Even with all the problems, we're still paying much more than we
should.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average consumer feels like he or she is being gouged,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry said past efforts to organize gas boycotts and promote
alternative modes of transportation have pretty much fallen flat.
``People are married to their vehicles,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true in the summer, when millions of
Americans take to the road. The AAA estimates that a record number
of motorists will hit the highway before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   This year, high demand for fuel and assorted snafus at
refineries have gone hand in hand with a run-up in crude oil
prices, which have climbed about $2 in the past two weeks alone.
</P>
<P>
   The AAA's Moreno said all these factors have made for
particularly turbulent prices at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GAS21 (4519 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In the Bay Area, gas prices typically rise or fall a few cents
from month to month. ``But when we get into double digits _ that's
unusual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   California's high gas prices stem in large part from the strict
rules requiring refineries to produce a cleaner-burning formula.
</P>
<P>
   But Moreno also said competition in the state is limited by ``a
gas and oil market that is dominated by vertically integrated
companies that are involved in everything from exploration to
pumping gas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no competition,'' said Will Woods, executive director
of the Automotive Trade Organizations, a nonprofit group
representing about 900 independent service station and repair-shop
owners statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil companies are making life miserable for our members,''
he said. ``They have total control, and nobody does anything about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Severin Borenstein, director of the University of California
Energy Institute in Berkeley, Calif., said a key reason for the
state's high gas prices is that the environmental restrictions
``cut off California from the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that competition is lacking, and that this is
especially the case in the Bay Area, where fewer off-brand gas
stations can be found compared to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But the simple fact, Borenstein stressed, is that the typical
two-car family uses about 80 gallons of gas per month. A 10-cent
increase at the pump means an overall rise of only about $8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people can afford that,'' Borenstein said. ``Drivers are
incredibly insensitive to gasoline prices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
