<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPTION21-AZR &LR;      07-20 1923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION21-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THEM TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   olice found the 10 children hungry and covered with lice in a
trash-strewn house in downtown Phoenix, cockroaches scurrying
across the babies asleep on the soiled floor.
</P>
<P>
   The kids were taken in by child welfare officials, thrust into
different foster homes, shelters and group homes and kept apart for
years.
</P>
<P>
   It will never happen again.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29, Shirley and Van Hughes of Mesa will be named the
children's legal parents, their adoptions final. It is the largest
adoption of a group of siblings that experts _ local and national _
can recall.
</P>
<P>
   But Shirley and Van have been Mom and Dad to &UR; these kids for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love us,'' says Maria, now 8, the first to arrive on the
Hughes' doorstep as a foster child at 3, the rest following over
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank. Teresa. Asucena. Steven. Agustino. Juan. Enrique. Maria.
Veronica. Doni.
</P>
<P>
   Torn from each other when their mother could no longer care for
them, they are a family again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the last day in April in 1995 when police found the 10
children, along with five of their cousins, fending for themselves
in a house near 10th and East Roosevelt streets. Their mother and
her sister, the mother of the other children, had been gone for
days, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, according to court records, had a history of
drunken driving and had spent time in jail. She was unreachable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest boy, Frank, was 14 at the time and sometimes stole
food for his brothers and sisters. Teresa, then just 13, was the
closest thing they had to a mother.
</P>
<P>
   The children have four, maybe five different fathers, Shirley
says. No one knows for sure. Anyway, none of them are around.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; At about the same time police discovered the siblings, Van and
Shirley decided to take in foster children. The last of their own
two sons, both now grown with children of their own, had moved out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too quiet,'' Van says.
</P>
<P>
   So, in June of 1995, Maria, then just 3, arrived. She said
little more than ``yes'' or ``no'' for the first six months. She
did everything she was told though _ and quickly, obviously afraid,
Shirley says, of what would happen if she didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Maria talks a lot _ and happily _ about living here. She
likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to have a big house. My Dad makes a lot of stuff new,
like that,'' she says, pointing to the recently enclosed back
porch. ``He also made us a new air conditioner.''
</P>
<P>
   A month after Maria arrived, state caseworkers asked the Hughes
to take in Enrique, then 5, and Juan, who was 6. They were living
in separate shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Enrique had hair to his shoulders and was mad. He pitched fits
and kicked. Now 9, he's learning to control his temper. He has deep
dimples and plays basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Juan had been told that he was stupid so many times that he
believed it. Now 10, he is his teachers' favorite, Shirley says. He
is a natural soccer player, named the best on his team two years
running.
</P>
<P>
   Then came two more _ 2-year-old Doni and 3-year-old Veronica,
the youngest of the lot.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica, now 6, has a loose tooth. She'll have to repeat
kindergarten because her mother's drinking while she was pregnant
has made it hard for the tiny girl to remember things, like numbers
and letters. &UR; Doctors diagnosed her as being fetal alcohol affected.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Four-year-old Doni suffers because of his mother's drinking,
too, diagnosed as having fetal alcohol syndrome. Like his sister,
he has trouble remembering things. Doni was just 6 months old when
the police found him dirty, congested and running a fever with only
a bottle of spoiled milk in his crib.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy's hearing is bad. He often asks Shirley to repeat
what she says. Still, no matter where he is in the house, he can
hear Shirley pick up the keys to the van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you goin'?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going crazy,'' Shirley tells him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I go?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're driving me there,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Doni follows Shirley everywhere, even camping outside the
bathroom door while she is in there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, with the five youngest children already in the
Hughes' home, state caseworkers asked them to take the older five
as well. Van and Shirley balked. They were 50 and should be
planning their retirement, not another family.
</P>
<P>
   But if they didn't take the remaining five, Shirley says, they
would have been sent to different adoptive homes out of state and
likely never see their siblings again. The kids had been visiting
their brothers and sisters living with the Hughes for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything they have gone through, we couldn't let them
be split up,'' says Shirley, who wears a gold charm on a necklace
that says ``I love Mom,'' a birthday present from the kids.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; So, Shirley ordered pizza and invited the older children over.
She and Van asked them if they wanted to live with them, if they
wanted to live there permanently.
</P>
<P>
   The children voted to stay and moved in in May 1997. Van and
Shirley told the kids that they could call them by their names or
``Mom'' and ``Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   All chose to call them Mom and Dad.
</P>
<P>
   So do their friends. Often, Shirley looks up after hearing
someone say, ``Mom, can I talk to you about something?'' only to
discover that it isn't even one of her own kids.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa, Asucena, Steven and Agustino arrived at the Hughes'
together.
</P>
<P>
   Now 16, Teresa, the little mother, wants to work in child care.
Asucena, 14, wants to be a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   The boys are heavy into video games. Agustino, 12, saved his
money and bought a Nintendo 64. Steven, 13, and Enrique pooled
their money for one.
</P>
<P>
   Frank bought his own.
</P>
<P>
   He was almost 16 when he came to live with the Hughes, the last
to arrive. Caseworkers warned the couple that he was a tough kid.
</P>
<P>
   Frank was in four different foster homes and shelters. He talked
mean and sometimes stayed out all night. During a heated argument,
Frank told Van: ``What are you going to do? Beat me like my other
Dad did?''
</P>
<P>
   Van hugged him instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best Dad in the world,'' Frank, now 17, says. ``It's
pretty cool here. I don't got to worry about nothing, like I did
before. I'm glad that we're together. That's what I'm grateful for,
everyone sticking together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every Friday night, Shirley orders six large pizzas _ for a tab
of $55.
</P>
<P>
   ``First few times I called, they thought I had a party every
Friday night,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   They do have a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Their Mesa home is surprisingly quiet for the number of kids
inside. It's never just the Hughes' 10. Friends come for dinner and
stay the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's one more kid?'' Van asks.
</P>
<P>
   In the driveway is a 1991 gray second-hand, 15-passenger van
with 401,000 miles. Six kids are in braces; four wear glasses.
</P>
<P>
   At Calvary Southern Baptist Church in Mesa, the family fills the
front two pews. At breakfast, the kids put away two or three boxes
of cereal and two gallons of milk.
</P>
<P>
   The washer and dryer run all day. The kitchen floor gets mopped
twice a day. And the monthly grocery tab is about $1,500. Some
days, Shirley has to go to the supermarket twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids eat it all on the way home,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Three cats and two dogs live here, along with a variety of
rabbits and turtles that come and, well, go, may they rest in
peace, Shirley says.
</P>
<P>
   A converted garage and dining room make this a six-bedroom house
with three bathrooms. Little kids bathe at night, big ones in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Van is retired from the Navy and works nights as a security
guard at Phoenix City Hall. Shirley stays at home with the kids.
They receive $6,600 a month from the state for the children's care
that they'll continue to get after the adoption.
</P>
<P>
   On a rainy evening, they eat dinner next door at the home of
Shirley's parents, Larry and Vera Russo. The kids swim there most
afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday, Larry cooks something on the barbecue and
everyone troops next door to eat. This week, he is wearing a
T-shirt that says, ``Dad knows a lot but Grandpa knows
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who agrees that Dad knows more than Grandpa?'' Van asks over
the chicken, steak, chili and salad. His query is met with a rare
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who agrees that Grandpa knows more than Dad?'' he asks. Ten
hands shoot into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bunch of little suck ups,'' Van mutters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Dad, the light is reflecting off of your head,'' Teresa,
16, says, eliciting hoots of laughter from her brothers and
sisters. ``I'm going to smack you!'' Van warns, running his head
over his balding head.
</P>
<P>
   They know he is kidding, of course. These children have had
enough of that. What they get here is love, lots of hugs and
kisses. No one goes to bed without at least one of each.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to show them love,'' Shirley says. ``How else are
they going to learn to love?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The children set the rules of the house. No running. Bed at 8:30
p.m. for the little kids, 10 p.m. for the teenagers. Curfew.
Chores. Homework before television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them, ``You have to be able to walk out of this door
one day and stand on your own two feet,'' Shirley says. ``And the
only way they are going to do that is to get a good education.''
</P>
<P>
   This is no place for a dictatorship, Van says. Start barking
orders, and there would be mutiny. And Van and Shirley would be
outnumbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this home, God is the foundation. These four adults,''
Shirley says, pointing to herself, Van and her parents, ``are the
pillars, and every child is a building block.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems get hammered out at family meetings, which anyone _
even the 4-year-old _ can call. Attendance is mandatory. Shirley
called one recently to complain that the children were slow to do
their chores but quick to ask for their allowances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing we cannot sit down and talk about,'' Shirley
says. ``There are no mistakes that cannot be rectified, nothing
that cannot be forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Shirley and Van don't have a solution to a problem,
they turn to the big Bible that lays open on a shelf near the front
door.
</P>
<P>
   With the teenagers, they talk openly about sex. Teresa and
Asucena wear gold promise rings that signify they will not have sex
until they are married. They can date but only with other couples
until they are 17 and ``no smooching all over each other,'' Shirley
says. She tells their dates: ``You toucha my girl, I toucha you
face.'' The girls laugh. Frank gets the same lecture.
</P>
<P>
   They keep no secrets. Some of the children talk to their mother
by telephone. The others are still angry. Shirley sends the woman
the kids' school pictures every year.
</P>
<P>
   That is a different life than the one they are living now. They
laugh here and play sports _ soccer, baseball, swimming,
cheerleading _ with parents cheering from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   They wear new clothes, paid for over time on lay-a-way, the same
way the computer, kitchen table and bunk beds for the girls were
paid for. There's plenty to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always someone here,'' Asucena says. ``And you know
they care.''
</P>
<P>
   At night, after the kitchen _ and the kids _ are clean, prayers
have been said _ and hopefully heard _ the house is quiet. Van
comes home from work at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Both are 52, married for 32 years. Van puts his arm around his
wife, as he does every night, kisses her and says, ``These are
happy times, Shirl, you know that?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
