<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS TO EXCESS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's record trade deficit _ $21.3 billion in May _ is a
tribute to the American economy, a combination of the confidence
that goes with rising personal and corporate earnings and a strong
dollar. However, too much success can become a problem _ for which
the remedy may be uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the causes for the deficit are out of
American hands. The Asian economies have begun to recover from
their debacle of 1997 and 1998 but have not yet resumed their full
role as major American customers. As former treasury secretary
Robert Rubin observed, the United States can't be Asia's customer
of last resort forever. The yen has risen against the dollar, but
Japan's deep-seated cultural unwillingness to give foreign goods
and services full access to its economy has kept its trade surplus
high.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, too, has lagged as a customer. Trade relations have been
clouded by nasty squabbles over minor issues like bans on imports
of American hormone-fed beef and retaliatory American moves. Of
more substance, the newly launched euro has sagged more than 10
percent against the dollar, though it has been bolstered in the
past few days, primarily by the perception of American trade
problems. If the euro resumes its decline, US competitiveness will
be further diminished.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Americans luxuriate in the best of
conditions. US unemployment rates are the lowest among major
industrial nations. Prices are steady, and the prices of imported
goods have played a major role in keeping domestic prices down
while consumers enjoy wide choices in quality and variety of goods.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot last forever. Bringing trade back into balance
requires economic recovery elsewhere and relentless American
efforts to improve the quality and lower the cost of US goods and
services so they are competitive in world markets.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is that the American economy will soften and that the
siren song of protectionism, never far beneath the surface of the
American political scene, will lure the unwary into that
destructive trap. That would be a bad sequel to these good times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
