<SLUG> BC-DRUG-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 DRUG MAKERS REPORTING MIXED RESULTS DURING SECOND QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's largest pharmaceutical companies are expected to
notch some healthy gains in second-quarter earnings this week, but
analysts are not convinced that will be enough to rouse investor
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson, long dismissed as an industry laggard,
surprised analysts Tuesday by announcing a 14.9 percent increase in
its second-quarter earnings, to $1.16 billion. The company, which
makes such disparate brands as Tylenol, Neutrogena and the anemia
drug Procrit, said it had earned 84 cents a diluted share, 2 cents
above First Call Corp.'s consensus estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Two other drug makers also reported results Tuesday, with
varying success. SmithKline Beecham PLC, the world's 10th-largest
drug maker, posted a 12 percent earnings gain, to $487 million;
sales of its popular antidepressant Paxil increased 27 percent.
SmithKline said it had earned 40 cents per American depository
receipt, which met analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Even though American Home Products Corp. warned investors last
month that its earnings would fall below expectations, the
company's performance startled some analysts. The company, which is
based in Madison, N.J., said that its second-quarter earnings
decreased 13.7 percent from last year's period, to $451.7 million
before a special charge.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday that despite American Home's warning, they
were surprised by the depth of the 29 percent plunge in the
company's agricultural division. The company attributed the decline
to lower demand in the United States for its Pursuit, Raptor, Prowl
and Scepter herbicides.
</P>
<P>
   American Home also raised eyebrows by taking a $53 million
charge to suspend shipments temporarily for Rotashield, its vaccine
against the rotavirus. Some analysts interpreted the charge as a
signal from American Home that it would not continue the drug.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when most drug stocks declined, investors had mixed
reactions to the earnings news. Shares of Johnson &AMP; Johnson
increased 0.5 percent, or 50 cents, to $96.4375. American Home
Products' stock dropped 3.95 percent, or $1.9375, to close at
$50.9375. SmithKline Beecham's ADRs dropped 2.7 percent, or $1.625,
to close at $61.375.
</P>
<P>
   After being one of the globe's best- performing sectors last
year, drug makers have lagged this year. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index has increased 12.03 percent so far this year but
the S&AMP;P drug index has fallen 10.2 percent. Shares of Eli Lilly &AMP;
Co. are down 16.95 percent this year, while Pfizer Inc.'s stock has
decreased 14.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year, the drug stocks were
overvalued,'' said Sergio Traversa, an analyst with Mehta Partners
in New York. ``But now the prices have fallen so much that they are
undervalued. A lot of people moved their money out to put it in
another sector. And some people may have been nervous about
President Clinton's Medicare plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the drug makers remain solid. Second-quarter
earnings are expected to increase 11 percent over last year, thanks
to enormous gains of pharmaceuticals sold in the United States. For
the full year, earnings are expected to increase 15 percent, one
percentage point below last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some drug makers could still report higher gains than expected.
Analysts said pharmaceutical sales at the Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.
and Eli Lilly might be higher than expected. Bristol-Myers is
expected to report a 15 percent earnings gain Thursday and Lilly is
expected to report an increase of 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, Warner-Lambert Co., the industry's earnings
leader, is expected to notch a second-quarter gain of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson's performance came with a caveat. Analysts
noted that drug wholesalers had stocked up about $100 million worth
of the company's drugs _ as they did in lesser amounts from other
companies _ in anticipation of a price increase. Yet, even with
that stockpiling, Johnson &AMP; Johnson's performance was stellar.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported record second-quarter sales of $6.85
billion, thanks largely to a 37.3 percent increase in
pharmaceutical sales in the United States. Analysts said Tuesday
that Procrit's sales increased more than 90 percent during the
quarter in the United States, while the company's deep portfolio
appeared to pay dividends. Worldwide sales of Neutrogena skin
products jumped 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any way you look at it, J&AMP;J's performance was really good,''
said Traversa. ``They received some savings from their
restructuring, but most of this came from the top line in
pharmaceutical sales.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
