<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-CHAINSTORES-SFC     07-20 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-CHAINSTORES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VIDEO WARS _ BIG CHAINS SQUEEZING INDEPENDENT RENTAL STORES  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- It's summertime, but the living isn't easy for
most independent video rental stores.
<P>
   The economy is hot. Kids are out of school and watching movies.
Yet the Video Software Dealers Association annual convention in Los
Angeles last week looked more like a wake than a celebration of the
$17 billion-a-year home video industry, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Just as independent booksellers have accused the giant chains of
using predatory prices to try and drive them out of business,
independent video stores make similar claims. They argue that
Blockbuster and Hollywood Entertainment have made a concerted
effort to capture their customers by offering super-low prices on
new releases, even though they may lose money in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Katz, owner of Five Star Video stores in Berkeley, Calif.,
and Albany, Calif., figures that the two giants of the rental
business ``don't want to peacefully coexist. They want to gain
market share at any cost and, once they control it, raise prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The chains have a big advantage because they can acquire
cassettes at lower costs and strike favorable rental
revenue-sharing agreements with the Hollywood studios. The moves
have allowed the chains to both conserve cash and plaster their
walls with scores of copies of the latest releases that have the
greatest appeal to young renters.
</P>
<P>
   In response, stores like Five Star have de-emphasized new
releases and try to draw customers with fuller libraries of foreign
and independent films and old chestnuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the point of going deep with copies of movies like
`Saving Private Ryan?' '' Katz asks rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Blockbuster (which has a location five blocks away)
will guarantee they have it in stock or give something for free if
they don't,'' Katz says.
</P>
<P>
   He says his business is down 20 percent from its peak in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is even worse at Captain Video on San Pablo Avenue
in Albany. With two Blockbusters within a mile striking distance,
``there's been a slow loss of market share,'' said store manager
Bill Wood. ``We've lost money for over a year.'' As a result, this
Captain Video store and its 4,000 titles will close permanently
after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 20,000 independent video stores in the United
States. ``But they are going out of business at an alarming rate,''
said John Merchant, owner of 49er Video stores in the Sacramento,
Calif., area and a director of the Video Software Dealers
Association and the Independent Video Retailers Group. ``I've heard
as many as 400 a month are leaving the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Merchant used to have five stores but he is down to four _ and
only three are profitable. ``We've taken quite a beating,'' he
said. ``We know we can't compete going head-to-head with
Blockbuster on new releases.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Blockbuster's market share of the home video industry
is close to 35 percent and Hollywood Entertainment's is approaching
7 percent, according to Marcy Magiera, editor of Video Business
Magazine, a weekly published by Varsity Group in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little guys believe they are at a huge and unfair price
disadvantage compared to the big stores,'' she said. ``They've been
talking about filing an antitrust action for a long time but
whether volume discounts are untoward, unethical or illegal is an
open question.''
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster, a unit of media giant Viacom Inc. and the largest
video rental chain with about 6,500 stores around the world, has
recovered from a two-year slump largely as a result of revenue
sharing agreements with Hollywood studios. Nevertheless, the Dallas
company has lost close to $1 billion since Viacom Chairman Sumner
Redstone bought it for $8.4 billion five years ago, according to
industry estimates. Blockbuster will soon sell 18 percent of its
shares to the public, and Redstone said he expects to reach 40 to
50 percent market share sooner than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Entertainment, based in Wilsonville, Ore., has more
than 1,000 outlets and lost $50.5 million on $763.9 million
revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how to order is crucial to success in the movie rental
business. But it is far from simple, according to Five Star's Katz,
46, who has an MBA from MIT and was a commodity broker and Chevron
marketer before getting into the movie rental business 12 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to sell securities, but this is the most difficult
portfolio I've ever managed,'' he said. ``With stocks or options,
it usually doesn't make much difference if you buy one or 100
(units). But in videocassettes, the more you buy, the less chance
you have of making money if they just sit on the shelf. But if you
have too few, your customers will go elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other video shop operators say that before ordering
cassettes it is essential to analyze how well the movies did at the
box office and how well they are likely to do in the rental market,
anticipate what the big chains will do, and assess the tastes of
their own customers.
</P>
<P>
   To break even on new releases, Katz figures he needs to rent out
each cassette 23 times for $3.25. Katz is wary of buying too many
cassettes because he realizes the giants will stock hundreds of
copies on the expectation that everyone who wants to see the movie
will have done so in a few weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   For new releases like ``Analyze This,'' the Warner Bros. comedy
starring Billy Crystal and Robert De Niro that comes out next
month, Katz said that he will order six copies per store. Five
years ago, he would have bought 15 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Blockbuster and Hollywood will guarantee (the
availability of) rentals, and if I buy 15, I'll lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent stores increasingly try to compete on everything but
new releases.
</P>
<P>
   Le Video in San Francisco has one of the best movie libraries,
with nearly 50,000 titles, and customers including Robin Williams,
Nicholas Cage and Joan Chen.
</P>
<P>
   The store is doing well enough to expand recently from one
storefront to two to house all its movies, which typically rent for
$3.50 for four nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focus on a different market,'' said Rudha, the store
manager. Le Video has no ``new release'' wall, and recent releases
account for less than a third of its inventory. By contrast, there
are large sections devoted to cult and classic films and and movies
cataloged by country, director and actor.
</P>
<P>
   Five Star's store, on University Avenue in Berkeley, has a
library of close to 15,000 VHS tapes and sections devoted to
Humphrey Bogart, gay and lesbian films, El Cerrito, Calif.,
filmmaker Les Blank and other specialties. It also has a wide
selection of about 1,400 DVD disks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independent stores can differentiate themselves by offering
more DVDs, foreign, independent and adult titles and more
personalized service,'' said video market consultant Barbara
McNamara of Alexander &AMP; Associates in New York. ``But with limited
budgets to buy films and advertise it has definitely become more
difficult for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to competition from the chain stores, independent
operators face consumer defections to pay-per-view cable services
and satellite TV broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, they will have to confront ``streaming'' video,
or ``movies on demand,'' which will allow consumers to conveniently
download movies directly from Web sites in just a few minutes and
play them whenever they want, just like home videos.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, savvy independents can compete on
selection, service, clever promotions and even consumer preference
for the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   49er Video's John Merchant, who offers defensive strategy
seminars to independent operators, recommends special pricing deals
like discounts for senior citizens or five catalog movies for five
days for $4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
