<HEADLINE>
PILOT ERROR LOOMS LARGE IN KENNEDY CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Airplane accident investigators frequently say any accident is
the result of seven or eight factors coming together in a deadly
combination. Remove any one of them from the sequence and the
accident would not occur.
</P>
<P>
   While the cause of Friday's crash that killed John F. Kennedy
Jr., his wife and sister-in-law is still under investigation, pilot
error is something investigators are closely considering. The
plane, with Kennedy at the controls, went into a steep dive in the
moments before it crashed off Martha's Vineyard. There are two
possible explanations: mechanical problems or pilot error. Based on
previous accidents, the latter seems more likely, said a longtime
accident investigator who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   If Kennedy was at fault, one crucial element in the sequence of
events that led to the accident, was the pressure on him to make
the flight in uncertain weather. Pilots call it ``gethome-itis.''
</P>
<P>
   There were reasons for Kennedy not to make the flight _ the
weather was questionable, he and his party were delayed leaving New
York City and stuck in traffic which resulted in the flight
departing three hours later than he had planned _ critical factors
for a pilot not qualified to use instruments to fly the plane in
poor visibility.
</P>
<P>
   But there were even more reasons to make the flight: His cousin
Rory was to be married the next day; he had promised that he would
drop his sister-in-law Lauren Bessette off on Martha's Vineyard
before flying to Barnstable Airport; he had spent about $300,000 on
the the Piper Saratoga II HP 2 1/2 months ago and wanted to use it;
and, quite possibly, as celebrities, Kennedy and his wife found the
idea of flying in their own private plane much more attractive than
traveling on a commercial flight.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on a pilot to reach his or her destination has
afflicted pilots much more seasoned than Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, an American Airlines MD-82, which was piloted by
Richard Buschmann, American's chief pilot in Chicago for the MD-80,
landed in Little Rock, Ark., in a driving thunderstorm, went off
the end of the runway at 90 m.p.h. and slammed into a light pier.
Buschmann and 10 others were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the areas investigators in that crash are examining are
Buschmann's decision to land at Little Rock in a thunderstorm. The
plane, scheduled to spent the overnight in Little Rock, was two
hours late leaving Dallas and its crew had spent 13 1/2 hours
flying that day, 30 minutes less than the maximum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something that comes up in many accident investigations,
but we have never made any specific recommendation to deal with
this issue,'' said an official with the National Transportation
Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Komich, a commercial airline pilot who works for Damos
Research, a Los Angeles-based aviation consulting firm, said that
Kennedy almost certainly realized the margins of safety for his
flight were diminished, but did not consider it unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not as safe as daytime flight in good weather, and that
is part of the judgment process, but 99.9 percent of the time, it
would work and I guarantee you, pilots like him do what he did
everyday, said Komich.''
</P>
<P>
   Komich said commercial pilots are bitten by the same bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``You push to get home,'' he said. ``You don't want to lay over
in East Umpty Ump when your car is parked at the airport you are
supposed to fly to.''
</P>
<P>
   Succumbing to pressure to make the flight was just one link in
the chain that led to the accident. If spatial orientation caused
the accident, then almost certainly, leaving three hours behind
schedule, was a contibuting factor, since safety experts think it
likely Kennedy could have easily made the flight in daylight.
</P>
<P>
   But in the night-time, looking away from the horizon, even to do
something as simple as change the radio frequency dial in order to
prepare to talk with controller at Martha's Vineyard, could spell
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Spatial disorientation has brought down pilots much more
experienced than Kennedy, who had in excess of 300 hours of flight
time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 a US Air Force tactical air command report found that
command fighter pilots with as much as 6,000 hours of flying time
could become disoriented flying at night by simple distractions
like changing radio frequencies. The study found that if it took
pilots as much as 45 seconds to scan their instruments to realize
their plane was in trouble _ either losing altitude or flying at an
unsual angle _ they had wasted too much time to successfully
recover.
</P>
<P>
   And the closer the pilots were to the ground, the less time they
had to recover the aircraft. Kennedy was at 2,200 feet at the start
of the plane's dive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
