<HEADLINE>
REPORT CRITICIZES CLINTON'S PLAN FOR TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Spelling of ``Kati'' in penultimate graf is CQ) 
(yn) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adding fuel to widespread concern about the looming shortage of
qualified public-school teachers, a new report contends that some
of the most trumpeted plans for change would only make matters
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-page report, ``Better Teachers, Better Schools,'' was
released by the Thomas B. Fordham Foundation last week just as
Congress was getting ready to debate competing proposals to spend
billions in Federal funds to raise the quality of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is a three-year-old research group based in
Washington (it has no connection to Fordham University) that has
become an influential voice on the conservative, free-market side
of many education debates. Its president, and a principal editor of
the report on teaching, is Chester E. Finn Jr., who was an
assistant secretary of education in the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   The report takes sharp issue with the Clinton administration's
proposal to raise the standards for teacher certification. ``Every
additional requirement for prospective teachers _ every additional
pedagogical course, every new hoop or hurdle _ will have a
predictable and inexorable effect,'' it says. ``It will limit the
potential supply of teachers by narrowing the pipeline while having
no bearing whatever on the quality or effectiveness of those in the
pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   It recommends scrapping most teacher-hiring regulations,
particularly those that tie would-be teachers to education schools
and courses on methodology, and instead make it easier for local
school districts to hire teachers who know their academic fields
well. ``Instead of requiring a long list of courses and degrees,
test future teachers for their knowledge and skills,'' it says.
``Focus relentlessly on results, on whether students are
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   With retirements and record enrollments, 2 million teachers are
expected to be hired in the next 10 years. President Clinton has
called for tightening teaching requirements, and the Education
Department is working with the states in drafting tougher standards
for teacher training. The Fordham report calls these approaches
counterproductive; in turn, the Education Department, major teacher
unions and accreditation agencies are attacking the report as
simplistic.
</P>
<P>
   The report's essays are particularly hard on two leading
accreditation agencies: the National Board for Professional
Teaching Standards, which seeks to identify master teachers and has
been praised by Clinton; and the National Council for Accreditation
of Teacher Education, the largest accreditor of teacher-training
programs. It accuses both of playing into the hands of teachers
unions by disregarding academic knowledge in favor of fuzzy,
unproven theories that focus on a congenial learning environment
instead of the learning itself.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from those criticized in the report has been quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chapter about the National Board is wrong on so many
scores that it isn't possible to quickly cite the inaccuracies and
misrepresentations in it,'' said James A. Kelly, president of the
teaching standards board. He said the board's standards are
developed by leading scholars, undergo a lengthy review process and
are supported not just by teacher unions but also by the National
School Boards Association, prominent business groups and the
federal and state governments. He said the Fordham report reflected
Finn's preconceived views, and called it ``a polemic cleverly
camouflaged as scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chase, president of the National Education Association,
the nation's largest teachers union, defended teacher licensing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Licensure isn't a regulatory intrusion,'' he said. ``It's a
standard to protect children. The loosey-goosey approach suggested
by Mr. Finn would sweep away all requirements. We don't need warm
bodies _ we need good, qualified teachers teaching our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Therese Dozier, special adviser on teaching to the secretary of
education, said the Fordham Foundation report actually buttressed
the administration's contention that teachers should not get
licenses outside the fields in which they are qualified. Tightening
certification is not incompatible with opening up alternative
pathways to teaching, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position has always been, we don't care how you acquire
the knowledge and skills to be an effective teacher, as long as you
can demonstrate that,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kati Haycock, director of the Education Trust, a nonprofit group
that advocates better training of teachers, said she agreed with
the report's emphasis on teachers knowing their subjects, and
warned that the administration was likely to leave it too easy to
hold a teaching certificate. But she added that methodology is
still important, particularly when dealing with younger children
and beginner skills like reading. She also said the report appeared
to place too much faith in the ability of principals and parents to
choose teachers wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the foundation report, she said, ``This is a group of
essentially conservative folks going to war with the Democrats and
each pretending that the other is doing something that it isn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
