<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7709 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROWABUSINES-COLUMN-S     07-20 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWABUSINES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A FINE TIME TO TAKE A TAX BREAK  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q: What tax incentives are available to businesses that are
starting or expanding in California and how do you apply for them?
<P>
   A: It's a good time to win tax breaks. The clamor of states,
counties and countries to create jobs and bolster their industrial
and tax bases has set off fierce bidding battles around the world.
The favored weapon in this corporate dating game is a nifty package
of tax incentives.
</P>
<P>
   California now has one of the richest programs. Last year,
California state and local programs to promote economic growth
granted nearly $9 billion in corporate, sales, use and other tax
exemptions, according to Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bigger than the budgets of many states,'' notes Richard
Sloniker, a multistate tax partner for the accounting and
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche's Center for Multistate Taxation at the
University of Wisconsin at Milwaukee has just published ``A
Lawmaker's Guide to the use of Business Tax Incentives.'' The
booklet discusses the various types of incentives, including income
tax credits and deductions; exemptions from sales, use and property
taxes; and enterprise zones. (For a free copy, e-mail
hightech &LR; dttus.com.)
</P>
<P>
   This guide also discusses the pros and cons of tax incentives
and has interesting tales of how states have used financial lures
to persuade companies to relocate, expand or stay put. For example,
North Carolina awarded $155 million of incentives to Nucor last
year to locate a steel mill in Hertford County that will create 300
jobs. That translates into an astounding $517,333 per job.
</P>
<P>
   There are several steps you can take to win business tax
incentives, starting with simply asking. Sloniker says that many
companies falsely believe they do not qualify so they do not bother
to ask. That can be a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start your research is the California Trade and
Commerce Agency. It has offices in the Bay Area or you can go to
its Web site (www.locate.ca.gov/) and click on Section 5
Incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Also, contact your local chamber of commerce about incentives
offered by your county or city. The state and local governments
often form so-called Red Teams with the private sector to identify
and package programs to lure or retain particularly attractive
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the main programs in California:
</P>
<P>
   _ Enterprise zones. There are various sites in California, such
as San Francisco, Oakland, San Jose and elsewhere, that provide
generous incentives to hire the economically disadvantaged. Credits
can be as much as 50 percent of first-year pay. That means a
business might be able to deduct $8,000 of a worker's $16,000
compensation directly from its tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   _ Manufacturer's investment credit. Businesses that purchase
equipment for use in California manufacturing can offset income
taxes by 6 percent of the purchase price. For example, a company
that buys $10,000 of equipment could deduct $600 from its state
income tax bill. New corporate taxpayers can get a credit on their
state sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Research and development credit. Companies that increase their
R&AMP;D spending can deduct up to 11 percent of the incremental
increase in expenditures directly from their tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   Sloniker said that most any business that contributes to the
economic health and well-being of the state and local economy is
eligible for something. Typically, these companies have 100 or more
employees. But smaller firms that are prestigious or have
high-paying jobs or great growth prospects can qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Start researching and negotiating early. The bigger your
company, the more time it will take. &UR;  &LR; Deloitte &AMP; Touche says a good
rule of thumb is to start preparing for credits and incentives
negotiations about two years prior to a move, acquisition,
expansion or expiration of a lease option.
</P>
<P>
   It is good to select two or three comparable sites and then
prepare your case by compiling the following data:
</P>
<P>
   _ Business profile. This includes basic information such as
number of employees, combined annual salaries and tax payments.
Also emphasize what your company offers the community and the
state, such as positive publicity, charitable work or environmental
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   _ List of desired business tax incentives. You may not get all
the tax credits, incentives or special waivers you seek. But
Deloitte &AMP; Touche says it doesn't hurt to ask. Consider reductions
in utility fees, relaxed permits, carry forward of net operating
losses, accelerated depreciation for certain equipment and
discounts on city fees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
