A7712 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVIS-SWEATSHOPS-SFCH     07-20 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-SWEATSHOPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEVI'S JOINS WAR AGAINST SWEATSHOPS  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. Tuesday joined the Fair Labor
Association, an alliance of corporations, human-rights groups and
universities that is fighting against abusive labor conditions
overseas.
<P>
   The move adds the San Francisco jeansmaker's prestige and market
clout to an ungainly, deeply divided consumer movement that has
shamed some leading corporations by casting light on the low wages
and often-abusive conditions in their global production networks.
</P>
<P>
   The association plans to monitor its member companies' factories
for three years before they can use the FLA seal on its products _
indicating that they are sweatshop-free and guilt-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are increasingly educated and concerned'' about
international labor rights, said Gare Smith, a vice president at
Levi's, which contracts its clothes manufacturing to about 500
firms in more than 50 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, nobody thought about child labor, and now
President Clinton goes to the International Labor Organization to
talk about it. ... If you want to address these concerns in a
cost-effective way that has credibility, the FLA is the way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining the FLA is a logical management step for Levi's, which
in 1991 was the first large U.S. firm to adopt a code of conduct
for its international operations.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of its this code of conduct, Levi's has avoided
much of the unfavorable publicity received by some of its
competitors, such as the controversy that arose in 1996, when TV
personality Kathie Lee Gifford found out that her line of clothes
were made by child laborers under sweatshop conditions.
</P>
<P>
   FLA was founded in November after a two-year gestation process
sponsored by the White House. Its members now include firms such as
Adidas-Salomon, Nike, Liz Claiborne, Reebok and Phillips Van
Heusen; several human-rights groups; and 107 colleges and
universities, including the seven Ivy League schools, San Francisco
State University, California State University at Sacramento, Santa
Clara University and University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   When it starts its monitoring programs next year, the FLA will
inspect its member companies' foreign factories to see whether they
comply with the following provisions: freedom to form labor unions,
no child or forced labor, inspection of up to 30 percent of a brand
name's factories by independent monitors such as local human-rights
groups and a ban on requiring workers to work more than 60 hours
per week.
</P>
<P>
   The FLA has critics on both sides of the aisles. Many student
anti-sweatshop activists say its standards are not strong enough.
For example, they say the FLA's standards lack any provision for
paying workers more than poverty-level wages and they do not
require companies to publicly disclose the identities and locations
of their contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Levi's will support the adoption of a ``living wage''
provision once the FLA is fully operational.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the University of California _ which has not
joined the FLA _ reacted to growing student pressure by adopting a
code that has a living-wage clause _ but does not have any
enforcement mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, many firms have been leery of joining because
they see the FLA as unwanted interference in boardroom decision
making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firms have to understand that business as usual is no longer
an option,'' said Roberta Karp, a vice president at Liz Claiborne
and a key FLA organizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have transparency, you have to have input from
people outside industry, rather than hoping you can keep flying
under the radar screen. ... This issue is not going away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
