<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GM PROFIT BEATS FORECAST BUT MARKET SHARE SHRINKS
</P>
<P>
   Pocketing higher profits even as its market share continues to
erode, General Motors said that it earned $1.73 billion in the
second quarter, a vast improvement over the $306 million it earned
from continuing operations during the same period last year, when
there was a costly strike.
</P>
<P>
   The results amounted to $2.66 a share and beat analysts'
expectations of $2.56 a share. Second-quarter revenue rose to
$45.07 billion from $37.27 billion, allowing GM to maintain its
position as the world's largest company, ahead of Ford. In a down
market, shares of GM fell $1.8125, to $66.50.
</P>
<P>
   EURO GAINS, BUT THE YEN DECLINES
</P>
<P>
   Europe's single currency rallied sharply against the dollar
after a key economic report showed business confidence in Germany
growing much more than expected. In contrast, the dollar climbed
higher against the Japanese yen after the Bank of Japan sold yen
for dollars through the Federal Reserve System.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSICO PROFIT SURPASSES FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico said that its second-quarter earnings rose 50 percent,
based in large part on a one-time gain from the spinoff of its
bottling operations. Without the $270 million gain from the
spinoff, Pepsico's earnings rose 7.4 percent, slightly beating the
expectations of Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   GOP LEADERS TRY TO SAVE TAX CUT
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the House scrambled to head off a revolt
by party moderates and avert a humiliating defeat on their
signature issue of tax cuts. With a vote on the biggest tax cut
since 1981 scheduled for Wednesday, Republicans said it was unclear
whether enough of the 20 or so moderates would break with the
leadership to defeat or block passage of the bill, the centerpiece
of the party's domestic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE GROUP SETTLES ON LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   Members of the World Trade Organization, which sets the rules
for global commerce, resolved a prolonged and bitter dispute over
who would be its next leader by agreeing that the two finalists
would share the job in consecutive three-year terms. Mike Moore,
the New Zealand candidate, will go first, followed by his Thai
rival, Supachai Panitchpakdi.
</P>
<P>
   KRAFT BOLSTERS PHILIP MORRIS RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris said that its second-quarter profit, excluding
charges, rose nearly 3 percent as its Kraft food unit lifted sales
and cut costs, softening declines in cigarette profits.
</P>
<P>
   TRASH-HAULING MERGER IS APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department approved the merger of Allied Waste and
Browning-Ferris, one of the largest combinations in the
trash-hauling business, on the condition that the companies sell
operations in 18 cities in 13 states.
</P>
<P>
   THREE DRUG MAKERS POST EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson surprised analysts by announcing a 14.9
percent increase in its second-quarter earnings. Two other drug
makers also reported results, with varying success. SmithKline
Beecham posted a 12 percent earnings gain, but American Home
Products said that its earnings decreased 13.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT NET INCOME INCREASES 45 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, the maker of telecommunications equipment,
posted a stronger-than-expected 45 percent jump in its
third-quarter net income on strength in its international and
microelectronics operations.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT RISES AT SBC AND AMERITECH
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications and Ameritech, which plan to merge into the
United States' largest local telephone company, reported
second-quarter earnings that topped forecasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
