<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-DIVERSITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WB PUTS A FACE TO ITS PLEDGE FOR MORE DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The ``WB'' in The WB doesn't stand for white
bread. But if you looked only at the network's hourlong dramas, it
very well could. Painfully aware of recent complaints about lack of
racial and cultural diversity in prime-time programming, the
producers of two new WB series _ ``Roswell'' and ``Jack &AMP; Jill'' _
said they are keenly aware of the need to reflect a multicultural
society.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there isn't a producer in Hollywood who hasn't said
the same thing. What sticks in the craw of many critics is that
these pledges to add diversity _ after the pilot episodes have been
shot with lily-white casts _ usually end up as unseemly exercises
in tokenism.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps for that reason, The WB took the unusual step of
trotting out Yvette Lee Bowser, creator of ``Living Single'' and
the current WB comedy, ``For Your Love,'' to announce plans for a
new drama series about a young African American woman whose parents
have gotten remarried to form multi-ethnic couples.
</P>
<P>
   The series, tentatively titled ``The Miseducation of Piper
Fein,'' is at least a year off, but Bowser's appearance here before
TV critics Tuesday showcased at least one network's desire to show
that it's hearing the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser, who is biracial, said she thinks The WB is
``enthusiastic'' about showcasing actors of color in the dramatic
form. ``A change is going to come,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Here's a concept. The WB has ordered 22 episodes _ a full
season pickup _ of ``Roswell,'' which centers on normal and
paranormal teens living in Roswell, N.M. Like ``Felicity'' and
``Dawson's Creek'' before it, ``Roswell'' has tons of favorable
buzz preceding it, and network chief executive officer Jamie
Kellner says the 22-episode order is testament to The WB's belief
in the series.
</P>
<P>
   (Actually, the show's studio, Twentieth Century Fox Television,
pretty much forced the issue, demanding a firm commitment from The
WB after the Fox network, for which the show was originally
intended, failed to find a spot for ``Roswell'' on its fall
schedule.)
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's a nice situation for creator Jason Katims, who
never got much support from ABC for ``My So-called Life'' and
``Relativity.'' Neither lasted a full season, despite critical
acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's really wonderful about the order, from a
writing perspective, is that it's much easier to plan,'' Katims
said. Knowing that he's got more than a six- or nine- or 13-episode
pickup makes for a strength of continuity that's impossible to
achieve otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   So, even if The WB's motives aren't entirely altruistic, give
'em credit for taking a chance. Series star Sarah Michelle Gellar
says she figures ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' would have been
canceled after three episodes if it aired on any other network.
This fall, it enters its fourth season on The WB.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gellar says she wept when ``Buffy'' creator Joss Whedon
announced plans to do a spinoff series featuring David Boreanaz's
character, Angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joss is our show,'' Gellar said Tuesday. ``I didn't know if we
knew how to make this show without him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Whedon has assured the world and the ``Buffy'' cast that he
will remain as hands-on as ever next season, despite the enormous
demands of getting a new series up and running.
</P>
<P>
   _ Odds 'n' ends: Nick Turturro, who plays detective James
Martinez on ``NYPD Blue,'' will leave the series after the
1999-2000 season to create a comedy series for The WB.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
