<HEADLINE>
PRODUCER GETS OK FOR SERIES PILOT FOCUSING ON BLACK WOMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _Yvette Lee Bowser, who created Living Single for Fox
and currently produces For Your Love for The WB, has gotten the
green light to shoot the pilot of what would be an hourlong series
focusing on an African-American woman.
</P>
<P>
   The Miseducation of Piper Fein will center on a black woman
whose parents have gotten remarried. The show _ part comedy, part
drama in the form of Sports Night and Ally McBeal _ plans to
explore the realities of a modern-day multi-racial extended family,
to which Bowser herself belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser says she's been working on the idea for about three
years, but the timing is intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   The networks, particularly The WB, which is becoming known for
developing dramas with all-white or predominately white casts, are
under extreme pressure to diversify casting and mirror the society
in which they serve. Of the more than 30 new comedies and dramas
premiering on The WB, CBS, ABC, Fox and NBC _ not one features a
minority in a leading role. UPN has two sitcoms featuring
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   During an often raucous press session yesterday where most of
the questions centered on race and whether the networks were being
exclusionary, Susanne Daniels, president of entertainment for The
WB, denied that the programming deal was struck in order to appease
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser, who began her career as a writer on A Different World,
concurred, saying she was too busy with other series to do the
dramady. `I wanted to make sure I was ready to do it,` she said.
`This is a good time.`
</P>
<P>
   For her and The WB.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) .MDBO/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
