<SLUG> BC-HOTEL_CENTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL CORPORATION TO OPEN RESERVATION CENTER IN LANCASTER, CALIF.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JIM SKEEN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANCASTER, Calif. _ Starwood Hotels and Resorts will establish a
reservation center in Lancaster, 55 miles north of downtown Los
Angeles, selecting the city over 160 others for the 250-job
operation, officials announced.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood, which includes the Sheraton and Westin Hotel chains,
plans to establish a regional reservation center at the former
La-Z-Boy furniture showroom. The center is expected to employ 150
people when it opens in late September, then add 100 workers over
the first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great operation for the city of Lancaster,'' said
Mayor Frank Roberts on Tuesday. ``We've enhanced this shopping
center by bringing in a Fortune 500 company.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the reservation center, Lancaster offered a $200,000 loan
that will be considered paid off, provided the company hires 250
employees and maintains their jobs. The chief incentive, however,
was the enterprise zone designated in Southern California's
Antelope Valley, which can provide the company $2 million to $4
million in state tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses in the enterprise zone are eligible for state tax
breaks, including credits on equipment purchases, interest
deductions for income earned on investments and wage credits for
workers hired through certain programs or from certain low-income
areas. The wage credits can be as much as $26,000 per worker over a
five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be here here without it (enterprise zone),'' said
Michael English, director of regional reservation centers for
Starwood.
</P>
<P>
   The company was also drawn to the region by the building and the
availability of a skilled work force, English said.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood plans to spend about $2 million to convert the
17,000-square-foot building from a showroom to a phone operation
center. That work will include providing an uninterrupted power
supply, installing phone lines and remodeling the interior of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood expects to begin recruiting in the Antelope Valley in
early September. Antelope Valley College and Starwood plan to
develop a training program for the company's employees.
</P>
<P>
   The training program will include computer and customer service
skills. The program will use existing facilities at Antelope Valley
College.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood has more than 700 hotels in 72 countries. The company
employs more than 130,000 people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
