<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOLLO 11 CREW RECEIVES AVIATION'S MOST PRESTIGIOUS AWARD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the 30th anniversary of their historic mission
to the moon, the crew members of Apollo 11 reunited Tuesday at the
National Air and Space Museum to receive aviation's most
prestigious award.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a stage with the Columbia command module that
brought them back to Earth, space pioneers Neil Armstrong, Buzz
Aldrin and Michael Collins were presented with the Smithsonian
Institution's Samuel P. Langley Medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mission taught us a great deal about the moon, but it
taught us even more about ourselves, what we could accomplish as a
nation if we set our hearts and minds to it,'' Vice President Al
Gore told the astronauts as he presented the medal.
</P>
<P>
   The three spacemen later delivered a moon rock to the White
House and, in a televised discussion of their mission, credited
Cold War tensions with the Soviet Union for America's victory in
the race for the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we would have gone to the moon in the time that
we did without competition'' from the Soviets, said Aldrin, the
second man to walk on the moon. ``Competition got us there in a
hurry, but left us without a clear vision'' for future space
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Although some would have preferred a cooperative effort, ``in
many cases, competition is more effective,'' said Armstrong, the
Apollo 11 commander and the first man to set foot on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports that then-President Nixon's speechwriter had
prepared remarks for use if Armstrong and Aldrin had become
stranded on the moon, the astronauts said they were unaware at the
time but expected such steps had been taken.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrin said he figured the lunar-landing portion of their
mission had little better than a 50-50 chance of succeeding, so
``it is not surprising'' that officials made contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who remained in moon orbit in the Columbia capsule,
recalled that he was safer than Armstrong and Aldrin aboard the
landing module Eagle and might have been the only one to survive
the mission. ``I didn't want to come home by myself, but if I had
to, I would have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's rare joint appearance by the three astronauts
coincided with the scheduled launch of the first space-shuttle
mission commanded by a woman, Air Force Col. Eileen Collins. The
launch was delayed after sensors erroneously reported an abnormal
amount of hydrogen in an engine compartment. Liftoff was reset for
12:28 a.m. EDT Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary of the July 20 moonwalk by Armstrong and Aldrin
also was marked by the recovery of the Liberty Bell 7, the Mercury
capsule that carried astronaut Virgil ``Gus'' Grissom into space
and almost dragged him to the floor of the Atlantic Ocean. The
capsule sank near the Bahamas moments after splashdown at the end
of Grissom's suborbital flight July 21, 1961.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday's ceremony at the Air and Space Museum, Gore
recalled the challenge of President Kennedy in 1961 to put a man on
the moon and return him safely to Earth by the end of the decade.
It was Kennedy, the vice president said, ``who taught us to reach
for the moon and the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore lauded the slain president's vision for America's space
program, then took note of the loss of Kennedy's son in an airplane
crash Friday night. ``John Kennedy Jr. wore that mantle of
possibility and discovery, the belief that we can reach a new
horizon if we have the urge to try,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore praised Armstrong, Aldrin and Collins, calling them heroes
during a period of civil unrest amid Vietnam War protests and the
assassinations of Robert F. Kennedy and the Rev. Martin Luther
King. ``With your first step into the Sea of Tranquillity, you
brought tranquillity to the millions waiting here at home,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong spoke for Aldrin and Collins as they stood against a
backdrop of their space capsule. Hanging overhead was Charles
Lindbergh's Spirit of St. Louis and the airplane flown at Kitty
Hawk by the Wright brothers. Armstrong said the Apollo 11 crew was
accepting the award ``on behalf of all the men and women of the
Apollo program ... (and) the contributions of so many in this past
century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The important achievement of Apollo was a demonstration that
humanity is not forever chained to this planet, and our visions go
farther than that,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   The solid-gold Langley medal, named for a U.S. aviation pioneer
and the Smithsonian's third secretary, has been awarded to only 19
others, including Wilbur and Orville Wright; Lindbergh, the first
trans-Atlantic aviator; Robert Goddard, the rocket scientist; and
Alan Shepard, the first American in space.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Armstrong, Aldrin and Collins presented
President Clinton with a half-pound rock from the moon. Armstrong
said NASA was only loaning the rock to the White House and might
someday ask for its return. He then assured Clinton that the rock
``will be here a while.'' The rock was collected by Armstrong on
July 20, 1969, about four paces from the spot where the Eagle
landed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, while answering students' questions during a television
appearance at the Newseum in suburban Washington, the astronauts
recalled being ``concerned'' and ``worried'' _ but not scared _
during the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that much equipment, always there are some things that go
wrong, but it really wasn't the equipment we were worried about,''
Armstrong said. ``We were concerned that we might somehow make a
mistake that would not allow the flight to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scared, no; worried, yes,'' Collins said during the program
broadcast live on CNBC and NASA's internal television network.
``Spaceflight is just kind of an awareness in the back of your mind
that a lot of things can go on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
