<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHWARZ-CONDUCTOR-3TA     07-20 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWARZ-CONDUCTOR-3TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOSTLY MOZARTEAN SO FAR: MOSTLY A SUCCESS?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 25) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   (af)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Gerard Schwarz was named music adviser of the
Mostly Mozart Festival at Lincoln Center in 1982, his conducting
career had the brilliance and momentum of a rocket streaking across
the heavens. Then 34, he had resigned as a trumpeter of the New
York Philharmonic seven years before to devote himself to
conducting, which he had done as a sideline since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   He was the music director of two orchestras _ the Y Chamber
Symphony (now the New York Chamber Symphony), which was created for
him at the 92d Street Y in 1976, and the Los Angeles Chamber
Orchestra, which he inherited from Sir Neville Marriner in 1978 _
as well as the founding director of the Waterloo Festival in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He had established his credentials as an advocate of new music,
both at the Y and at Merkin Concert Hall, where he started the
series Music Today. He was making inroads on the guest-conducting
circuit. And the Mostly Mozart position, which soon morphed into a
full-fledged directorship, raised his visibility around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk, as there always is when a young American
conductor begins piling up accomplishments, of a future at the helm
of a major American orchestra. ``With talent on this order,''
Harold C. Schonberg wrote in The New York Times in 1980, after a
New York visit by the Los Angeles Chamber Orchestra, ``there is no
place for him but up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years after that prediction, it is fair to ask whether
Schwarz, now 51, has indeed made his way up in the music world. But
how one answers that question is bound up with one's view of what
constitutes success for a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz continues to direct Mostly Mozart, which opens its 33d
season on Tuesday evening. But the festival has been scaled back in
recent years to make way for the Lincoln Center Festival, and
Schwarz has become less of a presence. Of the 19 programs this
summer, 11 are to be performed by guest ensembles, leaving only 8
for the festival orchestra, with Schwarz conducting 3.
</P>
<P>
   He also remains music director of the New York Chamber Symphony,
conducting four of its six programs a season at Alice Tully Hall.
His other two directorships in 1982 have fallen by the wayside, but
in 1983 he became music adviser to the Seattle Symphony, and two
years later he was appointed its music director. His involvement
with Seattle has since eclipsed his other activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career as a conductor is based in Seattle,'' Schwarz
recently said by telephone from his home there. ``I believe that if
you're going to do something significant in the music world, you
have to plant your roots and fight for what's important
artistically. If you think about it, I am the major representative
of classical music in Seattle. And that's a tremendous
responsibility, not only to the public and the orchestra but also
to the art form. Seattle is not New York. If we don't do a
Tchaikovsky symphony, there is a strong possibility that no
Tchaikovsky symphony will be played in Seattle that season. We are
the orchestra of this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly Mozart, by contrast, has been as much a battleground as a
home for Schwarz in the 1990s. Still, it would be wrong to take his
accomplishments there for granted. When he took over the festival,
it had become tired and formulaic. He quickly reinvigorated it,
reconfiguring its repertory to include 19th- and early 20th-century
examples of Neo-Classicism while maintaining Mozart's centrality.
</P>
<P>
   He also broke an unfortunate pattern in the orchestra's
performances. In the festival's early years, the group produced
polished, energetic performances during the first week, and then
increasingly frayed ones as inadequate rehearsal time and a heavy
performing schedule took their toll.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz upgraded the freelance band, bringing in players who
worked with him at the 92d Street Y. An improvement in performance
was immediate.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to sour in 1992, at the end of Lincoln Center's
misbegotten Mozart Bicentennial, a two-year traversal of Mozart's
complete works. In the original plan, Lincoln Center's constituent
organizations and visiting performers were to have divided the gems
and the juvenilia equitably.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Mostly Mozart was saddled with a
disproportionate number of early and minor works that no one else
wanted to perform. Neither Schwarz nor the players could muster
enthusiasm for these pieces, and the festival was scrappily played,
badly attended and generally stultifying: ``a horrible
experience,'' Schwarz now calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse. William Lockwood, an architect of Mostly
Mozart, left Lincoln Center, and Nathan Leventhal, the center's
president, talked about replacing Mostly Mozart with a broader
summer program, which has become the Lincoln Center Festival.
Schwarz, seeing an opportunity to expand his activities at Lincoln
Center, lobbied behind the scenes, arguing that as a musician with
programming experience, he should have more say in Lincoln Center
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   His timing was not ideal. In November 1992, Lincoln Center
appointed Jane S. Moss vice president for programming, specifically
to revitalize the center's offerings. Ms. Moss, not yet inculcated
with Lincoln Center's sense of corporate diplomacy, made no secret
of her desire to see Schwarz ousted, and Mostly Mozart with him.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz was not defenseless. In his years on the podium, he has
developed an ability to make powerful friends and a sense of when
to enlist their clout. As members of the Mostly Mozart Festival
Orchestra took to the streets, encouraging patrons to write letters
and sign petitions, Schwarz called Jerome L. Greene, a
philanthropist whose foundation provided hefty support to Lincoln
Center.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry was a great man, a great supporter of the arts and a
dear friend,'' Schwarz said of Greene, who died last month. ``Yes,
I did, at the time, speak to him, eliciting his aid. What did he
do? I don't know. I just called him on the phone, and he said he'd
help.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Mostly Mozart was reduced rather than jettisoned,
and it has continued to evolve, largely through Ms. Moss'
initiatives. She has expanded its role as a presenter of other
ensembles, this year including the Freiburg Baroque Orchestra, the
Salzburg Camerata Academica, the New London Consort and Gidon
Kremer's Kremerata Baltica.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Ms. Moss and Schwarz profess great admiration for
each other, and Ms. Moss denies that the spotlight on visiting
ensembles is meant to diminish Schwarz's role in the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all developments that Gerry has embraced,'' Ms. Moss
said. ``I think the reality of Mostly Mozart is that since it has a
theme and identity, one is always looking for ways to expand what
it is and what it does. But I think Gerry is doing a wonderful job
with Mostly Mozart.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz returned the compliment: ``Look, Jane and I were on
opposite sides, slightly, but we have gotten along wonderfully
since then. She came to Lincoln Center with lots of good,
innovative ideas, some of them unrealistic, as we all do. But she
has become a realist. I think she understands that we are guided by
the public. I'm a great believer in the public. I want to lead
them, but if I lead and they don't like what they hear, they're not
going to come back. If they trust me, whether in New York or
Seattle, they'll keep coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schwarz's work in Seattle shows that he understands that
balance. His success is quantifiable. The Seattle Symphony played
30 percent more concerts last season than a year before, with
ticket sales at an impressive 92 percent. Schwarz has also expanded
its activities to include Baroque and Mozart series beyond the
regular season. During his tenure, the orchestra retired its
longstanding debt.
</P>
<P>
   There have been minor dust-ups. In one, Schwarz sought to hire a
principal horn player over the objections of the orchestra
committee. In another, his chosen choral director raised hackles by
radically reconfiguring the orchestra's choir, dismissing several
longtime members in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But such disputes have been overshadowed by Schwarz's
accomplishments: not least, the construction of Benaroya Hall,
which opened to glowing reviews last September. Built at a cost of
$118 million, it has a main auditorium that seats 2,500 and a
recital hall that seats 450. Schwarz was involved in every aspect
of the project, from the acoustics to the color of the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't an inch of that hall that I didn't have the
ability to be involved with,'' Schwarz said, correctly noting that
it is unusual for a conductor to take such an active hand. What's
more, the project benefited from the same talent for making
influential friends that helped save Schwarz's job at Mostly
Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't raised any money,'' he said. ``I'm an artistic
person, not a fund-raiser. But as a part of this community, I know
a lot of people. I didn't ask Jack Benaroya for his initial gift to
build the new hall. He asked me to lunch and said he was thinking
of giving us 10 or 15 million dollars. And I quickly said, `15.'''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz spends most of his time in Seattle now, and has become
entrenched in its civic life. His children attend school there, and
when a school tax was proposed, he joined members of the Seahawks
and other Seattle celebrities in a phone bank, calling voters to
enlist support for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, he contributes editorials to The Seattle Times. He
conducts the Seattle Opera on occasion and is said to be as
recognizable in the city as Leonard Bernstein was in New York in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Seattle, Schwarz's career has blossomed more slowly than
his supporters of the 1970s and 80s expected. The commonest measure
of a podium career is the extent to which a conductor has been
embraced by major orchestras in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For an American, success with the so-called Big Five _ the New
York Philharmonic, the Boston Symphony, the Philadelphia Orchestra,
the Cleveland Orchestra and the Chicago Symphony _ is generally
considered crucial. The podiums of those orchestras are coveted in
a way that others are not, and right now, music directorships in
New York, Boston and Philadelphia are up for grabs (Cleveland's
having just been filled, by Franz Welser-Most).
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Schwarz is rarely mentioned as a likely candidate
for such a directorship is striking. But it is not surprising,
since the major orchestras have been slow to hire him as a guest
conductor. He has conducted the Philadelphia Orchestra three times:
twice as a substitute for an ailing conductor, and in a scheduled
appearance last season. He was invited to conduct the Boston
Symphony, he said, but had a scheduling conflict.
</P>
<P>
   He points out, too, that he conducts annually in Paris. He has
led the London Symphony, the English Chamber Orchestra and the
Czech Philharmonic, and has conducted opera at the Kirov in St.
Petersburg, as well as in Washington and Seattle. He has
engagements in Dresden and recently completed a three-year term as
artistic adviser to the Tokyo Bunkamura Orchard Hall, which
involved conducting the Tokyo Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from his resume are conducting appearances
at the New York Philharmonic, where he was co-principal trumpeter
from 1972 to 1975. Deborah Borda, the orchestra's executive
director, refused to comment on whether Schwarz might conduct the
orchestra, but several of his supporters, who would not speak for
attribution, say that the Philharmonic musicians oppose extending
an invitation. Schwarz's own theory follows similar lines.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I think part of the problem is that in New York, I'm very
familiar,'' he said. ``There are players in all the major
orchestras who went to high school with me at Music and Arts, or
who were in my class at Juilliard, or who were students of mine at
Waterloo. I am an open book. But I went to Berlin to conduct a
radio orchestra recently, and I had a big success there. They don't
know me. They don't even know that I was ever an instrumentalist.
There is comfort in ignorance. It allows the relationship to evolve
over a period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Symphony remains on the periphery of the major
American orchestras. But the city has had a higher national profile
in the age of ``Frasier,'' Nirvana, Starbucks and Amazon.com, and
Schwarz is riding that wave. He records plentifully with the
orchestra, and because many of his Seattle recordings offer
repertory otherwise unavailable _ including works by
mid-20th-century American symphonists like Howard Hanson, David
Diamond and Deems Taylor _ they inherently attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   The move to Benaroya Hall has improved the orchestra's sound,
Schwarz said, and he hopes listeners around the country will gain
some sense of his accomplishment with the orchestra next month,
when it gives its first nationally telecast concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at someone like me, and when Cleveland, say, is
looking for a music director, I'm not there,'' he said. ``I've
never conducted there. They've never seen me. And in New York,
which is the most important city in the world for most people, most
concertgoers have never seen me conduct a Brahms, Mahler or
Bruckner symphony. I do those things in Seattle. In New York, I
conduct chamber orchestras, and the fact is, important conductors
have always emerged from large orchestras, not from chamber
orchestras.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the resistance to Schwarz is undoubtedly artistic. Like
most musicians, he has detractors, some of whom find his
performances concerned with fussy detail rather than the larger
musical line; others find his readings of standard repertory
wooden. But those opinions are far from unanimous. In both New York
and Seattle, his reviews have largely been favorable.
</P>
<P>
   Even Schwarz's detractors concede that his programming has
always been adventurous, and his interpretations of 20th-century
American music have always been persuasive. He revived neglected
works by Hanson, Diamond and other American Romantics almost
single-handedly, and he continues to explore obscure corners of
that repertory.
</P>
<P>
   He has kept up with younger composers as well, particularly
those writing music that is accessible but not simplistic. Richard
Danielpour, Deborah Drattell, Michael Nathaniel Hersch and Vivian
Fung all had early performances in Schwarz's programs.
</P>
<P>
   Few conductors have devoted themselves to 20th-century American
music with his methodical devotion, and those who have _ among
them, Michael Tilson Thomas, Leonard Slatkin, David Zinman and
Dennis Russell Davies _ also seem to have hit a glass ceiling that
keeps them from Big Five directorships.
</P>
<P>
   It seems clear that for whatever reasons _ orchestral players'
artistic or personal qualms, administrators' distrust of Schwarz's
backstage maneuvering, or his own increasing focus on Seattle _ he
is not about to crack into the top rank of international superstar
conductors. But whether his career has so far been a success is
another question.
</P>
<P>
   If classical music is to thrive, it must do so beyond the cities
of the Big Five orchestras and their European counterparts. Schwarz
has lighted a fire under symphonic music in Seattle and, along the
way, campaigned hard for an expanded repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Gerry hasn't had the big opportunities in New York,''
said Omus Hirshbein, who founded the New York Chamber Symphony and
is now its executive vice president. ``But he has done in Seattle
what the great conductors have done with their cities. In artistic
terms, in terms of the public, in terms of the hall, he has taken
that orchestra from one level to another. That's the success a
music director should have in a community. Maybe the community
should have been Boston. But it was Seattle. And so what?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
