<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-HEWLETT-PACKARD-     07-20 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEWLETT-PACKARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CRACKS IN THE GLASS CEILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 21: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carleton S. Fiorina, the new chief executive officer of the
Hewlett-Packard Co., says there is no need to focus on her gender
in discussing her appointment. ``I truly hope,'' she told reporters
after her appointment was announced, ``that we are at the point now
where everyone has figured out that the accomplishments of women
across industry demonstrate that there is not a glass ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice if that were true, and it was impressive that
questions about her gender came at the end of a lengthy news
conference at which far more attention was paid to her plans for
Hewlett-Packard and to the challenges it faces. Nonetheless, we
have not gotten to the point where it is common to see women at the
helm of major corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fiorina's appointment reduces to 497 the number of companies
in the Fortune 500 whose chief executives are men. (The other
exceptions are Jill Barad of Mattel and Marion Sandler of Golden
West Financial.) When Fortune magazine ranked the most powerful
women in American business last fall, Ms. Fiorina, then a senior
executive at Lucent Technologies, ranked first. Catalyst, a
nonprofit research organization that focuses on women executives,
reports that in 1998 11 percent of senior executives at Fortune 500
companies were women.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, there is an age factor at work in the small
number of female chief executives. Ms. Fiorina, 44, earned her MBA
degree in 1980, by which time many companies were willing to hire
women as junior executives. Most chief executives are in their 50s
or 60s, and entered the business ranks at a time when there were
fewer opportunities for women.
</P>
<P>
   There are also industry issues, as Ms. Fiorina noted in an
interview Tuesday. ``You get a very competitive industry, with a
very intensive pace of change,'' she said. ``The companies that are
going to survive or excel have to focus on getting the best talent,
regardless of gender, regardless of race or anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still institutional resistance to women at some
companies. Until recently, few companies have had women in senior
posts who could serve as role models and mentors for younger women.
In that regard, Hewlett-Packard has been a pioneer. Its executive
committee will now have four women and three men on it. One of the
women is Ann Livermore, the 40-year-old head of Hewlett-Packard's
enterprise computer systems business, who was widely viewed as the
top inside candidate for chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The greater challenge for Ms. Fiorina may stem from her status
as an outsider at a company that has historically promoted from
within. (She last worked for Hewlett-Packard as a secretary during
the summer before her sophomore year at Stanford University.) Her
hope that the glass ceiling no longer exists may be premature, but
her appointment is a signal that it is at least cracking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
