<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ALBANY BUDGET MINUET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 21: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally the New York State Legislature has resumed work on its
budget, now 112 days late, with a $73-billion spending plan that
was mapped out the old-fashioned way, behind closed doors. Last
year's open negotiations were deemed a failure by the lawmakers
after Gov. George Pataki, Zorro-like, slashed through much of the
legislature's early effort. Now, declaring that their process is
more like Washington's, the governor, assembly speaker and Senate
majority leader have adopted a structure that cedes only small
changes to 10 conference committees open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The big three _ Pataki, Speaker Sheldon Silver and Joseph Bruno,
the Senate majority leader _ have produced what was once called a
gentlemen's agreement that the governor will not shred this year's
budget if the legislators stay within its $73 billion limit. The
legislative leaders convened the 10 conference committees this week
to figure out how to spend $1.1 billion on schools, health and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The budget deal already approved by Albany's legislative triad
restores some crucial spending for Medicaid and tuition assistance
for low-income college students. Money can be allotted for
pre-kindergarten classes and reducing early-grade class size,
increases that come at the expense of basic operating aid for
schools. New York City's school system, the nation's largest, still
needs extra attention as it imposes new standards and ends social
promotion, sending over 300,000 children into un-air-conditioned
summer schools next year.
</P>
<P>
   Albany also needs to find enough money for an anti-tobacco
campaign, given the $1-billion-a-year windfall coming soon from the
national settlement with tobacco companies. At this point the state
spends $6.5 million annually, compared with Florida's $70 million
or California's $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   As for fiscal responsibility, the governor deserves credit for
planning to use nearly $2 billion in surplus funds to help pay for
future deficits. However, the present plan also calls for several
shaky one-shot revenue proposals that include selling the state's
malpractice insurance fund, delaying an end to New York's sales tax
on clothing and raiding a program for retraining health care
workers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The big-ticket items for the future, unfortunately, are still a
matter of ``internal debate.'' They include how much to borrow for
capital projects and how much to cut taxes. So much for an open
budget process in Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
