<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTIMES-EDITORS-NYT &LR;      07-20 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTIMES-EDITORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN EDITOR AT NEW YORK TIMES STEPS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joyce Purnick will step down as metropolitan editor
of The New York Times after two years of supervising the paper's
largest news department, it was announced Tuesday. Jonathan
Landman, the editor of The Week in Review, will succeed her.
</P>
<P>
   In a 20-year career at the newspaper, Ms. Purnick has covered
city and state government, written editorials and written the Metro
Matters column. She will return to writing a twice-weekly column on
politics and government in the fall, said Joseph Lelyveld,
executive editor of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I'm leaving is simple,'' Ms. Purnick said at a
meeting with her staff on Tuesday. ``After a lot of soul-searching,
I decided I want my future to be in writing, not editing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Purnick, 53, has overseen coverage of the New York region by
a department of nearly 140 reporters and editors since June 1997,
when she became the first woman to be metropolitan editor at The
Times. She received the 1997 Meyer Berger Award from the Graduate
School of Journalism of Columbia University for her columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``During her two years as metro editor, Joyce Purnick has made
an indelible mark in one of our most demanding leadership roles,''
Lelyveld said in a memo to the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Landman, 46, has been editor of The Week in Review since January
1994. He joined The Times as a copy editor in 1987, and was later
an assistant editor on the national and metropolitan desks. He was
deputy editor of the Washington bureau in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to The Times, Landman was deputy city editor at
The Daily News. He also worked as a reporter at Newsday and as a
reporter and an editor at The Chicago Sun-Times.
</P>
<P>
   Lelyveld said that at The Times, Landman had shown himself ``to
be anything but a play-it-safe organization guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Outspoken to a fault, contrarian in his zest for ideas and
passionate in his love of good copy, he has long been recognized as
one of our most original editors,'' Lelyveld said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2204EDT &QL; 
