<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PIONEERS-NYT &LR;      07-20 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PIONEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RELEASES NAMES OF 115 `PIONEERS' WHO RAISED $100,000 FOR HIS
CAMPAIGN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mich., Wash., Colo., Md., Conn.)   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bowing to criticism from several groups, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas has revealed the identities of some of the
``Pioneers'' who have raised at least $100,000 each for his
deep-pocketed presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   They comprise a cross-section of some of the most wealthy and
powerful people in the Republican Party, including several Bush
family members, former members of President George Bush's
administration, several chief executives, several members of
Congress (Rep. Joe L. Barton of Texas and Jennifer Dunn of
Washington) and two governors (John Engler of Michigan and Bill
Owens of Colorado).
</P>
<P>
   The 115 friends and supporters identified by Bush have already
met their money targets and played a crucial role in helping his
campaign accumulate a record-shattering $37 million in just four
months. But the campaign declined to identify several hundred
others who are still working to make their goals.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, several public interest groups here and in Texas and
several news organizations, including The New York Times, had asked
Bush campaign officials for a complete list of the Pioneers, but
the campaign zealously guarded their identities. But after being
asked about the fund-raising program again at a news conference on
Monday, Bush agreed to release the identities of the 115 Pioneers
who had raised at least $11.5 million for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who've decided to take time out of their
lives to help me become the president,'' Bush told reporters in
Austin, Texas. ``And I am really grateful and very humbled by the
outpouring of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six of the Pioneers, nearly half, live in Texas, including
Kenneth Lay, chairman of the Enron Corp., and A.W. Riter Jr., a
managing partner in Pinstripe Investments and a regent of the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which takes its name from an offhand remark made by
Bush at a meeting of campaign strategists earlier this year, also
includes some powerful Republican fund-raisers who collected huge
sums for former Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, the party's presidential
nominee in 1996, and for the elder Bush in his re-election campaign
in 1992. They include Peter Terpeluk Jr. and Wayne L. Berman, both
Washington lobbyists; Hank Greenberg, the chairman of American
International Group; and Dr. Zach Zachariah of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist estimated Tuesday that there were 300
other Pioneers still trying to meet their $100,000 goals. Bush's
campaign did not disclose precisely how much each of the 115
Pioneers had raised.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Texas public interest group that pressed for
a full list of Pioneers said he was dissatisfied with the
campaign's response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush took a step in the right direction, but it is far
short of full disclosure,'' said Craig L. McDonald, director of
Texans for Public Justice, a nonpartisan research group that
studies the role of money in Texas government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a formalized sophisticated bundling operation,''
McDonald said of the Pioneers program. ``In a sense, the Pioneers
are $100,000 donors or $200,000 donors who are skirting the
post-Watergate campaign finance reforms. We wish the practice would
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Bush on Monday, McDonald complained that each
Pioneer has ``a secret identification number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pioneers reportedly instruct the donors whom they recruit to
note their secret code number on their checks so that your campaign
can credit the money to the proper Pioneer,'' McDonald wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, did not
return several phone calls seeking comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pioneers program is one secret of Bush's success, but
several of his opponents have similar programs. Vice President Al
Gore, for example, has an incentive program for fund-raisers who
raise at least $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed the intense interest in the Pioneers among
reporters and advocates for an overhaul of the campaign finance
system, saying he had nothing to hide. He also reminded members of
the news media that his campaign had received more than 80,000
donations, ranging from $5 to the $1,000 maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Two Bush family members are among the Pioneers who have raised
at least $100,000 each: Bush's sister, Dorothy B. Koch of Maryland,
and his uncle Jonathan Bush of Connecticut. At his news conference,
Bush mistakenly said that his brother Marvin was a Pioneer who had
met his goal. But his name was not on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a Pioneer,'' the governor said. ``If he's not, we
need to expose that he's not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
