<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-EARNINGS-460&AMP;ADD-N     07-20 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-EARNINGS-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM PROFIT BEATS WALL STREET EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Pocketing higher profits even as its market share
continues to erode, the General Motors Corp. said Tuesday that it
earned $1.73 billion in the second quarter, a vast improvement over
the $306 million it earned from continuing operations during the
same period last year, when there was a costly strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went right during the quarter,'' said David B.
Healy, an auto analyst at Burnham Securities. ``It represents the
best GM can do, given the way the company is laid out these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Others concurred, particularly because auto sales have been at
record levels so far this year. ``Given the circumstances, they
pretty much had a license to print money this quarter,'' said
Nicholas Lobaccaro, an auto analyst at Lehman Bros. In a down
market, shares of the largest auto makers declined. GM fell
$1.8125, to $66.50.
</P>
<P>
   The profit, which amounted to $2.66 a diluted share, compared
with 40 cents a share in the quarter a year earlier, beat analysts'
expectations of $2.56 a share, according to the First Call Corp.,
which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Those results exclude Delphi Automotive Systems, the giant auto
parts unit, which GM spun off on May 28. Including Delphi, GM's
second-quarter net income hit $1.92 billion, or $2.94 a share,
compared with $389 million, or 52 cents a share, during the period
a year earlier. Second-quarter revenue rose to $45.07 billion from
$37.27 billion, allowing GM to maintain its position as the world's
largest company, ahead of Ford, which had $42.28 billion in
second-quarter sales.
</P>
<P>
   Profits strengthened in North America and Europe but turned to
losses in Latin America. Losses worsened in Asia, and GM's Hughes
Electronics unit took a one-time, pretax charge of $125 million
that caused a $92 million loss, compared with a $56 million profit
in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consolidated results show the strength of our globally
integrated company,'' said John F. Smith Jr., GM's chairman and
chief executive. He was particularly pleased with the company's
performance in North America ``in one of the most intensely
competitive markets in recent history.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rising profits, GM executives have been watching the
company's market share in the United States continue its
decades-long slide. By the end of the second quarter, it hit 29.5
percent, down 2.1 percent from the figure in the quarter a year
earlier. If the drop in share persists for a year, GM would have
lost buyers for more than an entire factory-worth of products.
</P>
<P>
   J. Michael Losh, GM's chief financial officer, said that will
not happen, noting that market share had topped 30 percent in June.
``We expect the share to continue to improve as we go through the
balance of the year,'' Losh said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wendy Beale Needham, an auto analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette said, ``Imagine what will happen to profits when their
market share improves.'' She raised her earnings estimate for the
year to $8.32 a share from $8.14 on the basis of Tuesday's strong
results. The consensus among auto analysts is that GM will earn
$8.22 a share for the year, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall second-quarter results are a mix of impressive
strengths and lingering weaknesses. The company had $16.7 billion
in cash at the end of the quarter, up from $11 billion a year ago.
Most shareholders have applauded two recent moves: its spinoff of
Delphi earlier this year and its huge stock buyback plan. GM has
spent about $7.3 billion buying back about 15.2 percent of its
outstanding shares since January 1997. During the second quarter,
it bought back $520 million worth.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, GM has been searching for ways to cut costs. It
trimmed $1.8 billion in the first half of the year, Losh said.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the company remained bloated. ``They are still
a high-cost producer,'' Healy said. ``They'll turn out to have
lower profit margins than either Ford or the domestic operations of
DaimlerChrysler.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said last week that its North American auto operations
earned profit margins of 7.7 percent in the second quarter.
DaimlerChrysler is scheduled to report its first-half results on
July 29.
</P>
<P>
   GM's automotive profit margins worldwide were 4.2 percent, short
of the company's own goal of 5 percent. Margins hit 5.1 percent in
North America, beating the goal for three consecutive quarters now.
</P>
<P>
   The company also sold a greater proportion of its cars and
trucks at discounts to car rental fleets: 21.2 percent of its
vehicles were sold to fleets in the second quarter, up from 18.4
percent last year. That helped lift its market share. Some analysts
predicted the company would struggle to increase its share, as
executives have vowed to do. ``They are going to continue to have
frustration in their market share,'' Lobaccaro said.
</P>
<P>
   But continuing talks with the United Automobile Workers union
amount to the biggest wild card of the year. The union's three-year
contract expires this fall, and GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler are
negotiating the next contract this summer. Analysts are not
expecting a strike, but GM is most at risk because it has strained
relations with the union.
</P>
<P>
   Losh refused to comment on the negotiations Tuesday except to
say that the company had ``a strong cash position and a strong
balance sheet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
