<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7762 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-CRASH-HNS &LR;      07-20 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-CRASH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD FOCUSES ON `SPLASH POINT' AS DEBRIS SCATTERED OVER WIDE
AREA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOE STINEBAKER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODS HOLE, Mass. _ Federal officials confirmed Tuesday that
John F. Kennedy Jr.'s airplane smashed into the Atlantic Ocean with
such force that it scattered debris over an area several hundred
yards wide, hampering their search efforts. The search was then
made more difficult by strong currents off the Massachusetts coast,
which scattered the debris even farther along the ocean bottom.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-dozen ships from at least three federal
agencies have been scouring the ocean floor for days in an as-yet
unsuccessful effort to retrieve debris and, more importantly, the
bodies of Kennedy, his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her
older sister Lauren Bessette who were killed Friday night when
their airplane crashed while on approach to Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The search area has been narrowed to a 12-square mile field a
few miles southwest of Martha's Vineyard. While some ``target
areas'' within that field have been eliminated, sonar searches have
added others _ leaving the Navy, Coast Guard and the Massachusetts
State Police with more than a dozen specific sites remaining to be
searched.
</P>
<P>
   One target area seven-and-a-half miles southwest of Gay Head,
near where investigators believe the plane crashed into the water,
has attracted much of the searchers' attention. Although officials
would not describe the size of the debris they believe they have
located, the site has dominated their attention thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the day (Tuesday) with a much more accurate
projection of what the airplane's splash point was,'' said Coast
Guard Rear Adm. Richard Larrabee. ``We have a theoretical splash
point that we feel pretty good about.``
</P>
<P>
   A sonar-equipped Coast Guard ship, the Willow, identified
something near that ``splash point'' Tuesday, and searchers dropped
scuba divers from the Massachusetts State Police at the site. But
officials said the divers were hampered by strong currents, poor
visibility and limited dive times.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Bert Marsh, a salvage operation supervisor with the Navy,
said Tuesday that the divers were dropped over the spot, but
struggled with visibility of less than eight feet, 52-degree
temperatures and a ``significant'' current along the ocean floor
115 feet below the surface. Ultimately, no debris was found at the
site, but divers continued to search the site into Tuesday night
and were considering continuing all night.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, investigators released more radar information
about the position, speed and altitude of Kennedy's plane in the
seconds before its high-speed ditch into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pearce, the chief investigator for the National
Transportation Safety Board, which is in charge of the
investigation, said his agency had collected radar agency from
several radar sites in Massachusetts, Connecticut and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The radar data show that Kennedy's plane was at 5,600 feet above
sea level as it got within 34 miles of its goal, the airport at
Martha's Vineyard. The plane descended at a rate of nearly 700 feet
per minute _ a descent rate pilots say is typical for a plane such
as Kennedy's. Within five minutes, the plane had descended to 2,300
feet and was within 20 miles of the airport. It is then that the
flight takes an unusual turn.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce said radar indicates that the plane then turned to the
right and climbed back up to 2,600 feet for one minute. Thirty
seconds later, the plane turned right again and began a dizzying
descent that Pearce said may have exceeded 5,000 feet per minute.
Pilots and other experts say that means Kennedy's plane was in a
virtual freefall, or ``death spiral'' for the approximately 30
seconds before it smashed into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Although NTSB officials have been careful not to characterize
the speed of the plane's final descent or its crash, the aircraft
apparently shattered on impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you could draw your conclusions from the pieces we've
been bringing in, which are fragmented,'' Pearce said at an
afternoon news briefing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although divers were unable to retrieve any debris Tuesday, more
pieces were found floating or washed up on shore. Pearce said the
new debris included interior pieces of the plane's cabin and
overhead lining. Investigators declined to say whether any of the
new debris included personal effects, saying they had not yet had a
chance to discuss the finds with the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Cod Times reported that the debris included
registration papers from the plane that had washed ashore and been
delivered to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration spent part of Tuesday
battling reports that it had mishandled a warning about the Kennedy
plane just 25 minutes after it is believed to have crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Budd, a 21-year-old intern at the Martha's Vineyard
airport, called the FAA office in Bridgeport, Conn., at 10:05 p.m.
EDT Friday at the request of an unidentified couple waiting for
Lauren Bessette's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennedy Jr.'s on board,'' transcripts quote Budd telling the
FAA employee. ``He's, uh, they want to know, uh, where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   After repeated questions about Budd's identity, the FAA employee
rejected Budd's request to track the plane, saying, ``We don't give
this information out to people over the phone.'' The call ended
with Budd commenting, ``It's no big deal.``
</P>
<P>
   No action was taken until the Coast Guard received an urgent
call from a Kennedy family friend about 2:15 a.m. Saturday. The
friend was concerned that the Kennedy couple was late for their
expected arrival at Hyannis Port, where they were expected to
attend the wedding of Rory Kennedy, the youngest daughter of the
late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB officials have begun clamping down on the flow of
information to the media and the public in the past day or so.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gary Jones, a public information officer with the Coast
Guard, said Tuesday that Coast Guard officials would no longer be
allowed to grant interviews to the media other than at daily media
briefings. That decision prompted speculation that James Hall, the
presidentially appointed chairman of the NTSB, was responding to
political pressure from the Kennedy camp.
</P>
<P>
   Jones declined to comment on the speculation, saying only that
the gag order ``is not within usual Coast Guard public affairs
doctrine,'' but acknowledged that the Kennedy crash was ``a very
unusual case.``
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision came from above the Coast Guard, above and
outside the Coast Guard,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also have been careful to protect the crash site,
forbidding media outlets and sightseers from coming within 3,000
feet or from flying within a mile overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The search was expected to continue at least throughout the day
Wednesday. Officials have been hesitant to take on the sensitive
question of when the search might be called off if it continues to
show little success.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a question we have been pondering, and I have been
pondering,'' Larrabee said, adding that he and others were
struggling to define what would be ``a reasonable amount of time.``
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, mourning continued for the Kennedys and Lauren
Bessette on Tuesday, with hundreds of people lining up to tour the
John F. Kennedy Library and Museum in Boston and sign a condolence
card to the Kennedy family. Well-wishers also piled cards and
flowers at makeshift shrines at the Manhattan homes of the Kennedys
and Lauren Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   Flags were lowered to half-staff Tuesday throughout Cape Cod,
most conspicuously at the Kennedy family compound at Hyannis Port.
Sources close to the family said the Kennedys were discussing
arrangements for a memorial service at St. Thomas More Catholic
Church in New York City on Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
