<SLUG> BC-FBC-ACC-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warrick back to try again
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greensboro, N.C. _ Florida State wide receiver Peter Warrick is
one of the preseason favorites to win the Heisman Trophy and the
fleet pass-catcher was the center of attention during the final day
of the annual ACC Football Kickoff meetings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick surprised most Seminole fans by turning away from a sure
first-round pick in the NFL to return to Tallahassee for his final
year. ``After the Florida game (a 23-12 FSU victory), I decided I
was leaving, but I couldn't leave on a losing note after the
(national championship) Tennessee game,'' he said. ``I didn't
really feel it in my heart to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a year ago, I thought I'd be living in fame and
riches,'' he added. ``Well, it's fame all right, but it sure ain't
riches.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick says quarterback Chris Weinke is back 100 percent after
missing FSU's last four games with an injury. ``Weinke knows the
game,'' Warrick said. ``He's fine now. He rips a pair of my gloves
every day at practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-0, 195-pounder says he's done everything he can think of
to keep his distance from sports agents. ``I've already had my
telephone number changed three times,'' he said. ``I don't know how
they get those numbers. They must be the FBI or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Different strokes
</P>
<P>
   Clemson free safety Robert Carswell, a graduate of Stone
Mountain High, says the Tommy Bowden approach differs from last
year's coaching staff headed by Tommy West.
</P>
<P>
   ``This coaching staff shows you what they want. They'll take you
out on the field and walk you through it,'' he said. ``Last year,
that coaching staff just told you what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Carswell said he knew Bowden meant business on his first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a team meeting and one guy had a dog in there and he
threw the dog out. A couple of guys had their hats cocked to the
side and he made them take them off. We were in limbo and we wanted
a coach. We wanted to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback draw
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State senior quarterback Jamie Barnette has 7,295 career
total yards of offense compared with the 6,846 yards of Georgia
Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton, but Hamilton is the one being touted
as a Heisman Trophy candidate. Barnette shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the man well,'' he said. ``We've become good friends.
He kids me a lot about not having (split end) Torry Holt to throw
to this year and about not having a big offensive line to take care
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnette says he kids Hamilton about only one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taller than he is and I let him hear about that a lot.''
Barnette is listed as 6-0 while Hamilton is listed as 5-10. Both
are actually closer to 5-9, but Barnette may be a half inch taller.
</P>
<P>
   Who's calling?
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton lives with three teammates and says nobody wants to
answer the telephone when it rings. The all-conference quarterback
says he just refuses to answer it for fear it'll be an agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we'll answer it using other people's voices,'' he
said. ``Sometimes we'll answer it in a girl's voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
