<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-PIONEERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH `PIONEERS' INSIST FUND RAISING BY 115 IS A GRASS-ROOTS EFFORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's elite 115 fund-raisers are
called ``Pioneers'' because they are blazing new trails in campaign
finance by raising at least $100,000 each for his Republican
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raisers and Bush's campaign insist that the money is a
result of a populist grass-roots campaign, not the work of elite
business leaders seeking favors.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the Pioneers are people who helped the governor's
father, George Bush, win the presidency in 1988 by donating
$100,000 or more of their own money to the Republican National
Committee, a feat that granted them membership to Team 100. At
least two were criticized for getting special favors from the Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Another four are Gov. Bush's relatives: two of his father's
brothers, a cousin and his sister, Doro Koch. Seven are developers
and lawyers who helped Bush's brother, Jeb, win office as governor
of Florida last year.
</P>
<P>
   Midland, Texas, independent oilman and Pioneer Joe O'Neill is
probably more important to Bush than just for the money he has
raised. O'Neill introduced Bush to his wife, Laura.
</P>
<P>
   Four Pioneers are men who owned shares in the Texas Rangers
baseball team with Bush, including the governor's former Yale
fraternity brother Roland Betts. Another is Austin radio station
chain executive Steve Hicks, whose brother, Tom, bought the Rangers
last year.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven Pioneers have received Bush appointments to state
boards and commissions, including four University of Texas regents,
transportation commission Chairman David Laney, parks and wildlife
department Chairman Lee Bass and board member Dick Heath and public
safety commission Chairman Jim Francis, who also is chairman of the
Pioneers organization.
</P>
<P>
   One group of Pioneers appears to be aligned with Michigan Gov.
John Engler, frequently mentioned as a possible Bush running mate.
Another group of Pioneers are backers of Pennsylvania Gov. Tom
Ridge, another potential Bush running mate.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pioneers have helped Bush raise his record $37 million
campaign fund, the campaign also has drawn criticism for appearing
to use ``power brokers'' to pay for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush released the list of Pioneers late Monday under pressure
from the news media and public interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   The group Texans for Public Justice, however, said Tuesday that
Bush had not gone far enough because he has not released the list
of more than 250 people who have pledged to become Pioneers but
have not yet raised $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has a right to know who these high rollers are and
exactly how much money they have delivered,'' said Craig McDonald,
director of Texans for Public Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Simon, acting president of Common Cause, said Bush's
Pioneer organization indicated the governor is ready to launch a
financial arms race in next year's general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``These so-called Pioneers are the new class of political power
brokers whose status and access are determined by the big money
they bring to the campaign,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker defended the organization Tuesday,
calling it grass-roots fund raising that differed from a normal
campaign finance committee only in what its members are called.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like having a block captain for door knocking before
the election,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign finance Chairman Don Evans said voters will have
to trust Bush not to give his fund-raisers any special privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a leader who does the right things for the
right reasons,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   But several of Bush's Pioneers have been criticized in the past
for benefits they received from government under a Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Common Cause criticized actions involving California
agricultural investor Howard Leach, now a Pioneer. Leach, a member
of Team 100, told President Bush that growers needed low-cost water
released from the Central Valley Project. The water was released 10
days later.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Pioneer Heinz Prechter of Michigan, who was a Team
100 member, traveled to Japan with President Bush as a member of
the President's Export Council. The trip resulted in Prechter's
company getting a lucrative contract to sell sunroofs for Honda's
American-made cars, Common Cause reported.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas investor Charles Wyly was one of President Bush's Team
100 members and now is a Pioneer. In 1993, Wyly and his brother Sam
formed the Maverick Capital Fund, which last year received a $90
million investment from the University of Texas Investment
Management Co. Fund managers will receive more than $900,000 in
management fees.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pioneer is Boston real estate developer Herb Collins.
The Washington Post reported in 1996 that Collins was among a group
of developers trying to persuade House Ways and Means Committee
Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, to retain a lucrative tax break at
the same time they were raising money to help Archer's son-in-law
run for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Pioneer Marty Fiorentino, vice president of CSX
Transportation, helped Jeb Bush win the Sunshine State's
governorship. In 1997 Fiorentino was critical of a Democratic
National Committee retreat in Florida that allowed 70 people who
gave $50,000 to the DNC to meet privately with President Bill
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll get access to individuals in a small setting and you'll
get to show that you are a supporter in a very graphic way,''
Fiorentino told a Florida newspaper. ``This is as close to the
mother's milk of politics as you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent Bush fund-raisers from Houston, investment banker
Peter Coneway and lawyer-lobbyist Joe B. Allen, said they were part
of a grass-roots effort that belies the criticism from public
interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the facts that I have seen, it (the contributions to
Bush) has been a great groundswell of individuals,'' Coneway said.
``It's exactly the opposite of what these people are objecting
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Coneway said he volunteered to collect Bush campaign money from
friends and colleagues across the country as ``a labor of love''
because he thinks Bush would be a good president. He said he did
not raise the money as a member of a particular industry or
political group.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the individuals who have given $1,000 each have far
less influence on the political process than industries and
organizations that give unlimited funds to the political parties.
With so many individuals willingly contributing to Bush's campaign,
``what this campaign proves to me (is) you don't have a limited
number of people who are `the big contributors,''' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, along with Pioneers Robert Whilden and Tom Marinis, all
are with the firm of Vinson &AMP; Elkins in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he gathered the money primarily from friends, lawyers
and their spouses without regard to the legal and political causes
he represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues that I care most about probably don't have as much
to do with my law firm as they do with my long-term well-being,
which I think is connected to what generally happens in the whole
country,'' Allen remarked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
