<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7772 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEHLDAU-JAZZ-2TAKES-$     07-20 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEHLDAU-JAZZ-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAZZ PIANIST WITH A BRAHMSIAN BENT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Adam Shatz's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
Chicago Underground Trio.  
 By ADAM SHATZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jazz has an Oedipal problem, and critics are at least partly to
blame. A good deal of jazz writing comes down to matching sons with
their putative fathers, the men (for they are almost invariably
men) who influenced young musicians and whom the young resemble
with apparently biological precision.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing these lines of descent may be unavoidable, and even
illuminating at times. But it proves a crude, not to mention
patriarchal, way of listening. (Is it any wonder that young jazz
musicians revolt against the traditions handed down to them?)
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, the reception of Brad Mehldau, who, at
28, is among the most celebrated jazz pianists of his generation.
If you've heard his name mentioned, you've probably heard that he's
``the next Bill Evans.'' High praise, to be sure. But like most
such comparisons, this one is more than a little misleading, as
unfair as it is flattering.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Mehldau has often suggested the wounded,
melancholic Evans on his three ``Art of the Trio'' recordings with
the bassist Larry Grenadier and the drummer Jorge Rossy. And he has
Evans' gift for elevating standard material. (He has also battled
on and off with heroin addiction, which ultimately felled Evans.)
</P>
<P>
   But with each new record, Mehldau sounds less and less like
Evans, and his latest, ``Elegaic Cycle,'' a solo piano effort, is
further evidence of their differences. Evans, who died in 1980,
seemed to find it unbearable to shatter the perfection of silence,
which gave his music a haunting reticence. Mehldau, by contrast,
tends toward rapture, lavishly embroidering his improvisations with
counterpoint and caprice.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason behind the Evans analogies, one suspects, has
less to do with music than with race. Evans is the most famous
member of the tiny coterie of great white jazz pianists, a club
that also includes Lenny Tristano, Paul Bley and Keith Jarrett.
Being likened to him is the lot of sensitive white pianists, even
when, as in Mehldau's case, their playing carries equally strong
echoes of Herbie Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Elegaic Cycle'' underscores, however, Mehldau has his own,
eccentric sensibility. Like Evans, he is profoundly drawn to
classical music, but where Evans invoked early French modernists
like Debussy and Ravel, Mehldau demonstrates affinities with
19th-century German Romantics like Schubert and Brahms. On this
record, he has embraced what he admires of this repertory in a
manner so audacious that it seems ungenerous to refer to him as a
jazz musician.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau's interest in European concert music is one he shares
with many of his fellow pianists. Hancock made his concert debut at
the age of 11 in a performance with the Chicago Symphony Orchestra;
Cecil Taylor was an avid student of Stravinsky and Bartok; Jarrett
has recorded Shostakovich and Bach. Among Mehldau's exact
contemporaries, Jason Moran and Marc Cary have offered jazz
interpretations of, respectively, Ravel and Satie.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mehldau's passion for the brooding, metaphysical
sensibility of German Romanticism is unusual in jazz, in which
classical influences tend to be French, and casually held. During a
recent interview at the Avatar Studio in midtown Manhattan, where
he was mixing a forthcoming trio record, Mehldau reflected: ``If
there's any German ethos that attracts me, it has to do with the
incredible amount of welled-up emotion that's being conveyed.
There's a kind of longing that you feel in the literature and in
the music of Schubert and Schumann.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a studious, unpretentious air about Mehldau, who could
easily be mistaken for a graduate student in comparative
literature. The humble, worshipful mode comes naturally to him, as
he meditates on what he calls ``greatness'' _ the quality, he says,
of ``something so removed from me that it, like, feels above me.''
He added: ``When I hear Beethoven's string quartets or Coltrane's
`A Love Supreme,' I have no clue to how they pulled it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau felt exactly this commingling of awe, exaltation and
terror when, in his early 20s, he began practicing classical music
for the first time in a decade. (He studied jazz at the New School
in lower Manhattan.) ``I came back to classical more for pleasure
than anything else,'' he said, ``and it led me to this discovery of
Brahms, and that led to Schumann and Schubert.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, he read Thomas Mann's 1948 novel, ``Doctor
Faustus,'' an allegory of Germany's descent into fascism. The tale
of a composer who sells his soul to the Devil, the book features a
stirring lecture on Beethoven's late piano sonatas by Wendell
Kretschmar, a thinly disguised caricature of the music philosopher
Theodor Adorno.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau was overwhelmed by Mann's book, and went on to read
Rilke, Goethe and other German writers. Last summer he flew from
Hollywood, where he lives, to Berlin to spend a few months studying
German.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived, Berlin was celebrating the 50th anniversary of
``Doctor Faustus'' with an exhibit of Mann's manuscripts at the
national library. Just then, it occurred to Mehldau that he was
retracing the steps of his favorite author, for Mann had written
his novel in Pacific Palisades while in exile from Nazi Germany. It
was a good time to be in Berlin, and it was there that ``Elegaic
Cycle'' was conceived.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the piece, he said, ``came from the song-cycles
that I love in the German lieder tradition of Schubert's
`Winterreise.''' Composed in 1827, ``Winterreise,'' or ``Winter's
Journey,'' is a composition for piano and baritone set to two dozen
poems by Wilhelm Muller. In this bleak, hallucinatory work, a
jilted lover trudges through the snow, despairing of his love and
coming to terms with his mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau has tried to recreate something of this circular,
death-obsessed mood in ``Elegaic Cycle.'' One of its pieces,
``Ruckblick,'' or ``Retrospect,'' is named after the penultimate
movement of Brahms' Third Piano Sonata. Two tracks are explicit
elegies: one for William S. Burroughs and Allen Ginsberg, the other
for his mentor Fred Myrow.
</P>
<P>
   The three-note motif that starts the first piece, ``The Bard,''
recurs throughout the cycle, in some cases played upside-down. The
cycle as a whole is, by design, exceptionally dense with harmonic
cross-referencing. As Mehldau explained, ``There's something that
has always appealed to me about music that lets you know it's
bringing its themes back, because it's a real play on your
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Such devices were, in fact, (italics)the(end italics) hallmark
of Romantic elegies. As the musicologist Charles Rosen points out
in his study ``The Romantic Generation,'' the song-cycle's listener
is forced to ``listen back in his memory to the earlier songs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only then can he perceive how the cycle is taking shape,''
Rosen writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elegaic Cycle'' does not always wear its Germanic
predilections lightly, and Mehldau is certain to be faulted for
indulging them. Although recognizably a jazz record in its emphasis
on improvisation, it is occasionally lugubrious _ ponderous rather
than poetic. Not surprisingly, Mehldau was warned early on by
Warner Brothers, his label, that a solo album of original,
classical-inspired compositions would be a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau himself worried that ``it would come off sounding like a
misfired attempt at doing something classical.'' But he reminded
himself that most of the music he loved ``broke away from whatever
genre it was in.'' He went on: ``And with jazz, the people who do
that for me are musicians like Miles Davis, coming along with
`Bitches Brew' or `In a Silent Way.' I mean, (italics)what the hell
was that?(end italics) Or Keith Jarrett, who made this whole series
of solo piano records on ECM, which are so completely
unclassifiable.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett is a pianist who often comes to mind here, which is not
to say that Mehldau is the ``next Keith Jarrett.'' For Jarrett
virtually invented the genre in which ``Elegaic Cycle'' belongs:
the sprawling, introspective solo recital.
</P>
<P>
   One of the distinguishing genres of jazz in the 1970s, it had
largely vanished by the '90s when Bley, Andrew Hill and finally
Jarrett himself sought to re-establish their reputations in more
straight-ahead contexts.
</P>
<P>
   Like these pianists, Mehldau is an individualist with an
obsessive streak; or, as he would prefer, he is a ``hopeless
Romantic.'' And his recording raises the larger and more
interesting question of whether jazz contains an impulse that is
not, in the deepest sense, Romantic.
</P>
<P>
   After all, jazz is derived from the blues, a music that is on
intimate terms with grief and loss _ the signature concerns of
Romantic art. And as Mehldau suggests, jazz musicians are perhaps
dealing with the hard stuff when they're doing what comes
naturally, namely improvising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of improvisation,'' he writes in his liner notes,
``is a kind of affirmation of mortality. Even in the moment you're
creating something, it's already gone forever, and that's precisely
its strength. Improvisation would seem to solve the problem of
death by constantly dying as it's being born. It scoffs at loss,
and revels in its own transience.''
</P>
<P>
   What Mehldau is saying, in essence, is that jazz is an
inherently Romantic art, one that finds transcendence in the
ephemeral _ ``in the moment,'' as jazz musicians put it. The
pleasures of ``Elegaic Cycle,'' like those of Jarrett's seminal
``Koln Concert,'' are grandly provisional, achieved at the price of
occasional noodling.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau has not yet succeeded in fusing jazz improvisation with
the classical elegy. American listeners, who are as uncomfortable
with failure as they are with death, are not likely to give it the
hearing it deserves. But as Romantics have always insisted, art
that risks nothing in pursuit of the sublime is not worthy of the
name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
