<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7776 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGAPORE-ARTS-2TAKES     07-20 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGAPORE-ARTS-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVER PRAGMATIC SINGAPORE IS MAKING ART ITS BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for SINGAPORE-DANCE)  
 (af)  
 Susan Heller Anderson, a former New York Times reporter, writes
about the visual and performing arts.  
 By SUSAN HELLER ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ In less than five years the arts scene here has gone
from invisible to explosive. With a combination of seduction and
subsidies, the Singapore government is aggressively wooing artists
and arts organizations around the world to make their homes in this
affluent city-state.
</P>
<P>
   The first annual Singapore Arts Festival ended its monthlong run
at the end of June, having attracted 29 international troupes, more
than 200 fringe performers and a mammoth citywide sculpture
exhibition, thanks to generous government support.
</P>
<P>
   Three new museums have opened since 1996, with the expansion of
one under way. On the waterfront rises the Esplanade, an ambitious
$265 million performing-arts center with two concert halls,
rehearsal studios, outdoor performing spaces and a panoply of food
and entertainment amenities.
</P>
<P>
   These state-of-the-art facilities, combined with an
infrastructure of excellent transportation, communications and
financial services, greatly enhance Singapore's potential as an
arts center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the mid-'90s we realized that we must have a more
creative approach and encourage cultural activities,'' said Liu Tai
Ker, a Yale-educated architect and chairman of the National Arts
Council. ``A person involved in cultural activities will be a more
creative, thinking person, better in the work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many officially sanctioned developments here, cultural
activity is a result of pragmatic financial considerations. A zeal
to achieve first-world economic status coupled with three decades
of authoritarian, repressive leadership, had nearly obliterated
creativity. The city-state had become bland and boring, compared
with the bawdy glamour it had acquired under British rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is art for business' sake,'' said Christine Khor, the
assistant director for arts and entertainment at the Singapore
Tourism Board, which promotes the arts to attract tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of these factors _ the importance of business creativity
in an information age and culture as a tourist magnet _ the
government has established financial incentives for the arts
similar to those with which it has lured business.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Cirque du Soleil announced that it would make
Singapore its Asian touring base for at least six years. In return,
the government awarded it ``business headquarter status,'' a new
tax category that insures the Cirque several years' exemption from
paying income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Donors to museums are offered income-tax deductions and
permanent residency, depending on the size of their donations.
Gifts in excess of about $590,000 allow the donor a $1.2 million
tax deduction, twice the amount of the gift.
</P>
<P>
   The downside? The specter of censorship. Officially, Singapore
has no written censorship laws, according to Yong Pung How, the
chief justice of the supreme court. Yet every public performance
requires a license from the Public Entertainment Licensing Unit,
part of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. Unofficially, except for
outrageously controversial works, a number of established groups
are exempted, like the Singapore Repertory Theater, the Singapore
Dance Theater and Theaterworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already given them guidelines,'' said Goh Ching Lee, the
festival's organizer and the program development director at the
National Arts Council. She explained that the guidelines
``discourage'' works that are racist, pornographic, excessively
violent or politically offensive, which covers the majority of
themes that artists find provocative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood is a more open one, but it's not totally unmanaged,''
said Liu of the National Arts Council. ``It's very difficult for a
big country like the U.S. to recognize the vulnerability of a small
country to political unrest.'' How does a country merge wariness of
new ideas with an open cultural climate? ``That's the challenge,''
Liu admits.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from the festival's offerings and art exhibitions
and from interviews with artists and heads of arts organizations,
the government's rules have relaxed considerably. ``I've been here
six years and never once saw a guideline,'' said Tony Petito, the
founder and artistic director of Singapore Rep.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he directed ``Kiss of the Spider Woman,'' with its
themes of political repression, military brutality and
homosexuality. ``That could never have happened a few years ago,''
Petito said. ``We just applied for an R(A) rating, got the license
and did the show.'' Recently the government introduced a rating
system for films and plays to alert audiences about content.
</P>
<P>
   ``R(A) means `restricted artistic,' and may contain scenes and
language that are objectionable,'' Ms. Goh explained. R(A)
indicates viewing restricted to people 18 years old and over, but
there is no official enforcement. ``In more than 95 percent of
cases we don't even ask for an R(A) rating,'' Ms. Goh said, adding
that she could not recall a performance piece that had been banned
recently.
</P>
<P>
   But all limits are not suspended in this tightly controlled
city-state. Artistic decisions are policed by arts administrators
themselves. While Petito, a Brooklyn-born director who plans to
return to the United States this year, dares test the government's
boundaries, most older Singaporean arts administrators tread more
gingerly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual curators have to deal with the artists,'' said Liu,
who recalled a recent incident at a pan-Asian contemporary art
exhibition. ``One artist was asked not to submit a work which we
felt was disrespectful of our political leaders,'' he said. ``The
development of culture cannot exist separately from what we are, a
small country vulnerable to destabilization.''
</P>
<P>
   The Singapore Dance Theater does not submit works for licensing.
``We have blanket approval,'' said Ng Siew Eng, the company's
general manager. ``We're mindful of being a national dance company,
that our works should be appropriate for children and people of all
ages and levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Goh Soo Khim, the troupe's artistic director (no relation to the
arts festival's organizer), recently told a young choreographer to
modify a ballet scheduled to have its premiere at one of its
outdoor performances, which usually attract thousands of
spectators, many of them families with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about sexual identity, so there was cross-dressing,
then dancers would undress to reveal their true sex,'' explained
Andrea Pell, the company's assistant ballet mistress, who came from
the Atlanta Ballet. ``Ms. Goh thought it went too far, so she asked
him to tone it down. And he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Many society-bending works do, however, reach the public. At the
festival, the Famous Door Theater from Chicago performed
``Hellcab,'' larded with four-letter expletives, sex between
unmarried partners, drug addicts, gangsters and out-of-control
aggression, behavior frowned upon, at the very least. Drug
possession carries the death penalty, but there was no R(A) rating
for ``Hellcab.'' Merely an innocuous, small-print warning about
strong language.
</P>
<P>
   The two festival entries that carried the R(A) rating played to
attentive, appreciative audiences. ``The Plastic Woman,'' a Thai
theater piece, featured an androgynous actor in flesh-colored
tights and baby-blue high heels.
</P>
<P>
   The main prop was a life-size doll's head with flowing hair. The
plastic doll, which symbolized women in male-dominated cultures
like Singapore's, was alternately beaten, caressed, sexually
assaulted, praised, insulted and abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Even to a Western sensibility the work was tough stuff. But
nothing compared with the second R(A)-rated work by Dairakudakan, a
Japanese dance group, which performed ``Ryuba,'' an abstract
two-hour performance created by Akaji Maro, the troupe's founder.
``Very dark and grotesque,'' Ms. Goh, the festival's organizer,
observed, explaining the rating.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ryuba'' nearly nude dancers moved to electronic music
layered with terrifying sound effects _ bombs falling, machine-gun
fire, human screams _ with the bass turned up so that it vibrated
the theater seats. The set consisted of panels strung with splayed
skins (perhaps human, perhaps animal), suggestive of primitive
mankind.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One segment depicted the walking wounded: dancers wore crimson
bikinis and held bloodied rags in their mouths; jaws were agape,
lips twisted in fear, agony, pain, horror or silent cries.
``Ryuba'' was profoundly gut-wrenching, riveting in its depiction
of human emotions. ``A cry from the soul,'' said Ms. Khor, a dance
critic before joining the tourism board. ``This is totally Asian;
why would we ban this? It touches our common humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Such works are far from the feel-good, Disneyesque entertainment
Singaporeans were accustomed to when theater and film were
rigorously censored. Nevertheless, life is still carefully ordered
and behavior prescribed. Spraying graffiti and chewing gum, for
example, carry stiff penalties. The image of an American who was
caned in 1994 for spray-painting cars has not faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Singapore has gone through three cycles of development,'' said
Liu, the arts council chairman, explaining the history of the
nation, established in 1965 from a British colony. ``Consolidation
as a nation, membership among the upper leagues of nations in
providing housing and health care services and, since the mid-'90s,
recognition that to have a quality work force, we need a more
creative approach to cultural activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``consolidation'' to which he refers was imposed by the
government, a stern work-and-behavior ethic often unacceptable in
the West, but to which most Singaporeans credit their disciplined
society and the resulting ebullient economy. Nonadherence to those
standards brought swift punishment, leading to the local joke that
Singapore is a ``fine'' country, referring to its monetary
penalties for a variety of frowned-upon social behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In the performing arts this societal rigor enhances the artistic
result. ``Discipline is very good,'' Ms. Pell said about her
dancers. Henry Ong, a Singaporean playwright based in Los Angeles,
noted, ``Production values are wonderful.'' He traveled here on
government money to oversee Singapore Rep's festival production of
his play ``Fabric.'' Ong left Singapore in 1977 for the University
of Iowa, to pursue a journalism career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been such a tremendous evolution in the appreciation
and support of the arts. When I left there was no arts scene,'' Ong
recalled. ``I don't get the sense of actors here feeling
censorship,'' he said of his mix of American and Singaporean
actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theater started when we did, in 1993,'' Petito explained.
Singapore Rep is moving into a restored former warehouse on the
Singapore River, thanks to rent subsidies from the arts council,
which houses arts organizations and artists' space in restored
landmark buildings. The Singapore Dance Theater and Theaterworks
share an airy building in the greenery of Fort Canning Park,
overlooking the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterloo arts complex, just northeast of the new museums in
the heart of the government center, includes studios, art galleries
and a cafe. The new museums are jewel boxes set in renovated
colonial buildings redolent of Colonial Britain _ white stucco,
mahogany-hued woods, languid palms, whirring fans, spacious
courtyards. The council houses 53 arts groups and 25 artists, in
addition to the museums.
</P>
<P>
   Some 99 percent of government money for the arts flows from the
National Arts Council and the National Heritage Board, formed in
1993 to oversee the museums. Together they spent $36 million in
1998 on the arts, compared with $20 million in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The number of art exhibitions doubled from 1994 to 1998, from
200 to 400, while the number of performances increased 15 percent.
The figure does not include free performances, given frequently by
the Singapore Symphony Orchestra, the Singapore Dance Theater and
most of the eight resident theater groups.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the increasing demand for performing and visual artists
and all the supporting activities of scholarship and stagecraft,
the government plans a new Institute of the Arts and to upgrade the
existing colleges, LaSalle and Nanyang. Again, arts for business'
sake, in this case employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more Singaporeans have qualifications,'' said Dr.
Kenson Kwok, the director of the new Asian Civilizations Museum,
which will expand further into a 135,000-square-foot space. ``Five
years ago we would have had trouble with staffing. Now, people are
studying subjects not conventionally useful to making money.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer docents give tours of the national museums. Kwok, an
art historian, said:``Five years ago, they were all expatriates.
But in the last three years many locals have begun to volunteer.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Asian nations, Singaporeans have a melange of
backgrounds, 78 percent Chinese from various regions, 14 percent
from the Malay Peninsula, 7 percent Indian and 1 percent
miscellaneous, in a population of 3.78 million. Four official
languages are spoken, although English is mandatory in school.
Travel for educational and cultural purposes is widely encouraged.
``We send scholars all over the world for doctorates,'' Liu said.
``We welcome foreigners here, to have cross-fertilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Singapore looks to the West, not to its neighbors, as the model
for cultural development. ``They've decided that they made their
money,'' Petito said. ``Now they feel they want world-class arts
organizations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
