<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEMINGWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: HEMINGWAY AND THE DRAMA OF THE WRITER'S SELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About the time T.S. Eliot was advancing the idea that an
artist's progress is a ``continual extinction of personality,''
another American, 11 years Eliot's junior and just out of high
school, was putting in a brief apprenticeship at The Kansas City
Star and preparing to head off to the war in Europe. He _ Ernest
Hemingway, that is _ reached the Italian front in June 1918 and was
badly wounded by early July, narrowly avoiding a more complete
extinction of personality than even Eliot seemed to require.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hemingway, too, the writer's personality was something
of a crux. If he had not disliked Eliot so much, he might even have
agreed with Eliot's limpid statement of the problem. Poetry, Eliot
concluded, is an escape from emotions, from personality. ``But, of
course,'' Eliot famously added, ``only those who have personality
and emotions know what it means to want to escape from these
things.'' This could have served as an epigraph, with Gertrude
Stein and Ecclesiastes, to Hemingway's first novel, ``The Sun Also
Rises,'' which is the story of people who have personalities and
emotions but do not want them.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 100 years today since Hemingway was born, and,
looking back, it is plain to see that he, more than any other
American in the past century, has changed our sense of what it
means to be a writer, if not necessarily to write. The very posture
with which young writers sit before blank computer screens, instead
of blank sheets of typing paper, is borrowed from Hemingway or from
those who have since refracted Hemingway. Whether he intended to or
not, Hemingway dramatized the gulf between what his personality
exacted from him _ the outer career of the man on safari, at war,
in the bull ring _ and what his prose exacted. Writing might not
have been action, but it was conflict. That drama has given comfort
to many who wished to write and found they could not.
</P>
<P>
   But Hemingway _ it is still necessary to say it _ could write.
And, as his literary executors have proved with posthumous
publications of steadily decreasing merit, he could also edit. The
writer in him may have struggled as he grew older, but the editor
never did. The silence in his early work, his best work, is brutal,
as brutal as the silence into which he lapsed just before killing
himself nearly 40 years ago. It was the asperity of his prose, as
much as its emotional distance, that made him modern.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway the man was never finished, and neither was the body
of his work. But his style, as a man and writer, was settled early
on, and so was his fame, which came to him while still very young.
In a sense, Hemingway tried always to be bigger than his
reputation, to outman his masculine self. This has made it harder
than it should be to sense the freshness, the intuition of his
finest work, the qualities that still give it life. It was a career
of internal conflict, and death has resolved nothing. Hemingway
will wrestle with himself, man and writer, for as long as the
language lives. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
