<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-20 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7779 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BRETT-HALL-TEX     07-20 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 '' Brett said. ``Obviously it's something, when you start playing,
it's a dream that someday you'll make it, but you really don't
think that dream will come true.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 21 years, American League pitchers tried in vain to find a
weakness in Brett. Finally, six seasons after his retirement, one
is revealed. Brett is too modest.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it can give a modern-day player pause to realize that
he is about to join the likes of Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Hank Aaron
and Willie Mays.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt that Brett deserves a place in the Hall,
if not a separate wing.
</P>
<P>
   Brett, who spent his entire career playing for the Kansas City
Royals, finished with 3,154 hits, 13th all-time. He had 665
doubles, fifth in the history of the game. He hit .305 for his
career, and had 11 seasons of better than .300. He hit 20 or more
homers in eight seasons, including 30 in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He flirted with .400 for most of the 1980 season before
finishing at .390. It was the highest since Ted Williams batted
.406 in 1941 and has been topped just once since, by Tony Gwynn's
.394 average in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was the best hitter I ever played with,'' said former
Rangers catcher Jim Sundberg, who spent two of his 16 seasons as
Brett's teammate in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't think there was a lot of natural ability. He worked
pretty hard. But he didn't see himself as clear as it really was.
He had a great swing.''
No one-hit wonder Ah, yes, the swing that launched a thousand
accolades.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Brett could roll out of bed on Christmas morning and
hit a line drive,'' said John Schuerholz, former Royals and current
Braves general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Brett could get good wood on an aspirin,'' former
Royals manager Jim Frey said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody said that about Brett during his three seasons in the
minors after the Royals drafted him _ as a shortstop _ in the
second round in 1971. He wasn't a slouch, hitting .291, .274 and
then .284 at Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   But when he made it to the majors, he adopted the distinctive
style of batting guru Charlie Lau, hitting off his front foot with
the high, one-handed follow through.
</P>
<P>
   Brett said he expects to tear up when talking about Lau during
his induction speech, and with good reason. The two men were close,
and Brett credits Lau for turning him into a great hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Under Lau's tutelage, Brett hit over .300 for the first time as
a pro in 1975. He then proceeded to do it as regularly as Nolan
Ryan won strikeout crowns. Brett batted over .300 in nine of the
next 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Brett won batting crowns in 1976, with a .333 average, and with
the .390 average in 1980. He ``slumped'' in the last half of the
1980s, although most players would take his averages of .290, .290,
.306 and .282.
</P>
<P>
   He rebounded with a league-leading .329 in 1990, becoming the
first player to win batting titles in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the best player right there,'' Yount said. ``To me, he
was the best player.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a knack for driving in runs. Juan Gonzalez has made
knocking in more runs than games played almost routine, but no one
had done it since Joe DiMaggio in 1948 when Brett drove in 118 in
117 games in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Brett finished with 1,595 runs batted in, tied for 22nd with
Mike Schmidt, but Brett didn't have the raw power of his fellow
Hall of Fame third baseman. Brett hit his share of balls over the
fence, but his strength was line drives that found gaps.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Brett's 212 hits included 42 doubles, 20 triples and 23
homers. Only four other players had put together 20-20-20 seasons
before that.
</P>
<P>
   The individual numbers _ which include three seasons of leading
the league in hits and triples, something only Ty Cobb accomplished
before or since _ are remarkable. They are why Brett was elected
with 98.19 percent of the vote, the fourth highest percentage ever
behind Tom Seaver (98.84), fellow '99 inductee Ryan (98.79) and
Cobb (98.23).
Mr. Postseason However, Brett was first and foremost a team player.
His grandest memory isn't of the .390 season, or the 1980 American
League Most Valuable Player award. It's of winning the World Series
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standing on the mound and hugging Bret Saberhagen after an
11-0 defeat of the St. Louis Cardinals to win our first world
championship ... I can wear this ring proudly and say I was a world
champion,'' he said. ``It's the one thing I shared with 24 guys,
from April to October, in the grind of the season every day. That
was an extraordinary bunch of guys. It wasn't one of the better
teams I played on, but it was one of the closest-knit.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett was the hero of the '85 postseason, batting .348 with
three homers in the American League Championship Series against the
Toronto Blue Jays and .373 in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   That was nothing new, though. The Royals won the AL West six
times during Brett's career, and he excelled in the playoffs almost
every time. He holds ALCS records for highest slugging percentage
(.728), triples (4), home runs (9), extra-base hits (18), and total
bases (75).
</P>
<P>
   ``He had this knack of focusing when the pressure was on,''
former teammate Jamie Quirk told the ``Kansas City Star''. ``He had
this amazing concentration. The rest of us, we have a thousand
things going on in our mind. We think about the situation or the
pressure, we think about our swing or we guess what pitch is coming
or whatever. George just saw the ball. That was it. Everything else
was gone. That's what made him great, I think. The rest of us saw
shadows. George saw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest postseason hit came in 1980, in the ALCS against the
New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had beaten the Royals the previous three years,
despite averages of .400, .300 and .389 by Brett. He hit just .273
with three hits in '80, but the final hit was a three-run homer off
closer Goose Gossage that put Kansas City into the World Series for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1980, finally winning, for us it was like winning the World
Series,'' Brett said.
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't come until five years later; the Royals lost to
the Philadelphia Phillies in '80.
</P>
<P>
   In between World Series appearances, Brett had his most infamous
moment, the ``Pine Tar'' game.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a home run in a regular-season game against the Yankees,
but New York manager Billy Martin protested that the pine tar on
the bat extended too far up the barrel. The umpires agreed, and the
homer was taken away.
</P>
<P>
   The lasting image is of Brett charging toward the ump, a crazed
look on his face, seemingly intent on doing bodily harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time it wasn't funny,'' said Brett, who later had the
home run restored when the league office ruled that Martin should
have protested before Brett used the bat. ``But now my oldest son,
Jackson, says, `Dad, let's put in that tape where you go berserk.'
So we fast-forward to that point in the tape and I have to explain
to him that's not the type of behavior I expect from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time Brett and his son watch the tape, perhaps they
should fast-forward to the spot where Brett hits the home run and
stop there.
</P>
<P>
   It was that swing, that churned out line drive after line drive,
that got Brett into the Hall of Fame. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
