<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BENCH BETTERING DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ There's a reason the Los Angeles Dodgers are
winning, and it extends beyond the starting pitching and the
regulars in the field. It's the bench brigade _ Craig Counsell,
Trenidad Hubbard and Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson has waited since opening day to
have an able-bodied bench, and for the past month he's had it,
though it's taken time for the roles to become visible.
</P>
<P>
   The bench is the fire of this club, bringing versatility and, in
the case of Hollandsworth and Counsell, left-handed bats. And it
especially helps that they can hit at the top of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier in the season when Eric Young played hurt, now
Johnson can put Counsell at second and bat him leadoff when Young
is ailing, which he was Tuesday with a still-sore right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have won eight of 10, and during that spurt
Hollandsworth (10 for 25), Hubbard (7 for 14) and Counsell (6 for
19) have combined to go 23 for 58 (.397) and score 19 runs. ``I've
got a backup for the first and second hole,'' Johnson said.
``That's what I've been trying to get to, to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' No. 2 spot in the order has been a black hole.
Second hitters entered the day batting .234 with a .293 on-base
percentage despite the second spot producing a .368 batting average
and a .442 on-base mark during the hot spell.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst is Counsell, usually a defensive replacement for
Young. However, the Dodgers have won five of the six games he's
started, and in those games he's hitting .296 and has scored seven
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like Wally Backman,'' Johnson said in reference to his
days managing the Mets. ``He's a foxhole guy. He would battle his
(butt) off and get his uniform dirty. You know if they were in a
foxhole, they wouldn't be sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Opening de ja vu: When Kevin Brown signed as a free agent in
December, the immediate talk was of a super showdown with Arizona
lefty Randy Johnson on opening day. It never materialized into the
pitcher's duel everyone thought it would be, but the two
high-profile free agents of last winter will meet again Sunday in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Johnson both pitched Tuesday and will do so again in
the finale of a three-game series at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   When they met opening day, neither was around by the time Raul
Mondesi hit a two-run homer in the 11th to win it for the Dodgers.
Brown allowed five runs in 52/3 innings. Randy Johnson allowed two
runs in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Searching for hope: The Dodgers are in their best stretch of
the season, but they remain in fourth place and were 7{ games back
of San Francisco before the Giants played Texas.
</P>
<P>
   However, this could be the best time for the Dodgers to make a
move. The Giants, who are 1-4 since the All-Star break,
traditionally have problems coming off the three-day hiatus. Last
season they went 3-12 after the break. In 1997, they were 6-11, in
1996 they were 6-10 and in 1995 they were 6-12.
</P>
<P>
   __ Offseason positioning: Seven weeks of spring training and 92
games of the regular season is enough to show Johnson what needs to
be done in the free-agent market or with trades after the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are playing well now, but the delicate balance on
the club could be drastically altered if an injury occurs, since
they lack insurance at the minor-league level.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, our job in the offseason is to be set up so we're a
little more flexible in the system, so when there's injuries,
there's insurance in the system,'' Johnson said. ``Then we have
options.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
