<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CLEMENS IS LOOKING FOR HIS KEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First came a bit on morning television with Regis and
Kathy, and then came the key to New York, New York. At City Hall on
Tuesday, it occurred to an appreciative David Cone that maybe this
glad-handing had all gone a bit too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was overwhelming to hear the mayor announce that July 20 is
David Cone Day,'' Mr. Perfect said. ``I was thinking, `There's got
to be something else more important going on in New York.'''
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, there was. Roger Clemens was pitching on
Tuesday night, searching again for his old, breathless form to
eradicate his more recent unconfident air.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have predicted that Clemens, on July 20, David Cone
Day, would need to silence the Montreal Expos' bats to keep those
heartless Yankee Stadium fans from booing him off the mound? With
the possible exception of Dave Stewart, no one.
</P>
<P>
   It was Stewart, the Toronto assistant general manager and
one-time Clemens tormentor, who had wondered out loud what Clemens
stood to gain by demanding a trade to a team that had in the
previous season won 125 games without him. ``He's great, a Hall of
Famer, but how much more can he add to the Yankees?'' Stewart said,
in Dunedin, Fla., the day David Wells showed up a bloated,
bummed-out Blue Jay.
</P>
<P>
   The dime-store psychology was that Clemens wanted to hop aboard
the gravy train, take the easy ride to his first championship ring.
The less cynical perspective, the one that the Yankees are selling
as Clemens struggles to find himself, is that he wanted into New
York so that he could step onto the sport's grandest stage, and
continue to be the dominant pitcher of his time. And he will be
again, before it's over.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees say the radar gun doesn't lie. ``His fastball is
still big-time, to me,'' Joe Torre said before Clemens went out to
test it against the Expos. So Torre said the explanation for the
4.98 ERA, for the inability to beat the Mets, is in the mechanics,
in the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really wanted to come into Yankee Stadium and make his
mark,'' Cone said. ``It's bothering him that he hasn't done better,
really bothering him. But it's very difficult to come to New York
your first year.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially this year. The Yankees sprinted for all of 1998, took
everything from a regular season they could possibly take. Clemens
has brought his trademark game-day passion to a Yankee team that
appears to be driving monotonously toward the postseason, on cruise
control.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Torre and Cone talk about the Yankees' one
significant addition to this most decorated team, you get the idea
that Clemens has pressured himself to dance as fast as he can and
in the process has forgotten which foot comes first. The result is
that he's looked out of step in a room full of teammates who are
engaged in a waltz.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is 36, a certain Hall of Famer, and yet he goes to the
mound every fifth day, trying to convince people that those five Cy
Young awards on the resume were not fudged. This is apparently no
career point of immunity to the misplacement of know-how, or to the
loss of belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a humbling game made up of negative statistics,'' the
manager said. ``The thing is, the bar is set so high for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone added: ``He's always been a hyper guy. He's legendary for
his intensity, almost unapproachable on game day. You can tell how
much he wants to do well, how much he wants to be part of this
whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone couldn't help notice how Clemens planted himself on the top
step of the dugout on Sunday, and stayed there, as if not to jinx
the perfect game, right until the 27th out. How he was one of the
first Yankees out onto the field to reach, to lift him up by the
sleeve. Cone, also 36, understands how the great aging pitcher
straddles the line between where he has long been and where he must
inevitably go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You constantly have to prove yourself,'' Cone said. ``Each
start, each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone shocked everyone, including himself, by winning 20 last
year along the way to Yankee championship No. 24. Clemens won 20 in
Toronto, but those victories don't mean anything in New York. Wells
also pitches now to an ERA of almost five in Toronto, but Yankee
fans' only basis for comparison is 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the big games, the postseason, are going to define
his first year as a Yankee, should we make it,'' Cone said of
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will make it, one way or another. Clemens has, in
effect, a whole season to get the mind and body working together,
to find the key that unlocks 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
