<HEADLINE>
FIVE AMERICAN LEAGUE UMPIRES DON'T WANT TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The blue wall of solidarity that the umpire union
created a week ago is not so solid anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Five American League umpires have asked the league to rescind
the resignations they submitted last week, baseball officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig and the leagues declined to comment on
the development that threatened to expand in coming days as umpires
reconsidered the unexpected step they took last Wednesday when they
signed letters saying they were resigning effective Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips, the head of the Major League Umpires
Association, did not return telephone calls seeking comment. But
when Bruce Froemming, an N.L. umpire and a member of the union's
board of directors, was asked whether the reversal by some umpires
was bad for the union's position, he said, ``Nothing is good when
you have people going in different directions.''
</P>
<P>
   The five A.L. umpires who changed their minds were identified as
Larry Barnett, Davey Phillips, Rocky Roe, Dale Scott and Jim Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Roe, in his 19th year as an A.L. umpire, said he rescinded his
resignation after consulting a lawyer friend in Detroit. ``After
the smoke cleared, you have the reality you've resigned,'' Roe said
before working a game in Toronto. ``I was told by my good personal
friend that it wasn't a good move.''
</P>
<P>
   Roe, 48 years old, acknowledged that others had rescinded their
resignations but wouldn't talk about them. ``Right now I'm kind of
hot property,'' he said. ``I'm not the only guy who's rescinded,
but I don't want to be the poster boy, so to speak. There are a lot
of issues and people who are unhappy with the stance.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant the union position in staging the mass resignation.
Roe, however, declined to say why he joined the move initially. Roe
was one of 14 umpires who voted against Richie Phillips at a union
meeting last February when Phillips received a five-year contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett and Davey Phillips, in their 31st and 30th years,
respectively, are the two most senior A.L. umpires. Barnett, 54,
has accepted a buyout and is retiring at the end of the season.
Phillips, 55, hasn't worked in a month because of a back injury.
Both he and Barnett are crew chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, 39, is in his 14th year, and Joyce, 43, is in his 11th
year.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has not announced a position on the
resignations and gave no indication on how the umpires' request to
rescind their resignations would be viewed. Officials plan to let
the evolving situation play out and see what other umpires do.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires initiated their mass resignation at a meeting in
Philadelphia last Wednesday. Richie Phillips said the umpires
initially wanted to strike, but their labor contract with the
leagues prohibits that action.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips said that all 57 umpires at the meeting signed
letters of resignation and that the next day he faxed 63 letters to
the league offices. One baseball official said 54 letters were
received.
</P>
<P>
   Nine union members did not attend the meeting and did not submit
resignations. The remaining two members of the 68-man umpiring
crew, Derryl Cousins and John Shulock, are not union members; they
were replacement umpires during the 1979 umpires strike.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball official said two N.L. umpires, Greg Bonin and Mark
Hirschbeck, were among the umpires who did not submit resignations,
leaving 34 N.L. umpires who did. With the five defections, the A.L.
resignation contingent dropped to 15 of the league's 32 umpires.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If umpires seek a second opinion, as Roe did with his friend in
Detroit, they may reconsider a contention that Richie Phillips was
said to have made at their Philadelphia meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials were told that Richie Phillips told the
umpires that baseball had a list of 20 umpires who had been singled
out for dismissal after the season. But officials, speaking on the
condition of anonymity, denied that any such list exists.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has had a group of six former minor league
umpires evaluating minor league umpires to determine the best 25
who will be assigned to work in the Arizona Fall League later this
year. Baseball is also seeking umpires to replace three or four who
are retiring from the American League staff and for a possible
seven new positions in the majors next season.
</P>
<P>
   With the commissioner's office planning to centralize umpires in
that office beginning next season, officials are thinking of using
five-man crews instead of the current four-man crews. Each umpire
in a crew would have a week off every fifth week.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips, however, has suspected that minor league
umpires are being evaluated to find replacements for umpires who
will be fired. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
