<HEADLINE>
CSUN PICKED TO FINISH NEXT TO LAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ Before the vote they said all the right things
about Cal State Northridge. But when the Big Sky Conference
football coaches' poll was released Tuesday afternoon, it was
obvious what the coaches said and what they really felt were two
different things.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were picked to finish eighth in the nine-team
conference, one day after several coaches said they thought CSUN
would have been a team picked among the top three or four.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go by what's on a piece of paper,'' said Terrance
Johnson, the team's administrator-in-charge since CSUN head coach
Ron Ponciano was fired last Friday. ``We know what our guys are
capable of doing. The events that have taken place, that's the way
(the coaches) see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll placed Montana first and Northern Arizona second. CSUN
returns 14 starters from a team that went 7-4 last year, 5-3 in the
Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Washington, which returns 19 starters, was picked to
finish third by the coaches. The rest of the order: Portland State,
Montana State, Sacramento State, Weber State, CSUN and Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
   The media poll was similar to the coaches'. The order: Montana,
Northern Arizona, Eastern Washington, Montana State, Portland
State, Sacramento State, CSUN, Weber State and Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
   __ He's interested: Johnson, who has been on staff for two
years, said he considers himself a candidate to become the interim
head coach for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   He described Ponciano's firing as ``devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at (Ponciano) as my mentor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ The new rules: Doug Toole, the Big Sky's first-year
coordinator of football officials, went over rule changes for the
upcoming season Monday _ and two seem to have CSUN in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Toole said a team will be charged a full timeout if a player
doesn't have his jersey tucked in or is wearing a visible bandana
on the field. That doesn't mean a player can't wear a bandana, but
if he takes his helmet off on the field with it showing, the team
would be charged.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN senior defensive back Chazz Moore often wore his uniform
top out last season. Many Matadors wore bandanas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990720.0428 </DOCNO>
