<SLUG> BC-ALLIED-BROWNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT APPROVES TRASH HAULERS' MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department gave its approval Tuesday to one of the
largest mergers in the trash-hauling business on the condition that
the combining companies, Allied Waste Industries and
Browning-Ferris Industries, sell operations in 18 metropolitan
areas in 13 states, from Massachusetts to California.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will create a trash-hauling giant with revenues of
about $6.4 billion, second only to the industry leader, Waste
Management Inc., which had 1998 revenues of $12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When the merger, a leveraged takeover for $7.3 billion in cash,
was announced in early March, analysts raised concerns about
whether Allied Waste would be able to complete the financing and
whether the Justice Department would object.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the agreement with Allied on selling operations in
Chicago, Boston, Atlanta, Dallas, Detroit, Oakland, Calif., and
other cities, Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general in charge
of the Justice Department's antitrust division, said, ``Without
these divestitures, consumers in these 18 areas would have lost a
significant competitive alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied does business in about 28 states, Browning-Ferris in
about 40, the Justice Department said. The companies collect
garbage from residential and commercial customers, competing
directly in many places.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Van Weelden, the chief executive of Allied, said in a
statement, ``We are pleased'' to have reached agreement with the
Justice Department. Making clear that he, like the analysts, had
anticipated a divestiture, Van Weelden added that the sale of
operations with revenues of about $197 million, was ``well within
our expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Varoli, an analyst for Merger Insight and one of those who
had suggested that financing the deal might be difficult, said that
according to Allied documents, the company expected to borrow $5
billion from banks and raise $3 billion by issuing bonds and
preferred stock. The company said in its statement Tuesday that it
expected to close the deal on July 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Ms. Varoli said, ``they feel they will be able to
get the financing they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the operations that are to be sold, the Justice Department
said, are landfills and incinerators, transfer stations where
garbage is dumped and then taken elsewhere, trucks, containers and
garages.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said the sale of the facilities ``could
well surpass'' the $500 million that Waste Management received when
it was forced to make a divestiture after its purchase of USA Waste
in 1998. Previously that had been the largest divestiture in the
industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
