<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-COMMENTARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PILOT'S OPINION ON WHAT MIGHT HAVE HAPPENED ON KENNEDY FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LEE J. GUITTAR  
 SPECIAL TO THE SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. _ Moments after early reports of John F.
Kennedy Jr.'s missing single-engine airplane hit the television
airwaves, I began getting telephone calls from friends, relatives
and former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   They all knew that, for seven years, I had commuted summer
weekends from New York City to Martha's Vineyard, Mass., piloting a
single-engine airplane. They wanted my take on what might have
happened to Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   My route on those flights was from Teterboro, N.J., to the
Vineyard, under Visual Flight Rules (VFR) as JFK Jr., did Friday
night, I flew essentially the same route, hugging the Connecticut
and Rhode Island coastlines and keeping the over-water segment to
the Martha's Vineyard Airport as short as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, my flight instructor on the Vineyard was Arthur
Marx, who was one of JFK Jr.'s, flight instructors. Marx is a
splendid instructor; the best I ever had. There is every reason to
believe then that JFK Jr., was a well-coached pilot.
</P>
<P>
   I told my callers that even though I have an Instrument Flight
Rating (IFR), (a difficult rating for a private pilot to acquire,
demanding completion of a rigorous written exam and in-flight
performance test), I have never flown the route at night. My reason
is simple: I don't consider it the safest thing to fly a
single-engine airplane when I cannot see the surface beneath me.
</P>
<P>
   I fly a Cessna-172, a plane that is simpler and slower than JFK
Jr.'s Saratoga. I know that the odds of losing an engine, or
encountering some other emergency that would call for an immediate
landing, are slim. Yet, if an emergency occurs in daylight, I also
know that with my airplane's ``stall'' speed of about 45 miles per
hour, I should be able to find some level ground that would give me
an excellent chance to walk away from a forced landing.
</P>
<P>
   After dark, all I could do would be to trim the plane for its
best glide speed and hope that it would find a reasonably
appropriate site. I just don't like the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of my fellow pilots would conclude that I am much too
conservative. Some say that flying at night is the best because the
ground lights are beautiful and the air is generally smoother. So,
when JFK Jr., elected to make the trip to the Vineyard, he was not
doing anything that most pilots would consider all that risky.
</P>
<P>
   I am puzzled why he did not ask an FAA flight controller for
``flight following,'' a voluntary program under which the
controller assigns the airplane a specific radar ``squawk,'' tracks
the airplane, and keeps the pilot informed of nearby traffic. It is
a practice most pilots consider helpful even in daylight.
</P>
<P>
   There is an on-going debate about whether an instrument rating
should be required for every pilot who flies at night, and I think
it makes a lot of sense. And, if weather conditions deteriorate, as
the visibility seems to have done Friday night, the rated pilot can
easily contact an FAA flight controller, file an IFR flight plan
from the air, and ask for vectors to the airport. It seems like
good insurance to me.
</P>
<P>
   Most of my callers wanted me to speculate on what I thought may
have happened inside Kennedy's airplane that would cause it to go
down. I said we don't know and probably never will. But I told them
that when I heard the news that FAA radar had the plane descending
at 4,700 feet per minute, I knew the Saratoga was in a steep dive,
and probably accelerating as it passed through the 1,100-foot
level, at which FAA's radar had last contact.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it was in a spin, corkscrewing toward the sea, it
is doubtful JFK Jr., had enough altitude to pull out of the dive.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some speculation that JFK Jr., was attempting to
turn the plane, and having lost his visual horizon in the haze and
darkness, overbanked the plane and put it into a spin. That's a
possibility, but since he was still over water some 15 miles from
the airport, there was little need for much maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   From that distance out, he should have been calling the airport
tower to report his position and that he was ``inbound'' and had
listened to the Martha's Vineyard automated weather report. The
tower would then provide instructions (``Left downwind, Runway
24,'' for example), and the pilot would require only a gentle turn
to put himself on course to enter the landing pattern.
</P>
<P>
   A better guess, I think, is that when he found himself in the
haze and darkness, he became disoriented. His body sent him
erroneous signals. He responded to those signals with incorrect
control inputs, making the situation worse. Understandably, he
probably froze at the controls.
</P>
<P>
   My callers had trouble with that scenario. How, they asked,
could anyone not know whether he was going up or down? Or right or
left?
</P>
<P>
   I told them that the technical explanation had to do with canals
in the inner ear that I couldn't explain in great detail. I
explained that in my early instrument training, I could remember
many instances when I thought the plane was straight-and-level,
only to have my instructor thump his finger on the altitude
indicator, or artificial horizon, which showed me to be flying a
20-degree bank. Or, when I might fixate on nailing a directional
heading, I had to be reminded that I was unintentionally descending
at 700 to 800 feet a minute!
</P>
<P>
   One caller asked, ``I can understand some disorientation, but if
you're going down at 4,700-feet-a-minute, how can you not know
you're going down?'' My guess is that they knew they were going
down, but the pilot's mind was providing little constructive input
to help out.
</P>
<P>
   My take on the tragedy is this. It was a horrible accident. It
was not a death-defying decision to make the flight. It was a
mistake not to request ``flight following'' from the FAA. We may
find it was equipment failure, but I doubt it. Unless the wings
fell off the Saratoga, there's little to cause it to descend at
4,700-feet-a-minute.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, JFK Jr. inadvertently got into an unusual situation
beyond his experience and piloting skills. It is something every
pilot has to be wary of every time he or she flies an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the cautions we constantly emphasize to ourselves
sometimes are overcome by the extra jolt of confidence we all seem
to carry with us.
</P>
<P>
   Editor's note: Lee J. Guittar retired last year as editor and
publisher of the San Francisco Examiner. He has a private pilot
license for single and multiengine aircraft, and is instrument
rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
