<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE SLIP ADDS TO ANGELS SLIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was symbolic of the Anaheim Angels' season,
a season that is quickly slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   Angels reliever Mark Petkovsek had the ball slip out of his hand
on a fake pickoff attempt, allowing Carlos Baerga to score in the
ninth inning of the Padres' 2-1 victory before 35,247 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' fifth loss in a row and their sixth in seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek, who has been one of the Angels' best pitchers this
season, was set to face Quilvio Veras with runners on first and
third and one out in the ninth of a 1-1 game.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek was attempting the fake-to-third, throw-to-first
pickoff move. But when he faked to third, the ball came out of his
hand and bounced toward the Angels' on-deck circle on the
third-base side.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Jeff Huson scrambled to retrieve the ball and
threw home, but it was too late to get Baerga and prevent the
Padres from completing the three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``After nine innings like that and then a play like that decides
the game, it leaves you shaking your head,'' Petkovsek (9-3) said.
``It was more arm action than sweat (that caused the ball to slip
out). A couple of guys have tried the move this year and it's
worked. I was trying to steal an out, but it backfired.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn, who was on-deck when the play
took place: ``I said to myself, `Did I really see what I just saw?'
I've never seen that before.''
</P>
<P>
   What made the loss even tougher for the Angels was that it
spoiled Chuck Finley's best start in weeks. Finley shut out the
Padres for seven innings before yielding a run in the eighth on
Eric Owens' two-out RBI double. Finley gave up one run and three
hits in 72/3 innings, striking out six and walking five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he wanted that game bad,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said of Finley. ``He always competes great, but he wanted this game
bad and he deserved to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's previous five starts represented the worst stretch of
his career. In those games he allowed 32 earned runs in 22 innings.
But it all came together for him Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Finley said when asked to explain the
turnaround. ``I was just trying to do the same things as in the
last couple starts. It worked out this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference was that Finley had all three of his
pitches _ fastball, curveball, forkball _ working, so he was able
to use all three and keep the hitters off balance all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to use them all right away and not wait until the
second time around in the lineup,'' Finley said. ``And I tried to
mix them up.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance didn't result in a win because of the botched
pickoff attempt and the lifeless offense. But Finley said the team
can't waste time feeling sorry for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to walk out there, throw a quarter in the well
and wish good things,'' he said. ``We've got to do it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start doing it would be on the offensive end.
They've scored nine runs during their five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored their only run when Darin Erstad hit Padres
starter Andy Ashby's first pitch of the game into the right-field
bleachers for his eighth homer of the season. After that, the
Angels got nothing. Ashby (9-4) gave up one run and five hits in
eight innings and Trevor Hoffman (25th save) pitched the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't been able to push across runs,'' Angels
shortstop Gary DiSarcina said. ``Two-out hits, sustaining rallies .
. . we haven't been doing it. You can't come out here in the
American League and score two runs a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
