<SLUG> BC-CLARK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B.C. PREMIER CLARK UNDER PRESSURE FROM MINISTERS TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying it is time for ``a new style of leadership,'' influential
senior Cabinet ministers have launched a drive to force
controversial, confrontational British Columbia Premier Glen Clark
to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Clark told a Vancouver news conference on Tuesday that he
intends to stay on, but two Cabinet ministers have resigned and
influential Attorney General Ujjal Dosanj is expected to quit after
he returns late this week from a trip to Central America.
</P>
<P>
   The public crisis follows a stormy closed-door session last
week, in which provincial legislators of Clark's left-leaning New
Democratic Party challenged the premier's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The premier agreed that his style needed to change in order
for us to be able to govern,'' said an internal memo prepared after
the meeting of the 40-member caucus, which includes the entire
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes he can change to be more inclusive, to listen, to
limit the battles he takes on, to let his ministers lead without
taking over their proper functions, and to offer a real
plan/vision/message for gaining back the public's confidence,'' it
added. ``If he cannot make those changes, he will make the decision
to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   But senior figures in the party want Clark to go _ now. The New
Democrats were supported by just 16 percent of those surveyed in a
recent poll. The poll figures indicate the party is in danger of
being wiped out in the next provincial election.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has plummeted in popularity, both with the public and
fellow politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Royal Canadian Mounted Police officers raided the
premier's Vancouver home, apparently seeking evidence of possible
bribery in a friend's application for a casino license.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for two new hydrofoil ferries, a pet Clark project,
has nearly doubled. The B.C. Ferry Corp. recently disclosed that
its debts total more than $1 billion (Canadian) and substantially
exceed its assets.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was bypassed by U.S. and Canadian government officials,
and by Northwest governors, in the recent negotiation of a new
long-term U.S.-Canada salmon treaty. The premier once offered to
pay the legal fees of British Columbia fishermen who in 1997
blockaded the Alaska ferry ``Malaspina'' for four days in the
harbor at Prince Rupert.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Gov. Gary Locke was one of those put off by Clark's
militance during the salmon treaty negotiations. At one point, the
premier moved to bar U.S. Navy ships from using a torpedo testing
range on the Strait of Georgia, as retaliation against alleged
American overfishing. The Canadian government stopped Clark by
moving to expropriate the testing range from provincial ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with unending scandals and controversies _ and plummeting
poll numbers _ senior New Democrats began to plan several weeks ago
to force Clark to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Dissent has since spiraled. The province's finance minister, Joy
MacPhail, resigned last week. So did Graeme Bowbrick, a legislator
who served as Clark's parliamentary secretary in the B.C.
Legislature. Women's equality minister Susan Hammell tendered her
resignation on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 20 former Cabinet ministers and legislators, all
stalwart New Democrats, sent a letter to Clark predicting disaster
if he leads the party into another election.
</P>
<P>
   Others calling for new leadership include agriculture minister
Corky Evans and environment minister Cathy McGregor, repeatedly
upstaged and preempted by Clark on major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But the key players have been three Cabinet ministers thought to
be in line to succeed Clark.
</P>
<P>
   MacPhail is a former chief economist with the B.C. Labor
Federation, who reportedly was overruled when she tried to limit
the deficit in the latest provincial budget. Dosanj is a prominent
Indo-Canadian lawyer who has repeatedly rebuffed political
interference in the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   The third Cabinet minister is Gordon Wilson, a former opposition
politician who joined the New Democrats only five months ago. He
was hastily appointed finance minister last week after MacPhail
quit.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has reportedly agreed that Clark must go, but argued that
no date should be imposed upon the premier.
</P>
<P>
   Under Canada's parliamentary-style government, the New Democrats
can name a new premier and go on governing if Clark resigns. They
hold 40 seats in the 75-member B.C. Legislature. The party has
until April of 2001 to call a provincial election.
</P>
<P>
   Clark insisted Tuesdsay that he will carry on, and that his
critics are a minority. ``When you're not popular and you've got
these economic challenges, these divisions on direction, these
strains start to show and that's what we're seeing,'' he told a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The premier is reportedly planning to shuffle his Cabinet to
reward those who have stayed loyal.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be too late. ``It's time for a new style of
leadership,'' said the memo out of last week's contentious meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Former B.C. agriculture and tourism minister Bill Barlee put it
more bluntly when asked when Clark should resign. ``Yesterday,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
