<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-JAYS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toronto's sweep deepens Atlanta's slide to 4
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Braves only wished that puff of smoke swirling
high above the turf in the sixth inning at SkyDome on Tuesday night
was announcing their disappearance. No such luck.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke was a remnant of celebratory fireworks after another
Blue Jays grand slam, this one by Darrin Fletcher to spark an 11-6
Toronto win that completed a three-game sweep of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   A Shawn Green grand slam had fueled the Blue Jays'
come-from-behind win Monday night. Fletcher's shot did the same for
the Jays on Tuesday. He broke a 5-5 tie in the sixth inning by
pulling a two-out, two-strike pitch from left-handed reliever Mike
Remlinger into the Braves' bullpen in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger might wish he were still back there, after following
Tom Glavine to the mound and giving him no relief. With the score
tied and runners at first and second, Remlinger recorded one out
before giving up three hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves bid adieu to interleague play, the American League
and Toronto bitterly as their interleague record for the season
fell to 9-9. Their losing streak has grown to four, matching their
longest of the season, going into a two-game series against the
Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   With Odalis Perez, Kevin Millwood and Bruce Chen coming up empty
over the previous three games, the Braves had turned to Glavine for
a little reassurance and a win.
</P>
<P>
   What he and the Braves found was more American League trouble.
The Blue Jays patiently awaited their chances against Glavine and
jumped on him for two runs in the first, two in the fifth, and then
batted around in the sixth for six runs, four on Fletcher's third
career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   With Keith Lockhart batting second in the order and Bret Boone
dropping to seventh, the Braves showed a little offensive life
early, spotting Glavine a 3-0 lead in the first inning on
consecutive hits off Chris Carpenter by Chipper Jones (single),
Brian Jordan (two-run double) and Javy Lopez (RBI double).
</P>
<P>
   But the Blue Jays weren't fazed, coming back with two runs off
Glavine in the bottom of the inning on three hits and a walk. They
got only one run out of a bases-loaded, one-out opportunity but
kept it close for the next four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then, using two-out hits by Tony Batista and Jose Cruz Jr. in
the sixth inning, the Blue Jays cut the lead to 5-4, before tying
it on a Carlos Delgado RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
