<HEADER>
A7795 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-RDP-ART-1STLD     07-20 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY WAS LOST OR DISORIENTED, EXPERTS BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for extensive rewrite starting at 8th graf. Rewritten
material contains much new reporting. Recasts grafs 2-5 to conform
with rewritten material. Adds 2nd name to byline.)  (With KENNEDY-PILOT, KENNEDY-SCENE, KENNEDY-TEXT,
KENNEDY-BESSETTE-TEXT) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN and MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURNE, Mass. _ John F. Kennedy Jr. turned sharply away from
Martha's Vineyard before his plane began plunging toward the sea,
federal investigators said Tuesday, leading several authorities on
aviation to conclude that he had become lost or disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure came on the fourth day of a search for the
wrecked plane and the remains of Kennedy and his wife, Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy, and sister-in-law, Lauren Bessette _ a search
that has generated many questions here and in Washington about the
use of federal resources in what could be a fruitless search. In
part, as a result of the new radar information, investigators
warned Tuesday night that they might never find any large pieces of
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing Tuesday evening, Robert Pearce, who is leading the
investigation for the National Transportation Safety Board, said
radar records are filling in the harrowing details of the last
seven minutes of the flight as Kennedy, 38, and his 33-year-old
wife headed for a family wedding on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce said that Kennedy had been headed straight toward
Martha's Vineyard, about 34 miles out and traveling at 5,600 feet,
when the plane began to descend at about 700 feet a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The descent continued for about five minutes to 2,300 feet,
when the airplane was about 20 miles from the airport,'' Pearce
said. ``The airplane started a turn to the right and climbed back
to 2,600 feet. It remained at that altitude for about one minute on
a southeasterly heading. Thirty seconds into the maneuver, the
airplane started a turn to the right and descended at a rapid rate
of descent. The rate of descent may have been greater than 5,000
feet per minute. The last radar return was about 16 miles from the
airport and the altitude indicated 1,100 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Kennedy was headed away from the airport when
the plunge began. Pearce would not characterize the information
beyond saying that Kennedy had been on the right path before he
began turning. ``Anything from that would not go to Martha's
Vineyard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Barr, the director of the Aviation Safety Program at the
University of Southern California, a leading training center for
accident investigators, said Kennedy apparently lost his way after
making the first turn, then went into a dive as he tried to right
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this getting yourself in a square corner, when you run
out of ideas and experience at the same time,'' said Barr, who was
a fighter pilot during the Vietnam War. ``He would have been
looking straight out at the dark ocean on a nearly moonless night.
He probably looked over his right shoulder for lights, then when he
started to sink, he would have been trying to get the nose back to
the horizon, get the wings level and find where he was, all at the
same time. Even for a good pilot, that could produce a death
spiral.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts offered a similar assessment, while cautioning
that it may never be possible to know what happened in the cockpit.
Warren Morningstar, the director of media relations for the
Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association, said the scenario
``suggests that the pilot was disoriented.'' He said a pilot might
intentionally turn away from his destination to reduce altitude,
but he said Kennedy had been at about the right altitude for his
approach before he began the turns.
</P>
<P>
   The new information is based on an analysis in Washington of
radar data that is being collected from stations along Kennedy's
flight path, including stations in New Jersey, New York,
Connecticut, Rhode Island and Massachusetts. So far all the records
reviewed have been on paper, and Pearce said an even more complete
picture might emerge as specialists delve into computerized records
that are being sent to them.
</P>
<P>
   After four days of searching, investigators said no debris has
been salvaged from the ocean floor; the small pieces that have been
found were floating or washed ashore. Pearce said most are interior
cabin pieces, and the largest piece found so far is a three-foot
section of overhead molding. Asked about the likelihood if finding
sizable pieces of wreckage, Pearce said, ``I'm sure you could draw
a conclusion based on the debris that we've been bringing in, which
is fragmented.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the search itself, several officials said Tuesday that
the effort was the first to retrieve an aircraft other than for
public safety. While salvages of crashed planes, even at sea, are
common, they are almost always paid for by insurance companies or
by families, according to aviation officials and salvors.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, a spokesman acknowledged the unusual nature
of the effort. ``We're taking some reasonable measures beyond what
we might normally do in this instance,'' said Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Transportation Safety Board, which is in charge
of air crash investigations, Lauren Peduzzi, a spokeswoman, said
that the board has in the past paid for salvage when the board had
an extraordinary reason to discover what happened.
</P>
<P>
   But aviation officials were clear in stating that they are not
undertaking this search because they expect to uncover a generic
flaw in Piper Saratogas of the type Kennedy was flying.
</P>
<P>
   In ordinary circumstances the government does nothing to
retrieve such wreckage. The Federal Aviation Administration
provides radar data to help find a wreck, and the Coast Guard will
control marine traffic while private parties pay for salvage.
Airplanes that crash, whether they are operated by private
individuals, corporations or airlines, are almost always salvaged
by the insurance company that covered them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An exception was TWA 800, the Boeing 747 that went down off the
south shore of Long Island three years ago. The airline and its
insurer declined to recover the wreckage, but the National
Transportation Safety Board said the plane had to be raised to
determine the cause of the explosion and to help improve public
safety in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy search is using many of the same ships.
</P>
<P>
   But James O'Dell III, a spokesman for the Coast Guard, said that
this was the first time he knew of that his agency had participated
in the salvage of a private plane.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in finding bodies poses an awkward dilemma as Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and other family members try to plan a
funeral or memorial service. The Kennedy family has not requested
that Kennedy be buried with his parents, at the eternal flame in
Arlington National Cemetery, a White House official said Tuesday
afternoon. ``We don't think they are going to ask,'' the official
added, citing informal contacts with members of the family. Because
Kennedy does not qualify for burial in the military cemetery,
interment there would require a presidential waiver.
</P>
<P>
   As the family waits in seclusion at Hyannis Port, two Navy
ships, two Coast Guard cutters and two research vessels from the
National Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration are being
used in the effort to map the sea off of Martha's Vineyard, using
high-resolution sonar to detect objects with straight edges,
indicating they are manmade. Then 10 divers from the Massachusetts
State Police and 20 from the Navy use those maps to look for
wreckage. But many of the seemingly promising targets turn out to
be things like barrels or fishnets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
