<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND PATAKI PICK ADELPHI PRESIDENT TO HEAD CUNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani have
selected Matthew Goldstein, the president of Adelphi University, as
their choice to be the next chancellor of the City University of
New York, they said in a joint statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With that backing, Goldstein's appointment is considered
virtually certain. The governor and the mayor exert strong
influence over CUNY's board of trustees, most of whom they named to
the board.
</P>
<P>
   As a City College alumnus, Goldstein, 57, would be the first
CUNY chancellor to have graduated from the university.
</P>
<P>
   A mathematical statistician who received his doctorate from the
University of Connecticut, Goldstein earned the respect of CUNY's
trustees in his role as president of Baruch College from 1991 to
1998. By narrowing Baruch's focus somewhat to the liberal arts,
business and public affairs, and by raising more than $50 million
in private donations, he helped make Baruch one of CUNY's most
selective campuses and gave it a growing national reputation among
business schools.
</P>
<P>
   The board is expected to approve Goldstein's appointment on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a first-rate administrator with a proven record of
improving one of the CUNY campuses,'' Ronald Marino, a trustee,
said. ``He has a true dedication to reforming the City University
system and still maintaining access to students.''
</P>
<P>
   The release issued by the governor and the mayor quoted
Goldstein as saying, ``This is a wonderful honor for me to return
to the university that provided me with the tools that launched my
career and opened my eyes to wider worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his long affiliation with CUNY, Goldstein had relished
the challenge of trying to rebuild Adelphi University after the New
York State Board of Regents dismissed most of its trustees for
mismanagement. Colleagues of Goldstein's said that he had been torn
over the decision about leaving Adelphi, which is in Garden City,
N.Y., on Long Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
