<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HASIDIC-DRUG-COURIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASIDIC JEWS SAID TO BE COURIERS IN DRUG SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In their black hats, dark suits and side curls, the
stream of young Hasidic men flying home from Europe seemed unlikely
to raise the suspicions of U.S. Customs officials.
</P>
<P>
   But federal prosecutors say the sober young men were enlisted as
couriers in a huge operation to flood New York with the designer
drug MDMA, popularly called Ecstasy, for resale at high markups to
young people partying their nights away at clubs and ``rave''
dances.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, law-enforcement officials announced the indictment
of seven people suspected of running the operation, which the
officials said brought in more than 1 million MDMA pills into New
York and laundered millions of dollars in subsequent profits. None
of those indicted were couriers, but investigators said they
expected more arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments followed a 21-month investigation by an
organized crime and drug-enforcement task force. Officials said the
Ecstasy-smuggling operation was based in Amsterdam, the
Netherlands, and also operated in Brooklyn and Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the indictments, Loretta E. Lynch, the new U.S.
attorney for the Eastern District of New York, said that Ecstasy
tablets were ``aggressively marketed to young adults and teen-agers
in the New York metropolitan area.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy is a synthetic drug similar to the stimulant
methamphetamine and the hallucinogen mescaline. It causes euphoria,
increased alertness and some psychedelic effects, which has made it
popular among young people.
</P>
<P>
   But Ecstasy can damage parts of the brain that are critical for
thought and memory, according to researchers at Johns Hopkins
University. Experimenting with squirrels, they found that four days
of exposure to the drug caused damage persisting six or seven years
later.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictments, young men, primarily from the
Hasidic communities in the Williamsburg section of Brooklyn and
Monsey were offered a free trip to Europe and about $1,500 in
return for smuggling back some contraband. Some were also offered
$200 for each new courier they recruited. The authorities said that
each courier smuggled as many as 45,000 Ecstasy tablets into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The recruiters chose the couriers, whose exact number was not
given, believing that their religious dress and appearance would
not attract the attention of Customs inspectors. Some couriers were
reportedly told that they would be bringing back diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   But a news release issued by the U.S. attorney on the indictment
said, ``Although there were warning signs along the way that the
couriers were smuggling drugs, they generally closed their eyes to
these facts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
