</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS TO RESURRECT QUICK DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lawmakers negotiating details of the state budget
have agreed to resurrect the Quick Draw video lottery game, and to
postpone the elimination of sales tax on clothing for three months,
legislators and aides to the governor said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures will increase state revenues, bringing in $180
million during the fiscal year. Officials were quick to insist that
with the sales tax, at least, revenue was not a consideration. But
the moves underscored the odd spectacle of lawmakers scouring the
budget for sources of extra cash, at a time when the state has a
surplus of nearly $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gov. George Pataki also warned the Assembly and Senate
that if they went too far in cutting taxes or borrowing for capital
projects, the governor would withdraw his agreement to make sparing
use of his veto pen on the final budget bills.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and the Senate majority
leader, Joseph Bruno, agreed last week to the outlines of a $73
billion spending plan, with the Republican governor pledging not to
veto large portions of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   With that accord in hand, the Legislature began meeting Monday
in conference committees to hammer out the details, with final
passage expected as early as next week. The budget will be 112 days
overdue on Wednesday, the second-latest in state history.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal between the governor and the legislative leaders
said nothing about borrowing and tax cuts, which can be structured
so that they cost nothing in the current fiscal year but expand to
billions of dollars in future years.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno and Silver have said they will negotiate the tax cuts and
borrowing this week and reveal their conclusions on Friday. But
administration officials are already concerned about reports that
the Legislature plans to use these areas to make major new
commitments, borrowing to build roads and housing for the mentally
ill and cutting taxes for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything with major future-year implications would be a
violation of our agreement, and once that happens, there is no
agreement,'' said a top aide to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration of Quick Draw, which is found in 3,200 bars,
restaurants and stores, concludes one of the oddest tales in this
year's budget. Pataki fought hard to implement the keno-style game
in 1995, and this year he proposed expanding it. The law that
created the game expired on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, a Democrat, refused to have the Assembly re-authorize
the game in March, letting the law die. The governor insisted that
he did not mind if the game died, but the Democrats have never
believed that, holding it as leverage in the overall budget fight.
People involved in budget negotiations say that it was Pataki who
urged that the game be revived, but in the end, the game mattered
to everyone, because the revenue will let them spend more.
</P>
<P>
   Quick Draw generates $120 million a year in profit for the
state. This fiscal year, $40 million of that has already been lost.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature and the governor decided last year, in part at
the urging of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, to eliminate the sales tax on
clothes, up to $110 per item, starting on Dec. 1 of this year. But
stores have complained that the timing of the change would be a
burden to them in the midst of their heaviest season. They also
worried that it would discourage people from shopping on the day
after Thanksgiving, traditionally the busiest shopping day.
</P>
<P>
   The stores had asked that the tax elimination be changed to Nov.
1. But instead, Silver, Bruno, a Republican, and the governor have
agreed to make it effective March 1 of next year, legislators and
aides to the three leaders said Tuesday. In the interim, they will
provide for two tax-free sales weeks for clothes, up to $500 per
item, in September and again in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
