<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-DUVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL-WOODS IS SLATED TO LAST ONLY 3 HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tiger Woods and David Duval meet in their match-play duel
on Aug. 2, they will not only be fighting for the $1.1 million
winner's prize.
</P>
<P>
   They will also be fighting for daylight in a rare prime-time
golf showcase.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction of the matchup is obvious. They are the world's
top two players based on the current ranking, both in their 20s,
but they have shared no Jack-and-Arnie moments on a final Sunday,
one stroke apart, with the tournament on the line.
</P>
<P>
   It's natural to wonder who is better, even if the outcome of
their made-for-TV exhibition will decide nothing, at least not
officially.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disrespect to Davis Love, Ernie Els or Vijay Singh,'' said
Mark Steinberg, Woods' agent, ``but these two guys have been the
dominant forces in golf for two or three years. They're No. 1 and
No. 2 and well ahead of No. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   To justify the $1.5 million purse, and to appeal to a casual
audience bored with the reruns of the summer doldrums, it made no
sense to stage the match in any part of the day but prime time. The
only way to stage it from 8 to 11 p.m. for the Eastern time zone
was to start it out West in the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farther west the better,'' said Barry Frank, a senior vice
president of International Management Group. ``We talked to several
clubs. One club in Las Vegas was interested, but the sun sets 45
minutes earlier than we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   For sunsets, Hawaii would have been ideal, but it is too far
away.
</P>
<P>
   The Sherwood Country Club, in Thousand Oaks, Calif., the site of
the Shark Shootout, agreed to pay $1 million for the right to stage
the event, and in turn received the benefit of having its name
appear in the official title ``Showdown at Sherwood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been a fool to think this wouldn't be beneficial
for the club,'' said Alexandra Castenskiold, Sherwood's general
manager. Attendance will be limited to 3,000 fans, who will pay
$225 to $550 each.
</P>
<P>
   ABC Sports, whose new president, Howard Katz, was eager to make
a bold statement about his leadership, signed for about $1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   When the event was announced in May, there was no hint of the
debate over whether Woods and Duval can complete all 18 holes from
5 to 8 p.m., Pacific time.
</P>
<P>
   Can Woods and Duval finish a round, with no golfers ahead or
behind them, in three hours?
</P>
<P>
   Or should the telecast abide by the PGA Tour's insistence that 3
hours is too short, and a cushion must be created in case of a
playoff?
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour, which is sanctioning the event for a $1 million
fee, said match play needs from 3 hours 20 minutes to 3:40.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have the competition end in a timely manner, we'll commence
at 4:30,'' said Henry Hughes, the Tour's chief of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said the decision is up to ABC and the Tour, but hopes the
entire match can be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to decide until that day,'' Frank said. ``I want
to see how late it gets dark on Saturday and Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank believes Woods and Duval can finish in 3 hours, especially
because in match play, easy short putts are usually conceded and
the round can end early if one golfer is 4-up with three holes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Even if ABC does not show Duval and Woods on the first two
holes, viewers will see the end, in regulation, or a playoff, for
which the 17th and 18th holes will be lighted with stadium-type
lighting. Unlike regular Tour events, the players and the caddies
will wear microphones.
</P>
<P>
   This is very much an IMG event. Frank devised the match while
watching Woods putt during a tournament in the spring and mused
about the attraction of a Woods-Duval match. He did not have to
venture far to find them: Woods and Duval are IMG clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a `let's pick the best of IMG's players for an
event,''' Steinberg said. ``It was `let's pick the two best players
in the world.'''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said that Woods, who recently finished seventh at the
British Open, was quickly enamored of Frank's concept, and
ruminated about the merits of match play against stroke play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Match play intrigued him,'' Steinberg said, ``but you don't
talk Tiger into things. Usually we agree. He thought this was a
good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval was more reluctant. ``He thought it would separate him and
Tiger from the rest of the Tour,'' said Charley Moore, Duval's
agent. ``David respects the guys. He doesn't want to be a
separatist guy. But at the end of the day, this is about
introducing golf to a new audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner is to receive $1.1 million, the loser $400,000. Each
golfer will donate $200,000 to charity, split between First Tee,
which introduces golf to minority-group members, and a charity of
each golfer's choice.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of a one-on-one exhibition on an open Monday night
(the week before the final major, the PGA Championship, begins)
will not determine who is the world's best golfer _ at least the
organizers and the golfers insist it should not.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference announcing the match, Duval said, ``It's
not the U.S. Open or the Masters on a Sunday, going head to head.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said: ``We're not out to prove who's No. 1. To do that you
should play 20 matches.''
</P>
<P>
   But the match will invite speculation _ at least about who is
the best on Aug. 2 _ which should help ABC's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it's the kind of event that people will talk about in
the days leading up to it,'' Katz said, ``and in the days
afterward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
