<SLUG> BC-BKC-FRESHMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL WANTS FRESHMEN ELIGIBLE IN BASKETBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 27-member panel recommended to the NCAA Tuesday that freshmen
continue to be eligible to play basketball. But the college
presidents, athletic directors and the retired North Carolina coach
Dean Smith, who made up the panel, recommended that the NCAA
tighten the rules governing freshmen and also reward colleges that
have high graduation rates for basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators have been concerned over the fact that graduation
rates for male basketball players have dropped in recent years. The
latest figures, for players who entered college in the 1991-92
school year, show that only 44 percent of the 844 men involved
graduated within six years.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen have been eligible for NCAA sports since 1972. If the
panel's recommendations are adopted by the NCAA's executive
committee Aug. 5 and the board of directors in January, freshmen
will remain eligible if they complete 12 course hours and achieve a
grade point average of at least 2.0 in their first term. Freshmen
who do not qualify academically would still be allowed to receive
financial aid despite being ineligible to play.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Shaw, the Syracuse chancellor, headed the panel. He said
he favored making freshmen ineligible but added, ``We have had to
temper the enthusiasm of some with the realities of what we can
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel would create an athletic scholarship system based on
graduation rates. Men's basketball teams at schools with graduation
rates of 75 percent or higher would have 14 annual grants, those
with rates from 33 to 74 percent would have 13 grants, and those
below 33 percent would have 12 grants. In addition, a maximum of
four new grants could be given each year. Another recommendation
was intended to reduce midyear transfers. It would require all
transfer athletes, not just some, to sit out one year.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also recommended that starting with the 2000-1 season,
regular-season games could not begin until the day after
Thanksgiving and practice could not begin until 34 days before the
first game. In some cases, that would delay the start of practice
for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen and transfer students would be encouraged to enroll in
summer school before their first fall term, and if they took at
least six hours of classes they could receive financial aid for
that term. While that recommendation would apply only to
basketball, the panel said it would urge that it be adopted for all
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the panel recommended that all male basketball players
at Division I colleges attend programs that ``should address
sportsmanship and leadership, manners and etiquette, on- and
off-court behavior and public-speaking skills.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
